<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMCAST-MERGER-NYT &LR;      03-22 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMCAST-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMCAST-MEDIAONE MERGER TALKS REPORTED
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Comcast Corp. and Mediaone Group Inc., two of the nation's
largest cable operators, were in intense talks late last week about
a possible merger, a person familiar with the discussions said on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of the two companies planned to take the proposed
merger to its board over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear on Sunday night if the proposed merger had been
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Should a merger, which some industry executive valued on Sunday
night at $40 billion, be approved, it would create the
third-largest cable company in the country after Time Warner and
Tele-Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The merged company would have 11 million subscribers, ranking it
behind Time Warner with 13 million and Tele-Communications Inc.
with 12 million, according to Paul Kagan, who heads a media
consulting firm that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has a market capitalization of $26.8 billion, and
Mediaone is capitalized at $36.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, which is based in Philadelphia, is controlled by the
Roberts family through so-called supervoting stock in which each
share counts for more than one vote.
</P>
<P>
   According to the person familiar with the discussions, Comcast
would plan to issue new low-voting stock for the Mediaone stock,
leaving Comcast in control of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Comcast president, Brian L. Roberts, nor the
Mediaone president, Charles M. Lillis, could be reached on Sunday
night for comment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the cable industry has been swept by
consolidation, the benefits of which include, among other things,
the ability to buy programming at lower cost. The mergers also let
cable companies operate cable systems in the same geographic areas
more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Among Comcast's holdings is QVC, a home-hopping network. The
company is also branching into various Internet services. Mediaone,
which is based in Englewood, Colo., provides services to 17 states
and has interests in wireless businesses abroad. Mediaone was spun
off from US West.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast shares closed Friday at $70.125, down 18.75 cents.
Mediaone shares closed at $60.75, down 68.75 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-FOODSTAMPS-NYT &LR;      03-22 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FOODSTAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER ERROR BRINGS EARLY FOOD STAMP CREDITS AND A SHOPPING
SPREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shoppers packed grocery stores throughout New Jersey on Sunday
after food stamp accounts were accidentally credited 11 days early
because of an error resulting from an effort to fix year 2000
computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   About 180,000 families could have used next month's food stamps
from 6:30 A.M. to 9:30 p.m., when the problem was fixed, state
officials said. The premature credit _ about $275 for a mother with
two children _ showed up in the accounts of the 90 percent of New
Jersey food stamp recipients who get their benefits through
electronic cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely nuts,'' said William J. Glovacz, a manager at
Edwards Super Food Store in Trenton. ``People have carts full of
food. They're shop-happy.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials did not immediately know how many people had
withdrawn the benefits, although the number appeared to be in the
thousands. The officials were still debating what to do about the
mistake, which could put the state in the position of losing
millions of dollars if no penalty is imposed on those who used the
credit to shop for food on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Grocers at a dozen stores reported a startling crowd of
shoppers. The grocers said few people have much of a balance left
on their cards this late in the month. The windfall was discovered
by people who made small purchases on Sunday morning, then received
receipts showing unexpectedly large balances in their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread quickly through low-income neighborhoods, and people
phoned friends and relatives throughout the state. Shoppers,
enjoying a good fortune they could not explain, said it was like an
early Mother's Day gift.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, grocers said, people did not ask questions. They
just bought.
</P>
<P>
   The Pathmark store in Paterson reported it was busier than on
the day before Thanksgiving, recording sales of more than $10,000
an hour, more than double the usual peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``My meat case is empty,'' said Eloy Espinal, a manager. ``They
don't even care what's on sale. Most of them are assuming it was a
mistake, and they think tomorrow it'll be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   They were right.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake occurred after a state government computer in
Trenton was upgraded to protect against the much-publicized year
2000 programming flaw, which could cause many computers to fail on
New Year's Day. For a reason that state officials still could not
explain on Sunday night, when the ``repaired'' computer sent
another computer information about the payment date for next
month's food stamps, it transmitted the date as April 1, 1990,
instead of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in an immediate credit to accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The error offers a foretaste of the possible disruptions arising
from the so-called Y-2K problem. Older computers used a programming
shortcut to identify the years in dates by their last two digits,
meaning they could respond as if 2000 were 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Tencza, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Department
of Human Services, said officials had not yet decided whether the
shoppers who used their balances on Sunday would get another credit
on April 1, which is when the food stamps should have become
available. ``This was definitely our mistake,'' she said. ``We
don't know if the client will be held responsible, or if the state
will be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   If the state decides to re-credit the accounts, that would mean
Sunday's mistake could cost as much as $49.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is among the states that have replaced the familiar
paper food stamps with magnetic cards, much like debit cards, that
food stamp users swipe at the cash register. Then they receive a
receipt showing the balance in the account.
</P>
<P>
   The program, known as electronic benefits transfer, started in
some New Jersey counties in 1995 and now is used in all but 6 of
the state's 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   The computer that credits accounts belongs to a private
contractor in Milwaukee. The repairs to the state computer were
made about two weeks ago, but the flaw was not apparent until
information about April benefits was sent to the contractor early
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   State officials learned of the problem about 8 a.m. when some
food stamp recipients called the contractor's toll-free number to
inquire about the surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Store managers said the throngs in their stores reminded them of
the rush before a snow storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw so many people in the store _ ever,'' said
Clemente Espinel, the owner of Spring Supermarket in Newark.
``Everybody happy. Everybody got a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Garden Market in Camden ran out of milk, bread, eggs, ham and
cheese. ``A lot of people don't think it's the computer,'' said
Carmen Reyes, the cashier. ``They think it's good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pathmark in Paterson, Jeff James, a 32-year-old
warehouseman who had come to use his windfall, said he had
discovered one catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were excited,'' he said. ``But now the lines are too
long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
