<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LAD     03-22 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NATURE' FORCES ITS WAY TO TOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Moviegoers stormed the nation's multiplexes for
``Forces of Nature'' as the romantic comedy took in an estimated
$13.9 million at 2,058 theaters, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The DreamWorks release, starring Sandra Bullock and Ben Affleck
as a couple thrown together while Affleck is on the way to his
wedding, performed in line with industry expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came across as a clever movie with good chemistry between
the stars,'' said film analyst Arthur Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks distribution chief James Tharp said the ``Forces of
Nature'' audience was 65 percent female. ``It's playing very well
among young women,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
predicted ``Forces'' would take in $46 million by the end of its
run but noted that final figures for this weekend could fall short
of estimates due to the Academy Awards telecast. ``It's hard to
determine what impact the TV show will have since it's never been
on Sunday before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gangster-comedy ``Analyze This'' continued to attract moviegoing
mobs with $11.9 million at 2,537 theaters. The Warner Bros.
release, starring Robert De Niro and Billy Crystal, has topped $57
million in 10 days and dropped only 23 percent from its previous
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a distant third was Warner's opening of Clint
Eastwood's Death Row drama ``True Crime,'' with a disappointing
$4.9 million at 1,852 theaters despite generally positive reviews
and Eastwood's star power. ``Movies about Death Row generally
haven't done well outside of `Dead Man Walking,' '' Bucksbaum said.
``People are just not interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony's second weekend of ``Baby Geniuses'' continued to overcome
poor reviews in fourth with $4.5 million at 1,698 theaters,
underscoring moviegoers' strong appetite for comedies. ``People
want to be entertained these days rather than shocked and
horrified,'' Rockwell noted.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's third weekend of ``Cruel Intentions'' came in fifth with
$4.2 million at 2,235 theaters to hit $30 million overall, followed
by MGM's second weekend of ``The Rage: Carrie 2'' with $3.8 million
at 2,286 as the sequel performed the usual fast fade for horror
films.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. also suffered a setback from the opening of its
animated ``The King and I,'' which finished seventh with $3.7
million at 2,352 screens despite a large marketing campaign and the
general success of animated movies last year. Bucksbaum said the
remake of the Rodgers and Hammerstein musical might have been too
tame and traditional for children's tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids between ages 5 and 10 want to see more sophisticated
movies like `Cruel Intentions,' `The Rage,' `Baby Geniuses' and the
new `Star Wars,' '' he said. ``Audiences can get tired of animation
unless it's really state of the art.''
</P>
<P>
   New Line's second weekend of the police drama ``The Corruptor''
came in eighth with $3.2 million at 1,804 screens, followed by
Miramax's 15th weekend of ``Shakespeare in Love'' with $2.8 million
at 1,266 sites to push its 101-day total to nearly $73 million.
``Shakespeare'' has continued to benefit from the buildup to the
Academy Awards and has now doubled its gross since its 13 Oscar
nominations were announced Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's second weekend of ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' continued
to flounder as the drama sank 52 percent from its debut weekend to
10th place with $2.7 million at 1,907 theaters. But another Oscar
contender, Miramax's ``Life Is Beautiful,'' posted impressive
results in 11th with $2.2 million at 647 locations _ a 22 percent
gain from the previous weekend and enough to pull it past $36
million overall.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' ``Saving Private Ryan,'' with 11 Oscar nods, also
saw a considerable upward bump of 31 percent with $1.1 million at
548 theaters to push its total to $210.3 million. ``Ryan'' needs
less than $500,000 to top ``Back to the Future'' for the 22nd spot
on the all-time domestic chart.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's horror-comedy ``Ravenous,'' a tale of
cannibalism in the Old West, posted the weekend's most abysmal
results with $950,000 at 1,047 theaters. Gramercy racked up
moderate returns from expanding ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking
Barrels'' with $500,000 at 156 theaters in its third weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Overall grosses hit about $76 million, down about 19 percent
from the same weekend a year ago when the 14th weekend of
``Titanic'' led the box office. Year-to-date grosses have topped
$1.1 billion, trailing the 1998 period by about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Three new movies will open Friday, including Universal's comedy
``EDtv'' with Matthew McConaughey, MGM's police drama ``Mod Squad''
and Disney's animated ``Doug's First Movie.'' Bucksbaum said
``EDtv'' should lead the box office due partly to strong word of
mouth from test screenings and sneak previews while ``Mod Squad''
should benefit from teen and young adult moviegoers being on spring
break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-ANALYSIS-LADN &LR;      03-22 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL'S FAIR IN `LOVE' AND WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
must feel collectively good about itself for choosing the literary
over the lethal at Sunday's awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   With seven Oscars, including the best picture prize,
``Shakespeare in Love'' took down longtime front-runner ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' which earned a deserved statuette for director
Steven Spielberg and four technical craft awards for the evening's
second highest tally.
</P>
<P>
   However literate ``Love'' may seem, though, can the academy
voters truly convince themselves in the morning that this
seductively clever entertainment even stands close to ``Ryan'' as a
milestone of visual storytelling? The category is, after all,
called best picture, not best written or spoken lines.
</P>
<P>
   But heck, let's be charitable. It's the end of the millennium,
and everybody's a little out of whack about it. There's no reason
why this year's Oscars shouldn't fit right in with the overall
zeitgeist. Indeed, for both good and ill, the 71st Academy Awards
was awash in change of era summings-up, scab-pickings and
generational reconciliations.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's thanks to his father for teaching him to honor the
past essentially keynoted the whole evening. From John Glenn's
surprise appearance to Martin Scorsese's elegant montage of the
departed Frank Sinatra's best filmed moments; from Gen. Colin
Powell's simple tribute to our greatest generation's wartime
sacrifices to the troublesome emblem of that same age group's
political agonies and human frailties, Elia Kazan; from that Roy
Rogers hymn to cowboy heaven to the too little, too late (but
nonetheless crucial) acknowledgment of our most prescient cinematic
futurist, the never-Oscar'd Stanley Kubrick, it was truly a night
of taking stock.
</P>
<P>
   All Hollywood style, naturally, but a welcome and perhaps even
necessary change from the usual unfiltered self-congratulation. And
thanks to Jim Carrey blurting out the banished, non-p.c. phrase
``And the winner is ...,'' we were reminded of what this show
always was, is and will be really all about.
</P>
<P>
   As for those winners, Roberto Benigni copping the best actor
award for ``Life Is Beautiful'' hopefully means that Americans will
appreciate foreign films to at least partially the extent that the
rest of the world enjoys our movies. (Benigni is the first male
actor to win for a non-English language performance.) That, at
least, is the optimistic way of spinning the fact that difficult
but towering work from ``Gods and Monsters''' Ian McKellen and
``Affliction's'' Nick Nolte scared the voters off.
</P>
<P>
   That said, with Nolte co-star James Coburn's supporting actor
award, the voters seemed to go back to their recently abandoned
practice of noticing long-overlooked veterans. But rather than
making it a purely sentimental journey, they recognized Coburn for
playing an uncompromisingly vicious character _ in an unrelentingly
dark film that represents a newer, healthier academy trend to
acknowledge true and daring independent filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   The female acting choices were anything but adventurous, but
delightfully so. And the ``Shakespeare'' ladies, weepy Gwyneth
Paltrow and regal Judi Dench, made a symbolically felicitous age
pair _ Paltrow was the youngest of the best-actress nominees and
Dench the eldest of the supporting actresses. A nice end-of-century
twosome if ever there was one.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite award of the evening: Bill Condon for his brilliantly
adapted, psychologically astute ``Gods and Monsters'' screenplay.
Favorite non-surprise: as previously admitted, ``Shakespeare's''
original (though some claim pilfered) script was a joy to ... well,
behold's not the right word, but Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard's
cascades of good ones gave us the most fun to be had in a theater
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite snub: The punishingly pretentious ``The Thin Red Line''
got all that it deserved _ zilch.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's most anticipated controversy, the lifetime
achievement award to landmark filmmaker and blacklist name-namer
Kazan, proved, well, wimpy. Of course, ending the film clips on the
note of Marlon Brando's pained, post-testifying walk in Kazan's
``On the Waterfront'' could be taken either way. But by adamantly
refusing to directly acknowledge the controversy this particular
honor has dredged up, the academy actually honored, and settled,
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting, but no doubt depressing, to read the
postgame partisan quarterbacking. Was presenter Martin Scorsese
trying to hide behind Kazan before the old man forced him to accept
a hug televised worldwide? Did co-presenter Robert De Niro
purposely give his caress at arm's length? And was that
mohawk-gone-weedy haircut of his some arcane, subversive ``Taxi
Driver'' reference?
</P>
<P>
   Out in the audience, Warren Beatty, that most dedicated of
Hollywood leftists who also happens to owe his movie career to
Kazan, appeared to lead the standing ovation (Meryl Streep, Kathy
Bates and Helen Hunt were among the Oscar winners who followed).
The notable non-applauders broadcast were Nick Nolte and Ed Harris
_ and was a statement being made by having ABC's cameras single out
these two never-wons to represent the quiet protesters?
</P>
<P>
   Only Chris Rock had the guts to really say anything, and he took
a cheap shot using the rodent word. If anything hopeful emerges
from this whole, misguided fiasco, it may only be that it doesn't
trigger a whole new generation of recalcitrant recriminations _
like the old ones, which, it has taught us, will never die.
</P>
<P>
   On a cheerier note, the ceremony's expansive spirit was nicely
symbolized by Benigni and Spielberg holding hands when the
Italian's ``Life Is Beautiful,'' which the ``Schindler's List''
director had reportedly criticized, won the foreign language film
award _ although that whole category, from presenter Sophia Loren
to the extended screening of ``Life'' footage over clips from the
other foreign language nominees, smelled mighty like a set-up.
</P>
<P>
   Like the three Oscars for ``Life,'' the feature documentary
award for the Spielberg-presented Holocaust film ``The Last Days''
continued the academy's habit of honoring works that examine the
century's vilest crime. On the other end of the spectrum, the
documentary short award for ``The Personals'' director Keiko Ibi
surely broke boundaries as the first Oscar ever bestowed on a
former Miss Japan Grande Prix.
</P>
<P>
   Probably not as big a step toward an international film culture
as the night's clown prince, Benigni's, loose-limbed leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Looking again to the future, Irving Thalberg award recipient
Norman Jewison's plea that young filmmakers ignore demographics and
commercialism in favor of good storytelling seemed like the
evening's most futile suggestion, ``Shakespeare'' semi-sweep or no.
But somebody had to say it.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Shakespeare's'' big win could feasibly be attributed
to that other major controversy of this year's Oscar season: its
distributor, Miramax Films', conspicuously costly get-out-the-vote
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tradition as old as Hollywood to spend a lot of money in
order to attract attention. And if the final Oscars of this century
are any indication, that's one thing we can count on working well
into the Y2K millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
