<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 03:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9117 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTIFICIAL-CELLS-SFCH     03-22 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIFICIAL-CELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ARTIFICIAL CELLS SOLVE REAL PROBLEMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID PERLMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a unique quest for new tools to study the
chemistry of life, researchers headed by Stanford University
chemists have created microscopic artificial cells that they call
``the world's smallest test tubes.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``vesicles,'' the tiny fluid-filled cell-like objects
can house the same chemical reactions that go on inside human cells
when the many processes that support human life proceed from birth
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Held together by microscopically thin two-layered fatty
membranes _ much like human cells _ the vesicles can range in size
from the thickness of a human hair to dimensions 100 times smaller,
according to Richard N. Zare, the Stanford chemistry professor who
leads the laboratory where the objects were created.
</P>
<P>
   Although the scientists who created the containers have already
used them to conduct experiments showing how lifelike chemical
reactions can in fact be housed inside the vesicles, they have yet
to undertake experiments that attempt to solve problems of
real-life biology, Zare stressed.
</P>
<P>
   But the vesicles hold the potential for developing important new
avenues of research. In studying the biological processes that go
on in living organisms, scientists generally have only two choices:
to reproduce the reactions in laboratory test tubes or other inert
containers, or to reproduce them in the living organisms
themselves. And although using organisms like bacteria, plants or
animals to test chemicals or transfer genes rarely pose ethical
questions, the human body is far out of bounds for many such
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, chemical reactions in test tube experiments often
don't accurately mimic living processes because the chemicals mix
at much different speeds and sometimes in ways that bear no
relation to what happens in a living system, Zare said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Creating the synthetic cell-like vesicles is ``remarkable for
its technical virtuosity,'' and offers major potential applications
in studying processes that go on inside human cells, said George
Whitesides, a distinguished organic chemist at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the vesicles could be used to study how enzymes
called proteases act to digest foreign proteins, Whitesides said.
In test tube experiments right now, researchers are trying to
understand just how the the protease inhibitor drugs act against
HIV, the AIDS virus, and the new cell-like objects could well prove
useful in that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Other important studies relating to human disease could well be
aided by the Zare team's work, Whitesides noted: They could be used
to study how neurotransmitters are released when nerve cells
transmit impulses across their synapses, or junctions, he said.
They could also aid in studying how proteins are synthesized, or to
investigate the biochemistry of disease-causing microbes that
inhabit many types of human cells.
</P>
<P>
   The vesicles might even be used eventually as tiny containers to
deliver new drugs into single cells, or for transferring genes from
one cell to another, Whitesides suggested.
</P>
<P>
   In one series of ``microchemistry'' experiments so far, Zare's
team first created vesicles containing a single type of fluorescent
dye and immersed the cell-like containers in a solution containing
a different chemical dye. Then, by zapping the vesicles with a mild
electric current between two electrodes, the scientists caused the
pores of the containers to open so the chemical from the solution
could enter the vesicles and react with the dye inside.
</P>
<P>
   In a second set of experiments, the electrodes sent a stronger
current through two tiny vesicles, each containing a different
chemical. The electric pulse caused the membranes of the two
vesicles to break down so the two containers fused into one,
leaving the two chemicals to react so the scientists could study
the event in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Zare's group at Stanford collaborated in the research with other
teams at the University of Goteborg in Sweden and at Pomona College
in Claremont (Los Angeles County). Their work is reported in the
current issue of the journal Science.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
