<P>
   ``It could be bypassed with suitcase bombs, pickup trucks and
sea-launched missiles,'' said Rep. Rush Holt, D-N.J., who is a
physicist. ``It would be billions of dollars down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon brass dismiss the naysayers, arguing that military
contractors and engineers will work out the technical kinks and, by
2005, field a limited system of radars and missile-killing
interceptors _ perhaps in Alaska, North Dakota or on ships at sea _
if Clinton gives the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fast-emerging consensus for missile defenses at home,
however, collides with growing anxiety abroad, particularly in
Beijing and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has long opposed a U.S. missile defense system, fearing
that Washington would use it as an excuse to reprise the much
grander Star Wars, which would be dauntingly expensive to match.
</P>
<P>
   While the anti-missile issue is of little concern to ordinary
Russians struggling with dire economic conditions, it is core
national security for Russian politicians, and a matter of
considerable national self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   With the United States moving ahead on such a system, Russian
nationalists could use the argument that Russia was losing its
nuclear deterrent _ since an anti-missile defense could encourage a
nation with one (that is, the United States) to risk a nuclear
exchange. That argument could undercut, for example, efforts by the
Russian Parliament to ratify the second strategic arms reduction
treaty between the two countries, or Start 2.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Foreign Ministry warned after last week's U.S. Senate
vote that building even a limited system ``poses a serious threat
to the whole process of nuclear arms control, as well as strategic
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   And for this reason, arms control advocates are nervous about
doing anything to upset further nuclear arms reductions with
Russia. After all, they say, North Korea may threaten America with
one to five missiles, but instability in Russia is a much greater
risk. ``Our overwhelming and sustained concern has to be Russia,''
said Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who voted reluctantly for the
Senate measure. ``They got the most, they got the biggest, and they
got the most accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans and a growing number of Democrats say that
building an anti-missile system is just as necessary to insure a
safer world as reducing Moscow's nuclear stockpile, which is
declining with or without a treaty because Russia no longer can
afford to maintain it at Cold War levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate balance with Russia,'' said Paul Wolfowitz, a
senior Pentagon official under President George Bush and a member
of the Rumsfeld panel. ``We don't want to alienate the Russians,
but on the other hand we can't let them bully us.''
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, U.S.-Japanese plans to develop a missile system to
defend Japan, South Korea, Taiwan and the U.S. troops in the region
got under way about a decade ago, in anticipation of the possible
missile threat from North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   As that threat has become more real, the plans to defend against
it have encountered growing criticism from China _ and even from
key allies. Two weeks ago, South Korea's defense minister said a
joint U.S.-Japanese missile defense would be ineffective against
North Korean missiles, and added that his government would not help
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the possibility that such an anti-missile system
might not be ready for years, when there is at least a chance that
there won't be a North Korea left to worry about. This is a point
not lost on China, which views the proposed missile umbrella
primarily as a threat to its plans to reunify Taiwan with the
Chinese mainland. Since the early 1990s, China has more or less
doubled, to several hundred, the number of missiles on the Chinese
coast pointed at Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The fear among many national security analysts in Asia is that
missile defenses could do to China what the creation of NATO did to
the Soviet Union: help to trigger a new escalation of arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are for the development of advanced missile defense
systems, we are going to touch off new rounds of an arms race,''
said He Yafei, a senior Chinese diplomat in Washington who has long
experience in arms control.
</P>
<P>
   And the idea of including Taiwan under any missile umbrella ``is
an obstruction on our course of unification of our motherland,'' he
added. ``Taiwan is part of China. Politically, that is an
interference, a very serious interference in our internal
affairs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
