u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SMALL-ISSUES-REVIEW     03-22 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SMALL-ISSUES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING BABY-SIZE ISSUES INTO VOTERS' HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First he decried the evils of traffic congestion.
Then he vowed to do something about cow manure that pollutes
streams. Then he called for larger print on over-the-counter drug
labels.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the mayor of Los Angeles or a county agriculture
commissioner or a pharmacist in Sarasota, Fla. This was the vice
president of the United States, Al Gore, unveiling his latest
initiatives recently as he competes for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   If President Clinton transformed the presidency (some say shrank
it) from a wellspring of grand ideas to one of itsy-bitsy
proposals, his vice president has gone further. Forget the
bite-size morsels like school uniforms that Clinton doled out four
years ago. To some, Gore is serving up crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Well beyond Gore, the smaller-is-better movement threatens to
infiltrate American political discourse. A favorite line of
Republican presidential aspirant Elizabeth Dole is her boast about
how, as transportation secretary, she championed emergency aisle
safety lights on airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   These appeals to everyday life may reflect a radical change in
what people expect from their president. They may also be spurred
by an inward-looking culture in which Americans are relatively
content and more preoccupied with challenges of their daily lives
than with the less tangible state of the country.
</P>
<P>
   But that some leading politicians are as eager to talk about
tiny things as they are about grand matters of war and taxes may
also reflect an era of caution. Humbled, for example, by the
spectacular collapse of Clinton's huge health care overhaul,
politicians these days may be more inclined to propose sure-fire
initiatives than more ambitious or imaginative ones that may be
difficult to enact. These candidates may also be encouraging voters
to hold low expectations about what government can actually
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Even in areas like health care, where there is general agreement
that the system needs an overhaul, political polarization stands in
the way of any meaningful changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more risk in proposing big changes _ it's harder to
get it done,'' said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. ``And there is in life
a general and very understandable tendency to make an assessment of
what can be done and work on that. I've been working on
entitlements since 1993. I think we're making progress. But it's
not something we can put on a press release.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., who is thus far Gore's only
rival for the nomination, derides the concept of baby proposals,
asserting that as president his priority would be ``to cultivate 10
strong oaks rather than sprinkling water on a thousand house
plants.'' Bradley speaks ambitiously of rescuing the quarter of
American children living in poverty and tackling the deepening
crises in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, to be sure, talks about big things. But he risks becoming
known as parochial _ as Mayor Al _ when he dwells on matters that
his predecessors would never have raised.
</P>
<P>
   He produced titters for proposing an ``Airline Passenger Bill of
Rights,'' that calls for such things as increasing the compensation
for lost baggage. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a prospect for the
Republican presidential nomination, actually came up with the idea
first.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Kerrey said, he did a radio show in Omaha, Neb., and
the announcers started laughing when the subject of the Airline
Passenger Bill of Rights came up. ``Jesus! I'm sure there's a need
there somewhere,'' Kerrey said. ``But it makes me a little
uncomfortable as an American.'' Mocking the measure, he said, ``All
of a sudden, I'm going to pass a law saying, `Give me sparkling
water instead of plain water!'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore may be practicing smart politics. A common frustration
of elected officials is that they cannot break through and explain
to voters how what they do touches people's daily lives. So when
Clinton in 1996 made small-bore ideas a centerpiece of his
campaign, voters rewarded him. Pollsters have also found that there
is a surge in potential voters who are part of an upper middle
class; these proposals are designed to appeal to them.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is particularly well placed to promote these
ideas because he and Clinton can dream up _ and announce _ all
sorts of executive decrees that do not require congressional
approval. (Democrats are generally more eager than Republicans to
want to impose new government regulations.)
</P>
<P>
   But Gore and his loyalists warn that matters that to some appear
trivial may, in the eyes of others actually loom large. ``There
seems to be a difference of perspective between politicians and
journalistic elites on the one hand and the American people on the
other as to what counts as an idea that's large enough to be
meaningful,'' said William Galston, a professor of public affairs
at the University of Maryland who was a domestic policy official in
the early days of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Galston, a longtime adviser to Gore, added that politicians need
to adjust to the changing times. ``There is no reason to believe
that Bill Clinton was harmed in any way in 1995 and 1996 by
addressing issues that during the cold war might not have been seen
as presidential,'' he said. ``Obviously, you can go too far down
that road. These are questions of judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Castellanos, a Republican consultant, said, ``Our next
president is not going to be Gore or small-minded Republicans. It's
going to be the candidate with one big idea. That's what America is
hungry for.''
</P>
<P>
   But just what constitutes a big idea these days? Gore asserted
that the next president will understand ``how tired working parents
are'' and that they do not want to be ``caught in traffic jams.''
For frazzled working parents with interminable commutes _ many of
whom are important swing voters _ that may be as big an idea as
they get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0829EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 08:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9196 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-POLITICAL-HANGERS-O     03-22 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-POLITICAL-HANGERS-ON-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE POLITICIAN CAN'T TAKE A HINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In New Jersey, former Gov. Jim Florio wants to run
for the U.S. Senate. In California, former Rep. Robert Dornan is
threatening to challenge a fellow Republican congressman. And in
New York, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato keeps floating his name as a
candidate for his old job.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every state has them, defeated politicians trying to
reclaim old glory. Like ghosts of elections past, they rattle their
platforms and demand attention from voters, local officials and the
media. But the people they often end up scaring the most are
members of their own parties.
</P>
<P>
   In Florio's case, many of his fellow Democrats are worried that
he will end up in a replay of his loss in the 1993 gubernatorial
race to Christie Whitman, who Republicans say is leaning toward
running for the Senate next year. Voters are still angry with
Florio for raising taxes, those Democrats say, and are sure to
punish him and possibly other Democratic candidates if he runs
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was someone prominent the Democrats could push
forward against Florio, someone with statewide name recognition,
they would do it,'' said Russ Baker, a professor of political
science at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   Dornan, a combative conservative Republican from Orange County,
was unseated in 1996 by Loretta Sanchez, a Democrat. Dornan
disputed the results, failed, tried to get the House of
Representatives to overturn them, failed again, and then challenged
Ms. Sanchez in 1998, failing for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Dornan now says he may challenge Ms. Sanchez again
next year, or possibly take on a fellow Republican, Rep. Dana
Rohrabacher, who Dornan says failed to help him in the 1998 race.
</P>
<P>
   To many Republican leaders in California, Dornan is a divisive
candidate whose attacks on immigration have hampered the party's
efforts to attract Hispanic and Asian voters. But their efforts to
block him in 1998 failed when Dornan won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear the groans from Republicans when he said he
might run next year,'' said Amy Walter, an editor of the Cook
Report, a nonpartisan newsletter that tracks congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   When D'Amato was ousted by Charles Schumer last year, many
political analysts chalked it up in part to voter exhaustion with
the brash three-term Republican. So when D'Amato started saying on
national television recently that running next year was ``very
tempting,'' not every New York Republican cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulk would be mortified'' if he ran again, said Norman
Adler, a political consultant who works for both Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   What makes people like Dornan, Florio and D'Amato hard to ignore
is their ability to move blocs of loyal voters, even small blocs.
And since only a small percentage of the electorate votes in
primaries, those loyalists can carry the day, particularly in
crowded fields.
</P>
<P>
   But why would politicians subject themselves to the rigors of a
campaign after voters had rejected them before? Political analysts
say the comeback personality usually falls into one of two
categories (and sometimes both): the vindication seeker and the
egoist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vindication seekers are the people who lost by just a few
hundred votes, which is a very tough pill to swallow,'' said Ms.
Walter. ``They can't help thinking, `If only 200 people changed
their minds, I would win.'''
</P>
<P>
   The egoist thrives on public attention, seeming unfocused,
unfulfilled and disoriented without it. ``A lot of guys need to
reaffirm their importance,'' said Adler. ``And one way to do it is
to say, `I'm running for something.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing seems to inspire not-ready-for-retirement
politicians: the examples of comeback kids who succeeded. Michael
Dukakis in Massachusetts and Bill Clinton in Arkansas were both
defeated after their first terms as governor, then won their jobs
back in the next election. And Richard M. Nixon lost the 1960
presidential campaign and 1962 California gubernatorial race before
winning sweet vindication in the 1968 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the defeated candidates expressed contrition for
being prideful, aloof or hard-charging, and claimed to have become
more in tune with voters' concerns, Baker said. He calls it the
``politics of epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic forgiveness among Americans,'' he said,
``this idea of a second chance, particularly if someone is willing
to humble himself and say they've made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics of epiphany seems to be at the heart of Florio's
current pitch for becoming a Senate candidate. Criticized as an
intense, unemotional man who failed to sympathize with middle-class
voters' worries in 1993, Florio now says that five years as a
lawyer in private practice, battling traffic jams and navigating
government bureaucracy, has made him more empathetic to the gripes
of regular folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a better understanding of the frantic pace of life,''
he said in a recent interview, ``the stresses and strains that real
people go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said Florio will have to battle suspicions that his new
image is ``packaging over substance.'' And Adler said Florio may
have a hard time convincing major contributors that he can win
again, a potentially towering obstacle given the high cost of
statewide campaigns today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most big contributors give not for ideological reasons, but to
people they think will be winners,'' he said. ``And it's very hard
to resuscitate a dead politician.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0829EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
