<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marijuana Finds Its Niche
</P>
<P>
   It has been smoked for centuries, lionized in poetry and song
(``Everybody must get stoned!''), vilified in film (``Reefer
Madness''). Now marijuana, which can bring both euphoria and a
federal prison term, has secured its place in the medical
literature, with a comprehensive government-financed report that
finds its active components help patients with pain, nausea and the
severe weight loss associated with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The report, conducted by an independent panel of experts at the
Institute of Medicine, set off much hullabaloo when it was
released. Gen. Barry McCaffrey, who commissioned the study as
director of the National Office on Drug Control Policy, trumpeted
its conclusion: There is ``little future in smoked marijuana.''
Proponents of legalizing the drug for medical use seized upon the
report as evidence that ``therapeutic cannabis'' is not a
contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   Both were correct. The 250-page report found that the benefits
of smoking marijuana are limited because of the toxic effects of
the smoke, and urged that new delivery mechanisms, particularly
bronchial inhalers of the sort used by asthma patients, be
developed. At the same time, it recommended that the drug be given,
under close supervision and for a limited time, to patients who do
not respond to other therapies.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion that caused the biggest stir, however, had more
to do with policy than medicine. The authors found no evidence that
giving marijuana to sick people would increase illicit use
elsewhere in the population. Nor, they said, is marijuana a
``gateway drug'' to more dangerous narcotics like cocaine and
heroin. McCaffrey said the next step is more research.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   A Money Titan's Obscurantism
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the first time Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. prepared to go
public, it honored a tradition that dates from its founding as a
private partnership 130 years ago: obsessive secrecy. Now Goldman
has augmented its prospectus with 1,400 pages filed last week with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Readers can learn that Goldman pays $35,862,435 each year to
Metropolitan Life Corp. of New York to rent land. The land is
defined obliquely as ``beginning at the corner formed by the
intersection of the northerly side of Pearl Street with the
easterly side of Broad Street, then still southerly along westerly
line of Stone Street and forming an angle of 153 degrees 30 minutes
16 seconds on its westerly side.''
</P>
<P>
   This land is said to be located in the City of New York, County
of New York, State of New York,'' though the reader is left to
surmise that it is included in the United States. It is possible to
determine after searching the appendices that this area contains
Goldman's headquarters at 85 Broad St.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the condition of Goldman's offices at One Carter
Lane in London notes a troubling-sounding loss of fluid in the
``system one Altu filter indicator,'' and documents scratches on
the transom of an elevator, bay 50, at the same location. But
admirers of Goldman's proven agility will be pleased to read that
``a dedicated movement joint is located in the E-W direction along
the demise line between One Carter Lane and the site of One Old
Change Court.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospectus says that 41 percent of the Forbes 400 list of
the world's richest people maintain private investment accounts at
Goldman. The firm is spending $150 million to update its computer
systems to handle four-digit dates so they won't crash when the
millennium begins. The firm has committed about $3 billion to
private investments around the world.
</P>
<P>
   There were five days last year in which Goldman's traders earned
the firm more than $60 million, but nine days in which they lost
more than more than $60 million. That undoubtedly led to a great
deal of fingernail biting in the area bounded by the westerly side
of Stone Street and northerly side of Pearl Street.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
<P>
   A Truck, a Train and a Fatal Encounter
</P>
<P>
   An Amtrak train heading from Chicago to New Orleans crashed into
a truck at a crossing in Bourbonnais, Ill., 50 miles south of
Chicago, raising fresh questions about the safety of the country's
track crossings. Eleven people were killed and more than 100 were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver said the gates started closing after he was
already crossing, but another truck driver behind him reportedly
told investigators he saw the truck enter the tracks despite
flashing warning lights. Investigators were trying to determine if
the driver of the truck, which was loaded with steel bars, was
attempting to go around the gates as they were descending. If tire
tracks found nearby match those of the truck, they would show that
the driver tried to defeat the system, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PAM BELLUCK
</P>
<P>
   Bombing Threatened
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said NATO must be ready to carry out
airstrikes against the Serbs, who have acted in a manner that
provoked a military response. Calling his first full news
conference in almost a year, Clinton said, ``Hesitation is a
license to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton not only discussed bombing Kosovo but also addressed his
administration's handling of China's suspected theft of secrets
from U.S. nuclear labs in the 1980s. ``To the best of my knowledge,
no one has said anything to me about any espionage which occurred
by the Chinese against the labs during my presidency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
