<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 08:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9207 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LATAM-TAXES-REVIEW-     03-22 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LATAM-TAXES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICA'S CONTAGION: WHERE TAXES AREN'T SO CERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ As the year began, the Ecuadorean government
was nearing bankruptcy, unable to pay teachers, doctors and other
public employees or to repair $2.6 billion in damage inflicted by
El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of global economic contagion? Not directly. It
reflected a much older, if related, problem in Latin America _ tax
evasion. Here it had become so bad that the Ecuadorean Congress
took a truly unorthodox step: It abolished the income tax
altogether in favor of a 1 percent tax on financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador's move was ``an act of extraordinary desperation and an
admission of defeat,'' as one U.S. aid official put it last week.
In effect, it wrote off the 60 percent or more of taxpayers here
who are thought to be dodging their obligations, in hopes that the
new tax would be easier to collect.
</P>
<P>
   Americans grumbling over their 1040 returns this month might be
envious. But there is a sobering context: Governments all over
Latin America are coming under pressure from the International
Monetary Fund and other lenders to cut their yawning budget
deficits and open their economies to the outside world to prevent
the spread of the financial slump that has humbled Southeast Asia
and crippled Russia (a country with severe tax collection problems
of its own).
</P>
<P>
   Latin America may yet prove particularly vulnerable to this
contagion because development and growth are already crippled by
the inability to collect taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any more vital issue in Latin America
right now,'' said Michael Shifter, a senior fellow at the
Washington-based policy analysis group Inter-American Dialogue.
``It's a vicious cycle that is very, very hard to break. People
don't want to pay taxes because they say government doesn't deliver
services, but government institutions aren't going to perform any
better until they have resources, which they obtain when people pay
their taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the dimension of the problem is that Brazil,
Ecuador and other governments that have been forced to carry out a
``fiscal adjustment'' have preferred to emphasize spending cuts
over new ways to increase revenues. ``Since there is a culture of
noncompliance in the region,'' said Luisa Rains, an economist who
heads the fiscal division of the Inter-American Development Bank,
``you're going to run into resistance and affect various interest
groups any time you attempt a real tax modernization.''
</P>
<P>
   When Guatemala, another glaring example, signed a United
Nations-sponsored peace accord ending its civil war in 1996, it
promised to nearly double its tax revenues, to 12 percent of gross
domestic product. But the country has failed to comply, and
therefore is unable to adequately finance the education, health and
land reform programs the accord stipulates. A powerful coalition of
agricultural, industrial and financial groups is simply refusing to
pay up and has blocked all efforts at tax reform.
</P>
<P>
   Guatemala, of course, is not the only Latin American country
famous for the gulf that separates the few who are rich from the
many who are poor, and sometimes governments tolerate tax evasion
because they are simply too weak to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, as in Mexico, or in Brazil and other military
dictatorships during the 1970s, they do so with political advantage
in mind. Newspapers and television stations, for instance, were
allowed to evade obligations with the understanding that their
debts would be called in if they published material that angered
the government.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, many large Latin America companies simply hold onto
the income tax and social security payments they deduct from their
employees' paychecks. Bribery of tax inspectors, underdeclaration
of income and hiding ownership of property are other popular forms
of evasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Leona Helmsley came out and said only little guys pay
taxes, she ended up with a jail term,'' Ms. Rains recalled. ``But
in any number of Latin American countries, tax codes do not even
treat the failure to pay taxes as a crime that requires you to
serve a jail sentence.'' Even when arrests are made, cases can drag
on for years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their inability or unwillingness to collect income
taxes, Latin American countries have traditionally relied on
measures such as the value-added tax, which runs as high as
Uruguay's 23 percent. But such forms of taxation are highly
regressive, placing a heavy burden on the poor and stoking their
resentment.
</P>
<P>
   The problem may be especially acute in this Andean nation of 12
million people, which is in the midst of its worst economic crisis
since the Great Depression. ``Nobody pays taxes,'' a longtime
diplomat here said. ``Those in a position to pay the most pay the
least, and then they cry the most.'' As a result, he continued,
``the poor say, `Why should we pay if the rich don't?'''
</P>
<P>
   The flat tax on financial transactions that Ecuador enacted last
January (and that resembles a measure approved by Brazil's Congress
last week), was supposed to curb the possibilities for evasion. But
once again, the citizenry demonstrated an exceptional ability to
find a way around paying up.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the new tax was imposed, local bank deposits dropped
16 percent. Canny depositors simply converted their sucres into
dollars and then spirited their money out of the country. That led
to a run on the local currency that saw its value drop by more than
40 percent in just a few weeks. So last week, President Jamil
Mahuad again gave up in desperation. He agreed to restore the
income tax, though without specifying how he intends to enforce
collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0836EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
