<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SADDAM-MILOSEVIC-RE     03-22 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SADDAM-MILOSEVIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DIFFERENT TYRANTS, VERY MUCH THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review) 
(bl)  
 By ALISON SMALE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the West's halcyon days, spring 1991, when Saddam
Hussein had just been vanquished in the gulf war and Eastern Europe
had apparently jettisoned communism for good, few Americans had
even heard of the Serbian leader, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was cultivating ethnic hatreds and threatening war,
but in a seemingly isolated corner of Europe known to few outsiders
and apparently of little concern to Washington. The Iraqi leader,
by contrast, had invaded a neighboring country and lobbed missiles
at Israel, and was found to have a scary near-ability to launch
weapons of mass destruction in the Middle East, an area of
undeniable strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first post-Cold War decade, however, the
challenges posed by the Iraqi and Serbian leaders appear remarkably
similar, at least in this: Both have become tactical experts at
cornering the world's only superpower, frustrating its diplomatic
strategists, tying down its military and periodically daring the
United States to use force to get its way. Each has laid bare the
lack of a Western strategy to deal with dictators who, simply by
continuing in power, further weaken the ability of their peoples to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Milosevic and Saddam seem almost to have been playing
tag team with the United States and its allies. A look back at the
1990s reveals some startling similarities in the ways they operate,
and in the ways the West seems to have missed opportunities to
weaken each of them.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders are skilled autocrats, easily able to exploit the
inevitable differences that crop up in the coalitions, alliances or
international organizations that have tried to rein them in. When
it's convenient, each can count on support from Russia or China. At
home, each is adept at manipulating power and at turning foreign
embargoes, threats or bombing to his own advantage: Who, after all,
would publicly oppose a leader who paints himself as defender of a
victimized nation under foreign attack?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional seeming defeat inflicted from outside,
and the suffering of people in economies squeezed by embargoes and
by the control of these leaders and their cliques, neither man
seems in danger of being dislodged.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as that spring of 1991, before the old Yugoslavia
descended into war, demonstrators in Belgrade picked up on the
similarities, chanting ``Slobo-Saddam!'' to demonize their leader.
With the instinct born of the direct experience of repression, they
sensed that both men were master players of high-stakes poker,
prepared to use violence and even to gamble their very countries to
preserve their own power.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson that the West, however, appears to have spent
little time understanding: that the key to the survival of
Milosevic and Saddam has been their intimate acquaintance with the
yearnings and frailties of their people (Milosevic has even won
several flawed but not entirely unfair elections).
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who is now president of what is left of Yugoslavia,
has retained power largely by stirring up crisis after crisis, then
uniting Serbs behind his alleged defense of their interests.
Long-term success is not required for his own survival _ he has,
for instance, lost the territories he mobilized Serbs to seize in
Croatia and Bosnia _ so long as the attention of his weary people
can be channeled elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with NATO threatening to bomb Serbia if Milosevic does
not allow the alliance to police his restive province of Kosovo, he
appears secure. Indeed, he retains the power to ignite a far
bloodier war in Kosovo and beyond, a power that commands the West's
attention. He can survive in his self-cast role as his people's
champion against the hostile, powerful outside world.
</P>
<P>
   So too Saddam. Saddam has lost some formal control over Iraq.
Foreign inspectors have probed his arsenals. The CIA has reportedly
tried to muster resistance inside Iraq. For more than two months,
foreign jets have regularly bombed targets inside the northern and
southern reaches of the country.
</P>
<P>
   These regions are home to the Kurdish minority and the Shiite
Muslim majority who oppose Saddam's Sunni Muslim minority, which
has traditionally ruled Iraq. Yet Saddam, whose security apparatus
is far larger and more ruthless than that of Milosevic, also seems
in no obvious danger of losing control. He retains large oil
reserves, and perhaps even an ability to build weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam, whose image entirely dominates public life in Iraq,
brooks so little opposition that dissent can be openly voiced only
abroad. America has been slow to engage the admittedly murky and
bitterly divided opposition groups. Belated attempts to do so have
yielded a new radio station, Radio Free Iraq, and a $97 million
Iraqi Liberation Act that so far has dispensed none of the materiel
it pledged to make available to opposition groups. Of the
opposition groups targeted to receive support, at least one
announced from its Tehran headquarters that it had no interest in
Washington's backing.
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, a number of parties that are now arrayed against
Milosevic sprang up largely as he was assuming power in the late
1980s. He has proven skilled at infiltration and at buying off
these rivals. The opposition is now so feckless that even its
members say they have little hope. Students or independent media
that do challenge Milosevic are weak and immediately feel a
repressive hand if they start to make an impact. They also lack any
significant foreign backing.
</P>
<P>
   Individual diplomats and outside groups have tried to support
what Warren Zimmermann, the last U.S. ambassador to Yugoslavia, has
called ``the other Serbia.'' But during mass demonstrations against
Milosevic that erupted in the winter of 1996, many Serbian students
wondered why the rest of Europe was ignoring their movement. It
was, they felt, as if they were being demonized along with their
leader. The few foreign envoys who do come to Serbia see Milosevic
and pay any others scant heed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of U.S. diplomacy say that by ignoring Serbs and Iraqis
who oppose Milosevic and Saddam the West has missed a chance to
advance democracy in the Balkans, where the Serbs traditionally
have played a vanguard role, and in the Middle East, where Iraq's
middle class was once among the most enlightened and educated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, unwittingly, Western policy has helped smash that
vibrant middle class in both countries. Official media drive home
the siege mentality, playing on the threat from outside to squelch
dissent. Tough sanctions have fostered rampant corruption, which
gnaws ever deeper into the moral fiber of societies weakened by
wars the leaders helped to launch.
</P>
<P>
   Emigration has added to the ruin. In both countries, a new
merchant class has sprung up, owing its wealth to smuggling. To ply
their illicit trade, these people must make at least a tacit pact
with their governments and are thus a crucial source of support for
Saddam and Milosevic. They help convey an illusion that the two
countries are still part of the modern world; despite the United
Nations' embargo, almost any consumer wares are available in
Baghdad, as they were in Belgrade when it was under sanctions from
1992 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In the Iraqi countryside, the government reportedly gives seed,
land or machinery to traditionally respected rural leaders, who in
turn help ensure obedience. In rural Serbia, the source of most of
Milosevic's votes in elections, the leader and his Socialist Party
can use structures inherited from the old league of communists to
exercise similar control.
</P>
<P>
   Can anything now be done to turn the tide in Serbia, or Iraq? In
both countries, hopeful Clinton administration officials suggest
that the demise of Saddam and Milosevic is closer than either may
believe. If NATO does bomb Serbia, the Yugoslav army might turn
away from Milosevic. But even if he is then forced to accept NATO's
soldiers in Kosovo, he will remain in control of most of Serbia,
with all of its new resentments of the West. High-ranking foreign
visitors could invest in a different future by visiting Milosevic's
critics, as was routinely done, say, in Moscow under the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   Neither country will change overnight. One journalist who has
lived in Belgrade all her life recently wrote to a friend about a
change she had seen in the last decade in how Serbs treat each
other. A woman tending flowers in a park had hurled an ax at the
journalist's dog, she wrote. Even after Milosevic goes, she
concluded, ``we will be left with all those semihumans'' that the
recent past has created.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SADDAM-MILOSEVIC-RE     03-22 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SADDAM-MILOSEVIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DIFFERENT TYRANTS, VERY MUCH THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review) 
(bl)  
 By ALISON SMALE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the West's halcyon days, spring 1991, when Saddam
Hussein had just been vanquished in the gulf war and Eastern Europe
had apparently jettisoned communism for good, few Americans had
even heard of the Serbian leader, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was cultivating ethnic hatreds and threatening war,
but in a seemingly isolated corner of Europe known to few outsiders
and apparently of little concern to Washington. The Iraqi leader,
by contrast, had invaded a neighboring country and lobbed missiles
at Israel, and was found to have a scary near-ability to launch
weapons of mass destruction in the Middle East, an area of
undeniable strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first post-Cold War decade, however, the
challenges posed by the Iraqi and Serbian leaders appear remarkably
similar, at least in this: Both have become tactical experts at
cornering the world's only superpower, frustrating its diplomatic
strategists, tying down its military and periodically daring the
United States to use force to get its way. Each has laid bare the
lack of a Western strategy to deal with dictators who, simply by
continuing in power, further weaken the ability of their peoples to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Milosevic and Saddam seem almost to have been playing
tag team with the United States and its allies. A look back at the
1990s reveals some startling similarities in the ways they operate,
and in the ways the West seems to have missed opportunities to
weaken each of them.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders are skilled autocrats, easily able to exploit the
inevitable differences that crop up in the coalitions, alliances or
international organizations that have tried to rein them in. When
it's convenient, each can count on support from Russia or China. At
home, each is adept at manipulating power and at turning foreign
embargoes, threats or bombing to his own advantage: Who, after all,
would publicly oppose a leader who paints himself as defender of a
victimized nation under foreign attack?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional seeming defeat inflicted from outside,
and the suffering of people in economies squeezed by embargoes and
by the control of these leaders and their cliques, neither man
seems in danger of being dislodged.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as that spring of 1991, before the old Yugoslavia
descended into war, demonstrators in Belgrade picked up on the
similarities, chanting ``Slobo-Saddam!'' to demonize their leader.
With the instinct born of the direct experience of repression, they
sensed that both men were master players of high-stakes poker,
prepared to use violence and even to gamble their very countries to
preserve their own power.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson that the West, however, appears to have spent
little time understanding: that the key to the survival of
Milosevic and Saddam has been their intimate acquaintance with the
yearnings and frailties of their people (Milosevic has even won
several flawed but not entirely unfair elections).
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who is now president of what is left of Yugoslavia,
has retained power largely by stirring up crisis after crisis, then
uniting Serbs behind his alleged defense of their interests.
Long-term success is not required for his own survival _ he has,
for instance, lost the territories he mobilized Serbs to seize in
Croatia and Bosnia _ so long as the attention of his weary people
can be channeled elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with NATO threatening to bomb Serbia if Milosevic does
not allow the alliance to police his restive province of Kosovo, he
appears secure. Indeed, he retains the power to ignite a far
bloodier war in Kosovo and beyond, a power that commands the West's
attention. He can survive in his self-cast role as his people's
champion against the hostile, powerful outside world.
</P>
<P>
   So too Saddam. Saddam has lost some formal control over Iraq.
Foreign inspectors have probed his arsenals. The CIA has reportedly
tried to muster resistance inside Iraq. For more than two months,
foreign jets have regularly bombed targets inside the northern and
southern reaches of the country.
</P>
<P>
   These regions are home to the Kurdish minority and the Shiite
Muslim majority who oppose Saddam's Sunni Muslim minority, which
has traditionally ruled Iraq. Yet Saddam, whose security apparatus
is far larger and more ruthless than that of Milosevic, also seems
in no obvious danger of losing control. He retains large oil
reserves, and perhaps even an ability to build weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam, whose image entirely dominates public life in Iraq,
brooks so little opposition that dissent can be openly voiced only
abroad. America has been slow to engage the admittedly murky and
bitterly divided opposition groups. Belated attempts to do so have
yielded a new radio station, Radio Free Iraq, and a $97 million
Iraqi Liberation Act that so far has dispensed none of the materiel
it pledged to make available to opposition groups. Of the
opposition groups targeted to receive support, at least one
announced from its Tehran headquarters that it had no interest in
Washington's backing.
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, a number of parties that are now arrayed against
Milosevic sprang up largely as he was assuming power in the late
1980s. He has proven skilled at infiltration and at buying off
these rivals. The opposition is now so feckless that even its
members say they have little hope. Students or independent media
that do challenge Milosevic are weak and immediately feel a
repressive hand if they start to make an impact. They also lack any
significant foreign backing.
</P>
<P>
   Individual diplomats and outside groups have tried to support
what Warren Zimmermann, the last U.S. ambassador to Yugoslavia, has
called ``the other Serbia.'' But during mass demonstrations against
Milosevic that erupted in the winter of 1996, many Serbian students
wondered why the rest of Europe was ignoring their movement. It
was, they felt, as if they were being demonized along with their
leader. The few foreign envoys who do come to Serbia see Milosevic
and pay any others scant heed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of U.S. diplomacy say that by ignoring Serbs and Iraqis
who oppose Milosevic and Saddam the West has missed a chance to
advance democracy in the Balkans, where the Serbs traditionally
have played a vanguard role, and in the Middle East, where Iraq's
middle class was once among the most enlightened and educated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, unwittingly, Western policy has helped smash that
vibrant middle class in both countries. Official media drive home
the siege mentality, playing on the threat from outside to squelch
dissent. Tough sanctions have fostered rampant corruption, which
gnaws ever deeper into the moral fiber of societies weakened by
wars the leaders helped to launch.
</P>
<P>
   Emigration has added to the ruin. In both countries, a new
merchant class has sprung up, owing its wealth to smuggling. To ply
their illicit trade, these people must make at least a tacit pact
with their governments and are thus a crucial source of support for
Saddam and Milosevic. They help convey an illusion that the two
countries are still part of the modern world; despite the United
Nations' embargo, almost any consumer wares are available in
Baghdad, as they were in Belgrade when it was under sanctions from
1992 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In the Iraqi countryside, the government reportedly gives seed,
land or machinery to traditionally respected rural leaders, who in
turn help ensure obedience. In rural Serbia, the source of most of
Milosevic's votes in elections, the leader and his Socialist Party
can use structures inherited from the old league of communists to
exercise similar control.
</P>
<P>
   Can anything now be done to turn the tide in Serbia, or Iraq? In
both countries, hopeful Clinton administration officials suggest
that the demise of Saddam and Milosevic is closer than either may
believe. If NATO does bomb Serbia, the Yugoslav army might turn
away from Milosevic. But even if he is then forced to accept NATO's
soldiers in Kosovo, he will remain in control of most of Serbia,
with all of its new resentments of the West. High-ranking foreign
visitors could invest in a different future by visiting Milosevic's
critics, as was routinely done, say, in Moscow under the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   Neither country will change overnight. One journalist who has
lived in Belgrade all her life recently wrote to a friend about a
change she had seen in the last decade in how Serbs treat each
other. A woman tending flowers in a park had hurled an ax at the
journalist's dog, she wrote. Even after Milosevic goes, she
concluded, ``we will be left with all those semihumans'' that the
recent past has created.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
