<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9209 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SEX-MANUAL-TEXT-REV     03-22 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SEX-MANUAL-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU EVER WANTED TO KNOW ABOUT CHANGING WITH THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (editors: in the book title, an asterisk should immediately follow
the word `Sex' and immediately precede the word `But'; in the
abbreviation EYAWTKAS BWATA, an asterisk should immediately follow
the `S' and immediately precede the `B'.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1969, the California psychiatrist Dr. David Reuben published
a groundbreaking book with the improbable title ``Everything You
Always Wanted to Know About Sex But Were Afraid to Ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering hundreds of blush-inducing questions about the most
basic of human relations (``What does impotence mean?'' ``What
happens during orgasm?''), it was a blockbuster primer for those
confronted by the polymorphous excesses of the Age of Aquarius.
Reuben was touted as ``the new apostle of sanity in sex'' and his
carnal Baedeker became a No. 1 best seller in 51 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, we live in a culture of AIDS, Viagra and
presidential oral sex discussed publicly in Congress. So on
Valentine's Day, HarperCollins released an updated edition of
Reuben's magnum opus (hereinafter referred to by its catchy
acronym, EYAWTKAS BWATA). The work is far from 99 44/100 percent
pure, but it is being billed as ``96.9 percent new.''
</P>
<P>
   Some idea of the revisions that Reuben has wrought in his pages,
and in his thinking, can be gleaned even by comparing some of the
tamer bits of his book's two editions (below). Not the least of the
eye-popping changes is the one in price, from $6.95 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   _ By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)In the original ``EYAWTKAS BWATA,'' Reuben
anticipated Dr. Ruth Westheimer's exhortation to ``Have good sex!''
by a dozen years:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The average person has not even begun to experience the range of
sexual gratification of which he is capable. Or as one patient
jokingly put it, ``Sexually, the surface hasn't even been scratched
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of this book is to tell the reader what he wants to
know and what he needs to know to achieve the greatest possible
degree of sexual satisfaction. It is designed to answer questions
that have never been answered except in obscure medical books.
</P>
<P>
   (END ITALICS HERE)Thirty years later, Reuben has added this
disclaimer:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   PLEASE READ THIS!
</P>
<P>
   I am confident that you already know this but I would like to
emphasize it again.
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING IN THIS BOOK IS MEDICAL ADVICE.
</P>
<P>
   It is educational and informative. I hope it will encourage you
to discuss any medical problem you might have with your trusted
personal physician. ... Since I can't see you or examine you
through the pages of this book, I couldn't begin to give you the
tiniest bit of medical diagnosis, advice or treatment. ...
</P>
<P>
   Don't try anything in this book without getting the advice of a
doctor you know and trust. Neither I nor my publisher assume any
responsibility for anything that may result from your failure to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)When ``EYAWTKAS BWATA'' was first published,
the Roe vs. Wade decision legalizing abortion was four years in the
future. Reuben graphically described the dangers of back-alley or
self-inflicted abortions that many women saw as their only
recourse:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there a way to prevent all this terrible suffering?
</P>
<P>
   There should be. ... Because the guardians of public morals, few
of whom have ever been pregnant themselves, have decreed that
abortion is a sin, millions of women each year are sentenced to
terrible danger, crippling illness and financial ruin, and the
bungling, incompetent butchers are able to ply their trade. ... In
an era when man is transplanting organs, exploring distant planets,
and manipulating living molecular structures, it is incredible that
he is not allowed to control his own reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Yet 30 years later, with Roe vs. Wade a fact
of life, Reuben isn't exactly ecstatic over safer, more readily
available abortions:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``You sound like you're against it?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not against it and I'm not for it. Abortion is not something
that anyone takes lightly. Ask any woman who has had one. And ask
the doctors who have done them. It's a procedure that takes a
certain emotional toll on everyone involved, and it's really a
method of last resort. ... One of the most common complications of
abortion is depression and serious emotional problems in the woman
who is operated on. That's compounding the already physical stress
of the operation. A woman who faces _ right from the start _ the
harsh facts of abortion has a much better chance of coming through
it emotionally intact. An abortion usually takes an hour or so. But
the mental suffering can go on for years.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Perhaps no part of the original ``EYAWTKAS
BWATA'' was as controversial as Chapter 8, ``Male Homosexuality.''
With pronouncements like ``The majority of gay guys, when they
cruise, dispense with the courtship'' and ``Homosexuals thrive on
danger,'' it depicted homosexual life as unrelievedly bleak and
impersonal:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``But all homosexuals aren't like that, are they?''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they are just like that. One of the main features
of homosexuality is promiscuity. It stands to reason. Homosexuals
are trying the impossible: solving the problem with only half the
pieces. They say they want gratification and love but they
eliminate, right from the start, the most obvious source of love
and gratification _ woman.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)In 1999, Reuben eschews such
characterizations. The word ``male'' is gone from the chapter
title. And he starts by observing:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuality isn't what it used to be. Years ago it was simply
a set of Sexual Practices. Now it is tied in with human rights,
civil rights, political correctness, job rights, freedom of
expression, military service, sexual harassment and a lot of other
things. ... You may believe that homosexuality is good or you may
believe that it is bad. But as a physician and a scientist, I
cannot pass that kind of personal judgment. Therefore nothing in
this chapter should be _ or can be _ interpreted as being against
or in favor of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Pornography was originally broached in
Chapter 10, ``Sexual Perversion'':(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't pornography harmful?''
</P>
<P>
   It is very difficult to see how. Pornography simply represents
people as they really are, sexual organs and all. They are shown
doing what they really do: using these organs. Everybody has
genitals and everyone uses them, one way or another.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)In ``EYAWTKAS BWATA'' '99, the subject has
been moved to Chapter 5, ``Aphrodisiacs.'' The value-neutral term
``sexography'' is substituted for ``pornography,'' which now has
specific, negative connotations:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean you are in favor of pornography?''
</P>
<P>
   No. Personally, I hate pornography. ... ``Pornography'' isn't
men and women in all their charm and beauty _ either alone or
sharing the magic of sex with each other. Pornography is sickness.
... It's images of the sexual abuse of children, of sex with
animals, of people degrading and abusing other people with sex as
the alibi.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The original ``Sexual Perversion'' chapter
included descriptions of obscene phone calls:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   How do men make a fetish out of a voice?
</P>
<P>
   ... This is the usual pattern: Late in the evening, the
telephone rings. When the woman answers, there is a moment of
silence, followed by an obscene monologue. Typically this consists
of descriptions of sexual intercourse, promises to engage in sexual
relations with the recipient of the call (promises that are never
fulfilled), and sometimes recitations of obscene words. The woman
must react emotionally _ otherwise the caller is disappointed,
hangs up and calls someone else. Most women give him what he is
after _ not sex, but shouting.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)Today, with some forms of phone sex having
gained a measure of acceptance, Reuben skips the subject entirely.
He introduces the hitherto undiscussed problem of ``plushiephilia''
_ an unnatural attachment to stuffed animals. Of its practitioners,
he notes, ``You may love those cute little critters, but they
literally LOVE them'':(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   What do you mean, ``literally LOVE them''?
</P>
<P>
   ... Listen to what Arnold says. He is an insurance executive,
and vice president of a big agency. He is 46 and unmarried.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big bunny, Ginnie, is really my best friend. She's so warm
and huggable. I just love to feel her fur against my bare skin. She
never rejects me, and when I've had a hard day at the office, she's
there to console me and make me forget all my problems. It's just
pure happiness _ perfect love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0838EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 08:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4016 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-SEX-MANUAL-TEXT-REV     03-22 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SEX-MANUAL-TEXT-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING YOU EVER WANTED TO KNOW ABOUT CHANGING WITH THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
