<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-PORN-PALACE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKING THE HUSTLER SENSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 (ATTN: Calif., Nev., Ga.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Also see PORN-CULTURE and BRAND-DIVERSIFICATION-REVIEW, both for
Sunday release)  
 (bl)  
 By FRANCES ANDERTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ It's 11 o'clock on Friday night in a
brightly lighted store on the Sunset Strip. Men and women with
expressions ranging from nonchalance to embarrassment are perusing
the merchandise: saucy lingerie, edible body powders and, behind a
translucent partition bearing the words ``Relax, It's Just Sex,''
hardcore videos and sex toys. Elsewhere, customers are sipping
lattes and looking over shelves of best-selling books, newspapers
and sexually explicit magazines.
</P>
<P>
   This is Hustler Hollywood, a 9,000-square-foot up-market sex
emporium. With its floor-to-ceiling windows and coffee bar, it
unashamedly pitches erotica. Opened last December, it is the
flagship of what its owner, Larry Flynt, hopes will be a nationwide
Hustler chain. Its sleek design, prominently displayed aromatic
candles and Kama Sutra massage oils are intended to appeal to
women.
</P>
<P>
   The name and its raunchy connotations may be a marketing gamble,
but Flynt said he never considered any other. ``Hustler signifies a
certain something to people, and that is rebellion,'' he said.
``People identify with this type of rebellion and associate the
same thing with the store, so it becomes sort of taboo or forbidden
fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   And that forbidden fruit is brazenly marketed, from the vivid
red neon sign outside to Hustler mugs, Larry Flynt T-shirts and
stacks of Flynt's autobiography. When he opened a more conventional
adult store called ``Hustler Magazine Books and Gifts'' in
Cincinnati two years ago, he said, a quarter of the customers were
women.
</P>
<P>
   In designing the West Hollywood store, he wanted to create an
atmosphere different from the typical sex store, he said, ``more
comfortable for women, more like Barnes &AMP; Noble or Neiman Marcus.''
</P>
<P>
   About half the customers on a recent Friday night were women.
``I like the unisex aspect of it all,'' said Caroline Gomez, a
college student. The store was ``really tasteful,'' she said,
``which makes the products look appealing.'' She said she was
attracted to the store because of its controversial owner.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Hustler can become the chain envisioned by Flynt is not
clear. During the course of its day, from 8 a.m. to 2 a.m., the
store fluctuates from bustling to nearly dead. Still, Flynt said he
plans to open stores in Las Vegas and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, ``I'm really very, very disappointed that I
didn't move into the retail business years ago, because I never
realized the marketing power of the Hustler name and logo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 0840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
