<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN23-C     03-22 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In deflating economy, it pays to think small
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've done a great job this year. Congratulations! Your raise
will be 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you are lucky. One percent, lucky? It is, if deflation sets
in.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 21st century, a new world where wages and prices
go down even as the economy booms. For the millions of baby boomers
who learned to cope with the brutal price hikes of the 1970s and
the low-grade, but constant, inflation of the 1980s and 1990s, this
new deflationary environment may take some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier generations who survived the Great Depression of the
1930s knew what it felt like to have prices fall. During that
miserable decade, workers were thrilled if their wages merely held
steady. Throughout their lives, those Depression-influenced
Americans tended to pinch pennies and avoid debt.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic outlook of post-World War II generations was
shaped by the raging inflation of the 1970s and early 1980s, when
consumer prices were shooting up as much as 13 percent a year.
``Buy Now'' was a motto that made sense to consumers who feared the
price would only be higher later. Baby boomers typically tried to
buy the biggest house possible because they knew inflation would
increase the value of their property and diminish the relative
weight of the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Though Americans have spent decades complaining about inflation,
the truth is, inflation can be fun. It can justify the urge to
splurge at the mall or to remodel the kitchen. Business owners get
to report record increases in sales year after year. And workers
can feel proud of their annual raises.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation suits our national character. It means that next year,
everything will be bigger _ sales, profits, wages and real estate
prices. And in this country, bigger always seems better.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, many prices have been falling. The
government says that last year, the Consumer Price Index increased
only 1.6 percent. That figure probably will decline in the coming
year as products ranging from pork roasts to computer monitors get
cheaper. In February, wholesale prices fell 0.4 percent from last
year, according to the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   And now, manufacturers are predicting another round of
price-cutting. Last week, the National Association of Manufacturers
reported that 44.2 percent of 2,500 companies polled said the
prices of their final products are dropping. As a result, 43.2
percent of those polled expect growth of earnings to decrease.
</P>
<P>
   Why are prices falling? Because of greater productivity and
increasing global competition. Take clothing as an example. Instead
of going to a tailor for a handmade suit, today's consumers go to
huge retailers who can buy suits made with computerized equipment
and cheap, foreign labor. Better equipment, more competition and
bigger economies of scale will continue to bat down prices for
goods and foods.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, consumers will love these changes, which will
allow us to buy better-quality goods at lower prices. But how will
we feel when our home's value slides? Will investors remain as
enthusiastic about buying stocks when flat earnings are considered
good news? Will workers feel as confident about the future when
they go for years without a raise?
</P>
<P>
   With deflation, we'll have to remember that smaller profits,
declining homes prices and stagnant wages aren't signs of hard
times. Just very different times.
</P>
<P>
   This is a weekly report by Atlanta Constitution editorial writer
Marilyn Geewax on issues raised by the coming of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Y2K, visit these Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ millennium(at)whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.everything2000.com
</P>
<P>
   _ http://www.igc.org/millennium/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
