A9279 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN23-     03-22 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jobs prove to be big anti-crime solution
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even in these times of high employment, with many
companies scrambling for workers, some people find it next to
impossible to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   In a metro area where the unemployment rate is less than 3
percent, and where even the convenience stores are bidding for
services, there are people who cannot get a job application.
</P>
<P>
   They include ex-convicts, older job applicants, certain disabled
people who have physical or mental problems, and young black males.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of those we euphemistically call ex-offenders, we
have a growing legion of people who have broken the law and face
tougher sentences for their wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But even as that group grows, many people who come out of
incarceration will not find the means to support themselves
legally.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rules of probation require them to find jobs or
make a persuasive case they are either in school or actively
pursuing work.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuant to a new federal law called the Workforce Investment
Act of 1998, Georgia and the other states are assigned a new role _
to oversee new ways to employ or train people formerly imprisoned
or who have other problems that keep them out of the ordinary job
market.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Thurmond, the state labor commissioner, is in charge of
putting together the Georgia program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to make the program local, and to make it deal
with the actual needs of Georgia companies and the actual training
programs that we have available here,'' said Thurmond, previously
in charge of programs in human resources to put welfare recipients
to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important aspects of this program will be its
convenience, the fact that the job seeker can come to one place and
hear about employment opportunities and training in the same
place,'' Thurmond added.
</P>
<P>
   Where ex-prisoners are concerned, the obstacles are formidable,
and any help could be a step forward.
</P>
<P>
   A memorable piece in The Wall Street Journal on Feb. 19
chronicled a Korean Athletes Foot store owner in Chicago who hired
gang members and ex-offenders as his sales staff.
</P>
<P>
   As the story made plain, the business was helped by the fact the
sales people were talented and very much in touch with young, often
street-savvy customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationship between the store owner and his staff was
intense, demanding and often troubled.
</P>
<P>
   It was also taxing on the ex-offenders, who had to deal with
huge measures of distrust and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, however, was that work helped people get back
on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my favorite statistical stories is that for young men
white and black, the crime rate is the same regardless of race, but
for jobless blacks the crime rate is astronomically higher,'' said
Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   Parole officials say self-reported figures show unemployment for
people on their way to prison is about 65 percent, and for
ex-offenders in the parole system, it is 90 percent and more.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is elementary. In one way of thinking, jobs are a
powerful crime prevention program.
</P>
<P>
   It can work if agencies and businesses are more savvy in looking
for ways to create employment, instead of finding excuses for not
putting people to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to take a new outlook and new skills for staff
people in the state government,'' said Thurmond, ``including a
willingness to look for potential in people, and help sell them to
industry as suitable employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
