<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9280 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN23-COX     03-22 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A place to hang your troubles
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``I had a terrible day,'' a friend moaned to me.
</P>
<P>
   She then recited a litany of miserable mishaps and misadventures
that certainly justified her assessment. Any one of us could have
recalled a similar day from our own lives. I shook my head in
sympathy, but what she said next totally surprised me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided on the way home from work I could recount my lousy
day to my family and make all of us have a rotten evening,'' she
said, ``or I could let it go, not think about it, and enjoy that
time with the people I love.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what she did. They had a lovely dinner together and
then went out to a bookstore to browse contentedly.
</P>
<P>
   We have all heard the advice to leave our job at the office and
not take it home with us. As with all good advice, it's much easier
to say than do.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles we deal with from 8 to 5 are a significant part of
our lives, and whether we leave them at work or not, they have a
way of still being there the next morning when we unlock the office
door. Although they are a signficant part of our lives, they are
not the most important part of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   I have often wondered as our family sits around the dinner table
and we ask abour our sons' days, why they never ask about ours.
They seem to assume their days are worthy of notice, but that our
days are not. That's probably just normal teen-age self-absorption,
but it reminds me that as adults, we shouldn't have that same
self-absorption. In other words, leave it at work.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they don't ask because when they have, we've told them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there's much in any person's day that is worth sharing. No
one can go through a day without some redeeming or uplifting
moment. Whether you note and remember it is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   One recent morning as my husband and I sat reading the morning
paper, our youngest son tumbled out of bed, plopped on the couch
next to me and stretched hugely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahh,'' he smiled sleepily. ``It's going to be a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Curious, and wanting to believe likewise, I asked him how he
knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The birds are singing. I love waking up to hear the birds
singing,'' he said happily, going off to get his cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Those same birds had been singing 30 minutes earlier when I
tumbled out of bed. Had I heard them? Had I chosen to believe they
were a harbinger of good things to come?
</P>
<P>
   Recently, at the end of a very hard week at work, I saw a story
on the Internet that once again reminded me of an essential truth:
We cannot control what happens in our lives, but we can control how
we react to it.
</P>
<P>
   The story was about a carpenter who was hired to restore an old
farmhouse. On the carpenter's first day at work, everything went
wrong. At day's end, the carpenter sat in stony silence as the
farmhouse owner drove him home.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving, he watched the carpenter walk toward his front
door, pause briefly at a small tree and touch the tips of the
branches with both hands. When he opened the door, his countenance
underwent an amazing transformation. Smiles wreathed his face and
he hugged his two small children and gave his wife a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the carpenter walked the man back to his car. The
man asked him about the tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's my trouble tree,'' the carpenter said. ``I know I
can't help having troubles on the job, but one thing's for sure.
Troubles don't belong in the house with my wife and the children.
So I just hang them on the tree every night when I come home. Then
in the morning, I pick them up again.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused. ``Funny thing is,'' he smiled, ``when I come out in
the morning to pick 'em up, there ain't nearly as many as I
remember hanging up the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
