</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The distraction of boys
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ My eighth-graders are reading a novel about a
13-year-old boy who bumps into a dead body (literally) as he and
his best buddy are enjoying an unlawful midnight swim in the local
quarry. Decision time _ do the boys go to the police and report a
floater and get themselves into a peck of trouble with the law for
trespassing, as well as with their parents for not being safe in
bed where they're supposed to be?
</P>
<P>
   The boys make the obvious choice. They hightail it for home,
phone in an anonymous tip, and burrow under the blankets until the
stink blows off.
</P>
<P>
   My classes always enjoy this bit of fluff reading as a break
between Proficiency Tests and a particularly scintillating session
on dangling participles. (While walking up the stairs, the clock
struck midnight.) Being a schoolteacher, however, it is my duty to
spoil their fun with writing assignments designed to stimulate a
higher level of thought as so carefully measured on Mr.
Whatsisname's taxonomy of successful questioning (educanese for:
Don't ask dumb questions like, ``How many fireplugs did Spot visit
the day he followed Dick and Jane to school?'')
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the questions I asked were still too easy for
Rachel, one of my more accomplished young writers, because in
addition to composing a substantial essay on the psychological
difficulties of being 13, doing a water ballet with a stiff, and
waking up the next morning with a new zit (worst-case scenario),
she felt obliged to add the following conclusion:
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I have found this book to be quite entertaining. I
especially enjoy that it is written from the viewpoint of an
eighth-grade boy since I am also in the eighth grade and have
always wondered how boys my age think or what goes on in their
heads (or rather if anything at all is going on up there. I do
wonder because they are extremely capable of displaying the actions
of complete stupidity ... and then they still have their bad days
too.)''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, even though she has more than fulfilled the
assignment, the essayist obviously becomes enamored of the topic
switch and her writing takes on a life of its own: ``Boys get such
a kick out of the dumbest things _ like at lunch when they take
their Fruitopia cans and stuff them into styrofoam vegetable cups
and then slam their hands on them causing them to make a really
loud noise. Girls hate it but the guys think it is so cool. Boys
are seriously stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   About here, the writer apparently becomes aware of her
digression and tries to tie the loosely related addendum to the
topic. ``Because Tyler and Lymie (the main characters) think like
boys, they make all of the wrong choices. My ignorant little
brother did the same thing when he created a relief map of
Australia on a piece of wood he found in the basement. It was a
social studies project and on the day he was supposed to take it to
school, he asked my dad for help getting it to the car. That's when
Dad discovered what my stupid brother had been doing down there. He
had built mountains and painted oceans on our new front door. My
dad was waiting for a warm day to put it up. It was a very
expensive door because it was an anniversary present for my mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hoping they'd kill the kid, but no such luck. He
just has to spend the entire summer working on the farm for two
dollars an hour until the door is paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Rachel earns an A, not only for the weight of her
content but the precision of her mechanics. And there's an
ingenuous P.S. addressed to me: ``Ms. Schuett, do they ever get any
better?''
</P>
<P>
   Intending to inspire, I scribble in the margin, ``They grow
up.''
</P>
<P>
   I should have known better. First period, Rachel bopped in with
a story she'd ripped out of this morning's paper. An inmate in the
county jail had attempted suicide by wrapping one end of a bed
sheet around his neck, tying a knot in the other end, and trying to
flush it down the toilet. Luckily a guard caught him before they
had to send for the Roto-Rooter man.
</P>
<P>
   Circled in red marker was the prisoner's age (20). In the
margin, Rachel had carefully printed: ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
Mail to 320 W. Madison, Gibsonburg, OH or email
eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
