<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-HANDHELD23-COX     03-22 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-HANDHELD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The war of the handheld computers
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   First came the Newton, a hand-held computer which was shaped
like a brick and weighed like one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Apple's Newton never took off, and neither did
the market for hand-held computers. It took a light, pocket-sized
competitor called the PalmPilot to ignite popular interest.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot has sold nearly 3 million units, and its success
awakened the giant in Redmond, Wash., known as Microsoft.
Microsoft's entry into the market has spawned scores of new
hand-held computers, powered by a light version of its Windows
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are plenty of models, and they come in all sizes,
colors and configurations. But don't be fooled. There's less
variety than meets the eye. Most hand-held computers are pretty
much alike. They track appointments, keep telephone numbers and let
you take notes. A growing number of hand-helds also let you send
and receive e-mail or browse the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The more-powerful models, which are also larger and heavier,
also let you write memos and create spreadsheets. Hand-helds range
in price from $199 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-held market has become a smaller version of the one for
desktop and notebook computers. There are really only two choices:
hand-helds running Windows and the three PalmPilot models, which
use a unique operating system and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds familiar, right? It's Microsoft leading a pack of clones
challenged by one upstart. There is, however, a key difference.
PalmPilot's parent, 3Com, has learned from Apple's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, 3Com designed its PalmPilots to work smoothly with
Windows-driven computers. It released the Palm OS, or operating
system, to all comers, generating a large choice of software for
users. There are some 3,000 titles to choose from today.
</P>
<P>
   In short, PalmPilot has clung to the underbelly of Microsoft
like a remora to a shark. The PalmPilot has fed off Windows'
success but avoided the powerful jaws of its host. At least so far.
</P>
<P>
   While largely similar, PalmPilot and Windows hand-held computers
do have some important differences. The biggest, of course, is the
operating system. That software controls the workings of any
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Most hand-held models now run Windows CE, a slimmed-down version
of the Windows operating system running on 90 percent of all
computers. You'll recognize the familiar Start button on the bottom
screen of any hand-held running Windows CE.
</P>
<P>
   The use of Windows lets hand-helds run slimmer versions of
Microsoft's other ubiquitous software such as Word and Excel.
PalmPilot models cannot run Word or Excel, although there are other
software programs designed for them that perform the same word
processing and spreadsheet functions.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some hardware distinctions between Windows and
Palm hand-helds. Some of the Windows hand-helds, for example, let
you record simple voice messages. Philips' Nino is one example.
</P>
<P>
   And other, bigger models of Windows hand-helds include small
keyboards so you can write memos and crunch numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Windows CE hand-helds, such as the Nino, let you
record a simple message. Others, such as models by Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard, let you write memos and create spreadsheets with
scaled-down versions of Microsoft Word and Excel. Your work can
then be seamlessly shipped onto a desktop or portable computer for
use.
</P>
<P>
   This, Microsoft executives argue, is the key advantage of
hand-held computers running their software. ``You're going Windows
to Windows,'' says Marty Paradise, general manager of Microsoft's
Atlanta-based Southeast District office. ``It's a seamless
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, adds Paradise, there'll be more and better software
for hand-helds running Windows CE because of the millions of
developers already writing for the Windows platform.
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot executives, of course, dismiss this advantage. ``It
turns out that what's really important isn't matching operating
systems, but fast, error-free seamless synchronization,'' says E.
Michael Lunsford, a Palm senior product manager.
</P>
<P>
   And, so far, the market for hand-helds has not given the
advantage to hand-helds running Windows. There are three PalmPilots
in circulation for every one Windows CE counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been successful because we built, from the ground up, a
simple, straightforward, intuitive interface with an operating
system designed for the hand-held space,'' says Lunsford.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's early in the game. Especially for Microsoft,
which tends to gather steam in releasing better and more powerful
versions of its products over time.
</P>
<P>
   A simple test drive of a PalmPilot and a Philips Nino running
Windows shows the strengths and weaknesses of each platform.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot is clearly simpler and more portable. You can run
it without ever reading a manual. But the PalmPilot is not as
powerful as a Windows hand-held. These machines can do many more
things. But with power comes complexity. You definitely need to
read the manual with a Windows hand-held, especially if you're used
to a Mac.
</P>
<P>
   WINDOWS CE
</P>
<P>
   _ Runs Windows platform
</P>
<P>
   _ Runs Word and Excel
</P>
<P>
   _ Limited voice recording
</P>
<P>
   _ OS more complicated than
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot's
</P>
<P>
   _ A dozen-plus models (Philips' Nino, shown right, $300)
</P>
<P>
   _ Performs more complex
</P>
<P>
   tasks, such as memo writing
</P>
<P>
   PALM PILOT
</P>
<P>
   _ Runs Palm operating
</P>
<P>
   system
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't run Word or
</P>
<P>
   Excel
</P>
<P>
   _ No voice recording
</P>
<P>
   _ OS easy to use
</P>
<P>
   _ Three models, priced
</P>
<P>
   from $249 to $429
</P>
<P>
   _ Strong basic functions
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of handheld computers
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot IIIx $349
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot V $429
</P>
<P>
   Nino $300
</P>
<P>
   HP 620LX $649
</P>
<P>
   HP 660LX $749
</P>
<P>
   Source: Microwarehouse
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
