<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-TOOLS23-COX     03-22 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eyes of the Nation a superb look at history
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new CD-ROM from SouthPeak International called ``The Library
of Congress: Eyes of the Nation'' is a splendid reminder that the
Smithsonian Institution is not this nation's only repository of
historical documents and artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Made up entirely of material from the library, and put together
largely by curators and experts, it is a multifaceted and
compelling look at the history of the United States, from the
continent's discovery to the present decade.
</P>
<P>
   It is divided into five main sections, beginning with an
introductory look at the library's special collections, which is
essentially everything not available to anyone who just drops in at
the library. The main experience is called Eyes of the Nation,
which is a fairly long study of U.S. history written by historian
Alan Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   The American Experience breaks down history by topics:
entertainment, exploration and settlement, the African-American
experience, the Native American experience, the American woman,
arts, entertainment, government, war, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress exhibits document five special exhibits on
such narrow topics as British satirical images of the American
Revolution and Rosie the Riveter.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth section is called Gateways to American Memory, and
features essays on four of the most significant graphic periods of
American history: daguerreotypes, the craze for hand-drawn,
bird's-eye-view maps of cities, the work of the Farm Security
Administration photographers and the collection of Detroit
Publishing Co. The latter was one of the biggest postcard
publishers in the nation, and judging from the images displayed
here, its archives are truly a treasure.
</P>
<P>
   All of these sections, with the exception of the American
Experience, are narrated very professionally, with appropriate
background music. The narrations are very interesting and not very
long, and when they have concluded the viewer can browse through
the images at will.
</P>
<P>
   The images, incidentally, are not limited to photographs. There
are fantastic antique maps, paintings, sketches and prints, sheet
music, posters, cartoons, and documents. Each can be enlarged to
nearly full screen; some of the more interesting ones can be
enlarged in a zoom mode through which the viewer can manipulate a
box around the screen to see greater enlargement of sections.
</P>
<P>
   All images can be printed out. There is a built-in notepad, and
a means of putting together a portfolio and making a slide show.
Additionally, the whole CD is indexed. There are World Wide Web
hooks to more library information on nearly every general topic
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes of a Nation is the best-designed educational CD-ROM I've
encountered. Navigating through the disc is entirely intuitive and
smooth as silk.
</P>
<P>
   The CD offers a unique perspective on history, but more than
that, I believe, it reminds us of the splendor of the Library of
Congress, the world's largest library.
</P>
<P>
   It will make you want to camp on the library's doorstep and
spend every waking minute inside.
</P>
<P>
   While its $40 list price is a bit on the high side, I can find
only one problem with Eyes of the Nation. It's not long enough. One
can only hope for a DVD version.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
