<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9297 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCHER23-COX     03-22 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCHER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETWATCHER: MP3 sites are way cool, but don't tell anybody
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's 2 o'clock in the morning. Armed with two 20-ounce
bottles of Diet Coke and a bag of Doritos, I am ready to surf the
Web. I'm not looking for portals, the closing figure of the Hong
Kong stock exchange or a new pair of jeans. I'm not looking for a
community, local news or a way to make my busy life more
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   I'm looking for MP3 files, free music I can download and play on
my computer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, downloading MP3 files, uploading MP3 files and pretty much
doing anything with MP3 files is illegal. Maybe that's why I'm
doing it at 2 in the morning. I won't even park my car illegally,
even if it's only to run into Starbucks for a tall latte. So, I
feel vaguely guilty doing this, half expecting Joe Friday to bust
into my den flashing a badge, read me my rights and confiscate my
hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not advocating anyone else do it, either. But
downloading MP3 files is a big trend now, especially among
students. I tried it myself to see what all the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 stands for motion-picture-experts group, Audio Level 3,
which probably explains why they shortened it to a few letters. MP3
technology is a compact way to store CD-quality music and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   What it really means is music. All kinds of music, from Madonna
to your friendly garage band playing nightly at the local bar.
</P>
<P>
   If you have the time and the right tools, you too can have the
keys to the Web's musical candy store. If you really want to get
into it, check out MP3.com (http://www.mp3.com), which offers a
beginner's guide, including what's needed to play MP3 files, a
frequently asked questions list and a few files to get you started.
</P>
<P>
   The idea ordinary folks can download music from any of the
zillion MP3 sites on the Web has the recording industry in a tizzy
trying to figure out how to make money from the estimated 10
million to 15 million people downloading music to MP3 players.
(After sex sites, the most popular sites on the Web are MP3 sites
offering downloadable files.)
</P>
<P>
   Dean Kay, president and CEO of Lichelle Music Co. and
co-chairman of music publisher ASCAP's New Technologies Committee,
calls the Web's MP3 craze a counterculture phenomenon. He says the
majority of MP3 junkies are college kids using the extensive
resources of their university computing centers to trade music with
fellow music lovers and Web geeks worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3 is about rebellion,'' Kay says. ``There's a subversive
nature to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites like Lycos, SavvySearch (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .savvysearch.com) and who knows how many others offer search
engines that will help you find which MP3 files are located on
which Web sites. Users of some versions of Netscape's browser can
tap the What's Related button on the far right of the toolbar to
find even more MP3 sites.
</P>
<P>
   A simple search for Rock and Roll Hall of Famer Bruce
Springsteen came up with seven pages of MP3 files, including rare
and bootleg tracks Springsteen fans are constantly searching for.
</P>
<P>
   You really don't need to be a rocket scientist to figure out the
recording industry is not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are like Rykodisc (http://www.rykodisc
</P>
<P>
   .com), which lets you download MP3 files for 99 cents a pop. But
the majority of music is still free _ until the record companies or
someone else catches up with the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Kay says many MP3 sites don't stay up long because the Recording
Industry of America finds them and shuts them down. So, if you are
looking for a live version of your favorite song by your favorite
artist, you may find yourself traveling down one blind alley after
another, as MP3 sites appear and disappear as RIAA, ASCAP and
others ferret them out and shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   But the looking is half the fun, even if it leads nowhere. Kay
is right: MP3 junkies are a subversive lot, willing to spend hours
surfing the Web into the wee hours of the night to find that one
rare track or the latest hits from the biggest stars.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's illegal, but so is buying bootleg CDs at record fairs
or from some guy named Vinnie who's set up shop on eBay or in any
of a million music-related newsgroups.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are tired of listening to veteran Web surfers yammer
on and on about the good old days of the Web when you never knew
exactly what you were going to find when you fired up your browser,
might want to spend an hour or so in the online world of MP3.
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensive lists are hard to find, and many of the download
sites you can locate will turn you away because there are too many
people downloading files at one time. Others simply don't exist
anymore, having been caught in the act by recording industry types
wanting to protect the rights of the session musicians and
songwriters who don't earn a dime from MP3.
</P>
<P>
   What the superstars like Garth Brooks or Madonna get is free
promotion, which leads to ticket sales, CD sales and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Some MP3 sites are legal, some aren't. Let your conscience be
your guide. Sooner or later the record companies will find a way to
make MP3 legal and profitable, but in the meantime, it's all out
there on the Web. Check out this little subversive nook while you
still can. But don't say who told you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
