<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE23-COX     03-22 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nose around for free allergy advice
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   That computer of yours is nothing to sneeze at. But if you're
like most Americans, you'll soon be sneezing _ to one degree or
another _ at almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit is pollen of various kinds and, in this part of the
country, the pollen season is almost upon us. All the beautiful
Atlanta plants and trees and grasses will conspire against you _
irritating your sinuses while they delight your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There is help to be found for allergies on the Web. The best
place to start our medicinal visit to the Internet is to a plain
Jane site called Pollen Allergy at
http://www.hoptechno.com/book46.htm.
</P>
<P>
   In these days of multimedia and video clips, this page looks
downright old-fashioned. It's simply text. But the text is from the
National Institutes of Health, and is one of the clearest
explanations you're likely to find for the reason that your eyes
may soon be bloodshot and your nose itchy and prone to sniffles.
</P>
<P>
   This is really a comprehensive site that gives you both the
theory of allergies in words that a layman can understand as well
as practical ways to avoid pollen as much as possible and the
medical treatments available for those who can't avoid being
outside during the peak pollen season.
</P>
<P>
   Let's travel from there to another rather plain page called
Patricia Wrean's Asthma and Allergy WWW Resources page at
http://www.cco.caltech.edu
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)wrean/resources.html.
</P>
<P>
   While this page may not be a feast for the eyes, it lives up to
its name. It is a collection of links to the various allergy
resources on the Net. In fact, this page is so comprehensive you
can use it to find almost any allergy-related topic.
</P>
<P>
   The page is divided into sections that include, but aren't
limited to, asthma, medications, related diseases and medical
conditions, and general medical resources. Just find the topic that
interests you under one of these headings and click to be taken to
the page.
</P>
<P>
   At least two Atlanta-based Web sites are worth visiting when it
comes to allergy information. The Weather Channel site offers
allergy information _ mostly in the form of text and links to other
sites _ at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.weather.com/health
</P>
<P>
   /allergy1.html. While you're there, you can also check out
various maps, including one that tracks respiratory disease hot
spots in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Allergy Clinic has a site at http://www.atlallergy
</P>
<P>
   .com/ that offers some of the most useful information for local
sufferers. It has, at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .atlallergy.com/forms/pollen
</P>
<P>
   .asp, a daily chart that shows pollen levels and describes the
type of pollen that is most common. This is a real help, especially
if you already know what type of pollen causes you the most
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are familiar with how the Web and the Net work already
know the term FAQ. That's Net-talk for frequently asked questions.
You'll find FAQs for almost every topic, including one that
discusses Internet resources (not limited to the Web) about
allergies and asthma at http://www.cs.unc
</P>
<P>
   .edu/(tilde)kupstas/FAQ.html. Reading the material here can save
you a lot of searching and also serves as a good foundation of
knowledge for those who have an academic interest in allergies.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature of this page is an excellent collection of
links. You'll see quickly that there's no lack of information about
allergies. But despite all the help, most of the experts agree that
the best you can hope for is to control the symptoms, not
completely eliminate the allergy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
