<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAC-REPORT23-COX     03-22 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software that turns a Mac into a PlayStation gets mixed reviews
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to hand it to Connectix. This Mac developer is always
pushing the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   First, the company designed a great emulator of Windows 95 for
the Mac, and now it's doing the same for Sony PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   Called Connectix Virtual Game Station, this emulator software
lets Macs _ at least in theory &Cx1f;  _ run any computer CD game designed
for Sony PlayStation. The implication of this software is huge.
</P>
<P>
   Sony PlayStation ranks either No. 1 or No. 2 in the video
console market at any given time. There are literally hundreds of
game titles for the platform. In one swoop, Connectix has
quadrupled the number of games for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   But does Virtual Game Station really work? The answer, based on
some initial reviews on the Web, is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers are reporting that not all PlayStation games will work
with Connectix's software. ``Resident Evil'' and ``Wing Commander
IV'' are two examples of games that do not work, according to some
reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some games run so slowly they're unplayable. One
example is ``Final Fantasy Tactics,'' which took one reviewer 100
hours to complete on a Mac with Virtual Game Station.
</P>
<P>
   You should also know that Virtual Game Station does not work
well, or at all, with Macs that predate the new G3 microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these drawbacks, Virtual Game Station is garnering some
strong reviews. For one thing, reviewers are saying it is
intuitively easy to use and set up.
</P>
<P>
   Second, some games play as well on a Mac as on a Sony
PlayStation. Two examples cited by reviewers were ``Metal Gear
Solid'' and ``NFL Blitz.'' These are graphically complex games
rendered in 3-D, yet they ran like a dream, according to reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers caution users not to buy any games for Virtual Game
Station at first but to rent them. That's because what works and
what doesn't work is so unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing is that Connectix is diligent about upgrading its
software. You can be sure Virtual Game Station will improve over
time. In fact, the company just released an upgrade on its Web site
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Game Station sells for about $50.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
