<HEADER>
A9307 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MEDIA23-COX     03-22 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Informative book chronicles the state of virtual reality, the
people behind it
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for a fun but informative book about the
technology behind virtual reality, check out ``The Visionary
Position.'' It chronicles both the state of virtual reality and the
people behind it. The book is written by Fred Moody, who earlier
wrote the much-praised ``I Sing the Body Electronic,'' a book about
the internal workings of Microsoft. Published by Times Business,
``The Visionary Position'' retails for $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   You know computers have become mere commodities when companies
start giving them away. And that's exactly what is happening. Read
about how you might get one of these free PCs in the April issue of
PC Computing. Beware, though _ there are plenty of strings attached
to any free PC. Computers are given away primarily as a promotion
for another service, such as Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   ``The King and I'' is a talking book on a computer CD, designed
for kids ages 4-7. Publisher SoundSource claims, though, that this
is much more than an entertainment title. It says ``The King and
I'' teaches problem solving, planning and observation through
puzzles that are built into the talking story. ``The King and I,''
based on the classic tale of the same name, is available for both
PCs and Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Grolier Interactive has released the latest version of its
popular multimedia encyclopedia. It works with both PCs and Macs
and features a number of new things. Among them are full-screen
video, digital stereo music and 360-degree panoramas of famous
locations such as the Great Wall of China. The encyclopedia now
features 58,000 articles, 15,000 images, 1,200 maps and 163 videos.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Looking to spruce up your desktop with some new art? Begin your
search at the Web site of the famous art collections at the
Guildhall Library and Guildhall in London. The site offers free
images of art in both galleries. You can use the images as
wallpaper on your computer. You'll find the site at Art Gallery,
http://collage.nhil.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
