</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mercedes puts office on wheels
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We can shave, sing, talk and sleep, but we really couldn't do a
whole lot of work in our cars.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the folks at IBM and DaimlerChrysler, a new gadget
promises to turn the car into a rolling office. This week, the
recently merged international automaker announced an optional
feature in the Mercedes-Benz V-Class multipurpose vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Console creates an ``office on wheels'' designed to
enhance productivity and convenience for business people who spend
much of their day in cars, such as sales agents. The console
includes a desk, IBM ThinkPad Notebook computer with
voice-recognition software, printer, telephone, fax and high-speed
modem.
</P>
<P>
   The console will let drivers send and retrieve e-mail, documents
and calendar items. A passenger will be able to use the equipment
while someone is driving, even when the vehicle is going through
tunnels, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer equipment can be taken out of the vehicle and used
at home or in the next V-Class vehicle, if the first one is sold.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology potentially could actually add a little joy
to the family road trip.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler said it based perceived customer interest on
consumer studies that show drivers and passengers are interested in
saving time; the ability to do work conveniently and easily from a
vehicle; the ability to navigate; the ability to track vehicle wear
and tear; and the availability of games and other entertainment
over the Internet during trips.
</P>
<P>
   GM goes online
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, the granddaddy of the automakers, has stepped
onto the Internet retail sales floor.
</P>
<P>
   GM unveiled its online shopping site, GM BuyPower, http://www
</P>
<P>
   .gmbuypower.com.
</P>
<P>
   More than 73 percent of GM's 7,800 dealers are enrolled in the
program. The Web site gives users information about each vehicle
made by GM; access to dealer new-vehicle inventory; the ability to
apply online for GMAC financing; and a place to send e-mail to the
GM BuyPower dealer you choose to get price quotes.
</P>
<P>
   GM BuyPower debuted as a pilot service in four Western states in
October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The site gives consumers access to the inventories of about
6,000 GM dealers nationwide. GM said its site is the only one that
lets consumers locate the exact vehicle they want and find out
detailed information via the vehicle identification number, or VIN.
</P>
<P>
   The site automates the car- or truck-buying process.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can print a customized brochure, schedule a test
drive, ask a dealer to hold or locate a vehicle, or get a price
quote. Once a consumer has picked the car or truck, including the
options and color, he or she can go to the dealership to fill out
the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Faster laptops
</P>
<P>
   Compaq this month started selling what it calls the consumer
market's fastest Internet notebook PCs.
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq Presario 1675, 1670 and 1270 have 380-megahertz and
350-megahertz processors. The new models also have matrix display
screens and a 100-megahertz system bus architecture. A bus is a
data path. Compaq said the 100-MHz bus makes for a faster overall
system and enhanced audio, video and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   The notebooks are designed to enhance Internet use. The ``easy
scroll'' feature, located near the touchpad, lets users scan Web
pages and documents. The notebooks also feature Compaq's Internet
Zone, a cluster of four buttons that allows one-touch connections
to the Internet or the Web for searching, secure online shopping
and e-mail. Each Presario notebook comes with an integrated 56k ITU
V.90 modem.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario 1675, with a 14.1-inch display, carries an
estimated retail price of $2,399.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario 1670, with a 13.3-inch display, sells for an
estimated price of $1,999.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario 1270, geared for the mobile user or student, sells
for an estimated $1,699.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
