<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX     03-22 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Buying slaves is wrong, right?
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a snap being ethical when right and wrong are clear, as too
many of our glib public scolds make out they usually are. But
puzzle this:
</P>
<P>
   Slavery has come back to southern Sudan with a literal
vengeance, a nasty spinoff from the civil war that has been
grinding away there since 1983. The Muslim north is trying to
suppress separatist guerrillas of the Christian and animist south,
a fight that intensified after the extremist Nationalist Islamic
Front took over the Khartoum government in 1989 and imposed severe
Muslim law nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's military and freelance slave traders make periodic
sweeps into the south, capturing civilians, especially young women
and children, to sell as field hands, personal servants and _ most
valued _ concubines.
</P>
<P>
   No one has a sure handle on how many have been sold. A southern
Catholic bishop estimated 3,000 were captured in the unusually busy
first six months of last year. Over the years, tens of thousands
have been enslaved. Slavery is one of the several terrorist horrors
by which Khartoum, rather than by set-piece battles, prefers to
prosecute its war. Starvation is another.
</P>
<P>
   The international response has been inconstant and mostly pro
forma, and in the absence of any truly promising effort to finagle
or force an end to the civil war, humanitarian organizations,
mostly Christian, have been raising funds and buying slaves into
freedom, at prices ranging from $50 to a few hundred, depending
upon market conditions and who's the better haggler.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Solidarity alone has freed nearly 6,000 in the past
four years. Kids at a school in Colorado, bless them, raised an
awesome $50,000 to free Sudanese slaves. One can only honor the
impulse and the effort.
</P>
<P>
   But is that the right thing to do? How can it not be? Mustn't a
life be redeemed from misery if it can be?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but then UNICEF, the estimable U.N. children's fund, has
doubts, bordering on opposition. One spokeswoman went as far as to
call the buy-backs ``intolerable.'' Human Rights Watch also is
uneasy. The group's advocacy director says the practice creates a
``real danger of fueling a market in human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, although Sudan's government is by far the greater
offender, southerners are entering the trade as a straight profit
deal. Buy-back groups can't be sure people aren't being enslaved
just so they can be sold to humanitarians bearing cash. Too, some
freed slaves have been returned home only to be recaptured.
</P>
<P>
   The only sure way to stop all this, as UNICEF and others
emphasize, is by a committed international effort to end the war,
which probably means forcing a partition of Sudan. We all have an
obligation to set up a clamor for that. Meantime, and with such a
commitment by no means certain, what's the right thing to do?
</P>
<P>
   I lean against the buy-backs, as risking more harm than good,
but I lean that way uncomfortably and with honor for those acting
forthrightly for the enslaved. Sometimes good can be attempted only
in a Hell of ambiguities.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
