<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIE23-COX     03-22 1750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barbie: Has she come a long way, baby?
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The case is powerful, if largely
circumstantial: The triumph of Barbie reaching her 40th birthday
must mean something important. And a number of apparently serious
scholars are dedicated to figuring out just what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the triumph is unassailable. Barbie redefined babe when
she debuted in a market crowded with toddler dolls that waved,
whined or wet themselves. She may not have been every girl's ideal,
but she wasn't meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   She was every dad's ideal, and dad had two words for anyone who
suggested that a real woman built like Barbie would tip over: Jayne
Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this was 1959, a time when dads still ruled the roost
along with pretty much everything else. This was long before NOW.
Long before anyone imagined it might ever be illegal for a boss to
grunt ``hubba-hubba'' when his secretary sauntered by.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder Barbie, modeled after a German novelty doll
intended for men, was a hit back then. The wonder is that she still
is. Not only has Mattel sold more than a billion Barbies and Barbie
pals, it still sells two every second worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   American girls between 3 and 11 own an average of eight Barbies
each, and their appetite for more is evidenced by the regular
appearance of each new Barbie incarnation on the toy industry's top
10 list.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the most popular doll on the planet,'' said Kathleen
Lawrence, an associate professor of communications at the State
University of New York-Cortland who is on sabbatical while doing an
intensive Barbie study. ``That's a concern, a real issue for
feminists.''
</P>
<P>
   Their cause for concern is what Lawrence calls the stranglehold
that patriarchy still has on our society. Apparently, dad's still
in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbie embodies the idea that there is a purpose for women
that is, for the most part, wrapped up in being doll-like, being
plastic, looking a certain way, being limited to performing certain
tasks,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, who is three months older than Barbie, is not assuaged
by the manufacturer's attempts over the years to dress Barbie in
professional robes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see Barbie as a dentist, but you don't see the work it
would take to get a dental degree,'' she says. ``Playing with
Barbie comes down to changing clothes. Girls get the message: All
it takes for me to change careers is to change my dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, director of the school's Center for Multicultural and
Gender Studies, is planning a Barbie book tentatively titled ``The
Good, The Bad, The Barbie.'' In the meantime, she's working on a
paper titled ``Intern Barbie,'' assessing the influence of Barbie
on Monica and Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   She's convinced most people accept the Barbie ideal of beauty
and that the fantasy can have a harmful effect on emotional or even
physical health.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd have the fat composition of someone 10 percent smaller
than an anorexic model if she were real,'' Lawrence says.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Barbie is truly harmful in measurable ways is, at least,
debatable. Academic studies lean heavily on testimonials from women
who felt excluded, threatened, intimidated or angered by Barbie's
overwhelming blondeness. The notion that she is responsible for
anyone's bulimia or low SAT scores is hard to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   But there's little disagreement that she is an extraordinary
touchstone among under-50 women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something the vast majority of students have used in
childhood to think through the construction of their own gender,''
says Marc Steinberg, assistant professor of sociology at Smith
College, a women's school in Massachusetts. ``It's not a passive
object.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg encourages students to study images of Barbie in
various roles and even to play Barbie dress-up. ``The idea is for
students to think about the ways that gender is not something
natural or given but, in fact, a social product,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of images to study. Barbie's transmutational
ability matches any creature from Star Trek.
</P>
<P>
   She has been garbed in many roles, from cheerleader to doctor.
She's been reshaped several times toward a more realistic
waist-bust ratio. And, after decades of criticism from non-blondes,
Mattel now allows girls to dabble in genetic engineering by
specifying Barbie's eye color, hair color and one of four skin
colors ranging from pale to brown.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are all the unofficial permutations, some of them
downright odd. Barbie's face has become the Campbell's Soup can of
today's pop artists. The Internet offers hundreds of altered
Barbies, aged Barbies, distorted Barbies. Some people even take
Barbie deconstruction literally; a group calling itself the Barbie
Liberation Organization claimed to have switched voice boxes with a
number of G.I. Joe dolls.
</P>
<P>
   These might seem like acts of Barb-arity, but Steinberg says
they are a symbolic revolt against male dominance. ``The image of
Barbie constricts what women can do in our society,'' he says. ``By
subverting that image, they can undermine the dominant ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   That sure sounds like a cue for a deep breath. Perhaps it's time
for a reminder that, after all, she's just a doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear that all the time,'' says SUNY's Lawrence. ``Mostly
from male colleagues. If she's just a doll, why does everyone say
`she' instead of `it'? ''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence says the just-a-doll contingent has even questioned
whether Barbie is a suitable topic for serious study, a question
that she considers a threat to academic freedom and part of an
overall attack on women's studies.
</P>
<P>
   Others, predictably, disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like a question of academic freedom to me,''
says Glenn Ricketts, spokesman for the National Association of
Scholars, an academic reform group that urges a return to rigorous
standards and traditional studies.
</P>
<P>
   The liberal arts in general have gotten excessively
contemporary, Ricketts says. ``What Barbie studies indicate, to me,
is that it's gotten positively trivial. We're studying ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The academic press faced similar charges of triviality with Duke
University's 1995 publication of Barbie's Queer Accessories. ``I
was accused of nearly causing the downfall of Western
civilization,'' says author Erica Rand, associate professor of art
at Bates College in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The book's title is taken from one of its primary topics, the
effect of Barbie on lesbians. Rand interviewed or heard from
hundreds of women, many filled with hostility toward Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   They've told her about throwing Barbie down the stairs or into
the fireplace. Or painting on pubic hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people's reactions are clearly based on other things in
their life,'' she says. ``Some people hated Barbie because she was
given to them as a role model. If a girl wasn't really girly, she
might resent being given this doll to emulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say Barbie made them feel bad about being fat, or about
being too poor to afford official Barbie clothes and doll houses.
But Rand also hears from Barbie lovers. ``I think it is hard to
take one cultural product and put the blame on it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Rogers laughs when asked whether male colleagues have
challenged her Barbie studies at the University of West Florida.
``They know better!'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers says she realized the power of Barbie several years ago,
when she delivered one lecture on the doll in her sociology course.
``I never had so many students stay after class,'' she says. ``They
all wanted to tell Barbie stories.''
</P>
<P>
   In Barbie Culture, published by Sage Publications, Rogers
explores Barbie as consumer and body template. But the shocker, at
least for those '50s dads, is her take on Barbie's bombshell image.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie, she concludes, is . . . sexually ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not entirely the mainstream girl she may appear to be to
some people,'' Rogers says. ``If you look at veterinarian Barbie or
astronaut Barbie, where she's all suited up to go into space,
bombshell doesn't quite fit anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, she's 40 years old and never married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a man at the center of your life is pretty definitive
of mainstream heterosexuality,'' Roger says. ``You should be
overtly coupled with a man, but she isn't. Ken is, ah, kind of
peripheral.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mattel's official Barbography bundles Ken under the
category of ``supporting cast,'' along with Barbie's sisters and
her admirably diverse friends Christie, Kira and Teresa (who are,
in order, black, Asian and Hispanic).
</P>
<P>
   So, it is possible, Rogers argues, to view the otherwise
heterosexist Barbie as feminist icon, the ultimate independent and
omnicapable woman.
</P>
<P>
   Or, she concedes, to view her any way you like.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why she's sold so well for 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can say for sure how old Barbie is supposed to be, what
her social status is, whether she ever gets a bill for all that
shopping. This marvelous murkiness allows every girl to give Barbie
her own meaning, and she probably carries that meaning into
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   But what does this say about Barbie? If the doll that has made
so many millions of girls happy and at least some others miserable
has no inherent meaning, if it symbolizes only what each girl wants
it to, then couldn't Barbie be replaced by any other doll?
</P>
<P>
   ``Or a shoe, or a melon,'' says David Geary, psychology
professor at the University of Missouri-Columbia. Doll play, a form
of practice parenting, is intuitive among girls in all cultures, he
says. Just about anything that can be picked up and cuddled will
do.
</P>
<P>
   Geary's book, Male, Female: The Evolution of Human Sex
Differences, will not win fans among academics who see Barbie as a
powerful, gender-role influence.
</P>
<P>
   He concludes that gender stereotypes are the result of prenatal
exposure to sex hormones, not parental example or childhood
experience: Boys play with trucks, girls play with dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Geary concedes that Barbie represents male ideals that could
have harmful effects, including eating disorders, but he notes that
men have many ways of letting women know what they expect.
</P>
<P>
   So, what if Financial Genius Barbie simply took her billions and
retired at 40?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other dolls girls can play with,'' Geary says.
``There are still fashion magazines and models and all those
influences. I don't think much would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
