r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-Q&AMP;A23-COX     03-22 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-Q&AMP;A23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:Can you find out why Pedialyte cannot be used after 48 hours?
The bottle says to discard it. What gives? It looks fine to me.
</P>
<P>
   A:''As soon as the seal is broken, air contacts the product so
it is no longer considered sterile,'' according to a Ross
Laboratories statement. Beyond 48 hours ``the bacteriological
safety'' of Pedialyte is compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, makers of the popular children's electrolyte maintenance
solution, advises a cup of Pedialyte can sit safely at room
temperature for three hours; however, once a child drinks from a
cup or bottle containing Pedialyte, it is considered safe for only
one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I have a problem with my dogs, a mother and daughter team.
Recently, the daughter tries to keep the mother from eating her
fair share. To keep them from fighting over the food I simply sit
outside until the mother finishes.
</P>
<P>
   What possible reason would the daughter have for not letting the
mother eat? Is there anything else I can do?
</P>
<P>
   A:It's a dog eat ... well, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, dogs share the wolf pack's dictum of only one dominant
female. The two may be vying for the position, says Diana Smith of
Hearts and Paws.
</P>
<P>
   The younger dog may be trying to get leadership, sensing the
mother is getting older; the mother may comfortably acquiesce. Have
you noticed any other behavior indicating leadership? Which dog
gets to the door first? The competition may escalate into fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Smith recommends you feed the dogs in different rooms (one
outside, one inside?) if possible. If not, put the younger dog on a
leash to eat to prevent her from munching on mom's rations.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I am very interested in finding information on Bill Bradley's
campaign for president. Where would I write to him?
</P>
<P>
   A:The 55-year-old Bradley was born in Missouri and matriculated
at Princeton University and Oxford University. Bradley played
professional basketball for the New York Knicks and served three
terms in the U.S. Senate (from New Jersey).
</P>
<P>
   Write to him in care of Bill Bradley for President, 395 Pleasant
Valley Way, West Orange, N.J. 07052.
</P>
<P>
   Q:My Waterford Crystal bud vase and rose bowl are ``cloudy.'' Is
there a product to clean them? I've tried denture tablets, which
did not work. Please help me!
</P>
<P>
   A:Ooh oh. The denture cleanser is the last stop. Could be too
late.
</P>
<P>
   But here are some ideas from Waterford.
</P>
<P>
   Wash vases in warm, not hot, water with a mild liquid soap. Some
water leaves deposits, which may be removed by using vinegar on a
cloth. Use vinegar every time you clean the vase or bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The interiors of vases may benefit from filling them half full
with warm water, two tablespoons of white vinegar OR ammonia and
1/4 cup uncooked rice. Swirling this mixture around removes
interior residue gently. Rinse with clean, warm water and dry with
a lint-free cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Never place in the dishwasher.Q:I want to know who owns the Hope
diamond and where is it stored at this time.
</P>
<P>
   A:The Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Hope diamond is named for Henry Phillip Hope, who owned the
diamond in 1839. The uncut stone, probably from India, was
described by its original owner, Jean Baptiste Tavernier, as ``a
beautiful violet.'' A beautiful 112 3/16-carat diamond violet!
</P>
<P>
   It sojournedjourneyed through history around the necks of kings
such as Louis XIV and on the headpieces of Americans like such as
Evelyn Walsh McLean. Jeweler Harry Winston purchased the stone from
McLean's estate in 1949 and donated it to the Smithsonian in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   The Hope diamond (cut to 45.52 carats) is currently set on a
45-white-diamond necklace, surrounded by 16 white diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com
or fax (512) 445-3968. Due to the number of inquiries, Jane cannot
respond to every request.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
