<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREW-BARRYMORE-IN-NEVER-BEEN-KISSED-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURN TO HIGH SCHOOL: BEHIND THE SCENES WITH DREW BARRYMORE ON
`NEVER BEEN KISSED' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Drew Barrymore with David Arquette in a
scene from ``Never Been Kissed.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Drew Barrymore wasn't always cool.
 &HT;    At Cal Prep School in Stoneridge, Calif., Barrymore was
overweight and awkward. She had braces and skin like a
connect-the-dots game.
 &HT;    ``My lowest moment in high school was when one of the
cheerleaders said I could practice with the team,'' Barrymore
recalls. ``You see, I was always dying to be a cheerleader.''
 &HT;    It turned out to be a cruel trick. The cool girls just wanted to
watch the school dork squirm.
 &HT;    ``That day at practice, the most popular girl in my school saw
fat little me arrive in the gym,'' Barrymore says. ``She stopped
mid-cheer to scream, `What is SHE doing here?' I was mortified, and
then this girl insisted, `Get that idiot out of here!'
 &HT;    ``I ran out in tears,'' says Barrymore, who eventually dropped
out of school. ``It is still the most humiliating moment of my
entire life. I will never forget it.''
 &HT;    And finally she can use it. Her latest film _ ``Never Been
Kissed,'' opening April 9 _ casts her as a Chicago newspaper
reporter who goes undercover as a high-school student for a trend
piece on ``the kids of today.''
 &HT;    On the set _ a dilapidated office building in downtown Los
Angeles _ Barrymore is having flashbacks. She wears an ill-fitting,
drab, light-blue dress that seems to add 30 pounds to her slim
frame. Her lips are covered in garish, red lipstick.
 &HT;    ``Josie thinks that, since she's older, she will be able to join
the cool kids, but when Josie goes back to high school she finds
out that the inner geek has survived,'' Barrymore says. ``She
thinks it will all be different, and it's all exactly the same.''
 &HT;    Well, not exactly. She falls in love with one of the teachers
(Michael Vartan), for one thing. But for Barrymore, the point to
the movie, which also stars David Arquette, Molly Shannon and
Leelee Sobieski, is how much it resonates with her own life.
 &HT;    ``I think it's about how kids just look at the surface,'' she
says. ``It's like high-school students have this blueprint from
magazines about how you're supposed to look and feel. They can't
see beyond this perfect image.''
 &HT;    Barrymore isn't looking especially perfect right now. Her eyes
are actually a bit glazed over, after weeks of juggling her roles
as actress and as the film's producer. So far today, between scenes
she's called record companies about rights for the soundtrack,
argued with studio executives regarding a poster design and, oh
yes, read through a few script rewrites.
 &HT;    Even her lunch hour will be all business, spent with a reporter
and a takeout salad.
 &HT;    ``I have never worked harder in my life,'' she says. ``I've had
many, many sleepless nights.''
 &HT;    Not that she's complaining.
 &HT;    ``I can't believe how many studio executives are actually
listening to what a young woman has to say about a major
investment,'' she says, grinning. ``To me, that's its own victory.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't sure I wanted to produce,'' Barrymore adds, ``because
I always questioned power. It seemed like such a greedy thing. But
now I think power is the ability to change the world for the
better.''
 &HT;    And, yes, she sees ``Never Been Kissed'' as an opportunity to do
exactly that, if only in a small way, while perhaps working through
some of her own demons.
 &HT;    ``One of the things about acting that's so cathartic to me is
that you get to use some of your idiosyncratic behaviors and
mannerisms in a character,'' Barrymore says. ``So there are fears I
truly still embody from high school _ about not fitting in, about
everyone hating me _ that I really get to live through Josie.''
 &HT;    A harried-looking assistant interrupts.
 &HT;    ``Drew, we need you,''
 &HT;    Barrymore gets up and makes the trek to another part of the
building, which has been set up to look like a big-city newsroom,
complete with crumbled Post-It notes and magazines dating back to
World War II.
 &HT;    She spends the next two hours being yelled at by her editor
(John C. Reilly, of 1997's ``Boogie Nights'').
 &HT;    ``I'm probably going to be the most hated man in the country,''
Reilly says during a break. ``I'm yelling at the girl who played
Cinderella.''
 &HT;    Finally the scene works and ``Cut!'' has been called, but
Barrymore still has work to do. A producer's job is never done, she
says as she finally settles down to lunch.
 &HT;    Barrymore even helped come up with the film's title, she adds.
 &HT;    ``It's not that Josie has never been kissed by a boy,'' the
actress explains, digging into her salad in a room which actually
resembles a high-school cafeteria. ``One of the film's themes is
that you haven't really been kissed until you lock lips with
someone you love.''
 &HT;    Obviously, this is a topic on which Barrymore, a born romantic
most recently involved with Luke Wilson, her co-star in ``Home
Fries'' (1998), considers herself an authority.
 &HT;    ``Oh my God,'' she says brightly to anyone within earshot in the
crowded lunchroom, ``is there nothing worse than when you're really
in love with someone, and then they kiss you and you realize
they're a terrible kisser?
 &HT;    ``It's over in, like, one second.''
 &HT;    Two plump Teamsters at a nearby table nod in agreement.
 &HT;    ``I mean, concrete lips and darting tongues,'' the actress adds.
``It can be so awful.''
 &HT;    ``We've all been there,'' a 300-pound grip says, digging into
his salmon.
 &HT;    Barrymore's laugh fills the room, and everyone else joins in.
 &HT;    ``I want people to have a good time on this set,'' she says. ``I
never understood that feeling of incorporating tension into a
project. I want people to look back on this shoot with wonderful
memories.''
 &HT;    Memories, she adds, are what this film is all about. Scarred by
her own high-school recollections, she hopes that ``Never Been
Kissed'' will ease some younger women's passage.
 &HT;    ``I want teens to see this movie and feel good about
themselves,'' she says. ``I want young girls to look at the
so-called `fat' Josie and think, `This is a beautiful girl, and she
doesn't need to go on a diet. She doesn't need to look like a waif
out of a magazine. She's beautiful in all the ways that count.
She's a good person on the inside.'
 &HT;    ``With this movie,'' she concludes, ``I want kids to tell each
other how much they can change the world individually and how much
power they actually possess.''
 &HT;    Barrymore shakes her head sadly. She knows perfectly well that
her movie won't change things much. Jocks will still pick on geeks.
Nerds will still wish they were prom queens.
 &HT;    ``High school is so brutal _ but then again, life is brutal,''
the actress laments. ``I swear, I walked into the high-school set
for this film and I got immediate butterflies and ulcers. And it
was just a set.''
 &HT;    She sighs.
 &HT;    ``I felt the pressure tightening around me,'' she says.
``Pressure to excel, pressure to be smart, pressure to fit in.
Pressure to be wearing the right clothes and have the right body
type.''
 &HT;    Barrymore pauses.
 &HT;    ``Wow,'' she says in surprise. ``High school is like
Hollywood.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
