<HEADER>
A9337 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-FEATURE23-COX     03-22 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FOR KIDS: It's tornado time again
 &HT;    By Shelia Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've probably heard of tornados _ whether it's from reading
the newspaper or watching popular movies such as ``The Wizard of
Oz'' or ``Twister.''
</P>
<P>
   Tornados are violently rotating columns of air. These columns of
air extend from a thunderstorm cloud to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Tornados can be scary, but understanding how and when they
appear can take some of the wind out of your fear.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado's birthday
</P>
<P>
   Weather conditions have to be just right for a tornado to be
born, says Colin Marquis, a meteorologist at the Weather Channel.
Tornados take shape when an area has warm, moist conditions in the
lower atmosphere and the temperature above it is falling rapidly.
As you move farther from the ground, the atmosphere becomes
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   The strength and direction of winds help determine whether a
tornados forms. If the wind speed increases dramatically as you
move higher and the wind changes direction, chances are a tornado
is forming, says Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   Shaping up
</P>
<P>
   Usually when we think of tornados, we picture a funnel-shaped
cloud. While the funnel is the classic shape, tornados can resemble
gray or black-colored ropes with the same width from top to bottom.
And sometimes, they look chaotic and jumbled.
</P>
<P>
   But the size and shape don't have anything to do with the
strength of a tornado. You can have a very weak wide-bodied one or
a very intense, narrow funnel.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite hangouts
</P>
<P>
   Tornados can occur anywhere in the United States. Most tornado
activity occurs in the Great Plains states, which include Texas,
Nebraska and Oklahoma. Between 1950 and 1994, Texas averaged 122
tornados a year; Oklahoma averaged 51; and Georgia was hit 20
times.
</P>
<P>
   Last year it seemed Georgia got more than its fair share of
these violent winds. In 1998, there were 39 tornados reported in
our state. Marquis said the increase was likely caused by El Nino.
El Nino created unusually warm water in the Pacific Ocean, which
later affected other weather patterns, such as tornados and snow.
</P>
<P>
   Tornados usually occur at certain times of the year. Often, they
hit the the Gulf Coast first because it has a lot of warmth and
moisture. There, tornado season begins as early as mid-February. In
Georgia and surrounding states, the season begins in March and
lasts until May.
</P>
<P>
   More brawn than brain
</P>
<P>
   Tornados range in strength from weak to horrific. Meteorologists
use the Fujita Scale to rank the level of intensity. The scale,
which ranges from an F-0 to an F-5, estimates wind speed based on
the damage caused.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1950 and 1994, 74 percent of all tornados were ranked
F-0 or F-1; 25 percent were F-2 or F-3s; and 1 percent were F-4 or
F-5. The higher the number, the more damage.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-seven percent of the people who were killed in tornados
died in F-4 and F-5 levels.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the worst period on record for tornados was in April
1974. On April 3 and 4, 148 tornados hit 12 states, killing 309
people. About six of those tornados were categorized as F5s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
