<HEADER>
A9326 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTRY-SINGER-DEANA-     03-22 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-SINGER-DEANA-CARTER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEANA CARTER: EVERYTHING REALLY IS ALRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of country singer Deana Carter. 
 By JANET E. WILLIAMS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Overnight success hasn't changed Deana Carter one bit _ and no
wonder, since her success was actually five years in the making.
 &HT;    That's how much time passed between the day she signed with
Capitol Records and the release of her debut album, ``Did I Shave
My Legs for This?'' (1996).
 &HT;    Being used to delay came in handy with her second album. Despite
its predecessor's success, ``Everything's Gonna be Alright'' was
stalled by several executive shuffles, long enough that the singer
feared that it might languish in a vault for as long as her first
album had.
 &HT;    ``I was freaking out, going `Why do I have to have album delays
every project?''' she recalls.
 &HT;    As it turned out, this time the delay was measured in months,
not years.
 &HT;    ``What I've found out is that the powers that be _ meaning karma
and the spiritual side of life _ always take care of me,'' she
says. ``So if it's delayed, or when things happen to me that I find
abrasive, I try to pull back and go, `OK, what's the big picture?
Am I paying attention?'
 &HT;    ``And it always works out for the best.''
 &HT;    The bubbly blonde _ who is that rarity, a country star who's
actually a Nashville native _ hasn't forgotten her years as a
struggling singer/songwriter. Carter and her husband, songwriter
Chris DiCroce, found themselves at the governor's mansion in
Nashville for a party after the 1998 Country Music Association
Awards, and she felt a sense of deja vu.
 &HT;    ``I was talking to Roy Lott, the head of Capitol,'' she recalls,
``and I said, `You know what? The last time I was here, I was
serving people at a party. I had on my tux shirt and a tie, and I
drove my ratty little Honda up here. I know where your wine glass
goes in the kitchen. I was serving people here, and this is
freaking me out!' We laughed about it.''
 &HT;    Back then Carter wanted nothing more than stardom, but in
retrospect she admits that she still wasn't ready when it arrived.
 &HT;    ``You know what's weird?'' she says. ``I still go back and forth
_ I ping-pong on this. It's like you feel like people aren't really
paying attention to you, because they didn't for so long.
 &HT;    ``Before I could do something, go out with no makeup at all,''
she explains. ``Now every time I do it people go, `You look so
different in person.' It never fails _ you go out without your
makeup on, and what are you going to do but run into somebody you
don't need to see.
 &HT;    ``So I'm still having a hard time realizing that people are
paying attention to me.''
 &HT;    Unlike many stars, she still gets a kick out of being recognized
by fans.
 &HT;    ``People usually come up and say, `Hey, Deana!''' she says.
``I've never met them before, so I think that's kind of cool. They
feel like they know me a little bit. It's never in an invasive
way.''
 &HT;    It helps that she comes from a performing family. Her father is
noted session guitarist Fred Carter Jr. _ the two recently appeared
together on the PBS series ``Austin City Limits'' _ and her younger
brother Jeff plays in her band.
 &HT;    And her mother, Anna, is there to help them all stay grounded.
 &HT;    ``The other day, my mom said something that was like a sledge
hammer in the teeth,'' Carter recalls. ``We were talking about
something, and she goes, `I don't care if you are a star ... ' She
pulled that card on me, and it just made me so mad! But, really,
that my mom would say that is hilarious.''
 &HT;    Her family ties helped Carter through years in which she
supported herself through a succession of what she unceremoniously
calls ``crappy jobs.''
 &HT;    ``I did the janitorial service _ literally,'' she says,
laughing. ``I always joke around about men's urinals and about
those things _ what is the stopper for in urinals? What is going to
go down there that shouldn't? It's a urinal, right? How many pieces
of gum I've pulled out of the stoppers of urinals _ it's just
disgusting.
 &HT;    ``What else? Selling china door-to-door was pretty bad,'' she
says. ``You cold-call people, and then you go over. The gear was
great, it was worth it _ but, oh, I am not a salesman.''
 &HT;    Not all of her day jobs were so unpleasant.
 &HT;    ``I loved waiting tables and I loved bartending,'' Carter says
with a smile. ``That was great. (Former Capitol Nashville chief
Jimmy) Bowen always said, `Don't do business with somebody til you
play golf with them and see how they are. Are they fair? How are
they as a person _ hotheaded, levelheaded?' You learn that by
waiting tables, too.''
 &HT;    Carter credits much of her current success to those days.
 &HT;    ``I waited tables at Zanies, the comedy club here, for a long
time, about three years,'' she recalls. ``I learned so much from
those comedians. I used to be really envious of the way that they
were self-destructive on the stage _ they would sit there and
self-bash and abuse themselves and the human spirit and human
nature.
 &HT;    ``That was hilarious. When you see comedians making fun of what
we all have in common, then you're on the right track.''
 &HT;    Carter tries to bring that same spirit to her music, she says,
especially in her more personal songs, such as ``Absence of the
Heart,'' the first single from ``Everything's Gonna Be Alright.''
 &HT;    ``Musically I have to keep exposing myself,'' she says. ``It's
just therapy, really. It makes me feel better when I sing a song
like `Absence of the Heart' and I see someone crying or relating to
it. I'm really contacting that person, and at least half of that
weight is gone because you know someone else is going through it
too.
 &HT;    ``You don't want them to, but there is so much release in
knowing that you're not the only one. Musically, it's important to
put your guts out there.''
 &HT;    ``Absence Of The Heart'' is one of many strongly narrative
Carter songs. The singer says that she needs a story that she can
relate to if she's to give a song her best.
 &HT;    ``All the singles off the first album were little stories or
specific instances that you could visualize,'' she says. ``You can
plug your life into that. I am a song girl, and I love to be able
to plug my life into it, where I can either escape into the song or
feel like I am reliving something that I've been through before.''
 &HT;    One of the tunes likely to evoke memories for baby boomers is
Carter's cover of ``Brand New Key,'' the 1970s hit. Although Carter
infuses her version with a fun spirit, she doesn't take this song
any more lightly than anything else on the album.
 &HT;    ``A lot of energy goes into that, to have fun,'' she says. ``The
first album, there were serious sides and lighthearted sides, but
there was also a fun element. I wanted to make sure that this album
had that too.''
 &HT;    Although it had been five years since she'd been in the studio,
Carter says that she's generally pleased with ``Everything's Gonna
Be Alright,'' despite its relatively hurried genesis. But next time
out she aims for a more relaxed pace.
 &HT;    ``I love this album, but it came around so much faster than the
first one,'' she says. ``It's kind of like planning your children _
the second one, we were surprised!
 &HT;    ``I want to have a little more time for the next project. I
appreciate foresight and I like to be respectful of that, because I
don't want the music to suffer.''
 c.1999 Janet E. Williams  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Janet E. Williams is a Nashville, Tenn.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
