<HEADER>
A9331 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLAIRE-DANES-IN-THE-M     03-22 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLAIRE-DANES-IN-THE-MOD-SQUAD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOROUGHLY `MOD': CLAIRE DANES REVISITS `THE MOD SQUAD' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Claire Danes with Omar Epps and Giovanni
Ribisi in a scene from ``The Mod Squad.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Claire Danes is blushing.
 &HT;    ``I was really lame and pathetic,'' she says. ``I played with
Barbies.''
 &HT;    Danes sighs, relieved to have bared her soul at last.
 &HT;    ``I used to lie and say I didn't like them because they weren't
representative of my life and of real women, because they didn't
have bruises on their legs,'' she says. ``But I secretly adored
Barbies.
 &HT;    ``God, that sounds so calculating, but I never played cops and
robbers,'' the actress adds. ``I played teacher, which I guess is
more in keeping with the traditional feminine role.
 &HT;    ``I'm probably making up for all that pathetic stuff now.''
 &HT;    Danes smiles, and it's a genuine, ear-to-ear grin. She's
unwinding in a trailer parked on a street in the East Village
section of Manhattan, after spending a couple of hours shooting an
MTV promotional show on behalf of her latest film, ``The Mod
Squad.''
 &HT;    That's right, ``The Mod Squad.''
 &HT;    The actress, known for such serious fare as the acclaimed ABC
series ``My So-Called Life'' and the films ``Little Women'' (1994),
``Romeo &AMP; Juliet'' (1996) and ``Les Miserables'' (1998), is finally
getting her chance to play cops and robbers. She kicks some serious
butt as delinquent-turned-cop Julie Barnes in a big-screen version
of the oh-so-hip ``Mod Squad'' television series, set to open April
2.
 &HT;    ``I'd seen a few episodes of the show when the movie started to
be born, but I hadn't watched any episodes prior to that,'' says
Danes, a pretty young woman with short blonde hair and huge blue
eyes. ``It's not really my generation's show.''
 &HT;    To try to make it more accessible to her generation,
director/co-writer Scott Silver has updated the story while
retaining elements of the 1968-1972 series.
 &HT;    The action now unfolds in present-day Los Angeles, for example,
though there's plenty of 1970s style on view, from the cars to the
outfits to the architecture. The mod troika remains Julie, Pete and
Linc, though they're now portrayed by Danes, Giovanni Ribisi and
Omar Epps.
 &HT;    ``What made it appealing and exciting to me is that you have a
bunch of groovy, swanky, rebellious kids fighting the system,''
Danes says. ``That will always be seductive. It's a common process
that kids have to work through. You have to kick and scream at the
adults until you can finally become one.''
 &HT;    Danes got a kick out of acting with Epps and Ribisi, she adds,
and loved playing a character so reserved and stoic. She even
welcomed the opportunity to perform stunts and get dirty.
 &HT;    Even better, the actress says, was the chance to display her
sexuality, especially now that her real-life experiences, for the
first time, can inform her onscreen performance.
 &HT;    ``It took me a long time to figure out what sex was,'' says
Danes, who will turn 20 on April 12 and is dating Australian
musician Ben Lee. ``It was really hard to communicate that idea
onscreen without having resolved any of those issues in my own life
and on my time.
 &HT;    ``It's natural for me now to manipulate that, to use it as a
tool to do my acting,'' she adds. ``It was really foreign to me as
a kid. It's a relief to have finally learned that language.
 &HT;    ``Now it's like, `Oh, I get it! I can play that.'''
 &HT;    Danes comes to ``The Mod Squad'' fresh from a whole other life.
Between films, she's in her freshman year at Yale, where her course
load includes such nonglamorous offerings as women's health,
adolescent psychology, graphic design, English, ``Modernism in the
City,'' computer science and ``The Modern Intellectual Agenda.''
 &HT;    Not everyone can handle the demands of college and a
simultaneous film career _ Danes' friend and role model, Jodie
Foster, all but dropped out of Hollywood during her Yale years. But
Danes says it's worth the effort.
 &HT;    ``I like it,'' she says. ``I'm in the middle of midterm week at
the moment, so I'm not as enthusiastic as I was when the semester
began. But it's been really healthy for me. I'm smart _ I learned
that at school, and it was something very reassuring to figure out.
 &HT;    ``I guess I had a complex about being an actress and a blonde,''
she explains, ``because people all of a sudden assume you're a
bimbo. I needed to confront that and prove to myself that I was
totally confident and capable of reading, writing and analyzing.''
 &HT;    Juggling her two lives can be jarring at times, Danes
acknowledges, but she isn't asking for sympathy.
 &HT;    ``People there have full-time jobs or are on a varsity sports
team, and everyone is separating from their parents,'' she says,
noshing on a pack of orange Twizzlers. ``Everyone is overwhelmed,
and you have to struggle to maintain a bit of a life while you're
there. It's easy to lose yourself in the course readings and never
return.
 &HT;    ``Also,'' she adds, ``I haven't had to turn down any great roles
yet to attend school, which is good _ though I am going to take off
a semester to do a movie that should start this summer and go into
the fall.
 &HT;    ``I'm willing to do this for five years, if that's what it
takes,'' she concludes. ``I really miss acting when I'm denied
access to it, and I start getting shaky.''
 &HT;    This summer, Danes says, she's also planning to spend as much
time as possible with her boyfriend.
 &HT;    ``Right now Ben visits me at school whenever he can, and we get
together on weekends,'' says Danes, who lives on campus in New
Haven, Conn., but often spends weekends at home in her Manhattan
loft. ``We've been together two years.''
 &HT;    She smiles softly.
 &HT;    ``He's the one,'' she says.
 &HT;    This summer will also see the long-delayed opening of
``Brokedown Palace.'' Far more serious than ``The Mod Squad,'' it
features Danes and Kate Beckinsale as recent high-school graduates
who are busted for drug trafficking while visiting Thailand and
sentenced to 33 years in prison.
 &HT;    Adding to her busy summer, Danes will be heard _ but not seen _
as the voice of the title character in ``Princess Mononoke,'' a
Japanese animated film that has already grossed more than $150
million in Asia. For the film's American release, Miramax hired
Danes, along with Billy Crudup, Gillian Anderson, Minnie Driver and
others, to dub the dialogue into English.
 &HT;    The shape of her life and career after Yale remain a tantalizing
prospect for Danes, who's in no hurry to make plans. She continues
to be compared to Foster, who directed her in ``Home for the
Holidays'' (1995) and may team with her for a remake of ``All About
Eve,'' but Danes doesn't think the world needs another Foster.
 &HT;    ``The Jodie Foster we've got now is still thriving and still has
a lot more work to do,'' Danes says. ``I don't want to be her
younger doppleganger. I don't know what I'm going to be yet.
 &HT;    ``I did know since I was 5 years old that I wanted to be an
actress,'' she adds. ``I was so directed and focused, and my life
changed because of this dream that became real.
 &HT;    ``Now I don't have that map, that dream to rely on,'' she says
thoughtfully. ``I am an actress and I am doing what I want to do,
but I really don't have a concrete goal to attain. That's a little
frightening, but it's good, too.
 &HT;    ``I'm ready to push my acting to the next level,'' Danes
concludes. ``I feel like I'm evolving as a person at a pretty rapid
rate, and that must affect my work. So I'm interested to see how
all that shapes my work as an adult.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
