<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-GOES-HOLLYWOOD-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION GOES HOLLYWOOD: TURN-OF-THE-CENTURY TV TURNS THE CAMERA
ON ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a 350-word sidebar and a color slide of Jennifer Grey and
Chris Eigeman in a scene from ``It's Like, You Know.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any day now, someone will announce a television show that has no
cast or setting _ just two cameras filming each other filming each
other filming each other ...
</P>
<P>
   Since the dawn of the medium, television has focused on the
entertainment world _ look at its most legendary sitcom, ``I Love
Lucy,'' with starstruck Lucy Ricardo aching to get a taste of her
bandleader husband's stardom.
</P>
<P>
   But lately it's moved to a new level. Though two of the best
have recently departed _ ``Seinfeld,'' which starred Jerry Seinfeld
as a popular comic named Jerry Seinfeld, and ``The Larry Sanders
Show,'' Garry Shandling's dark, insightful and scabrously funny
look at the talk-show business _ there's plenty more where they
came from.
</P>
<P>
   Al Franken's ``Lateline'' brings the spirit of ``Sanders'' to a
television news program, for example, while ``SportsNight'' offers
a similarly behind-the-scenes look at a cable sports program. Like
``Sanders,'' these shows often feature celebrities guesting as
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This spring the ante is raised even further. ABC's ``It's Like,
You Know'' centers on a Seinfeldesque group of Los Angeles
denizens, including actress Jennifer Grey as herself, while ``Movie
Stars'' is a family sitcom whose family just happens to feature
mom-and-pop superstars. Jennifer Grant, daughter of Dyan Cannon and
Cary Grant, stars, and the cast also includes the real-life
brothers of Patrick Swayze, Sylvester Stallone and John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   More self-reference is on the way: Sara Gilbert will star in a
comedy about a late-night-comedy-show writer, and New York actress
Rosie Perez will headline a comedy about the travails of a New York
actress.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in the spirit of the big screen, where Robert Altman's
``The Player'' (1992) featured legions of stars cameoing as
themselves, ``Get Shorty'' (1996) viciously spoofed the movie
business and ``Wag the Dog'' (1997) let Dustin Hoffman do a
sarcastic turn on producer Robert Evans. Coming soon to a multiplex
near you is ``Being John Malkovich,'' a quixotic look inside the
quixotic character actor's brain, and ``Free Enterprise,'' in which
William Shatner portrays a version of himself _ a pompous actor who
cons a couple of ``Star Trek'' fans into financing a musical
one-man show reminiscent of the legendarily bad album Shatner
himself recorded in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertainment Tonight started it,'' says James Widdoes, the
co-creator and executive producer of ``Movie Stars.'' ``The success
of that show and everything that came after it, the magazines and
all that stuff, that began it all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People _ viewers, readers _ love to get behind the scenes,''
agrees Ted Harbert, former ABC Entertainment president and
executive producer of ``It's Like, You Know.'' ``That's the reason
talk shows work. That's why award shows work. That's why game shows
like `Hollywood Squares' work.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the idea of a star playing themself in a fictional sitcom
is, I don't want to go as far is to say irresistible, but you're
going to want to check out what Jennifer Grey says about herself in
the show,'' he says. ``There isn't much in the show that hasn't
happened to one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty fresh idea, and `Larry Sanders' broached it,''
says Grey, whose background, life and even her nose job are mined
for the show's scripts. ``And this specifically has never been done
before. I think that's part of the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Like'' creator Peter Mehlman, a former ``Seinfeld''
writer, has collected stories from Grey and the rest of his cast to
use in his scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody takes themselves so seriously out here,'' he says.
``Every quote, every newspaper article's like, you know, the end of
the world. I said to Jennifer, `You know, you're going to get all
the stuff, with the nose and everything like that, it's all just
words. Have fun with it _ it's not going to change who you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   The self-reflexive trend comes at a time when the sitcom format
itself seems a bit tired, making it ripe for self-parody.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest with you,'' Mehlman admits, ``I'm
trying to avoid getting bored with this form. I was on `Seinfeld'
for seven years _ I'm in great danger of getting bored doing
standard shows. I'm feeling a little restless.''
</P>
<P>
   But can it be healthy for the world of entertainment if its main
subject is increasingly itself? Is immersing ourselves in the
fantasy factories good for our self-image, for maintaining a sense
of perspective in living our own lives?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very profound question,'' Widdoes says thoughtfully.
``We make things out of whole cloth here, we make entertainment.
Are we curing cancer? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he repeats for emphasis. ``I wish I could do a really
smart comedy about the fact that America's children are getting
dumber every year. I can't come up with the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I have to do shows that afford me the opportunity to make
sure that my kids get the best education they can.''
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; SIDEBAR: JENNIFER GREY'S PERFECT ROLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first time actress Jennifer Grey, playing actress Jennifer
Grey, turns up in ``It's Like, You Know,'' Chris Eigeman's
character doesn't think it's her.
</P>
<P>
   He's a huge fan of ``Dirty Dancing'' (1988), which he saw in its
recent re-release, and she looks nothing like she did in that
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nose job!'' Grey exclaims, and hopes the matter will rest
there.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't. Most people, let alone most celebrities, don't
advertise their plastic surgery, certainly not on prime-time
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved how I looked'' before the nose job, she insists.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she says, ``Dirty Dancing's'' phenomenal success
didn't translate into any boost for her career. She didn't work for
a year after it was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I looked specifically Jewish, and I think that
there are not a lot of parts for Jewish girls specifically,'' she
says. ``I really wanted to be able to be considered for all sorts
of parts, to play an unspecific ethnicity ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to help myself get work, and I was trying to
not compromise myself and do the right thing to help myself be a
working actress.''
</P>
<P>
   She took some flak for the decision, but insists that she
doesn't regret it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of my life, it's part of who I am,'' she says.
``Without having had that happen, I would never have gotten the
lessons I've gotten. I had to completely rebuild who I thought I
was without anyone's input. That's the most valuable thing in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also given her a sense of humor about her own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a part in my contract where I basically have approval
over things directly pertaining to my personal life,'' Grey says.
``But I also find that the more open-minded I can be and the more
freely I can allow them to go nuts and throw wild stuff at me, the
more opportunity I have to have a great time as an actress.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all sitcom actresses, Grey wouldn't mind winning an Emmy
for her work. But if she doesn't get one, will it mean that she
didn't even have the acting chops to be convincing as herself?
</P>
<P>
   Grey laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she says. ``I guess it'll mean I've been miscast as
Jennifer Grey. That'll just be one of the knocks I'll have to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a Los Angeles-based senior writer for TV Guide
Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; (Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
