<HEADER>
A9338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN23-COX     03-22 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Wedge-issue politics steps up to the plates
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The state of Florida is jumping into the
political bumper-slogan business. So why aren't bumper-sticker
manufacturers outraged and mobilized?
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is poised to give Florida an anti-abortion
license plate. If passed and approved by the governor _ as is
likely _ a ``Choose Life'' tag will join the 42 specialty plates
that now enliven license-plate bingo games on the state's highways.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators love specialty license plates. They are easy to vote
for and each makes some group happy. Since the state started
authorizing them in 1987, hardly a session has gone by without
legislators approving new tags. This year, they want five new tags.
Last year, they added six.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the tags have been noncontroversial. Florida
bumpers sport beloved team mascots, floating manatees, leaping
fish, prowling panthers and smoke-belching space shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   Which is as it should be. Political causes that bring
table-conversation to a dead stop and cause folks to be crossed off
Christmas-card lists would seem to be poor choices for license
plate themes. Why are we no longer satisfied with license plates
that simply give a place and a number? Why must they be A
Statement?
</P>
<P>
   Abortion is one of those hard issues over which people of good
will, sound morals and normal intelligence will disagree, call each
other astounding names and argue themselves hoarse without
resolving. It is an issue people have been murdered over. Is this
really a debate that fits on a license plate?
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what the next legislative session will bring. A
death-penalty license plate (``Choose Death'')? An ``I'll Give Up
My Guns when They Pry My Cold, Dead Hand from the Trigger'' plate?
``Hamburger is Murder'' and ``Wake Up to the Teletubbie Menace''
plates?
</P>
<P>
   Once Florida starts stamping polarizing political slogans on its
plates, is there any issue too weird to be proposed? Hint: we are
talking about Florida Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's experience with a politically charged license
plate motto should be instructive. Since 1973, prisoners have
stamped the motto ``Live Free or Die'' on that state's license
tags.
</P>
<P>
   The slogan was a call to resist tyranny but over the years had
been taken up by enough militia groups, white supremacists, gun
nuts and right-wing kooks that some New Hampshire folks are
uncomfortable with it. The state had to prosecute people for taking
the slogan off their plates _ until the U.S. Supreme Court ruled
that a state can't force people to say they value freedom.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, declaring for or against the slogan is an easy way
in New Hampshire to start a fight when people would otherwise be
frozen and bored. Attempts to change it are ritually shouted down.
</P>
<P>
   I do not have a specialty plate on my car. I have the old,
pre-1997 plate with the state's outline on it. I liked the one
before that even better. The one that said ``SUNSHINE STATE.''
Sentiments I dare anyone in the room to contradict or gainsay.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like the newer Florida plates, which feature an orange,
because the orange is smooth and looks too much like a peach. I
like my oranges to look like oranges. I'm funny that way.
</P>
<P>
   We get to drive around with different license plates here: 42
specialty plates, old plates and new plates. I see this as
symbolic. Floridians tend to come from somewhere else, so we have
less in common than people in other states do.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to unite around the symbol of a peachlike orange, we
drive around sporting an ever-growing number of symbols and
slogans. Until now, all of them have at least been nonpolitical and
nothing anyone would argue about _ with the exception of the
University of Florida or Florida State University tags.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that last little bit of common civic space, a little
rectangle of sheet metal on our cars, is going to be up for
political grabs. Something to be argued over, legislated, lobbied,
featured in mailings, used in attack ads and forced into effect
over the other side's objections.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, we will have even less in common. And a new
legislative game on the road _ capture the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
