<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FOR KIDS: Kosovo no closer to peace
 &HT;    By Theresa Walsh Giarrusso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Albanians and Serbs couldn't agree to a peace plan
last week and were preparing for more fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its allies may get involved in the war.
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) is threatening to
bomb Serbian targets and send soldiers to try to keep peace.
President Clinton is warning that the missions could be very
dangerous and Americans could die.
</P>
<P>
   The province of Kosovo is part of the country of Yugoslavia.
Albanians who live there want Kosovo to be its own nation, but the
Serbian leaders of Yugoslavia are opposed. The two groups fight
about religious differences, as well as other issues.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks hit 10,000 mark
</P>
<P>
   If your parents seemed extra happy last week, it might have been
because their stocks were doing well. The Dow Jones industrial
average hit 10,000 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks are little shares of companies that anyone can buy. All
together, the stockholders own the companies. The Dow Jones average
is the average price of some major stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, as stocks are bought and sold, the Dow rises
and falls. When the Dow rises, it usually means that the economy is
doing well and stockholders are making money.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones average began in 1896. It rose slowly in the
beginning, but it has leaped dramatically in recent years. It took
76 years to hit 1,000, in 1972. Fifteen years later, in 1987, it
rose to 2,000. And in only four more years, 1991, it hit 3,000. In
1995, it rose to 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   Cartoons not role models
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever noticed Dumbo getting drunk or Cruella de Vil
chain-smoking throughout ``101 Dalmations''? A professor from the
University of North Carolina took note and started studying just
how often cartoon characters abuse alcohol or tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Goldstein found that 34 out of 50 G-rated movies released
during the last 60 years showed alcohol or tobacco abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are clearly seeing positive images of addictive
substances that their parents, teachers and society all
discourage,'' Goldstein wrote in an article for the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   TREND
</P>
<P>
   Japanese love Dumplings
</P>
<P>
   Children in Japan are screaming for more dumplings. They're not
extra hungry for sticky dough balls. They're in love with ``The
Three Dumpling Brothers,'' animated characters on a Japanese kids'
show that is similar to ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   The three dumpling boys, who are stuck together on a skewer,
fight, make up and turn dry and hard when they sleep in the
cupboard overnight. After the dumplings sang a song, the TV network
was flooded with calls. The dumplings made a CD to satisfy their
fans, and it went straight to the top of the pop chart.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the records, the sales of rice dumplings have also
increased.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
