<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9370 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHNOBUDDY23-COX     03-22 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Running too fast guarantees short life span
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I grew up in the South during the days of four-wheeled
dinosaurs. The association I have for the word ``speed'' is shaped
by a two-lane highway outside of Arkadelphia, Ark., a road that
magically turned into an illegal and dangerous drag racing strip
around midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the days of muscle cars. It all happened so long ago
that even the description of those cars won't mean a thing to most
kids growing up today. We had GTOs with three two-barrel
carburetors that sat atop a log manifold, on an engine with a
three-quarter race cam that gave it a strange loping sound ... like
KER KER KERPLUNKA.
</P>
<P>
   So when I think about a growing problem for computer buyers
today _ hopped-up processor chips that are forced to run at a speed
beyond the design specifications _ I understand how much and how
little has changed. It's still all about speed just for the sake of
going fast. But the new status symbols are computers, not fast
cars.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, we tortured engines to get the most out of them, even
though we knew that shortened their life span. The same thing
happens with hopped-up computer chips: They live a short but
exciting life.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the frightening news, though: Some manufacturers and
retailers hop up the chip before you buy it and don't tell you.
Some unsuspecting customers pay extra for a computer with a high
megahertz rating and are actually buying a slower chip that has
been hopped up. That's where the short life span comes into play.
That hopped-up chip may run fine for a while but _ because of the
stress _ it ought to have a tattoo on it that says ``Born to Die.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand why Intel is worried about these hot-rod chips,
we'll have to talk about that mysterious megahertz rating, and
along the way, you'll learn something you probably didn't know. The
speed of a processor is determined by an oscillator that vibrates
electronically at a set frequency. It is called the ``clock'' for
the chip. Think of it as the pace car that determines how fast the
chip will run.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what newcomers to computing might not understand: Did you
know that a Pentium II running at 300 megahertz is identical inside
to a Pentium II running at, say, 450 megahertz? When I say
identical, I mean precisely that. That 300-megahertz chip comes off
the same production line as the 450-megahertz chip.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happens at Intel and other chip manufacturers: In a
process that any grocery store meat manager will recognize, the
best chips are clocked at the highest speeds and sold for a premium
price. It's just like selecting the best cuts of meat and labeling
them prime. The chips that didn't turn out quite as good are
clocked at lower speeds and sold for less.
</P>
<P>
   Some computer hobbyists have understood this clocking system for
years. And they've taken advantage of it to home-brew computers
that run faster, simply by changing a few settings on the
motherboard of the computer. Intel is not bothered by that at all.
After all, these folks have every right to trade longevity for
speed in their own computers.
</P>
<P>
   But what's scaring Intel these days is that some retailers and
manufacturers are overclocking chips and selling the machines at a
higher price without telling the buyer. In fact, Intel has warned
consumers about the problem and has even created a small program
that can be downloaded by the Intel Web site (http://www.intel.com)
that checks Pentium III chips for overclocking. That program won't
detect overclocking on earlier models of chips, including the
Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a way to protect yourself from overclocked
chips. Even Intel acknowledges that the problem is limited to
small, no-name manufacturers and retailers. So if you're worried
that you might be sold a hot rod of a computer that won't last,
then you can buy with safety from the brand-name companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
