for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH _The cell phone, which turns 15 this year, has
displaced lots of calls that once were made on desk phones. Many
pay phones are unoccupied in busy passageways such as those in
airports. No need to scramble for coins or stand in lines, because
so many people are carrying their own phones. Welcome to the
wireless generation. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Lead art includes magnificent 4-column illustration of numerous
cellular phones surrounding a brilliant-blue planet Earth with the
sun emerging on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHONE FACTS -- A list of facts about land-line phones and
cellular phones. (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes thumbnail
illustrations of a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS -- A St. Louis company has come up with a
software program that lets you make your own funeral arrangements,
from choosing a funeral director to picking the hue of your
headstone. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 18
pica photo of cover art from software package.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY -- I love e-mail when it comes from a friend.
But so much of what I receive is true junk, and I delete that
unread. Nowadays the junk seems to outnumber the good mail.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column color
sig of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MAC NEWS: It has been a long time coming but apparently
worth the wait. At least that is the initial review coming from the
Internet about 3Com's new Mac software for its PalmPilot line of
hand-held computers. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art
includes 1 column color photo of a PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-HANDHELD _ The hand-held market has become a smaller
version of the one for desktop and notebook computers. There are
really only two choices: hand-helds running Windows and the three
PalmPilot models, which use a unique operating system and hardware.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ When I think about a growing problem for computer
buyers today _ hopped-up processor chips that are forced to run at
a speed beyond the design specifications _ I understand how much
and how little has changed. It's still all about speed just for the
sake of going fast. But the new status symbols are computers, not
fast cars. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ A new CD-ROM from SouthPeak International called
``The Library of Congress: Eyes of the Nation'' is a splendid
reminder that the Smithsonian Institution is not this nation's only
repository of historical documents and artifacts. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCHER _ Downloading MP3 files, uploading MP3 files and
pretty much doing anything with MP3 files is illegal. Maybe that's
why I'm doing it at 2 in the morning. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ There is help to be found for allergies on the Web.
The best place to start our medicinal visit to the Internet is to a
plain Jane site called Pollen Allergy at
http://www.hoptechno.com/book46.htm. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ If you're looking for a fun but informative book
about the technology behind virtual reality, check out ``The
Visionary Position.'' (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ Does Virtual Game Station really work? The answer,
based on some initial reviews on the Web, is mixed. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDS _ The ``Rugrats Adventure Game'' is a fun, interactive
way to introduce children to the computer. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ We can shave, sing, talk and sleep, but we really
couldn't do a whole lot of work in our cars. Until now. Thanks to
the folks at IBM and DaimlerChrysler, a new gadget promises to turn
the car into a rolling office. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-RACE _ Is the Internet empowering minorities? A study by
Forrester Research suggests that African Americans and Hispanic
Americans are jumping onto the Internet in higher percentages and
Caucasian Americans. Technofiles looks at the issue of race and the
Internet. (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE _ Barbie: Icon of Feminism or Death Knell to the Feminist
Movement? (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Three or four briefs of world and national news,
written for kids to understand. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-FEATURE _ You've probably heard of tornados _ whether it's
from reading the newspaper or watching popular movies such as ``The
Wizard of Oz'' or ``Twister.'' It's their time of year again.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   POPE-CD _ The story behind, and critical comments on, Pope John
Paul's ``Abba Pater'' CD, in stores March 23. It contains speeches
in five languages from over the years recorded off Vatican Radio
and laid on top of some unfortunate New Age-y music. (Green,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   PBS-AFFIRMATIVEACTION _ Reviews of PBS' ``Beyond Black and
White: Affirmative Action in America'' airs this night; also, CNN
begins its 10-part ``People'' magazine profile series, starting
with Harrison Ford. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICS-BALLET _ In a session examining the science of art,
scientists hold a seminar on the physics of dance with the Atlanta
Ballet at the 100th anniversary meeting of the American Physical
Society. (Green/Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-DEFIBRILATOR _ The American Red Cross's acting director,
Steve Bullock, is in town for one of the first demonstrations of
the organizations new initiative of training corporations to use
heart defibrilators to revive people whose hearts have stopped.
Bullock will be demonstrating the device at Cox corporate offices.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
