<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-COX     03-22 0263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes
 &HT;    Forgiving Elia Kazan
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 1976 memoir of the Holocaust, ``The Sunflower,'' Nazi
hunter Simon Wiesenthal recalls how as a young concentration inmate
he was called to the deathbed of a grotesquely wounded SS officer.
The SS man begged Wiesenthal, as a Jew, to forgive his role in a
wartime atrocity. Wiesenthal thought about it, then refused. He had
no right, Wiesenthal reasoned, to forgive on behalf of the victims.
Wiesenthal asked his readers what they might have done. Good
question.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary film director Elia Kazan was honored the other
night with an Oscar for his lifetime achievements. Outside, pickets
protested. Inside, many refused to rise in respect. Elia Kazan had
once named names. The names were those of friends, who Kazan
identified as Communists before the infamous House Un-American
Activities Committee. Now an old man, and either out of pride or
conviction, Kazan has refused to seek forgiveness or to apologize
for the pain he caused..
</P>
<P>
   Life is filled with close calls. This is one. Kazan was not
being honored for his life, but for his directorial
accomplishments. Only the victims have a right to forgive. We have
no right to feel more virtuous than we are. Let him have his award.
He has earned it, if not our respect as a man.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
Email: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.co
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
