<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     03-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, March 22, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-CONTRIBUTION (San Antonio) _ The Army's elite Delta Force
offered to donate $20,000 to the favorite charity of a city
councilman in order to win his support so anti- terrorist
operations could be conducted in his council district, several city
officials say. The councilman declined the donation. By SIG
CHRISTENSON and CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-2012 (San Francisco) _ Put aside for now lost Olympic
innocence and negative thoughts about the International Olympic
Committee _ $1.2 million in graft paid to members to award the 2002
Winter Games to Salt Lake City _ and think of the possibilities for
the 2012 Bay Area Summer Games. The Bay Area Sports Organizing
Committee (BASOC) will submit a bid one year from now for the games
13 years hence. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-SOFTWARE (San Francisco) _ By and large, Apple Computer
Inc.'s foray into the open source software world was met with open
arms last week when the computer maker announced it was giving away
the software coding for its newest Macintosh server operating
system. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-UNSEINFELD (Undated) _ Finally there's a show that doesn't
look like ``Seinfeld,'' although it sounds like it and feels like
it, in no small part because its creator and executive producer is
former ``Seinfeld'' writer Peter Mehlman. Premiering Wednesday on
ABC, ``It's like, you know ...'' leaves you scratching your head:
What took ABC so long to put it on the air? By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PROFILE-McCONAUGHEY (San Francisco) _ ``The sexiest thing
of all,'' drawls Matthew McConaughey, leaning forward and
intensifying his blue- green gaze, ``is when two people are having
a conversation within inches of each other . . . to be able to talk
going into a kiss and coming out of a kiss. Some actors'll tell ya
it's weird or a pain.'' The 29-year-old East Texan grins
blindingly. ``But they're lyin'. It's daaaaamn great.'' By JANE
GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-REVIEW-TUNA (San Francisco) _ ``Red, White and Tuna,''
the newest installment of the Tuna saga, opened here with the
original Tuna creators Joe Sears and Jaston Williams as the entire
population of the third-smallest town in Texas. Billed as the third
part of the Tuna trilogy, it isn't as sharply satirical or crisply
structured as ``Greater Tuna'' nor quite so comically iconoclastic
as its holiday sequel. But it is wonderfully funny, pointedly
topical and genuinely heartwarming. By ROBERT HURWITT.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-CLICHES (Undated) _ Betty Kirkpatrick cut her teeth
as a wordplay expert while editing both ``The Bloomsbury
Thesaurus'' and the latest edition of ``Roget's Thesaurus.'' Now
she's given students of the language something else to chew on:
``Cliches: Over 1,500 Phrases Explored and Explained.'' By JUDYTH
RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-TEXAS (San Antonio) _ Spring is here, and what
better time to consider a heartwarming book about the season. The
spirit of ``Heralds of Spring in Texas'' by naturalist Roland H.
Wauer (Texas A&AMP;M University Press, $24.95) can best be captured in
the author's story about his yearly anticipation of the return of
the buff-bellied hummingbird to his back yard. By JUDYTH RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BABIES-2000 (San Francisco) _ The global Y2K baby sweepstakes is
under way. Would-be contestants have conceived a winning strategy _
now they just have to conceive a baby. Experts say from now until
April 10 is the optimal fertilization window for couples hoping to
create the first offspring of the millennium. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-FASHION (San Francisco) _ When
Oscar-winner-for-best-actress Gwyneth Paltrow stepped onto the red
carpet to greet Joan Rivers before the 71st annual Oscar broadcast
from the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles, there was an
audible gasp. Not only was Paltrow a bona fide Hollywood princess,
she looked the part. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   WRITING-TABLES (Albany, N.Y.) _ The writing table evolved from
the Spanish writing cabinet, called a vargueno, that rested on a
set of collapsible legs. Because of its easy portability, this
simple box, which also stores writing implements, can be moved from
room to room and house to house. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Human beings learn by making
mistakes, sometimes even male human beings. Last week I made a big
mistake and learned that modern young women can play hardball _
literally. I called 14-year-old star baseball player Carey
Myslewski a boy and, boy, am I sorry. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ With roughly a million people
behind bars, the single most crucial problem the police face is the
widespread perception that they're not fair. Overwhelmingly,
Americans believe that people with connections or resources
routinely are given passes for conduct that would land a lesser
individual in the slammer. Sadly, there may be some truth to that.
By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
