<HEADLINE>
EUROTRASH: EC HOUSECLEANING BRINGS SWEEPING CHANGES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors _ NOTE BERLIN SUMMIT, MARCH 24, 25)   (This excellent 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 20 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not meant to be like this. With the single currency
comfortably in place, spring was supposed to bring a general
tidying up in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   There would be radical changes to the European Union's farm
policy, a wider reform of its entire budget, and then a final
making ready to receive applicants from the east.
</P>
<P>
   With a new government firmly in place, Germany, as current
president of the EU, would hold a triumphant summit in its
once-and-future capital Berlin, on March 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of its presidency in midsummer, a new chairman of the
EU's executive, the commission, would have been chosen; a new
European Parliament would have been elected; and the way would be
clear to start serious talks to admit new members.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the EU has lost the entire commission and Germany, the
Union's biggest economic power as well as its president, has lost
its finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is, undeniably, awkward, yet good can come of all
this confusion.
</P>
<P>
   It will do so if the chance is taken to rid the EU of some of
its Mediterranean practices, exploiting the Union's more northern
balance and mores; and if Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroder,
can make up his mind about what he wants to do with the new power
he holds, and then use it well.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, neither outcome is at all certain. The immediate
task is the appointment of a new commission. The trouble with the
old one was not just that its members, or at least some of them,
were complaisant about fraud, cronyism and mismanagement _ as an
independent committee found this week, making it impossible for
this lot to stay in office.
</P>
<P>
   It was also that the commission's president, Jacques Santer, was
too weak to control them. The next president needs to be stronger.
For a period, someone not censured in the report, Sir Leon Brittan
perhaps, might take over. But the sooner a permanent appointment is
made, the better.
</P>
<P>
   The new president needs to be strong enough to keep his troops
in line, to command the ear of heads of government, and to have the
confidence of Euro-MPs. Italy's Romano Prodi, having squeezed Italy
into the euro, might be such a man.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament has, on the whole, come well out of this episode.
Like the Council of Ministers, it has been accruing power at the
commission's expense. Yet it too suffers from weak leadership, and
is hardly a paragon of financial rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   It needs to attend to its own faults if it is to exercise better
control over the executive, bringing to an end, in particular, its
expensive dual life in Brussels and Strasbourg. Best stick to
Brussels, even though this would require a treaty change.
</P>
<P>
   The main business before the EU is expansion. A new
inter-governmental conference will be needed to reform the Union's
institutions to accommodate its new members.
</P>
<P>
   In the light of this week's damning report, it should also
strengthen the provisions for accountability and control.
</P>
<P>
   One improvement would be to allow the president, with the
approval of the parliament, to sack individual commissioners.
Another would be to open up Council of Ministers' meetings to
public scrutiny when the ministers are legislating.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, however, the budget must be settled, and the
responsibility for that rests largely with Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Berlin summit next week will be Schroder's first unambiguous
test. So far, he has been able to blame his government's long list
of failures on others: his Green partners, who have helped to
antagonize so many companies with their anti-nuclear and other
policies; the opposition, which has frustrated Schroder's proposed
rewriting of Germany's citizenship laws; and, most notably, his
turbulent finance minister, Oskar Lafontaine, who flounced out on
March 11.
</P>
<P>
   With Lafontaine gone, the tug-of-war at the center of government
should also be gone. The Greens are cowed, at least for the moment.
And Schroder is expected to take over Lafontaine's other job, the
chairmanship of the Social Democratic Party, on April 14, leaving
him free, in theory, to pursue his politics of the ``New Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroder faces two general difficulties, however, and one
particular one.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has to show that he really has some sense of what he
wants to achieve;he has, in other words, to dismiss the impression
that he has no central values and no clear idea of how Germany, or
indeed Europe, should be run.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he has still to reform his party, which has been
subjected to none of the colonic irrigation of that other New
Middler, the British Labour Party.
</P>
<P>
   And then, unrelated to these general concerns, and perhaps even
harder to achieve, he has to cajole the other 14 members of the EU
into accepting a budgetary arrangement that makes it possible for
newcomers to join. The miserable deal reached by the Union's farm
ministers on March 11 is not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   However, the events of the past ten days have at least provided
the possibility of better outcomes. German politics should be less
confused. European politics should be more open and accountable,
less off-putting to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, time is short. If Europe's leaders are serious about
reform and about opening the way for the EU's overdue expansion,
hard decisions must be taken within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   A Berlin summit that produces just fudge and waffle will only
confirm doubters in their belief that the Union is incapable of
putting its house in order, let alone opening its doors to
newcomers. &QL; 
