<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-DOLLARIZATION-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICA'S FISCAL ILLS REQUIRE SEVERAL CURES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 20 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, conventional wisdom held that Latin America would
easily weather the Asian financial storm. While economies crumbled
on one side of the Pacific, free-market reforms would pay off on
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, although Latin stock markets have recently rallied, the
outlook remains gloomy. Brazil faces its steepest economic decline
since the early 1980s. Ecuador is having its worst financial crisis
for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters expect a fall of 1.5 percent in Latin American GDP
this year; and net inflows of private foreign capital will shrink
from $80 billion in 1998 to around $50 billion. Can anything be
done to make Latin America less vulnerable and less volatile?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes. A first step is simply more of the same. Most
governments have reacted responsibly to the past year's turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   As foreign finance has dried up, governments have tightened
their fiscal belts and raised interest rates. There has been no
giving in to populism or to protectionist pressures. Maintaining
this resolve is a precondition for greater stability.
</P>
<P>
   But the region has not been uniform in its newfound virtue _ and
it is the most prudent that have fared best. Although every Latin
American country has found it more expensive to tap external
capital, those with sound budgets (such as Mexico, Peru and Chile)
have been hit less hard.
</P>
<P>
   While several countries have suffered from financial contagion
or plunging commodity prices, the biggest weaknesses have often
been self-inflicted: in particular, politically difficult fiscal
reforms have been put off for too long.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, notably, fiscal reform must mean more than simply
abiding by the recent IMF agreement. This agreement was a clever
compromise between the economically desirable and the politically
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   But, rather like a crash diet for a compulsive eater, it does
not solve the underlying problem _ and it could have unwelcome side
effects. Distortionary tax increases hurt the private sector; the
root cause of public profligacy, which is excess spending on wages
and pensions, remains untackled.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve stability, Brazil must find a more sensible tax
structure, get better control of fiscally lax state governments and
reform its public pensions.
</P>
<P>
   A second path to virtue is to be found in better risk
management. Even countries with healthy budgets could do more to
insulate themselves from capital-market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Careful debt-management strategies that avoid short-term
borrowing or the bunching of maturities and hedge against
interest-rate or exchange-rate swings should come high on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening the region's commercial banks should be another
priority. A big reason for Ecuador's current mess is its weak
banks. In a region with such a history of volatility, banks also
need quicker access to cash.
</P>
<P>
   High reserve requirements, especially against foreign borrowing,
are one option. Another is to encourage contingent arrangements
with foreign banks that guarantee limited credit lines in advance.
A third is to encourage the internationalization of the banking
system.
</P>
<P>
   As Argentina has found in recent years, a bigger role for
foreign banks usually means a safer banking system.
</P>
<P>
   The other, more controversial, matter that needs attention is
exchange-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   Pegged but adjustable currency regimes such as Brazil's have
been discredited by the recent crisis. So far, the preference has
mostly been for free floating _ witness Mexico, Brazil, even
Ecuador. But the wholly opposite notion of ``dollarization'' is
also gaining support.
</P>
<P>
   Dollarization is, in essence, merely a stronger version of the
currency boards that seem to have protected countries such as
Argentina from financial contagion.
</P>
<P>
   Even places without a currency board are already heavily
dollarized: that is, many people hold their assets in greenbacks
rather than domestic currency.
</P>
<P>
   At the first sign of trouble, investors across Latin America
tend to flee to dollars. So many countries suffer the volatility of
floating currencies without the benefits of flexibility _ for if
they try to cut interest rates or prop up their banks, their
currency tends to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   That gives dollarization its appeal. But it is not a panacea.
Important questions, such as how to create a limited lender of last
resort, need to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, which is toying with dollarization, has thought up
ingenious schemes for using seignorage revenue (returned from
America) as collateral for private credit lines.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, it will be more feasible in small, open
economies than in big, closed ones such as Brazil's, where the
consequent abnegation of monetary policy would be hugely
controversial. But it should be considered as a serious option for
some Latin American countries. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 750-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
