<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EL-TORO-BATTLE-CRY-EC     03-22 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EL-TORO-BATTLE-CRY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETREAT, HELL: EX-MARINE BASE SPARKS SUBURBIA `GETTYSBURG'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Southern California)   (This excellent 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 20 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE _ There is nothing quite like the peace dividend for
creating civil wars.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that the citizens of Orange County, Calif.,
would relish the chance of getting their hands on 4,700 acres of
prime property, particularly when a single acre in the area can
fetch as much as $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the decommissioning of the El Toro Marine Corps Air
Station has created the biggest row in the county for decades. It
has set neighbors against neighbors, Republicans against
Republicans, the filthy rich against the disgustingly affluent.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the citizens of Newport Beach have been irritated by
the growing number of aircraft using John Wayne Airport. (It is
regarded as a local tragedy that the city's most popular former
resident has given his name to its least popular institution.)
</P>
<P>
   They have also been worried that air traffic will grow hugely
with federal deregulation in 2005. After news came through in 1993
that the local Marine base was being decommissioned, George
Argyros, a leading citizen of Newport Beach, spent about $1 million
promoting a ballot measure to turn the base into a commercial
airport.
</P>
<P>
   El Toro may be only seven miles away from John Wayne Airport,
but Argyros correctly sensed that seven miles could as well be 170.
Moving the airport even such a short distance diverts the flight
path from Newport Beach to Irvine and seven other cities farther
south.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was carried by a tiny majority, 51 percent, and
ever since then the citizens of Irvine have been stretching
ingenuity to reverse the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Most arguments in the area are discreetly solved by the Irvine
Company, which owns more than a fifth of the county. But this time
the company is keeping studiously silent, probably because it owns
land on both sides of the noise divide. This means that the
citizens have the unfamiliar task of sorting things out for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They are making heavy weather of it. The County Board of
Supervisors, which is split three-to-two in favor of the new
airport, is frequently paralyzed by airport-related bickering.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican political machine is divided down the middle on
the issue; in particular the Lincoln Club, one of the biggest
collections of Republican moneybags in Southern California, is
losing key members because of its support for the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Feelings in Irvine are running so high that ways are being
explored of ending the subsidies it pays to the fire departments of
cities that support the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is so explosive that all the local papers have
assigned at least one full-time reporter to cover it.
</P>
<P>
   The Irvine town council has set up no fewer than five committees
to fight the airport. Christina Shea, Irvine's glamorously blonde
mayor, admits to devoting half her time to fighting the airport _
and thinks it could get to be more than half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to the death,'' she argues. ``It's our Gettysburg.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvine and its allies have no shortage of arguments against the
airport. The ballot violated the proper procedures for
decommissioning bases.
</P>
<P>
   The hills behind the base are so high that they pose a safety
hazard. The planned doubling of the size of Los Angeles
International Airport (LAX) means there will be no need for yet
another international airport in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the real reason why Irvine's citizens hate the airport is
that it will threaten their (somewhat peculiar) quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine is a planned community where you cannot change the color
of your door without getting permission. But the new airport may
introduce all sorts of unplanned things from junk-food joints to
(if LAX is anything to go by) strip clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Laguna Woods is the only city in the United States
that consists almost entirely of people aged 55 and over: the
airport will send air traffic directly over its plush golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   So far the Newport Beach crowd have outmaneuvered their
opponents at every point. They have managed to persuade the north
of the county (which contains 70 percent of the population) that
the new airport will be good for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   So the airport's opponents are trying two loosely related
tactics: putting a measure on the ballot to require a two-thirds
vote before public money can be used to support ``noxious'' land
uses; and a grand ``millennium plan'' which involves buying the air
base and turning it into an ``urban village,'' complete with
houses, offices, a sports complex and parkland.
</P>
<P>
   For all their political naivete, however, the airport's
opponents have two important things on their side: the glacial pace
of the American legal system and an iron determination to prevent
the ``incursion of the airport into our quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   They are willing to spend whatever it takes to delay the
proposed airport for years, perhaps decades, to come.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving such a valuable piece of land empty for the foreseeable
future might seem folly. But the strength of the passions involved
may mean that there is no other choice: unless, that is, both sides
decide to give the land back to the Marines. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
