<HEADER>
A9479 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SUSPENSE-RESEN     03-22 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SUSPENSE-RESEND-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO: ON THE EDGE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (RESENDING with corrected slug)  
  
 (This TIMELY 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 20 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA _ ``What are we without you, our holy ground? I'm not
giving up what's mine to anybody, even if I perish with it. Even if
the skies open, and even if judgment day comes, we will stay here
where our roots are.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the chilling new jingle broadcast by Serbia's state-run
television with the main evening news, even as NATO has been
revving up its own war machine in an increasingly desperate effort
to impose a peace on the battered Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Serbia's delegation to the second round of peace talks in
Paris this week makes an 11th-hour about-face, negotiations with
the Contact Group _ America, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and
Russia _ over a peace deal look set to end abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs still reject the deal that would give broad autonomy
to the Kosovars, with some 28,000 NATO-led peacekeepers
guaranteeing peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a climb-down by Slobodan Milosevic, technically the
president of Yugoslavia but still in effect the boss of Serbia, its
main part, diplomacy now seems exhausted _ though the talks' two
co-sponsors, Britain's foreign secretary, Robin Cook, and his
French counterpart, Hubert Vedrine, were expected to make a
last-minute appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Western embassies in Belgrade have again been preparing to
evacuate their staff in preparation for oft-threatened NATO air
strikes against military targets in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, say members of his much-reshuffled inner circle, is
still keeping his options open. But they are narrowing fast.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of talks in France last month went his way. To
the annoyance of Madeleine Albright, America's secretary of state,
the divided delegation representing Kosovo's Albanian majority
refused to accept the deal. That weakened NATO's ability to squeeze
the even more recalcitrant Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, however, the leaders of the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) agreed to the deal. Milosevic's team in Paris
have been trying in vain to reopen it. But, if anything, Serb
intransigence seems to have united the sometimes fractious Contact
Group in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's strong-arm tactics on the ground have also
backfired. Since the earlier talks fizzled out on Feb. 23, Kosovo
has seen some of the worst fighting since last October, when, under
NATO pressure, Milosevic agreed to halt his offensive, reduce his
forces and cooperate with unarmed ``verifiers'' from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
   That agreement is now in tatters. More than 80,000 ethnic
Albanians have fled their homes over the past three weeks, as more
Serb troops have been moved in and around Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But if Milosevic was trying to provoke the KLA into abandoning
the deal, he miscalculated.
</P>
<P>
   His next gamble is probably that NATO's missile threats will
prove hollow. Since they were first made last year, western
embassies have twice evacuated staff, while the threats have yet to
be made good.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has probably lost count of the number of western and
Russian emissaries to his palace in Belgrade. But a western
mediator in Paris has warned the Serbs that air strikes would come
in days, rather than weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently unperturbed, Milosevic seems to be digging his heels
in more deeply. He sacked the generals who advised him six months
ago to make concessions to NATO and accept a cease-fire, and
replaced them with loyal hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   They have told their commander-in-chief that to allow NATO
troops into Kosovo without a fight might be a final humiliating
blow to his regime. Many Serbs already blame Milosevic for losing
former Serb lands in Croatia and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is closer to home, its ancient Orthodox monasteries a
symbol, if rarely visited, of Serbia's birthright.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, increasingly fed up with Milosevic and the burden
of sustaining his bankrupt economy with cheap gas, publicly oppose
NATO air strikes but have refused to break a U.N. arms embargo
against Yugoslavia or give it sophisticated air-defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav armed forces are in no position to resist NATO,
which is why they are being dispersed around Serbia for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic may be hoping that NATO will settle for hitting a few
remote installations, causing little real damage to his army. That
would allow him to channel popular anger towards the United States,
and away from himself, while he capitulated on Kosovo to save the
Serb nation from further harm.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a risky gamble. And NATO has its own credibility
to think of. It is due to celebrate its 50th anniversary next
month. Milosevic will not be allowed to spoil the party. &QL; 
