<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9493 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-GOLF-SEMINAR     03-22 1792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-GOLF-SEMINARS-&AMP;SIDEBAR-RESEND-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIZ LINKS: TURN GOLF COURSE INTO YOUR OFFICE; DRIVE HOME A DEAL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from March 15 for those needing)   (This interesting ``separate buy'' business/lifestyle story _ WITH
A SIDEBAR OF USEFUL INFORMATION _ is from ``WORTH'' magazine. To
publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS _ AT 750 (75 WORDS), AND AT 1,200
(225 WORDS). TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,450 WORDS, FOLLOWED BY A
100-WORD SIDEBAR.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By RESHMA MEMON YAQUB  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch financial consultant Kirsten Bratti needs a firm
grasp on the minds and moods of her clients if she's going to aptly
manage their life savings. But she felt she wasn't getting quite
far enough.
</P>
<P>
   So last summer Bratti, who works in San Mateo, Calif., decided
to break the grass ceiling. She took a seminar called Golf 101,
which teaches not the techniques of golf but how to do business on
the course.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, she invited a $400,000 client to play _ and
everything changed. ``Every time we got together, she would bring
up other things in her life and say how fantastic it was that she
was really getting to know me,'' says Bratti. Within a few months,
the client asked Bratti to manage all her assets: $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to doing business on the golf course, it doesn't
matter how well you play the game, as long as you can play the
game. And that's what seminars on business golf teach: how to
develop a relationship with a client between swings, when and how
to talk business, and how not to screw up a transaction with golf
faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that deals are done on the golf course. A
Hyatt survey shows that 93 percent of executives who play golf
agree it's a good way to tighten links with a business associate.
In fact, 35 percent have clinched some of their biggest deals on
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, you won't actually sign your contract on the
fairway. Course time is dedicated to developing the relationship,
to creating shared moments that you can reminisce about later, and
to culling clues about what your client values.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel compelled to talk numbers, don't bring it up until
the middle third of the round, says Dan C. Weilbaker, who teaches a
business golf seminar at Northern Illinois University in DeKalb,
Ill., and organizes an annual golf outing in which his students
practice with executives.
</P>
<P>
   In case the client brings up business, have a few short points
prepared, says Sue Wietzman, a former financial analyst who now
teaches business golf. ``You might only have 20 or 30 seconds
before somebody needs to shoot, so don't have a ten-minute test,''
she days. ``Have five soundbites that you can drop in.''
</P>
<P>
   Experienced golfers don't care about your skill level, as long
as you don't slow down play. But they do care that you know the
rules and etiquette of the game. Not knowing how to tend the pin
when your client is putting, for example, could turn her birdie
into a bogey and her into an enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: If she's putting from the green, you ask whether she
wants the flagstick in or out of the hole. (If she wants the flag
in, you pull it out after she putts but before the ball reaches the
hole.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're not as skilled as the other person, be good-natured
about it, says Peter Titlebaum, as assistant professor of sport
management at the University of Dayton and a teacher of
business-golf seminars.
</P>
<P>
   Don't keep apologizing, and don't blame inanimate objects. If
none of you plays well, consider inviting the clients for a golf
lesson instead of a round, says Weitzman.
</P>
<P>
   If you're much better than your client or boss, don't throw the
game. It could destroy your credibility. At the same time, suspend
your ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is not about you,'' says Will D. Rhame, who runs
BusinessLinks International in Tampa, Fla. ``It's about the person
you invited. Don't focus on trying to impress somebody with your
playing ability. Focus on being the best host.''
</P>
<P>
   And keep your golf tips to yourself, says Weitzman. Keep the
emphasis on fun, rather than competition. Rhame recommends agreeing
in advance to be lax: Mulligans are okay. Picking up the ball if
you're overmatched on a hole is okay.
</P>
<P>
   Half the people in the Hyatt survey agree that the way a person
plays golf is a reflection of the way he does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone's willing to cheat on the golf course, they're
probably willing to cheat in a business deal,'' says Titlebaum.
``If they throw clubs and swear, it may tell me they don't have as
much control as I would like for people I want to be associated
with.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye out for other clues. Bratti noticed that one
particular client liked to mull things over before making a
decision. ``She took quite a while before lining herself up and
hitting the ball,'' she says. Bratti now uses that knowledge when
doing business with her: ``Before something needs to be done, I put
it in writing and give her enough time to think about it,'' Bratti
says. Some of her other clients prefer to wing it or have decisions
made for them. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scope out the course beforehand, says Ilene Sokoloff, who used
to run a business-golf seminar and now writes about golf. If you
don't know soft spikes are required, you could end up having to buy
your client and yourself new shoes _ and you'll look unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   If you bring a female client to play during men-only hours, or
vice versa, you'll embarrass everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Get to know course employees so you're treated like a regular in
front of your client, adds Rhame, who's the co-author along with
James A. McNulty of ``Pat Summerall's Business Golf: The Art of
Developing Relationships Through Golf'' (Birch Lane Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   On game day, says Rhame, arrive early. Have your golf bag put on
the driver's side, especially if you're a woman, says Sokoloff. It
creates equal footing. Greet the client as he drives in. Pay in
advance so the client understands he's your guest. Have a gift
waiting, ideally a golf shirt with your company logo.
</P>
<P>
   Don't scrimp on anything. If the client needs golf balls, don't
buy her three _ buy her a dozen. Pay for the cart, too. Exception:
If the client wants to walk, you walk.
</P>
<P>
   Make it a foursome. Invite two other people who will interest or
be of help to your client and who will help keep the conversation
moving, says Rhame. Or let the client bring someone, says Bill
Storer, who runs Business Golf Strategies in Basking Ridge, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Pulitano, CEO of Computing Concepts, a computer integrating
company, played with a client who was a purchasing agent, and the
client brought his father, who was a purchasing agent for another
company. ``We picked up another account,'' says Pulitano, who pays
for his employees to attend Storer's seminars.
</P>
<P>
   Establish the format in advance. One of the most conducive for
business is best ball, with two-person teams. After you both tee
off, each of you plays from the spot where the better drive landed
and so forth for the rest of the hole. That makes you and your
client a team, calling each other partner and working off each
other's success, says Rhame. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 225 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1200) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember _ during the game, you're being watched as closely as
you are watching. Storer tells the recent story of a salesman who
made the mistake of drinking during a round and tipped the cart on
a sharp turn. His client fell out and was knocked unconscious.
After recovering, the client didn't stick around to do more
business. The salesman was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Woo, who runs Golf 101, encourages women to play off the
middle tees, where men usually start, instead of the forward tees,
which used to be called the ladies' tees but are now less
chauvinistically referred to as the beginners' tees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're out there trying to build a relationship, you don't
want to be coming in and out of the conversation,'' she says. If
the more difficult drive holds a woman's game back, she should tell
the other players she'll move her ball from where it lands to where
theirs land, to keep the game moving.
</P>
<P>
   If you're playing with someone who plays from the forward tees,
don't sit in the cart and wait for her to tee off, says Rhame.
``Give her the courtesy to get out of the cart, and go stand with
her like she stood with you.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, send a thank-you note, maybe even an article about an
interest that your client casually mentioned. Follow up with a
phone call to set up an appointment to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People take my calls more frequently after we've played a
round of golf,'' says Dave Lakhani, director of sales at Cougar
Mountain Software in Boise, Idaho. And that's what it's all about. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Reshma Memon Yaqub is a staff writer at WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SIDEBAR FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE TO TEE IT UP &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS GOLF STRATEGIES &LR;  &QL; : $2,500 and up. Basking Ridge, N.J.
908-204-9350  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESSLINKS INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QL; : $2,500 to $10,000 for a half to
full day.
Tampa, Fla. 813-269-7599  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAN WEILBAKER'S STUDENT OUTING &LR;  &QL; : $100. West Chicago, Ill.
815-753-6216
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOLF 101 &LR;  &QL; : $250 for a two-hour one-on-one seminar, 43,500 for
a half
day, or $7,000 for a full day. Berkeley, Calif. 800-722-8909  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOLF MATTERS &LR;  &QL; : $500 for a half-day. Deerfield, Ill.
847-945-0390
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PETER TITLEBAUM SEMINARS &LR;  &QL; : $1,500 to $5,000 for a day-long
seminar.
Dayton, Ohio. 937-229-4222  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
