<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-BIZ-STOCKS-WORTH-     03-22 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-BIZ-STOCKS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLES APART: VALUATING THE BIG THREE SKI-RESORT COMPANIES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: VAIL, Colo. and Vancouver, B.C.)   (This 1,050-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By JONATHAN BUTLER  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Global warming notwithstanding, the big three ski stocks _ Vail
Resorts, American Skiing, and Intrawest _ have a lot going for them
these days.
</P>
<P>
   Snowboards and new,
easier-to-turn-without-falling-and-snapping-fibula skis are
propelling more American families to the slopes _ where, in posh
locations like Vail, Colo., Mom and Dad can bid adieu to an average
of $300 per family member per day.
</P>
<P>
   Geographic diversification has made these companies less
vulnerable to capricious snowfalls. They've also taken a page from
Disney and become more adept in the art of total resort management.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there may be few better investing plays, at least in
the long run, on the as-yet-unrefuted maxim that the rich get
richer.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, though, there may be a few drawbacks. First,
because swooshing down mountains on plastic slats is hardly a basic
human need, ski stocks tend to be hypersensitive to swings in the
economy (the $10,000 family ski trip is still regarded as
postponable even in many well-to-do households).
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, fears of a looming recession caused the stocks
of the big three to tumble an average of 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A second drawback is the market's relative inexperience with
these companies. All three listed their shares for the first time
on the New York Stock Exchange only in 1997. And even professional
analysts are still ill-at-ease when it comes to determining the
value of a ski stock.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are probably best viewed as two businesses
rolled into one: entertainment and real-estate development.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment side, which typically accounts for about 75
percent of revenue, is fairly straightforward. At Vail, lift-ticket
sales provided $147 million, or 34 percent of total revenue, during
the 1997-98 season, up 8 percent from the previous winter.
</P>
<P>
   Food service accounted for another 12 percent of Vail's revenue.
Retail sales, equipment rentals, property-management fees,
instruction, and summer activities provided the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that the way to value this side of Vail's
business is to project its future cash flow (its earnings before
interest expenses, taxes, depreciation, and amortization).
</P>
<P>
   They then multiply its EBITDA forecast by nine _ a rule of thumb
that's based on historic ski-resort transaction prices. Goldman
Sachs, for example, values the entertainment side of Vail's
business at $1.125 billion, or $32 a share (before subtracting
debt).
</P>
<P>
   This is based on Goldman's forecast that Vail's EBITDA in the
fiscal year ending in July will reach $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street hasn't come to a similar consensus about how to
value the real-estate side of the business _ the subdivision and
sale of property, typically in the forms of time-shares, homes, and
undeveloped lots.
</P>
<P>
   This is tricky terrain because the ski companies themselves each
advocate a different valuation approach.
</P>
<P>
   When American Skiing went public in November 1997, its
investment bankers at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette advocated
applying the EBITDA model equally to the entertainment and
real-estate operations and raising the multiple to ten.
</P>
<P>
   Conveniently, the resulting valuation of $18 a share generated
just the amount needed ($265 million) to fund American Skiing's
acquisitions of Steamboat Springs and Heavenly Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A major drawback of this technique, however, is that cash flow
from a ski resort's real-estate operations can swing wildly from
year to year _ in the case of American Skiing, from $1.7 million in
1997 to $17.6 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Intrawest, based in Vancouver, British Columbia, urges investors
to apply a multiple not to cash flow but to net income. That's
because Intrawest is something of a real-estate profit machine _
selling between 1,200 and 1,400 condominiums a year at locations
ranging from Stratton in Vermont to Whistler outside Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Jarvis, Intrawest's chief financial officer, says the
company could keep up this pace for at least another 15 years.
Intrawest also likes the earnings-multiple approach because it's
the tool Wall Street uses to gauge hot growth stocks that carry
lofty valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Vail prefers a third valuation model _ one that emphasizes the
book value of its real estate. This is partly because Vail sells
few condominiums on its own, leaving that job to its developer
partners. Rather, it views its real estate as a strategic asset for
enhancing the value of its total operation.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Resnick, a Vail managing director, points out that hastily
completing a condo project (to get the sales on the books) can mar
the total environment at a resort.
</P>
<P>
   A patient real-estate strategy, he adds, can also produce
longer-term benefits, such as when Vail bought Arrowhead Mountain
in 1993 and focused on developing lifts and trails that boosted
skier volume 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Vail would rather an investor follow these steps for assessing
its value: Add the book value per share of its real estate ($3.98)
to the per-share value of its entertainment side ($32, as
previously calculated). Then subtract corporate debt minus any cash
on hand. Result: $28.60 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Vail's stock fares less well under the
valuation approaches advocated by its rivals. Applying American
Skiing's EBITDA model to Vail produces a valuation of just $23 a
share, while Intrawest's earnings-multiple approach lowers it even
further to $19. (The stock is currently trading at just above $21.)
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern holds true at all three companies. Intrawest's
stock is worth only $16 a share under the Vail model and $18 under
American Skiing's EBITDA approach.
</P>
<P>
   But its value rises to $19 under the earnings-multiple approach
that, for reasons that should be clear, it likes best. (Intrawest's
stock is currently trading below $17 a share.)
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, American Skiing's blended EBITDA model still gives it
the most favorable result: $16 a share. The company can't be
assessed on its earnings because it hasn't had any lately (due to
the high depreciation and interest payments associated with an
aggressive development program).
</P>
<P>
   The Vail model, meanwhile, pegs American Skiing at $11 a share _
an amount that's still more than $3 above the trading prices.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't likely that these resorts will abandon their accounting
disagreements anytime soon. Nevertheless, an investor who wants to
become a mogul should, at the very least, know that there are
different ways of valuing one. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Jonathan Butler, a former writer at WORTH,
recently served as the chief financial officer at a small start-up
company in New York.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,050-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
