<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9503 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOOD-NEWS-US-STOCKS-W     03-22 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOD-NEWS-US-STOCKS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELENTLESS U.S. ECONOMY IS STILL RUNNING HARD  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Financial Editors)   (This 1,000-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 By JIM JUBAK  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What goes 'round, comes 'round. But not quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   After outperforming the economies of the rest of the developed
world for most of the 1990s, the U.S. economy has begun an almost
invisible restructuring that will keep it growing faster than
Europe or Japan through 2000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't supposed to happen. Historically, countries that have
enjoyed a long period of competitive advantage go soft and lose
their edge.
</P>
<P>
   With profits pouring in, companies stop counting pennies and
allow costs to rise. Workers demand to share the pie, and wages
creep upward and then soar out of control. Management gets
complacent about products and manufacturing technologies and fails
to invest enough to stay on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, beaten-down foreign-competitors cut costs to the
bone, squeeze concessions out of workers worried about losing their
jobs, and gamble on new products, new management structures, and
new manufacturing processes, figuring that unless they take these
risks they'll be out of business pretty quickly anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they've erased the cost advantage enjoyed by companies that
call the leading economy home. And then, riding the momentum, these
upstart companies sprint into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the story that played out in the 1980s and 1990s
between Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Japanese companies seemed about to take over the
world. Sumitomo Bank was going to overwhelm U.S. financial
companies such as Citicorp (now Citigroup) and Merrill Lynch.
Hitachi was going to put IBM out of the mainframe business.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, however, Sumitomo has abandoned its retail-banking
drive in the U.S. and retreated to the home islands. IBM's biggest
competition isn't Hitachi but American companies such as Dell
Computer and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. economy now in the longest economic recovery in
its history _ 95 months and counting, as of February _ U.S.
companies should be showing signs of going soft. After all, the
fear that drove the top-to-bottom restructuring of companies is
well in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But 1998 didn't show that at all. Even though the U.S.
unemployment rate hovers near a low 4.5 percent, layoffs _ as
measured by the Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas employment survey _
surged last year.
</P>
<P>
   As of November, the pace was running better than 30 percent
above the 1997 rate. With a month still to report, the 1998 totals
were 28 percent above the annual average for 1995 through 1997 and
just 7 percent short of the layoff record for the decade set in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Where are all these layoffs coming from? Troubled firms account
for some. It's no surprise, for example, that Boeing, a company
struggling with plunging profits as Asian airlines cancel orders
for new planes, decided to cut 48,000 jobs by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But companies with the lowest costs in their industry have also
joined the trend. Exxon, a company known for its attention to
saving every penny, will bring this sensibility to its merger with
Mobil, and the combined company will cut 7 percent of its work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the layoff numbers fully capture the trend. Companies in
the U.S. are clearly not relaxing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in December, General Electric decided that this
fierce, fast-moving competitor needed to run even faster. Rather
than putting more of its profit into a long-standing program of
buying back its shares, GE stepped up its plan to purchase
floundering competitors in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies seem to be running just as hard as they did a
decade ago, even though nobody is chasing them.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence from Japan and Europe is that the competitive gap
between those economies and the U.S. economy may actually be
growing.
</P>
<P>
   For example, hourly compensation in European manufacturing
already runs 12 percent above the wage rates in the same sectors of
the U.S. economy, and politics on the continent are pushing wages
higher.
</P>
<P>
   France has recently mandated a 35-hour workweek (without a wage
cut) by 2000, and politicians in Italy and Spain have begun to
consider similar laws. (Compensation in Europe's largest economy,
Germany, is even higher _ about 55 percent above U.S. wage levels.)
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, layoffs are slow in coming despite a desperate need to
cut costs in industry after industry. Plant closings have been few
and far between, and job losses after most mergers have been
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting profit squeeze at Japanese companies is taking
place just as Japanese banks have almost stopped lending, and this
has cut deeply into the ability of Japanese companies to invest in
capital equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Japanese makers of computer chips and other
semiconductors are lagging behind their U.S. and Taiwanese
competitors in buying next-generation production equipment that
radically cuts manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
   When global demand recovers for chips and other products, all
but the very biggest and financially strongest Japanese companies
will find themselves facing U.S. corporations that have higher
profit margins because they have become more efficient
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to figure out from this which stock market will be
most attractive to investors as the global economy gradually digs
out from the wreckage of the financial and economic crisis that
began in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As growth rates from Thailand to Brazil inch up and consumers
around the world start to buy goods and services again, the profits
will flow disproportionately to lean, aggressive U.S. corporations.
</P>
<P>
   It's this scenario that may actually justify the Wall Street
projections that earnings per share (before special items) will
climb 21 percent in 1999 for the stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 Stock Index, and why many analysts are calling for even higher
earnings growth of 23 percent for the companies in the S&AMP;P
Industrials.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate restructuring that produced annual gains of 20
percent or more for the S&AMP;P 500 in each of the past four years may
not have run out of steam yet. In fact, it might just be getting a
second wind. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Jim Jubak is senior markets
editor for Microsoft Investor (www.investor.msn.com).)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
