<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTHS BEHIND THE PUBLIC PERCEPTION OF POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With roughly a million people behind bars in this
country at any given moment, the single most crucial problem the
police face is the widespread perception that they're not fair.
</P>
<P>
   Every poll on the topic shows that most people think the cops
are tougher on those without power, wealth or position.
Overwhelmingly, Americans believe that people with connections or
resources routinely are given passes for conduct that would land a
lesser individual in the slammer.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I can't ignore the sad case of Michael J. Sinclair.
He came across the border from Canada on March 5. He was missing
from active duty with the U.S. Marine Corps. He was packing a
stolen, loaded .45-caliber pistol. The U.S. Customs Service turned
him over to the New York State Police.
</P>
<P>
   And what did the state police do with him? Did they charge him
with felonies for possessing the stolen pistol? Did they turn him
over to the federal government's AWOL unit? No, in direction
violation their own policies, they released Michael J. Sinclair
into the custody of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Sinclair's father, by the way, is Col. John H.
Sinclair, director of the Vermont State Police.
</P>
<P>
   When word of this reached me, I started calling around to nail
down the facts. I got a serious runaround. Col. Sinclair refused to
discuss it. New York State Police Senior Investigator Bob Denny was
involved in all this. When he heard me mention Michael J.
Sinclair's name, he immediately booted the call to Lt. Bruce
Dunning. Dunning heard Sinclair's name and said he would call right
back. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   After several phone calls to Dunning _ and after I told whoever
answered the phone the last time that my next call would be to the
office of New York State Police Superintendent Jim McMahon, I
finally heard from the Troop B commander, Maj. Bill Warburton. He
asked if he could talk to me about this the next morning. I figured
he had some bad news to break to his bosses, so I said fine.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Warburton told me the next day, it's true. The Sinclair kid,
he said, wasn't AWOL in a technical sense, so the state police
didn't have to turn him over to the feds. Yes, he had the loaded
gun, but it had been stolen from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was suicidal,'' the major explained.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'm not sure how many psychiatrists are serving in Troop B
of the New York State Police, but I do know that proper procedure
involving a suicidal guy with a loaded gun is to get him to a
secure medical facility and let a judge figure out what to do with
him. Maj. Warburton, however, decided that wasn't the best course
of action here. Instead, a call went out to Col. Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father comes over with tears in his eyes,'' the major
said. ``I don't care how it looks. You know, I would have done it
if it had been your kid, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he would have. You can decide for yourself how likely that
scenario might be. The problem is that, if the polls are accurate,
you'll probably conclude that Michael J. Sinclair got special
treatment not because of his emotional problems but because his
father is a high-ranking police officer.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent annual report, McMahon wrote, ``Society
bestows upon police officers the highest degree of public trust ...
The public has a right to demand, and indeed expect, that police
officers perform their duties with the utmost degree of integrity,
fairness and professionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's discretion involved in police work _ and properly
so.
</P>
<P>
   But it's precisely the trust that McMahon mentioned that's
placed in such serious peril by preferential conduct like this.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
