<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9550 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-22 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING EQUAL OPPORTUNITY FIELDS OF DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Human beings learn by making mistakes, sometimes
even male human beings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week I made a big mistake and learned that modern young
women can play hardball _ literally. I called 14-year-old star
baseball player Carey Myslewski a boy and, boy, am I sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' Carey said, when I phoned her. ``I've had umpires
call me `young man' before, when I cut my hair short.''
</P>
<P>
   No excuse. It's a male thing. We have the ``don't get it'' gene.
</P>
<P>
   I had asked readers what San Francisco could name for the late
Joe DiMaggio. Carey's dad, Rik Myslewski, sent an e-mail suggesting
fixing kids' baseball fields in Joe's name. He said they're so bad
his kid risks twisted ankles on rutted base paths.
</P>
<P>
   I called Myslewski to find out his child's name, but couldn't
reach him. So I made the dumb male assumption: Boys play hardball.
Thus I referred to Carey as his ``baseball-loving son.'' It turned
out Carey is a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Just my luck. Carey says she's the only girl in the Pony League,
or 7th- and 8th-grade division, of San Francisco's Recreation and
Park youth baseball league. This 8th-grader also starred on Hoover
Middle School's baseball and basketball teams, and is the city
champion in the 800-meter run.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the best guy on the team,'' Andy Cedarblade, her coach,
said wryly. ``She gets some looks, but people only underestimate
her once.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Carey how she handles it when boys give her trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of ignore them,'' she said, ``Then I strike them
out.''
</P>
<P>
   My feminist editor suggested that I should do penance for my
male chauvinist assumptions by trying to hit some of Carey
Myslewski's high inside fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a better way to make amends. Maybe some good can
come of this.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Carey was hurt by a sexist mistake somewhat worse than
my own, and by her favorite team, the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the team asked Hoover Middle School to select kids
to be bat boys during the last home game of the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They offered it to anybody on the Hoover baseball team, and I
was on the Hoover baseball team and I was chosen,'' Carey said.
``But they hadn't really guessed that there were girls on the
Hoover team, and they said I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked her how she felt when she was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt disappointed,'' she said. ``I would have liked to have
done it. I was a little angry at the organization, not the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a straight-A student, she's a real baseball girl.
Her mom, Marilyn Myslewski, once told Carey after a loss, ``You
don't have to win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``Yes, you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason the Giants gave for not allowing Carey to be a bat
kid was that the duties included working in the locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents don't want to bash the Giants. They just think the
team should have let her be a bat kid, or whatever you'd call it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have let a girl do it, A, because Candlestick is a
public accommodation and, B, because it's the '90s,'' Rik Myslewski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carey's parents wrote the Giants about the matter, but didn't
receive a response.
</P>
<P>
   I called Giants Vice President Larry Baer, and he said it was a
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   It happens to the best of us.
</P>
<P>
   Baer said both boys and girls are allowed to be honorary bat
kids, but girls have to stay out of the locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Carey Myslewski is a tough, quiet kid. She doesn't want anything
special from the Giants. When she was 11 she was hit in the mouth
by a ball that took a bad hop off a ruined infield.
</P>
<P>
   According to her dad, ``She kept with the play, made a perfect
peg to home and then worried about her lip.''
</P>
<P>
   She's almost worn out her tape of the movie ``A League of Their
Own,'' about a women's baseball team, and she loves Tom Hanks'
line, ``There's no crying in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But her very favorite line in the movie is: ``Baseball is
supposed to be hard. If it wasn't hard, everybody would play it.''
</P>
<P>
   So here's a baseball idea. Carey's mom, who is a fund-raising
consultant, says that the Giants could become the leader in
repairing San Francisco's youth baseball fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the consortium of people who own the Giants
represents the elite of San Francisco, and they're so generous in
so many other ways,'' Marilyn Myslewski said. ``The easiest way to
do it would be to set up a public/ private partnership through
Friends of Rec and Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are leaders in the field of dreams, and kids like
Carey Myslewski dream of better fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``In moving to the new ballpark, we're thinking of having a
fund-raiser, black tie, for a good cause,'' Baer said. ``This could
be a perfect beneficiary.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
