<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UNSEINFELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ABC SHOW COMES CLOSE TO CLONING `SEINFELD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Network television has shot itself so many times in the foot
trying to replicate ``Seinfeld'' it probably has no toes left.''
</P>
<P>
   I got it! Let's put a single twenty- or thirtysomething in a
lavish New York City apartment he could never afford, surround him
with some whacky, zany, cuckoo friends _ one of whom has to have
really bad hair _ and, well, yada, yada, yada ...
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't worked. Careers and viewing time have been wasted as
Hollywood chases that phantom Holy Grail. When will the networks
learn?
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a mid-season show on ABC that doesn't look like
``Seinfeld,'' but sure sounds like it. More importantly, it feels
like it, in no small part because its creator and executive
producer is former ``Seinfeld'' writer Peter Mehlman.
</P>
<P>
   Premiering Wednesday, ``It's like, you know ...'' comes late in
the fray, even by mid-season replacement standards. While other
mid-season fill-ins have been successful in recent years (``King of
the Hill,'' ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Becker,'' to name just a few),
this series, with two of the best casting moves in memory, leaves
you scratching your head: What took ABC so long to put it on the
air?
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantages are that in a year where the fall shows were
generally regarded as a fairly mediocre crop, you are set apart
from that,'' Mehlman said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   First great casting move: The central character is
self-possessed, superficial and absolutely fascinated with the
banal. Sounds like Jerry, doesn't it? So who is he?
</P>
<P>
   Try Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never see in television where the actual city where the show
takes place has an actual impact on the show,'' Mehlman said.
``Even `Seinfeld,' which was known for its New York sensibility,
was not dominated by the city.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure there will be some Los Angeles-based critics dismissing
the jibes at the city as passe (surprisingly, the pilot did not
test well).
</P>
<P>
   Here is the short take: Arthur (Chris Eigeman) is a New York
City writer who moves to L.A. for two months to write a book about
why he hates the city, even though he has never been there.
</P>
<P>
   He moves in with his former college roommate Robbie (Steve
Eckholdt), who despite making millions off of televising Yom Kippur
services (``Pay Per Jew'') lives in the massive guest house of his
friend, Shrug (Evan Handler).
</P>
<P>
   Now understand that Shrug is a ``trustafarian'' who lives off a
trust fund, never worked a day in his life and occasionally feels
guilty about it. He lost all his hair because of stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrug! I love Shrug!'' Handler said recently. ``I want to go
back and do more. Shrug is just a result of his circumstances. He
is socially inept and unaware, yet savant-like in his wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   Did we mention everyone in Los Angeles is rich? For example,
Shrug was convinced he borrowed $50,000 from Robbie, who doesn't
remember loaning the money. Finally, Robbie does recall the loan:
Shrug pulls out a wad of crumpled cash from his pocket: ``I only
got like 20 (thousand) on me.'' Robbie shrugs at Shrug.
``Whatever,'' he replies, stuffing the bills in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The inanities of ``Seinfeld'' are still there, such as an
extended discussion about why Elliott Gould (in a cameo) was
driving a Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what's so great about L.A.,'' Robbie cheerily replies
to Arthur questioning whether it merited conversation. ``You don't
even have to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where ``It's like ...'' resonates its ``Seinfeld''
roots. ``When you look at the success of `Seinfeld' and look how
the networks took it and tried to copy it they took a lot of
elements ... but the most important elements were not taken: the
incredibly natural dialogue,'' Mehlman said.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the cast is the delightfully airy Lauren (a
grown-up A.J. Langer of ``My So-Called Life''), a transplanted
masseuse/process server from Columbus, Ohio, whose philosophy is
``don't have a philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the funniest bit of casting since John Wayne was tapped
to play Genghis Khan _ only this time it's intentional _ Jennifer
Grey stars as ... Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Grey is Robbie's celebrity neighbor, far removed from her
``Dirty Dancing''/``Red Dawn''/``Ferris Bueller's Day Off''
successes. She is now unrecognizable (but extremely attractive),
the result of a complete nose job that prompts Arthur to ask her if
she got ``just one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Jennifer in the back of my mind because we were
friends,'' Mehlman said. ``She was totally game for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were considered like ``Flashdance'' star Jennifer Beals
but they would not have had the comedic impact of Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Only six of the 13 episodes shot are slated to air this season.
Mehlman and Handler kept talking about ``if'' the network picks up
the show this year. It is a no-brainer. This is great fun.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, so was ``Cupid.'' Of course, it got axed just before
Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Below the Norm: ABC will be trucking out another late premiere,
``The Norm Show,'' at 9:30 p.m. EST Wednesday. The sitcom stars
Norm Macdonald (late of ``Saturday Night Live'') and Laurie Metcalf
(``Roseanne''). Macdonald plays a former professional hockey player
banned from the game for gambling, who must work as a social worker
or go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   This is a pretty weak offering, and a waste of both Macdonald
and Metcalf. The only reason to tune in to this show Wednesday is
you probably won't get many more opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
