<SLUG> BC-WRITING-TABLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITING TABLES HAVE VALUE BEYOND WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Almost any table can function as a desk or
writing table. The table becomes distinguished by the addition of a
drawer or the lack of one, the amount of detailing, such as leather
inlay writing surface, carvings, painted design, inlaid woods,
hardware, the type of wood and/or finish.
</P>
<P>
   Writing table is a contemporary term coined by 18th-century
cabinetmakers for various types of tables with drawers below and/or
a superstructure of racks, pigeon holes, small cupboards for
stationery and perhaps secret compartments for private papers (as
there were no safes back then).
</P>
<P>
   A writing table also is called a davenport, which is a special
English desk or table that originated in the late 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   The writing table evolved from the Spanish writing cabinet or
box, called a vargueno, which rested on a set of collapsible legs.
Because of its easy portability, this simple box, which also stores
writing implements, can be moved from room to room and house to
house. In 18th-century England, cabinetmakers were combining the
portable writing box with a set of permanent legs. English
cabinetmaker Thomas Chippendale designed a variety of writing
tables with graceful lines and Rococo ornamentation in the late
1700s.
</P>
<P>
   To enlarge the work surface of a writing table, early
cabinetmakers included a writing drawer, where the front panel
dropped down to create extra writing space when pulled out.
Sometimes it was an extension of the top, which pulled out, like a
dining room table leaf, and was supported by its own set of legs,
which were often cleverly concealed within the writing table.
</P>
<P>
   Pop-up writing surfaces were also popular. This pop-up surface
was part of the table top when not in use, and easel-like when put
into service.
</P>
<P>
   Some writing tables even included a brass or wooden galley
(decorative railing), where there was sufficient room to place
necessary writing implements and a few small books. In some cases,
this section, which rested on the top of the desk, included fitted
drawers for inkwells, quills, sand, embossed wafers (for sealing
the envelope) and stationery.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th century, the writing table, which was often referred
to as a library table, was placed in the center of the room. Thomas
Sheraton designed the drum writing table. Chippendale created the
round rent table in 1770, which like the drum table had drawers all
around and a pedestal base.
</P>
<P>
   An original or reproduction Louis XV writing table is still
considered very de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   A lady's writing desk, which was smaller than a man's writing
desk, would often be open beneath the writing surface so the writer
could take advantage of the warmth of the fireplace, with a
concealed pop-up fire screen to shield her face from the heat of
the scorching flames.
</P>
<P>
   Tables can be found in used furniture, consignment and antiques
shops, as well as flea markets and classified ads of newspapers,
for anywhere from under $50 to thousands of dollars and under $200
for a new table.
</P>
<P>
   Writing tables were once a means of status and affluence. Today,
they are a necessity and often hold more than quills and paper.
</P>
<P>
   A sturdy plain rectangular table can be perfect for a computer
work station. Storage can always be added in the form of a rolling
open metal wire cart, two-drawer file cabinet or stack of wicker
baskets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
