<HEADER>
A9566 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      03-22 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDSMOBILE SEDAN A STYLISH PERFORMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOG GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For '99, Intrigue boasts a potent V-6 engine that
improves power and performance. And, supposedly, it's nearly
maintenance-free.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigue needs an ego boost after more than two years of going
up against import heavyweights Honda Accord and Toyota Camry.
Marketed directly against the duo's high-end V-6 models, Intrigue
has caused some ripples in the midsize-sedan mainstream, if not a
very big splash.
</P>
<P>
   But Oldsmobile is on a roll, with the success of its compact
Alero, the continuing praise for the big Aurora, and the Aurora V-8
engine's overwhelming success in the Indy Racing League.
</P>
<P>
   Indy racing hasn't had a strong crossover effect the way NASCAR
has for Pontiac. But for those in the know, the Motorsport Aurora
V-8 has proved to be a sturdy power plant, eclipsing rival
Infiniti. This could signify that Oldsmobile's civilian engines are
bulletproof, too, though not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   The new Twin Cam 3.5-liter engine is an outgrowth of the Aurora
V-8 program, replacing the venerable pushrod 3.8 engine. It's
smoother and stronger, though highway gas mileage is a bit off in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   As well as being a good performer on the highway, it's also
interesting on paper. With a total of four camshafts and two-piece
cast-aluminum-block design, the V-6 seems more like something
designed by Alfa Romeo than Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   For it to become a mainstream engine in a midsize General Motors
sedan is somewhat remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile says that other than routine oil and filter changes,
the engine is zero maintenance for 100,000 miles, including no
attention needed for spark plugs and engine coolant. I don't know
about you, but I think I'd get nervous after about 50,000 miles of
ignoring my engine.
</P>
<P>
   With its Twin Cam V-6, the Intrigue proved to be a quick and
enjoyable driver. The engine has lots of torque right off the line
and soars smoothly to its upper rpm limits. It's also smooth and
quiet, with refined behavior and minimal vibration, and it runs on
regular.
</P>
<P>
   On a quick freeway drive to Cottonwood, the Intrigue proved to
be a comfortable cruiser. Just past Black Canyon City, it sprinted
up the long, steep incline to Sunset Point with minimal effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Intrigue, a good-looking sedan with styling cues that echo
Oldsmobile's flagship, the Aurora sedan, is surprisingly roomy
inside. The GLS model we tested was plush and loaded with comfort
and convenience features, including an excellent Delco-Bose stereo
system. At nearly $1,000, including a 12-CD changer, it had better
be good.
</P>
<P>
   Another expensive option on the test car was a set of chromed
aluminum wheels at $700. They do look sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the wheel, the Intrigue feels like an import, and you can
tell that Olds designers and engineers spent a lot of time studying
the competition from Europe and Japan. Handling is quick and
balanced, though Intrigue feels too plush and heavy to be
considered sporty.
</P>
<P>
   It shares the same basic chassis design as Pontiac Grand Prix,
which has a muscle-car flair, and Buick Regal, a nicely designed
luxury ride with a softer feel. Intrigue is the most distinctive,
with its broad-shouldered Aurora styling and low-front aspect.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to steal customers from the imports, Intrigue has the
disadvantage of not offering stick shift, unlike V6-powered foes
Camry, Nissan Maxima and Volkswagen Passat. Accord offers stick in
four-cylinder models only. Many foreign-car drivers like to shift
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser GX version of Intrigue starts at just more than
$21,000, about comparable with the V-6 versions of the imports, but
no real bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile seems to be back in action after a few years of
marginal existence as GM's weak-sister division. It looked for a
while that America's oldest continuous car company barely would
make it past its 100th birthday before keeling over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a collection of attractive new products and a lock on
IRL competition, Oldsmobile seems back in the race. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Oldsmobile Intrigue GLS &QL; 
 &QL; 
- Vehicle type: &QL; 
Five-passenger, four-door sedan, front-wheel drive. &QL; 
- Base price: &QL; 
$24,945. &QL; 
- Price as tested: &QL; 
$27,410. &QL; 
- Engine: &QL; 
3.5-liter V-6, 215 horsepower at 5,600 rpm, 230 pound-feet of
torque at 5,200 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: &QL; 
Four-speed automatic. &QL; 
- Curb weight: &QL; 
3,434 pounds. &QL; 
- Wheelbase: &QL; 
109 inches. &QL; 
- EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
19 city, 27 highway. &QL; 
- Highs: &QL; 
Cool new engine. Nice styling. Overall refinement. &QL; 
- Lows: &QL; 
No stick shift. Heavy handling. Highway gas mileage. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at bob.golfen(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
