<SLUG> BC-BOTANICAL-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN ONE-UPS THE DESERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Due to circumstances beyond our control, the Sonoran
desert's wildflower display will be puny this year.
</P>
<P>
   A dry winter is producing a dull spring - unlike last year, one
of the best for viewing desert vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   But floraphiles can take heart. A glorious display of native
foliage is waiting at the Desert Botanical Garden in Phoenix, where
the experts have fooled Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The trick? Water.
</P>
<P>
   When plants are watered, they bloom. Irrigation can do for
captive plants what wild plants must depend on rain for. Gardeners
have been watering their charges diligently, and the results are
rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is at the mercy of the weather,'' said Mary Irish,
the botanical garden's director of public horticulture. ``We can
make things happen . . . There are the same species here that you
would see on the desert and many, many more. It's a good substitute
for the color of the desert. ''
</P>
<P>
   Of the garden's 145 acres (including administrative offices and
research acreage), 45 are open to the public, featuring a mile of
walking trails that wind past trees, flowers, cacti and succulents,
including a separate Cactus House and Succulent House.
</P>
<P>
   With plenty of drinking fountains and comfortable benches along
the way, it's a comfortable and pleasant expedition. Garden docents
are stationed at various points to explain and demonstrate the
magic of the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors learn, for example, about the healing benefits of aloe
leaves and objects made from desert plants.
</P>
<P>
   People are surprised by what they see, Irish said. Most expect
some cactus, some succulents, some rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much more than that,'' she said. ``I think they think
it's very stark until they come to this garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Such beauty doesn't escape the notice of winter visitors,
accustomed to vastly different species of plant life in their home
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so different for us,'' said Minnesotan Phyllis Clover,
whose garden in Duluth features such perennial flowers as
geraniums.
</P>
<P>
   She and husband Charles have made the Phoenix garden a must-see
during their annual two-month stay in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come every year for 7 years,'' she said. ``This is where
we bring guests who come to visit us.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Irv and Mabel Kaufman are habitual garden-goers when
they visit their son, Alan Kaufman, a Scottsdale attorney. The
couple are avid gardeners back home in New York, where they have a
place in the city and also a house in a wooded area in East
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Mabel Kaufman is the former editor of a horticultural newsletter
in her community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get tired of it,'' Irv Kaufman said of the botanical
garden. ``I love it - the wide range, the shapes and adaptability
and the habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marvelous place.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish well understands the appeal her garden has for
out-of-towners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they like is that it's such a potent display of plants
that are not (available) where they live,'' she said. ``And it's a
really big garden. It has a powerful impact on you. Most people
don't realize there are so many plants that are desert plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the garden's most prized specimens are four crested
saguaros - surreal-looking cactus that develop tangled crowns
instead of stately arms. The plants are a botanical enigma,
baffling scientists as to how they develop their unusual shapes.
The phenomenon is apparently due to unchecked cell differentiation
that occurs only once in many thousands of saguaros.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the cascalote tree, which is located near the
garden's Webster Center and produces glorious yellow blossoms, and
the agave, from which tequila and mescal are made.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd favorite is the skunk tree, an Australian plant named
for its odor that increases with atmospheric humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will knock you out,'' Irish said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   What visitors often find hard to believe is that this is not a
natural desert preserve. Except for the creosote trees, all of the
vegetation has been transplanted to this spot and carefully
propagated like backyard landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives a very naturalistic feel,'' Irish said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only our own Sonoran desert but similar regions from around
the world are represented. There is a piece of the Australian
desert as well as the desert of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Irish said, ``the South African bulbs are blooming
like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other specialty areas include the vegetable and herb garden, the
native crop garden (featuring such traditional crops as corn,
beans, gourds, squash and cotton), the mesquite bosque (natural
shelters formed by mesquite root bundles) and the Hispanic gardens
(plants originally brought to Arizona from Mexico).
</P>
<P>
   A stand of telescopes is located near the Mountain Vista ramada
for viewing the far edges of the garden as well as such sites as
Camelback Mountain and the Superstition Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the garden is the Patio Cafe and Ullman
Terrace, where visitors can enjoy lunch under the trees. Arcadia
Farms sells sandwiches, salads, muffins, cookies and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this the perfect place to have lunch?'' Helen Wooden
commented as she and friend Shirley Lewis, both Scottsdale
residents, enjoyed lunch on a recent balmy day while birds chirped
and the garden's two resident cats ambled past their table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who can't climb the desert
anymore,'' said Wooden, who uses a Bobcat motorized scooter to get
around. ``Just to be here, I feel I'm out in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden, who visits the garden at least three times a week, is
training to be a volunteer. She says the facility is completely
accessible to people with disabilities. In her snappy bright red
scooter, she can easily navigate the trails and access the patio.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Desert Botanical Garden celebrated its 60th
anniversary, marking a milestone as the third oldest such facility
in the West. The Boyce Thompson Arboretum in Superior, Az., opened
in 1929, and the Huntington Library, Art Collections and Botanical
Gardens in San Marino, Calif., opened to the public in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a gift shop and plant shop, the Phoenix garden
offers a full schedule of public events and welcomes school groups.
</P>
<P>
   Best time for viewing the garden is now through mid-April, while
the blooming cactus are in their glory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
IF YOU GO &QL; 
Pretty flowers all in a row &QL; 
WHAT: Desert Botanical Garden. &QL; 
WHEN: Open daily 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. May to September; 8 a.m. to 8
p.m. October to April. &QL; 
WHERE: 1201 N. Galvin Parkway, Phoenix. &QL; 
ADMISSION: $7.50 adults, $6.50 seniors, $1.50 children 5-12,
children 4 and younger free. Discount for AAA members. &QL; 
PHONE: 941-1225. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
