<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CLICHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK ON CLICHES CAN BE READ OVER AND OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDYTH RIGLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer and lexicographer Betty Kirkpatrick cut her teeth as a
wordplay expert while editing both ``The Bloomsbury Thesaurus'' and
the latest edition of ``Roget's Thesaurus.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's given students of the language something else to chew
on: the overused, often abused phrases that cover a multitude of
sins when we're grasping at straws, have a lot on our plate or find
ourselves at sixes and sevens, glad to find any port in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cliches: Over 1,500 Phrases Explored and Explained'' (St.
Martin's Press, $12.95 paperback) runs the gamut from ``absence
makes the heart grow fonder'' to ``yours truly,'' and Kirkpatrick
provides origins and meanings for every man jack of them. She
defines ``cliche'' as ``a pejorative term for an expression that
has lost its first bloom and thus its potency but is nevertheless
widespread and sometimes even loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, Kirkpatrick's book should be popular far and
wide; you might call it the greatest thing since sliced bread or
the cat's meow, or you may think it's just a flash in the pan that
should be nipped in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What lives without a body, speaks without a tongue; Everyone can
hear it, yet no one can see it? An echo, according to a Lithuanian
riddle. What is the wink that inspires fear? A bolt of lightning,
says a riddle from the Philippines. Phil Cousineau has collected
many examples of sophisticated wordplay in ``Riddle Me This: A
World Treasury of Word Puzzles, Folk Wisdom and Literary
Conundrums'' (Conari Press, $13.95 hardback). The book's foreword
notes that all riddles have evolved from the riddle of who we are
and why we're here, and that more wordplay can help us find our
place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest forms of folk wisdom, the riddle is explored
in all its variations. Here's a Breton riddle: ``What is it that a
young man can give a maiden/ That he does not have, That he cannot
have, that he has never had,/ That he will never have,/ and that he
cannot give to a young man?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The name of a wife.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Fractured Fairy Tales,'' told by A.J. Jacobs (Bantam, $9.95
paperback) will be highly prized by anyone who grew up with the
wacky and wonderful stories on the television shows ``Rocky and His
Friends'' and ``The Bullwinkle Show.'' Many of the funny tales,
long and convoluted, are collected here; they generally end with a
punny punch line such as ``A mule and his honey are soon parted''
or ``Fishing might make it so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
