<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUINTANA-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S `FUSION' CUISINE A CULINARY TAPESTRY  
 (INCLUDES RECIPES AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AJIJIC, Jalisco, Mexico _ In the open-air restaurant of the
Danza del Sol, the cooking-class participants focused on the slim,
elegant woman in the white chef's coat with flags of Mexico
embroidered on the collar.
</P>
<P>
   She sauteed a mixture of mushrooms and roasted, peeled poblano
chiles. Cooked with an onion and lots of garlic, the aroma was
fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Quintana, the first break-out cook, author and teacher
who has received widespread international recognition for
popularizing the cuisines of Mexico, gave numerous ideas for the
mushroom-chile mixture. The recipe was much more than its stated
name, Queso Fundido con Champinones y Rajas de Poblano (Melted
Cheese with Mushrooms and Poblano Chile Strips).
</P>
<P>
   ``As the rainy season starts to come, we will have a lot of
mushrooms,'' said Quintana, who is based in Mexico City. ``You can
make a soup with the mushrooms, (begin ital) rajas (end ital)
(chile strips) and squash blooms. You can also do mushrooms and
(begin ital) rajas (end ital) in crepes, or stuff into enchiladas.
I feel you have to prepare a simple dish for vegetarians at
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   You could also add just a little cream to the mixture and serve
it over rice, she said. To change the flavor a bit, add either
cilantro or epazote (a Mexican herb that is slowly gaining
acceptance in this country), or fennel or a touch of anise.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of two mornings, Quintana wove a colorful spell
of high culinary adventure over fascinated students at the first
class of Jalisco Culinary Adventures. The new cooking school has
Phoenix ties through its consultant, Joanne Goldwater, who for 10
years ran a catering business in the Valley and is one of the
founders of Goldwater Foods.
</P>
<P>
   One of Goldwater's friends, Norman Fierros of Norman's Arizona,
is scheduled to teach April 18-24 in Ajijic, a lovely village on
Lake Chapala.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater and Sally Leonard help with some of the social events
for the week of the tour, such as leading trips into the (begin
ital) abastos, (end ital) the wholesale market, in Guadalajara, a
half-hour away. During the week of the culinary tour, class members
take other trips, too, such as through the Sol brewery, known by
ubiquitous Sol advertising in even the smallest Mexican villages.
</P>
<P>
   Students go to Tlaquepaque, an upscale area in Guadalajara, or
may ride the Tequila Train, four new train cars that depart from
Guadalajara every weekend for the village of Tequila, 35 miles to
the northwest. Mariachi music and beverage service start
immediately on the all-day excursion, which includes a tour of a
tequila factory, ballet folklorico performances in the town plaza
and a buffet meal.
</P>
<P>
   Because Jalisco state is the major producer of tequila, some of
the recipes include cooking with tequila. Bruce Jensen, head of the
school, teaches a class focusing on tortillas, salsas and soups.
Staff member Andrew Bosworth, who holds a Ph.D. in international
relations, lectures on the rise of Mexican culture and history.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico was the first country to have ``fusion'' cuisine,
Bosworth pointed out, the first example of Old World foods fusing
with New World techniques and ingredients when the Spanish brought
wheat, olive oil, sugar and almonds, among other foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the world's most sophisticated and subtle
cuisines,'' he said, ``although many people think otherwise because
of Taco Bell.''
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting thing about Mexican cuisine is its history,
Quintana said. And there is no one ``Mexican food'' because all
dishes are regional: ``Chiles and so much else are local to the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 32 different regions of inland cooking, and
spectacular things you can eat on the Pacific Coast and the
Caribbean and Gulf of Mexico,'' she said. ``I hope in the next
century, Mexico will be the next cuisine to be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   Seed sauces, such as the Pipian Verde with chicken that she made
the first day, with raw peanuts and unsalted pumpkin seeds, were
used by pre-Hispanic Indian tribes. To bring out their flavor,
Quintana first sauteed the seeds in a little oil. Pumpkin seeds are
a great source of calcium, she told the class.
</P>
<P>
   Quintana gracefully handled the situation when disaster nearly
claimed the second day.
</P>
<P>
   A beautiful pork crown roast had marinated overnight in an adobo
sauce made from vinegar, onion, guajillo and guajillo puya chiles,
garlic, cumin, coriander, oregano, allspice and pepper. It was
baking in a big Pyrex dish, and Quintana pulled it halfway from the
oven to add hot water.
</P>
<P>
   The dish suddenly shattered, glass all over the inside of the
oven. No one knew why, but it was certainly dramatic. Jensen
decreed a break while cleanup took place.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there was extra adobo sauce to be poured over the
roast when it was cleaned up and transferred to another dish. Soon,
Quintana, unruffled, was making guacamole, chopping it with two
knives at once with controlled vigor. Tie the pork roast together
into its crown shape and serve the guacamole in the center, she
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Her guacamole recipe: Chop together three avocados, about 1/2
cup white onion, 6 or 7 raw tomatillos, one serrano chile or to
taste, plus cilantro, salt and lime juice to taste. Drizzle with a
little olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guacamole is very indigenous to native people,'' Quintana
said. ``And it is a sauce. You can garnish it with tomatoes on top,
and onion.''
</P>
<P>
   Her Zoque Black Beans, named after an ancient Indian community
that still exists in Chiapas state, were a revelation. Quintana
pureed half the beans with only a little of the cooking broth to
make a thick mixture that she then made into ``refritos'' _
``well-fried'' beans. Eventually, they were so thick she flipped
them in the skillet like an omelet.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the beans were also pureed, but thinned with
bean broth to a soupy consistency. These became the sauce for
Enfrijoladas, an enchiladalike dish of corn tortillas passed
through the bean sauce, folded on a platter, garnished with more
beans, chopped onions, creme fraiche and feta or ranchero cheese.
Simple. Wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe is from ``Cuisine of the Water Gods'' , one of nine
cookbooks Quintana has written in English and Spanish. Her Web site
at www.abqsearch.com/index.html lists them all. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Zoque Black Beans &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From Patricia Quintana) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beans:
</P>
<P>
   12 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound dried black beans, sorted, soaked overnight in water
to cover, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 medium white onions, peeled and halved
</P>
<P>
   3 bunches scallions, tied in a bundle
</P>
<P>
   1 whole head garlic, halved but not peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 strips bacon (or 1/4 cup minced chorizo sausage)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium white onion, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup corn or safflower oil, as needed
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   12 dried de arbol chiles or 20 small Simojovel chiles or 14
dried japones chiles
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Bring water to a boil in a large pot. Add the beans, onion,
scallion and garlic. Cook the beans, covered, over medium heat for
1 to 1 1/2 hours or until tender. If the water evaporates before
the beans soften, add small quantities of hot water. Season with
salt and simmer the beans until thick. Remove the scallions and
garlic and puree the beans with 1/2 cup of the cooking liquid in a
food processor or blender until they form a thick puree.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat a large skillet, fry the bacon strips until crisp.
Remove the bacon and drain on a paper towel. Crumble and reserve
the bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Add the onion and cook, uncovered, until it has begun to
caramelize. Add small portions of the bean puree, stirring
constantly while cooking over medium heat. Add oil if needed. Add
all of the beans and simmer uncovered until they are very thick and
can be flipped like an omelet.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare garnish:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the 2 tablespoons oil in a medium skillet. Add the chiles
and quickly stir-fry them with a pinch of salt. Do not let them
burn. Remove the skillet from the heat as soon as the chiles are
crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Scoop the beans onto a large platter and garnish with the
reserved bacon and whole chiles. Or, chop the chiles and sprinkle
over the beans, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with freshly made tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 to 12 servings. Approximate values per serving: 190
calories, 10 g fat, 4 mg cholesterol, 19 g carbohydrates, 4.4 g
fiber, 7 g protein, 204 mg sodium, 46 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Enfrijoladas &QL; 
(From Patricia Quintana) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zoque beans (see recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   Zoque bean broth (or water)
</P>
<P>
   24 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   2 cups oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup creme fraiche (or half sour cream and half heavy cream)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup feta, farmer's or ranchero cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Place the beans in a blender and add the broth. Blend until a
medium-thick sauce is formed. Pour into a large skillet and cover
to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   In another skillet, heat oil and pass the tortillas through it,
one by one, for a few seconds each. Dry on paper towels and
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the blended beans in the skillet. Dip each tortilla into
the bean sauce and remove. Fold and place the tortillas on a
serving platter. When all are dipped, pour more sauce over them.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with cream and crumbled cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: Fill enfrijoladas with eggs, shredded chicken or
fresh cheese before folding, or sprinkle tops with cooked,
well-drained chorizo.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. Approximate values per serving: 304 calories,
12 g fat, 13 mg cholesterol, 43 g carbohydrates, 5.6 g fiber, 8 g
protein, 237 mg sodium, 42 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Raw Salsa Verde &QL; 
(From Patricia Quintana)
</P>
<P>
   14 tomatillos
</P>
<P>
   3 jalapenos (with seeds)
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in food processor or blender.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 1/2 cups. Approximate values per 3-tablespoon
serving: 19 calories, 1 g fat, 0 cholesterol, 4 g carbohydrates, 1
g fiber, 1 g protein, 205 mg sodium, 17 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pollo en Pipian Verde &QL; 
(From Patricia Quintana)
</P>
<P>
   Chicken:
</P>
<P>
   5 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds bone-in chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1 entire head garlic
</P>
<P>
   4 small onions
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil, divided use
</P>
<P>
   1 pound raw, unsalted pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   9 ounces raw, unsalted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 white onions, sliced, plus
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 white onion, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   12 tomatillos, husks removed
</P>
<P>
   8 chiles serranos
</P>
<P>
   4 leaves of lettuce
</P>
<P>
   4 radish leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch coarsely chopped cilantro, stems discarded
</P>
<P>
   2 slices white onion
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   12 sprigs cilantro
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the chicken: Bring water to a boil in a saucepan. Add
chicken, garlic, onions and salt to taste. Return to boil, and
reduce heat to low. Cook for 30 minutes or until the meat is
tender. Cool chicken in broth. Meanwhile, prepare the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the sauce: Heat a saucepan and add a little oil. Fry
the pumpkin seeds, remove and drain on paper towels. Add more oil
and fry the peanuts. Remove and drain on paper towels. Add more
oil, brown the sliced onion and 4 garlic cloves, and remove. Fry
the sesame seeds in a little more oil, being careful not to scorch.
Remove and drain.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate saucepan, bring 2 cups water to a boil. Add
quartered onion, 4 garlic cloves, tomatillos and chiles. Boil
slowly for 25 minutes. Remove from heat and drain.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender or food processor, blend pumpkin seeds, peanuts,
sesame seeds, browned onion and garlic and the tomatillo mixture
with lettuce leaves, radish leaves, and cilantro. Puree until
smooth, strain through a sieve, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Remove bones from chicken breasts. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a little more oil in a saucepan, and brown the remaining
onion slices. Add pipian sauce and cook until the fat rises to the
surface. Add broth to thin sauce to desired consistency. Add
chicken and salt. Simmer for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle the chicken in pipian sauce onto plates, and garnish with
cilantro sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings. Approximate values per serving: 673 calories,
46 g fat, 66 mg cholesterol, 29 g carbohydrates, 3.8 g fiber, 40 g
protein, 362 mg sodium, 60 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: To lower the fat and calorie content in this recipe, use
minimal amounts of oil. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Queso Fundido con Champinones y Rajas de Poblano (Melted Cheese
with Mushrooms and Chile Strips) &QL; 
(From Patricia Quintana)
</P>
<P>
   1/ cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium white onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds mushrooms, washed and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds chiles poblanos, roasted, peeled, deveined, seeded
and thinly sliced into strips
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds mild cheese, (fontina, Monterey Jack or other
cheeses) grated (combine more than one cheese if desired)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Heat the oil in a heavy, large
skillet, and brown the onion and garlic. Add the mushroom and
chile, and cook for about 20 minutes. Add the cheese and season to
taste with salt, if needed. Simmer gently until the cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon equal portions of mixture into eight (begin ital)
cazuelitas (end ital) (little clay bowls) or ramekins. (You can
also use a larger dish to hold the entire mixture if you don't have
(begin ital) cazuelitas (end ital) or ramekins.) Bake at 350
degrees for 8 minutes or until cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot with flour tortillas and salsa of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. Approximate values per serving: 421 calories,
33 g fat, 76 mg cholesterol, 10 g carbohydrates, 2 g fiber, 24 g
protein, 532 mg sodium, 69 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mangos y Platanos Flamedos con Tequila &QL; 
(From Patricia Quintana)
</P>
<P>
   4 cans (15 ounces each) mangoes in syrup, syrup drained and
reserved, mangoes chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lime peel
</P>
<P>
   2 cups orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup tequila
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup rum
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch dissolved in 1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   7/8 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   2 fresh mangoes, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 bananas, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup almonds, peeled, toasted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Place the mango syrup, orange peel and lime peel in a large
saucepan and let boil for 5 minutes. Add the orange juice, tequila,
rum and cornstarch dissolved in water. Cook until a semilight sauce
is developed. Add butter and the chopped canned mangoes. Keep warm
over hot water if not serving immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serve mango slices on a plate with the hot sauce over. Place
banana slices around the mango and dust with chopped almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. Approximate values per serving: 207 calories,
4 g fat, 3 mg cholesterol, 32 g carbohydrates, 3.7 g fiber, 2 g
protein, 16 mg sodium, 19 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
