<SLUG> BC-QUINTANATIPS-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN CUISINE TIPS  
 (WITH QUINTANA-FOOD) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cooking teacher and author Patricia Quintana offers these
pointers: &QL; 
- To approximate the taste of the thick Mexican crema that so
captivates visitors: Mix equal parts sour cream and heavy cream. &QL; 
- Toast dried chiles to bring out their flavor but be careful not
to burn them. Open them to flatten and mash down with a spatula on
a hot, dry griddle or skillet. &QL; 
- What about removing seeds from chiles to reduce their heat?
Quintana believes the flavor is in the seeds but advocates taking
seeds out of large dried chiles. &QL; 
- Any kind of chile seeds can be toasted and used for garnish. &QL; 
- Wash dried chiles with a little brush to remove dust or sand
before using them. &QL; 
- Dried chiles need air to prevent bug infestation. Keep them in a
non-airtight container or pierce them with a needle to let air get
inside each chile or freeze them. &QL; 
- To reduce heat, soak fresh chiles in a water and vinegar solution
for 15 minutes. &QL; 
- Top a pizza crust with refried beans, strips of chipotles in
adobo sauce and cheese. &QL; 
- If you put a little oil on your hands first, handling chiles
won't hurt you. However, if you wear contact lenses, be sure to
wear gloves so you won't get chile residue on your hands. &QL; 
- Add salt to beans only after they have cooked long enough to
soften. &QL; 
- When cooked with beans, avocado leaves, especially the leaves
from the small variety known as cocktail avocados, have the same
gas-eliminating effect as epazote. &QL; 
- Use an inexpensive wicker basket as a colander or strainer.
Quintana demonstrated how she uses a basket to strain cooked
nopales, or diced cactus pads. It cut the sliminess of the
nopalitos like magic. &QL; 
- Use a large spoon to scoop the flesh out of a mango half. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
