<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE FASHION LOSERS THAN WINNERS FOR THE OSCARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Gwyneth Paltrow, winner of the Oscar for best actress,
stepped onto the red carpet to greet Joan Rivers before the 71st
annual Academy Awards broadcast from the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion
in Los Angeles, there was an audible gasp.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Paltrow, on the arm of her father, Bruce, a bona
fide Hollywood princess, she looked the part. Pretty in pink
doesn't even describe Paltrow's full-on Ralph Lauren ball gown with
its simple princess lines, graceful skirt, deeply veed back and
graceful matching organza shawl.
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow has become the Tinseltown fashion icon _ a cool blonde
whose stylists have chosen the best of the fashion trends and
displayed them on the beyond-perfect dress hanger. And on Oscar
night, with her sleek, neat hair and simple diamonds, Paltrow set
the bar for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Full-on ballgowns, worn by probably half of the women at the
Oscars, are a blessed relief from years of skin-tight slip dresses
that have as much personality as cold spaghetti. Anne Heche's gray
T-shirt top looked like a sweatshirt and needed more support than
partner Ellen DeGeneres' arm. The other slipdress came on Goldie
Hawn _ a sky-blue, side-split, sequin-sparkled slink that did
nothing for Hawn's sunny complexion.
</P>
<P>
   For true old-style Hollywood glamour, you had to turn to
Jennifer Lopez, whose strapless Badgley Mischka, embroidered with a
Victorian necklace motif across the front, was black silk taffeta
with a massive skirt. For the past two years, Lopez has worn more
skin than clothes, stuff guaranteed to show off her shapely booty.
This year, she was positively ladylike.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Hunt decided to wear more makeup this year. Instead of the
pale, skinny wraith who wore skin-bleaching ice-blue Gucci last
year, Hunt was the picture of the '70s Italian screen goddess in
her sleeveless, backless, brilliant- trimmed dove gray Gucci. Her
hair was middle parted and Cher-straight; her lips were pale
yellowed-down peach; and her eyes, raccoon-rings of kohl assisted
with fake eyelashes.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Canadian songbird Celine Dion is faultlessly dressed.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in her reverse tuxedo-jacketed white pants ensemble
from John Galliano for Dior, with its matching fedora and $28,000
diamond-encrusted Ray Ban sunglasses, she was better suited for
MTV. Galliano also dressed ``Elizabeth'' star Cate Blanchette in a
simple, mini-fleurette embroidered net gown.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Renee Zellweger should fire the stylist who did up
her hair like Mrs. Miniver and put her in a lavender gown trimmed
in gold braid that was not only so skin tight she could hardly
walk, but made her look fat and 40. Sharing honors with Zellweger
and Dion for worst dress was Meryl Streep, whose sequin-sparkled
beige-peach gown may have complemented her complexion but resembled
something Hints from Heloise would have recommended to scrub pots.
</P>
<P>
   Without Ashley Judd, her gardenias and her leg-revealing Richard
Tyler, there was no real va-voom dress except for the top of Lisa
Kudrow's steel-gray Randolph Duke. Beautifully cut and spangled, it
promised to be the slinky dress of the night when viewed from the
waist up, but disappeared in an a-line length of duchesse satin.
</P>
<P>
   Most women were gowned so politely, they should have been
wearing white gloves. Pamela Dennis' blue strapless number for Liv
Tyler was quite sweet but nothing special; Dennis did better for
Joan Rivers with a two-piece ruby red sequined gown. Rivers'
daughter Melissa, co-hosting E! Entertainment's pre-Oscar show,
covered up her fresh lime green Vera Wang with a turquoise pashmina
shawl.
</P>
<P>
   Duke dressed quite a few women, including Geena Davis _ the sexy
number she wore for the Oscars themselves, that is. (For her boring
pre-Oscar show, Davis wore a peach satin corset dress by a designer
named Bradley Bayou that looked like Escada lite.) Duke put Kim
Basinger in a plain white strapless dress and also gowned Minnie
Driver for the second year. Last year's second-skin cranberry
number (which Duke did while designing for Halston) started a run
on color that flowered at this year's awards like Giverney.
</P>
<P>
   Very few women even considered black except for Annette Bening,
whose Armani shtick is wearing thin (tastefully boring), and Sophia
Loren, whose belle poitrine is bigger and belle-er all the time.
(Roberto Benigni buried his nose in her net-draped bosom and almost
had a heart attack.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men, meanwhile, played it fairly safe with a few
variations. Robin Williams is still schlepping around in his
knee-length preacher coats. But Jim Carey's black monochromatic
look, with his black satin tie on a black silk tux shirt, was
handsome and striking. Ellen DeGeneres still had the best-looking
tuxedo, a white Richard Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Val Kilmer's Western-style satin-yoked jacket and string tie was
particularly appropriate as he presented an homage to the film
Western (alas, he was upstaged by a beautiful blonde, a skittery
palomino better groomed than he was).
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth'' director, India's Shekhar Kapur, was festively
attired in a burgundy velvet jacket trimmed in gold with an
embroidered shirt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
