<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SOFTWARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE MAKERS APPLAUD APPLE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The computer industry welcomed Apple Computer
Inc.'s decision to give away the software coding for its new
Macintosh server operating system.
</P>
<P>
   By giving away the code for its new Mac OS X Server, Apple has
endorsed and entered a new era of software development, allowing
any programmer to improve upon and make new applications based on
the software.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's announcement by the Cupertino, Calif.-based company
means the Mac OS X ``kernel,'' or programming core, is available to
pretty much anyone through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should provide a quicker turnaround for developers,''
said Scott Seebass, chief executive of Berkeley-based Xinet Inc.,
which produces software programs for the printing industry. ``You
can develop (programs) without relying on the operating system
vendor to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mac OS X Server software costs $499, about half what Apple
had originally announced in January. The server and software
together cost $4,999, and are faster than systems running
Microsoft's Windows NT, Linux and Sun's Solaris brand of Unix.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of open source distribution of the software is to
encourage developers to make new software based on a core program.
In theory, when those software applications become popular, a
standard evolves that benefits the company, Apple in this case,
that created the core program.
</P>
<P>
   Open source programming has gained momentum recently due to the
growing popularity and acceptance of Linux, a free, Unix-based
operating system developed by Finnish student Linus Torvalds, that
is shaping up to be the only viable alternative to Microsoft's
dominant Windows NT operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Like Apple's Mac OS X, Linux is primarily used to run servers
and not individual computers.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing companies and educational institutions, the mainstay
of Apple's non-consumer business, should benefit most from the move
toward open source distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect a huge rush of people to convert (to the
Macintosh platform) but it will maintain Apple's dominance in
education and publishing,'' Seebass said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris LeToq, an analyst at San Jose, Calif.-based Dataquest
Inc., said Mac OS X Server ``supports what Apple is doing in these
marketplaces and really means that their customers don't have to
look elsewhere for server technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts were mixed on whether businesses using other
software platforms, namely Windows NT, will switch to Mac OS X.
</P>
<P>
   Seebass was optimistic about Apple's open source attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will attract the same people who are converting from NT to
Linux,'' he said. ``If you're working on NT, you have to rely on
Microsoft. (Apple) might convert some people who aren't happy with
their current options.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Mazzucchelli, an analyst at Gerard Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co. in
New York, said Apple probably would not gain many new business
customers immediately, but there could be more interest down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The open source thing will promote cross-fertilization,'' he
said. ``The Linux guys who've been frustrated because there's no
Apple support (may convert). That's a potentially very big win for
Apple. But that's a longer-term thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Mazzucchelli said Apple needs to be very
careful in how it advertises and markets Mac OS X. Because the
product is targeted toward business customers, Apple shouldn't
advertise in general interest newspapers or magazines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have to focus and not get their messages mixed,''
Mazzucchelli said. ``They don't want to confuse their consumer
customers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
