<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-VULGARFAVORS-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRIPPING POST-MORTEM OF A SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timing is everything, especially in book publishing. Maureen
Orth, best-known for her work in Vanity Fair, has written an
exceptionally good account of suspected serial killer Andrew
Cunanan's spree in 1997, and odds are that very few people will
notice _ or be able to recall just who Andrew Cunanan even was.
</P>
<P>
   A monster, that's who, a man who lied his way through most of 30
years and, when he finally ran out of lies or at least an audience
for them, turned violent. The combined forces of virtually every
national law enforcement agency never could catch Cunanan, who
traveled from Minnesota to Florida, killing five people, police
say. In the end, Cunanan was shot down by his worst enemy: himself.
</P>
<P>
   But being suspected of taking the lives of designer Gianni
Versace, along with four others, isn't enough, in these sad days,
to earn Cunanan eternal or even lengthy infamy. ``Vulgar Favors''
debuts on bookshelves at the same time as ``Monica's Story'' and
George Stephanopoulos' ``All Too Human,'' tales of White House
shenanigans that are (we assume) more rare than a nut-case with a
gun. We can rephrase a popular bumper sticker from the Nixon era:
``Nobody Died at Monicagate.'' But it won't help sell copies of
``Vulgar Favors'' _ even though it may be a far more important book
than Monica Lewinsky's.
</P>
<P>
   In some sense, Andrew Cunanan is very much one of us. Orth takes
us into Cunanan's childhood, when he was alternately spoiled by
doting parents and forced to arbitrate Mom and Dad's stormy,
ultimately failed, marriage. The kid turned to fantasy, trying to
convince schoolmates that he came from a wealthy blue-blood clan.
If he went further than was safe, well, there was no one around to
tell him he had taken fantasy far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Orth tells this twisted story with grace and courage, taking
readers to some very warped places without condescending; Cunanan
and many of his pals are homosexual, but Orth demonstrates why they
are often despicable without suggesting that all gays are bad. What
simultaneously mesmerizes and repulses are the sadistic sexual
places Cunanan and company went, none of which can be properly
described in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Cunanan, his belly thickening and his audience
dwindling, leaves his beloved California to confront an ex-lover in
Minnesota, there is a tragic certainty to Orth's tale. In the final
third of her book, we marvel less that Cunanan snapped than at how
long it takes police and federal agencies to come up with a
coherent plan to capture him. Much of their hesitancy to act, Orth
notes, stems from the O.J. Simpson debacle _ nobody wanted to step
out front in a high-profile case unless success was absolutely
assured. And while the feds bumbled, Cunanan apparently kept
killing.
</P>
<P>
   And now, almost two years after Gianni Versace died in a pool of
his own blood, who will want to read about it? We live in a society
that inadvertently nurtures the occasional Andrew Cunanan. ``Vulgar
Favors'' tells us how, and we ought to listen.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX:
</P>
<P>
   TITLE: ``Vulgar Favors: Andrew Cunanan, Gianni Versace, and the
Largest Failed Manhunt in U.S. History''
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR: Maureen Orth
</P>
<P>
   TYPE: True crime/sociology
</P>
<P>
   PUBLISHER: Delacorte, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
