<HEADLINE>
FAVORITE WEB SITE LIST GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Back in February, we ran a list of your favorite Web
sites for 1998. If you missed the list, it can still be found at
www.azcentral.com/computing/viewpoint/0215hoyewebsites.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of creating such a list proved so popular with readers,
that I continued to receive recommendations long after the
submission deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sites that didn't make it on the original list are
very good. So I've decided to revisit the topic by publishing a
sort of addendum to our original list.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, are additional Web sites recommended by readers of
``The
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Republic'' as top sites for 1998:
</P>
<P>
   - www.trafficspy.com: The Traffic Spy Home Page is a handy site
if you need instructions on how to get from Point A to Point B, or
if you'd like to check out traffic cameras anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   - www.superkids.com: Thinking of buying your child some
educational software or a game? Check here first. The site offers a
lengthy list of software reviews and information for parents and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   - www.litsoft.com: Literate Software Systems, makers of Across
Lite crossword puzzle software, operates this site. If you are a
crossword puzzle lover, check it out.
</P>
<P>
   - www.hboi.edu: If you like boats, fish or the ocean, check out
the home of the Florida-based Harbor Branch Oceanographic
Institution Inc. The site offers visitors a chance to follow along
on a 20-day expedition to explore sharks.
</P>
<P>
   - investormap.com: Looking for information on a mutual fund? A
brokerage? Financial software? Global markets? Stock quotes? This
is a place to find all that, and lots more.
</P>
<P>
   - www.digitaldog.com/breeds.html: If you're a dog lover or a
would-be dog owner, you'll want to bookmark this site. It lists dog
breeds alphabetically, and provides images and useful information
on each, such as average lifespan and whether the dog is good with
children.
</P>
<P>
   - www.yesterdayusa.com: Remember old-time radio shows such as
``Abbott and Costello,'' ``Amos and Andy'' or ``Burns and Allen''?
You can hear them and many, many more thanks to this site. (You'll
need the RealAudio plugin found at www.realaudio.com.)
</P>
<P>
   - slis-two.lis.fsu.edu/isweb/lrc/helpsheets/searchengines.html:
New to the Internet? This site includes helpful information on how
search engines work and links to many of the more useful search
sites.
</P>
<P>
   - www.cactus-punch.com/links.html: If you love embroidery,
sewing, crafts or anything related to those activities, you'll
probably find a bunch of great Web sites by checking out this list.
</P>
<P>
   - www.infoplease.com: Information Please offers an online
dictionary, an online encyclopedia and statistics galore via
almanac-style entries. Everything is listed by category.
</P>
<P>
   - www.iamyourchild.org: If you are expecting a child or are a
parent of a child under age 3, this site, sponsored by Yahoo! and
filmmaker Rob Reiner, will be useful. It includes parenting tips,
information on what to expect at different ages of development and
lots of child-related links. &QL; 
Unhappy over happy99.exe &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I received a lot of e-mail following last week's column on
happy99.exe, a type of worm or Trojan horse program that spreads
via e-mail. Infected systems send copies of happy99.exe with each
outgoing e-mail without the user's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers said they had received copies of happy99.exe the
very morning the column appeared. I'm glad the information helped
stem the advance of this annoying program.
</P>
<P>
   A couple readers tipped me off to a file that happy99.exe
creates and that goes undetected by anti-virus programs. It's
called ``liste.ska.''
</P>
<P>
   The file isn't anything to be concerned about. In fact, it's the
only good file included in the whole happy99.exe mess.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the maker of happy99.exe decided it would be nice to
keep track of everyone sent a copy of happy99.exe from an infected
computer system. The list is kept in the file liste.ska.
</P>
<P>
   If you've had happy99.exe on your system, and didn't know about
this list, you've probably still got it bouncing around on your
hard drive. Conduct a file search, and you'll probably dig it up.
</P>
<P>
   You can open liste.ska using Notepad or any other
word-processing program you have installed on your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Before deleting liste.ska, you might want to jot down the people
it lists (or print it out) and then send them an e-mail warning
that their computers might be infected with happy99.exe.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, here are some good sites to bookmark if you are
interested in keeping up on the latest computer viruses and/or
computer virus hoaxes:
</P>
<P>
   - ciac.llnl.gov: This is the home page of the Computer Incident
Advisory Capability, a service of the U.S. Department of Energy.
This site contains reliable information on computer viruses and
computer virus hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   - www.symantec.com/avcenter/index.html: This is the Anti-Virus
Research Center maintained by Symantec, which produces the Norton
Anti-Virus software. The site has good information about the latest
viruses, and, in my experience, is a bit quicker to post
information on brand new viruses than the CIAC site.
</P>
<P>
   - www.commandcom.com/html/virus/virus.html: This is the
anti-virus page maintained by Command Software Inc., which is a
distributor of the F-PROT anti-virus software. I like this site
because it offers a lot of educational information about viruses.
It also offers links to other anti-virus-related sites.
</P>
<P>
   - www.Europe.Datafellows.com/vir-info: This page is maintained
by Data Fellows, a respected source of information about computer
viruses and hoaxes. The company claims that theirs was the first
anti-virus information Web site. They also distribute the F-PROT
anti-virus software.
</P>
<P>
   - www.av.ibm.com/current/FrontPage: IBM maintains this
anti-virus Web site. The site, which has ties to Symantec, offers
lots of valuable virus information, including a step-by-step primer
on what to do if you suddenly realize your computer has a virus.
</P>
<P>
   - vil.mcafee.com/villib/alpha.asp: McAfee, makers of VirusScan
and other software, run this site. It offers a vast database of
virus information, including a frequently updated list of the top
viruses.
</P>
<P>
   - www.hitchhikers.net/av.shtml: To round out our bookmark
selection, this is an independent Web site that includes
information on a variety of anti-virus programs. It also has a lot
of helpful information for those who are not clear on what a virus
can do to a computer system.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other anti-virus Web sites. To find more, go to a
search site such as HotBot (www.hotbot.com) and conduct a search
using the keyword ``antivirus.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Make me laugh . . . please! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After all this talk of virus problems, we all need a good laugh.
This week's chuckle comes courtesy of Pat's Computer Jokes, which
can be found at www.patsjokes.com/computer/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Top 10 Signs You Bought A Bad Computer:
</P>
<P>
   10. Lower corner of screen has the words ``Etch-a-sketch'' on
it.
</P>
<P>
   9. Its celebrity spokesman is that ``Hey Vern!'' guy.
</P>
<P>
   8. In order to start it, you need some jumper cables and a
friend's car.
</P>
<P>
   7. Its slogan is ``Pentium: redefining mathematics.''
</P>
<P>
   6. The ``quick reference'' manual is 120 pages long.
</P>
<P>
   5. Whenever you turn it on, all the dogs in your neighborhood
start howling.
</P>
<P>
   4. The screen often displays the message, ``Ain't it break time
yet?''
</P>
<P>
   3. The manual contains only one sentence: ``Good Luck!''
</P>
<P>
   2. The only chip inside is a Dorito.
</P>
<P>
   1. You've decided that your computer is an excellent addition to
your fabulous paperweight collection. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
