<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OSCAR FOR THE END OF PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ When the 39 board members of the Motion
Picture Academy of Arts and Sciences approved ``with enthusiasm''
an honorary Oscar for Elia Kazan, their historic, high-profile
decision hastened the demise of the ``politically correct''
instinct in America.
</P>
<P>
   PC, whatever it was, lies in ruins, defeated by art, not
politics. It never was a movement, more like a conditioned reflex
or a college prank. Kazan shares his triumph with another Greek
genius, Aristotle, who propounded an iron rule of artistic
criticism: Judge the work, not the author.
</P>
<P>
   This artistic affirmation eclipses the ideological quarrels that
have surrounded Kazan since 1952, when he named names before the
House Committee on Un-American Activities. Kazan's honorary Oscar
ignited ``controversy,'' journalistic jargon suggesting that
somebody is unhappy about something.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy about what, exactly? That is where the politically
incorrect reflex tends to buckle and collapse. History was never
its forte, nor indeed was scholarship. If a snap judgment can not
explain a controversy, let's move on to another trend. Gywneth
Paltrow's hairdo will do.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, congressional investigators proceed on the
assumption, as preposterous as it was sinister, that communists in
Hollywood were poisoning American minds. Since ``informing'' and
``the blacklist'' mean little in today's Hollywood, Victor S.
Navasky wrote ``Naming Names'' in 1980, ``a moral detective story''
that allows readers to decide about Kazan and others.
</P>
<P>
   Working his way through Williams College and Yale's drama school
made Kazan an egalitarian. In 1935, he joined the Communist Party,
which he soon quit because of its ``slavery of the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after his testimony, he took out an ad in The New
York Times, which Navasky reprints. It attacked ``specious
reasoning which has silenced many liberals. It goes like this: `You
may hate the communists, but you must not attack or expose them,
because if you do you are attacking the right to hold unpopular
opinions and you are joining the people who attack civil
liberties.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I have thought soberly about this. It is, simply, a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazan was troubled, but not apologetic, which riled his enemies.
``Anybody who informs on other people is doing something disturbing
and even disgusting,'' Kazan has said. ``It doesn't sit well on
anybody's conscience. . . . But I think it has to be judged from
the perspective of 1952.'' PC is rooted in hindsight, not real-time
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   After his testimony, Kazan teamed up with writer Budd Schulberg
for ``On the Waterfront,'' awarded the Oscar for best picture in
1954. Karl Malden, who proposed this year's honorary award, was one
of five actors from that film nominated for Oscars. He was best
supporting actor in 1951, directed by Kazan in ``Streetcar Named
Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   As Father Barry, the waterfront priest, Malden implores Terry
Malloy, played by Marlon Brando, to inform on mobsters and
racketeers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's my own brother they're asking me to finger _ and
Johnny Friendly. His mother and my mother was first cousins. When I
was this high he took me to the ball games,'' Malloy mumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ball games! Don't break my heart! I wouldn't care if he gave
you a life pass to the Polo Grounds!'' the priest interjects, then
speaks softly: ``Listen, I'm not asking you to do anything, Terry.
It's your conscience that's got to do the asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Conscience does not compute in PC software. Conscience doth make
cowards of us all, said Shakespeare, also lavished with Oscar
honors despite being certifiably dead, white, and possibly male.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan's politics will not long endure, but his art will. He
vanquished his foes and also transformed the style of protest.
Instead of ransacking the dean's office, Kazan's critics chose
silence, a blissful silence that also marks the passing of the
philistine era of political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1437EST &QL; 
