u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-22 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH LEADERS CARRY HOME THE MESSAGE ON PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Seamus Mallon was remarking the other day on the
presence here of nearly 200 very big shots from Ireland _ North and
Republic _ for what is, after all, Ireland's own great day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we all come here,'' said the new deputy first
minister of the North's new elected Assembly on his first such
visit, ``is a sign of our political immaturity.''
</P>
<P>
   A good point, if a bit harsh in light of all that's been done in
the '90s to give peace and power-sharing a chance. But Mallon was
correct: When Washington is not crawling with Irish government and
political leaders during St. Patrick's week is when a functioning
new society in the North will be reality.
</P>
<P>
   They don't come for the fun. In Bill Clinton's time, the week
has been the occasion for very hard work; this year it started on
the Sunday before and continued without pause right through the
huge White House bash and equally stunning Irish Embassy
after-party on the day itself.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Mallon (also deputy to John Hume in Northern
Ireland's largest Catholic party) and his fellow leaders were given
an unambiguous message from their trusted American friends and
supporters _ absolute intolerance of any remaining roadblocks or
stalemates in implementing last year's historic Good Friday
agreement to administer the Northern six counties fairly.
</P>
<P>
   They got it from President Clinton, from Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, from the US mediator of last year's triumph,
former Senator George Mitchell, and from their friends in American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody said it better than Senator Edward M. Kennedy:
``Enough is enough is enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was honored by the American Ireland Fund for being at
the center of every move over the past generation that made a
settlement first possible, then probable, then reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been asked to do a great deal already,'' Kennedy said.
``Now you're asked to do even more because we know you will not
fail.''
</P>
<P>
   As the final steps to set up the governing machinery unfold this
month, the message got through to the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the life of me,'' said Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahearn
over lunch, ``we are not going to give up. We keep coming back at
it. We've squared more circles than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the first minister in the new Northern Assembly, Protestant
leader David Trimble, thinks the latest stalemate-crisis is
resolvable, and he's the one who provoked it.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble has for the moment refused to convene his new Cabinet in
the North _ which by electoral apportionment must include two
members of Sinn Fein, the onetime political arm of the
now-splintered Irish Republican Army _ by the latest British
deadline of March 29.
</P>
<P>
   He has refused to do so unless Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
arranges some ``credible'' beginning to the turning in of the IRA's
substantial caches of arms and explosives. Adams has both pleaded
impotence and opposed any act of ``surrender'' so long as a
reconstituted police force in the North, trusted by all sides,
remains unformed.
</P>
<P>
   They're both right, which misses a few larger points that
Trimble alluded to over breakfast with a few columnists under the
auspices of the nascent Northern Ireland Voluntary Trust, a
pro-settlement American group. The most important is that all this
is ultimately about the government power that Britain's Prime
Minister Tony Blair is preparing to delegate to the North _ power
Trimble must share.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's votes, North and South, approving the Good Friday
Agreement, the Protestant community was deeply split, and its ranks
in the new Assembly are similarly divided. Trimble claims he's
taken his Unionist community as far as he can and needs help to
maintain momentum. Within the Assembly, he says the Protestant
ranks are evenly split and any future defections to rejectionism
would be more than ominous.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Wales and Scotland, the planned devolution of
authority to Belfast is not eagerly anticipated by the guardians of
the unjust status quo. More than half the economy in the six
counties is public sector, in dramatic contrast to the economically
vibrant Republic, which is the fastest growing country in Europe,
thanks in no small part to vigorous US business investment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the huge security aparatus, this public sector
economy in the North is heavily subsidy-dependent _ spoils and jobs
whose unjust distribution is at the root of the long Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   All that is going to change, and none of the change is going to
be easy, but the irony is that so far all the provisions of the
agreement _ within the North and to create new institutions linking
North and South _ have been implemented on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the latest ``crisis,'' it doesn't approach the
difficulties the peacemakers encountered and resolved in the past.
Especially in the wake of last week's horrific car-bombing murder
of a prominent Catholic lawyer, Rosemary Nelson, there was an
almost defiant optimism in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Even Trimble shares it. He said he can envision ``choreography''
in which the negotiating answers are ``no'' right down to the last
instant when they become ``yes,'' ``with no advance clue for the
usual security reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd better be right. The American message, which was received,
is that the economic and political stakes for Ireland's future are
simply too great to countenance renewed stalemate or crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1440EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
