<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-22 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWISTS AND TURNS CHARACTERIZE STARR'S INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the US Senate's acquittal of President Clinton on
impeachment charges, the Clinton-Starr-Lewinsky affair continues to
take more twists and turns than a mystery novel.
</P>
<P>
   The ironies occurring along the way make the title of an Al
Pacino movie _ ``And Justice For All'' _ increasingly appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was acquitted, justice was served. Now, justice may
also be in the offing for the person who is largely responsible for
the injustices heaped upon Clinton, Monica Lewinsky, and others
connected to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth W. Starr, the independent counsel, might have thought
that the last person who would ever come under federal
investigation would be Kenneth Starr. But a federal appeals court
decision last week has made that once-remote possibility a reality.
The court gave the Justice Department the green light to
investigate Starr's tactics and actions in the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts argue that if the Justice Department
determines that Starr and his assistants engaged in illegal
tactics, such as preventing Lewinsky from calling her lawyer when
she was held by Starr's office, he would have to be removed as
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens _ if the man who sought to remove Clinton from
office on charges of wrongdoing finds himelf being removed from
office on charges of wrongdoing _ it would indeed be an ironic
twist of fate.
</P>
<P>
   Events have taken some unexpected turns in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republicans and Democrats were split along party lines
over Republican-led impeachment charges arising from Starr's
investigation, both parties came together to reject an effort to
cut off financing for most independent prosecutors, primarily
Starr, by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move against Starr would have been seen by some as pure
revenge, by others as blatant pettiness _ thus creating the
possibility that the highly unpopular inquisitor would end up being
cast as a martyr. And that is not exactly what most Democrats, as
well as most of the nation's populace, envision for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   They know the best way to get to Starr is to use the same method
he and his GOP colleagues used in their efforts to get Clinton: the
legislative and legal process.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the law which resulted in the office of the
independent counsel. Since Democrats now realize how that law can
be used as a political weapon in an opponent's hands, and
Republicans realize how this political weapon can blow up in their
faces, it is probably that a majority from both parties will allow
the law to simply expire at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Although such expiration does not prevent Starr and other
current independent counsels from continuing their ongoing
investigations, Starr would _ and here's another irony _ have to
live with the knowledge that his zealous pursuit of Clinton is the
main reason the OIC ceased to exist.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr decides to indict Clinton during or after his
presidency, or indict Hillary Rodham Clinton, or go after any
others connected to the Clintons, chances of his staying on the job
would be about as good as chances the independent counsel law will
be renewed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Justice Department doesn't remove Starr after its
investigation, Attorney General Janet Reno could still fire him if
he continues his pursuit. Such an action would probably enhance
Reno's favorability rating with the public, because by that time
weary voters would welcome an end to Starr's personal agenda
against Clinton. Reno would be seen as a hero, rather than Starr as
a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is that ironic twist of fate that last week put both
Starr and the Justice Department on the same side of an issue, even
if inadvertently.
</P>
<P>
   When the conservative Landmark Legal Foundation sought to block
the Justice Department from investigating Starr, Starr's office
contended in court that Landmark had no legal basis for its
lawsuit. Meanwhile, the Justice Department said the court had no
authority to intervene in its investigation. The court ruled that
both Starr and the Justice Department were right and let the
investigation go forward.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Justice Department and Starr's office concurred,
for different reasons, that they were better off without Landmark's
involvement, don't expect to see such agreement in the future.
</P>
<P>
   If the Justice Department determines that Starr's tactics were
in violation of the independent counsel law, it will have no choice
but to, at the very least, remove him. Criminal charges cannot be
ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   But as this legal, political, social, and personal saga
continues, it becomes increasingly clear that one of the most
sordid chapters in this nation's history will end only when Starr's
career as an independent counsel is finally over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
