<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MARS-BOS &LR;      03-22 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METEOR MICROBES CAUSE EVEN SKEPTICS TO RETHINK MARTIAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Signs of life in a meteorite from Mars? After the
excitement of the initial claims three years ago, it seemed the
true answer might never be sorted out, as scientists argued
fiercely over what secrets the Martian rocks really held.
</P>
<P>
   But now, prospects for a definitive declaration of life beyond
Earth seem better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, new reports about the tantalizing fossilized microbes
in Mars meteorites seriously challenged the questions and
counterarguments raised about the announcement in 1996 of possible
microbial life signs in a Martian meteorite found in Antarctica,
called ALH 84001.
</P>
<P>
   Possible fossils found in two new meteorites, several scientists
said last week, not only seem more likely to be real, but, because
they are much larger, will be easier to analyze and thus settle the
issue once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, other reports presented here last week seem to have
decisively shattered claims that the original Mars meteorite was
subjected to temperatures so high that nothing living could have
survived inside it. The new reports show that nearly identical
formations can be produced in the laboratory at low temperatures,
and that some Earth rocks that formed at low temperatures contain
similar forms.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wave of new evidence, skeptics remain. But some,
like geologist Allan Treiman of Houston's Lunar and Planetary
Institute, agree that the formations found in the new meteorite,
dubbed Nakhla, should be easier to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   The bombshell at last week's Lunar and Planetary Sciences
Conference here came from the lead researcher from the original
report, in August 1996, about possible fossils in ALH 84001 (so
named because it was the first meteorite found in the Alan Hills
section of Antarctica in 1984). David McKay, a geologist at the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Johnson Space
Center, said he has now found what appear to be Earth-like
microbial fossils in two younger meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   While ALH 84001 formed on Mars 4.5 billion years ago _ right
after all the planets formed _ Nakhla, named for a town near Egypt
where it was found, is just 1.3 billion years old. Another, called
Shergotty, for the town in India where it was discovered, was
formed a mere 165 million years ago, McKay said.
</P>
<P>
   And while ALH 84001 lay on _ or inside _ the ice of Antarctica
for 13,000 years before being found, Shergotty landed on Earth in
1865, and Nakhla in 1911. Both were collected almost immediately,
thus greatly reducing the possibility that anything seen inside
them is just earthly contamination.
</P>
<P>
   But the major difference in these new finds is the size of the
apparent fossils. The most contentious issue of all the questions
raised about the original claims concerned the tiny size of the
fossil-like shapes _ far smaller than any reliably known form of
microbial life on Earth
</P>
<P>
   There is no such problem with the new bacteria-like shapes in
Nakhla and Shergotty. The suspected fossils in those rocks are
about one micron (a millionth of a meter) across, exactly the same
size as some well-known Earth bacteria. Simply put, they look
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Thomas-Keprta, a member of the team that made the
original 1996 report, said she has analyzed hundreds of tiny
crystals of magnetite found inside that rock and found that they
show clear signs of having formed inside bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of both the Nakhla and Shergotty meteorite
formations, the biggest question now is whether these shapes formed
inside them are nothing more than terrestrial microbes that managed
to penetrate the rocks after they landed _ as unlikely as that
seems given their swift collection and careful storage in museums.
</P>
<P>
   In a particularly promising development in this polarized,
acrimonious debate, the new meteorite samples are being
simultaneously analyzed by two separate teams who are approaching
them with opposite assumptions _ one looking for proof that the
shapes really are remnants of Mars life, the other trying to prove
they are not. This ``red team-green team'' approach was initiated
by McKay himself, in an attempt to get past some of the acrimony of
the adversarial research so far.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the team that will try to disprove the Martian origin of
these formations is microbiologist Andrew Steele, who provocatively
suggested that the geologists examining the Mars rocks simply don't
know enough about Earthly microbial life to know what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   He demonstrated that many meteorites are contaminated with
terrestrial microorganisms that go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Steele doesn't rule out the possibility that they
might really be looking at Martian fossils and in fact sharply
criticized other researchers who stop looking once evidence of
contamination is found. ``Don't run away from contamination,'' he
urged the other scientists. Steele says he finds the shapes found
by McKay in the Nakhla meteorite to show convincing signs of life.
``They look like the real thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the nearly featureless blobs originally seen in ALH
84001, Steele said, the Nakhla shapes include appendages that look
like bacterial flagellae, the tiny hairlike filaments cells use to
move around, as well as what look like fibrils surrounding the cell
to attach it to a surface. There are alos surface textures that
resmble those of known microfossils, and a filmy material
surrounding the cell-like shapes, similar to those secreted by
living cells. All of these make a convincing case to
microbiologists who have examined it, Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   But it still could be that we'll never know for certain.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists now suspect that life on Earth might actually
have originated on Mars, and was carried to Earth inside meteorites
similar to those now being studied. Under this theory, we are all,
in effect, descendants of Martians _ and there might be no chemical
sign that would allow us to distinguish Earth life from microbes
from Mars.
</P>
<P>
   McKay thinks the answers will be known within a year. Steele is
less optimistic, but agrees that it should be possible to pin down
the nature of these formations long before the first rock samples
are brought back to Earth from Mars rovers in about 2007.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's essential that we do,'' he said. And perhaps, one
of mankind's most persistent questions _ whether we are alone and
unique _ will finally have been answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
