<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FOSSA-BOS &LR;      03-22 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FOSSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET THE FOOSA, A MISUNDERSTOOD MAMMAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's spelled fossa and pronounced FOO-sa. And if by chance you
know anything at all about Madagascar's largest predator, it's
probably wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The fossa, according to researcher Luke Dollar, is one of the
least understood mammals on earth. But Dollar, a graduate student
at the University of Tennessee at Knoxville, is hoping to change
that by studying the cat-like fossa in the wild (there are only a
few in captivity). So far, just about every piece of information he
gleans is either brand new or has challenged the scant literature
that exists. So little is known of them, in fact, that Dollar's
first fossa-related grant was to ``confirm their presence'' in
Ranamafana, a rain forest in southeastern Madagascar.
</P>
<P>
   He's done that. Now he wants to address bigger conservation
questions about the fossa: how does this animal affect populations
of prey animals, such as the lemur, and how does its existence
impact the environment of this nature-rich but fragile island? He
also wants to show Malagasy farmers who both fear and loath the
fossa that this predator is vital to keeping down the numbers of
rats that eat and foul the important rice harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Often described as puma-like in appearance, the fossa is slinky,
sinewy, and low slung. Its arboreal athleticism is said to be
rivaled only by that of the clouded leopard of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   With rounded ears and a shortened muzzle, these 15-pound
predators can look cute, but their ferocity is fabled. By using
their massive canine teeth fossas grab prey animals by the face and
then eviscerate them with formidable, retractable claws. Dollar
says they are ``killing machines'' that will ``eat anything with a
heartbeat.'' And they are strong enough to bring down animals at
least their own size.
</P>
<P>
   Though the fossa is categorized as a member of the mongoose
family, its cat-like attributes could be giving us a glimpse of
what the common ancestor to the cat and mongoose families looked
and behaved like.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar's path to this predator was through studying primates. In
Boston for last year's Earthwatch Festival of Science &AMP; Culture, he
said he first went to Madagascar, a 1,000-mile-long island off the
southeastern coast of Africa, to study its most famous animal
inhabitants: lemurs.
</P>
<P>
   As a lowly assistant, or as he says ``a research slave,'' Dollar
lost one of his first study subjects _ a rare red-bellied lemur _
when it was eaten by a fossa. Although disappointed, he was
intrigued with the reverence and respect the native trackers
accorded it when they discussed the fossa. Standing in the
rainforest in 1994, looking at the frayed radio collar of the
fossa's victim, Dollar says he had an epiphany. He was about to
dedicate all his energies to studying an animal he hadn't yet seen.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the United States with a mission, Dollar's
excitement only grew at the paucity of information his library
research yielded. What were these animals like? How do they hunt?
What do they eat? Could these small creatures really bring down
cattle? Dollar wanted to answer those very basic questions that
have lingered since the fossa was first seen by Westerners in the
19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Securing a grant with the help of leading lemur expert Patrica
Wright (who succinctly describes fossas with a dismissive: ``big
teeth, small brain''), Dollar returned to Madagascar in 1996.
Carrying $4,000 worth of tracking equipment to heave deep into the
rainforests of southeastern section of the island, Dollar trudged
through mud, braved hordes of terrestrial leeches and found his
fossa. Since many researchers have spent a decade or more working
in the forests of Madagascar without ever having glimpsed one, it
is no surprise that the first live fossa Dollar saw was caught in
one of his traps (traps baited with live chickens are the only ones
fossas visit). The first thing that struck him was the scent: an
overpowering wall of musk. ``It's almost indescribable,'' Dollar
says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Since that first fossa in 1996, Dollar has spent most of the
last two years trapping, darting, examining, radio collaring, and
tracking fossas with the help of a dedicated team of Malagasy field
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no evidence these small animals kill cattle,
Dollar has witnessed their impressive strength. One fossa chomped
through the side of a wooden trap that held him, and another
escaped a steel Tomahawk trap by twisting and bending the solid
metal door.
</P>
<P>
   But more important than the adventure, Dollar is, in his words,
``shaking up'' the literature on fossas. First, through activity
sensors on the radio collars, Dollar has determined that wild
fossas are not nocturnal, as reported in all the texts, but instead
cathemeral _ active both day and night. ``They basically sleep,
eat, hunt, and walk, and not necessarily in that order,'' Dollar
says.
</P>
<P>
   He is also the first to report that fossa catch fish and that
their preferred meal are lemurs. But their exact hunting strategy
is yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Fossas are also smaller and lighter than reported. Most of those
examined had been in zoos (such as San Diego, which has one; the
Montpelier Zoo in France; or Zoo Duisburg in Germany, which has had
success in breeding them), and are likely to grow heavier in
captivity. While many reports have said that fossas may tip the
scales at nearly 30 pounds, Dollar has never captured one weighing
more than 17 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   All these little pieces are helping fill in the larger portrait
of a little-known creature. And Dollar says that understanding the
carnivores of Madagascar is ``his passion.'' Right now, Dollar can
only guess how many fossas there are in the wild, perhaps 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be leading four expeditions to Madagascar this summer.
Information on joining him in his quest can be found on the
Internet at http://www.earthwatch.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything more blissful,'' Dollar says, ``than
hiking three days to a study site with a month's worth of rice and
beans on my back, and trapping animals where no researcher has ever
been before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
