<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE METAL DETECTORS HARMFUL TO YOUR HEALTH?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I re-enter the building where I work several times a day.
Each time my belongings are X-rayed and I walk through a scanner. I
am concerned about my health and wonder if the contents of my purse
are becoming increasingly radioactive.
</P>
<P>
   I.T., Cambridge, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's a lot of high-tech stuff happening as you walk
through that metal detector, or as your belongings pass through the
X-ray detector, but manufacturers say none of it is harmful to you
or your belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Detectors work in one of two ways: they either see, or they
smell. The archway you walk through to get into buildings or to
your gate at the airport detects for metal using pulses of
electromagnetic energy, nearly 200 per second. They're transmitted
from one side and received on the other, passing easily through the
body's soft tissue. But metal creates interference. The receiver on
the other side of the archway can tell if something metallic has
changed the shape of the radio wave, sped it up, or slowed it down.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Allman, of EG&AMP;G Astrophysics, which makes about 80 percent
of the security detectors used in America, says the Federal
Aviation Administration requires the machines to operate with a
small energy output, which is reported in gauss, the term for
measuring electromagnetic fields named after the German
mathematician who invented it. Airport metal detectors operate at
no more than one gauss. The background level emanating from the
earth is about .7 gauss. Using a blow dryer exposes you to roughly
1.5 gauss, and an electric can opener exposes you to about 4 gauss,
depending upon your distance from it. Allman says security
detectors in stores generate up to 20 gauss.
</P>
<P>
   No one has determined any health problems associated with metal
detectors, Allman says. There's no interaction with pacemakers,
either.
</P>
<P>
   The other detecting technology is X-ray. That's what your purse
or luggage is exposed to. It works the same way medical X-rays do.
Because of the unique characteristics of the X-ray beam, it is
either absorbed by the object it hits, penetrates the object, or is
scattered by it. The detector translates the beam's distortions
back into the ghostlike visual image of what you have in your
purse.
</P>
<P>
   Security X-ray machines usually use two beams, which pass
through the objects they're scanning between 100 and 200 times per
second. The total radiation exposure is about 1 millirem, Allman
says. Its not even enough to fog your film.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation can damage living cells, but not the inanimate objects
in your purse or luggage. And it doesn't build up in those objects
either.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how 1 millirem compares with other radiation exposures we
face in everyday living, according to the EPA:
</P>
<P>
   200 millirem per year from the air (mostly radon).
</P>
<P>
   40 per year from radioactive elements, like potassium, in food.
</P>
<P>
   40 per medical X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   26 millirem per year from cosmic radiation from outer space.
</P>
<P>
   23 millirem per year from the earth.
</P>
<P>
   1 millirem from watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA estimates the average American receives 360 millirem per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic sniffers looking for weapons or explosives vacuum up
an air sample and subject the collected molecules to fancy-sounding
processes like gas chromatography and ion mobility spectrometry.
They're all designed to break those molecules apart and look for
one thing; nitrogen. It's the most common telltale element that
signals the possibility of explosives. NITROglycerin and
triNITROtoluene (TNT) are some well known examples. Molecular
differences between nitrogen compounds help scientists design
sniffers that can even recognize one explosive from another.
</P>
<P>
   Sniffers are incredibly sensitive. They can detect a picogram,
one trillionth of a gram, of nitrogen. If you're carrying something
with a handle, like a briefcase or suitcase, and you fired a gun
several days ago, sniffers can detect the nitrogen from the
gunpowder on the handle of your baggage.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of X-ray detectors that can see explosives by
detecting the difference between organic and inorganic molecules
and the unique density of the organic molecules in explosives will
soon be on the market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
