<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MUST PAY FOR ENERGY CONSERVATION; SOME GET OFF HOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATTY WEN 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It always seems that it's the little items on bills that drive
people crazy. William E. Shea of Arlington, Mass., has two items on
his electric bill that drive him nuts. One is a monthly charge for
energy conservation, and the other is a fee to promote renewable
energy.
</P>
<P>
   For a typical customer, the two charges add up to $2.05 a month.
For Shea's business in Somerville, Ames Safety Envelope, it's an
extra $20,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   What irritates Shea is not the cost of the fees or the causes
they promote, but the fact that some communities don't have to pay
them at all. All customers of private utilities like Boston Edison
and Massachusetts Electric have to pay. But the charges don't apply
to residents of the 50 communities with municipal light
departments, including Belmont, Concord, Braintree, Hudson,
Wellesley, Peabody, and Danvers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I pay for their clean air?'' asked Shea. ``If clean
air is beneficial, why shouldn't everyone pay for it?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fair question. The best answer seems to be that the 50
communities did a good lobbying job on Beacon Hill when the state's
electric deregulation law was passed. They saved their residents
close to $27 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   William H. McLaughlin, a Boston tax attorney, has filed a class
action lawsuit with the Supreme Judicial Court to block the fees.
With Shea as his lead plaintiff, McLaughlin argues that the fees
are excise taxes that are not being applied uniformly. It's like
imposing the state's gasoline excise tax on residents of Brookline
but not Newton, McLaughlin argues.
</P>
<P>
   What is even more galling to McLaughlin and Shea is that a big
chunk of the money being raised from the renewable energy charge
will go to help defray costs that some of the 50 exempt communities
would otherwise be required to pay.
</P>
<P>
   As the electric deregulation law made its way through the
Legislature, an amendment was tacked on directing that nearly $50
million of the renewable energy money be used to pay for
environmental improvements at the state's waste-to-energy
incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   Which of the state's nine incinerators will get the money hasn't
been decided yet, but some of the communities exempted from the
renewable energy fee are likely to benefit. Belmont residents, for
example, don't contribute to the renewable energy fund, but they
are likely to get some of the money to offset $35 million of
planned environmental improvements at the Northeast Solid Waste
Committee incinerator in North Andover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see how someone would have the perception that we're
getting something for nothing,'' said Tim McCarthy, manager of the
Belmont Municipal Light Department and the head of the state's
Municipal Electric Association.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the fairness issues raised by Shea and McLaughlin will
prevail in court is hard to tell. The case will hinge on whether
the two fees are taxes, as McLaughlin insists, and whether the
taxes need to be uniformly applied.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Nogee of the Union of Concerned Scientists, which lobbied
hard for the fees, contends that they are not new taxes. The
state's private utilities were required to invest in energy
conservation and renewable energy before deregulation, Nogee said,
and they're required to do the same thing now. The only difference
is that before deregulation the costs were factored into rates; now
they're identified separately.
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that utilities are spending more now on energy
conservation and renewable energy projects and that part of the
renewable energy money is spent outside the utility's service
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Edison, for example, says it charged customers $29
million for energy conservation (energy audits, light bulb credits,
etc.) and renewable energy projects in 1997, the year prior to the
start of deregulation. This year, the first full year of
deregulation, the two new fees will raise a total of $54 million
from Edison customers, an 86 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the fees are determined to be taxes, one could argue
they are not unconstitutional because they will benefit everyone.
Even the incinerator improvements funded by the renewable energy
fund will make the air cleaner for everyone. And there is
historical precedent for not subjecting municipal utilities to
state regulation, since the municipal utilities are already
regulated locally.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the municipal exclusion seems to be more about politics
than practical sense. Says Nogee of the Union of Concerned
Scientists: ``From an environmental and public policy perspective,
it would be better if municipal customers did contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   We want your consumer ideas and tips. Please call 617-474-2510
or send e-mail to Mohl at mohl(at)globe.com or to Wen at
wen(at)globe.com. Their postal address is P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
