A9690 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCARY-THEOLOGY-POLITI     03-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARY-THEOLOGY-POLITICS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANGELICAL POLITICS COLLIDES WITH SCARY THEOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I recently felt 15 again.
 &HT;    Usually, when a 40-year-old woman feels like a teenager, it's a
positive thing. However, in this case, I didn't want to be reminded
of younger days.
 &HT;    Twenty-five years ago, I attended a conservative evangelical
church. After youth group one warm August night, I got ``born
again'' and accepted Jesus in my heart.
 &HT;    Jesus got there because the youth leaders scared me by teaching
that the end of the world was imminent. In the months previous, we
read one of the best-selling books of the 1970s, Hal Lindsey's huge
bestseller, ``Late Great Planet Earth.'' Lindsey believed that the
apocalypse, a period of terror immediately preceding the coming of
God's kingdom, was at hand.
 &HT;    Lindsey convinced us through an impressive array of evidence
about international politics, nuclear weapons and natural
disasters. The world is bad now, he warned, and it is about to get
much worse.
 &HT;    Luckily, God provided an escape plan for ``real'' Christians --
those saved by being born again -- called the Rapture. God would
take true believers from the earth and leave sinners to face his
wrath and Satan's unleashed power.
 &HT;    The Rapture seemed the better option -- I got scared to Jesus.
 &HT;    In 1975, nuclear annihilation, social chaos and economic
collapse threatened America. The world was shifting to what we now
know as the global, technological economy. It was a chaotic time.
 &HT;    Scary theology -- even if bad theology -- made sense.
 &HT;    Around 1980, however, scary theology made less sense. In
conservative churches, people began to talk politics instead of
apocalypse. Hal Lindsey was out; Ronald Reagan was in.
 &HT;    Instead of preparing for the last days, conservatives prepared
for primaries. Political consultants, rather than end times
prophets, made a killing.
 &HT;    As we approach 2000, the prophets are making a comeback. Why did
I feel 15? While on a recent business trip, I accidentally flipped
to Christian television. There, a well-dressed man was running
through a Power Point presentation on Y2K. Line by line, graph by
graph, the horror mounted: food shortages, urban violence, planes
falling to the ground, technological breakdown, nuclear
destruction.
 &HT;    At first, I didn't realize this was a Christian program. I sat
captivated by his smoothly delivered terror to what appeared to be
a suburban business seminar. Despite his nonchalant demeanor, this
man scared me. Should I buy a generator? A gun?
 &HT;    Get a grip, I told myself. Then I realized I had heard it all
before: as a teenager back in the 1970s. A slick evangelist was
playing off my fears. Only after an hour of calculated terror did
he finally push the button: come to Jesus (and stock up on food and
batteries) and everything will be fine.
 &HT;    In the 1970s, the Russians were a real threat, nuclear disaster
a real possibility. We were scared. The difference between then and
now is that the prophets have date for apocalyptic meltdown:
January 1, 2000.
 &HT;    Even the Rapture is popular again -- witness the 3 million
copies sold of Tim LaHaye's and Jerry Jenkins' last-days thrillers.
 &HT;    For many people, the apocalyptic worries of conservative
Christians seem fanciful -- if not fanatical. End times
speculations, however, are not just the stuff of fiction.
Millennial theology could play an important role in next year's
presidential elections -- especially for the Republican party.
 &HT;    Y2K points toward a disarming political reality: the religious
right is a theologically fickle group. In the 1970s, fear and
cultural disengagement kept them away from politics; in the 1980s,
prosperity propelled them into politics. Now, suffering from a
continued series of political losses and a gnawing apocalypticism,
they are politically unpredictable. Come New Hampshire, Christian
conservatives might go to the polls -- or they might be locked in
their basements.
 &HT;    Thus, Y2K is especially bad news for the Republicans who have
come to depend on the religious right. Their most reliable
constituency might not be raptured -- but they might not show up.
Evangelicals are moving back toward a policy of cultural
disengagement. Politicians who fail to account for this theological
promiscuity will misread the electorate and, perhaps, curry to an
absent interest group. People preparing for apocalypse don't vote.
 &HT;    And Y2K is bad news for evangelical political power. Already,
conservative Christian leaders are showing considerable ambivalence
regarding cultural engagement. Some leaders are urging religious
conservatives to get out of politics; others are reorganizing for a
major election-year push.
 &HT;    Will conservative Christians head for the polls or the hills?
 &HT;    If television evangelists are any indicator -- as they were when
evangelicals emerged as a political force in the 1980s -- I bet on
the hills. Or maybe their closets. In the world of the religious
right, Y2K means retreat. For a while, at least.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
