<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NICKELODEON-BOS &LR;      03-22 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NICKELODEON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 20 NICKELODEON IS TOP RATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two decades ago, certain truths about children's television were
held to be self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, that boys wouldn't watch TV shows whose main characters
were girls; that shows based on toys were the most surefire ticket
to commercial success; and that a cable channel devoted to children
wasn't likely to become a major player in the TV industry.
</P>
<P>
   And then, on April 1, 1979, Nickelodeon was born. You can now
find those old shibboleths in the bin marked ``Discard.''
</P>
<P>
   As the network prepares to celebrate its 20th birthday,
Nickelodeon is the top-rated cable network in the country, a
distinction it has claimed for four years in a row. Among kids aged
2 to 11, it is the top-rated network, period, besting ABC, CBS, NBC
and Fox even though it reaches millions fewer homes than the
broadcast behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   From a creative standpoint, Nickelodeon has helped transform the
world of children's television by emphasizing original series
rather than knockoffs, by putting girls in leading roles, and by
sticking to a resolutely ``kidcentric'' view of the world. Called
``one of the great innovations of the cable age'' by TV historians
Tim Brooks and Earle Marsh, the network also helped the young cable
industry market itself to new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Nickelodeon's creative strength has come from trying
to buck conventional wisdom,'' said Nickelodeon president Herb
Scannell, a 42-year-old graduate of Boston College. ``We challenged
a lot of myths and looked at the world from a kid's point of view.
Now a lot of people are imitating us.''
</P>
<P>
   That is doubtless prompted by the fact that Nickelodeon's
financial success proved once and for all that children's
television could be big business. ``It started to make a ton of
money, and that's something the rest of the industry pays attention
to,'' remarked Peggy Charren, founder of Action for Children's
Television. ``I don't know how much the industry cares about girls
getting good female role models, but they sure care about making
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But is there a price to Nickelodeon's own success? Can the
network retain what Scannell calls its kids-first philosophy as it
branches out into movies, websites, books, a magazine, live shows,
and merchandise ranging from clothes to video games?
</P>
<P>
   Scannell says yes, but questions intensified in November when
Nickelodeon came under fire for seeming to manipulate the child
audience in order to promote ``The Rugrats Movie.'' In the week
prior to the movie's premiere, the network took ``Rugrats'' off the
air and aired in its place a teaser reading: ``The Rugrats have
gone to Hollywood!'' The stunt dismayed and angered some parents.
Author Richard Panek argued in The New York Times that it was ``a
tactic that violates parents' trust, precisely because it treats
our children with something less than respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon vice president Cyma Zarghami said the network felt
it need to ``pull out all the stops'' to make ``The Rugrats Movie''
a success, but conceded: ``We'd think hard before we'd do that
again.'' Scannell seemed to concur, calling it ``a different kind
of marketing strategy'' but adding: ``I'm not saying we would do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Rugrats'' controversy is significant because for 20 years,
the relentlessly promoted notion that the network is for and about
kids has been central to Nickelodeon's strategy and identity. In
the early years, the philosophy was: No grownups allowed (except,
of course, at night when Nickelodeon airs nostalgia fare for
baby-boomers, packaged as Nick at Nite).
</P>
<P>
   Kids liked the message, liked the contemporary flavor and
playful wit of shows like ``Doug'' and ``Hey Arnold!,'' and eagerly
tuned in. Soon, when other networks wondered where many of their
young viewers had gone, the answer was: Watching Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals were watching too, often with apprehension. The
pioneering sitcom ``Clarissa Explains It All'' triggered a wave of
shows on other networks with girls as lead characters, while the
success of Nickelodeon's ``Rugrats'' got rivals scrambling to
create their own original animation rather than shows derived from
dolls or action figures. Recently, Nickelodeon's hugely popular
``Blues Clues'' put PBS on notice that it no longer had the
preschool audience to itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nickelodeon has had a tremendous impact on children's
television,'' said Amy Jordan, head of research on children's TV at
the Annenberg Public Policy Center of the University of
Pennsylvania. ``It created an island, this child-friendly place
where kids knew if they turned it on, there would be something for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But at first, notes Charren, ``There was nothing particularly
interesting about the programming'' on Nickelodeon. At the
beginning of this decade, that changed, as Nickelodeon introduced a
sitcom titled ``Clarissa Explains It All,'' whose popularity buried
the boys-won't-watch-girls myth once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Scannell was a development executive at Nickelodeon then, and
whenever producers asked what he was looking for, he would say ``a
show about girls.'' His answer arrived in the person of Mitchell
Kriegman, who created ``Clarissa'' for Nickelodeon.
</P>
<P>
   Kriegman, who is now executive producer of ``Bear in the Big
Blue House'' on the Disney Channel, says Nickelodeon was pulsing
with energy when he arrived in 1991, an atmosphere he attributes to
Geraldine Laybourne, president of the network from 1980 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very pure passion that Gerry engendered in
people,'' said Kriegman. ``It was a hugely creative place, with a
lot of people who had a new look at kids. The basic philosophy was:
`Do something for kids, take a risk, and do it so you like it too.'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was high-risk, innovative, take-a-chance programming,'' he
added. ``They weren't protecting a lead; they weren't protecting a
market share.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kriegman began work at Nickelodeon on ``Clarissa'' _ he was
also story editor on ``Rugrats'' and ``Doug'' _ the network was
largely identified with the raucous ``Ren and Stimpy,'' a gross-out
cartoon whose humor revolved around flatulence and vomiting. Though
Kriegman says he loved ``Ren and Stimpy,'' the programs he created
and championed helped change Nickelodeon's image. `` `Clarissa' and
`Doug' and `Rugrats' said we were more than slime,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of Nickelodeon in those years, and the key to
its current success, was Laybourne's decision that the network
would ``be all for kids, and all from their point of view,''
according to Kriegman. ``That meant they weren't for toys; they
weren't for the business; they were for what kids wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``radically redefined'' the way programmers throughout the
television industry approached the child audience, according to
Kriegman. Suddenly, programs based on formulas that had succeeded
elsewhere was out; original live-action and animation, based on
what kids said they wanted to see, were in.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon gained confidence as it gained momentum, so much so
that it even rolled out that rarest of kids' programs, a news show,
called ``Nick News,'' in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two years ago, Nickelodeon became home to ``Blue's
Clues,'' an educational game show for toddlers that Charren calls
``unlike anything else on television.'' Scratch the Nickelodeon
surface a bit further nowadays and you find a cockeyed gem like
``The Wild Thornberrys.'' It features a girl as its central
character, which follows in the tradition of not just ``Clarissa''
but also Nickelodeon's ``The Secret World of Alex Mack'' and ``The
Mystery Files of Shelby Woo.''
</P>
<P>
   One mark of Nickelodeon's longevity and success is the number of
alumni who now hold influential positions elsewhere in television.
Laybourne recently left a top job at ABC to form a new network
called Oxygen Media with Oprah Winfrey. Anne Sweeney, who got her
start under Laybourne at Nickelodeon, is now president of
Disney/ABC Cable Networks, which gives her control of the Disney
Channel and ABC's Saturday morning children's lineup. Some of the
writers who worked on ``Clarissa'' went on to write for such hit
shows as ``Friends'' and ``Roseanne.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nickelodeon under Scannell is doing more than fine. So far
this TV season, the network boasts 17 of the 20 most-watched kids'
shows in the country, including No. 1-rated ``Rugrats,'' which was
spun off into a movie that has grossed nearly $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three years, we've really taken the business to a
whole new level,'' said Scannell. ``We're in the movie business
now; we're in the consumer products business; we made a big move on
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some Nickelodeon watchers hope the network won't be
content to just flex its muscles. Jordan, the Annenberg Center
researcher, said she hopes Nickelodeon will follow the civic path
blazed by the network's ``The Big Help'' volunteer effort and
``show they can do more than just capitalize on their audience.''
Looking at the current Nickelodeon lineup, Kriegman wonders whether
his old network has moved from ``doing something original to just
doing something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Scannell, though, argues that the ``spirit of innovation'' is
very much alive at Nickelodeon, and added: ``The future is really
bright now.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the future holds for Nickelodeon, the two decades of
its past are considered remarkable by hard-to-impress observers
like Charren.
</P>
<P>
   ``To, the most amazing thing Nickelodeon has done is it became a
commercial venture that did all the things you would not expect a
commercial venture to do,'' she said. ``Nickelodeon did so much
right _ and it worked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
