<HEADLINE>
LIVING YOUR LIFE ON TV: FROM OPIE TO ED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that art imitates life. In the case of ``EDtv,'' a new
comedy directed by Ron Howard, the similarities are uncanny.
``EDtv,'' which opened Friday, examines obsession with celebrity at
a cultural moment when America's fascination with fame has reached
a nearly unimaginable zenith. The film deals with invasion of
privacy by the media, a topic turned super-hot in the last several
years. Even the cast members of ``EDtv'' have all been subjected to
intense media glare: Ellen DeGeneres, Elizabeth Hurley, Matthew
McConaughey, Woody Harrelson, and Jenna Elfman have felt, to
varying degrees, the limelight's glow deepen into an uncomfortable
burn.
</P>
<P>
   Howard himself is perhaps uniquely equipped to grapple with such
themes. He literally grew up on television, starring as Opie on
``The Andy Griffith Show'' in the 1960s and then as Richie
Cunningham on ``Happy Days'' the following decade. At 45, Howard is
as sweet, polite, and boyishly enthusiastic as the characters he
created on the small screen. ``Yeah, some of these ideas resonate
for me in a personal way,'' Howard says, smiling and settling into
the sofa in his suite at the Ritz-Carlton, where he's spending the
day doing promotional interviews for the film. ``For one thing, I
knew that if I did something really stupid it was going to get
noticed. It probably made me a little less adventuresome, which is
maybe a bad thing and maybe a good thing. I knew if I was arrested
for drunk driving it would be a huge humiliation. Part of me thinks
that if we all lived in such a way that we knew our dumb mistakes
would be noticed we might just use a tiny bit more caution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing,'' Howard goes on, ``is that weird, ongoing
relationship with people who have seen you on TV and therefore
think they know you. They can be really familiar with you, but you
don't know them back. That's odd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv'' chronicles four months in the life of _ you guessed it
_ Ed (McCounaghey), a charming but aimless video-store clerk who is
selected to star in a foundering cable TV network's last-ditch
effort to boost ratings: a 24-hour-a-day broadcast of one ordinary
guy's life. Cameras follow Ed's every move, from the moment he
wakes (usually with his hands down his jammies) to the moment he
falls asleep. If that sounds uncomfortably similar to last year's
``The Truman Show,'' rest assured the similarities, while striking,
are superficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nightmare,'' says Howard, ``is that people are going to
say, `Oh, I think I've already seen ``EDtv.' '' That would break my
heart. Because beyond that sort of one-sentence description,
they're totally different. `The Truman Show' was more like a
`Twilight Zone,' a drama about this guy who doesn't know he's on
television. This is about a guy who chooses to say `yes. I'm gonna
turn my life into an absolute media circus and I'm gonna ride that
wave. I'm gonna take that 15 minutes of fame and milk it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The film marks a reunion for Howard and screenwriters Lowell
Ganz and Babaloo Mandel (their last collaboration was on 1989's
``Parenthood''). ``EDtv'' is also a comedy with serious overtones _
dealing not only with issues of celebrity but also with family
dysfunction. Ed's family, a wonderfully motley crew played by Sally
Kirkland, Martin Landau, Dennis Hopper, and Woody Harrelson, begins
to unravel and reveal its dark underside in the glare of the TV
lights. ``One of the themes that's interesting to me has to do with
the myth of the functional family,'' Howard says. ``I think I've
got a great family.'' In perfect ``Happy Days'' form, Howard's been
married to Cheryl, his high-school sweetheart, for 23 years; they
have four children. ``But are we `functional'? I don't know that
anybody is. So we decided to take that idea of the life unexamined.
It's the TV experience that forces Ed's family to take a serious
look at themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But first and foremost,'' Howard goes on, ``I think the film
deals with the question: `Is fame in and of itself a worthy role?'
Why do people go on the daytime talk shows? Why is it important in
this country, and increasingly around the world, to get noticed?
Then when we developed the love story'' _ Ed falls in love, in
front of a million viewers, with his brother's girlfriend, played
by the luminously geeky Jenna Elfman _ ``suddenly it became a
question of what we think is going to solve our problems vs. what
actually will. These things are hard enough in private. How in the
world can you develop a love relationship under those
circumstances?''
</P>
<P>
   Howard is no stranger to loss of privacy. He moved his family to
Greenwich, Conn., when the children were young to avoid the high
visibility of Hollywood life. ``I mean, you're having an argument
with your wife and somebody wants to snap pictures. You can be
disciplining your kids, you're embarrassed, you're angry, you're
upset, and somebody's coming up and wanting attention from you. I'm
always patient with it, because my parents taught me to do that.
And I think I really began to understand it clearly when my kids
began to be dazzled by celebrities that they meet and suddenly it
became important to me, as a father, to give them that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its attention to matters close to home, there's no
takeaway message in ``EDtv.'' Howard, whose movies tend to be more
about feeling good than about provoking powerful reactions, doesn't
expect you to leave the theater with any answers. Rather, he hopes
audiences will have some good laughs. ``Nobody wanted it to be a
whiny movie about how crummy it is to be well-known. It
acknowledges that there are some thorns out there, but at the end
of the day it was a pretty positive experience for Ed. I think he
came out of it OK.'' So, quite clearly, did Ron Howard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
