<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-STORY-BOS &LR;      03-22 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-STORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPDIKE PICKS THE BEST SHORT STORIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BEST AMERICAN SHORT STORIES OF THE CENTURY 
John Updike, editor; Katrina Kenison, coeditor 
Houghton Mifflin. 775 pp. $28 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We can thank Scheherazade for keeping the story going and Edgar
Allan Poe for hauling it into the modern age, and one can hardly
imagine American literature without it. Born from the epic tale and
Westernized by Chaucer, the short story emerged in the mid-19th
century wearing its own suit of clothes. Nobody took it for granted
then; it hadn't yet been shoved around on the playground by the
bigger, more brutish novel. For a time, before publishing itself
became a predictable story of corporate earnings, short stories
prospered both aesthetically and commercially: The best writers
wrote them, and everybody, it seemed, read them _ in the Atlantic,
or Harper's, or that old literary mansion of short fiction, The New
Yorker. Then came the triumph of visual narrative, from ``I Love
Lucy'' to MTV, and an amazing short story, read the evening before,
could no longer get you into a conversation with a stranger on a
train.
</P>
<P>
   But if the mass appeal of short stories has narrowed in the past
few decades, its critical reputation has been fiercely guarded by
practitioners and devotees alike. The Houghton Mifflin literary
series of ``The Best American Stories,'' born in 1915 and taken
over by that publishing house in 1933, has been an integral record
of the century's short fiction; its tastes and selections have been
shaped, obviously, by its editors, which in the past two decades
have included an annual guest rotation that has ensured the
wideness of its net. As the only writer to have his own work chosen
in volumes from each of the past five decades, John Updike was
invited to select the best of the best (but alas, only one story
from each writer) for this millennial anthology. Katrina Kenison,
the series editor since 1990, made the first cut, winnowing some
2,000 stories from the original editions down to more than 200;
from that number, Updike chose the final 55 (Kenison insisted on
his own inclusion). They have done a splendid job: ``The Best
American Short Stories of the Century'' is a treasure _ a
one-volume literary history of this country's immeasurable pains
and near-infinite hopes.
</P>
<P>
   America! If you love the language that belongs to its fields and
regions and city streets, you can hear it here in myriad forms: in
the careful, impeccably sad craft of Sherwood Anderson, the
haunting, mystical sheen of William Saroyan, the bleak and
onomatopoeic poetry of Annie Proulx. You can feel the cold wind off
Ellis Island, the suffocating thickness of the Deep South, the
lunacies of war, the more ordinary cruelties of a marriage gone
bad, a child sick, or an old woman alone. There is the slyly
laconic modernist verse in Hemingway, the urban, celebratory battle
cry of Bellow, the slate-gray invocations of exurban America in
Cheever and Updike. Students of literature can trace the directions
of this century's fiction from the railroads laid by Faulkner to
the creepy Gothic strains of Joyce Carol Oates to the dark hilarity
of Lorrie Moore; students of history, having here what no straight
text can give them, will find Fitzgerald's tinseltown Babylon and
Roth's Second World War and Tim O'Brien's Vietnam. Largest of all,
though, is the unalterable private journey that literature
requires. You come back stretched and challenged from these
stories, awed by the quality of this century's fiction, and sobered
by how very unpretty much of America's story really is.
</P>
<P>
   What stands up, and what doesn't? It was a question the editors
had to ask themselves, and readers will as well. (Though sometimes
toward the same end by different means: I found myself agreeing
with Updike's choices, for the most part, but arguing with his
interpretations.) Nowadays, this selection from Fitzgerald _
``Crazy Sunday'' (1933), where a guy is trying to stay away from
drink and dangerous dames _ seems arch and somewhat
cardboard-melodramatic. Donald Barthelme's spooky absurdism,
captured in ``A City of Churches'' (1973), comes off merely as an
interesting card trick. The stories that display a haunting
longevity are often subtle ones: Elizabeth Bishop's ``The Farmer's
Children'' (1949), which contains an ice-white, terrible beauty; E.
B. White's ``The Second Tree from the Corner'' (1948), which
captures the wounds of a universal yearning. William Saroyan's
``Resurrection of a Life'' (1935), steeped in elegiac excess,
nonetheless still grabbed me by the shoulders. But the 1930s seem a
bit dull, even with Faulkner, while the '40s seem compellingly
rich, though the stories feel studiedly not about the war.
Literature sometimes takes time to catch up to history, even when
it surpasses it: Philip Roth's ``Defenders of the Faith,'' a
captivatingly moral story about a Jewish sergeant and his men
during World War II, is from 1960; while Cynthia Ozick's stunning
classic about a concentration camp, ``The Shawl,'' was published in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   Ozick's brief tragedy is so strong that it takes one's breath
away, but there are other classics as well: Jean Stafford's dark
journey into a woman's hospitalized consciousness in ``The Interior
Castle'' (1947); Cheever's ``The Country Husband'' (1955), with its
gorgeous last sentence; Flannery O'Connor's ``Greenleaf'' (1957),
still chilling with its take-no-prisoners grace. Isaac Bashevis
Singer's ``The Key'' (1970) beautifully displays his singular
position in his craft by capturing a frightened woman who's
forgotten how to trust. Raymond Carver, in his funny-painful detox
tale, ``Where I'm Calling From'' (1983), ushers in the contemporary
short story with grim, post-Hemingway detail; Ann Beattie
highlights the subjectivity and privacy of the modern world's
epiphanies in one of her better stories, ``Janus'' (1986). There
are also a few outright surprises here, most notably Mary Ladd
Gavell's ``The Rotifer'' (1968), a story of chance and swarming
life that begins under a microscope and ends with a question mark.
First appearing in the journal Psychiatry, it was the only story
she ever published.
</P>
<P>
   I read these stories straight through, from the Lower East Side
of 1915 (Benjamin Rosenblatt's ``Zelig'') to the desolate
destruction of the modern Western myth (Proulx's ``The Half-Skinned
Steer,'' 1998). That reading pattern isn't necessary or even
recommended, but it does display how the very feel of fiction has
changed over the years: the young, half-innocent irony of pre-World
War II America, the lushness that seems to have emerged in the '40s
and '50s, the desultory, even anarchic patterns of the stories from
the '80s and '90s that nonetheless often deliver a kind of
itinerant-narrative wisdom. No collection will have everything
everyone desires, but I particularly missed Robert Stone's
``Helping''; it also seems a travesty that the best short fiction
of the century would leave out Grace Paley, though I don't know
that her work was included in earlier volumes. Still, Updike has
the grace and sense to write about his regrets as well as his
choices, so that even a few of his omissions get a conciliatory
nod.
</P>
<P>
   Captured by a panoply of writers in this century, there is,
finally, the cumulative howl and refrain of America: a song of and
to itself, wild and mournful and unendingly alive. ``I am left with
myself unexpressed,'' says the heartbroken man in Bernard Malamud's
``The German Refugee'' (1964). But his frustrated sorrows, however
silent, are etched into stone by the fact of this story: by all the
voices in this extraordinary volume, and by the writers who were
able to hear their tones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
