<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HIPHOP-HILL-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURYN HILL TAKES HIP-HOP TO A NEW LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``My name is Lauryn Hill. My name was always Lauryn
Hill. My name will always be Lauryn Hill.'' With that simple
declaration of self, the artist who is arguably the most important
figure in popular music crystallized the essence of her one-woman
hip-hop revolution. She spoke the words quietly, between songs at
the Fox Theatre here last weekend, in the clear, unaffected voice
of one who makes no claim to the swaggering style and braggadocio
image that have characterized her genre for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has rewritten the crusty old hip-hop script _ littered with
aging gangsta rappers, paint-by-number crews, and rhyming fashion
slaves _ in a vibrant new language. It's a language of personal
revelation and religious dedication, one that's earthy and soulful,
spiritual and womanly. On stage, Hill tucks her turntables between
a drum set and an old wood organ. She'll bring 16 musicians with
her to the Wang Center on March 31 and April 1; only one of them is
a DJ. It's her respectful return to the roots of African-American
music and African-American experience _ and the maverick
individuality required to build that bridge _ that make Lauryn
Hill, at the age of 23, such a towering force in music.
</P>
<P>
   Hill wasn't merely paying lip service when she appeared at the
Rhythm and Blues Foundation Pioneer Awards in Los Angeles last
month to introduce Patti LaBelle and the Bluebells, telling them,
``You are my teachers.'' Her solo debut album, ``The Miseducation
of Lauryn Hill'' (which the artist wrote and produced and which won
five Grammys last month), is a visionary fusion of contemporary
hip-hop and old-school R &AMP; B. The sort of stripped, organic soul
that fueled Stevie Wonder's early work infuses ``Miseducation,'' as
does the smooth grace distilled by Marvin Gaye. Hill's voice is
thick with reggae's pungent lilt, and its social conscience. She
mines melodies with a feel as innate as Aretha's; she raps beats _
in a deep, husky flow of spoken rhythm _ like a born MC.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who grew up in suburban New Jersey and began her career as
L-Boogie in the Fugees, is a gifted rapper who eschews nearly every
hip-hop convention. Like the influential artists she's descended
from, Hill is beholden only to her ear and her heart. To a genre
weaned on guns and drugs, big cars and closed minds, she brings a
sustaining faith, political commitment, and sensuality. She's
expanded the parameters of hip-hop with a vision that is true to
modern urban experience but that skewers _ with the simple power of
her humanity _ the modern urban mythology.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Zion'' rises like a phoenix from the ashes of murdered rap
stars Tupak Shakur and Biggie Smalls: a chanting, simmering hymn to
motherhood, to the redemptive power of giving life. That Hill chose
to embellish such a transcendent (and, for hip-hop, radically
uplifting) theme with the swirling acoustic work of rock guitarist
Carlos Santana is one more testament to her singular vision.
</P>
<P>
   Hill (who declined to be interviewed for this story) is at the
vanguard of hip-hop's new positivity. Choosing to begin her concert
with a scratchy recording, played in the darkened theater, of Bob
Marley singing the luminous ``Redemption Song'' is not merely a
deferential gesture to the reggae icon. (Hill's fiance and the
father of her two young children, by the way, is Rohan, Marley's
son.) Blasting Bob Marley's folk anthem to freedom is an
unqualified statement of purpose: Hill is here to take her place in
a chain of passionate musician-philosophers for whom past and
present _ and music and message _ are inextricably linked . &QL; 
 &QL; 
An overarching faith &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the album title, which echoes Carter G. Woodson's ``The
Miseducation of the Negro,'' to her unfailing belief in God as the
source of all things sacred and profane, Hill reunites two segments
of the culture that have diverged over time. Where hip-hop is the
mouthpiece of the marginalized urban youth and religious faith is
the cornerstone of the old guard, Hill fuses the two. ``Be seen
through / Let God redeem you / Keep your deen true / Watch out what
you cling to / You can get the green too / Observe how a queen do /
And I remain calm readin' the 73 Psalm / 'Cause wit all this on I
got the world in palm,'' Hill raps in ``Final Hour.'' And on ``I
Used to Love Him,'' a duet with another groundbreaking musician,
Mary J. Blige, Hill proclaims, ``Father you saved me and showed me
that life / Was much more than being some foolish man's wife /
Showed me that love was respect and devotion / Greater than planets
deeper than oceans.''
</P>
<P>
   By daring to invoke her own spiritual transformation as the
bedrock of a hip-hop record, Hill has pushed the edge of the
envelope at a critical time in the evolution of urban music.
``Lauryn has redefined the notion of what it is to make a hip-hop
record,'' says Selwin Seysu Hinds, editor in chief of The Source,
hip-hop's preeminent publication. ``It's already had a huge impact
on the genre. Hip-hop has always responded well to people who show
that the parameters aren't fixed. When gangsta rap was in, that was
it. During Puffy's rule, that was it. What sets Lauryn apart is her
spirituality, her soulfulness. She is the first real MC rapper to
make a soul record. As hip-hop goes into the 21st century, she puts
the exclamation point on creative diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill is not unaware of her position, and in concert she made
good-natured reference to it by staging a series of spirited duels
with her DJ. It was old school vs. new school, as Hill and her band
broke into the Jackson 5's ``I Want You Back,'' only to be rebutted
by turntablist Leon Higgins's heavy beats. She and the band, which
included a horn section and a trio of female vocalists, alternated
soul classics (Stevie Wonder's ``Sir Duke'' and Gladys Knight's
``Midnight Train to Georgia'') with Higgins's hip-hop anthems,
until Hill eventually launched into a buoyant cover of rapper
Jay-Z's ``Hard-Knock Life,'' calling out, ``You think the band
can't play hip-hop? Let's put 'em all together like family.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
