<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HAMELIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANIST HAMELIN VENTURES FROM STUDIO TO STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marc-Andre Hamelin is a famous pianist in Europe, particularly
in Great Britain. His work is still not known to the general
musical public in America, however, though he has lived in
Philadelphia for 18 years and won the Carnegie Hall International
American Competition in 1985. His recordings have become a pillar
of the distinguished Hyperion label, and his 1994 disc of works by
the eccentric French romantic composer Charles-Valentin Alkan has
been praised in Fanfare Magazine as ``one of the best releases of
anything to have been made, a classic of the recording era.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin, now 37, has returned to Boston for the first time since
a 1986 recital and a 1988 appearance with the Harvard Chamber
Orchestra (under the direction of Leon Kirchner) to play a program
in Sanders Theatre benefiting Harvard radio, WHRB-FM (95.3). His
repertory is characteristically enterprising, including standard
works by Bach (the Fifth French Suite) and Brahms (the Intermezzi,
Op. 117) alongside such unusual works as the ``Sonata romantica''
by Rachmaninoff's contemporary Nikolai Medtner; the entertaining,
supervirtuoso variations by Alkan, ``Le Festin d'Esope''; and
Liszt's ``Reminiscences'' of Bellini's opera ``Norma.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from his home in Philadelphia, the
deep-voiced Hamelin said he was not a prodigy. ``My beginnings were
very modest. I was born in Montreal, and it was discovered very
early that I had perfect pitch, and I think that makes a lot of
difference _ it makes it possible to assimilate music faster;
reading music is easier and more efficient; and intramusical
hearing is facilitated. Later, this ability made it possible to
compose and practice away from the piano.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin has needed this gift. Every young pianist needs to be
prepared to jump in when a famous artist cancels. Hamelin is ready,
with 40 concertos in his repertory. ``The nature of our craft is
that we have to prepared for emergencies. My greatest
accomplishment along those lines so far was when I stepped in for
Peter Serkin in Beethoven's First Concerto on 3 1/2 hours' notice.
I was in Montreal, and ran out to buy a score because I didn't have
one with me. The orchestra sent a cab, and during the ride, which
took an hour and a quarter on the slippery ice, I practiced
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin began his studies with a private teacher, and when it
became clear he was talented, his parents enrolled him in what he
calls ``the best school in Montreal,'' the Vincent D'Indy School.
``There my progress was quite rapid. Every year we had
competitions. When I was 9, I played the Kabalevsky Variations;
when I was 12, I was ready for Debussy's `Jardins sous la pluie,'
and the next year brought a huge jump to Chopin's `Andante spianato
and Grand Polonaise.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin had been exposed to the standard literature from early
childhood. ``My father is a pharmacist and also a very good amateur
pianist. He had a good collection of music and I was always looking
through it. Instinctively I wanted to do what my father did, and I
also wanted to compose, so I wrote things that made no sense _
unfortunately, we didn't keep any of this stuff, because I'd be
curious to see it now. When I got to be a teenager, the urge to
compose came again. I still try to compose when I can, although
there is less and less time to do it. I've recorded some of my own
transcriptions _ Rossini's `La Danza,' for example.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin's interest in exploring unfamiliar repertory dates back
to his 13th year. ``I was looking around in a record store and I
found John Kirkpatrick's recording of Ives's `Concord' Sonata. I
was intrigued because in October 1974, Clavier magazine had put out
a special Ives centennial issue. I wanted to hear this music, and
now the recording was in my hands. It was the first record I ever
bought for myself, and I listened to it at least once a day for a
whole summer; a whole new world was opening up. Three months later
I bought the score and started fiddling with it, although I didn't
play it in public until 1985. I still play it today.''
</P>
<P>
   At 19, Hamelin came to the United States to accept a full
scholarship at Temple University, in Philadelphia. ``This was the
best thing I had ever done. I could have stayed in Canada, but I
probably would have had only a one-dimensional education there. I
would even urge European musicians to come to the States to study
music.''
</P>
<P>
   The last of Hamelin's American teachers was Russell Sherman,
with whom he worked privately between 1986 and 1988. ``This was the
last period when I was taking piano lessons. I was attracted to
Russell Sherman because of his reputation, and when I came to him,
I was not disappointed. He really teaches you to think, and
encourages you to create wonderful images _ he encourages the
imagination. I remember once I was playing for him the Beethoven
Sonata, Op. 10, No. 2, and in the trio of the second movement, I
wasn't catching the mood. So he said to me in his soft-spoken,
delicate way of speaking, `Think of these huge Roman temples, these
vast columns _ and behind one of them Julius Caesar is being
assassinated.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The 1985 Carnegie Hall International American Music Competition
was a prestigious prize that brought Hamelin a number of concerts,
including his Boston debut, and a first recording (etudes by
William Bolcom and the ``Battle Piece'' by Stefan Wolpe, for New
World Records; later he recorded Ives's ``Concord'' Sonata for the
same label).
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin's reputation has spread through his recordings. For a
small company named Altarus, he recorded the First Sonata of
reclusive and eccentric composer Kaikhosru Shapurji Sorbabji. Then,
for Music &AMP; Arts, Hamelin recorded an Alkan album, a Liszt album,
and an album of cabaret music with his wife, singer Jody Applebaum.
Their partnership has been compared with the celebrated work of
Joan Morris and Bolcom, but Hamelin says there is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They concentrate on American popular music of earlier periods,
and we perform an international repertory of French, German,
British, and American cabaret songs. We have another CD on the
Helicon label of work by German cabaret composer Friedrich
Hollander, who later fled from Germany and became a film composer.
The Nazis destroyed every trace of his work they could find, so 14
out of the 18 tracks are first recordings. We think the music is
just wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   In England and to some extent elsewhere in Europe, Hamelin is
now a top-ranking pianist, thanks mostly to the uniformly
enthusiastic critical reception for 15 recordings that have
appeared on Hyperion. He has an active European management, but the
American management scene is in such disarray, and operates under
such distorted priorities, that Hamelin has to look after his own
arrangements in this country. Hyperion has succeeded in the
international marketplace because it knows its priorities,
maintaining an old-fashioned commitment to quality over all things;
the company records music it wants to hear, performed by musicians
it believes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales manager for Hyperion is a fellow named Mike Spring,
who is the resident piano fan and specialist,'' Hamelin explains.
``Hyperion's series of romantic piano concertos, which is now in
its 18th or 19th installment, is his brainchild. He was looking for
other pianists to record some of these concertos, and he came to a
recital I was giving with a cellist in a London suburb. It took us
a while to agree over repertory, but we started with concertos by
Alkan and Henselt, and later moved on to concertos by Marx and
Korngold. I have a wish list and Mike has a wish list, and when our
wish lists coalesce, a record is usually born.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the concertos, Hamelin has also recorded many
solo discs for Hyperion, including sets of Reger Variations, the
complete Scriabin Sonatas, a Liszt record, a Grainger record, and
four discs of the Medtner Sonatas. ``My discovery of Medtner was
gradual and eye-opening. It rarely makes its best impression at
first. It doesn't come at you, like Rachmaninoff's music does; you
need to go to it, and then you begin to realize just how amazing it
is. The intensity of interest grows with each hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamelin is quick to emphasize that he is still ``in touch'' with
the standard literature and that he is looking forward to recording
an all-Schumann album. He is politically incorrect enough to object
to Beethoven on the early piano. ``I have never liked the unclear
attack and lingering resonances of the fortepiano. I have a problem
with that _ not with playing Bach on the piano! What I do think is
a problem is that the programs for piano recitals are becoming a
bit stale. I don't understand why every young pianist feels he has
to play Mussorgsky's `Pictures at an Exhibition.' Programs today
need some spicing up, and so that's what I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
