<HEADER>
A9711 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-HIPHOP-HILL-2ND     03-22 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HIPHOP-HILL-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ATLANTA: ... like family.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hill is joined in the charge to broaden rap's musical and
cranial focus by up-and-coming groups like the Roots, Black Eyed
Peas, Everlast, and OutKast, an Atlanta duo that won the opening
slot on Hill's current tour. ``Lauryn has let people know that you
can do more than one thing,'' says OutKast's Dre Benjamin, winding
down backstage after his set. ``You don't just have to rhyme all
day long. It's music. And the words are deep, know that.''
OutKast's stage was set with an enormous painting of a weeping,
pregnant woman. ``That's Mama Earth,'' explains Benjamin, a
teetotaling vegan who is the philosophical descendant of musical
explorers like Sun-Ra and George Clinton. ``She's crying 'cause
she's dying,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin is one of the new breed of rap stars unafraid to break
out of the mold and reveal their tender sides. His songs have
titles like ``Hold On, Be Strong'' and ``Rosa Parks.'' Like Hill,
Benjamin is a new parent; 16-month-old Seven Benjamin's mother is R
&AMP; B singer Erykah Badu. ``You can't teach kids one side. You got to
let them know there's two sides to things. . . . The audience is
like kids. Let 'em know what's going on the street, but at the same
time bring a positive outlook. And put it to something funky where
people can feel it. Lauryn is showing the world that you can get
back to that now.''
</P>
<P>
   When the artist who comes along to upend the rules is a woman,
however, one has to wonder how comfortably she manages to fit into
_ let alone transform _ hip-hop's firmly entrenched boy's club.
``Yes, hip-hop is, at its core, a celebration of black
masculinity,'' says Hinds. ``And it's an ongoing challenge for
women to figure out how to play in that club. The marvelous thing
about Lauryn is that she's sexy and beautiful, but everyone I know
has this reverence for her. Guys talk about her in a sense that's
not as a lover but as a friend and a sister. The hard-core rappers
accept her. There's a deep, abiding love for Lauryn and what she
represents. She's almost holy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Propelling hip-hop &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop has been slowly expanding its reach over the past
decade. In 1998 rap acts sold more than 81 million albums, the best
year in the history of the music. But Hill has given it a giant
push into the mainstream, breaking beyond hip-hop's core audience
to attract older music fans and women, who made up a majority of
the audience at the Fox Theatre show. Says rap-soul star D'Angelo,
who duets with Hill on ``Nothing Even Matters'': ``She did a lot
for black women and black folks in general. A lot of people have
been scared to do the stuff she's doing, because they felt record
companies didn't believe it would sell. But she's been an exception
to that. Her music is very marketable and is still dope.''
</P>
<P>
   For a sound born on the streets of the South Bronx, however,
acceptance by the popular establishment is a controversial
proposition. ``I think it's always a mixed blessing,'' says Hinds.
``The success of hip-hop as a market is attributable to the
maturing of the genre. It has the capacity to cross color lines.
But it will always retain the fringe element. As I said, it's a
celebration of black masculinity. America will never be comfortable
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Hill, hip-hop is now a celebration of female dignity
as well, a remarkably gratifying turn of events given the misogyny
and abuse glorified by the rap rank and file. Prominent female
rappers like L'il Kim and Foxy Brown do little to improve the
image, wielding sex and blatant materialism as their stock in
trade. For Hill, however, dignity isn't gender-specific, but rather
humanity's fundamental tool of empowerment. She counsels women
about self-respect (``When you give it up so easy, you ain't even
fooling him . . . showing off your ass 'cause you're thinking it's
a trend / Don't be a hardrock when you're really a gem'') and men
about responsibility (``The sneaky silent men the punk domestic
violence men / The quick to shoot the semen stop acting like boys
and be men'') on the hit single ``Doo Wop (That Thing).'' ``How you
gon' win,'' Hill asks over and over again, ``when you ain't right
within?''
</P>
<P>
   It's the striving toward what's right that fuels Hill's fire.
Social justice and emotional truth, the black experience and
religious faith, earthly pleasures and modern dilemmas, merge into
an extraordinary narrative, unmistakably credible and undeniably
potent. The stories are told in word and song, with spoken
incantation and transcendent melody weaving in and among one
another much as they do at a Sunday worship. Like Stevie Wonder,
Aretha Franklin, Al Green, and Bob Marley before her, Lauryn Hill
grounds the story of her life in a much older story, finding
meaning in a spiritual and musical legacy that can be summed up in
one word: soul. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
