<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-HIPHOP-CLONES-B     03-22 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HIPHOP-CLONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD INDUSTRY IS SEARCHING FOR CLONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are there any more Lauryn Hills out there? You can be sure that
record industry scouts are trying hard to find them, ever since
Hill's eye-popping five Grammy wins last month. It's symptomatic of
the industry to chase after anyone who might duplicate such a
windfall success.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: When Madonna hit it big, the industry had a feeding
frenzy for Madonna clones. When skinny-tied ``power pop'' bands
were the rage in the '80s, record labels went crazy signing their
own versions. And when Alanis Morissette made ``angry young
female'' rock popular in the '90s, more angry women turned up.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill, by any standard, is a tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many Lauryn Hills,'' says Tommy Mottola, chairman
of Sony Records, Hill's label. ``But when it comes along and the
talent is there, people will search it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Hill is so special because she's the example of hip-hop
evolving to the next step,'' adds Mottola. ``She's taken it from
rap music, which is a street genre, to a whole other form, yet
she's kept her respect and credibility. In some ways, Mary J. Blige
was the prototype for Lauryn's success _ a woman who was an urban
act and then crossed over. But Lauryn took it to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   However, don't exaggerate all those Grammy wins, says Roy Lott,
president of Capitol Records. ``I always think people make too much
of these things,'' he says. ``This Grammy success had to do with
Lauryn Hill, rather than with musical movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lauryn's success reminds everybody of the approach
I've always believe in _ that there is room for all musical
directions,'' says Lott. ``If you oversimplify it as one style,
then you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a legitimacy to the accusation that record labels are
going to be looking for cookie cutter types in the future,'' Lott
adds. ``I'm sure there are a lot of attorneys pitching the next
Lauryn Hill, the same way they did with Alanis clones. But Lauryn's
success had a lot to do with her, period. She's a great artist.
She's a great rapper and a great singer. She writes meaningful
lyrics and is darned good-looking, too. And she already had a base
by working with the Fugees and on Aretha Franklin's single
(``Rose'') last year. There were a lot of stars lined up for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do hope is that her success will cause more young women
aged 14 and 15 to be inspired by music and to become future Lauryn
Hills,'' says Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was her time at the Grammys, just as it was Bonnie Raitt's
time a few years ago,'' says David Leach, a general manager of the
new Universal Music Group (formerly PolyGram), which includes the
Def Jam rap catalog. ``Everybody is going to try to copycat her a
little bit. We all want to be ahead of the curve and people will
think this is the way to do it, but there's only one Lauryn Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lauryn is a brilliant artist,'' says singer and fellow Grammy
winner Lenny Kravitz. ``She has such a strong female energy and any
time that can get out there as an influence, it can only help other
women, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely other artists like TLC, who have blended
pop and hip-hop,'' says John Sykes, president of cable channel VH1.
``But Lauryn has done it the best and has brought hip-hop to the
next generation. What she has done is a milestone, much like what
Stevie Wonder did in the '70s with `Songs in the Key of Life.' Our
viewers grew up on Motown and R&AMP;B, so many of them love her. She's
bringing it all into the next generation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
