<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEW IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Death: A Love Story'' Despite some uncomfortable lapses
into New Age-speak and greeting-card imagery, Michelle Le Brun's
documentary is a noble, heartfelt examination of her husband, Mel
Howard, who was chairman of Boston University's film school, and of
the last months of his life as he battled cancer (Unrated) (Renee
Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``Forces of Nature'' There's not much fizz in this
neo-screwball comedy, but Ben Affleck (as the buttoned-down type on
the way to his wedding) and Sandra Bullock (not quite free enough
as the free spirit who upends him) are nice to have around. While
not entirely successful, the film at least avoids predictability.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (FL) &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The Harmonists'' Handsomely crafted German showbiz
biopic. A snappy musical group makes it big in between-the-wars
Berlin, then finds itself in trouble in the Hitler years because
three of its six members are Jewish. Sleek period finish is a big
plus. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``Pizzicata'' A sensitive debut feature from
documentary-maker Edouardo Winspeare. It's admirably textured and
acted, even if its subject matter seems overfamiliar: Two men (one
a downed US fighter pilot) clash over a woman in a feudal rural
Italian landscape at the tail end of World War II. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ! &LR;  ``Ravenous'' A clumsy attempt to reinvent the story of the
Donner Pass cannibalism in terms of 19th-century American
land-grabbing and Manifest Destiny. It traps some good actors _ Guy
Pearce, Robert Carlyle, Jeffrey Jones _ in a silly gorefest that
reminds us how much better Hannibal Lecter did this sort of thing.
(R)
</P>
<P>
   (FR)  &UR; !!! &LR;  ``True Crime'' Clint Eastwood is slyly funny as a
broken-down newspaper reporter juggling reprobate ways and
professional savvy as he goes to bat for a death-row inmate he's
convinced is innocent. Because there's more emphasis on
characterization and atmosphere than on formulas, and because this
film is so far above the genre average, you forgive the climactic
car chase. (R)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
