<HEADER>
A9736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-22 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRADE-OFF BETWEEN SECURITY AND RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am retired at 66 with the following investments: $48,000 in
BankBoston stock, $14,250 in Citicorp stock, $10,000 in Series E
Savings Bonds, $79,400 in bank IRAs, $8,400 in bank savings
accounts, $23,000 in bank CDs, $36,300 in AARP GNMA and U.S.
Treasury fund, $15,000 in AARP High-Quality Short-Term Bond fund,
and $5,000 in AARP U.S. Stock Index fund. My wife, who is 52 and
will continue working until she is 60, has a $240,000 401(k)
account to which she adds $400 a month. I get Social Security of
$1,207 a month. My wife thinks my investing is too conservative. We
are looking for security, but perhaps higher returns. Suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Los Angeles &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One of you is right, but you left out the most critical piece
of information: how your wife has invested her 401(k) account,
which represents a whisker more than half the combined portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Since you write that she thinks you are investing too
conservatively, let's consider first how the total portfolio will
look if her 401(k) account is dominated by stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
   If all of her investments are in stocks or stock funds, that
puts the combined portfolio at 64.1 percent equities _ a
traditional if slightly conservative position for a fellow your
age.
</P>
<P>
   If her 401(k) portfolio is invested in higher-risk stocks,
eliminate the phrase ``if slightly conservative'' in the previous
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But if her 401(k) is about evenly divided between stocks and
bonds, the overall portfolio is very very conservative and your
wife is right _ you want more stocks, and probably a lot more
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At the very minimum, I'd suggest you hold at least 40 percent
stocks, and 70 percent at the maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing about the 401(k) investments, I have no idea what
your portfolio returns may be. But there certainly are ways to
achieve a slightly better yield on the remainder of the portfolio
without dramatically increasing risk.
</P>
<P>
   One series of moves would be to put the money now in AARP
High-Quality Short-Term Bond fund, yielding 5.6 percent, into AARP
GNMA and U.S. Treasury fund, where the yield is 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A similar move might involve the $8,400 earning 4.7 percent in a
savings account _ unless you consider that a highly liquid cash
pool to deal with emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   What are the prospects for growth within the non-401(k)
portfolio during the next eight years until your wife retires?
</P>
<P>
   If we projected 5 percent growth for the portfolio you have
detailed, it would grow to $353,628 over eight years with no
additional contributions.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mysterious 401(k), with your wife's $400 monthly
contributions after eight years the accumulation would amount to
$431,329, $497,138, or $571,852, provided total returns were 6
percent, 8 percent, or 10 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But if I were you I wouldn't take that final figure very
seriously. Although 10 percent is a reasonable assumption for
long-term stock fund growth, it's probably high for an eight-year
accumulation, and especially for the accumulation that's likely to
be delivered by our current worn-out stock market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The investment mixes you discuss in your column seldom
include real estate. Why is that? While we don't want the
responsibilities of direct ownership of real estate, we think it's
a good thing to include in our long-term investment portfolio, and
we have liked the income stream provided by our existing REIT
investment. The overall REIT market has fared poorly during the
last year or so, and we're thinking now may be a good time to make
additional investments in this sector. We're in our mid-50s, expect
to retire in two or three years, and are thinking about raising our
allocation to real estate from 5 percent to 10 percent by investing
in the Vanguard REIT Index fund. We would appreciate your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   D.S., Eugene, Ore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I rarely discuss REIT funds because I consider them
higher-risk investments that are inappropriate for many investors.
If your retirement portfolio is sufficiently fat that you can
afford the substantial risks inherent in buying REIT funds, more
power to you. It certainly does seem as if they may have hit a low,
and a recovery could bring very generous returns.
</P>
<P>
   In point of fact, I have a position in one of the riskier REIT
funds _ CGM Realty _ which has delivered a spine-jolting 20.65
percent loss in the past 52 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I hold the shares in an IRA, so I remained calm
when the fund's year-end distributions exceeded 15 percent _ that
in a year during which the fund lost 21.15 percent. So let's begin
with that: Unless you can live with some unpleasant tax surprises,
don't hold a REIT mutual fund in a taxable account.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I'm hanging in there with CGM Realty. But despite the
fact that the chart has flattened out since its September-October
lows, I'm not doubling up as you propose to do.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have a higher appetite for risk than I do, or maybe
you're counting on the lower-risk profile provided by the Vanguard
Specialized Real Estate Index fund when compared with CGM Realty.
</P>
<P>
   The recent numbers for the Vanguard fund are less gory than
those of CGM, but they're still unpleasant. Over 52 weeks, it shows
a 17.13 percent loss (compared with a 20.65 percent loss for CGM
Realty and a 17.71 percent loss for the Wilshire REIT Index).
</P>
<P>
   Year-to-date, it shows a 3.97 percent loss, which compares with
a 3.62 percent loss for CGM Realty and a 5.75 percent loss for the
REIT Index. Vanguard's REIT Index fund yields 7.61 percent, nicely
leading the 6.71 percent of CGM Realty. You can trace most of that
variance to the expense ratios _ 0.24 percent for Vanguard compared
with 1.00 for CGM Realty. (Both of these are 1997 figures, the
latest provided in the Morningstar Mutual Funds reports.)
</P>
<P>
   For my money, which is staying with CGM, the abilities of fund
manager G. Kenneth Heebner are worth the extra 76 basis points on
the expense ratio. (I should also note that a vice president of CGM
is an old and valued friend of mine, and I am following his advice
_ wince and hang in there.)
</P>
<P>
   So in summary, I have nothing at all against REIT funds _
provided 1) it's in a tax-deferred account; 2) you keep the holding
to a small percentage of your overall portfolio; and 3) you can
both afford the risk financially and deal with the emotional
affects of that risk when things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Another way of thinking of it is this: The REIT sector has
already suffered what I think is ahead for the large-cap stocks as
a group, a fairly long and choppy slide until prices get back in
line with earnings and dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker will answer selected investors' questions in the
Sunday Mutual funds and Monday Money sections. Send letters,
including your name, address and telephone number, to: Kenneth
Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
