<HEADER>
A9739 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     03-22 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, March 23:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CELL-BEHAVIOR (Undated) _ Hoping to understand on a very
basic level how individuals _ whether cells in a body, plants and
animals in an ecosystem, or members of a society _ congregate into
complex wholes that take on autonomous existences of their own,
scientists based at the Santa Fe Institute in New Mexico are
studying how the simplest imaginable cells can interact to generate
surprisingly complex, coordinated behavior. By George Johnson. With
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRIEF-RESOLUTION (Undated) _ Researchers are now exploring
the concept they call ambiguous loss, in which a ``lost'' person is
still physically present but emotionally absent or a lost person is
physically absent but still emotionally present. Research, outlined
in new book, contends that in such circumstances it is often very
difficult for people to resolve their grief and get on with their
lives. By Jane E. Brody. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SOLID-CARBON-DIOXIDE (Undated) _ Carbon dioxide, a
ubiquitous chemical exhaled by all animals and incorporated into
plants as their main building block, has assumed a new and
astonishing form: a solid that resembles quartz, is nearly as hard
as diamond, and transforms light in intriguing (and potentially
very useful) ways. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DNA-SEQUENCE (Undated) _ Last week the public consortium
working to sequence the human genome said it would complete a
``first draft'' of the human DNA sequence next spring, well ahead
of the target date announced by its commercial rival the Celera
Corporation. The outcome of this battle between rivals seems to lie
to some extent in the hands of an esoteric computer program named
phred. By Nicholas Wade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COLD-FUSION (Undated) _ Cold fusion is alive today and doing
well in the scientific underground. Researchers around the globe
quietly claim success at getting tantalizing results, if not
blistering heats ready to topple the status quo. This hum of
low-level work confounds skeptics and delights believers. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COOLIDGE-DOCUMENATRY (Undated) _ Ancient footage of African
expeditions, with big guns and long lines of porters, by early
conservationists like Harold Jefferson Coolidge represent a sort of
gorilla skeleton in the closet of the global conservation movement.
But eventually Coolidge became a major force behind preserving the
kind of rare species he had once shot. Now, his expedition films
are being crafted into a documentary. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH &AMP; FITNESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-POISON-ANTIDOTE (Undated) _ Experts say the complicated and
sometimes tricky treatment of poisonings with ethylene glycol
(antifreeze) and perhaps other toxic alcohols could be radically
changed with the recent introduction of a new antidote drug that
appears to be highly effective, but prohibitively expensive for
some hospitals. By Warren E. Leary. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CARTOON-HEALTH (Undated) _ Parental concerns about the
messages small children receive in G-rated animated feature films
have resulted in a review showing that two-thirds of such movies
produced over the last 60 years include the use of tobacco and
alcohol by villains and heroes alike. By Nancy Beth Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   DUAL-DOCTOR-MARRIAGES (Undated) _ As the ranks of women doctors
grow, so do doctor-doctor marriages. Compared with other
physicians, doctors in dual-doctor marriages reported greater
satisfaction in discussing and sharing work interests with their
spouses, more involvement in child rearing by both partners and a
higher family income. By SANDEEP JAUHAR, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   ZERO-GRAVITY-EXERCISES (Undated) _ As a January 2000 launching
date for the first resident mission to the new International Space
Station approaches, NASA now is making its most serious effort ever
to break the muscle barrier to extended stays in zero gravity. By
John O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EATING-HABITS (Undated) _ Two new studies lend evidence to
the view that eating and other health habits of children just
starting elementary school play a major role in the problems they
may suffer in later life, including heart disease, high blood
pressure and possibly diabetes. By Eric Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Your science questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Items dealing with evolution
bioluminescence underseas, genetically engineered silkworms and
origins of the moon. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ A generation ago, researchers
at the University of Minnesota published findings that, if heeded
then, would have extended millions of American lives during the
last 30 years and millions more in the years to come. The
researchers examined the relationship between diet and heart
disease rates and found that people who lived along the
Mediterranean Sea suffered only a tiny fraction of the heart
attacks and coronary deaths experienced by Americans and people in
other Western industrialized countries. In the years since, other
studies have fleshed out those findings. The latest, in
Circulation, is a four-year follow-up of more than 400 men and
women in France. By Jane Brody. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Short news items, including: a study
by researchers who surveyed a decade's syphilis reports in North
Carolina counties and found that syphilis appeared more than twice
as often in North Carolina rural counties that bordered I-95 as it
did in rural counties that did not border the highway. With map.
</P>
<P>
   A new study finds that family doctors with the most impressive
credentials seem to be the most likely to be sued.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, therapists and police officers who give hearsay
testimony in court about young children's statements may not be
reliable witnesses, according to a new study.
</P>
