r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABIES-2000-HNS &LR;      03-22 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABIES-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLES PLAN FOR THE FIRST BABY OF 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The global race for the first baby in 2000 is
under way. Would-be contestants have conceived a winning strategy _
now they just have to conceive a baby.
</P>
<P>
   From now until April 10 is the optimal fertilization window for
couples hoping to create the first offspring of 2000, specialists
say.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy to conceive a millennium baby is a tad ironic. While
next year is symbolically the beginning of the new millennium, it
does not technically begin until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the first babies of 2000 can count on much more than
their photos in the newspaper: a bonanza of prizes and a place in
history await them.
</P>
<P>
   For people who want to simultaneously usher in a new life at the
dawn of next year, the San Francisco-based BabyCenter on-line store
is offering a $49.99 Millennium Conception Kit. Buyers receive a
best-selling fertility guide, an ovulation-predictor kit, a
pregnancy test, calcium supplements, a calendar, a pair of
hand-dipped red taper candles and a bottle of Terra Nova's Cloud
Nine massage oil _ all gift-wrapped in red tissue paper.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Seltzer, a software-company recruiter from Foster City,
Calif., has her fingers crossed that the kit will work for her and
her husband Eric.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not like these couples who are timing artificial
inseminations and planning to fly around the globe so they can have
the millennium's first birth,'' she said. ``Our primary goal is to
start our family _ having the year's first baby would make
something already special just a bit extra special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the marketing frenzy seems a bit much to me _ although
when I heard about a Dallas radio station offering the millennium
baby a full college scholarship I did think to myself, `Wouldn't
that be great?'''
</P>
<P>
   Frenzy may be an understatement: A San Diego couple has
announced plans not only to conceive a baby on April Fools' Day,
but also to fly to Kiribati _ an island nation in the Western
Pacific _ for a Caesarean section at 12:00:01 a.m. Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Duane and Susan Dimock are busy picking names: If it's a girl,
Millie; if a boy, Otto _ for aught, as in zero.
</P>
<P>
   A New Zealand radio station has booked 100 Auckland hotel rooms
on April 9 for couples to ``hit the sheets'' in pursuit of a
millennium baby. To ensure the proper ambience, the station is
furnishing aphrodisiacs such as oysters and champagne.
</P>
<P>
   China has been beset by rumors that the first babies of 2000
will qualify for special cash prizes and international passports _
the Beijing Youth Daily reported on one woman who had an abortion
so she could time her next pregnancy closer to the target date.
</P>
<P>
   British television network ITV plans to follow its ``Birth Race
2000'' kickoff ``Nookie Night'' _ an evening featuring shows like
the wildlife documentary ``Animal Passions'' _ with documentaries
tracking hopeful couples throughout gestation and into the delivery
room via live coverage Dec. 31. With similar hopes of inspiring
millennial conceptions, the Britain's Classic FM intends to flood
the airwaves April 11 with passionate pieces by composers such as
Rachmaninov and Ravel.
</P>
<P>
   Already, ``Official Millennium Baby'' is a trademark, right
alongside ``The Official Burger of the New Millennium'' and ``The
Official Air Freshener of the New Millennium.'' The Canadian
company that owns the baby trademark is soliciting sponsors to
donate $2 million in prizes _ from diapers to a minivan _ for the
``jackpot baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Intercourse affords only about a 25 percent chance of getting
pregnant, and not all those pregnancies will survive to term. Even
though the human gestation period averages 38 weeks, there are wide
variations. Only 5 percent of mothers give birth on their due date.
</P>
<P>
   The hype and technological tinkering troubles religious and
medical ethicists. They fear that the priceless miracle of creation
is being trivialized into a cheap publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's making a mockery of what a child is about,'' a papal
spokesman said. ``Having a child to get on TV must be the height of
absurdity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
