<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     03-22 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MUCH SOUND AND FURY, SAY READERS _ AND FOR WHAT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been working our way through the American Society of
Newspaper Editors' three-year-long research project to study the
issue of credibility, specifically as it relates to newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The ASNE reported six ``major findings,'' and today we deal with
No. 4:
</P>
<P>
   ``The public believes that newspapers chase and over-cover
sensational stories because they're exciting and they sell papers.
They don't believe these stories deserve the attention and play
they get. Americans say they're tired of having sensational stories
crammed down their throats. The public believes that underlying
newspaper excesses is a commercial motive, to sell more papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's deal with some facts first. A relatively small percentage
of Star-Telegram copies are sold from newspaper racks and other
locations. Most of our circulation is by subscription delivered to
your home, and what is on the front page makes no difference in
those sales.
</P>
<P>
   That said, obviously editors want the front page to be
interesting, and the folk who work in circulation tell us that
their single-copy sales are better some days than others. They
attribute that to what is above the fold on the front.
</P>
<P>
   Perception deeply held might as well be reality, and the authors
of the ASNE study say that public beliefs ``are clear indictments
of press credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not unreasonable perceptions ...,'' the report said,
``but they are pervasive accusations that newspapers are not using
journalistic judgment exclusively to build the news report, but
allowing personal or corporate objectives to shape or flavor it.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been a series of sensational stories during the past
few years, and the study cited several of them: the O.J. Simpson
murder trial, the allegations swirling around President Clinton
(including those by Paula Jones), the Monica Lewinsky story, the
death of Princess Diana, the death of JonBenet Ramsey, and the
Olympic bombing in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspaper editors' judgments about if and how and where to
play those stories on the pages of the newspaper must be carefully
made, then, with full realization that these kinds of stories will
likely already have had heavy television coverage,'' the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   There's no science about news selection on front pages.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, editors are looking for the most significant news of the
day, something interesting for the readers, something with great
impact on daily living and, depending on the top newsroom
management, perhaps a goofy change-of-pace story to lighten up the
gloom and doom often associated with the news report.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, whatever else is going on in the world on a given day
influences the selection. There have been comments attributed to
various people that all boil down to the admonition not to mess up
on a light news day. Stories that might not otherwise make it to
the front will do so when there's not much else happening.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite also is true: Significant stories that might
otherwise be played on a section front will be pushed inside and
shortened if there is major news taking place.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't matter what newspapers actually are doing if you
as readers believe them to be doing something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another, perhaps more insidious, contributor to these beliefs
is the public's perception that newspapers overplay otherwise
normal news stories,'' the authors said.
</P>
<P>
   They said that 48 percent of U.S. adults say they find
misleading headlines in their paper more than once a week and that
78 percent think that ``journalists enjoy reporting on the personal
failings of politicians and public figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, many of you calling my office think we don't report enough
on the personal failings of public figures _ one especially. But
others who call think that we overdo it. I suppose since both sides
call consistently, we're maybe somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The report by Urban and Associates used the Clinton sex scandal
as an example:
</P>
<P>
   ``In April and May of 1998 _ long before the Starr report _
almost every adult (96 percent) was aware of the Clinton/Lewinsky
story, and of that group: 82 percent believed the news reports
contained inaccuracies or omissions; 85 percent said TV had too
much coverage (66 percent said newspapers had too much); and 67
percent said they were not at all interested in the story.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that newspapers should be driven only by what
the public says it does or does not want to know. There will always
be instances when the proper thing to do is also the unpopular
thing to do, and newspapers must have the courage to print (or
perhaps not print) those stories.
</P>
<P>
   But the ASNE report also suggests that perhaps newspapers ask
for trouble without needing to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that 74 percent of adults say they want local
news every day; 54 percent say newspapers are their primary source
of local news (the only content area in which newspapers
consistently are given the edge over television or other media);
television is overwhelmingly seen as the dominant source of
national and world news; and television is almost universally
accepted as the news medium that gets the news first.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this interest and the clear advantage of newspapers
in local news, ``editors need to seriously examine the amount of
energy and space spent on the sensational stories that the public
doesn't want, resources that could, perhaps, be better redirected
toward giving them what they do want,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a time when daily newspapers are still hanging on to their
local news franchise _ but only barely _ the risks inherent in
chasing and over-covering sensational wire stories just don't seem
worth it,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I can also show you research that contradicts that,
and that is one of the things that makes this challenging. We must
be all things to all people, and we are expected to be good at all
of them.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is reader advocate for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. His e-mail address is harral(at)star-telegram.com.
You may telephone him at (817) 390-7692 or write him at P.O. Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1556EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
