<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-22 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, 10,000 IS NOT SIGNIFICANT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the Dow Jones industrial average is so near closing
above 10,000, it's time for a reality check.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a great milestone and something to be celebrated. But
last week's struggle to close above 10,000 shows why there are
reasons to beware of the hot stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me is the concentration of securities,'' said
money manager George Briggs, president of Briggs Management and
Research in Houston, who's been in the business for more than 20
years. ``It's a difficult market in which to invest money because
those selected ones that people are invested in are so high-priced
and they carry a lot of risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the market's July 1998 peak, just before last summer's
correction, the benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index of
large stocks has risen 9 percent, according to the Outlook, an
investment newsletter published by Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp.
</P>
<P>
   However, things look different if you didn't invest in that
select group _ which is the investment benchmark for index funds,
which buy those S&AMP;P stocks to emulate the performance of these 500
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P MidCap 400, which is made up of smaller players, is down
3 percent, and the S&AMP;P SmallCap 600 is off 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have matched or beaten the most widely followed market
averages are likely to be invested in stocks that are just plain
expensive. If you overpay for something, there's far greater danger
you will fall from the sky later on.
</P>
<P>
   The price investors are paying for the assets and earning power
of the companies in the Dow average is twice as expensive as it was
just 3 1/2 years ago, when the Dow crossed 5,000 for the first
time, in the fall of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Undeterred by extreme price/earnings ratios, investors are
doing what has been working best _ staying with the winners, the
large-caps,'' said S&AMP;P analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreigners are flocking to the big-name issues they identify
with the U.S. economic boom. Money managers, fearful of being left
behind, are piling into stocks that are the most liquid and the
most influential in the performance benchmarks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TECH STOCKS STOKE THE FEVER &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: Dell Computer Corp., the Nasdaq-listed Round
Rock-based company, trounced Wal-Mart Stores, the top performer in
the Dow, during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, such as Dell, have been at the forefront of
the investment fever.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors have gotten so enamored of Internet stocks that
they don't appear to show any interest in whether an Internet
company has made money or not.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers of the shares of energy companies, basic industries,
heavy goods firms are likely to feel left out of the loop. Steel,
and oil and gas have suffered from low worldwide prices.
</P>
<P>
   Other basic industries just don't offer the potential growth of
the computer and software sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a rather large segment there where money isn't
invested,'' Briggs said. ``People think they're not growing fast
enough, but I just think it makes the market difficult to invest
money in.''
</P>
<P>
   When so many stocks aren't involved in the rally, there's not
enough strength to propel the market further ahead, said Mark
Arbeter, S&AMP;P technical analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``What eventually happens is that it causes the market to pull
back,'' Briggs said. ``Either the laggards have to catch up or the
leaders have to pull back, and frequently they've been pulling
back.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third time last week, the Dow failed to lock in at the
10,000 level at the close. Perhaps it's because some investors fear
that once it closes at that level or above, the market will hit a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very difficult to maintain a level above
10,000 for a while,'' said David Lapin, president of Lapin &AMP;
Wigginton Asset Management, a Houston money management firm.
``You'll see waves of selling each time advances are attempted at
that level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LOOSEN YOUR TIE AND REST A BIT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's time to take a breather.
</P>
<P>
   Lapin had 100 percent of his clients' money invested last year
in stocks. He's reduced that to 70 percent stocks and 30 percent
fixed-income investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher we go, the more you need to pull off the table,''
he said. ``We're going to reduce our equity exposure 1 percent for
each 100-point advance in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider pulling back a bit on your buying so that the Dow's
surge doesn't take over your investment common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax considerations permitting, lighten up a bit on stocks if
the market advance has pushed that portion of your portfolio above
the 55 percent we are recommending,'' said S&AMP;P analysts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
