<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Washington) _ As U.S. special envoy Richard
Holbrooke makes another appeal to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, NATO is preparing for ``long and protracted'' aerial
bombardment. The Clinton administration warns Milosevic that ``this
is the 11th hour'' for allied action. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate considers a
House-passed resolution on the use of U.S. forces to police the
stalemated cease-fire deal in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., insists on
congressional authorization for Pentagon operations in Yugoslavia.
By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA (Washington) _ President Clinton and the U.S.-led
International Monetary Fund seek to bolster embattled Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov with pledges of fresh aid for his
nation's failing economy during his visit to Washington beginning
Tuesday. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERCROOKS (Washington) _ The Internet has become a new vehicle
for stock scams, a Senate panel is told. Sen. Susan Collins,
R-Maine, who heads the panel, says she is ``concerned that the
Internet appears to provide `cybercrooks' with ... avenues for
committing financial fraud.'' By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-SCHOOLS (Washington) _ In a pair of cases with
significance for parents, students and communities across the
nation, the Supreme Court rejects a challenge to a teen curfew law
in Virginia but refuses to let a school district in Indiana require
drug tests before suspended students are readmitted to classes. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OPEC-MEETING (Vienna) _ Crude oil prices fall in New York as
traders await Tuesday's meeting of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries in Vienna. The ministers are expected to ratify
a plan to reduce supplies and end a worldwide glut. By DAVID
IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ Now that the Dow Jones industrial
average is so near 10,000, it's time for a reality check. Yes, it's
a great milestone and something to be celebrated. But last week's
struggle to close above 10,000 shows why there are reasons to
beware of the hot stocks. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Here's the latest scenario on the
Clintons' future: When Hillary declares she'll run for the Senate
in New York, Bill will resign to move to Manhattan with her, ending
gossip about a separation and letting Vice President Al Gore run in
2000 as a sitting president. Gore will then issue a blanket pardon
for Clinton, sparing him any future indictment. There are holes in
this, but who knows? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ With six victories in their past seven
games, the Houston Rockets enter the second half of this
abbreviated NBA season on a high note as they play host to the
Sacramento Kings tonight. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKC-NCAAFOUR (Undated) _ On the one hand, you have three
newcomers whose most recent Final Four appearance was 20 years ago.
Then there is Duke, which seemingly held a reserved seat at this
elite event for the first half of the `90s but hasn't been back in
five seasons. A preview of what to expect in this weekend's Final
Four matchups between Duke-Michigan State and Ohio State-UConn. By
BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
