 No. 290 2  Mon ., March  22 : 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (NYLite items can be published if desired; &LR;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Late one afternoon on Madison Avenue, I fell into step behind
two young people apparently heading home, as was I, from a day at
the office. ``I'm assigned to the boss's son,'' one said earnestly
to the other. ``He's a great business getter but not a very good
accountant. The trouble is I'd like to learn how to do things right
before I learn how to be a crook.'' I shuddered and crossed the
street.
</P>
<P>
   _ HARRISON J. GOLDIN
</P>
<P>
   Abbie Snyder was walking into the room at the Whitney Museum of
American Art where the ``Circus Women'' by Elie Nadelman are kept,
pieces that at first glance look like ancient artifacts. She
overheard the following exchange between another visitor and a
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Visitor: ``Where were these found?''
</P>
<P>
   Guard: ``Where were these found? In storage.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 p.m. on a school night and Elsa Adler heard the sounds
of activity on the pool table in the basement. She walked down to
reprimand her 16-year-old son, Michael, who should have been
studying, and heard her husband telling her son that he was
``looking for a color printer, copier and fax.'' Mrs. Adler,
increasingly angry as she descended each step, called out, ``And
I'm looking for a boy who is going to get A's on his report card.''
At this, Michael looked up and retorted, ``Then I suggest you look
into adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   An obviously frustrated mother and her daughter, who appeared to
be in her late 20s, were having lunch when Robert B. Peltz
overheard this conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Mother: ``You've been living together for almost a year. When
are you getting married?''
</P>
<P>
   Daughter: ``We're still testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother: ``What are you testing, the mattress?''
</P>
<P>
   My daughter, Alden, collected for charity every week for a year
and each week when her tin was full, she proudly carried it to the
man in the wheelchair we passed on our way to her nursery school.
On occasion we brought him breakfast, and for several months he and
my daughter exchanged niceties.
</P>
<P>
   When we passed him on the day of her nursery school graduation,
he asked her why she looked so excited. She told him it was her
graduation day, and he said, ``Come here, I have something for
you.'' He reached into his pocket and gave her $2. She accepted
with the same grace that he did from her in the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ KAMMI REISS
</P>
<P>
   Carl Coraggio was amused by the sign he saw displayed by a
street vendor on Times Square. ``Webstir's Dictinary,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's creation of Fortress City Hall brings
to mind an incident in 1955 when I was in my first post-Army job,
handling public relations for Pace College diagonally across from
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, a call for help came from the mayor's office. Mayor
Robert Wagner and his wife were to be hosts to the shah of Iran and
Queen Soraya at City Hall at noon. But, the caller said, he had
just discovered that ``someone forgot to send out invitations to
the prelunch reception.'' Could I bring a couple of dozen
appropriately dressed men and women to greet the city's guests?
</P>
<P>
   I raced into the halls and rounded up a group of students who
were dressed for the office jobs they went to after classes.
</P>
<P>
   Just before noon, our team breezed into City Hall, casually
informed a guard what we were about and just as casually were
directed to the room where the reception would take place.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the principals showed up, we had each put away about
a pound of quite nice hors d'oeuvres. We then went through the
receiving line _ ``Hello shah, hello queen, hiya Mr. and Mrs.
Mayor'' or something like that. Everyone seemed satisfied and we
left the exalteds to resume our humdrum lives across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Was the mayor aware of what had happened? Probably not. But it
would never happen today.
</P>
<P>
   _ WALTER GRAY
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year-old son of a playwright friend of ours just got into
the Stuyvesant High School class of 2003, one of about 700 accepted
from among approximately 20,000 applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he received the good news, he was on a bus with
his father and confessed that he had really prayed a lot, asking
God to get him into Stuyvesant. However, he added, now that he had
been accepted he wished that hadn't prayed quite so much, because
now he'll never really know if he got in on his own merit or if
only because God pulled strings for him.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Collimore was recently in Vermont where, he says, New York's
reputation is ``inexplicably mixed.'' He was given change in one of
the rural general stores for a new $20 bill and realized the
cashier had taken it for a $100 bill. He returned the extra money
and, bearing his city's reputation in mind, said: ``Remember this
moment. I AM FROM NEW YORK.''
</P>
<P>
   I was recently walking near Times Square after a matinee and
dropped an earring, which fell through a sidewalk grating in front
of a hotel. The doorman saw what happened but told us the grate
belonged to Con Edison and the hotel had no access to it.
</P>
<P>
   The earring had been a gift from my husband, so I decided to try
my luck with the utility company. On Monday morning, I telephoned,
finally reached a live person and explained what had happened. On
Tuesday morning, the phone rang: It was the chief of the emergency
crew and he had my earring. So much for impersonal giant
corporations!
</P>
<P>
   _ SARI REIFBERG
</P>
<P>
