<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-REVIEW-TUNA-H     03-22 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-TUNA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TUNA' SAGA IS FUNNY BUT IS SHORT ON BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT HURWITT  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Big, lovable Bertha Bumiller is back, and so is
her sardonic, dog-poisoning sister Pearl Burras.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are such favorite residents of Tuna, Texas, as
gun-merchant Didi Snavely, vindictive Vera Carp, rebellious young
Stanley Bumiller, meek, animal-loving Petey Fisk and the
ever-popular Radio OKKK broadcast team of Thurston Wheelis and
Arles Struvie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red, White and Tuna,'' the newest installment of the Tuna
saga, opened Friday at the Marines' Memorial Theatre, starring
original Tuna creators Joe Sears and Jaston Williams as the entire
population of the third-smallest town in Texas. Billed as the third
part of the Tuna trilogy, it's clearly meant to provide Sears and
Williams with a graceful exit after almost two decades of touring
with its wildly popular predecessors, ``Greater Tuna'' and ``A Tuna
Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's their plan, it may backfire. ``Red, White and Tuna''
isn't as sharply satirical or crisply structured as ``Greater
Tuna'' nor quite so comically iconoclastic as its holiday sequel.
But it is wonderfully funny, pointedly topical and genuinely
heartwarming. It may turn out to be as hard for Williams and Sears
to get out of Tuna as it is for most of their characters.
</P>
<P>
   For those who've yet to tune in to Tuna, Williams, Sears and
director Ed Howard created ``Greater Tuna'' in 1981 as a satire on
the ascendant right-wing politics of the Reagan era. With rapid
changes of costume and personality _ at comic odds with the
deliciously slow amble of the show _ Sears and Williams created 19
sharp cameos. A perversely subversive tale of one teen's rebellion
emerged from beneath the apparently aimless collection of
caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas,'' created in 1989, picked up many of the same
characters plus a few new ones, for a total of 22, some years
later. ``Red, White and Tuna'' looks back in on the same town at a
still later date, revisiting most of the same folks from the first
two shows.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, who (once again) shares writing credits with the actors,
stages it at the same comically slow amble _ with Sears or Williams
wandering behind an upstage flat and emerging from the other side
of it as a different character without seeming to have broken
stride. Linda Fisher's inventive quick-change costumes are as
effective in defining the caricatures as her work was in the first
two shows. Kevin Rupnik's lonesome prairie Texas landscape recalls
his set for the first ``Tuna.''
</P>
<P>
   A rambling, comic newscast by Sears' garrulous Thurston and
Williams' laconic Arles sets the scene. It's the Fourth of July,
which in Tuna means both a low- rent fireworks display and the
annual high school reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the news is the heated battle for Reunion Queen between
the town's reigning matrons _ Sears' ever-wonderful Pearl Burras, a
mountain of tough tenderness, and Williams' vividly mean-spirited
Vera Carp.
</P>
<P>
   Carp is also engaged in a Smut Smashers campaign to expurgate
suggestive lyrics from church hymns, as well as trying to shut down
the latest theatrical production by the misfit fey thespian, Sears'
flamboyant Joe Bob Lipsey (whom she skewers as a ``yard sale
Liberace''). Interwoven with the reunion plot line is another
involving the pending, on-again, off-again marriage of Arles and
Sears' Bertha, matriarch of the Bumiller clan.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed in Tuna. Klan spokesman Elmer Watkins (Sears)
appears briefly as leader of the new Independent Nation of Free
White Texas, setting up a running gag about militiamen running
afoul of a no-nonsense rancher woman. Bertha's kids have grown up.
Whiny, ever-hungry teen Charlene (Williams) is now married,
pregnant, still ravenous and dreaming of moving to Bakersfield (her
``I hear it's like paradise'' brings down the house).
</P>
<P>
   Teen rebel Stanley (Williams) has moved to Santa Fe and become a
successful taxidermy artist with his spray-painted roadkill, a
device that will recur in his latest act of vengeance against the
town. Williams' hilarious gravel-voiced Didi Snavely, of Didi's
Used Weapons, is still chain-smoking and waiting _ just barely _
for her possibly UFO-abducted milquetoast husband R.R. (Sears) to
return. Her habit of taking a long drag in the middle of a song,
and picking up the lyrics after an interminable inhale, is
brilliantly funny.
</P>
<P>
   The man-hungry Tastee Kreme waitresses, Helen Bedd (Williams)
and Inita Goodwin (Sears), are back as well, demonstrating what
happens when you serve potato salad on a hot day (``110, but it's a
dry heat'').
</P>
<P>
   Other characters from the previous shows put in appearances as
well, more for the sake of another quick change than for what they
add to the story. More significant are two new, bright creations,
Tuna's renegade flower children Star Birdfeather (Sears) and Amber
Windchime (Williams).
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it's a kinder, gentler, though still very funny,
``Tuna.'' Williams, Sears and Howard wrap up their saga on a
positive note, focusing on the emotional depth of their more
attractive characters. The show ends with new possibilities for
Bertha, Arles and Stanley in particular. Even the introduction of
some delightful special effects helps emphasize the theme that life
is pretty much the same everywhere, even in outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end, Sears and Williams break with the past by making
one of their costume changes onstage. It's a magically understated
moment, and one well-devised to bring the Tuna saga to a close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
