<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPING A GLOW  
 MORE COLORS IN NATURE  
 THE MOON AND THE EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deep oceans are filled with creatures that emit light for
use as camouflage, to attract a mate or as a lure for food. But
understanding how such bioluminescence evolved in these organisms
has been practically impossible, because fossils contain no record
of what is essentially a chemical process.
</P>
<P>
   The recent discovery of a bioluminescent octopus, however,
offers a few evolutionary clues. The octopus, discovered by
researchers from the Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution in
Fort Pierce, Fla., has what at first glance appear to be ordinary
suckers on its eight arms. But the suckers have lost their ability
to stick to anything, and instead emit a blue-green glow, making
the octopus look as if it got entangled in a string of Christmas
lights.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who describe the species in a recent issue of
the journal Nature, suggested that the octopus evolved from a
shallow-water, bottom-clinging species as it colonized deeper
water.
</P>
<P>
   The suckers were no longer needed for clinging, but another
function _ signaling to a potential mate _ was still important, and
more difficult in the deeper and dimmer waters. The species first
may have developed a reflective layer in the back of the suckers,
and then, over time, light-emitting cells replaced the sucker
muscles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to use in mating, the octopus' light-emitting
suckers may function in food gathering, attracting tiny crustaceans
the way moths gather around a bug light.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue light from an octopus is one addition to nature's palette.
Here's another: fluorescent green silk from a silkworm.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the color is the work of Japanese
scientists, who have re-engineered a silkworm gene responsible for
producing a fibroin, a protein that is a major component of silk.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who described their work in the current issue
of the journal Genes and Development, altered the fibroin gene by
inserting a jellyfish gene that produces a fluorescent green
protein. To get the altered gene back into silkworms, the
scientists used an insect virus as a carrier, swapping out a gene
in the virus with the modified gene.
</P>
<P>
   Female moths were then infected with the virus, mated with
males, and the resulting larvae _ the silkworms _ contained the
altered genes, producing silk that glows green when exposed to
ultraviolet light.
</P>
<P>
   While fluorescent green silk suits are unlikely to appear on the
racks anytime soon, the technique could be used with other kinds of
insects, and other genes, to custom-produce various proteins useful
in industry. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long debated the moon's beginnings, whether it
was created when a planet-sized object smashed into the earth eons
ago or had an independent origin.
</P>
<P>
   New data from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Lunar Prospector spacecraft support the idea that
the moon is in fact a chip off the old block. Measuring slight
fluctuations in the spacecraft's low lunar orbit (an indication of
gravitational variations), scientists have confirmed that the moon
has a relatively small core, with a radius of 140 to 280 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Such a core makes up 4 percent or less of the moon's total mass.
By contrast, the earth's iron core is about 30 percent of the
planet's mass.
</P>
<P>
   In the collision theory of the moon's formation, the impact
occurred after the earth's core was formed, and only iron-poor
material closer to the surface was ejected into orbit. This
material, coalescing into the moon, would create an object with a
small core.
</P>
<P>
   If, as another theory holds, the moon was formed independently
from the same swirling dust and debris that created the earth, its
core should roughly match the earth in proportion of total mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
