<HEADER>
A9853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BERLIN-BOS &LR;      03-22 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BERLIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRVING BERLIN HAD LUCK AND PLUCK AND A FEEL FOR AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
IRVING BERLIN 
American Troubador 
By Edward Jablonski 
Holt, 406 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Irving Berlin'' is a smooth, lyrical take on a fascinating
subject. It will be enjoyed by anyone curious about the Golden Age
of American popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   The book is not only about the genius of Berlin, one of the
world's best-known and best-loved composers. It's something of a
survey of the glittering landscape of popular culture before TV and
before rock 'n' roll _ before the latter became popular music. The
sun king at the center of what was a hit parade of stage, movie,
and radio musicals that supplied that culture was a very real,
palpable, pragmatic Russian-Jewish refugee. And his own biography _
a near-incredible rags-to-riches story _ is only incidental to the
accounting of what he gave (back) to his adopted country: a heart
and soul that it desperately needed and was searching for without
necessarily knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   His ``White Christmas'' and ``Easter Parade'' celebrated
America's principal Christian holidays; his ``God Bless America,''
a virtual national anthem, sanctified the country itself. ``There's
No Business Like Show Business'' was an anthem to the world where
he made his living.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these are just the tips of the Irving Berlin iceberg. Shrewd
as he was, he couldn't have succeeded by his own design; he gave
luck as well as pluck a plug. As a Russian-born immigrant
13-year-old, he fled his large family's Lower East Side tenement to
survive. He became a ``Bowery bard,'' a busker performing in
saloons for money. He inhaled popular American tastes. He was a
quick study who grew up fast, knew who and what he was and, with
rare exceptions, didn't forget to keep his eye on the sparrow.
Rarely was he diverted from his songwriting skill _ he insisted on
calling himself a ``songwriter,'' not a composer or lyricist,
though he qualified as all those things. He ``unconsciously,'' the
author writes, created art.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Kern said that Berlin had no place in American music _ he
was American music. Kern wrote: ``Both the typical Yankee and a
Berlin tune had humor, originality, pace and popularity; both were
wide awake, and both, sometimes, a little loud _ but what might
unsympathetically be mistaken for brass was really gold.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not universally beloved. His future father-in-law, an
anti-Semite, couldn't bring himself to speak his name. Songwriter
Harry Warren, no admirer, is supposed to have said in 1944, after
an American attack on the German capital, ``They bombed the wrong
Berlin.''
</P>
<P>
   The eminently readable Jablonski, who knew Berlin personally, is
the author of innumerable books on American musical theater,
including biographies of George Gershwin, Alan Jay Lerner, and
Harold Arlen. He has a way with backstage stories and insider's
knowledge. Stephen Foster's music in the public domain was the
music most often played on radio's popular ``Your Hit Parade'' back
when a bitter, far-reaching licensing dispute kept most
contemporary music off the air. An infectious song Berlin wrote for
a Judy Garland solo in the movie musical ``Easter Parade'' was cut
from the movie because ``the song stopped the show.'' When a
jealous friend remarked that ``Annie Get Your Gun'' _ the musical
for which Berlin wrote what many have said was his best score _ was
``old-fashioned,'' Berlin answered, ``Yeah. A good old-fashioned
smash.'' The eminent New York Times critic Brooks Atkinson had a
``tin ear'' for music, Berlin said, adding: ``Aren't we lucky that
the critics only write about the music and don't try to write it
themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, who wrote some 1,500 songs, could play piano in only one
key and never learned to read music or transcribe it. George
Gershwin called him ``America's Franz Schubert'' because of his
prolific inclinations toward both genius and schmaltz. He was an
original who spoke and sang in the American idiom, making him a
fortune. And irreplaceable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
