<P>
   MEDIAONE-Comcast, the fourth-largest cable company, buys
MediaOne Group, the No. 3 cable operator, for $48.7 billion in
stock, to create a cable network with 11 million customers. The
acquisition will create one of the largest broadband networks,
which allow several channels, such as television and Internet
access, to be transmitted on the same cable wire. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   w/MEDIAONE-SIDE _ The consolidation of cable companies makes
them much more formidable competitors to phone companies for
everything from local phone service to Internet access. What battle
lines will be drawn by this merger between Comcast and BellSouth?
``The battle lines for local competition are being drawn as cable
companies step in as alternative providers of phone services and
Internet access,'' said Alan Lyons, an analyst at ABN Amro. ``Cable
companies have decided bigger is better.'' Cable-TV companies are
seeking to expand their service areas so the costs of marketing and
new technology can be spread over bigger customer groups.
(Katz/Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BOTTLE _ In 1899, two Chattanooga, Tenn., attorneys
traveled to Atlanta and paid Coca-Cola Co. $1 for the rights to
bottle and distribute Coca-Cola to most of the U.S., establishing
the company's first bottling operation. On Wednesday, the company
celebrates its 100th year. We'll take the opportunity to look at
how Coca-Cola's bottling operations have grown, and consolidated
through the years, the strategy behind the changes and what lies a
head for the company's U.S. bottling operations. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 52.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-ASA _ Delta says its tender offer for ASA was successful,
giving it 91 percent ownership of the regional affiliate. ASA still
must formally approve the deal at a shareholder meeting next month,
after which it will be a Delta subsidiary. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-OVERSEAS _ Home Depot Inc. named Anders Moberg,
president of Sweden's Ikea Group, to be its group president for
international operations, as the retailer plans further overseas
expansion. Moberg, 49, joins Home Depot after serving 13 years as
president of Ikea. He will begin on Sept. 1, reporting to President
and Chief Executive Arthur Blank. Moberg is credited with expanding
Ikea's business throughout Europe and the Asia-Pacific region,
including a network of retail stores, catalogs and manufacturing
facilities, Home Depot said. This could help Home Depot to expand
internationally. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY PAGE
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH - The cell phone, which turns 15 this year, has
displaced lots of calls that once were made on desk phones. Many
pay phones are unoccupied in busy passageways such as those in
airports. No need to scramble for coins or stand in lines, because
so many people are carrying their own phones. Welcome to the
wireless generation. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Lead art includes magnificent 4-column illustration of numerous
cellular phones surrounding a brilliant-blue planet Earth with the
sun emerging on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   w/PHONE FACTS _ A list of facts about land-line phones and
cellular phones. (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes thumbnail
illustrations of a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS _ A St. Louis company has come up with a software
program that lets you make your own funeral arrangements, from
choosing a funeral director to picking the hue of your headstone.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 18 pica photo
of cover art from software package.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ I love e-mail when it comes from a friend. But so
much of what I receive is true junk, and I delete that unread.
Nowadays the junk seems to outnumber the good mail. (Husted,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art includes 1 column color sig of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   MAC NEWS _ It has been a long time coming but apparently worth
the wait. At least that is the initial review coming from the
Internet about 3Com's new Mac software for its PalmPilot line of
hand-held computers. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.) Art
includes 1 column color photo of a PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-HANDHELD _ The hand-held market has become a smaller
version of the one for desktop and notebook computers. There are
really only two choices: hand-helds running Windows and the three
PalmPilot models, which use a unique operating system and hardware.
(Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ When I think about a growing problem for computer
buyers today _ hopped-up processor chips that are forced to run at
a speed beyond the design specifications _ I understand how much
and how little has changed. It's still all about speed just for the
sake of going fast. But the new status symbols are computers, not
fast cars. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ A new CD-ROM from SouthPeak International called
``The Library of Congress: Eyes of the Nation'' is a splendid
reminder that the Smithsonian Institution is not this nation's only
repository of historical documents and artifacts. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCHER _ Downloading MP3 files, uploading MP3 files and
pretty much doing anything with MP3 files is illegal. Maybe that's
why I'm doing it at 2 in the morning. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ There is help to be found for allergies on the Web.
The best place to start our medicinal visit to the Internet is to a
plain Jane site called Pollen Allergy at
http://www.hoptechno.com/book46.htm. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ If you're looking for a fun but informative book
about the technology behind virtual reality, check out ``The
Visionary Position.'' (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ Does Virtual Game Station really work? The answer,
based on some initial reviews on the Web, is mixed. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDS _ The ``Rugrats Adventure Game'' is a fun, interactive
way to introduce children to the computer. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ We can shave, sing, talk and sleep, but we really
couldn't do a whole lot of work in our cars. Until now. Thanks to
the folks at IBM and DaimlerChrysler, a new gadget promises to turn
the car into a rolling office. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-RACE _ Is the Internet empowering minorities? A study by
Forrester Research suggests that African Americans and Hispanic
Americans are jumping onto the Internet in higher percentages and
Caucasian Americans. Technofiles looks at the issue of race and the
Internet. (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
