</P>
<P>
   MEDIAONE-Comcast, the fourth-largest cable company, buys
MediaOne Group, the No. 3 cable operator, for $48.7 billion in
stock, to create a cable network with 11 million customers. The
acquisition will create one of the largest broadband networks,
which allow several channels, such as television and Internet
access, to be transmitted on the same cable wire. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 24.
</P>
<P>
   w/MEDIAONE-SIDE _ The consolidation of cable companies makes
them much more formidable competitors to phone companies for
everything from local phone service to Internet access. What battle
lines will be drawn by this merger between Comcast and BellSouth?
``The battle lines for local competition are being drawn as cable
companies step in as alternative providers of phone services and
Internet access,'' said Alan Lyons, an analyst at ABN Amro. ``Cable
companies have decided bigger is better.'' Cable-TV companies are
seeking to expand their service areas so the costs of marketing and
new technology can be spread over bigger customer groups.
(Katz/Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-BOTTLE _ In 1899, two Chattanooga, Tenn., attorneys
traveled to Atlanta and paid Coca-Cola Co. $1 for the rights to
bottle and distribute Coca-Cola to most of the U.S., establishing
the company's first bottling operation. On Wednesday, the company
celebrates its 100th year. We'll take the opportunity to look at
how Coca-Cola's bottling operations have grown, and consolidated
through the years, the strategy behind the changes and what lies a
head for the company's U.S. bottling operations. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 52.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-ASA _ Delta says its tender offer for ASA was successful,
giving it 91 percent ownership of the regional affiliate. ASA still
must formally approve the deal at a shareholder meeting next month,
after which it will be a Delta subsidiary. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-OVERSEAS _ Home Depot Inc. named Anders Moberg,
president of Sweden's Ikea Group, to be its group president for
international operations, as the retailer plans further overseas
expansion. Moberg, 49, joins Home Depot after serving 13 years as
president of Ikea. He will begin on Sept. 1, reporting to President
and Chief Executive Arthur Blank. Moberg is credited with expanding
Ikea's business throughout Europe and the Asia-Pacific region,
including a network of retail stores, catalogs and manufacturing
facilities, Home Depot said. This could help Home Depot to expand
internationally. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
