<SLUG> BC-JUSTIN-PROFILE-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS JOHN JUSTIN HANGS BOOTS UP, AN ERA ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ John Justin Jr. was scarcely a teen-ager
when he let his ambitions be known.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1930, soon after H.J. Justin &AMP; Sons moved its boot
company from Nocona to Fort Worth, and there was a party for
employees. Justin remembers his grandmother speaking to the group
when suddenly she stopped, looked down at him and without warning
asked, ``John Jr., what do you want to do when you grow up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to run this company,'' the 13-year-old blurted out.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd laughed; Justin did not. He was embarrassed by his
uncalculated eruption, but he was also deadly serious.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, at the age of 82, Justin will end his 49-year reign
over the Justin-named businesses when he steps down as chairman and
chief executive of Justin Industries, the company that sprang from
H.J. Justin &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 120 years, there will not be a Justin
running the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'll still spend a lot of time here,'' he said, reflecting
on the change. ``But if I get up and don't feel like it, or have
something I'd rather do, then I'm going to do that. I won't be tied
down to the day-in, day-out routine.''
</P>
<P>
   His decision to step aside will end one of Fort Worth's most
influential business careers. Like his friends and peers Charles
Tandy and Amon Carter Jr., Justin blended business leadership with
civic responsibility. He served as mayor and has been a longtime
chairman of the Southwestern Exposition and Livestock Show and
Rodeo, where an arena bears his name and a statue of him astride
his horse welcomes visitors to the Will Rogers Memorial Center.
</P>
<P>
   He guided his company through five decades of change in the
business world: the postwar boom of the '50s and '60s, the
inflation and high interest rates of the '70s, and the bull market
and global competition of the '80s and '90s. Over that time, he
oversaw expansion, through a merger with Acme Brick in 1968 and
other later acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues peaked in 1994 at $483 million, and despite mounting
competition, Justin steadfastly kept most of his boot manufacturing
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He became one of only a handful of American CEOs to stay on the
job into his 80s. But in recent years, Justin has been challenged
both by physical problems and by the whimsy of modern-day Wall
Street, where fledgling Internet companies are the high fliers and
an old-line manufacturer of cowboy boots and bricks fails to
generate excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Industries' stock price has fallen 37 percent in the last
six years and profits have slipped during a time of strong economic
expansion in Texas and nationwide. Some Wall Street analysts are
calling for a restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a company with brick plants, wonderful land and
everything,'' Justin said. ``We've got a great balance sheet and no
debt. But it's below book value. You start one of these high-tech
companies that hasn't made any money ever, and probably won't for
10 years, and the stock just goes through the roof. I don't
understand it, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dee Kelly, a friend and Justin Industries director, said: ``He
built a great company with a tradition of quality. The quality of
the Justin products means more to John than the price of the
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin plans to remain active at the company as chairman
emeritus, even after a new chief executive is named. It is, he
says, his heart and soul, his life's investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I've got that they can't replace is the
knowledge of this company,'' he said. ``I know where the bones are,
and they need that, and I'll be glad to give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Justin knows that he can no longer offer his
once-inexhaustible physical drive. Although he has beaten leukemia
into remission and overcome a painful hip replacement, his mobility
is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Within reach of his desk, an aluminum walker sits as a reminder
of his frailty. Justin has a neurological disorder, and the walker
is an indispensable tool that has been with him for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors have told him his disorder comes with age _ the
nerve endings are worn _ and he'll have to adjust to it. It is a
bitter diagnosis and one he said he has not fully accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for his decision to step aside. He said
he still can't quite see a parallel between his departure, and his
arrival 49 years ago. The company history recounts that tale:
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
