<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-CONTRIBUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY ACCUSES ELITE ARMY UNIT OF OFFERING `BRIBE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 and CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Army's elite Delta Force offered to donate
$20,000 to the favorite charity of a San Antonio city councilman in
order to win his support so anti-terrorist operations could be
conducted in his council district, several city officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mario Salas declined the donation.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the offer, which was made in early 1998 before city
officials refused the unit's request to train in the city, surfaced
after the anti-terrorist team returned to San Antonio for a
mock-training exercise last month at Fort Sam Houston.
</P>
<P>
   That operation was conducted without incident Feb. 18 at the
abandoned Brooke Army Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   City permission for that training wasn't needed since the entire
operation took place on federal property.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different story in 1998, when the Delta Force planned
nighttime mock air and ground assaults using live ammunition over
vacant buildings on the east and west sides of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Salas said the Delta Force members, meeting stiff resistance
from Mayor Howard Peak and Police Chief Al Philippus, offered to
donate $20,000 to a favorite charity in return for his support.
</P>
<P>
   Salas said he neither selected a charity nor supported the
training exercise. As a result, the military made no donation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Peak took offense at the overture.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a bribe, that's what it is,'' the mayor said. ``That's
what it is, no matter who the money was given to.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Sokalski, a spokesman for the U.S. Special Operations
Command at Fort Bragg, N.C., where the Delta Force is based, would
neither confirm nor deny that an offer had been made to Salas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying they don't carry that kind of money,'' Sokalski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Salas said he was asked to support the team's urban training
after Peak, Philippus and other local officials refused to approve
the training operation.
</P>
<P>
   Salas said officials from the Army's Special Operations Command
told him the service had made similar donations in other cities,
but didn't tell him where.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, the Delta Force didn't give up, however, after
Peak and Philippus said no. Instead, they met with private property
owners and discussed the $20,000 donation with Salas.
</P>
<P>
   Though Salas said he initially liked the idea of helping the
military and a local charity, he said he withdrew support for the
proposal after talking with Philippus, who feared that Delta Force
operatives might alarm or hurt residents in the area of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I didn't consider that angle,'' said Salas, who
now wonders whether the Delta Force should have offered to make the
donation. ``In retrospect, it does seem strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
