<HEADER>
A9882 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUSTIN-PROFILE-2ndTak     03-22 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTIN-PROFILE-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: recounts that tale: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1950, the boot company was struggling. It needed new blood
and new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   H.J. Justin began the business in 1879 when he moved to Spanish
Fort from his home in Gainesville, just south of the Oklahoma
border. The business moved to nearby Nocona 10 years later, when
Spanish Fort dried up with the loss of the cattle drives.
</P>
<P>
   It was a family business, and when H.J. Justin died in 1918, his
sons _ including John Sr. _ took over.
</P>
<P>
   John Jr. hoped to become part of that business but was blocked
by his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt the boot business was dying,'' Justin said. ``My
father sincerely thought I shouldn't get in it, and he did
everything he could to keep me out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1950, John Sr. changed his mind. His son had proved
himself in business by laboring late into the night producing
women's belts in the family garage. He and his partner, a
neighborhood friend named Charles Tandy, took turns pounding at
scraps of leather with a 16-pound mallet. While one hammered, the
other burned made-up cattle brands into the belts.
</P>
<P>
   Justin then found a sagging belt company to invest in and turned
it into a profitable concern. He also served a stint in the
Merchant Marine during World War II. Finally, his father and Uncle
Earl asked him to save Justin Boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were doing nothing to help the boot business,'' Justin
said. ``They were trying every way in the world to do something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was making shoes, but Justin said they ``had no
styling or snap,'' and the business was losing $1.75 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   John Jr., over the objections of his father, quickly eliminated
the shoe business and turned his attention to boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were kind of like Henry Ford,'' Justin said of the
company he took over. ``You could have any color boots you wanted
as long as they were black. I started to get some styling and some
snappier things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very limited on money,'' he recalled. ``I went out and
bought a yellow leather, about the worst-looking yellow you can
imagine. And a green that was just about as bad. And a red and
blue. I got a bargain on it and I began to put those in different
combinations.''
</P>
<P>
   The dealers took interest. The boots weren't pretty, but they
were different, and different was unusual for Justin Boot Co.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investors say, Justin Industries needs to be different
again. It needs to catch the market's attention. This time it is
John Jr., and his board members, who must find a younger person to
lead the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get around like I used to,'' Justin said. ``I am
primarily an operations and a manufacturing man. I am a good
salesman, too. I used to be in a plant or two every week or riding
with a salesman or two. But I just can't do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He will still have other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Justin serves on the boards of Blue Cross Blue Shield of Texas
and AMR Investment Services, and he has been chairman of the Stock
Show board since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tandy and Carter in earlier times, Justin gave time and
energy to Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   He and Jane, his wife of 46 years, have worked tirelessly for
several Fort Worth organizations. He served as Fort Worth mayor
from 1961 to 1963 and is a trustee at Texas Christian University.
She is on the advisory boards of the Child Study Center, the
Lecture Foundation, the Jewel Charity Ball and the Van Cliburn
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin represents a unique link between Fort Worth's past and
present,'' Kelly said. ``He is one of the last of Fort Worth's
truly legendary figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin relishes an earlier era in business, when he and other
business owners would gather at night to talk about their trades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would just talk about selling, how you sold,'' he said. ``I
would go in there and say, `Well, I've got some boots and I can't
sell them, what do I need to do?' We'd talk all night about it.
We'd watch the sun come up, go home, shower and go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin is proud of the company he has built and confident in its
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Howard Jennings, one of our old directors,'' Justin
said. ``I would be down there at the factory on a Saturday morning,
worrying about the business, and he would tell me, `Run the
business the way it ought to be and the price will take care of
itself.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've run it the way it ought to be. The balance sheet
is as strong as horseradish. We have good factories and we're
building new factories. In footwear, we're getting new things on
the market. It doesn't worry me. It's going to make money and make
good money. It will pay a nice dividend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll still need me to give my ideas, and I've agreed.
They'll haul me off one day, and then they can find somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
