<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CARTOON-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOON-STAR DUO: TOBACCO AND ALCOHOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(kd) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Parental concerns about the messages small children
receive in G-rated animated feature films have resulted in a review
showing that two-thirds of such movies produced over the last 60
years include the use of tobacco and alcohol by villains and heroes
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Adam O. Goldstein and his colleagues at the University of
North Carolina School of Medicine screened 50 animated feature
films by five major production companies, beginning with ``Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' released in 1937, in which only a
poisoned apple was consumed. They found that 34 films had at least
one scene in which tobacco or alcohol was used and that the
depictions did not decrease over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The study was released in New York at a one-day briefing on the
media's impact on health behaviors and appears in the upcoming
issue of The Journal of the American Medical Association .
</P>
<P>
   In the journal, the researchers write of the films:
``Twenty-eight (56 percent) portrayed one or more incidences of
tobacco use, including all seven films released in 1996 and 1997.
None of the films studied suggested any long-term health
consequences of tobacco or alcohol addiction or any verbal messages
about negative health consequences of usage.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, who earlier investigated the effects of the Joe Camel
advertising campaign on young children, began the study after
watching ``All Dogs Go to Heaven'' with his children. In the film,
Charlie, a good character, is run over after drinking with his
buddies. But when he is given a second chance at life, he orders
another beer, Goldstein realized.
</P>
<P>
   Once he turned his researcher's eye to the films and videos seen
by millions of children, Goldstein found that characters using
tobacco or alcohol were almost equally divided between good and
bad. Cigar-smoking Pinocchio and wine-drinking Dumbo, for example,
were good; Captain Hook and the amusement park manager from ``Space
Jam,'' both of whom puffed on cigars, were bad, as was Cruella De
Vil, a smoker, from ``101 Dalmatians.'' Three smoking characters in
``Alice in Wonderland'' _ the dodo, with a pipe; the walrus, with a
cigar, and the caterpillar, with a hookah _ were considered
neutral. Goldstein noted that animals or objects were often
portrayed as smoking or drinking to make them seem more human.
</P>
<P>
   Whether such portrayals lead to alcohol or tobacco use was not
explored in the study. ``We don't know what the effect of exposure
is, but the question is why is there exposure,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey L. Brown, a Westchester pediatrician, said, ``I
think it would be hard to prove a cause-and-effect relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patrick Johnson, a social psychologist with the National
Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University,
said the study is important because it shows the range of exposure
to positive messages about substance use. ``On its own, it's not
very dramatic,'' he said, ``but added with other exposures like
parents smoking cigarettes or having drinks every evening or guys
on the corner drinking a can of beer, and there's a cumulative
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are not asking that childhood favorites be
banned from theaters or pulled off video shelves for re-editing,
but Goldstein suggested that parents watch the films with their
children and discuss the characters' behavior afterward.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
