<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DNA-SEQUENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'LL SEQUENCE HUMAN GENOME FIRST? IT'S UP TO PHRED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash.)  (af) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week the public consortium working to sequence the human
genome said it would complete a ``first draft'' of the human DNA
sequence next spring, well ahead of the target date announced by
its commercial rival the Celera Corp. Each side has committed $250
million to the project, but the outcome of this battle of titans
seems to lie to some extent in the hands of an esoteric computer
program named phred.
</P>
<P>
   Phred's significance has to do with the new model of DNA
sequencing machine, called the ABI 3700 sequencer, on which both
teams, but particularly Celera, are resting their ambitious
timetables. The ABI 3700, like its predecessor the ABI 377,
determines the order of bases in the fragments of DNA fed into it.
</P>
<P>
   Both sequencing machines depend on phred, a program that checks
accuracy, but no version of phred is yet available for the 3700,
which could prevent the machine from being fully effective for
several months.
</P>
<P>
   Development of the ABI 3700 by Applied Biosystems Inc., now a
division of Perkin Elmer, was the spur that led to the formation of
Celera, also a Perkin Elmer subsidiary. Michael W. Hunkapiller, a
co-inventor of Applied Biosystems' sequencing machines, and J.
Craig Venter, a genome sequencing pioneer, calculated that with a
fleet of 240 of the new 3700 machines, they could sequence the
genome's three billion letters by December 2001, handily beating
the public consortium's target of 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The public consortium _ which consists principally of eight
university centers finance by the National Institutes of Health and
the Sanger Centre in England backed by the Wellcome Trust of London
_ has responded to Celera's challenge by increasing its sequencing
efforts and ordering its own 3700s.
</P>
<P>
   These are expensive devices, costing $300,000 apiece. Besides
Celera's 240 sequencers, the NIH is negotiating for 200 machines,
and the Sanger Center 50. Whichever team wins the race, Hunkapiller
would seem to have already scored another kind of victory in
booking some $150 million of orders.
</P>
<P>
   Testing out the 3700, however, scientists at the Sanger Center
complained in an article in Science last week that the sequencer's
``read length'' _ the average number of bases in each fragment of
sequenced DNA _ was only 465 bases, compared with 655 bases for the
older 377 sequencer, which costs half as much.
</P>
<P>
   A shorter read length means more work for the people and
computers that assemble the complete sequence. ``There is no gain
in throughput in terms of capital investment,'' the Sanger
scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   But a reason for the short read length, Hunkapiller said, is
that the Sanger Center was using a computer program calibrated for
the older, 377 machine. The program, known as phred, was written by
Dr. Philip Green of the University of Washington, Seattle. It
assigns quality values to the base identifications deduced by the
sequencing machine and cuts off the read if the quality falls.
Phred is important for preparing highly accurate sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Green, whose university operates one of the centers in the
public consortium, has not yet prepared a version of phred that is
calibrated for the ABI 3700. He is at present adapting phred to the
MegaBACE, a rival sequencing machine made by Molecular Dynamics,
now owned by Amersham Pharmacia Biotech.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Celera camp believe Green is delaying the 3700
version of phred in order to delay Celera. Green denied that,
saying the problem was that he does not have enough sequence data
from the 3700 to adapt Phred. Also, he said, Applied Biosystems had
not made available a machine for him, as Molecular Dynamics had
done.
</P>
<P>
   Green said that he ``may have enough data by the end of the
summer'' to update phred for the ABI 3700. Given the fast
timetables announced by the two consortia, late delivery of phred
could be an impediment, especially for Celera, which is relying
solely on the 3700.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will certainly delay the public side,'' Venter said, but he
added that Celera had contracted for the development of a new
quality-score program after learning that Green could not supply an
updated version of phred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
