<SLUG> BC-SCI-EATING-HABITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY EATING HABITS TIED TO ADULT ILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new studies lend support to the view that by the time
children enter elementary school they may have eating and other
health habits that will play a major role in the problems they may
suffer in later life, including heart disease, high blood pressure
and possibly diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts said the findings suggested that it was never too
soon to teach children good dietary habits, as well the importance
of exercise. This is especially true for black and Mexican-American
children. As early as age 6, one of the studies found, they show
significant health differences, overall, in comparison with
non-Hispanic white children.
</P>
<P>
   One study, to be reported Tuesday in Circulation, the journal of
the American Heart Association, was conducted by Dr. Alan R.
Sinaiko of the University of Minnesota Medical School in
Minneapolis and colleagues, beginning in 1977. It involved 679
public schoolchildren who were followed from age 7 through 23. Over
the years, the children were periodically examined to determine
their weight, body mass index _ considered a more accurate gauge of
overall health _ and blood pressure. As adults, they gave blood
samples that were tested for cholesterol and insulin levels.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that body weight during childhood, and
especially the rate at which the weight was gained, was a good
indicator of whether an adult would exhibit risk factors for
cardiovascular disease and diabetes. This was especially true for a
condition known as insulin resistance syndrome, which is associated
with obesity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prevalence of overweight in youth is increasing,'' the
report noted. ``On the basis of the data from this study, it can be
expected that there will be a steady increase in the number of
at-risk individuals as today's children become adults.''
</P>
<P>
   The second study, described in the March 17 issue of The Journal
of the American Medical Association, involved differences in
cardiovascular risk factors among children in various ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been established that blacks and people of Hispanic
descent suffer from the disease at a greater rates than
non-Hispanic whites. But the Stanford scientists report they could
detect differences in the risk factors for the disease as early as
age 6 in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   They also found that while poor nutrition and low income often
went hand-in-hand, the health differences between white and black
children, and white and Mexican-American ones, appeared to
transcend economic factors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the health indicators researchers looked at were body mass
index, fat intake, blood pressure and cholesterol. In most
categories, they found significantly higher problems in the
minority children studied.
</P>
<P>
   While there may be many reasons behind the differences, from
genetics to culture, the lead author of the study, Dr. Marilyn A.
Winkleby, said many could be linked to a lack of knowledge about
basic nutrition. She said more should be done to design nutrition
education programs for blacks and Mexican-Americans. She also said
much more should be done to encourage physical activity among
children, and suggested that minority neighborhoods have not been
provided with enough good sports facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that it's not hard to do,'' she said. ``It's
cost effective in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   The study drew on data gathered by the third National Health and
Nutrition Examination Survey, conducted by the federal government
from 1988 to 1994. Stanford scientists focused on examinations and
surveys done of 2,769 blacks, 2,854 Mexican-Americans and 2,063
non-Hispanic whites, all from the ages of 6 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Winkleby said the study showed the importance of reaching
children as early as possible to prevent future health problems.
``This highlights the need for interventions as early as
kindergarten,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
