<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS &LR;      03-22 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO CRISIS LOOMS OVER PRIMAKOV'S VISIT WITH CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S.-Russian disagreement over allied tactics
in Kosovo threatens to complicate Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov's meetings with President Clinton during the Russian
leader's visit to Washington beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton wants to provide personal
support for Primakov and his efforts to win favorable debt
repayment terms from the International Monetary Fund to help
Primakov deal with Russia's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States and Russia are at odds over the threat by
NATO to bomb Serbian-dominated Yugoslav, Russia's long-time ally.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, just before his scheduled departure for the United
States, urged NATO to forego the air strikes that would be designed
to persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt his
campaign of suppression against ethnic Albanians' quest for
autonomy in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there will be no raids,'' Primakov said in Moscow,
adding that the Kremlin remains ``categorically against the use of
force against Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov did not rule out delaying his trip _ his first since
becoming prime minister seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, preparing for two meetings with Primakov later this
week, warned that NATO will move forward with military action if
Milosevic ``continues to choose aggression over peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was awaiting the outcome of last-minute
consultations in Belgrade between Ambassador Richard Holbrooke and
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said the president wants to
bolster Primakov's stature in Russia as he tackles the domestic
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov is a prime contender for the Russian presidency in 2000
when President Boris Yeltsin's term expires. Primakov would oversee
Russia until a special election, should Yeltsin not finish his
term.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Primakov's visit to
the United States would not delay military action against Yugoslav
forces if Milosevic continues his offensive against ethnic Albanian
civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a long-time ally of Yugoslavia, has opposed punitive
military action against Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian forces joined U.S.-led NATO troops in Bosnia in 1995
to enforce a U.S.-brokered peace agreement in that war-torn
republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is hoping that Russia will join
forces with the United States and NATO allies to deploy a
peacekeeping force in Kosovo, if a peace agreement can be achieved
between Albanian and Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton emphasized that both the western allies and Russia agree
on the goal of halting bloodshed in Kosovo and restoring the
political autonomy that Kosovo long enjoyed from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We and our NATO allies _ and Russia _ all agree that this is
the right goal,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov is banking on the United States and the IMF to help
Russia avert technical bankruptcy later this year as it tries to
pay off $17.5 billion in foreign debt payments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is hosting Primakov at the so-called
Gore-Primakov Commission _ a Cabinet-level forum that meets twice a
year to deal with non-ideological nuts-and-bolts issues that
complicate U.S. economic involvement in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov is expected to approve a plan that will enable the
Russian government to resume receiving hard currency. The
arrangement calls for a U.S. firm to buy from Russia about 550 tons
of weapons-grade uranium that has been diluted with other material
to yield a uranium product suitable for powering U.S. nuclear power
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov also will meet with IMF chief Michael Camdessus to
renegotiate the terms of payment of the $4.8 billion that the
Kremlin owes the IMF this year in loan repayments.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's foreign debt amounts to almost $144 billion, including
the Kremlin's Soviet-era debt. Failure to make timely debt payments
could trigger the flight of foreign investment that is sorely
needed to rebuild the economy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite White House hopes for helping Primakov, the Clinton
administration has taken a number of steps in recent months that
alarm the Kremlin and potentially fan anti-western nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration led efforts to expand NATO membership
to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, all former
Soviet allies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also plans a visit to Slovenia in the Balkans in June _
the next nation likely to be offered NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision to move ahead with development of an
anti-missile system to target incoming warheads from rogue nations
such as North Korea also has alarmed the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials insist the new defensive missile system will not
require revisions in the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty. But
Russian authorities remain unpersuaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration plan may complicate ratification of
the START II treaty by the communist-dominated Russian Duma. The
Duma has agreed to begin debate on the 1992 accord on April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov took over as prime minister after last August's fiscal
freefall in Russia. The output of goods and services stands at
barely 55 percent of 1989 levels, according to Keith Bush of the
Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NARAL23-COX     03-22 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NARAL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH, DOLE HIDING ANTI-ABORTION VIEWS, GROUP CLAIMS
 &HT;    400&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's largest reproductive rights
organization accused the two leading Republican presidential
candidates Monday of trying to mask their opposition to abortion
rights in order to fool voters.
</P>
<P>
   The group's television ad campaign, citing news accounts,
labeled both Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former American Red
Cross President Elizabeth Dole as ``anti-choice'' in the debate
over abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The ads began airing Monday in Des Moines, Iowa, and Manchester,
N.H., two early-voting states in the nomination battle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Dole are ``trying to hide their extreme views'' in the
Republican primary in order to avoid alienating voters in the
general election, said Kate Michelman, president of the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League (NARAL), the
organization sponsoring the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying just enough about their position to keep the
far political right, anti-choice groups and voters within their
primaries,'' she said in an interview. ``They know that if they
don't obscure their positions, if they are forthright and honest
about their anti-choice views, it would cost them voters in the
general election.''
</P>
<P>
   The NARAL ad cites several statements made by Bush since
entering politics, notably a 1994 interview with the Dallas Morning
News in which he vowed to ``do everything in my power to restrict
abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also said the Republican Party should maintain its
``pro-life tenor,'' but has not endorsed the longstanding GOP
platform plank calling for a constitutional amendment outlawing
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has refused to answer any questions about abortion since
resigning from the Red Cross earlier this year to explore the
possibility of running for the Republican 2000 presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The NARAL ad notes, however, that in 1996, when her husband Bob
Dole was running for president, she acknowledged to the New York
Daily News that she supports a constitutional amendment to outlaw
almost all abortions.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Bush told Reuters the governor opposes
abortion, except in cases of rape, incest or when the life of the
mother is endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Dole, told the news agency she
also opposes abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Dole feels so strongly about this matter that she will
say it in her own way and with her own words at the appropriate
time,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Michelman declined to say how much money NARAL would spend on
the ads. The group decided to air them in Iowa and New Hampshire
first because those states will host the first presidential
balloting next year. But she said NARAL would shift the ads to
other states if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   She also said NARAL would produce similar ads in congressional
races in which candidates try to obscure their positions on
abortion. But she said the presidential campaign was a priority
because, with anti-abortion majorities likely to remain in
Congress, ``the presidency could be the last line of defense''
against the overturning of the 1973 Supreme Court ruling granting
reproductive rights to women.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates for the Democratic president nomination, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, are
both advocates of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   All the other Republican candidates oppose abortion. One of
them, former Reagan administration adviser Gary Bauer, has made
opposition to abortion a centerpiece of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, ad campaigns such as the one launched by NARAL on
Monday occur during the general election. But Michelman said NARAL
did not want to wait any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to wait six months, eight months, a year when
they have already fooled half the people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
