<P>
   Michelman declined to say how much money NARAL would spend on
the ads. The group decided to air them in Iowa and New Hampshire
first because those states will host the first presidential
balloting next year. But she said NARAL would shift the ads to
other states if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   She also said NARAL would produce similar ads in congressional
races in which candidates try to obscure their positions on
abortion. But she said the presidential campaign was a priority
because, with anti-abortion majorities likely to remain in
Congress, ``the presidency could be the last line of defense''
against the overturning of the 1973 Supreme Court ruling granting
reproductive rights to women.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates for the Democratic president nomination, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, are
both advocates of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   All the other Republican candidates oppose abortion. One of
them, former Reagan administration adviser Gary Bauer, has made
opposition to abortion a centerpiece of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, ad campaigns such as the one launched by NARAL on
Monday occur during the general election. But Michelman said NARAL
did not want to wait any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to wait six months, eight months, a year when
they have already fooled half the people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
