<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEDEPOT-OVERSEAS-CO     03-22 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-OVERSEAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ikea president to head Home Depot's international dealings
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot has made another move to advance its
do-it-yourself culture overseas by hiring a Swedish executive to
run its international operations.
</P>
<P>
   Anders Moberg, president of Ikea Group, will become Home Depot's
group president for international operations and will report
directly to President and Chief Executive Arthur Blank, the company
said Monday. Moberg, 49, is noted for his 29-year career with Ikea,
a large Denmark-based furnishings chain and one of the world's
largest privately held companies.
</P>
<P>
   Moberg, a native of Almhult, Sweden, is in the process of
relocating to Atlanta and will begin working for Home Depot in the
fall, Blank said. A search firm helped fill the newly created post,
Blank added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for someone who had experience running a large
company in lots of countries and with a lot of experience in global
sourcing,'' Blank said. Moberg, who joined Ikea in 1970, has seen
the company expand into 28 countries. In 1973, Ikea opened a store
in Germany _ its first store outside Scandinavia, then worked its
way across the globe by hitting a new country nearly every year
through 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Moberg's importing experience was especially attractive, said
Blank, who noted that Ikea purchases from 65 countries. Imports
account for 3 percent of Home Depot's sales, and the company would
like to expand that to 11 percent over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Moberg drove Ikea's expansion of retail stores and manufacturing
plants throughout Europe and the Asia-Pacific region, Blank said.
The newest additions to Ikea's reach include Finland, Spain and
China.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot opened its first stores outside North America last
year in Chile and will expand to Argentina. Is Moberg's experience
a signal that Home Depot is revving up international growth beyond
its Latin American outposts?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a change or shift in strategy. We're focused on
Latin America, but we'll continue to look at the Far East and other
areas,'' Blank said. ``International growth is very important to
us, but it's important to understand that it's a long-term
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
