<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ZERO-GRAVITY-EXER     03-22 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ZERO-GRAVITY-EXERCISES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSCLE MACHINE FOR GREAT GYM IN THE SKY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (The Science Times)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(kd) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To get into space, astronauts have to fight gravity. To stay
strong and healthy in space, they have to make up for gravity's
absence, because muscles atrophy and bones lose calcium without the
earth's steady pull to struggle against. As a January 2000
launching date for the first resident mission to the new
International Space Station approaches, NASA is making its most
serious effort ever to break the muscle barrier to extended stays
in zero gravity.
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-year search for a space equivalent to weight
training, scientists at the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration are preparing a series of ``resistance exercise
devices,'' machines that give weightless astronauts a workout by
giving them something to pull or push against.
</P>
<P>
   An interim device, already in use by astronauts in training,
looks like two diaper pails bolted to a crossbar. A college
student's idea for an improved version, based on the principle that
makes a tape measure snap shut, was sent aloft above Houston last
week &UR;  &LR; for testing during free fall. And a call recently went out on
the Internet for any and all notions for a permanent, far more
advanced machine, which NASA is hoping will include virtual reality
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Stringham Shepherd, the chief strength trainer for space
station astronauts and the wife of William M. Shepherd, the
astronaut who will be the commander of the January mission, said
the goal was for astronauts to retain enough strength to be able to
walk on their own after a four- to six-month space station mission.
</P>
<P>
   The crew last year began training on the interim resistance
exercise device, or IRED, which will be bolted into a passageway
between the station's modules this year. Produced by Leonardo Inc.,
a Kansas City engineering firm, the device consists of two
cylinders containing 28 ``flex packs'' _ stacked disks connected to
an outer ring by rubber straps. As an astronaut pulls a cable, the
disks spin, stretching the flaps and creating work for the
astronaut's muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shepherd said the device worked better than anything that
NASA had tried before.
</P>
<P>
   But despite ingenious adjustments, the flex packs provide a
somewhat uneven, and therefore less efficient, workout, said Dr.
Suzanne Schneider, a research physiologist at the Johnson Space
Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It was the need for steady pressure that led Tara Rutley, a
biology student at Colorado State University and a would-be
astronaut, to turn to so-called constant torque springs to create
the device that she and three fellow students tested in two days of
weightless flight last week aboard a NASA cargo plane.
</P>
<P>
   Like the tape in a tape measure, these springs consist of flat
strips of metal that have been compressed in the process of being
wound around a central drum. It takes force to counteract that
compression and pull the spring out; when the force is released the
spring rolls back up.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rutley and her colleagues, Paul Colosky, Jon Dory and Jack
Zentner, all members of the university's branch of the American
Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics, took commercially
available springs and combined them into what they called ``force
packs'' hooked to cables. In its final version, the machine could
offer the equivalent of a 500-pound weight, Colosky said.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype tested last week, as part of NASA's Reduced
Gravity Student Flight Opportunities Program, was more modest, with
a maximum of 30 pounds of resistance. ``It looks like a sit-down
home gym because we went and bought one and cut it down.'' said Ms.
Rutley, who said the cost of the prototype was about $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider said she was enthusiastic about the prototype, but
uncertain whether the space station's complicated construction
schedule would allow it to be seriously considered as the station's
second-generation exercise device, scheduled to replace the IRED
early in the next century. That will probably be a flex-pack
machine improved with small motors and monitors. ``I really like
the kids' idea better than what we've got,'' she said. ``I just
wish it was further along and that we'd heard about it two years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for the ``advanced resistance exercise device,'' or
ARED, to be installed after the station's unfurled solar panels
make power abundant, is shaping up as more of that kind of free for
all. Schneider said ``some really neat ideas'' have been put
forward already for devices that would match the flexibility of a
small gym with the monitoring capabilities of a laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   One robotics company, she said, has proposed combining
wall-mounted cables connected to resistance-producing motors and
virtual-reality goggles. If the astronaut chose to play baseball,
she said, the cable would mimic the heft of a gravity-bound bat
while the participant watched the ball sail out of the virtual
park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
