<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-FRAUD-0323-C     03-22 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FRAUD-0323-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PROBES STOCK FRAUD IN CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON In 1993, when his young son, James, was diagnosed
with a rare form of muscular dystrophy, Galen O'Kane quit his job
in Ellsworth, Maine, and began to trade stocks online in a bid to
offset rising medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, while surfing the Internet, O'Kane saw an ad
for an Internet newsletter, The Future Superstock. The Web site was
promoting a company called Electro-Optical, which made a hi-tech
fingerprint identification device. The newsletter touted the
company as its stock pick of the year.
</P>
<P>
   O'Kane, trained as an electrical engineer, eventually put
$23,000 into Electro-Optical. Then, last March, having taken his
son to Boston for medical treatment, O'Kane decided to stop by the
corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked into the building and was shocked to find that it was
completely empty,'' O'Kane testified at a Senate hearing Monday.
``I expected to see an assembly line, equipment and employees, but
there was nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Kane quickly dumped his Electro-Optical stock. But by then it
was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presently, my total loss is over $20,000,'' O'Kane told Sen.
Susan M. Collins (R-Maine), who is chairing two days of hearings
into securities fraud on the Internet. ``It was a great deal of
money for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that the Internet appears to provide
'cybercrooks' with profound avenues for committing financial
fraud,'' Collins said. ``It gives some consumers a false sense of
security, credibility and control regarding their investments....
Technology in some cases is mistaken for truth.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ascent of the Internet, warned Sen. Carl Levin
(D-Mich.), ``we face the real possibility that the American stock
exchanges will become more like Las Vegas and less like Wall
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said she was weighing legislation that would provide for
third-party verification of Internet sites that tout
over-the-counter ``micro-cap'' stocks those with market values of
under $50 million. But none of the witnesses before the Senate
permanent investigations subcommittee seemed warm to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's dangers as well in too much censorship,'' said Howard
Friedman, who teaches at the University of Toledo College of Law.
He has written a book on the Internet and securities regulation,
``Securities Regulation in Cyberspace,'' which was published last
year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Friedman said, something needs to be done
about ``spamming,'' which allows promoters to reach large audiences
at low cost through bulk E-mail.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-policing is the answer,'' said Thomas Gardner, founder of
The Motley Fool, which has evolved into a multi-faceted service for
individual investors. As Gardner sees it, Internet securities fraud
is driven by ignorance. ``Although we believe that individuals can
and should make their own investment decisions, we don't believe
they should always do so alone,'' he told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the view of a much chastised Galen O'Kane. As he
put it in the wake of his big loss in Electro-Optical stock: ``That
was my first attempt at investing in a stock on the Internet and it
will be my last. I have continued to invest online, but now I turn
to an investment adviser for advice on all of my investments.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
