<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Eds.: Updates to add KOSOVO-NATO and expand skedlines.   
(js) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times is planning the the following
coverage on KOSOVO for the paper of Tuesday, March 23. These
stories are scheduled to move tonight in the New York Times News
Service report. Stories will move in the ``i'' news file. For more
information, call toll free at (888) 346-9867. The day supervisor
is Josephine Schmidt. The night supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ The NATO allies stepped up
their threats Monday, giving their top civilian leader the
authority to mount air strikes directly against Serbian forces
attacking ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo province. The
expanded authority is subject to consultation with Western leaders.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Developments in the
last-minute negotiations between Richard Holbrooke and the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic. By Steven Erlanger. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ How air attacks would affect U.S.
policy; Western relations with Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
(Scheduled for Page 1)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Serbia's latest offensive in Kosovo is
leading some of Russia's top foreign policy specialists to question
Moscow's long-standing support for Belgrade. With Prime Minister
Yevgeni M. Primakov set to leave on Tuesday for Washington,
Russia's top priority is to wrest billions of dollars in fresh
credits from the International Monetary Fund, not argue over the
Balkans. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Srbica, Yugoslavia) _ The general commander of the
Kosovo Liberation Army called for NATO to launch air strikes on
Serbia and put an end to the bloodshed, as Serbian army and police
forces continued their ransacking and burning of villages Monday.
By Carlotta Gall. With locator map. (Scheduled for Page 1.)
</P>
