<HEADER>
A9957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-NOTES23     03-22 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High school reunion may take place in final game
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Avery says he doesn't stay in touch with Ricky Moore as
much as he used to. But if Duke and UConn win in Saturday's NCAA
Final Four in St. Petersburg, Fla., the two high school teammates
from Augusta, Ga.'s Westside High will have a high-profile reunion
in the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's Moore is two years older than Avery, the Duke point
guard, but in 1996, when Avery was a sophomore, they teamed to lead
Westside to a 33-1 record and a state championship. The following
year, with Moore gone to UConn, Avery led Westside to a 25-4
season.
</P>
<P>
   Avery is Duke's third-leading scorer and one of the bright
rising stars in college basketball. Moore is the team's defensive
stopper and played a key role in the Huskies' 67-62 win over
Gonzaga for the West Regional championship
</P>
<P>
   The two players were very close when Avery became a freshman at
Westside, where both his mother and father played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky kind of adopted William and they'd go one on one against
each other every chance they got,'' said Ken Wright, who coached
both players at Westside. ``It made both of them better players,
especially William.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery says the two aren't as close as they once were, but he
would certainly like the chance to play against him next Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two guys from Westside playing in the national championship
game? How cool would that be?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Three rookies and Coach K
</P>
<P>
   Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski will be making his eighth trip to the
Final Four since 1986 while the three other coaches in St.
Petersburg _ UConn's Jim Calhoun, Michigan State's Tom Izzo, and
Ohio State's Jim O'Brien _ will be there for the very first time.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski, in his 19th season at Duke, says the feeling never
gets old. Besides, he has a chance to join some elite company
should he win his third national title. That club includes only
John Wooden, Adolph Rupp, and Bob Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a chance to play for the national championship
until you get to the Final Four,'' said Krzyzewski, who won his
titles in 1991 and 1992. ``Now we can talk about winning the
national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrawell on the money
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the shuffle of Duke's lineup of All-Americans is junior
forward Chris Carrawell, but he was a major factor in the Blue
Devils' 85-64 win over Temple for the East Regional championship.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Carrawell used to pick up spending money by beating
older guys in pickup games on the tough playgrounds of East St.
Louis, Ill. So Carrawell was more than comfortable going against
the city kids from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Temple wanted to pack their zone around All-America center Elton
Brand. Carrawell made them pay by slicing through it to hand out
seven assists, grab seven rebounds and score 12 points. He also
held Mark Karcher, Temple's best scorer, to 7-of-25 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he plays like that,'' Krzyzewski said, ``it is a
beautiful thing to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   If Michigan State and Ohio State win Saturay, it would make the
first time two Big Ten teams played for the championship since
1976, when Indiana beat Michigan. . . . Duke, UConn, and Michigan
State, were ranked No. 1, 2, and 5 in the preseason Associated
Press poll. Ohio State, 8-22 last season, did not crack the
rankings until January. . . . Ohio State is the first team to reach
the Final Four without having been in the tournament the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
