<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SCENARIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bill and Hillary Clinton saga is so incredible
that almost any scenario about their future is plausible. As a
political pair, they have broken all the old rules.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the latest speculation:
</P>
<P>
   1) The first lady decides to run for the Senate in New York. The
president resigns to move to Manhattan with her, back up her
campaign and end gossip about a marital separation. It's her
political turn.
</P>
<P>
   2) With the Clintons gone, Vice President Al Gore becomes
president and can run for the 2000 Democratic nomination as an
incumbent, strengthening his political power and the likelihood of
a general election victory. Gore is free at last.
</P>
<P>
   3) Gore then returns the favor by granting both Clintons a
blanket pardon to protect them from any future indictment. They've
been punished enough.
</P>
<P>
   Something for everyone in this deal.
</P>
<P>
   But will it work? Who knows? There are holes in this vision, as
there are in any political experiment.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, of course, insists that he will never, ever
step down before the natural expiration of his second term. Richard
Nixon said that too, just before he resigned to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's continued high approval ratings depend in part on
public appreciation of his determination to carry on despite
everything. He did just that at the dinner of a journalists' group
called the Gridiron Club last weekend, demonstrating that he can
bring spontaneous, genuine laughter and applause from a
sophisticated press and political crowd even after an evening of
satire pummeling his behavior. What a pro.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he might not see the merits of the above
scenario. The rumblings from Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's
operation that he might try to send either or both Clintons to jail
after the president is out of office must be deeply worrisome. It
would be tempting to let Gore protect them with the stroke of a
pen.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's sense of loyalty to his mentor should guarantee that as
president he would indeed do the Clintons the favor of a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   When Gerald Ford, whom Nixon had named as vice president, did
the same for Nixon, he took a terrible political hit. The public
thought Nixon was guilty of the Watergate crimes and didn't like
the idea that a covert bargain might have been struck.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is not Nixon. Gore can get away with this.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has a job approval rating in the mid-60s, compared with
only 44 percent who approve of the way the impeachment-minded
Congress has been behaving. A majority of the country still
believes that he should not have been impeached for private sexual
misbehavior, let alone go to the pokey for it.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Nixon's crimes were violations of his public trust
involving serious constitutional abuses of presidential power. A
Gallup poll just before Nixon's resignation showed that only 24
percent of those surveyed approved of the way he had handled his
job. The public did not support an official pass on his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The current scenario, however, turns primarily on Hillary
Clinton's decision about whether to run for the Senate seat of
retiring incumbent Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. She looks good
in the polls, but if her Republican opponent is New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, it will be a tough, well-matched race.
</P>
<P>
   As her friends are becoming convinced she really wants to run,
the Republicans are growing more sarcastic about the possibility,
trying to scare her away. Conservative columnists muse that she is
too thin-skinned to take the pressure, too battered by the
president's infidelity, too unaccustomed to her own name on the
ballot rather than her husband's. They scoff at the notion that she
would be comfortable as a junior senator, one of 100 instead of the
only first lady in the land.
</P>
<P>
   My, but they underestimate her. Have they not noticed that she
is as good a public performer as her husband and seems to enjoy the
political game as much? I have watched her in action many times.
She knows how to arouse a crowd, give savvy interviews and
articulate national policy every bit as much as her husband.
</P>
<P>
   And the very notion that having little tolerance for criticism
is a problem unique to Hillary is downright silly. Guiliani and a
whole host of other male politicians have similar uneven
temperaments. Some of them have made it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Clintons can know the odds on the probability that Bill
would step aside prematurely and acknowledge that he has had his
day. Their relationship remains a mystery, a private affair that
seems to be constantly in flux. They have both invested a great
deal emotionally and mentally in their partnership.
</P>
<P>
   There must still be some glue between them despite the
humiliation and betrayal. If it binds him to her as much as her to
him, he may well accept the usefulness of reversing their roles.
After all, he would not be going into some male purdah.
</P>
<P>
   He will always be a former president, honored with endless
opportunities to serve on corporate boards, get rich and do
important things in the private sector. Look at the fun his
precedessors have!
</P>
<P>
   And if she becomes a senator and runs for president some day, he
can always manage her campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
