<HEADLINE>
LONG-LASTING IMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Why does immunization have long-lasting effects?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because some of the many kinds of cells that make up the
normal human immune system are naturally able to retain a
``memory'' of the defense efforts aroused by certain infections,
said Dr. Regina Rabinovich of the National Institute of Allergy and
Infections Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brain is not the only part of the body that has a
memory,'' she said. ``A vaccine fools the body into having the
memory of how to fight infection created by the vaccine rather than
by an infection.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, after an actual infection with a ``childhood''
disease like measles, which people rarely get more than once, the
immune response goes away, but certain cells are ready to fight
again extremely quickly upon re-exposure, Dr. Rabinovich explained.
The memory remains for years without a vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``So a vaccine mimics infection to get the memory cells to do
battle, to do particular chemical and physical things,'' she
continued.
</P>
<P>
   There are many kinds of immune cells, including T cells and
different types of white cells. Their combat with disease is
extremely complex and involves long chains of interactions and
responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some vaccines, protection may last a long time, even a
lifetime, but for others vaccines may protect only a short time,''
Dr. Rabinovich said, ``just as some diseases generate an immune
response that effectively protects from a second infection, while
other diseases can get us again and again.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to:
Question(AT)nytimes.com &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
