<SLUG> BC-SCI-SOLID-CARBON-DIOXIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID CO2 HAS EFFECT ON LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(kd) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carbon dioxide, a ubiquitous chemical exhaled by all animals and
incorporated into plants as their main building block, has assumed
a new and astonishing form: a solid that resembles quartz, is
nearly as hard as diamond, and transforms light in intriguing (and
potentially very useful) ways.
</P>
<P>
   By subjecting a small quantity of carbon dioxide gas to
pressures comparable to those deep within giant planets, physicists
at the Lawrence Livermore Laboratory in California have created a
polymer of carbon dioxide, in which chains of carbon dioxide
molecules are strung together to create a bizarre substance never
seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Choong-Shik Yoo and his colleagues at the Livermore
laboratory reported their discovery of CO2 -V, the new form of
carbon dioxide, in the journal Science this month.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists filled a tiny cavity between the opposing tips of
two diamonds with a small amount of carbon dioxide. By squeezing
the diamonds together, they applied immense pressure to the cavity
between them and to the carbon dioxide inside it. With a laser,
they heated the carbon dioxide to about 2,800 degrees Fahrenheit,
and at that point, the carbon dioxide underwent a radical change.
</P>
<P>
   X-ray diffraction and other types of analysis revealed that the
carbon and oxygen atoms in the carbon dioxide had rearranged
themselves in chain-like patterns connected by single carbon-oxygen
bonds, a structure similar to that of quartz, in which silicon and
oxygen atoms are also chained together.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo and his colleagues found that as long as the pressure was
maintained, the new carbon dioxide polymer retained its form, even
when the temperature was lowered to room temperature. The highly
compressed molecular structure resembled that of cubic boron
nitride, the second-hardest of all known substances, exceeded only
by diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that this stuff will prove to be as hard as cubic
boron nitride, and as good a conductor of heat as diamond,'' Yoo
said. ``But the really intriguing thing is the way CO2 -V shifts
the frequency of light.''
</P>
<P>
   CO2 -V, Yoo and his colleagues found, shifts the frequency of
laser light passing through it to its second harmonic, that is, to
a frequency double that of the incoming beam. Crystals that can do
this, yielding a green laser beam from an incident infrared beam,
for example, are important elements in a hydrogen fusion reactor
Livermore has been developing in recent decades. CO2 -V might be an
improvement over existing crystals, if it could be made in bulk
quantities.
</P>
<P>
   The forms and uses of carbon dioxide seem nearly endless. Long
used in solid form as ``dry ice,'' it is an important refrigerant.
Heated and under moderate pressure, it becomes a ``supercritical''
fluid _ a peculiar intermediate between a liquid and a gas _ that
is used to extract caffeine from coffee and to separate chemicals
from each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only just found this CO2 -V, and now we have to begin
looking for alternative ways of making it,'' Yoo said. ``In the
beginning artificial diamonds could be made only with lots of heat
and pressure, but in more recent years, people had found the
carbon-vapor deposition method of making thin films of diamond,
requiring no pressure and little heat. We'll be looking for
something like that with this new carbon dioxide.''
</P>
<P>
   Might CO2 -V be found in nature?
</P>
<P>
   ``One place to look for it,'' Yoo said, ``would be in the rocks
of Mars, where the impacts of meteors could have provided the
necessary pressure. We plan to try some impact experiments with
carbon dioxide ourselves, using Livermore's big gas gun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
