<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO VIES FOR OLYMPIC GOLD IN 2012 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Put aside for now lost Olympic innocence and
negative thoughts about the International Olympic Committee and the
$1.2 million in graft paid to members to award the 2002 Winter
Games to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The instead about the possibilities for the 2012 Summer Games in
the San Francisco Bay area. Great athletes. Great exposure. Bundles
of money dropped into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   This is the message from the Bay Area Sports Organizing
Committee (BASOC). First formed in 1987 with the aim of hosting the
1996 games, its members are reconstituting themselves to submit a
bid one year from now for the games 13 years hence.
</P>
<P>
   For 2012, the Bay area's U.S. competition is Cincinnati, Dallas,
Houston, Los Angeles, New York, Tampa, Fla., and the
Washington-Baltimore area. Seattle recently aborted its candidacy
because it lacked broad business support.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee names its candidate in 2002, and the
IOC makes its worldwide choice in 2005. Larry Baer, chief operating
officer of the San Francisco Giants and a member of BASOC's
executive committee, senses a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either have it or you don't. When you consider the Bay
area's natural beauty, that it is the technology center of the
world, then there is an international case to be made for the Bay
area as host for the games. That, plus we have all the athletic
facilities in place,'' said Baer, adding that the host committee
will stage the games with private funding.
</P>
<P>
   BASOC was founded by Quentin Kopp, a former San Francisco
supervisor and state senator and now a San Mateo County Superior
Court judge. After Atlanta was chosen as the pick for the 1996
games, BASOC was ready to compete for the 2008 games. However, in
1997 the IOC said it would not choose a U.S. city so close in time
to the Atlanta and Salt Lake games. U.S. bidders were moved to
2012.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp has had to step down because of judicial restraints,
leaving the campaign in the hands of the 42-member BASOC. The
committee is comprised of 10 former Olympians living in the region,
three retired athletes and 29 prominent executives and individuals,
including former Secretary of State George Schultz; Bill Walsh, San
Francisco 49ers vice president and general manager; David Pottruck,
president and co-chief executive of Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.; Carl
Pascarella, president of VISA USA; and Baer.
</P>
<P>
   They believe that the Olympic committee scandal, the worst in
the IOC's 105-year history, will be a cathartic experience. They
also believe that reform measures and removal of the corrupt will
restore Olympic luster, and that if the event is properly planned
and presented, many millions of dollars could be injected into the
regional economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City scandal has revealed a culture of rampant
impropriety. In all, some $1.2 million in scholarships, lavish
gifts, cosmetic surgery, Browning rifles and more largess was given
to IOC members _ in exchange for their votes _ by Salt Lake City
bid committee members consumed with winning. The IOC expelled six
of its members last week, and several leaders of the Salt Lake host
group resigned in disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cleaning up process taking place regarding bidding is only
working to our benefit,'' said BASOC executive committee member
George Broder, an executive at Eller Media Co. in Oakland who was a
press agent at the 1984 Los Angeles games. ``It establishes clear
rules and guidelines, and if all the bid cities abide by them, it
will be a very fair process moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles games in 1984 are regarded by the U.S. Olympic
Committee as a model for Olympic success. Private funds produced
the games, and the city used existing athletic facilities for
venues and university dormitories for housing, thus incurring
minimal capital costs. At the end, the hosts had a $230 million
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   IOC reform will help reinvent the Olympics, benefitting the Bay
area, Baer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what is happening with the bidding process will be
comforting to us to the extent the change will be substantive,''
Baer said. ``After that, we're blessed because we have the raw
material that lends itself to an Olympics that is pretty much a
turnkey form of Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever city is selected to host the 2012 games, early, rough
projections imagine a budget of as much as $3 billion, said Mike
Moran, assistant executive director of the USOC in Colorado
Springs, Colo. Baer questions that number.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget number cannot be legitimate until you look at how
many facilities you need to build, if any. What would be $3 billion
for City `X' would be half that for City `Y' if `Y' has a minimum
of facilities to build, and I think we are City `Y,'' Baer said.
</P>
<P>
   Having begun planning in 1987, BASOC believes that with the
exception of a velodrome that will need to be built for cycling,
virtually all games can be accommodated in existing facilities.
It's all in the talk stage, but Baer and others say Bay-area
colleges and universities may be used as venues along with a host
of other facilities _ for example, Pacific Bell Park for baseball,
Golden Gate Park for archery, the San Francisco Bay for yachting _
as well as stadiums in Sacramento and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are that Olympic sponsors are quickly
overcoming their queasiness about the corruption that played out in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co., a sponsor of the games for 100 years, and
McDonald's Corp. last week applauded early signs of IOC reform.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the games present a major marketing opportunity, said
John Britton, a spokesman for Pacific Telesis in San Francisco,
which contributed $20,000 of the $100,000 non-refundable payment
the Bay area was obligated to make to the USOC this year to
demonstrate its seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in supporting large events that benefit the
region, but beyond that ... we would hope to win part of that
business,'' said Britton, whose company used the 1996 Republican
Convention in San Diego to launch its wireless digital telephone
service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1814EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
