<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROAD TO FLORIDA, MAINE AND SYPHILIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interstate 95 runs along the Eastern Seaboard linking rural
Maine to Florida, enabling people and commerce to travel north to
south. But in one area, epidemiologists believe the highway may
also be a pipeline for syphilis.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by researchers at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill and the University of Pittsburgh, who
examined a decade's syphilis reports in North Carolina counties,
the disease appeared more than twice as often in North Carolina
rural counties bordering I-95 as it did in rural counties that did
not border the highway. The results appear in the current issue of
The American Journal of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   For the study, North Carolina's counties were divided into
groups based on population and whether I-95 passes through them.
Eleven counties claim a piece of the highway; 84 do not.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers obtained annual syphilis data from 1985 to 1994
for each county and examined it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of 10 years, the rate among rural I-95 counties
was 38 reported cases for every 100,000 people, compared with 16
cases of syphilis for every 100,000 people in non-I-95 counties.
Though low, the national rate of syphilis surged during the
mid-1980s, reaching a high of 20.3 cases per 100,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers speculated that the high rates of syphilis along
the highway might be related to drug trafficking and distribution.
In the 1980s, cocaine was mainly imported into the eastern United
States through Miami and New York City, both of which lie along
I-95, they wrote. The emergence of a cocaine market may have
increased risky sexual behaviors that lead to syphilis and other
sexually transmitted diseases, owing in part to the exchange of sex
for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Syphilis may have also been spread along the highway through
contact between truck drivers and prostitutes, the researchers
suggested, though there are no data available on the sexual
behavior of American truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rachel A. Royce, an assistant professor of epidemiology at
the University of North Carolina, said: ``While individual
behaviors contribute to the spread of syphilis, the drug trade can
amplify an epidemic and make a community more vulnerable. ``We need
to bring drug treatment and S.T.D. control together to help reduce
the community's vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   ULTRA-SKILLED DOCTORS MORE LIKELY TO BE SUED
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and health officials have long been eager to determine
which doctors are most likely to be sued for malpractice. Some
studies have suggested that bedside manner is the most effective
tool for preventing litigation; other experts have found that
lawsuits do not seem to be linked to actual incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists have added a new piece of data to the puzzle of
medical litigation. According to University of Iowa researchers,
family doctors with the most impressive credentials were most
likely to be sued.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined the malpractice records of family doctors who
practiced in Florida for a year or more from 1971 to 1994 and found
that doctors who possessed better qualifications, like board
certification, residency training and various medical honors, were
more likely to be involved in malpractice suits than their peers
without those credentials and awards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, male doctors and those who practiced in nonurban
areas were more likely to be sued than female doctors and those
practicing in cities.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John W. Ely, associate professor of family medicine at the
University of Iowa, speculated that more experienced, board
certified doctors might be taking care of sicker patients.
``Therefore, they may have worse outcomes and expose themselves to
a higher risk of being sued for those adverse outcomes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Physicians who have poor interpersonal skills are
seen as cold and uncaring and are more likely to be sued for
malpractice. It's possible the physicians with the worst
interpersonal skills had the most experience and knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least,'' Ely continued, ``the study casts doubt on
whether you can use a history of frequent malpractice suits, or
any, as a way to judge a physician's skill.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   HAZY MEMORIES OF CHATS WITH CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   Parents, therapists and police officers who give hearsay
testimony in court about young children's statements may not be
reliable witnesses, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which appears this month in The Journal of
Experimental Psychology, found that although adults usually can
recall the gist of a conversation they have had with a child, they
have difficulty remembering the exact wording or the structure of
the conversation. They are also likely to remember incorrectly
whether information was offered spontaneously by the child or
elicited through questions, and to confuse specific statements they
made themselves with statements made by the child.
</P>
<P>
   Courts often accept adults' reports of conversations with
children as if they are entirely accurate, said the lead author of
the study, Dr. Maggie Bruck, a psychologist who is an associate
professor in the psychiatry department at Johns Hopkins University
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four mothers with preschool-age children took part in the
study. The children spent 20 minutes playing in a separate room
without their mothers present. Afterward, the mothers were
videotaped while interviewing their children about the play
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Half the mothers were told that that they were participating in
a memory experiment and that they should try to remember the
conversation as exactly as possible. The other half were told that
the research concerned mother-child conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, the mothers were tested to see how accurately
they recalled the interview. Even the mothers who were warned ahead
of time omitted large parts of the conversations when they tried to
reconstruct them. They also made significant errors when they were
asked to identify passages in a transcript of the interview that
had been altered by the researchers. They often incorrectly
attributed statements they had made themselves to their children,
and were unaware of how many questions they had asked to elicit
information.
</P>
<P>
   The results, the researchers conclude, ``raise concern about
hearsay testimony that is provided by adults about prior
conversations with young children.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ERICA GOODE
</P>
</TEXT>
