<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow fell on Sunday evening into early Monday across
northern Pennsylvania and central New York as vigorous low pressure
moved through New England into southeast Canada. Up to 14 inches of
snow accumulated in some areas. Meanwhile, on the warm side of the
system, drenching rains and gusty winds lashed southeast New
England.
</P>
<P>
   A much more tranquil day will occur in the Northeast Tuesday as
weak high pressure slides off the Maryland coastline. Abundant
sunshine and light breezes will grace much of central and southern
New England and the Great Lakes states. Clouds and snow showers
will persist, though, in the mountains of northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Weak low pressure will support scattered rain showers from
southern Ohio to the Texas Gulf Coast as it moves quickly eastward.
A few thunderstorms are even possible in east Texas and Louisiana
Tuesday evening as an advancing cold front acts to lift warm, humid
air over the region.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will provide much of the Rocky Mountain states and
desert Southwest with sunshine and mild readings. Some showers and
high elevation snows will fall, however, in northern Nevada and
southern Idaho as a disturbance moves eastward.
</P>
<P>
   An advancing storm system will bring increasing clouds and late
day showers to coastal areas in the Pacific Northwest. Snow will
blanket the Cascades above 4,000 feet, while the valleys of eastern
Washington and Oregon will be mainly dry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it will be generally sunny in southern California
with seasonal temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Syracuse Snow
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse, N.Y., is the only large city in the Northeast whose
annual average snowfall is at least 100 inches. Principally,
lake-effect snows fall throughout the winter as cold air moistened
in transit over the ice-resistant waters of Lake Ontario is lifted
over the rolling hills of upstate New York. Snow also falls from
low-pressure systems moving north up the Hudson River Valley. All
told, the average annual snowfall in Syracuse is just over 110
inches. Monday, nearly 4 inches of new snow fell, bringing the
seasonal total to 97.6 inches. More snow will arrive late this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
