<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, March 23. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Developments in the
last-minute negotiations between Richard Holbrooke and the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic. By Steven Erlanger. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Washington) _ How air attacks would affect U.S.
policy; Western relations with Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
(Scheduled for Page 1)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MANDELA (Waterkloof A.F. Base) _ After nearly five years
in the office of president, Nelson Mandela is still beloved. As he
nears retirement, his popularity crosses all racial lines and is
such an absolute here that even opposition leaders attacking his
party pause to make it clear that they don't mean him, too. In a
recent survey, 43 percent of those asked to rate his performance
gave him a perfect 10. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MIT-DISCRIMINATION (Boston) _ MIT says it discriminated against
female faculty members in terms of pay and other issues for years.
By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE-TELEVISION (New York) In a takeover that will create the
third-largest cable television company in the nation, the Comcast
Corp. said on Monday that it would acquire Media One in a $50
billion merger that has very little to do with television and
everything to do with the race to offer superfast access to the
Internet. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ Pressure mounts for New York City Police
Commissioner Howard Safir to resign as protests continue against
the shooting by police of an unarmed African immigrant. By Robert
D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-PRICES (Undated) _ Even before the OPEC meetings begins,
gasoline prices have been rising, jumping more than 8 cents a
gallon at the pump in the last two weeks. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
</TEXT>
