<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International Soccer Notes: Keegan making moves, raising
eyebrows as interim coach
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Keegan's four-game interim stint as England manager gets
underway Saturday with his club in critical condition for next
year's European Championships. England, still reeling from the
contentious dismissal of Glenn Hoddle last month, needs a win over
visiting Poland (10 a.m., Pay-Per-View) to have a realistic chance
of getting out of its qualifying group. Poland and Sweden lead with
six points apiece, while England has four points.
</P>
<P>
   The national side also is seeking a dose of stability after
Hoddle was let go because of impolitic statements about the
disabled. However, Keegan, named last month to a caretaking role,
won't be around long enough to see it through because of his
commitment to coach second-division London club Fulham.
</P>
<P>
   But Keegan already has turned some heads, naming warring Premier
League stars Robbie Fowler and Graeme Le Saux to the squad. And he
hasn't dismissed reports that his wife is training to become a
faith healer. Hoddle generated media derision last summer for
saying in his World Cup autobiography that his only regret was not
bringing faith healer Eileen Drewery with the club to France.
</P>
<P>
   England: Man Utd. bid questioned
</P>
<P>
   The British Mergers and Monopolies Commission last week ruled
that Rupert Murdoch's BSkyB is not acting in the public interest in
its $1 billion offer to purchase Manchester United. Trade secretary
Stephen Byers will have the final say. The deal has been protested
because of BSkyB holds live coverage rights for the English Premier
League. . . . Tottenham Hotspur, playing a man down, won the
Worthington (English League) Cup final 1-0 over Leicester City on
Sunday. Allan Nielsen scored on a diving header three minutes into
second half stoppage time. Spurs also have qualified for the F.A.
Cup semifinal. . . . Arsenal, trying to repeat its Premier League
and F.A. Cup double, beat Coventry City 2-0 in league action on
Saturday. The Gunners, who have reached the F.A Cup semifinals, are
unbeaten in their last 17 league and cup matches.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Zidane injures knee
</P>
<P>
   Juventus midfielder Zinedine Zidane might miss both Champions'
League semifinal legs against Manchester United after injuring a
knee last week against Olympiakos. . . . Inter Milan manager Mircea
Lucescu resigned after his club was routed 4-0 by lowly Sampdoria
on Sunday. The loss followed Inter's elimination from the
Champions' League. . . . Lazio striker Christian Vieri has a broken
toe that might keep him out of Italy's Euro 2000 qualifier against
Denmark on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Elber out for year
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich, which apparently has the Bundesliga crown all but
wrapped up, will be without top scorer Giovanne Elber for the
Champions' League semifinals with Dynamo Kyiv because of a knee
injury. . . . Germany coach Erich Ribbeck named six Bayern players
to his 22-man squad for two Euro 2000 qualifiers in the coming
week.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Barca pads lead
</P>
<P>
   Dutchman Philip Cocu had two goals as Barcelona extended its
lead in the Primera Division with a 2-0 win over Real Sociedad. . .
. Former Spain coach Javier Clemente appears to be on the verge of
being ousted at his current position in charge of Real Betis. He
and high-priced Brazilian playmaker Denilson have been at odds all
season.
</P>
<P>
   MLS: Fire hot in opener
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Chicago Fire opened the season Saturday with
a 3-1 win over San Jose. The Fire prevailed without forward Roman
Kosecki, who is suspended for two more games for allegedly spitting
on a referee during an exhibition. . . . Former D.C. United and
U.S. captain John Harkes has left England's Nottingham Forest and
has reported to the New England Revolution, which received him in a
trade last month. . . . Former MLS deputy commissioner Sunil
Gulati, ousted after re-signing Tab Ramos to the MetroStars without
the team's permission, has been named a consultant to the league.
Terms of his new duties were not specified.
</P>
<P>
   Around the globe
</P>
<P>
   After nearly five years of fighting with former manager Daniel
Passarella, Argentine midfielder Fernando Redondo has been recalled
to the national team. Redondo, the Real Madrid regular, will play
in a friendly next week against the Netherlands. He missed the
World Cup last year for defying Passarella's orders to cut his long
hair. Passarella also banned homosexuals and players with earrings.
. . . The Confederation of African Football has removed Zimbabwe as
hosts of next year's African Nations' Cup because of concerns about
playing facilities. The 16-country event will be played in Nigeria
and Ghana instead.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
