<P>
   SCHOOL-FUNDING _ WASHINGTON - Congress on Monday begins debate
on the budget, with Democrats and Republicans each claiming to
favor more spending than the other on elementary and secondary
education. But many of their differences are built on clever
arithmetic, rather than the actual amount of money that would reach
real schools in the real world. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CORDES _ WASHINGTON _ An Austin businessman faces a $3.5
million federal tax bill related to a business he says he doesn't
own. John J. Cordes, a construction consultant, and his wife, Sue,
have filed a petition asking the U.S. Tax Court here to overturn an
Internal Revenue Service ruling that he received $6.96 million in
benefits from the Cordes Jeep-Eagle dealership owned by his father
in Lawton, Okla. (Moskal, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-PAINTING _ JASPER, Texas _ About seven months after its
unveiling at Lamar University, a portrait commemorating Jasper
dragging death victim James Byrd Jr. will go on the auction block.
(Lufkin Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TDNA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ After speaking to the Texas Daily
Newspaper Association, Gov. George W. Bush addresses a variety of
topics and shows that he is honing an ability to waffle on just
about everything. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   LEGIS-BRITE _ ATLANTA _ House spends an hour today debating
seemingly innoucuous resolution urging school boards to display
writings and documents like the declaration of independence, etc.
Measure amended twice _ to add African Americanand Native American
heritage provisions. Debate deteriorated from there. Bob Holmes
wanted a more specific amendment to particular writings by MLK ,
Frederick Douglass, etc. Instead, almost all the white members
voted to table the bill. Afterward, Rep. Scott Tolbert, the
sponsor, said it was ``an American'' idea that had been ruined by
``stupid'' intentions. (Walston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
