<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-TV-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-22 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR AFTERMATH: AND THE WINNER IS NOT ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geena Davis, the host of ABC's first-ever Oscar pre-show, asked
Helen Hunt about having won an Academy Award. ``Did you have the
same experience I did, that when they called your name you went,
like, out of body?'' she asked, sounding out of her body at that
very moment, not to mention out of her mind. What possessed her to
take this inane job, in which she stood on a set inside the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion looking at a huge monitor that showed the red
carpet arrivals outside? Reading robotically from a teleprompter,
she said, ``It's so much fun to catch our first glimpse of the
stars as they arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure. She must have loved the tacit admission that she was
not out there being interviewed with all the nominees. She must
have been lured by the humongous television audience the Academy
Awards and its satellite shows usually draw, no matter how tiresome
or long the ceremony (a record-breaking four hours this year). As
the pre-show pointed out, this year's television broadcast would be
seen in 117 countries. As it did not point out, ABC got $1 million
for a 30-second commercial, for the pre-show as well as the
ceremony. And no one could have guessed going in that the ratings
would take an unexpected but well-deserved tumble. (Despite being
moved to Sunday from Monday the broadcast's ratings were down at
least 10 percent from last year.)
</P>
<P>
   Bloated self-importance is an Oscar television tradition, and
this year viewers got nothing less as ABC turned the Academy Awards
into more of a made-for-television event than ever. Ms. Davis'
ill-conceived half-hour, called ``Sunday at the Oscars,'' was part
of a package intended to milk every last commercial dollar from an
evening that began with the traditional Barbara Walters special
(shown after the awards on the West Coast), and went on with the
Davis show. After the ceremony, there was an hourlong Oscar episode
of ``Politically Incorrect.'' All of it displayed the sincerity
that makes the Oscar-watching experience predictable and unique:
television provides laughable solemnity and viewers sit around
making up their own jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis show was so awkward, though, with the host alternately
giddy and stiff, that it wasn't even funny. It blatantly tried to
steal the attention other pre-shows have gotten in recent years,
notably Joan Rivers' talked-about but increasingly mean-spirited
show on the E! channel. This past weekend's ``Saturday Night Live''
shrewdly parodied it by having Ms. Rivers turn into a shrieking
vampire as she interviewed arriving stars. The Rivers show is known
for hyping fashion designers by asking stars, ``Who are you
wearing?'' as if viewers care. In truth, viewers live with the
slender hope that when a nominee is asked that other standard
question, ``How are you feeling?'' someone will finally break down
and admit, ``I feel rotten: I'm going to lose!''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Moret of CNN was borrowed to do the red carpet interviews
during ABC's pre-show. (Other channels were not allowed to
broadcast live during that half-hour.) He actually said, ``Oh,
look, here's Roberto Benigni,'' as if it were a surprise when the
actor walked before the cameras. ``Thank you, Jeem,'' Benigni said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Barbara Walters Special'' was a more enjoyable Rorschach
test. You could take it seriously if you liked; or you could
observe that Celine Dion's house featured gilt-and-brocade chairs
and a marble floor under a long colonnade. What better prelude to
the Oscars than this silent testament to tacky excess? A
white-haired Elizabeth Taylor, who looked as if she had borrowed
one of Phyllis Diller's wigs, said her hair had ``grown in
platinum'' after surgery for a brain tumor. Apparently in Hollywood
platinum blond is considered a naturally occurring color.
</P>
<P>
   During the first commercial break in the Walters special, you
could have flipped to E! and seen Gwyneth Paltrow and Ian McKellen
being interviewed as they arrived. During the second commercial
break you could have flipped to CNN and seen Gwyneth Paltrow and
Ian McKellen being interviewed as they were still arriving.
</P>
<P>
   The awards ceremony itself was stuffed with all the elements
viewers have come to expect: the songs no one has ever heard, the
dance number that made no sense (a flamenco to celebrate the
Italian World War II film ``Life Is Beautiful''), and, this year,
so many obituary tributes the show threatened to become the
all-dead-stars Oscars. But however much viewers carp, high ratings
in the past gave the producers no motive to change. If they had
wanted something younger, hipper and livelier they would have hired
Conan O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   It has also become a tradition for the host to do a terrific
opening and for the show to move steadily downhill. Whoopi Goldberg
made her hilarious entrance dressed as Elizabeth I, in
Kabuki-white-face makeup, announcing, ``I am the African queen.''
She was easy to take, despite an overload of weak double-entendre
jokes. It wasn't her fault that as the evening dragged on you could
count the truly exciting moments. A highlight was Benigni, going up
to accept his award for best foreign film for ``Life Is Beautiful''
by standing on the top of his seat, climbing over Billy Bob
Thornton's head and literally hopping up the steps. Unlike most of
Hollywood, he realized that this was a night that demanded a
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious moment, the controversial lifetime achievement
award to Elia Kazan, who informed on friends during the McCarthy
years, was anti-climactic and notable for its swiftness as the
camera swept the audience to see who was standing (Warren Beatty)
and who was sitting with folded arms in protest (Nick Nolte).
</P>
<P>
   In the awards' aftermath, two scenes realistically captured what
the Oscars mean to viewers. The otherwise flaccid ``Politically
Incorrect'' began by introducing its so-called ``special
correspondents,'' Bob Odenkirk and David Cross of the sharp HBO
satire ``Mr. Show.'' Odenkirk arrived wearing a long red dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you wearing?'' asked the host, Bill Maher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vera Wang,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning on ``Today,'' Jon Stewart, Tracey Ullman and
Rosie O'Donnell sat around dishing the show like regular viewers,
trashing Celine Dion's white fedora and the flamenco dancer's
flabby body. (``Maybe he looks good in Madrid,'' Ms. Ullman said).
In the end, putting Hollywood solemnity in its place is what
watching the Oscars is all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
