<HEADLINE>
DEBATING AFFIRMATIVE ACTION BUT KEEPING IT CORDIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass.)  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The debate over affirmative action has been going on so long
that it has become a ritual. Both sides fall into incantations,
formulas and slogans to stand for worn arguments. Fresh ideas are
in short supply as the debaters concentrate on phrases with enough
emotional punch to move voters in the referendums that have become
the focus of national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the best efforts of the role-playing panelists on
``Beyond Black and White: Affirmative Action in America,'' Tuesday
night's ``Fred Friendly Seminar'' remains stuck largely in
long-held positions.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are those led by Ward Connerly, the University of
California regent hailed as the father of his state's Proposition
209 to do away with racial, ethnic and sex preferences in public
education, employment and contracting. His successful band holds
that race-conscious rules for, say, admission to college, offend
the Constitution, stir resentment among groups that do not receive
special treatment and stamp beneficiaries with the stigma of not
being able to make it on their own.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of affirmative action point out that many college
applicants, from athletes to offspring of alumni, are granted
``plus factors,'' and that ignoring the racial factor is
unrealistic and unfair. Ann F. Lewis, the White House
communications director, warns that blindness to race is a step
toward resegregation.
</P>
<P>
   And there are positions somewhere between the antis and the
pros. Tamar Jacoby, a writer who has made a specialty of looking
into the impact of affirmative action programs, reports that racial
preferences are having ``a poisonous effect'' on race relations.
She calls on government to help all the poor instead of ``making a
fetish of people's skins.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Edley Jr., a Harvard Law School professor who has
worked on the perennially hot subject for the Clinton White House,
comes down in favor of using race as a factor in student selection
but ``only very carefully.'' Whether that gets the nation much
``beyond black and white'' is itself open to argument.
</P>
<P>
   The hour's ringmaster of this and other ``Fred Friendly
Seminars,'' Charles J. Ogletree of the Harvard Law School, keeps
the conversation civil and even playful as the participants speak
as parents, spouses, college applicants and members of minority
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are not able to squeeze much juice out of a
much-squeezed subject, Tuesday night's model of civility is no mean
accomplishment given the passions still roiling around the issue. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `BEYOND BLACK AND WHITE: AFFIRMATIVE ACTION IN AMERICA'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kilberg, executive producer; Martha J.H. Elliott, senior
producer; Joan I. Greco, senior writer. For the Fred Friendly
Seminars: Barbara Margolis, executive director; Ruth Friendly,
senior editorial adviser. Charles Ogletree, moderator. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
