<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ISSUES-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP FRONT-RUNNER GEORGE W. BUSH HAVING IT BOTH WAYS ON KEY ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When a nationally renowned opponent of
affirmative action came to Texas recently, he cited an important
ally in the campaign to end race-based contracting policies in
state government: Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, state Sen. Rodney Ellis _ a Houston Democrat
and ardent backer of affirmative action _ cited his own, equally
important ally in keeping those programs: Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Which one is right?
</P>
<P>
   It depends on whom you ask, but one thing is clear: On
affirmative action, abortion and other potentially explosive social
issues, Bush has developed an uncanny ability to have it both ways,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Where does he stand on the proposal to provide state-financed
health insurance for children whose parents earn $33,000 a year or
less (for a family of four) _ a proposal many conservatives oppose?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take a definite position at the appropriate time,'' Bush
says.
</P>
<P>
   What about increased penalties for ``hate crimes''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush believes all violent crimes are crimes of hate,''
says spokeswoman Linda Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   A gay adoption ban?
</P>
<P>
   Bush hasn't reviewed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Far from costing him politically, the approach that some have
called ``evasive'' and ``ambiguous,'' has so far sold exceptionally
well. His approval ratings at home are at historic highs, winning
him accolades as a pragmatic, caring politician who avoids divisive
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody so blessed politically,'' said Allan
Saxe, a political analyst at the University of Texas at Arlington.
``It is the Teflon effect all over again. Nothing sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Saxe said Bush benefits not only from a docile Legislature that
wants to make the likely White House contender look good on
national television, but also from a high-rolling economy that has
left voters feeling complacent.
</P>
<P>
   Just how long the honeymoon will last is uncertain, however,
particularly as other presidential hopefuls take aim at the
Republican front-runner. A day after Bush officially announced that
he would explore a White House bid, the governor was already taking
hits for his ``ambiguous'' stands on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   James Dobson, head of the media ministry Focus on the Family and
a leading voice of Christian conservatives, blasted Bush for saying
America is ``not ready to ban abortions'' even if he would like to
do so himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give us double-talk,'' Dobson said in a recent telephone
news conference. ``We don't know what he believes.''
</P>
<P>
   `AFFIRMATIVE ACCESS': The controversy over Bush's stand on
abortion illustrates the political danger of stating specifically
what you believe: somebody won't like it. On the other hand, taking
positions on controversial issues is a staple of electoral
politics.
</P>
<P>
   There is the issue of timing. Bush has made it clear that he
will not be laying out any detailed national campaign agenda before
the legislative session ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many state issues _ including those with national
implications _ that Bush has long sidestepped, either by avoiding a
direct answer, delaying one until a final plan emerges or sticking
to a well-crafted slogan.
</P>
<P>
   One example is Bush's position on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has said he is against ``quotas'' and
``set-asides,'' his position on the state's affirmative action
program is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was highlighted earlier this month when Ward Connerly,
the renowned anti-affirmative action activist from California,
brought his message to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly came to lend his support to a bill, sponsored by a
Republican lawmaker from Houston, that would wipe out the state's
Historically Underutilized Business program. The HUB law is
designed to increase women and minorities' participation in state
contracting.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
