r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NETWORKS-2TAKES-SF     03-22 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NETWORKS-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMBLING INTO OBLIVION: 10 WAYS NETWORKS ARE ASSISTING IN
THEIR  OWN DEMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By dribs, by drabs, by hook and by crook, cable TV channels are
luring viewers from the seemingly helpless broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   The old networks, you might say, find themselves on the bloody
end of the course of natural events, their comfortable oligopoly at
an end.
</P>
<P>
   All true. But some smart historian in the future might conclude
that the networks died in part from their own negligence.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the big networks are often their own worst enemies.
With an arrogance and stubbornness stemming from their years atop
the TV heap, they are now contributors to their own decline.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 ways in which the networks hurt themselves:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Clutter. &LR;  Until the U.S. Justice Department intervened
during the Carter administration, the networks used to cooperate to
limit the minutes devoted to commercials, promotion spots and other
non-program material, through the code of the National Association
of Broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   Now the commercial load can seem overwhelming to viewers, and
it's self-defeating to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   A recent example was the NBC movie ``Alice in Wonderland'' in
February. Some viewers say they tuned out in frustration,
presumably lowering the show's ratings. Others were so angry that
they began counting commercials and promos, which by several
accounts consumed about a third of the program's three-hour time
period.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. Crudity. &LR;  The first words of the 1990 fall season on CBS _
words spoken by a 6-year-old on the sitcom ``Uncle Buck'' _ were,
``You suck.'' The episode concluded with the same girl saying of
her 16-year-old sister, ``Ignore her. She's ovulating.''
</P>
<P>
   It was something of a milestone for prime-time TV. The language
was controversial in 1990 and yet seems relatively mild compared
with what can be heard today.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since ``Uncle Buck,'' the networks have trimmed
their standards and practices departments and grown more lenient
toward writers and producers who want to shock or to ``stretch the
envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no accurate measure of the effect. But clearly a
segment of the prospective audience is now warier of network
programs. There has even been a network, PAX TV, founded on the
promise to eschew bad language, sexual situations and gratuitous
violence.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. Repeats and summer blackouts.  &LR; When did ``all new'' become a
breathless selling point for routine episodes of network shows?
About the time that ``all new'' episodes seemed to become a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   Most commonly, program producers provide the networks with 22
new episodes a year. In TV's earlier days, the number was more like
39. The practice of clustering new episodes in sweeps months tends
to exaggerate their seeming dearth, further frustrating viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, network executives annually bemoan the lack of original
programming during the summer. And annually do nothing about it.
The networks need summer reruns because the second airing is
typically when the network can turn a profit on the license fee it
paid to a program's owner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. Demographic tyranny. &LR;  Struggling to deliver the ``right''
viewers to advertisers, the networks harm themselves by
constricting their prospective audience.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers 18 to 49 are in television's broadest band of
desirability. CBS focuses on a slightly older demographic, and the
WB network targets teenagers. But television's prime demographic is
18 to 49, and programs are tailored to appeal to that audience.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that most Americans don't fall within those
brackets. According to U.S. census figures, 52 percent of the
national population is either younger than 18 or older than 49.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, because TV kowtows to advertisers, America's most
pervasive mass medium effectively ignores most of the population.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't even take into account the networks' apparent
reluctance to program for blacks, Latinos, Asian Americans and
other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. Schedule changes. &LR;  Where can you find your favorite show
this week? Chances are, it's not the same time slot where the show
was last week.
</P>
<P>
   When the TV universe was smaller and more manageable, it was
easier for viewers to keep track of programs. Now you need a
compass and flares.
</P>
<P>
   Shows appear willy-nilly ``at a special time'' or ``on a new
night.'' Or premiere in one time period and then promptly move to
another. A move can save a failing show, but more often it seems to
damage shows. Witness NBC's ``3rd Rock From the Sun,'' which has
had five time slots in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Many series also spend more time in and out of ``hiatus'' than
petty thieves spend in and out of jail. TV critics hear it
constantly from readers: Where is ``NYPD Blue,'' or ``Promised
Land,'' or ``Sports Night''? When, if ever, will a favorite show be
back on the air?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6. Cheapness and loss of glamour. &LR;  It's an intangible, but the
networks seem to have shed much of their gloss in the 1990s. The
grubbiness of the business is now on plain view to the public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
