<HEADER>
A9994 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      03-22 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR  
   
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, March 23. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
GRAND CANYON-GOOF (Grand Canyon, Ariz.) - So, there still haven't
been 5 million people visit the Grand Canyon in any year after all.
Grand Canyon National Park officials have admitted they goofed. It
turns out, park rangers at the eastern entrance to the park were
counting cars, coming and going. Park visitation has actually
remained relatively stagnant for the last several years, hovering
between 4.5 million and 4.9 million since visitation first topped
the 4 million mark in 1992. The revelation that park visitors
hasn't topped 5 million put a different light on a celebration 15
months ago. In December 1997, an Illinois man, his wife, niece and
two nephews from Phoenix, were showered with gifts and had their
pictures taken with National Park Service officials when they were
declared to be the 5 millionth-plus visitors. By STEVE YOZWIAK.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AMWEST-DEAL (Phoenix) - America West Airlines and flight attendants
are still going over the $80 million tenative contract and expect
to release details on Wednesday. Meanwhile, analysts are responding
to the settlement, saying the company lost momentum in March, but
did well enough that first-quarters earnings should be on target.
By PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MANAGEDCARE (Phoenix) - With eyes that sparkle as much as her sense
of humor, the only time Jean Anderson is anyone's dummy is when
she's at the bridge table. While she takes a break as her partner
rifles through their hands looking for tricks, the Scottsdale,
Ariz., senior says she's figured it out that it's cheaper for her
to get her Medicare through managed care. But starting in January,
Anderson, her card-playing cronies at the Scottsdale Senior Center
and thousands of other Valley seniors will be unknowing
participants in a new game: how to cut Medicare costs. Under a
federal plan, Maricopa county will be a part of a controversial
experiment to see if the government can pay HMOs less to insure
seniors like Anderson. The stakes are high: The Health Care
Financing Administration says Medicare must be change or face
bankruptcy; insurers say any changes will force them to increase
premiums or cut benefits. With HMOs. By JODIE SNYDER. Story will
move in the ``A'' catetory. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HMOS (Washington) - With letters, phone calls and a Web site, a
group of Arizona health maintenance organizations is furiously
lobbying Arizona's Congressmen to stop a federal experiment in
free-market medical economics. The government would like the HMOs
to submit competitive bids if they want to keep Medicare's
business, and the health organizations have targeted Arizona's
federal lawmakers to stop it, telling them that the demonstration
project, set to begin next year in Phoenix, could have a
``staggering impact'' on thousands of Medicare beneficiaries in the
state. The health-plan executives are asking the Congress members
to `take whatever action is needed to stop its implementation.''
With MANAGEDCARE. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Sunday night at the Oscars, evil was
made benign and shamelessness was elevated to high art. The old
man, Elia Kazan, was presented with an honorary Academy Award for
lifetime achievement and said, ``I thank you very much. I really
like to hear that and I want to thank the Academy for its courage,
generosity.'' If only he'd demonstrated a little of those same
traits _ courage and generosity _ when he appeared before the House
Un-American Activities Committee on Apr. 10. 1952. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO REVIEW (Phoenix) - Oldsmobile's import fighter just got some
new ammunition. For '99, Intrigue boasts a potent V-6 engine that
improves power and performance. And, supposedly, it's nearly
maintenance-free. Intrigue needs an ego boost after more than two
years of going up against import heavyweights Honda Accord and
Toyota Camry. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUINTANA-FOOD (Ajijic, Mexico) - Cooking at a new culinary school
with guest chef Patricia Quintana, the break-out Mexican cooking
teacher and author. With RECIPES and QUINTANA-TIPS. By JUDY WALKER.
Stories moved in the ``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOTANICAL-ARIZONA (Phoenix) - With the Arizona desert promising a
puny display this spring, out-of-town visitors might want to tour
the Desert Botanical Garden instead, where diligent watering has
made the landscape bloom gloriously. By BARBARA YOST. Story moved
in the ``T'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GLASS-MUSIC _ (Phoenix) - Philip Glass may be one of the best known
names in contemporary classical music, but where does he place
himself among composers at the end of the century? An interview
with Glass posits some surprising answers. By KENNETH LAFAVE. Story
moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COMPUTER-COLUMMN (Phoenix) - Back in February, we ran a list of
your favorite Web sites for 1998. If you missed the list, it can
still be found at
www.azcentral.com/computing/viewpoint/0215hoyewebsites.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of creating such a list proved so popular with readers,
that I continued to receive recommendations long after the
submission deadline. I've decided to revisit the topic by
publishing a sort of addendum to our original list. By DAVID HOYE.
Story moved in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
