<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9995 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NETWORKS-2NDTAKE-S     03-22 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NETWORKS-2NDTAKE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the public.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It might be a urinating secretary in Fox's ``Busted on the Job
III,'' or ``Pro Wrestling's Greatest Secrets Exposed'' on NBC. But
the public knows chintz when it sees it and recognizes the cynicism
of tacky, inexpensive ``specials'' designed to grab an easy rating.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the proliferation of newsmagazines, especially the
shoddier examples of the genre, have rubbed the sheen from TV.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the jewels in the network crowns are made of
paste.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7. Shortchanging viewers. &LR;  The networks can score early points
by promising more than they deliver. In 1996, for example, NBC's
``Pandora's Clock'' was a wretched TV movie gussied up for the
November sweeps and presented as a special event. The ruse worked.
</P>
<P>
   But as the network kept trying to defraud the public with more
sows' ears, the ratings declined. Same with NBC's saturation
campaigns for perpetual ``must see'' episodes of its regular
series.
</P>
<P>
   The networks seem to have lost respect for their own viewers.
They act accordingly, and inevitably the public becomes estranged
from the networks.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake of selling the public short extends far beyond
inflated promotional claims. It touches on every other item on this
list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8. Lack of originality. &LR;  The networks are repeating themselves.
Even some of the top network executives now acknowledge that TV
seems old and tired.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar culprits are the handful of TV producers _ start
with Aaron Spelling _ who dominate the airwaves because they've had
hits in the past and can make and deliver ``product.''
</P>
<P>
   But because Spelling can produce untold hours of television
programming, should he? The answer will be yes, until the networks
address the problem of too few producers making too many
predictable shows.
</P>
<P>
   TV acting is no worse than it ever was. It's probably better
than two decades ago. The practical problem the TV industry faces
is a shortage of talented writers.
</P>
<P>
   One would think, with their corporate lives at stake, the
networks would devise effective programs to seek out, train and
nurture new writing and producing talent. Isn't that what most
smart corporations do?
</P>
<P>
   Not the networks, which are the perfect corporate models of
ostriches.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9. Impatience. &LR;  The sagas of ``Cagney &AMP; Lacey,'' ``Hill Street
Blues,'' ``Cheers,'' ``Seinfeld'' and other slow-developing hits
are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   But as usual, the networks haven't taken the lessons to heart.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there are times when the data are incontrovertible,
and no amount of loving attention from a network can save a good
show with bad ratings.
</P>
<P>
   As the networks have grown desperate to stanch their bleeding,
though, they've quickened the hook. Promising shows are abandoned
for dead when they fail to make a fast Nielsen splash.
</P>
<P>
   Early cancellations don't just rob the networks of possible
hits; they also disillusion viewers who form attachments to those
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The networks impart the wrong message to the public. The message
is: Don't invest your emotions in this show; after all, it'll
probably be yanked from the air unceremoniously and killed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10. Bad communications. &LR;  Odd that companies in the
communications business are so often among the worst communicators
on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The networks' customers are advertisers. They may treat them
royally _ who knows? _ but they've fallen far out of touch with the
public. And without the public, the advertisers eventually will
wave goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   The networks can never be accused of interactivity. In 50 years,
they've established no effective two-way pipeline between
themselves and their viewers, though better communications could
probably alleviate much of the public's disenchantment.
</P>
<P>
   Press relations would seem to be one solution, however
imperfect, for the networks. But those too have deteriorated in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   These are companies that operate capriciously, frustrate their
viewers, narrow their base, cling to the familiar and communicate
poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Killed by cable? Sure, that's where the viewers have gone,
mostly. But cable might not be much more than helpful participants
in an assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
