<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ISSUES-2ndTake-T     03-22 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ISSUES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
AUSTIN, Texas: state contracting. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing a questionnaire in which the governor expressed
opposition to race-based affirmative action programs intended to
level the playing field among the races, Connerly claimed that Bush
backed the proposed ban on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But before Connerly even left town, Ellis, the state senator and
affirmative action supporter, issued a statement praising Bush's
stand, ``Thankfully, Governor Bush understands the importance of
inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, neither Bush nor his staff would say whether Bush
supports the state's Historically Underutilized Business program,
or whether he is for or against the efforts to eliminate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for `affirmative access.' I think the state ought to do
everything in its power to provide equal opportunity for all
citizens,'' Bush said at a recent news conference. ``I think quotas
pit one group of people against the other.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   `EVERYBODY'S HAPPY': Whether the state's HUB program involves
``quotas'' is central to the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The General Services Commission, composed of Bush appointees,
drafts rules that say agencies are to make a ``good faith effort''
to award a certain percentage of state contracts to women and
minorities. The percentages vary depending on the type of service
provided.
</P>
<P>
   For opponents like Connerly, those are quotas, identical to the
ones that have been successfully challenged in courts elsewhere.
For supporters, they're not quotas because the law says agencies
simply must try to meet the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, the program is not in danger of disappearing on
Bush's watch, according to Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've encouraged him to be supportive of it, and if not, to not
put himself in a position in which he would be hands-on trying to
kill it,'' Ellis said. ``To my knowledge, he has never tried to
pass a bill or kill a bill that involved affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the governor of the state of Texas doesn't get
involved in my business, I try not to get involved in his business,
and everybody seems to be happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HOMOSEXUAL ISSUES: Bush has also taken a cautious approach on
gay issues. While he has won praise for rebuking the
``name-calling'' and divisive rhetoric associated with some
anti-gay activists, his precise views on legislation addressing gay
issues are murky.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he opposes same-sex marriages: ``Marriage is
sanctified by the Almighty and it's between a man and a woman,'' he
told The Associated Press. He also has said he believes that
adoptions are best left to heterosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has not taken a position on bills that would place a
ban on gay marriages and adoptions _ measures sponsored by Rep.
Warren Chisum, R-Pampa. Chisum said he has no reason to think that
Bush is against the bills, but he said he isn't sure whether the
governor is for them, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has taken a similar, noncommittal position on proposed hate
crimes legislation, which would increase penalties for crimes
motivated by bigotry _ including those against gays. Many
conservatives oppose the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Hardy-Garcia, director of the Lesbian Gay Rights Lobby of
Texas, said Bush's lack of a definitive stand on the hate crimes
bill was ``pretty hard to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear all this talk about tolerance, and I don't see much of
it,'' she said. ``Because he's not saying we should all burn in
hell, people are hopeful he's tolerant. ... I think you need to do
more than just say you're tolerant.''
</P>
<P>
   BUZZWORDS WORK: Despite the complaints about Bush's reticence to
precisely state his positions, analysts say it's a politically
shrewd tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clarity on the issues is not exactly a criterion for winning
the presidency,'' said Allan Lichtman, a presidential historian at
American University. ``You can get away with it. You can use
buzzwords.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
