<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERCROOKS-HNS &LR;      03-22 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERCROOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING EXPOSES CONCERNS ABOUT STOCK FRAUD ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kristin Morris works for a small Virginia company
that sells computer equipment to the federal government and is
familiar with the Internet. Despite her background, Morris told a
Senate panel Monday that she fell victim to stock-fraud scheme over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has provided a new tool for stock schemes and its
fast-moving technology is making the scams more widespread and
making it harder for state and federal authorities to keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that the Internet appears to provide
cybercrooks with ... avenues for committing financial fraud,'' said
Sen. Susan M. Collins, R-Maine, chairwoman of the Senate Permanent
Subcommittee on Investigations, which held a hearing on Internet
stock fraud issues.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, 34, said she was losing money on a utility stock she
owned and began surfing the Internet in 1997 in an attempt to find
a new stock that was less ``conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said she ran across a site that listed small companies
that were about ready to issue stock through initial public
offerings, and was attracted to a California company that claimed
it was manufacturing new products that would allow people to use
their televisions rather than a computer to access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Morris printed out the information about the company that was
provided on the Internet and said the description of the products,
like a special keyboard that would be hooked up to the television,
were very detailed. She then called a long-distance operator to
verify the phone number she was given on the Internet and called
the company to make sure it really existed. After talking to a
company official about the new products, Morris said she sent
$1,000 for shares of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Morris never received a stock certificate, but several months
later she received a letter from the California Attorney General's
Office telling her that the company official was arrested for
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who has not recovered the $1,000, considers herself
lucky that the person who stole her money is now sitting in jail
because many people conducting stock-fraud schemes over the
Internet have yet to be caught.
</P>
<P>
   While federal and state law enforcement authorities have
recently established programs to combat Internet securities fraud,
the government's General Accounting Office said the rapid growth of
Internet stock scams ``could limit the ability of these programs to
protect investors.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the GAO, most securities fraud involves companies
offering stocks that trade at less than $5 per share and often
trade for $.50 or less _ so-called microcap or penny stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Many cases of securities fraud involve ``pump and dump'' schemes
where promoters push up a stock's price by making false claims
about the company, attracting new investors and raising the stock's
price. The con artists then sell their own shares to cash in on the
artificially high price, causing other investors to lose money
after the price falls. Such schemes were previously limited to
phone and mail solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gardner, the founder of The Motley Fool, an on-line firm
that provides investment advice, told the Senate panel that he
advises people to stay away from microcap and penny stocks. He said
about 75 percent of companies that issue stock at $5 or less
generally fail within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hillman, an associate director at the General Accounting
Office, said there are no comprehensive statistics available on the
incidence of securities fraud committed over the Internet but said
that federal and state securities officials call it ``an emerging
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also no firm statistics on how much money investors
have lost to Internet stock scams, but the GAO said, state
regulators have reported losses ranging from $18,000 to more than
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 7.5 million Americans buy and sell stocks over the
Internet and that number is expected to grow to 18 million by 2002.
Most on-line investors use a reputable Internet brokerage service
to buy and sell stocks. Internet stock scams typically involve
stocks that are directly purchased by an investor.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission reports that it receives
about 200 to 300 electronic-mail complaints daily about potential
Internet fraud, up from 10 to 15 daily complaints in 1997. Since
1995 the agency has opened 66 investigations into Internet stock
fraud cases and has concluded 32 of them.
</P>
<P>
   While no legislation is pending to help state and federal
investigators combat Internet securities fraud, Collins said she
hoped the panel's hearings would be an effective means for
educating investors about the risks of buying unknown stocks over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said the panel would continue to
examine Internet fraud and could develop legislation that could,
for example, make it easier for authorities in one state to
investigate Internet fraud schemes that are conducted in other
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
