<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-22 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONORARY BUT NOT HONORABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sunday night at the Oscars, evil was made benign and
shamelessness was elevated to high art.
</P>
<P>
   The old man, Elia Kazan, was escorted onto the stage by director
Martin Scorsese and actor Robert De Niro, where he was presented
with an honorary Academy Award for lifetime achievement.
</P>
<P>
   There was applause from some, silence from others, and Kazan
said, ``I thank you very much. I really like to hear that and I
want to thank the Academy for its courage, generosity.''
</P>
<P>
   If only he'd demonstrated a little of those same traits _
courage and generosity _ when he appeared before the House
Un-American Activities Committee on Apr. 10. 1952.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfires of the Communist witch hunts were consuming the
careers of hundreds of writers and actors and directors.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 would spend time in jail, including Ring Lardner Jr.
and Dalton Trumbo.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, Kazan, like many others, was a member of the
Communist Party. Mostly, they were liberals in a hurry. The
Communists were among the few actively speaking out against Hitler
in those days. They also supported minority voting rights and the
rights of labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, however, all that had changed.
</P>
<P>
   People were being persecuted for ideas they'd held 20 years
earlier. Lives ere being ruined. Careers ended.
</P>
<P>
   All a person had to do in order to save himself, was name names.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Kazan did.
</P>
<P>
   He was the best known director on Broadway in addition to
working in Hollywood, and he didn't want to limit his
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   So, he limited the opportunities of others.
</P>
<P>
   He ratted out his friends.
</P>
<P>
   And he went on to direct ``On the Waterfront'' and ``Viva
Zapata'' and ``Baby Doll'' and ``A Face in the Crowd'' and
``Splendor in the Grass.''
</P>
<P>
   He won two Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   He had a fabulous career, for which the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences decided to honor him, not caring that the
top of the heap on which Kazan stood was made of ravaged lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although you and I might feel he made a mistake,'' Kazan
supporter Warren Beatty said, ``neither you nor I were around in
that period.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true.
</P>
<P>
   Before judging Kazan we should ask ourselves what we would do to
keep a job, or better yet, what we'd tell our children to do.
</P>
<P>
   Would we tell them it's acceptable to sacrifice innocent friends
to protect themselves?
</P>
<P>
   Would we tell them people should be punished for their opinions?
Blackballed for their beliefs? Destroyed because of their
convictions?
</P>
<P>
   Only a month after Kazan played stool pigeon, the writer Lillian
Hellman went before the same committee and said, ``To hurt innocent
people whom I knew many years ago in order to save myself is, to
me, inhumane and indecent and dishonorable. I cannot and will not
cut my conscience to fit this year's fashions.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``On the Waterfront,'' the hero, Marlon Brando, decides to
inform on the evil men who control dock workers.
</P>
<P>
   The people Kazan informed on weren't evil, however. They weren't
dangerous. They were only sacrificial lambs to be slaughtered on
the altar of politics.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Academy Awards ceremony Sunday night none of that
seemed to matter. Kazan was old and frail. De Niro kissed him on
the head and Kazan ended his short speech by saying, ``I think I
can just slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   As if all you must to to win an argument in America is live long
enough to get in the last word.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were blacklisted should have gotten the honorary
Oscars, not Kazan. Kazan got to make his movies. He got to live his
life.
</P>
<P>
   He got to say and do exactly what he wanted to say and do _
including Sunday night _ without ever getting what he deserved. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
