<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-FUNDING-0323-C     03-22 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-FUNDING-0323-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP WANTS TO OUTSPEND CLINTON ON K-12 EDUCATION
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Congress today (Tuesday) begins its floor battle
over next year's federal budget with Republicans proposing to spend
more than President Clinton suggested on elementary and secondary
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite different from a couple of years ago when we were
fighting for our lives,'' Secretary of Education Richard Riley
marvelled Monday. ``People were seriously talking about doing away
with the Department of Education, or even of moving the federal
government out of education.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposes spending between $20.8 billion and
$22.7 billion on elementary, secondary and vocational education in
fiscal year 2000, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In votes last week within the budget committees, Senate
Republicans proposed spending $24.1 billion; House Republicans, $22
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we got a better number in the Senate, a not-so-good number
in the House,'' Riley said. ``Of course, at this stage, they don't
say where the money will be spent or where the money will come
from, or how it will be managed within the (budget's over-all )
spending caps.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich (R-Ohio), chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said, ``The Republican budget makes a strong commitment
to education.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate and House leaders expect the GOP budget resolutions to be
adopted with few changes, if any, before Saturday, when Congress
begins its spring break.
</P>
<P>
   The resolutions contain non-binding, but very influential,
instructions to the appropriation committees that write annual
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way: It's better to be on their list of priorities
for increases than on the list of things that are recommended for
cuts,'' said Joel Parker, a lobbyist for the National Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP resolutions also propose unspecified cuts within a large
category of expenditures that includes higher education, Head Start
and Labor Department training services.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed spending $31.3 billion on those programs in the
next fiscal year. The House and Senate Republican resolutions both
call for spending $28.1 billion - less than is being spent this
year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ed Elmendorf of the American Association of State
Colleges and Universities indicated he and other higher education
lobbyists have not panicked yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not prudent for the budget committee chairmen to say so
this early in the year,'' Elmendorf said. ``But my sense is that in
the end they'll bust the budget caps.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
