<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PRONOTES23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Inside pro tennis: Courier back on Davis Cup roster; Agassi's
out
</P>
<P>
   By Todd Holcomb
</P>
<P>
   Since America's best players aren't faithful to Tom Gullikson,
it's no wonder the U.S. Davis Cup captain keeps hauling out Jim
Courier.
</P>
<P>
   Although past his prime, the former No. 1-ranked player was
named Monday to the four-member U.S. team that will face Great
Britain next month in a first-round match. Gullikson also selected
Todd Martin, Jan-Michael Gambill and doubles man Alex O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi and Pete Sampras had long since ruled themselves
out of the April 3-5 match, putting a damper on the USTA's
celebration of the 100th year of Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, back up to No. 10 in the world, will be the clear No. 1
singles player. Gambill, ranked No. 44, figures to be No. 2. He has
beaten Sampras, Agassi and Britain's Tim Henman in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Courier won the clinching fifth match in five sets in last
year's first round in Atlanta against Russia's Marat Safin. If
anyone was slighted in favor of Courier, who is No. 52, it was
Vince Spadea, who beat Yevgeny Kafelnikov last week. Spadea is
ranked No. 41.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Richey Reneberg also was a candidate. He and Justin
Gimelstob won a doubles tournament at Scottsdale, Ariz., earlier
this month. Both were U.S. team members last year, and Gimelstob is
No. 66 in singles.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi quits Davis Cup
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said Saturday after his early-round loss at the Lipton
that he'll never play Davis Cup again, because the USTA fired the
team doctor. ``That's the last straw for me,'' Agassi said. ``I'll
never play again.'' USTA executive director Rick Ferman said Dr.
George Fareed, a long-time favorite among players, was a casualty
of new regulations that require board certification in specific
areas and daily treatment of athletes. Agassi called it ``another
example of how players aren't consulted about anything that
happens.'' Agassi remains bitter that last year's semifinal against
Italy was played in Milwaukee without his consultation. He said he
would have played had it been staged in California. Italy won 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
