<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0026 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-EVIL-BUNNY-$AD     03-22 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-EVIL-BUNNY-$ADV24-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AWFUL TRUTH ABOUT THE EASTER BUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, March 24)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 (Sarasota, Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year, the Easter Bunny hops into our homes on April 4, the
same day that daylight-saving time begins.
</P>
<P>
   The date also falls alarmingly close to the federal income tax
filing deadline (April 15) and within nine months or so of when all
the world's computers lock up and we revert to hunting mastodons
with flint-tipped spears and watching black-and-white TV.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? I hardly think so.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows (possibly because no one has asked) what, if any,
role the Easter Bunny plays, or has played, in the disintegration
of our American Way of Life.
</P>
<P>
   (Some may question how daylight-saving time contributes to the
disintegration of our American Way of Life and may even argue that
they prefer daylight-saving time to ``standard'' time. That is the
whole point; the Easter Bunny is fiddling with the clocks in order
to divide us and make us easier to conquer.)
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, many Americans still look upon the Easter Bunny as a
quaint bit of harmless folklore intended to bring joy to children
and profit to chocolate manufacturers, and to allow dentists to
stock a better brand of champagne on their yachts.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a small but possibly inebriated band of patriotic
citizens is working off and on between naps to expose the Easter
Bunny for the vicious fraud that he (she?) is. They call themselves
the Easter Bunny Hunters of America
(www.wsu.edu:8080/(tilde)twl/bunny/) and if you hyperventilate on
bus fumes for a few minutes, I think you'll find they make a lot of
sense. Here are some excerpts from the group's ``manifesto'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Easter bunnies are one of the rarest types of rabbits around.
They are valued because they have many uses. They have a rich,
delicious flavor that challenges any other meat except seal meat.
Their fur is of the highest quality and is great for coats and
other apparel. (It also makes good toilet seat covers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It can take many days to locate an Easter Bunny of legal size.
They can be found at malls and around residential neighborhoods.
They differ from regular rabbits by the noise they make. They make
a squawking noise similar to that of a chicken. They are also quite
vicious and contrary to popular belief, they are carnivorous and
prey on small mammals. They have caused many problems in the world,
the biggest one being El Nino. From their secret headquarters in
Walla Walla, Wash., these bunnies have been waging war against
humans.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this confirms what I've been saying all along, namely 1)
While the press has been focused on Monica Lewinsky, a lot of other
news has slipped through the cracks, and 2) If you put a pair of
long ears and a fuzzy cottontail on Bill Gates, he would look a lot
like the Easter Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Some might think that the Easter Bunny Hunters of America have
gone over the edge, that their ravings remind one of the Y2K nuts
who recommend we stock up on bottled water and Spam and head for
the hills of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Easter Bunny Hunters of America are a little more
grounded in reality, thank you very much. They would never tell you
to move to Montana. Why bother? The Easter Bunny will track you
down and sink its cruel, yellow fangs into your neck like it was a
sock filled with processed luncheon meat substance.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I wish to alarm anyone. Many people have had contact
with the Easter Bunny and lived to tell about it. My concern is
that the conjunction of unpleasant events (tax time, Y2K, spring
back, fall ahead, whatever) will put the Easter Bunny in an
especially dark mood, assuming he (she?) didn't arrange it all in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Someone told me that it is fun to put marshmallow Easter Bunnies
in the microwave oven and watch them swell and burst as they absorb
massive doses of radiation.
</P>
<P>
   I don't wish to spoil anyone's Easter holiday fun, but my advice
would be that you postpone this amusing little diversion until some
other time, like, say, the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you happen to detect a whiff of Spam in the air
and notice a yellow, 3-foot-wide, bloodshot eye glaring at you
through the window.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0027 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIAONE-SIDE-COX     03-22 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumers might reap benefits from MediaOne, Comcast mergerBy
Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although it won't happen until the end of 1999 or
early 2000, metro Atlanta's MediaOne subscribers may see better
pricing and more sophisticated offerings when the merger with
Comcast is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta's 550,000 MediaOne and Comcast subscribers will
become part of a cable company boasting over 11 million subscribers
nationwide, giving them the greater buying power and cable
expertise that such size commands.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MediaOne's move into high speed data and telephone
service ``will proceed as planned,'' said spokesman Dave Wood.
</P>
<P>
   The ten-month wait before MediaOne becomes part of Comcast is
largely due to local and federal regulation. Each municipality in
which MediaOne operates must approve the merger. Wood says the
companies must go before every franchising authority, not just in
Georgia but nationwide. It's not expected the deal will be
contested, but it will take time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We going to be MediaOne until the Comcast deal is consummated.
Everything as it stands today is going to go forward,'' he said.
``Whatever business is being transacted with customers will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   But once it happens, there may be exciting changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the goal of our merger is to offer the integration
of video, voice and data over a single line into the home, and
that's something we think is very exciting,'' said Comcast
spokesman Jason Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say that once Comcast/MediaOne merger is
final, MediaOne customers could see several changes in high speed
access and pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media One is one of the more aggressive rate raisers,'' says
Kent Gibbons, news editor at industry trade magazine MultiChannel
News. ``Comcast... is very aware of the need to keep increases
modest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons also thinks the merger might impact each company's cable
modem strategy and possibly bring about some consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Comcast will acquire MediaOne's 25 percent
stake in Road Runner, the Time Warner high speed cable modem
offering. Comcast already owns 12 percent of the At Home network,
the TCI/AT&AMP;T high speed venture. (Atlanta-based Cox Communications,
a unit of Cox Enterprises, owns a minority stake in AtHome, as
well.) Comcast and MediaOne are now contractually obligated to
offer cable modem Internet services with At Home and Road Runner,
respectively. That can't change until the deal is finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, they said they would offer At Home where
Comcast is now and Road Runner where they are MediaOne,'' Gibbons
says. It's possible, he says, that the merger could accelerate a
combination of the two platforms into one service.
</P>
<P>
   However, both MediaOne and Comcast say it's too soon to say what
unified strategies might evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus for local subscribers will be the sheer size of the
new company, which will be the third largest cable provider in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good thing for customers,'' says MediaOne's Wood.
``You want to have a large footprint. The larger the company, the
greater your economies of scale. You can negotiate better with
programmers if you are talking 11 million combined MediaOne/Comcast
subscribers as opposed to five million MediaOne subscribers alone,
but again we don't know,'' he says. ``I don't know if there is any
one outstanding thing that will make a huge impression on the
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0029 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-NYTR &LR;      03-22 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DVD SALES GROW BUT YOUR VCR IS NOT OBSOLETE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
(Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Barry's cell phone is the first clue that he has something
to do with the electronics industry. It's a little bigger than a
matchbox, but not by much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have a belt clip for it,'' said Barry, ``I'd lose
it.
</P>
<P>
   Barry is the spokesman for the Consumer Electronics
Manufacturer's Association. Its members produce cell phones,
digital photo cameras, digital video cameras, high-definition
televisions, DVD players for home theater systems and a raft of
other devices.
</P>
<P>
   The market for them is tremendous: Last year, said Barry,
Americans spent $80 billion on electronic equipment purchasing,
among other items, 18 million VCRs and 1 million DVD players.
</P>
<P>
   It's the 1 million DVDs sold last year that attracted a lot of
attention. In 1997, DVD sales were at 400,000. The under-$300
players that deliver high-quality pictures and sound for home-movie
viewing were expected to sell about 750,000 units last year.
Instead, more than 1 million were purchased.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one-million mark is a magic number for the electronics
industry,'' said Barry, who has written about the industry for 20
years, and is former editor of Video magazine. ``A million is 1
percent of all U.S. households. At that point, you start getting
into `the neighborhood effect,' where you go to someone's house in
the neighborhood and he or she has a DVD player or other new piece
of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The millionth product purchased within a year validates the
market for that product. And at that point, the efficiency of
manufacturing and marketing begins to kick in.''
</P>
<P>
   While the market for DVD continues to grow (sales this year are
expected to be double last year's), Barry said VCRs are a long way
from becoming obsolete. ``That won't happen until we get recordable
DVD disks,'' said Barry.
</P>
<P>
   The big attraction for VCRs (18 were purchased for every one DVD
sold) is that people can record what they want with them. Although
DVDs can hold an entire movie, and although there are more than
1,300 titles available, they're only good for playback.
</P>
<P>
   Recordable DVDs are on the way, ``probably within the next few
years,'' said Barry. ``Audio compact discs came out in 1982, and it
was 1992 before the first recordable CDs were on the market. That
10-year lag time has been greatly compressed now.''
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive gadget in his bag of tricks? I thought it
was the Panasonic Palm Theater. Not much larger than a portable
audio CD player and not much thicker than a hardcover book, the
Palm Theater has a fold-up color screen and a two-hour battery so
users can view an entire movie without recharging or changing
batteries. The unit can also be hooked to a home theater system.
</P>
<P>
   Price? It's one of those ``If you have to ask, you probably
can't afford it'' items. But since you did: about $1,300.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group. Lonnie Brown can be reached by e-mail at
LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His recent computer columns are on the
Internet at http://www.theledger.com/business/tech/).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
