A0033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-PROTECTIONISM-N     03-22 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-PROTECTIONISM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEEL LOBBY TESTS ITS METTLE IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Calif.)  (lh) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How strong is steel?
</P>
<P>
   Not as strong as recent events on Capitol Hill might suggest.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. steel lobby scored a victory last week with a
decisive House vote in favor of a bill that would restrict the
shipment of foreign steel, the celebration may be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   There is considerably less enthusiasm for the bill in the
Senate, which has generally shown more resistance to perceived
barriers to free trade. And President Clinton opposes the measure,
saying it violates international trade laws.
</P>
<P>
   The fight in the House over the steel quota bill underscores a
growing protectionist sentiment in Congress and illustrates the
shifting political dynamics of trade.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who have traditionally led the fight in favor of
free trade and business opportunities abroad, find within their own
camp lawmakers more worried about jobs in their own back yards than
the dangers of bucking party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, watch as Clinton extols the virtues of an
unfettered world market even as labor unions, a key constituency,
argue that foreign competitors are clobbering them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting to me that you've got the White House
defending free trade and the Republican-controlled Congress is
moving toward protectionism,'' said Bryan Johnson, a trade expert
at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative think tank. ``I can't
remember the last time that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost two years, domestic steel producers have been
decrying the flow of cheap, imported steel into U.S. markets.
Russia, China, Japan and several other countries with troubled
economies have turned to this country to unload goods at below-cost
prices that they can't sell back home.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. steel executives and workers say the flood of imports has
cost thousands of jobs and led to the closing of three plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``By allowing dumping we are deliberately sacrificing ...
productive United States jobs,'' said Rep. Robert Aderholt, R-Ala.,
whose district includes Gulf States Steel in Gadsden.
</P>
<P>
   Aderholt is typical of a new breed of Republicans on trade
issues. His stance can be explained in purely parochial terms. He
does, after all, represent a district with a sizable number of
steel workers. But there are other factors at work.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans elected in the past four to six years have
demonstrated a wariness on trade issues, whether it's granting the
president enhanced negotiating powers or signing off on world trade
treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this reluctance appears to stem from the social
conservatism that drives some of these Republicans. On China, for
example, many conservatives blasted the GOP for favoring
most-favored nation trading status even with that country's dismal
record on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   These new lawmakers are also more sympathetic to some U.S.
workers who see a threat in the emerging global economy, one where
borders don't seem to matter as much as business profits.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, of the Heritage Foundation, attributes some of that
sentiment to inexperience, asserting that the newer lawmakers
weren't around when quotas were used and bloated U.S. industries
couldn't compete effectively in world markets. ``They lack a
historical understanding of the issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the steelworkers' union has been well organized and vocal
about its needs, the truth is that there are other industries that
are quite happy with the prospect of cheap steel, no matter what
the source.
</P>
<P>
   Car manufacturers, for example, oppose the steel quota bill the
House passed Wednesday and will likely fight it hard in the Senate.
``The bill represents a rush to judgment on the steel issue that is
likely to have serious economic implications, including potential
steel shortages in the U.S. at a time of increased auto
production,'' said Mustafa Mohatarem, chief economist for General
Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., who led the fight against the steel
bill on the House floor, said far more workers would be hurt by its
enactment into law than helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we use protectionism to shield one industry, 40 times
more Americans are injured,'' Drier said. ``Protectionism is fool's
gold.''
</P>
<P>
   And the upcoming presidential election may encourage both
parties to retreat to their more traditional stances on labor and
trade issues. If that's the case, America's steel interests stand
to lose support in a Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The steel lobby is forging ahead. On Tuesday, steel union
leaders are scheduled to speak before the Senate Finance Committee
about the turmoil in their industry. Gary Hubbard, a spokesman for
the United Steelworkers of America, said that alone is a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who ever would have dreamed a union leader would be asked to
testify before a Republican committee on a trade bill in the
Senate?'' Hubbard asked.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual outcome of the steel quota bill is much harder to
predict. Skeptics abound, and even steel lobbyists acknowledge they
face a tougher fight in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a correspondent in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
