<P>
   INFLUENZA-DOCTOR (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Allen Parmet seems an
unusual soldier in his midtown Kansas City medical office that sits
above a sub shop. He forsakes a white lab coat for a shirt and tie.
But this retired Air Force doctor and pilot is a battle-hardened
veteran of both Vietnam and Project Gargle. That latter operation
didn't hit the headlines, but it was an important part of the
military's fight against influenza. Now, Parmet is again on the
front lines of a new nationwide fight against the flu. By RUTH E.
IGOE. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-SPOKESMEN-TWOTAKES (Washington) _ ``Never 9 to 5,'' is
how Laura Nichols describes her job. ``It's an opportunity that I
never thought that I would have,'' Pete Jeffries said. ``Front row
for history,'' Christina Martin said. And a seat all three have
shared. Nichols, Jeffries and Martin know what it's like to be the
voice for the most powerful people in the House of Representatives.
They are among the legions of 20- and 30-somethings drawn to the
capital who love the battles and intrigues. And they all believe
that politics, the present toxic atmosphere notwithstanding, can be
a noble calling. By DAVID GOLDSTEIN. Story will move in the ``w''
