dressing severed limbs and tying arteries in ravaged chest
cavities. Now he and former Marine Chuck Wright are looking for a
place in Kansas City to build the Combat Corpsmen National War
Memorial. It would honor the men and women who saved others in
combat. By KIM KOZLOWSKI. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-TWO TAKES (La Vergne, Tenn.) _ Since Tennessee's
right-to-carry law passed in 1994, almost 70,000 residents have
applied for permits. Tennesseans have bought more than 100,000 guns
since November, with dealers reporting brisk sales to permit
holders. Missourians vote April 6 on whether to adopt a similar
law. Those looking to Tennessee for clues might find it too early
to tell. Skeptics and supporters have been surprised by the
results. There were warnings that the state would turn into a
reckless, modern version of the ``Wild West.'' There were
predictions that violent criminals would be deterred. So far the
forecast has been wrong on both fronts. By OSCAR AVILA. Story will
move in the ``a'' category.
