A0035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VATICAN-CHINA-NYT &LR;      03-22 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN MAY CUT TIES WITH TAIWAN TO NORMALIZE THOSE WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A top Vatican official said Monday that the Holy See
would reconsider its ties with Taiwan in order to secure better
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   The comment, by the Vatican's foreign minister, Archbishop
Jean-Louis Tauran, was timed to coincide with the visit to Italy of
President Jiang Zemin of China. Jiang has no plans to visit the
Vatican, and relations between the Roman Catholic Church and the
Chinese government are strained.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope, who plans to visit Asia this year to conclude the
synod of Asian bishops, is eager to normalize relations with China
and improve the rights of Catholics there. China has long insisted
that the Vatican must cut ties to Taiwan as a precondition for
talks. China does not allow its Catholics to recognize the pope's
authority, and views the Vatican's desire to appoint its own
bishops as interference in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware that in order to normalize our relations with
Beijing, we will have to modify the form (or relations) with
Taipei,'' Tauran told the Italian daily Corriere della Sera. ``We
are willing to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time that the Vatican has expressed its
eagerness to open diplomatic relations with China; Pope John Paul
II wrote a personal letter to Deng Xiaoping in 1983 asking for
direct contacts. But Tauran's timing, as well as his wording, was
the sharpest public declaration of the Vatican's intent to date. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   China, however, does not appear ready to bend. Asked about the
archbishop's comment, a Chinese government spokesman, Zhu Bangzao,
said: ``Words are not enough. You have to follow through with
deeds.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there are signs of disagreement over the Vatican's China
policy even within the Church. Fides, the news agency of the
missionary arm of the Vatican, published an editorial by the Rev.
Bernardo Cervellera, director of Fides, in which he strongly
criticized China's demands that the Vatican break ties with Taiwan
and highlighted persecution of Catholic clergy in China by the
government. Cervellera demanded that China free two Chinese
Catholic bishops who disappeared three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican Monday disassociated itself from the priest's
editorial. The Vatican spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said the
editorial was ``a personal opinion,'' and added, ``Only the Vatican
secretary of state is authorized to say what pleases or displeases
the Holy See.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0036 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS--2NDTAKE-KAN &LR;      03-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS--2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (application system.)
</P>
<P>
   Several schools offer classes that go beyond the required eight
hours. Authorities point to Buford Tune's Academy of Personal
Protection and Safety in Nashville as a role model. Tune demands 16
hours of training, including segments on civil law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, authorities wonder how many training courses offer
quality programs. Some worry about ``fly-by-night'' schools that do
not have qualified instructors, although all schools must be
certified by the state Department of Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The state reports more than 175 certified schools, although
several random calls reached disconnected numbers. Training classes
have popped up in strip malls, office buildings and isolated gun
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Safety randomly inspects classes to ensure
that instructors are teaching properly. But they cannot police
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago a Nashville television news crew broadcast a
shocking series after taking hidden cameras to a class. The footage
showed instructors giving students answers to the written test and
one teacher confiding, ``I'm not supposed to tell anybody how easy
(the class) is, but it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories like that disturb Tune, an imposing man who, to simulate
stressful conditions, yells in his students' ears at the gun range.
He takes his duties as an instructor seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``An instructor is God to someone who has no experience,'' said
Tune, a former Nashville police officer. ``If they're not teaching
correctly, that's a scary thought. Some of these teachers can
barely spell G-U-N.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to questions about training, Tennessee worked
several years to develop an effective application system.
Originally, Tennessee used a system similar to the one Missouri
plans to adopt. An applicant requested a permit from the county
sheriff, who could deny it for almost any reason.
</P>
<P>
   Almost instantly the horror stories started. One rural Tennessee
sheriff issued the permit and then revoked it from an applicant who
had supported his opponent in a recent election. Tune said one
sheriff told him that he would not issue a permit to blacks or
Latinos, using slurs to describe each group.
</P>
<P>
   Even when sheriffs meant well, an inconsistent set of standards
naturally developed throughout the state's 95 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laws are like the Bible. We all interpret it differently,''
Arnold said. ``This sheriff says I can do this. This sheriff says I
can do that. And this one says he just doesn't care. It was a
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Tennessee switched to a centralized system in which the
state Bureau of Investigation makes the final call on who gets a
permit. Residents fill out application forms at a driver's license
station or sheriff's department, listing their history of crime and
mental illness. Then they submit fingerprints for background
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Applications are forwarded to the state Bureau of Investigation,
which matches names and fingerprints against state and federal
databases and grants permits if people come up clear.
</P>
<P>
   The background check presented another problem, though. Critics
said the checks were worthless, because the databases were
incomplete. Get the fingerprints For a while, local law enforcement
agencies were not sending all fingerprints of arrested persons to
the state databases. Authorities estimated that 30 percent of
felons were not accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper editorialized that the state was playing ``Russian
roulette'' with the checks.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Legislature passed a law requiring law
enforcement to send all their fingerprints to the state. If not,
the state would dock the salaries of sheriffs and police chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, no databases exist to check for mental illness or
substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is clear that law-abiding citizens are the ones going
through the permit process. Only about 1 percent of applications
are rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone agrees that the new centralized system is better
than the old format. A recent change in law still permits sheriffs
to get a copy of each application from their county so they can
provide information on why an applicant should be denied a permit,
such as an ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's experience shows that once a law is passed, expect
it to change.
</P>
<P>
   At one time applicants needed to pay a bond and often had to
wait months for a permit. Now, no bond is needed and permits are
automatically issued within 90 days, even if fingerprint checks
have not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   In this session lawmakers are considering measures that would
allow guns in schools and businesses that sell but do not serve
alcohol, two areas where they currently are banned.
</P>
<P>
   State observers are realizing that with the gun law in place,
its effects will be determined by how lawmakers tweak it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People carry guns, regardless,'' said Bob Barker, chief deputy
of the Sumner County Sheriff's Department, in Gallatin. ``You might
as well have a law. But if you're going to have a law, make sure
you do it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
