<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGIS-BRITE-COX     03-22 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGIS-BRITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia House members table measure after racial debate
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An apparently innocuous resolution sparked a racially
charged debate in the House Monday, with the measure's white
sponsor describing lawmakers' attempts to amend it as ''stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which would have urged _ but not required _
local school boards to display historical documents such as the
Declaration of Independence, the U.S. Constitution and the
Mayflower Compact in schools, was tabled with the backing of its
sponsor, Rep. Scott Tolbert (R-Pendergrass). Since there are only
two days remaining in the Legislative session, tabling the measure
effectively killed it for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Non-binding resolutions usually pass the House with unanimous
support and little debate, but black lawmakers said Tolbert's
proposal ignored the role of African Americans in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Holmes (D-Atlanta) said the documents included in
Tolbert's resolution ''distort American history,'' since they
didn't include anything ''by or about African American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes offered an amendment that would have added speeches and
writings by African Americans, including Martin Luther King Jr. and
Frederick Douglass, to the list. Although the House had approved an
amendment adding documents of the Cherokee Indian nation, most
white members balked at Holmes' suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than vote on the Holmes amendment, the House choose to
table the entire resolution. The vote was 106-62, with most black
members voting against tabling the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert said he voted to table the resolution because ''what had
started out as a very non-race, purely American bill turned into
something totally stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Replied Holmes, ''Mr. Tolbert doesn't really get it. Unless you
have inclusion by all groups, you're going to perpetuate the
distortions. ''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said his proposed amendment was ''not stupid. It's stupid
to perpetuate the myths.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Walston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1854EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
