<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITOL-STATUE-KAN &LR;      03-22 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITOL-STATUE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE WHO LIKE IKE WANT TO KICK GLICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ For 84 years, the marble image of former Kansas
Gov. George Washington Glick has greeted visitors to the U.S.
Capitol in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a move afoot to return Glick to Kansas and
replace him with a somewhat better-known Kansan: Dwight D.
Eisenhower of Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower, after all, was the supreme Allied commander during
World War II and went on to become president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Glick's claim to fame? He was the first Democratic governor of
Kansas, and, as one state lawmaker noted Friday, he once called a
special session of the Legislature to deal with an outbreak of
hoof-and-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
   Each state is allowed to have two statues representing it in the
Capitol in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Glick, who died in 1911 and is buried in his hometown of
Atchison, Kansas is represented by a statue of another Atchison
native, U.S. Sen. John James Ingalls, a Republican who served from
1873 to 1891.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Senate adopted a resolution Friday that would begin
the switch by asking Congress to evict Glick and replace him with a
statue of Eisenhower, yet to be commissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Glick's statue would be returned to Topeka for display in the
state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   It's now up to the Kansas House to deal with the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Dick Bond, an Overland Park Republican, offered
the resolution without funneling it through a committee for
scrutiny. ``I like Ike,'' said Bond, who was wearing a campaign
button bearing that slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said it would cost about $200,000 to hire a sculptor,
transport the work to Washington and bring Glick back to Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   He said it shouldn't cost the state anything, although the
resolution provides that the state is responsible if private
efforts to raise the money are unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, careful not to criticize Glick, said his resolution would
``bring him home.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bond couldn't resist referring to the special session Glick
called to deal with hoof-and-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
   That led Rep. Janis Lee, a Kensington Democrat, to come to
Glick's defense.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the special session in 1884 led to the creation
of a livestock commission and the hiring of a state veterinarian.
She also noted that Glick won passage of legislation to limit
railroad rates for hauling corn, wheat and cattle.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as a delegate to the convention that drafted the
state constitution in 1859 and was wounded during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some of you putting your hooves in your mouths,''
Lee said of those who made light of Glick's accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Todd Tiahrt, the Republican who represents the 4th
District, suggested switching Eisenhower for Glick.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hanna, Tiahrt's spokesman, said, ``We simply felt it was a
good idea and a way to honor one of the most prominent Kansans, not
only in Kansas but in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Anthony Hensley, a Topeka Democrat, said,
``You know, if Congressman Tiahrt doesn't have better things to do
than to try to remove a statue from Statuary Hall, I think we're in
a great deal of trouble in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna said state statues are placed in the Capitol's Statuary
Hall for at least six months after they arrive in Washington and
then are allocated space elsewhere in the building at the
discretion of the Capitol architect.
</P>
<P>
   The Glick statue currently stands on the entry level of the
south wing of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first effort to switch Ike for Glick. In 1971,
the Legislature tried to make the same change, but Congress, then
controlled by Democrats, ignored Kansas' resolution.
</P>
<P>
   James Maag of Topeka was a member of the Kansas House at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   With time on their hands, Maag and several other Republican
backbenchers formed a tongue-in-cheek group they named ``The Don't
Kick Glick Society.''
</P>
<P>
   Maag, a former history teacher at Dodge City Community College,
said the little-known Glick was chosen originally because Congress
requested the selection be made at a time when Democrats controlled
both houses of the Legislature in 1913 and 1914.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Glick was the only Democrat to have been elected to
any statewide office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
