<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPION BALLOONISTS HONORED IN SWITZERLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ As Dr. Bertrand Piccard and Brian Jones stepped from a
plane from Cairo Monday after becoming the first balloonists to
circle the world nonstop, a trumpeter played the ``Triumphal
March'' from ``Aida'' and a thunderous cheer rose from the
dignitaries and well-wishers who had gathered at Geneva
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   In their dark blue flight suits, the champion pilots raised
their arms in a victory salute and beamed at the crowd under a cold
drizzle and overcast sky, a crowd that included children who had
been given the day off from school.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief welcoming speech, Vice President Adolphe Ogi referred
to Antoine de St. Exupery's famous children's book, saying, ``Our
little prince came down from the sky and landed in the desert among
us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Piccard, 41, a Swiss psychiatrist, and his British
co-pilot, Jones, who will be 52 next Saturday, completed a historic
19-day trip around the world in their Breitling Orbiter 3 balloon
when they flew over an invisible finish line at 9 degrees 27
minutes west longitude in Mauritania. More than a score of pilots
had tried to go around the world in a balloon before, and all had
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the crowd that met the two pilots here was Richard
Branson, the billionaire balloonist who was one of Piccard's main
rivals in round-the-world attempts. The most recent of those ended
on Dec. 25 with a ditching in the ocean near Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   As the Breitling Orbiter 3 crew sprayed each other and Branson
with Champagne, Piccard praised his longtime and intense rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been friends, and even though Richard was not
the first to go around the world, I know he will still fly balloons
just for the joy of flying, a joy our elite group all share,''
Piccard said.
</P>
<P>
   Piccard and Jones spoke of ``a mysterious invisible hand'' that
had seemingly opened the way for them. After the craft had passed
Puerto Rico, he related, calculations suggested that their slow
speed would leave them out of fuel well short of their destination.
``And then,'' Jones said, ``suddenly the speed started to increase
very rapidly, up to 150 miles an hour, and I just threw all my
calculations away.''
</P>
<P>
   Their achievement has won Piccard and Jones the Budweiser Cup
and a $1 million prize from Anheuser-Busch Inc., with half to be
contributed to charities that the pilots choose. Piccard said they
would contribute the money to creating a foundation to improve
conditions for poor people in the countries that they flew over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
