A0041 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-SPOKESMEN-T     03-22 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-SPOKESMEN-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDES GET A FRONT-ROW SEAT TO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Late on election night last November, when House
Speaker Newt Gingrich watched the Republican Party's political
fortunes drop _ along with his own _ Christina Martin was there to
offer solace. Together, they sifted through the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, when J. Dennis Hastert, a little-known Republican
congressman from Illinois, was suddenly on the brink of becoming
speaker of the House, Pete Jeffries was with him. Together, they
tallied who would support his bid.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, when House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt
hastily prepared a speech lamenting the vicious political mood
surrounding impeachment, Laura Nichols was at his side. Together,
they crafted the right words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never 9 to 5,'' Nichols added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity that I never thought that I would have,''
Jeffries said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Front row for history,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   And a seat all three have shared. Nichols, Jeffries and Martin
know what it's like to be the voice for the most powerful people in
the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   They also share another trait: All three are from Johnson
County, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   They are among the legions of 20- and 30-somethings drawn to the
capital who love the battles and intrigues. And they all believe
that politics, the present toxic atmosphere notwithstanding, can be
a noble calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fighting for what I believe in,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts can peek through, however. ``I hope what we're doing here
is the right thing for the country,'' Jeffries said. ``I know that
sounds sappy and patriotic.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's some cynicism, too. ``It's not always as rewarding
as you hope it will be,'' Nichols said. ``In the last four years,
when it's been so partisan and so bitter, you don't get a lot of
satisfaction necessarily out of what you do here every day.''
</P>
<P>
   All three gained entry to the inner corridors of Capitol Hill
through a combination of serendipity and talent.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected occurrence 12 years ago eventually put the
34-year-old Nichols, who is Gephardt's communications director, on
the inside track.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols' political activism started early. ``I was the kid in
eighth grade that was wearing the Jimmy Carter button to school,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Missouri graduate had just accepted her first
political assignment as Gephardt's deputy press secretary for the
Iowa presidential caucuses. She arrived the day that Gary Hart,
then the top Democrat in the race, withdrew over his affair with
Donna Rice. Suddenly, Gephardt was the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My little job became a big job very quickly,'' Nichols
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt won the Iowa caucuses and placed second in the New
Hampshire primary, but he ran out of money and dropped out of the
race. Nichols went to Washington and, after a series of Democratic
Party positions, rejoined Gephardt as his press secretary after the
1992 elections.
</P>
<P>
   She's been his primary public voice ever since, the nexus
between his policy statements and the overall message of the House
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a good ear, and she also helps me think things through
and what I'm going to say,'' Gephardt said. ``She's just very
valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   The day the House voted to impeach President Clinton, when
speaker-in-waiting Robert Livingston announced he would resign over
an extramarital affair, Gephardt, aided by Nichols and a speech
writer, put into words what everyone was feeling. His impassioned
plea for political civility produced a standing, bipartisan
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dick said spoke volumes about how heartbroken we were
about what had happened to this place that everybody loved, that it
really was no longer the place that anybody remembered,'' Nichols
said. ``It was one of the saddest days in my political career, and
it was one of my proudest days.''
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, the White House... MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
