r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-SPOKESMEN-2     03-22 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-SPOKESMEN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDES GET A FRONT-ROW SEAT TO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ...my proudest days.''
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, the White House is trying to lure Nichols, who has
also had offers from the private sector. Recently she acknowledged
that she had considered leaving Capitol Hill. Then Democratic
victories last fall put the party within sight of a House majority
in two years. Now that Gephardt potentially is the next speaker and
has been re-energized _``in his zone,'' as Nichols said _ she put
that decision on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 32, now a vice president with the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association, had not even been exposed
to politics until her freshman year at the University of Kansas in
1985. She won an internship in the office of Sen. Bob Dole, then
the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did everything from walk the dog _ literally _ to answering
the mail, to giving tours, to answering telephones,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's break came in 1988. She was in Washington the summer
after her graduation looking for a job in economics, her field, and
the phone rang. It was the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years later, her resume included jobs as a White House
aide and speech writer for President George Bush, and roles in
three presidential campaigns: Bush in 1988 and 1992, a win and a
loss, and Dole in 1996, a loss. Martin said she admires both men.
But of the Dole campaign, she said, ``There was more backstabbing
than I have encountered in any political environment.''
</P>
<P>
   She has held several other political posts, with her last as
Gingrich's press secretary. Despite his combative style, Martin
said, Gingrich ``possessed all the characteristics of a favorite
uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a very good run,'' Martin said. ``We fought the good
fight against some very tough adversaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Her opponents would probably say the same about her. She was
always quick with the verbal stiletto, as in 1996 when she called
Clinton ``commander-in-thief'' for trumpeting his support of a
crime victims constitutional amendment after Dole already had done
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I liked about Christina was she played hard but
stayed within the foul lines,'' Michael McCurry, Clinton's press
secretary, said. ``You have to have a good sixth sense about where
the boundary lines are or you end up saying things and poisoning
debate further.''
</P>
<P>
   But by last fall, she had grown weary of the pace. It didn't
help that the Republicans had suffered surprising losses in the
election. Still, she was as surprised as anyone when Gingrich said
he would step down. Martin said she was holding in her hand the
list of Republican members who had committed to support him for
another term as speaker when she got the call.
</P>
<P>
   Like her boss, she decided to leave the House. ``It was time to
take the emphasis off adrenaline and put it back into balance and
quality of life,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeffries, 34, it was the upheaval associated with
impeachment that catapulted him to the upper reaches of Republican
congressional politics. When Gingrich went down, then Livingston,
it was his boss the party turned to.
</P>
<P>
   His job as communications director is to publicize Republican
legislation and coordinate the party's national message, ``so it
makes sense to that person sitting in Westwood, Kansas, at their
kitchen table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that table that he heard a considerable amount of
political debate. His mother, Nancy Jeffries, was the first woman
to run for a seat on the Westwood City Council in 1970. She served
11 years. She's a Democrat who reveres Franklin D. Roosevelt. Her
husband is a conservative Republican, which Pete Jeffries said,
``made for some interesting holiday dinners.''
</P>
<P>
   The son unveiled his politics at the University of Iowa, when he
became president of a Young Republicans chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine?'' Nancy Jeffries said in mock horror. ``I was
just sick.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated in 1986 with a journalism degree and little thought
of entering politics. Covering it was his intention. But while
Jeffries was working as a reporter in Cape Girardeau, Mo.,
Republican Rep. Bill Emerson offered him a job on Capitol Hill.
When Emerson died in 1996 and his wife, Jo Ann, won the seat,
Jeffries joined her staff.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides switch bosses often, and Hastert, then a
deputy House whip and a subcommittee chairman, had a job opening a
year ago. It was a step up, but Jeffries had no hint how big until
last fall, when the Hill was buzzing that Gingrich might resign and
when Hastert's name surfaced as successor.
</P>
<P>
   As speaker, Hastert couldn't be more different from his
predecessor. Gingrich was a bundle of nervous political energy,
often popping off in the most viscerally partisan way. Hastert is
low-key, almost to the point of being invisible. ``He tries to stay
above the fray,'' Jeffries said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffries, whose demeanor mirrors that of his boss, said the
change in political tone is a good thing. ``We understand there's a
political atmosphere around this place,'' he said, ``but there's no
reason you can't do it in a more civil manner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
