<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0043 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFLUENZA-DOCTOR-KAN &LR;      03-22 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFLUENZA-DOCTOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A REAL WAR GOING ON TO HALT SPREAD OF INFLUENZA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Allen Parmet seems an unusual soldier in his
midtown Kansas City medical office that sits above a sub shop. He
forsakes a white lab coat for a shirt and tie. With his handlebar
mustache and spectacles, Parmet looks like a man from a bygone age.
</P>
<P>
   But this retired Air Force doctor and pilot is a battle-hardened
veteran of both Vietnam and Project Gargle. That latter operation
didn't hit the headlines, but it was an important part of the
military's fight against influenza.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Parmet is again on the front lines of a new nationwide
fight against the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Parmet, 48, is one of about 10 volunteer doctors in the Kansas
City area who keep tabs on local flu strains. In all, 350 doctors
nationwide are part of U.S. Influenza Sentinel Physician
Surveillance Network.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with cotton swabs, sentinels ship throat culture samples
on to state health departments, which send the findings to the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Then the information makes its way to the World Health
Organization. There, germ experts predict what next year's
predominant _ and potentially lethal _ influenza strains will be
and what vaccine should be readied to fight them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're helping them make sure the vaccine they prepare is
appropriate,'' Parmet said.
</P>
<P>
   If the vaccine is on target, people have a better chance to ward
off those wintertime aches and pains. But if the flu shot misfires,
folks are in for a miserable season, not to mention at risk for
serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   Each year between 10 percent and 20 percent of Americans
struggle with the flu. Roughly 130,000 influenza victims are
hospitalized each year and about 20,000 patients die from
flu-related health complications.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 100,000 people in Missouri received flu shots given out
by the state health department last year. Kansas did not keep
similar statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shots, the flu infiltrates some areas and
circumvents others. Different communities, even doctors in the same
town, can see widely varying numbers of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide this year, as during the past three years, the flu
has reached widespread and epidemic levels, according to Carolyn
Bridges, a physician with the Influenza Branch at the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every year we have these epidemics,'' she said, ``And
when you are the one who is sick and your community is affected,
it's terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   National sentinel programs have been around for a long time, but
previous ones did not work with state programs, explained Lynnette
Brammer, an epidemiologist with the federal health agency's
Influenza Branch in Atlanta. The new program, which includes 40
states and the District of Columbia, is in its second year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly looking for good physicians who will
report,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Kliethermes works with Missouri's 56 sentinels, and Corinne
Miller coordinates 18 in Kansas. Both are pleased that the program
connects doctors in the field with scientists trying to fend off
the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Flu strains are constantly changing. Scientists believe many new
variations originate in Asia, because of the closeness between
people, birds and pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, travelers on planes, trains and automobiles can
export flu varieties from remote agrarian regions to cities across
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   At flu command central, World Health Organization scientists
sift through reports from far-flung doctors such as Parmet to
decide how to battle the prominent, fast-traveling strains.
</P>
<P>
   The health organization gives pharmaceutical companies a shot
recipe of three flu strains, two of the dangerous A strains and one
of the milder B form. The mixture helps ready the body to fight the
illness without passing on the full-blown symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Parmet knows the consequences of making sure people get the
right vaccine. He recalled his first year as an Air Force Academy
student, when influenza left entire barracks anything but battle
ready.
</P>
<P>
   Later Parmet worked with Project Gargle, a sort of military
version of the sentinel program.
</P>
<P>
   ``An epidemic is a serious thing on a military base,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a civilian, Parmet's preoccupation with fighting the flu
hasn't left him.
</P>
<P>
   During his daily routine, Parmet is on the lookout for any
flu-like symptoms among his patients, such as a cough or a sore
throat with a 100-degree fever or higher. If Parmet spots a likely
suspect, he takes a cotton swab and swipes the back of that
patient's throat, capturing samples of any viral visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people you sample, the less likely you are to miss
anything important and prevent an epidemic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parmet packs the samples into vials and ships them off to the
state public health lab in Jefferson City. Parmet and other
sentinels also pass on information about the severity and spread of
the illness.
</P>
<P>
   Vigilance is necessary to vanquish such viral enemies, Parmet
said. He hopes colleagues will become sentinels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for doctors to participate. It's protecting our
public health,'' he said. ``It just costs us time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
