<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIC-MEMORIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS ARE SEEKING KC HOME FOR MEMORIAL TO HONOR CORPSMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIM KOZLOWSKI  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ Army Col. Donald Ballard knows that Hollywood
won't make an Oscar-nominated film about him.
</P>
<P>
   He witnessed atrocities like those in ``Saving Private Ryan,''
but the movie couldn't match Ballard's horrifying experience in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard served as a Navy corpsman. He risked his life while
dressing severed limbs and tying arteries in ravaged chest
cavities.
</P>
<P>
   Now he and former Marine Chuck Wright are looking for a place in
Kansas City to build the Combat Corpsmen National War Memorial. It
would honor the men and women who saved others in combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the ultimate war, the ultimate price to pay in the
war,'' said Ballard, a Medal of Honor recipient from North Kansas
City. ``It's dealing with the blood and guts and tears. And it just
tears your heart out when you can't save their lives. And these
guys are your friends, your close friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 million memorial would honor some 6,000 Army, Navy, Air
Force, Marine and Coast Guard members who died while serving as
corpsmen or medics, the term the Army started using during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Their names would be etched on a 6- to 8-foot-tall, 96-foot-long
granite arc. The names of about 50 corpsmen and medics who received
Medals of Honor also would be engraved on the wall, alongside their
photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medics and corpsmen are held in very high regard,'' said Lt.
Col. Tom Begines, a Defense Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial also would include a life-size statue of a corpsman
treating two comrades as a Marine protects them. It would stand
under a 35-foot copper dome supported by four pillars, in front of
the granite wall. Four fountains, benches and flags _ representing
each branch of service _ would round out the monument.
</P>
<P>
   When completed, the memorial would stretch 300 feet, the length
of a football field. Ballard and Wright expect the total complex to
need 3 to 5 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, a Vietnam veteran from Gladstone, and Ballard haven't
found a home for the memorial. They have approached Kansas City,
Independence, North Kansas City, Gladstone, Overland Park and
Olathe for a land donation. They say it would be a coup for the
host because it would attract visitors from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McHenry, deputy director of the Kansas City Parks and
Recreation Department, said that the Board of Parks and Recreation
Commissioners would have to make the decision but that he needed
more details before presenting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some precedent out there, so there is a
possibility,'' McHenry said, referring to the Liberty Memorial,
built to honor those who served in World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard and Wright have collected $5,000. They have also lined
up the sponsorship of the American Legion Bennett and Dennis
Herrick Memorial Post 626, the Veterans of Foreign Wars Post 10906
and several other military organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help the community,'' said Roger Kohrs, a member of
the American Legion. ``It will be an asset to all veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   A pre-dedication ceremony is scheduled for Aug. 14 in
conjunction with the VFW's 100th anniversary convention in Kansas
City. The monument would be unveiled May 16, 2000 _ the 32nd
anniversary of the act that earned Ballard the Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard, then 22, was returning to his platoon from an
evacuation of two casualties when the North Vietnamese attacked.
Under heavy fire, he rushed to a wounded Marine and began treating
him.
</P>
<P>
   As Ballard directed four Marines to carry the man to a safer
area, a grenade landed nearby. He threw himself on it to protect
the others. When the grenade didn't explode, Ballard threw it back.
</P>
<P>
   The act inspired Wright to begin the project, but Ballard wanted
to honor all corpsmen, especially those who had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody needs to do this before it's too late,'' Wright said.
``Before I die. Before Don dies. Why can't we recognize people
while they're alive?''
</P>
<P>
   Contributions can be sent to American Legion Bennett and Dennis
Herrick Memorial Post 626, P.O. Box 10613, Gladstone, MO 64188.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
