<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0047 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS--TWOTAKES-KAN &LR;      03-22 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS--TWO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE'S EXPERIENCED WITH RESIDENTS CARRYING CONCEALED WEAPONS
LEGALLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA VERGNE, Tenn. _ Aside from the inventory of his wood-paneled
gun shop outside Nashville, John Arnold keeps a cache for his own
protection.
</P>
<P>
   There is a gun in his desk drawer, another in his assistant's
desk, a shotgun in an adjacent office and a spare gun in the glove
compartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what?'' said Arnold, owner of Specialty Arms II.
``I've never felt the need to use one for self-defense. I've never
had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a growing number of Tennesseans, Arnold is armed _ just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tennessee's right-to-carry law passed in 1994, almost
70,000 residents have applied for permits. Tennesseans have bought
more than 100,000 guns since November, with dealers reporting brisk
sales to permit holders. Missourians vote April 6 on whether to
adopt a similar law.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking to Tennessee for clues might find it too early to
tell. Skeptics and supporters have been surprised by the results.
There were warnings that the state would turn into a reckless,
modern version of the ``Wild West.'' There were predictions that
violent criminals would be deterred. So far the forecast has been
wrong on both fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Gun opponents' fears have not come true. Law enforcement
officials and legislators can think of no accidental shootings,
injuries or crimes tied to the legal carrying of guns.
</P>
<P>
   And contrary to what supporters promised, violent crime in
Tennessee actually increased 6 percent from 1994 to 1997, although
no one in Tennessee has proved that the law is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Thomas, executive director of the Tennessee Sheriffs'
Association, and other state officials said their experience could
hold lessons for Missouri, a neighbor with similar population and
racial demographics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to destroy the state of Missouri, at least if
it follows what happened to us,'' said Thomas, a former police
chief in Alcoa, Tenn., who had doubts about the law at first. ``But
it may not do anything to make the state a better place to live,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because authorities and gun owners agree that thousands
carried guns in Tennessee, even before the law passed. One former
officer said that if he had a dollar for every gun he found on a
motorist, he ``would own the Bahamas by now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you they're carrying guns in Kansas City, too,''
Arnold added. ``The only thing the law does is make it legal.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been effects, subtle ones.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say they feel safer, with polls finding a majority in
support of the law. Some law enforcement experts said people might
be feeling a false sense of security, considering that crime has
increased statewide.
Now that there is a carry law on the books, authorities say they
are taking illegal carrying, even by well-meaning persons,
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Gun owners are taking their weapons more seriously, too. A
required class is designed to teach them exactly when to use their
guns, even if they have decades of experience with firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Take Martin Bennett of Nashville. A few years ago thieves kept
breaking into cars at his auto dealership.
</P>
<P>
   One night Bennett waited for the thieves in a car. Soon he heard
the windows breaking a few feet away. Bennett emerged with a
shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed the gun at the man in front of him. Don't move,
Bennett said as he turned to call the police. The man took a few
steps toward him and reached under his coat. Was he pulling a gun?
</P>
<P>
   At the last moment the man ran away.
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds more and Bennett might have shot him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after taking an eight-hour course for his permit, Bennett
realizes he should not have brandished the gun in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most impressionable thing about the videos we saw is
stressing the responsibility and consequences involved. It makes
you think,'' Bennett said, minutes before taking his turn at a gun
range.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the training courses have helped turn gun owners
into responsible gun owners. Before applying for permits,
Tennesseans must complete four hours of training in a classroom and
on the gun range, at their own expense. Applicants also must pass
written and shooting exams.
</P>
<P>
   Not all states require training. Missouri would require 12
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Is that enough?
</P>
<P>
   Several instructors in Tennessee said no, especially for those
shooting guns for the first time. Many students request more
training on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Once approved, permit holders are not required to return to the
gun range. Some say residents should be required to follow the
example of police officers, whose job requires constant training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a crock,'' said Tom Gibson, owner of Crime Watch
security company. ``If a police officer needs more training, what
chance does John Q. Citizen have when they're confronting the bad
guy?''
Several schools offer classes that go beyond the required eight
hours. Authorities point to Buford Tune's Academy of Personal
Protection and Safety in Nashville as a role model. Tune demands 16
hours of training, including segments on civil law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, authorities wonder how many training courses offer
quality programs. Some worry about ``fly-by-night'' schools that do
not have qualified instructors, although all schools must be
certified by the state Department of Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The state reports more than 175 certified schools, although
several random calls reached disconnected numbers. Training classes
have popped up in strip malls, office buildings and isolated gun
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Safety randomly inspects classes to ensure
that instructors are teaching properly. But they cannot police
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago a Nashville television news crew broadcast a
shocking series after taking hidden cameras to a class. The footage
showed instructors giving students answers to the written test and
one teacher confiding, ``I'm not supposed to tell anybody how easy
(the class) is, but it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories like that disturb Tune, an imposing man who, to simulate
stressful conditions, yells in his students' ears at the gun range.
He takes his duties as an instructor seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``An instructor is God to someone who has no experience,'' said
Tune, a former Nashville police officer. ``If they're not teaching
correctly, that's a scary thought. Some of these teachers can
barely spell G-U-N.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to questions about training, Tennessee worked
several years to develop an effective application system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1902EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
