<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-BOTTLE23-COX     03-22 1687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BOTTLE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola faces crossroads as it celebrates 100 years
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ A hundred years and counting.
</P>
<P>
   The Coca-Cola bottling system has come a long way from its mule
and wagon beginnings. But as it celebrates its centennial
anniversary here Wednesday, the bottling system is at a crossroads,
facing increasing pressure to reinvent itself for the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Intense competition, the need for huge amounts of capital and
equipment, and the changing retail climate are three of the soft
drink industry's key challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Behind them all lurks one cold fact of life _ consolidation. The
big Coca-Cola bottlers are going to continue to swallow the smaller
ones as they try to drive up soft-drink consumption to fatten the
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Coca-Cola bottlers in the United States will drop
to fewer than 50 within five years, some analysts predict, down
from 96 today. Only 19 years ago, the country had 353 Coca-Cola
bottlers. A similar trend is occurring around the world, where
Coca-Cola is sold in nearly 200 nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect the consolidation to continue,'' said Jack Stahl,
president of Coca-Cola's North America Group. ``It will happen
naturally. I think it will happen in a way that works for the
bottlers. It will work for the Coca-Cola Company. It will work for
our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike takeovers in many other industries where local
operations often are shuttered after the deals are done, the
bottling companies that emerge must be strengthened in the local
markets they serve. If not, the deals can backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make the brand relevant on a market-to-market
basis,'' Stahl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing doesn't work everywhere because of local
tastes,'' added Bob Lovell, vice president of marketing for
Coca-Cola Bottling Co. United, which owns the Chattanooga plant.
``Barbecue in the South is pork. Barbecue in Texas is beef. ''
</P>
<P>
   HOW IT BEGAN
</P>
<P>
   To understand the significance of this consolidation, it's
important to first understand how Big Red operates from its Atlanta
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest beverage company does not produce or
distribute its soft drinks. It is essentially a huge marketing
company that sells the special concentrate used to make the drinks
to bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   The bottlers, some completely independent of Coca-Cola and some
owned partially by the company, then produce and distribute the
drinks in specific territories, or franchises.
</P>
<P>
   That system of franchising bottling companies dates back to 1899
when, for a $1, Coca-Cola President Asa Candler reluctantly agreed
to give two Chattanooga lawyers the exclusive right to bottle the
drink throughout most of the country. The lawyers teamed up with a
businessman and started selling franchises across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, it took about $5,000 to equip the average
soft-drink bottling plant, which used mules and wagons to
distribute the product to grocery stores. Before then, consumers
could only drink Coca-Cola at soda fountains.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the franchises were purchased as family businesses that
were passed from generation to generation. And much of the business
_ except for the mules _ remained the same until 1955, when
different size bottles were introduced. Five years later, Coca-Cola
bottlers started to use aluminum cans, and, in the early 1960s, the
company introduced new drinks, such as Fanta, Sprite and Fresca.
</P>
<P>
   Different brands and containers began to proliferate in the
1960s, '70s and '80s, while population growth, TV commercials and
other marketing efforts were driving consumption of soft drinks
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Bottlers needed more automated technology spread over larger
territories. That required lots of capital, as well as high levels
of debt in some cases, so more production plants and warehouses
could be built and equipped. More trucks and vending machines also
had to be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the game was, and still is, distribution _ you can't
sell it if you can't get it into people's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old cliche of wanting to be within an arm's reach
of desire,'' said Summerfield Johnston Jr., chairman of Coca-Cola
Enterprises, the system's largest bottler. ``That was true then,
and it's true today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottlers started to merge to maximize profits as their operating
costs rose to handle the increased volume. When the heirs of a
small, family-owned bottling operation wanted to sell out, large
bottlers were more than ready to pay the price. In fact, some of
the large bottlers would compete against each other for the chance
to buy that company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have bid against each other in the past, and I'm sure we
will in the future,'' said Lauren Steele, spokesperson of Coca-Cola
Bottling Consolidated, the system's second-largest bottling company
in the United States behind Atlanta-based CCE.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the retail climate in America was changing,
which drove bottling consolidation even further. Big supermarket
chains and convenience store operators were taking over much of the
retail industry from smaller stores. The big chains preferred to
deal with fewer and larger bottlers, which would simplify their own
retail operations.
</P>
<P>
   That situation continues to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customer profile is changing among our retail customers
across America. Consolidation is taking place,'' said Lovell, the
Coca-Cola United official. ``They're more sophisticated, both
technologically and information-systems wise than they have ever
been in the past. So it means that we have to keep up with them.
... Today, we've got to have people who are much more highly
skilled in selling and communicating with these customers.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG COKE'S BIG MOVE
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. itself made a dramatic move in 1986 to further
change the bottling landscape and accelerate consolidation. Big Red
spun off some company-owned bottling operations and merged them
with two other large bottling groups, creating CCE.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Coca-Cola had a 49 percent stake in the new publicly
traded CCE. The stake is now 40 percent. Last year, Coca-Cola spent
$1.2 billion on marketing and sales-related equipment for CCE, up
54 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In just 13 years, through an aggressive acquisition program, CCE
has corralled 74 percent of Coca-Cola's volume in North America.
Last year alone, CCE spent more than $2 billion buying up U.S.
bottlers. Analyst Andrew Conway of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
predicts CCE will capture about 80 percent of the U.S. market in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be 80 percent before five years,'' responded
Johnston, CCE's chairman, when told of Conway's prediction. ``The
acquisition business is one of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Coca-Cola's main rival, Pepsico, has decided to follow the
CCE bottling model. It's spinning off a publicly traded bottling
company that analysts say will intensify competition and
consolidation in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts don't necessarily think Coca-Cola or its large
bottlers will suffer over the long term from Pepsico's moves.
Several said there's more than enough business to go around,
especially if recent price increases in supermarkets stick and if
smart marketing campaigns continue to drive up consumption.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, the country's per capita consumption of soft
drinks was 31 gallons a year, analyst Conway said. Today, it's
about 56 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   But Stahl said Coca-Cola has the opportunity to boost annual
sales by 250 million cases in the United States, which translates
into an increase of 20 to 25 drinks per person per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge opportunity,'' Stahl said. ``The greater our
understanding of consumers, the greater our ability to connect with
our customers, the faster we'll create those growth cases.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes Coca-Cola is ``undersold'' virtually everywhere,
even, he quipped, in parts of its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key ways to drive up business is through high-margin
vending machines. Bottlers are responsible for financing those
machines, as well as figuring out where they can get the biggest
bang for their buck when they deploy them like an automated Red
Army.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last year alone, CCE spent $800 million _ half of
its entire capital spending budget _ to dispense and service
vending machines and coolers, which bolster the sales of higher
priced, individual units of soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHORS AWAY
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of such enormous capital requirements, Coca-Cola
has been expanding its system of huge ``anchor bottlers,'' which
have the resources to drive up sales volume throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   CCE is the largest of these anchor bottlers, with nine others
around the world and a 10th one in the making in Japan. There is no
more than one anchor bottler in any country, and most cover several
nations. Collectively, anchor bottlers distribute in about 50
countries and comprise 45 percent of volume worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enter into anchor bottler partnerships because we expect
results beyond what we could attain alone or with multiple
bottlers,'' Coca-Cola said in its annual report that was released
recently.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation in the soft drink industry, however, differs
from other industries. While ownership, financing and
administration may become centralized in some acquisitions, large
bottlers must maintain and even expand their local sales, marketing
and distribution forces.
</P>
<P>
   And they must keep a large part of the decision-making in the
hands of the local people because there are wide differences in
consumer preferences in different markets, as well as the need for
tailored marketing campaigns. A Coke promotion with the University
of Tennessee is not going to play well in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has to be locally run,'' said CCE spokeswoman
Laura Asman. ``It's a pretty old-fashioned formula, but it's one
that has worked well for our company. ... We have 66,000 employees,
with only a few hundred in Atlanta's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
