<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT MAY DELAY PALESTINIAN STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yasser Arafat, who is to meet with President Clinton
on Tuesday, has always been a master of the tightrope, and once
more his acrobatic skills are being put to the test.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank and Gaza, Arafat, the Palestinian leader, faces
mounting pressure to declare a state on May 4. That is the day when
a five-year transitional period of limited self-rule, established
under the Oslo peace agreement with Israel, was supposed to be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   But internationally, Arafat faces equally keen pressure to defer
any declaration, since many think it would provoke Israel to react
militarily and rupture the fragile understandings built through
years of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Most Israeli, Palestinian and U.S. experts believe that Arafat
is leaning toward delaying a statehood proclamation. Although he
has consistently referred to May 4 as a ``sacred date,'' he dropped
a couple of public hints in the last two days that he would be
willing to let it pass without making history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have an independent state sooner or later,'' Arafat
said in Sweden on Sunday, brushing off a question about May 4.
``It's a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arafat is clearly seeking international guarantees that
he can present to his people, evidence that there will be a payoff
for a postponement. This might include pledges to accept a future
Palestinian state, promises of more financial assistance or limited
but immediate recognition of Palestinian sovereignty by
international institutions that lend money, issue satellite
frequencies, and mediate trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, Arafat has traveled Europe and the Arab
world extensively, from Finland to Bahrain. Tuesday's meeting in
Washington with President Clinton will be the second in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unlikely that Clinton will promise to advance
diplomatic recognition of a Palestinian state. The Clinton
administration has long insisted that both Israelis and
Palestinians refrain from taking any unilateral action on the
issues _ like statehood _ that are supposed to be hammered out in
the final status negotiations between them.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton gives Arafat a kind of international recognition
just by meeting with him in the White House _ especially given what
the Israelis have dubbed the American ``snub diplomacy'' toward
their prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has not visited the White House at all this year,
although Yitzhak Mordechai, his former defense minister who is
challenging him for prime minister in the May 17 elections, was a
guest there last week.
</P>
<P>
   As Arafat flew to Washington Monday, Netanyahu was in Russia,
prompting some sarcastic commentary from Israeli columnists.
``There was a time when Israeli politicians were invited to
Washington, and Arab leaders went to Moscow,'' Akiva Eldar wrote in
the daily Haaretz Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why Arafat may not be eager to rush a
declaration of statehood. The most important is that he would not
want to make an empty pronouncement. That would invite comparisons
to 1988 when, while still in exile, he issued a declaration of
independence from Algiers that many Palestinians have since mocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he can declare statehood and everything is
transformed,'' said Itamar Rabinowitz, a professor at Tel Aviv
University, a former peace negotiator and the former Israeli
ambassador to Washington. ``The calculus is complex for Arafat.
Over what territory does he announce statehood? If it's only the
land they have so far, why bother? If it's more, then he draws
lines that make future negotiations difficult. And there will be
future negotiations no matter what.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also, many believe that a declaration of statehood by Arafat
would enhance Netanyahu's chance for re-election by scaring or
angering potential swing voters, pushing them to support his
right-wing campaign. If Netanyahu launched a retaliatory military
action _ by annexing parts of the West Bank, as he has threatened _
many Israelis would rally behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat speaks in various voices on the subject of Palestinian
statehood, depending on his audience. Last Friday, addressing a
rally in Ramallah, Arafat was his fiery revolutionary self. He
promised to ``wage battles,'' if necessary, to defend his right to
declare a state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state will be established with Jerusalem as its capital,
whether they like it,'' he said, continuing with a variation on an
Arabic saying, ``If they don't like it, they can drink from the
waters of the Dead Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, in Paris, before he flew on to Washington,
Arafat spoke like a diplomat. He said he was willing to defer a
statehood declaration if the Israelis, who have frozen the most
recent peace memorandum, engaged in ``precise and honest compliance
with everything that has been signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, arguing that the Palestinians had violated their
obligations under the latest peace memorandum, froze Israel's
compliance with the agreement in December, shortly before a
deadline to turn over a chunk of West Bank land. A few weeks later,
his government was dissolved by parliament, and Israel plunged into
a volatile election campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat does delay a statehood declaration, it is likely to be
only a short delay. After the Israeli elections, the new prime
minister will have to move quickly to reestablish peace
negotiations, analysts say. Building on the framework of the Oslo
accord, the government would have to negotiate a new time line for
compliance with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The final status talks, which deal with the issues of borders,
Jerusalem and refugees, would have to get under way immediately,
analysts say _ or else, the same threats and counterthreats will
repeat themselves next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has been pressured to postpone a declaration of statehood
_ not just by Americans and Europeans but apparently by Jordanians
and Egyptians as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian foreign minister, Amr Moussa, said in Amman,
Jordan, last weekend that the decision on when to make the
declaration lies in Arafat's hands. But he added, ``The Palestinian
state is a strategic goal, but the timing is a tactical issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran military correspondent for the Yedioth Ahronoth
newspaper, Ron Ben Yishai, reported Monday that senior officials of
the Israeli Defense Ministry feel that Netanyahu is making too much
of Arafat's declarations about statehood to his own people. He
wrote that the officials felt that Netanyahu, by issuing threats,
risked backing Arafat into a corner where he must make such a
declaration ``so as not to be appear to be a coward in his people's
eyes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
