<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0052 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-PARTIES-2TAKES-     03-22 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PARTIES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRAMAX PARTY BASKS IN A GOLDEN GLOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ As the long day's journey into Oscar night slid
into the chilly morning after, Hollywood's new clown prince finally
sat down to eat.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier, Roberto Benigni had waltzed across the
seats of the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion, trying not to step on the
big-studio egos he'd already big-footed to a pulp.
</P>
<P>
   Now the doe-eyed Italian comic and friends were yakking it up at
the Governors Ball, basking in their overnight status as part of
the new Oscar aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling that unlikely roost of semi-famous foreign actors and
offbeat flicks was Miramax Films, the once-scrappy independent
turned even scrappier Disney affiliate. Cementing its position as
Oscar's unofficial tastemaker, Miramax blew away the majors again
this year with wins in four of the big six categories: best picture
(``Shakespeare in Love''), actor (Benigni), actress (Gwyneth
Paltrow) and supporting actress (Judi Dench), plus best
foreign-language film (``Life Is Beautiful,'' the all-Benigni,
all-the-time vehicle).
</P>
<P>
   As the moussed and tuxedoed multitudes headed off to party, the
big studios licked their wounds and took whatever solace they could
in Steven Spielberg's being named best director for ``Saving
Private Ryan'' _ the biggest casualty of a costly pre-Oscar
publicity war with ``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hollywood's old guard, the debut of ``Sunday at the Oscars''
was anything but super. Technical glitches and tedious shtick
marred the grueling four-hour telecast, the longest in Oscar's 71
years. The academy's controversial decision to bestow an honorary
statuette on director Elia Kazan added more gray hues to an evening
fitfully brightened by Benigni's over-the-top effusiveness and
Dench's regal dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why even the Governors Ball, the traditional first
stop on the post-Oscar pub crawl, seemed subdued.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming through Listerine-colored lighting, with fabric
treatments and tablecloths to match, guests scarfed down white
herb-crusted salmon and chocolates shaped like vintage movie
cameras. The menu, courtesy of Wolfgang Puck, was inscribed on
individual pewter-framed party favors at each place setting.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd thinned out around 11, Warren Beatty and Annette
Bening could be seen chatting quietly with another couple near the
entrance. Gil Cates, producer of the interminable telecast, looked
like a man who could use a drink _ or a nice cup of Earl Grey tea.
By half past midnight, only a few die-hards were still getting
jiggy with the '70s boogie tunes. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
Miramax headroom &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across town, (night) life was a lot more beautiful at the
Miramax party in the Polo Lounge of the Beverly Hills Hotel, where
the studio celebrated winning 10 Oscars, including best picture for
``Shakespeare in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   The lounge, still a preeminently kitschy monument to Old
Hollywood, was stuffed with party-goers, despite being a relatively
tough ticket among A-list parties for the night.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner, best actor nominee Nick Nolte sat with girlfriend
Vicki Lewis, who plays the ditsy redheaded secretary on NBC's
``NewsRadio,'' at a small reserved table.
</P>
<P>
   She looked fabulous in a foam-green, form-fitting, vaguely
Elizabethan outfit with a corsetted top, floor-length skirt and
wonderful beading over a knee-length jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte, meanwhile, was nose-to-nose talking with evil twin Gary
Busey, who had a dark-haired beauty in tow. At other points, Nolte
was leaning back, puffing cigarettes and watching the room.
</P>
<P>
   The very sweet Lewis said they had decided against going to the
always-crazy scene surrounding the Vanity Fair party a couple of
miles away at West Hollywood's Morton's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In another corner, new Miramax adviser and former Vanity Fair
editor Tina Brown was schmoozing by the table reserved for
playwright Tom Stoppard, who co-wrote ``Shakespeare'' and won an
Oscar for it, and some of the movie's producers.
</P>
<P>
   Near Brown was her longtime associate, former Vanity Fair
publisher Ron Galotti, who came with her from the Conde Nast chain
when Brown signed a deal with Miramax to develop a new magazine and
other media properties. Galotti is to be the publisher of Brown's
new Miramax magazine, called Blather.
</P>
<P>
   By the entrance, shorthaired and just-plain-short singer Michael
Bolton, looking dapper and tan, was eyeing the crowd as it came in.
</P>
<P>
   In a side room, best actor winner Roberto Benigni was in a booth
with his family and decidedly not dancing on tables, chairs, other
stars or anyone's jokes.
</P>
<P>
   After a relentlessly ebullient evening both in front of the
camera and backstage before journalists, the previously effusive
Benigni managed to restrain himself quietly while the party raged
on around him.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, best supporting actor nominee (and previous
Oscar winner for ``Shine'') Geoffrey Rush smoked a series of
cigarettes in that flat-handed style so popular among English and,
it appears, Aussie artsy types, while posing for pictures with
admirers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the sushi and salmon bar (simply
scrumptious, by the way), South African sex kitten Charlize Theron
cemented her S&AMP;M credentials (already jacked sky-high by the
catfight scene in ``Two Days in the Valley'' a couple of years
back) with a floor-length black rubber skirt and brunette tresses
pulled tight against her head.
</P>
<P>
   Next to her was boyfriend and Third Eye Blind lead singer
Stephen Jenkins, with bad mutton-chop facial hair and a rocker's
look, as they picked through the food and chatted with numerous
well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   Another young couple in love, Rachael Leigh Cook and Ryan
Alosio, murmured like turtledoves as they moved through the room.
They are co-stars in ``The Hi-Line,'' a recent Sundance Film
Festival entry, and she appears regularly in ``Dawson's Creek'' and
recently starred in the teen ``Pygmalion''-esque flick ``She's All
That.''
</P>
<P>
   Out front, in the maddening push of limos, red-carpet paparazzi
and TV cameras, and general craziness, Vondie Curtis-Hall
(``Chicago Hope'') beat an early retreat from the scene, as did
many others, long before best actress winner Gwyneth Paltrow
showed.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the night's Elizabethan tone, many of the women
at the party wore gowns evoking that era, with huge, space-eating
volumes of skirts and shoes just this side of stilts. Few men
ventured into fashion statements, sticking to tried-and-true tuxedo
black. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
Your Standard affair &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scene was much different over at the even more exclusive
party at the Standard Hotel on the Sunset Strip.
</P>
<P>
   The recently opened hotel is owned by Andre Balacz, who also
owns Chateau Marmont a couple of miles down the strip and the Soho
Grande in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard, however, is a totally different kind of joint from
those two hotels, with a vibe that crosses Judy Jetson '60s
Futurama design with a decidedly postmodern irony.
</P>
<P>
   There's the live nudes, some of them pierced, shaved and
tattooed, that recline in turns on green-lit see-through inflatable
pillows in a wall cutout above and behind the check-in area.
</P>
<P>
   There's the diner area, taken pretty much from 1956, with curves
on every corner and waitresses wearing Madge clothes over their own
youthful curves.
</P>
<P>
   There's the blue, cushioned AstroTurf around the pool balcony,
cottage-cheese ceiling stucco, hanging ball-shaped plastic chairs,
and orange wall panels in the bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The look merged with a decidedly younger crowd from the Miramax
'do, with more same-sex couples, more gaunt but beautiful models of
both genders and more relentless hipness. And, as promised in the
invitation made to look like a food-ingredient label, the party had
``0 grams of photographers.''
</P>
<P>
   The early party in the hotel's lobby and other public areas
started to break up when the bars shut down around 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ( &LR; SECOND TAKE FOLLOW) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But another, much more exclusive party was already going on in
a red-lit room tucked off the diner. While the famous eased past
several beefy security guards blocking the diner's glass doors,
others pressed to get through _ with no luck. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Matt Dillon, recently shorn of former flame Cameron Diaz,
arrived with best actor nominee Edward Norton and a pack of
hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   Norton's hot young manager, Rick Yorn of Michael Ovitz's new
company, also was at the party. Yorn _ the subject of a recent
Vanity Fair piece detailing Ovitz's behind-the-scenes war with
Creative Artists Agency _ the company he used to head _ also
represents Leonardo DiCaprio and Drew Barrymore among others.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Vince Vaughan showed, without his longtime girlfriend but
with permed hair, a beard and a distinct Elvis impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   Other young bachelors about town at the party included Adrian
Brody of ``The Thin Red Line'' and Steven Dorff of ``Blade.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more than models at the party, however, including
Marisa Tomei, Rose McGowan, Julia Ormond and Gena Gershon, as well
as Sofia Coppola, who is following in her father Francis' footsteps
and about to direct her first film, ``The Virgin Suicides.'' &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
The Elton way &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest tickets of the post-Oscar evening was Sir
Elton John and InStyle magazine's bash at Pagani on Melrose Avenue,
which raised $400,000 for the Elton John AIDS Foundation and
attracted more than 1,000 from the entertainment and fashion
industries.
</P>
<P>
   It officially started at 4:30 p.m. with a dinner of organic
carrot and ginger soup, Chilean sea bass with risotto and warm
chocolate tarts for dessert prepared by chef Claude Segal with host
Elton John (in a purple beaded suit) stopping at each table to make
sure everybody knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   Then they turned on huge banks of televisions so guests could
watch the Oscars from their tables _ and also in the huge bar and
stage set up in a clear plastic tent where you could see
helicopters buzzing and searchlights crossing overhead.
</P>
<P>
   After the Oscars were over, the celebs started pouring in as
soon as the extensive security committee allowed them onto the
leopard print carpet leading into the chi-chi restaurant. Among
them were Oscar nominees Ian McKellen, Cate Blanchett, Emily Watson
and Lynn Redgrave, as well as the usual A-list members such as
Helen Hunt, Geena Davis, Kevin Costner, Alec Baldwin, Kim Basinger,
Goldie Hawn and Kurt Russell, Val Kilmer, Ellen DeGeneres, Anne
Heche, Jim Carrey and William H. Macy.
</P>
<P>
   From the music industry were Lionel Ritchie, LeAnn Rimes, k.d.
lang, Rod Stewart, Janet Jackson, Natalie Cole, Whitney Huston,
Lisa Marie Presley, Mariah Carey and Donny Osmond, with a saucy
vocal group called the Pussy Cat Dolls performing ``Hey, Big
Spender,'' and other show tunes on the center stage.
</P>
<P>
   TV stars turned out, too. They ranged from old guard members
such as Jay Leno, Jane Seymour, Ed McMahon and Robert Wagner (with
daughters Natasha, Katie and Courtney) to the newer generation,
including ``Sabrina'' star Melissa Joan Hart, ``Felicity's'' Keri
Russell, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer's'' Sarah Michelle Gellar,
``The Practice'' stars Dillon McDermott and Camryn Manheim, as well
as ``Caroline in the City'' star Lea Thompson, a Valley girl who
said she came for a good time _ and a worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   The party was supposed to end at 2 a.m., but you know how
parties in L.A. are. They never stop until the fire marshals go in
and turn the lights out, which at Elton's soiree was about 3 a.m. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
`Saving Private' party &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best director Steven Spielberg and his ``Saving Private Ryan''
star Tom Hanks, a best actor nominee, showed up at the
DreamWorks/Paramount party at Barnaby's, where guests dined on raw
oysters, shiitake mushroom pizza and chicken pot pie.
</P>
<P>
   Handshaking. Hugs. Air kisses. Make that big wet kisses from
Italy's ``Life Is Beautiful'' Oscar winner Roberto Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the best picture award, there was head-shaking,
too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ( &LR; Daily News Staff Writers David Bloom, &UR;  &LR; Barbara De Witt &UR;  &LR; and
Reed Johnson &UR;  &LR; contributed to this story). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1905EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
