<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GROUPS SAY BUSH OPPOSES ABORTION RIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With opposite motives, two national organizations that speak out
on abortion are declaring that Gov. George W. Bush is against
abortion rights as he readies his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's a roller coaster for Bush, who was criticized a few weeks
ago by conservative activists and another Republican presidential
candidate for a perceived softening of his stance.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League started television advertisements in Iowa and New Hampshire
that say Bush and another prospective GOP candidate, Elizabeth
Hanford Dole, are ``anti-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The two states hold early, key contests in the presidential
nominating process next year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the anti-abortion National Right to Life Committee
said last week that Bush ``has a pro-life record and has taken a
pro-life position'' but that by portraying his stance as moderate,
the news media has been misrepresenting him.
</P>
<P>
   For his own part, Bush said Monday that he does not expect to
get everyone's vote if he runs for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't view it in terms of winning or losing, I just know
what I believe. I am pro-life,'' Bush told reporters in Austin,
Texas. ``I've had a clear and consistent position ever since I got
into politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the abortion rights group, Kate Michelman, told
a Washington news conference that presidential candidates are
trying to hide their ``extreme views'' against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Dole ``oppose a woman's right to choose'' abortion, she
said, ``but both know they must communicate more moderate views if
they are to be elected.'' If they don't tell the voters about their
real positions on abortion, she said, ``We will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot afford to allow a single American to be fooled,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Michelman's statements put NARRAL in the unusual position of
agreeing with the National Right to Life Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of criticizing Bush's stance on abortion, people who
want to ``save unborn children'' should focus on the ``extreme
pro-abortion position'' of the likely Democratic nominee, Vice
President Al Gore, the National Right To Life Committee said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Bush said the nation was not ready to overturn
Roe vs. Wade, the U.S. Supreme Court decision that made abortion
legal. Instead of arguing about the case, he said, ``what we ought
to do is promote policies that reduce abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush said he believed abortion was wrong and
abortions should be banned except in cases of rape, incest or a
threat to the life of the pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also refused to commit himself to keeping anti-abortion
language in the national GOP's platform.
</P>
<P>
   His statements were criticized by Gary Bauer, a GOP candidate,
and by other conservative activists. They said Bush was not taking
a strong enough stand against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   As for Dole, a spokesman told Reuters on Monday that she opposes
abortion and ``will say it in her own way and with her own words at
the appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Right To Life Committee has not seen any other
Republican candidate's stand distorted, executive director David
O'Steen said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if other candidates have taken a stronger position against
abortion than Bush, O'Steen said, ``I am not going to get into who
is more pro-life'' because all Republican candidates are in
essential agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Michelman told the Houston Chronicle that she saw a slight
difference between Bush and Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries to soften it _ and Elizabeth Dole simply won't answer
the question on the issue, and I think that is not acceptable,''
Michelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Both would appoint U.S. Supreme Court justices who would
overturn Roe vs. Wade, Michelman contended.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, Dole has not formally declared her candidacy. Both
have established exploratory committees that allow them to raise
and spend money to decide if they want to run.
</P>
<P>
   One potential Republican candidate, New York Gov. George Pataki,
says the party should jettison its official opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should focus on what divides us from Democrats and not what
divides us as Republicans,'' he told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Pataki came under fire from two GOP contenders for
taking that stand.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative commentator Pat Buchanan, appearing on ABC-TV's
``This Week'' program, said removing the anti-abortion plank from
the platform would ``start a civil war'' within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, appearing on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' said the
New York governor's support for abortion rights would disqualify
him from being on a Forbes-led ticket. Last year, the
multi-millionaire publisher had said Pataki should be on every GOP
candidate's short-list of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
