</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICES AT THE GAS PUMP RISE, AND ARE LIKELY TO CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have risen more than 8 cents a gallon over the
last two weeks and motorists, who had been enjoying the cheapest
gas in a generation, are likely to see further increases in the
weeks ahead, energy experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The price hike of 8.5 cents a gallon over the last two weeks _
to a nationwide average of $1.0869 per gallon for all grades of gas
on Friday _ represented one of the steepest short-term surges since
the Gulf War in 1990, according to a Lundberg Survey of 10,000 gas
stations that was released on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of major oil producers, including those from the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, announced two weeks
ago that they planned to cut production of crude oil by 2 million
barrels a day. OPEC is expected to ratify that decision on Tuesday,
and many experts say they believe that prices could increase
another 8 to 15 cents a gallon as the summer driving season
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, even after the recent spike, gasoline prices remain
extremely low by historical standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went up? I didn't notice,'' Yolanda Etaeper said Monday
as she filled up her Toyota at an Exxon station in Tenafly, N.J.,
where regular gasoline cost 95.9 cents a gallon, up from 90.9 cents
last week. ``What can you do?'' she said. ``You have to buy
gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the quickness and size of the recent increase has
surprised many drivers and some industry experts, who over the last
six months had grown accustomed to prices not seen since before the
oil embargo of 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Leuffer, an oil analyst with Bear Stearns, said that
the reason that refiners have been able to put through price
increases of about 15 cents a gallon on the wholesale level during
the last two weeks is ``because of very strong demand for gasoline.
It's been up 3.5 to four percent this year. That's a huge jump.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that refiners, meanwhile, are continuing using
lower-cost crude that they bought before the current run up in
prices, which will help their profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Generally it takes several weeks to pass through the higher cost
of crude to the wholesale level and then several weeks for
retailers to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was unusual,'' said Ed Rothshild, a consultant based in
Washington D.C. and long an observer of energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the profit that refiners have been making on
gasoline has been falling in recent months, so when crude oil
prices began to rise in anticipation of the cuts by the major oil
producers the oil industry saw a glimmer of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not begin raising prices now rather than wait?'' was the
approach taken by the refiners, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus prices for gasoline at the wholesale level began to rise
sharply in some regions as early as mid-February even before crude
oil prices began to recover.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many station owners have been scrambling to keep up with their
sharply rising wholesale costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been going up continually,'' said Denise Pristera, a
manager at the Exxon on Dean Drive in Tenafly. ``I think it will go
up to $1 for regular.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil reached a low for this year in
mid-February when the price of the benchmark West Texas
Intermediate dipped to $11.37 in trading on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil for April delivery rose by 26 cents Monday to close at
$15.50 a barrel, the highest closing price since Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, in anticipation of the decision by major oil
producers to make substantial cuts, crude oil has risen by well
over $3 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Struth, an economist for Phillips Petroleum, said that
generally there is an increase of 2.4 cents a gallon in the price
of gasoline at the retail level for every $1 rise in the price of
crude.
</P>
<P>
   The higher price of crude combined with the seasonal
introduction of gasoline with lower volatility, which costs more to
make, he said, was about in line with an 8 cent a gallon average
rise the price of gasoline at the pump, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline margins have been very low through early March and
they are just beginning to recover,'' he said. ``There is some snap
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the industry can continue to further increase prices is
still uncertain, although there are some favorable trends for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Inventories of gasoline showed a sharp drop last week. Demand
has been unusually strong due to a seasonal upturn in driving, the
strong economy and the continuing growth in the number of sport
utility vehicles, which have lower gas mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the current sharp jump prices were still on the
average only about one cent higher than in a similar period last
year and well below the high of $1.33 a gallon of September of 1997
before prices began to weaken.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Lattif who is president of Gateway Industries of
Danbury Connecticut, a company that imports auto and body parts and
who keeps a fleet of six vans, said the higher prices will increase
his costs. So he watches the pump price carefully and keeps up with
the latest news from OPEC on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been going up all week,'' he added as he waited for his
credit card receipt at the Tenafly Exxon station. Still, he viewed
the price, 5 cents a gallon higher than the previous week, as a
good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``At another station its gone up about 9 cents gallon,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
