A0058 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-HOMES23-COX     03-22 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CITIZENS TELL OF NEED FOR STRONGER NURSING HOME REGULATION
 &HT;    480&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Private citizens and government officials told
Congress on Monday that stronger investigation and enforcement is
needed of nursing home problems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came at the Senate Special Committee on Aging's
second hearing to examine the quality of nursing home care that
more than 1.6 million elderly and disabled Americans receive each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're looking at allegations of poor care that never
reach the enforcers,'' said Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman
of the committee. ``The unresponsiveness to complaints is
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Bryant showed the panel a sketch of what her aunt,
Catherine Hunt, looked like with her head and neck caught in the
guard rails of a bed. An aide in Hunt's Michigan nursing home found
her unresponsive after getting caught between the mattress and the
bed's guard rail. Hunt died of asphyxia at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aunt Catherine had several unexplained injuries, was left wet
and soiled on many occasions, and suffered many other
indignities,'' Bryant said. ``I often complained about the
neglectful conditions, but it did little good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant called the government's inquiry into her complaints a
``drive-by'' investigation in which the nursing home was given a
grace period to correct the problems with the beds and was ordered
to pay a $100 fine as a result of her aunt's death.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional insert.)
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Cruz told the panel that a Maryland nursing home
transferred her critically ill grandmother, Elsie Wagner, to a
nursing home closer to her family. After her grandmother died one
week later, Wagner's physician told Cruz that she would have lived
had she been hospitalized immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After writing a letter to the state Licensing and Certification
Administration for nursing homes and the attorney general's office,
Cruz said, the administration informed her they were very busy with
complaints, but assured her an investigation would be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me they deal with the live residents before they
deal with the dead ones,'' Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional insert.)
</P>
<P>
   A congressional study released at the hearing showed that in
certain states, inadequate practices and limited guidance from the
federal Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA) led to
undesirable policies and practices.
</P>
<P>
   These included a limited number of complaints being filed, a
failure to investigate serious complaints that alleged harmful
situations, and incomplete reports on nursing homes' compliance
with HCFA regulations and complaint investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that too often there is a yo-yo pattern where homes
cycle in and out of compliance,'' said William J. Scanlon of the
General Accounting Office, the investigating arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier GAO report found that more than one-fourth of the
17,000 nursing homes studied nationwide had serious deficiencies,
including inadequate prevention of pressure sores, failure to
prevent accidents, and failure to assess residents' needs and
provide appropriate care. While many of the homes corrected these
deficiencies, about 40 percent of the homes were found to be repeat
violators, Scanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   In its new report, the GAO recommended that HCFA strengthen both
its standards and oversight of states' complaint practices. Other
recommendations were to improve the HCFA management information
systems to include complaint investigation results and to more
effectively identify and respond to homes with recurring problems.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Also at Monday's hearing, George F. Grob, deputy inspector
general for the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, said
that studies of various aspects of the quality of nursing home care
in 10 states also showed that problems with the quality of care
still exist. The states were Florida, Texas, Ohio, New York,
California, Illinois, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, New Jersey, and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the problems I have been talking about suggest that
inadequate levels of nursing home staff contribute to this poor
quality of care,'' Grob said.
</P>
<P>
   The studies also found problems with survey and certification
processes in several states, law enforcement of complaints and
family involvement in caring for elder loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   HCFA declined to send a representative to testify at the hearing
after the committee refused to allow the agency to testify prior to
the testimony of the private citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of (the citizens') testimony ... is that they lived
and suffered through the response process that HCFA oversees,''
Grassley said. ``It's the testimony of citizen witnesses like these
that Congress, HCFA, and the public can learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
