<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANCE AND FOLK TALES IN A TROUPE FROM TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Unlike modern dance, ballet has apparently not
thrived in Taiwan, where its popularity and training have waxed and
waned. Capital Ballet-Tapei, a small 10-year-old troupe that
performed at the Taipei Theater in Manhattan on Sunday afternoon,
suggests a promising path taken, with work still to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The program's four works were choreographed by Hsu Chin-feng,
the company's founder-director, and his wife Hsu Lee Shu-hui, who
is artistic director. Hsu, who has an economics degree from
National Cheng-chi University, and his wife were both dancers in
the defunct Theater Ballet-Taipei, founded in 1980 by Marsha
Wales-Brown, a Westerner who had lived in Singapore and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The Capital Ballet's members, graduates of dance departments of
the National Taiwan Academy of Arts and Chinese Cultural
University, are well schooled in classical style and on this
program were not called upon to exhibit exceptional virtuosity. In
the United States their company would be classed as a regional
ballet troupe.
</P>
<P>
   It is also obviously a creative instrument for its directors,
whose choreography sometimes draws upon Taiwanese cultural images.
Perhaps coincidentally, two of Hsu's works had a protagonist
sacrifice the object of his or her love.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Portrait of Romeo,'' inspired by a book, ``Strange Tales
From Liao-chai's Studio,'' a woman (Yeh Li-chuan) prefers to
destroy the man she loves rather than see him seduced by a rival
(Wang Mei-hua). The man (Liu Chi-ya) was pictured as a dream figure
with a white mask who comes to life when the mask is removed and
who becomes inanimate again when the heroine replaces the mask on
him.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography, set to Chopin, used conventional ballet steps
with Ms. Yeh and especially Liu, dancing fluently.
</P>
<P>
   Gesture was dominant in ``Sculptor and Goddess,'' which looked
like a Chinese ``Coppelia'' when Chen Chao-yu, as an aged sculptor,
removed a drape from Ms. Yeh, a statue come to life in a doll
dance. Things took a nicely dramatic turn when she pleaded to
remain human but was ``turned'' into a temple sculpture after being
imbued by a divine force. Chao Pei-chun was her fellow but immobile
goddess. The music was by Chu Yun-sung.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike these two pungent pieces, the others needed editing and
suffered from repeated false endings. Nonetheless, Chen Ling-wen,
Ms. Chao, Shih Ya-ling, Lee Shen-chi and the especially promising
Lu Hsin-yi had the right neo-Romantic style in ``Chopin Pas de
Cinque.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amis Images,'' by Ms. Hsu Lee, would look better if shorter:
But the company, which also includes Chen Yu-mei and Su Shih-chien,
plunged with energy into this mixture of ballet and folk dance,
drawn from Taiwan's Amis aboriginal people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
