<HEADER>
A0080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-800&AMP;ADD-N     03-22 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO THREATENS AIRSTRIKES AGAINST SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA) 
(jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO allies stepped up their threats
Monday, giving their top civilian leader the authority to mount
airstrikes directly against Serbian forces who are attacking ethnic
Albanian separatists in Kosovo province. The expanded authority is
subject to consultation with Western leaders.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana already had the authority
to send an initial barrage of pilotless cruise missiles against
selected Serbian military targets, followed by a systematic
campaign to destroy Serbian anti-aircraft missile-launching sites
and other air-defense installations.
</P>
<P>
   But the threat hanging over President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia since the end of January has clearly not been enough to
make him to call off attacks against the ethnic Albanian majority
in Kosovo and accept a peace accord that would provide autonomy for
the province and 28,000 peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian representatives in the Paris talks signed the
agreement on Thursday. The talks broke down the next day.
</P>
<P>
   While Western leaders have been agonizing over their decision,
Milosevic has had four full days to send thousands of heavily armed
troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance officials said Monday that intelligence reports showed
3,000 to 5,000 Serb troops with tanks and other armored vehicles
were moving toward Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, from
Montenegro, which along with Serbia, constitutes what remains of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO official said a similar force was moving south toward the
province from Serbia to reinforce the 40,000 Yugoslav army troops
and Interior Ministry police officers who began an offensive
against the base areas of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army after
the Paris talks had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for a more effective deterrent to the Serbian attacks,
the Clinton administration had sought to broaden Solana's
authority. With no sign of a pause in the offensive, the allies
agreed to let Solana broaden air operations, subject to
consultations with allied leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance officials here said Solana could approve intense
strikes by more than 400 American, British and French warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Milosevic agreed to limits on troops and police
officers in talks with U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke. That agreement
has long since been abrogated.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration sought the sharper threat to give
Holbrooke and other mediators leverage in ``last-chance''
negotiations with Milosevic on Monday in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to Belgrade under instructions from the secretary
of state and the president to talk, but not to talk while the
fighting gets worse and the rampage continues,'' Holbrooke said
after having conferred here with Solana and the allies' top
military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the moment of truth,'' Solana said. ``Mr.
Holbrooke has everything he needs from NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said he had also received full backing from Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine of France and British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook, co-chairmen of the Paris talks, in a breakfast meeting
with them and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer of Germany here
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   If Holbrooke succeeds, the threats will have been enough and the
allies will not be forced to break with Russia, which along with
Britain, France, Germany, Italy and the United States, has been
trying to find a diplomatic solution to the crisis for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he had 400 aircraft and dozens of ships armed with
cruise missiles ready to strike. ``The crews are ready, the
equipment is ready,'' he said. ``We know what the Serb capabilities
are. We know what the Serb vulnerabilities are. If required, we
will strike in swift and severe fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   His military headquarters at Mons in southern Belgium and the
sprawling NATO headquarters on the eastern outskirts of Brussels
were gearing up for sustained combat operations, officials said.
They are planning daily meetings of the 19 ambassadors here and
news briefings by allied commanders on airstrikes, if they are
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise missiles would be launched, officials said, from allied
naval vessels in the Adriatic and from eight-engine American B-52
bombers that would fly from Britain. Serbian air defenses include
hundreds of surface-to-air missiles and anti-aircraft guns
scattered around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials acknowledged that bombing units scattered
around the province might cause civilian casualties too, but said
pilots would do their best to minimize the effects. ``Any use of
force carries risks,'' one diplomat said. ``But there are civilian
casualties every day now in Kosovo without any NATO bombing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Without ``spotters'' on the ground to guide planes to moving
targets like troop concentrations and heavy M-84 tanks, accuracy
would diminish, military experts said.
</P>
<P>
   But American and allied strategists said the airstrikes would
considerably weaken Serbian forces. ``We hope at the least that
bombing would make Milosevic more likely to accept negotiations
later, if not right away,'' a senior diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   All the allies make little secret of their hope that Milosevic
will realize that after all the months of threats and blustering,
this time the allies mean business and that he will stop the
attacks and accept an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   All the allies, without exception, according to officials here,
are loath to order the 12,000 American, British, French and German
peacekeepers gathered in Macedonia to fight their way into Kosovo
to force the Serbs to accept peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not thinking of any forced entry into Kosovo,'' an
allied official said, ``and no NATO ally is asking for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
