<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD STARS OUT-`RADICAL' EACH OTHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to tell, reading the Hollywood issue of the Nation,
whether the six ``politically active members of the entertainment
community'' _  &UR; Warren Beatty &LR; ,  &UR; Alec Baldwin &LR; ,  &UR; Danny Glover &LR; ,
 &UR; Tim &LR; 
 &UR; Robbins &LR; ,  &UR; Oliver Stone  &LR; and &UR; Norman Lear  &LR; _ were together in one
room at one time for their ``conversation'' on ``Movies, Money &AMP;
Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   They agree on most things, among them disillusionment with
 &UR; President Clinton &LR; , disgust over the impeachment proceedings, the
notion of a right-wing conspiracy out to get the president and, in
general, a fondness for a liberal agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But while Baldwin, for example, threw a well-publicized
fund-raising party for Clinton in the Hamptons last summer, Glover,
without mentioning that event specifically, took exception to the
process. ``Campaigning and raising money, the whole thing with
Clinton or  &UR; Gore  &LR; and those guys,'' he said, ``I refuse to do it.
Those guys who want to sleep in the Oval Office, sleep in the
mansion, it's about access.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, in the nicest terms, of course, Baldwin tries to
demonstrate that HE'S more radical than Glover. ``I think political
activism has negatively impacted my career,'' he said. ``I wish I
had been more like Danny Glover, aggressively steering my career
more toward a box-office franchise kind of career, doing the
`Lethal Weapons,' and having those successes over and over and over
again. And you say to yourself, that's a guy that's generated
enough economic good will in the community to be able to do some of
the other things he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REMEMBERING JOE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A memorial for  &UR; Joe DiMaggio  &LR; is being ``quietly planned'' in
New York, says the New York Post, to be held next month at St.
Patrick's Cathedral. So far,  &UR; Henry Kissinger &LR; , for some reason or
other, is said to be the first choice to deliver the eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other celebrities who have expressed interest in
participating:  &UR; Jack Nicholson &LR; ,  &UR; Woody Allen &LR; ,  &UR; Kevin Costner &LR; ,
 &UR; Michael Bolton &LR;  and &UR; Tom Hanks &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S. New York Mets catcher  &UR; Mike Piazza &LR; , seen watching C-SPAN
at spring training, told a Newsday reporter that he's a
conservative and might run for office someday. ``I think I could
get into it,'' he said. ``Some of it is fascinating. I like the
range of opinions and ideologies in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep.  &UR; Mike Oxley &LR; , R-Ohio, who coaches the GOP team for the
annual Congressional Softball Game, told Roll Call he'd be happy to
have Piazza join his team. He said Piazza might be a little
disappointed with a congressional salary, $136,700 a year, but ``we
do provide Egg McMuffins and black coffee at practices and hot dogs
at the picnic. So we're not totally without resources.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
