   &UR; GLOBAL FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In response to last week's item about British complaints that
American moviemakers are taking credit for the British achievement
of cracking Hitler's encryption code,  &UR; Jon Ahlberg &LR;  points an
accusing finger at the 1952 British film ``Breaking the Sound
Barrier,'' in which a British flier _ not &UR; Chuck Yeager &LR;  _ was
pictured as first to break the sound barrier. And several irate
readers, among them  &UR; Stan Deresinski &LR; , noted that the person who
cracked Hitler's encryption codes was neither British nor American
but a Pole,  &UR; Marian Rejewski &LR; . And regarding nude ski vacations
mentioned herein,  &UR; Clark Peterson  &LR; recommends ``It's a Small World
After All'' as appropriate music.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gar Smith  &LR; noticed an Associated Press report last week that
identified the chief counselor to the prime minister of Hungary:
 &UR; Laszlo Toth &LR; .  &UR; Lazlo Toth  &LR; is also the letter-writing alter ego of
 &UR; Don Novello &LR; ; &UR; Lazlo Toth  &LR; was also the name of the Australian who
attacked the ``Pieta'' with a hammer in 1972. Novello says it's a
very common name.
</P>
<P>
   _ England's  &UR; Queen Mother &LR; , 98, is $6.5 million in debt, says
the Sunday Express, because of a high-rolling lifestyle that
includes expensive champagne, jewelry and clothing. Buckingham
Palace says the newspaper's report that she may have to move out of
Clarence House to pay off her debts is ``speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ German Chancellor  &UR; Gerhard Schroeder &LR;  is to appear as a
fashion model in a spring-summer Brioni catalog.
</P>
