<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-ART-NYT &LR;      03-22 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REBELS CALL FOR NATO AIRSTRIKES, AS FIGHTING CONTINUES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct slug;   no other changes)   (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLJANCE, Yugoslavia _ The general commander of the Kosovo
Liberation Army called for NATO to launch airstrikes on Serbia to
put an end to the bloodshed, as Yugoslav army and police forces
continued their ransacking and burning of villages Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special police units were setting houses and farm buildings
ablaze here Monday afternoon, leaving a trail of dead cows and
downed wire fences, before pulling back to their base in Srbica. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no terrorists here,'' said the officer, referring to
the ethnic Albanian rebels. ``It is all calm,'' he said as he led
out a column of 20 armored vehicles and police jeeps packed with
armed men. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost every second house in this sprawling village was on fire.
Flames leapt from the windows of houses beside the main road, while
others were already gutted shells, still smoldering, their
blackened rafters collapsed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon police forces in camouflage and carrying
automatic weapons, spare magazines strapped across their chests,
walked wearily up the road and gathered at the top of the village.
They climbed into jeeps, the day's work apparently over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two dark blue armored troop carriers and a vehicle mounted with
an anti-aircraft gun accompanied the column out of the burning
village. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police riding on top waved their guns, and raised a Serbian
three-finger salute as they passed. Further down the road two
stragglers walked away from a burning house and fired a burst of
gunfire into the air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the operation was going on, the top commander of the KLA,
Suleyman Selimi, accused the Serbian military of using heavier
weaponry against his people than ever before, and called on the
international community to act to stop the bloodshed in Kosovo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are using more modern weapons. The kind of tanks are more
sophisticated and they are using new mortars, 120-200 mm, as well
as ground-to-ground missiles,'' Selimi said of the Serbian military
Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the KLA had signed the peace agreement because they
trusted the West and he thought NATO airstrikes on Serbian military
hardware would stop the violence. ``I think if they want to stop
the violence, they should do that,'' he said of the NATO threat of
strikes. ``If we did not trust them we would not have signed the
peace deal.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a two-story house high in the Drenica region, some 30
kilometers northwest of the provincial capital Pristina, Selimi,
who is known among fighters and villagers by his nom de guerre,
Sultan, has a view of villages for miles around. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, missiles fired from a multiple rocket
launcher were audible, as was the whoosh and detonation a few
seconds later on impact. Smoke rose from Poljance and the
surrounding area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Selimi said Serbian forces had fired powerful ground-to-ground
missiles from positions near Istok, 40 kilometers away near the
provincial border with Montenegro on Sunday. Three hit the village
of Likovac, where the KLA headquarters are based, but landed
harmlessly in a field, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A foreign doctor from Medecins du Monde running a mobile clinic
in a nearby village confirmed that mortars were hitting civilian
areas, saying he had treated two civilians wounded by mortar fire
on Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fighting of recent weeks has been some of the heaviest since
last summer. Selimi said he had lost 47 men in the last three weeks
of fighting. But he said the KLA had inflicted casualties on the
Serbian forces as well.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Selimi, who is more than 6 feet tall and a former soccer player,
cuts an athletic figure. He wears combat fatigues and a short
military haircut. Soft-spoken, even shy, he said he studied metal
engineering in college and became one of the founding members of
the KLA in the early 1990s when he was a student. He is only 28 but
commands obvious respect from fighters and civilians alike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said his forces had knocked out three Serbian tanks in a
battle for the village of Prekaz on Saturday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said his strategy was to try to defend villages as long as
possible as a conventional army would, to delay the Serbian
advance. But he acknowledged that his fighters were in no position
to compete with Serbian forces, with their heavy guns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end the most important thing is not to lose any men,''
he said.  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He accused the Serbs of carrying out a scorched-earth policy,
trying to clear the area of civilians and soldiers, and then
sending in infantry to raze villages, burn crops and kill
livestock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Their aims are ethnic cleansing of the Albanian population and
the destruction of the KLA,'' he said. ``By this they aim to keep
Kosovo under their control.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were unconfirmed reports of killings of ethnic Albanians
in Srbica over the weekend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Selimi said he had heard that six people were killed by Serbian
police in Srbica, but he said he had only personally interviewed
one woman. She told him that her husband had been shot in front of
her and her children, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A teacher, Sabit Veliki, whose family lives in Pristina, was
killed in Srbica Saturday, according to the chief editor of the
Albanian language daily, Koha Ditore. The editor, Baton Haxhiu,
said he interviewed a man who was arrested with the teacher and
later released.
</P>
<P>
   The Council for the Defense of Human Rights and Freedom in
Pristina has collected a list of 15 men reported arrested and
missing by their relatives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Without intervention from the West, the Serbian offensive would
escalate and sweep not just the Drenica region but the whole
province, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he maintained it could not defeat the KLA. ``We will be here
no matter how they react,'' Haxhiu said. ``We will hang on as long
as we can. Kosovo never belonged to the Serbs, the Albanians will
be here always.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Violence exploded in Pristina late Monday night when two attacks
occurred on an ethnic Albanian cafe and a restaurant. One person
was reported killed and several wounded. A heavy police presence
scared people off the streets amid reports of beatings and
harassment of civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
