<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-HNS &LR;      03-22 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Running down his postgame checklist, Mike Krzyzewski made all the
appropriate stops.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trajan Langdon: outstanding when Duke needed him most.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Brand: a force on the inside for the Blue Devils, as
always.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carrawell: steady as ever and unsung as they come.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Maggette: some dunk, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Then the Duke coach got to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course,'' he said, ``Will led us.''
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski, en route to his eighth Final Four and fifth in the
1990s, was not talking about grit or determination here. Instead,
he was referencing ``Will'' as in William Avery, the Blue Devils'
brilliant young point guard.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Avery held only part of this job. Things have
changed. Now, with the Madness of March finally reduced to the
white-hot spotlight of the Final Four, the sophomore will be asked
to close the deal, running the show in St. Petersburg, Fla., for a
team that is not supposed to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? What pressure?
</P>
<P>
   ``Will has done the job for us all year,'' said Langdon, voted
the outstanding player of the East Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Avery will be asked to do it again. Nor will he lack
high-profile backcourt company as college basketball's elite
convene at Tropicana Field for what shapes up as a pointed weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, Duke's semifinal opponent, is led by its own
point man, junior Mateen Cleaves. Connecticut brings Khalid
El-Amin, the little fat kid who usually comes up big when it
matters most. Ohio State, in turn, shows up with Scoonie Penn, the
transfer from Boston College who was named the outstanding player
in the South Regional and may be playing the best of any of them
right now.
</P>
<P>
   Four for Florida, with much at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever one turns out to be the best little big man on college
basketball's biggest stage may have much to say about whose team
will be cutting down the nets come Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, William Avery felt the heat. It was one thing
splitting this job with Steve Wojciechowski a year ago, since the
pressure was mostly on the senior.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wojo was gone, and a sophomore was left with the task of
making a promising season special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like challenges,'' he said. ``I wanted to prove to everybody
that I could do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery responded, being named Most Valuable Player of the Great
Alaska Shootout early on and rolling into the East Regional
averaging 15.1 points and nearly six assists per game. He wasn't
quite as spectacular in New Jersey but still managed 13 points and
four assists in the East final against Temple's aggressive matchup
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Others scored more, grabbed more rebounds and shot better from
the field. Carrawell even topped the team in assists with seven.
Avery ended up bleeding from a cut on the leg and needing a moment
or two to recover from being poked in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' he said later. ``I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   All in a day's work, and Langdon was quick to acknowledge the
source of many of his 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``William did a great job of getting me the ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Will led. It might not have jumped out from the box
score, but folks who know him best appreciated the effort.
</P>
<P>
   For Mateen Cleaves, the road to St. Petersburg has been bumpy,
to say the least. Early in the season, he struggled with his
shooting, and his team followed suit as its leader tried to find
his way.
</P>
<P>
   In the NCAA Tournament, Cleaves has been up-and-down but good
enough to get the job done. Against Oklahoma in the Midwest
Regional semifinal, he missed his first eight shots. Against
Kentucky, however, he finished with 10 points and 11 assists as the
Spartans rallied from an early 13-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a melting pot on our team,'' said MSU coach Tom
Izzo. ``But for some reason, they all gravitate to him.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cleaves goes, so goes Michigan State. So far, he has gone
well enough to lead the way to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   He hears the fat jokes wherever he goes. At Stanford, the crowd
was particularly merciless, chanting suggestions that UConn's point
guard was not only a bit on the chunky side but a deadbeat dad,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't very classy,'' said Khalid El-Amin, a father of
two.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin responded more pointedly. With backcourt mate Richard
Hamilton out with an injury, the object of ridicule led the way
with 23 points, five assists and five steals as the Huskies picked
up a big late-season road win.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton gets more recognition, but El-Amin, a sophomore, gets
the point. His next charge is to get some points after a dreadful
West Regional final against Gonzaga, a game in which he got into
early foul trouble and missed all 12 of his shots but still managed
to make some clutch free throws in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Of the foursome, Scoonie Penn is the most unlikely entry, coming
from a team that bucked the odds to advance as a No. 4 seed,
upsetting Auburn and St. John's to emerge from the South.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, though, he might be the hottest commodity of the
group.
</P>
<P>
   Penn is averaging 17.5 points in the Tournament. Against St.
John's in the regional final, he chipped in eight rebounds as well.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been more instrumental in Ohio State's turnaround
from 8-22 last year to its first Final Four trip in 31 years. And
none of it comes as a particular shock to Penn, who predicted an
NCAA berth this season before many others considered it a
reasonable goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody thought we could do it,'' he said. ``But
here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, his matchup with El-Amin could go a long way toward
determining who will play for the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a tremendous backcourt,'' Penn said of the
Huskies. ``When I watch UConn on TV, I usually root for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun to play against those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   When you get this far, it's supposed to be. As the likes of
Avery, Cleaves, El-Amin and Penn understand, having fun is part of
the point.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
