<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOGGY BOTTOM OPENS A CRATERING SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 28)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics. Double parentheses
should be set as brackets. The word AT in parentheses should be
replaced by the ``at'' symbol.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sent a message to Serbian
strongman Slobodan Milosevic via Charles Gibson on ABC's
revitalized ``Good Morning America'': ``Whichever side  &UR; cratered &LR; 
the talks would be held responsible.'' The use of that verb was
surely planned and tested: The same night, the Queen of Foggy
Bottom repeated that high-impact figure of speech on Jim Lehrer's
``News Hour'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, we in the language dodge have been watching the
new verb, to  &UR; crater &LR; , undergo what we like to call ``sense
deterioration'' (much as  &UR; cunning &LR; , which originally meant
``knowledgeable,'' slipped in sense to ``slyly clever'').
</P>
<P>
   At first, the verb  &UR; crater &LR;  (originally a noun from the Latin
word for ``bowl,'' from the Greek ``to mix'') was intransitive,
meaning ``to form a hollow.'' In World War I, it learned how to
transmit action to an object, as ``scores of mine explosions had
 &UR; cratered &LR;  it.'' In World War II, Cecil Day Lewis gave the
terrifying term a poetic twist: ``Yet words there must be, wept on
the  &UR; cratered &LR;  present.''
</P>
<P>
   The verb, still associated with the pits and pockmarks left by
bombs, then gained its metaphoric extension. Following the Persian
Gulf war, during the 1992 presidential campaign, President George
Bush used the word to describe Saddam Hussein's grudging compliance
with U.N. inspection requirements: ``I'm glad that he  &UR; cratered &LR; 
once again.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it means ``collapse.'' In today's diplolingo, talks
 &UR; crater &LR; . In baseballese, pennant hopes  &UR; crater &LR; . In mutual fund
management jargon, ``sales lately have  &UR; cratered &LR; .'' With constant
use, the disastrous sense of a huge meteor slamming into Earth has
deteriorated; its slang sense shows signs of fading from
``collapse'' to merely ``abandon'' or ``cast aside,'' as in, ``We
 &UR; cratered &LR;  the project.'' I await the Arnold Schwarzenegger movie
``The  &UR; Craterer &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Like Judge Joseph Force Crater, who disappeared into a New York
City taxicab in 1930 and was never seen or heard of again, the
monosyllabic verb that this vogue usage has replaced _ the simple
but powerful  &UR; fail &LR;  _ has been all but lost to the public lingo of
movers and shakers. And to think how powerfully moving that little
verb once was. Words  &UR; crater &LR;  me.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, whatever became of the famous search for
the vanished jurist? According to a Detective Burns at the New York
Police Department, ``There has never been an arrest made on the
case, so it is not closed.'' For those still on the lookout, he's a
little, dignified guy with glasses, and he would now be 109 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   SCOT-FREE MUMBO JUMBO, TSK-TSK
</P>
<P>
   For a generation after the Civil War, the national bloodletting
was euphemized in the self-mocking phrase ``the late
unpleasantness.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant historians have not yet come up with the phrase to
describe the Clinton impeachment process, or the Monica Madness, or
the Clinton  &UR; Kulturkampf &LR;  (and entries will be accepted at
onlanguage(AT)nytimes.com), but during this yet-to-be-labeled
 &UR; annus incredibilis &LR; , a couple of great old phrases that deserve
examination were heaved around by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense Challenges Impeachment `Mumbo Jumbo,''' said a New
York Times headline over one of R.W. Apple's memorable articles,
which led with ``A White House lawyer ((Gregory Craig)) accused
House prosecutors today of resorting to `word games' and `legal
mumbo jumbo.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Mandingo peoples of the western Sudan were reported around
1740 to have a high priest who protected the villagers called the
 &UR; Mumbo Jumbo &LR; , an Englishing of  &UR; mam-gyo-mbo &LR; , supposedly
``magician who drives away troubled spirits of ancestors.'' Other
accounts describe the  &UR; Mumbo Jumbo &LR;  as a grotesque idol used to
scare women into subjection.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the reduplicated sound was similar to the
English  &UR; mumble jumble &LR; , the sense deteriorated from ``frightened
veneration'' to ``meaningless babble; gibberish'' and further to
``jargon designed to confuse.'' It is now an attack phrase often
used by lawyers against lawyers, with the racial or sex-subjugating
overtones long forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Those who grumbled about the acquittal of the president used a
phrase with an accusatory overtone,  &UR; scot-free &LR; . ``I assumed this
had to do with my own Scotch ancestry,'' writes a
Scottish-American, Duncan Steck, of New York, ``but lo, it comes
from Old Norse, meaning both a shot and a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. It has nothing to do with the slur on the proverbial
tightness of the Scots, or with their freedom. The  &UR; scot &LR; ,
sometimes spelled  &UR; shot &LR; , was a tax or required payment. It was
also a bar tab marked, or scored, on wood (the root of ``a  &UR; shot &LR; 
of booze''). ``Though I could scape  &UR; shot-free &LR;  at London,'' says
Shakespeare's Falstaff in ``Henry IV,'' ``I fear the  &UR; shot &LR;  heere:
here's no scoring, but upon the pate.'' That meant he feared
getting hit in the head in battle.
</P>
<P>
   Whether  &UR; shot-free &LR; , meaning free from either a tax or another
kind of  &UR; shot &LR; , or  &UR; scot-free &LR; , the terms came to mean
``unpunished'' with a connotation of unfair escape from
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton greeted the pope in St. Louis, Alessandra
Stanley reported in The New York Times that ``many people
throughout the world had been  &UR; tut-tutting &LR;  about the uneasy
juxtaposition.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tut &LR; , an interjection of disapproval or dismissal used by Ben
Jonson in ``Volpone'' and in reduplicated form as  &UR; tut, tut &LR;  by
Shakespeare in ``Richard II,'' is both a word in itself and an
attempt to spell an unspellable sound.
</P>
<P>
   The sound is a palatal click often represented by ``tsk, tsk,''
although that attempt at imitating the sound in print often results
in the mispronunciation ``tisk, tisk.'' Place the tongue on the
palate with lips apart and suck quickly; that's the sound of a
 &UR; tut &LR; , or a  &UR; tsk &LR; . We call that  &UR; tut-tutting &LR;  because it's awkward
to make two palatal clicks and follow them with an  &UR; -ing &LR; . Language
has its limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
