<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN EXPERTS WEIGHING DEGREE OF SUPPORT FOR BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Serbia's latest offensive in Kosovo is leading some of
Russia's top foreign policy specialists to question Moscow's
longstanding support for Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   With Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov set to leave on Tuesday for
Washington, Russia's top priority is to wrest billions of dollars
from the International Monetary Fund, not argue over the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Given the economic stakes for Moscow, the decision by President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to press the attack against ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo is more than a matter of bad timing. An
increasing number of Russian experts say it underscores Belgrade's
indifference to the Primakov mission.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Russian government, senior officials talk quietly
about their deep frustration with Milosevic. Some leading lawmakers
are more vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have invested too much into this problem,'' Vladimir Lukin,
the leader of parliament's foreign relations committee, told
Russian television on Sunday. ``We must know the limits of our
support.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that Russia would welcome a NATO bombing
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist sentiment at home further demands that the Russians
give their fellow Slavs in Yugoslavia oratorical support, even
though many ordinary people do not identify with the Serbian cause.
Russian Foreign Ministry officials, for their part, continue to
argue that NATO airstrikes will make a bad situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   Russia hoped to negotiate an accord that would obviate the need
for NATO action. Primakov put Russia's prestige on the line by
inviting Milosevic to Moscow last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Primakov sat by Milosevic's side in an ornate Russian
Foreign Ministry mansion as the Yugoslav leader denied that Serbian
forces had ever harmed ethnic Albanians and promised to ease the
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, President Boris Yeltsin sent a letter to
Belgrade, urging Milosevic to seek a political settlement, Russian
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But these days Belgrade does not seem to be listening to
Moscow's counsel. The Serbs, in fact, may have timed their attacks
against the Kosovo Albanians to coincide with Primakov's mission to
Washington, calculating that NATO would be reluctant to strike when
Primakov was in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a flare-up of the fighting may sour the atmosphere
for Primakov's trip or force him to defer it does not seem to have
mattered much in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   And if Russia's influence with Milosevic has dwindled, it seems
to have reached a low point with NATO. The alliance appears to have
concluded that it must take action soon if the Serbian attacks
continue, to salvage its own credibility, regardless of what the
Russians think.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Primakov has put Russia's
authority on the line and come out on the losing end. Two years ago
he engaged in an all-night negotiating session in Geneva, which
Moscow later asserted had broken the deadlock over weapons
inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   It only took a matter of months, however, before the Iraqi
leader walked away from the compromise and the Clinton
administration began planning a retaliatory strike. These days,
Moscow rarely objects to U.S. airstrikes in Iraq, apparently
calculating it can do little about it.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a breakthrough is achieved in Belgrade, Moscow stands to
be humiliated again. Even if there is progress, the credit is
likely to go to Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy, who arrived in
Belgrade armed with the threat of NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Primakov repeated, almost ritualistically, Moscow's
opposition to NATO bombing. But Moscow's senior diplomat in the
region, Boris Mayorsky, said Monday night that Moscow did not have
any special plan.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov appeared determined to go to Washington anyway. When
the Echo Moscow radio station asked its listeners Monday to phone
in their opinion, 69 percent of the 1,677 callers said Primakov
should not cancel his Washington mission, even if NATO attacked
Milosevic's troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have overinvested in terms of our support of Milosevic,''
said Sergei Karaganov, the chairman of the Council on Foreign and
Defense Policy, a group of opinion makers with ties to the Russian
government and military.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not mean that anybody here would support the
American policy of bombing at all costs,'' Karaganov added. ``But
support for Milosevic is largely a negative. It could jeopardize
the delicate balance in our economic dealings with the outside
world, including the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
