<HEADLINE>
POPE PLANS VISIT TO HOLY LAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul plans to visit the Holy Land next
March to mark the start of Christianity's third millenium, Israeli
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The church's most-traveled pontiff has long expressed his desire
to mark the start of the new millennium by visiting the traditional
sites of Jesus Christ's birth in Bethlehem and his death and
resurrection in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of meetings here Monday, the details and scheduling
of the visit began to be worked out among the senior Vatican
representative, Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, and Israel's tourism
minister and senior officials of the Religious Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems we will have a visit,'' said Uri Mor, the director of
Christian affairs for the Religious Affairs Ministry who was
present at the talks. ``But there are extraordinary planning and
protocol details for such a visit. Those details have not yet been
released.''
</P>
<P>
   Orly Doron, a spokeswoman for the Israeli Tourism Ministry, told
Reuters that ``the minister confirmed that he was informed that the
pope will visit Israel and the Palestinian territories in March
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Etchegaray, who is coordinating the Vatican's millennial
celebrations, could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Emil Salayta, an official in the Jerusalem Latin
Patriarchate, which represents the Middle East branch of the
Catholic Church, said Monday &UR;  &LR; night that the pope's intention to
visit the Holy Land is taking shape. He said there has not been an
official announcement from the Vatican, but sources close to the
church in the United States said the Vatican had unofficially
confirmed the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Salayta, who along with other priests met with Etchegaray
Monday, said the plans center around March 25, 2000, for the Feast
of the Annunciation, which in the faith marks the announcement to
Mary by the angel Gabriel that she would conceive and give birth to
a son named Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Salayta said the visit would include stops in Bethlehem, which
is under control of Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority;
Nazareth, which is in Israel and is the traditional site of the
annunciation; and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year old pope's health remains a critical factor in
whether he would make the visit as currently planned.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first papal visit to the Holy Land since 1964,
when Pope Paul VI came to Jerusalem. That was three years before
Israel captured East Jerusalem and the West Bank, which includes
Bethlehem, in the 1967 Six Day War. Shortly after that, Israel
annexed Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a trip by Pope John Paul, who leads about 1 billion
Roman Catholics worldwide, have been mired in a political quagmire
over the status of Jerusalem and the deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican and most nations, including the United States, do
not officially recognize Israel's sovereignty over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israel claims Jerusalem as its eternal and indivisible capital,
and Palestinians say East Jerusalem is the future capital of a
Palestinian state. Under the 1993 Oslo peace agreement, both sides
agreed to let the status of Jerusalem be determined in ``final
status'' talks that have been put on hold as implementation of the
interim agreements faltered.
</P>
<P>
   A papal visit, Israeli officials believe, could be seen as
official recognition by the Vatican of Israeli sovereignty over
Jerusalem. But Salayta disagreed with that interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have much to say for both sides, a message of
reconciliation, peace, but also justice,'' said Salayta.
</P>
<P>
   He compared the planned visit to Jerusalem to the pope's visit
last year to Cuba, where he delivered a strong message about the
injustices Christians suffer underc President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can expect a strong message about the injustice of
Israel,'' Salayta said. ``As well as a strong message of peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
