<HEADER>
A0118 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEC-MEETING-HNS &LR;      03-22 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEETING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELEGATIONS CALM ON EVE OF OPEC MEETING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Sometimes an OPEC meeting is an electric
affair, filled with the high drama of ministers from some of the
world's largest oil-producing states struggling to reach an accord
that will shake world markets.
</P>
<P>
   But this time it's as if their work is done.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of their spring meeting in Vienna, ministers from the
11-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries have an air
of accomplishment. They've come to ratify an agreement already
worked at The Hague earlier this month. They've agreed to join with
a group of non-OPEC producers to pull more than 2 million barrels a
day _ representing about 2.7 percent of world output _ off the
market.
</P>
<P>
   The oil markets Monday did nothing to dampen the mood. On
Monday, April light, sweet crude oil prices rose 26 cents to close
at $15.50 per barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. April
heating oil rose 1.70 cents to 42.39 cents a gallon; April unleaded
gasoline rose 1.78 cents to 49.42 cents a gallon; and April natural
gas rose 7 cents to $1.769 per thousand cubic feet. In London, May
Brent crude rose 43 cents, or 3.2 percent, to $13.88 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   C.W. Hornsby, president of Hornsby and Co., a Houston-based
energy risk management services firm, said the markets moved up
Monday because of the continued positive tone to the news out of
the OPEC meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But at the meeting, there are lot of signs that this time is
different.
</P>
<P>
   Absent are the flurry of secret, bilateral meetings in hotel
rooms, and the impromptu press briefings in which OPEC delegations
try to pressure one another with public statements.
</P>
<P>
   The only kind of statements being made to the packs of reporters
prowling the lobbies and hallways of Vienna's top hotels give
repeated assurances that all disputes have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians, who often arrive days before an OPEC conference to
bicker and joust with their arch OPEC rivals from Saudi Arabia,
aren't even scheduled to arrive until Tuesday, the morning of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   And instead, the shopping trips, which typically characterize
the end of OPEC meetings, are already in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a congenial feeling among the delegates because they
are all facing the dilemma of low oil prices,'' said Faleh Aljibury
of Fresno, Calif., a longtime OPEC watcher. ``They have made up
their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few loose ends is the Nigerians' insistence they have
not signed off on the pact, but that has not produced much of a
stir at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   All parties seem to agree they must make substantial cuts in
production, they must convince the markets the reductions will
stick, and they must present a united front to the world, Aljibury
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen the members so determined to make the
markets believe them,'' Aljibury said.
</P>
<P>
   Mussab Al-Dujayli, an oil expert with Iraq's State Oil Marketing
Organization, said all the OPEC members are suffering because of
low oil prices. ``Everybody needs the money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some OPEC members who were grousing earlier on that OPEC
heavyweight Saudi Arabia should cut more than its
585,000-barrel-a-day pledge concede that figure represents a
sizable reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Few oil analysts believe the coalition of OPEC countries and
non-OPEC producers _ Mexico, Norway, Oman and Russia _ will
completely live up to its 2 million-barrel-a-day goal. But even if
those countries reach only half that objective, that will go far
toward slimming down bloated stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those more-modest expectations, crude prices have
rallied significantly, rising more than 10 percent since the
likelihood of an agreement became apparent.
</P>
<P>
   If the parties' compliance with the agreement nears 75 percent _
not out of the question considering their adherence to more recent
cuts, argues Hornsby &AMP; Co.'s Nizam Sharief _ oil prices, which have
wallowed in recent months at record low levels _ could reach $18 or
$20 a barrel by the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, analysts agree, deserves much of the credit for
the accord because it made two major concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The kingdom agreed to drop its production below an 8
million-barrel-a-day floor. Saudi Arabia had established the mark
after the Persian Gulf War and Iraq's banishment from the world
market for all but United Nations-limited sales for food and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudis also accepted a key Iranian demand that Tehran be
permitted to cut back its production from a starting point of 3.6
million barrels a day, rather than from the 3.3 million barrel
level the Saudis and several other OPEC members would have
preferred.
</P>
<P>
   While their circumstances vary widely, all the OPEC members have
faced serious problems because of low crude prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudis faced the prospect of coping with a one-third drop in
government revenues. Venezuela has been forced to sell $1 billion
worth of bonds to help its state-owned oil company, Petroleos de
Venezuela, raise enough cash to pay its suppliers, while
perennially troubled Nigeria had to cut government spending to its
lowest level of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
