A0121 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-AFFIRMATIVE-BOS &LR;      03-22 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AFFIRMATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC TV ATTEMPTS TO COOL HOT ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Affirmative action continues to be among the most contentious US
domestic policy issues, not surprisingly often generating more heat
than light. Legislation like California's Proposition 209, which
since 1997 has barred consideration of race and gender in hiring
state employees or admitting students to state schools, has ended
up creating more controversy than closure.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you wean adversaries from reductive sloganeering and
reflexive responses and direct them toward more enlightening and
productive dialogue?
</P>
<P>
   With ``Beyond Black and White: Affirmative Action in America,''
public television tries to both dramatize and tame the affirmative
action debate at the same time. The worthy objective of the
program, part of the long-running Fred Friendly Seminar series, is
to present a lively version of the controversy while cooling the
rhetoric and clarifying the reasoning of proponents and opponents.
It's a tall order, but the engaging hourlong program often
succeeds. Toward the end of the generally orderly panel discussion,
airing Tuesday night, even some of the more adversarial
participants find a little patch of common ground.
</P>
<P>
   The cleverly contrived format of the series is the secret of its
success. But it's also exactly this air of artificiality
deliberately distancing the arguments from the real world that
raises some doubt about the TV seminar's practical civic value.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the selected panelists are asked to respond to a
hypothetical problem. Thus, host Charles J. Ogletree conjures a
university called Big State, in the state of Westralia, where race
is used as a factor in admissions, but where such affirmative
action is polarizing the community around an initiative sounding
suspiciously like 209. The scenario is familiarly Californian, and
among the panelists is Ward Connerly, a regent on the California
Board and a leading proponent of the real initiative. There are 13
other participants, including affirmative-action advocates Ruth J.
Simmons, president of Smith College, and Harvard law professor
Christopher Edley Jr., and opponents such as lawyer and writer Ann
Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a broad-ranging conversation touching law and history
and, of course, exposing some raw emotion. But the central point of
contention can be fairly reduced to the following. Those objecting
to affirmative action claim it promotes reverse discrimination and
perpetuates an obsession with race that inhibits creating a truly
colorblind society. Their generally principled arguments,
nonetheless, often seem dryly abstract, strong on occasional
debating points but sometimes willfully blind to contemporary
social realities.
</P>
<P>
   Those in favor of affirmative action reason that a colorblind
America is a viable but distant dream, that we're a nation still
too deeply rooted in discriminatory prejudice to abandon every
race, ethnic, and gender-based ``plus factor'' or preference
designed to remedy ongoing injustice. Over and over, they cite such
widely accepted ``plus factors'' often vital to college acceptance
as athletic prowess or the legacy of family alumni. We don't ignore
these differences, says Ann Lewis, director of communications at
the White House, so how can we ignore race?
</P>
<P>
   A good deal of nuance and detail emerges in the largely
eruption-free and often congenial exchange of ideas. But the final
words sounding a note of conciliation are tentative and not
altogether credible. ``Beyond Black and White'' is exemplary as an
exercise in civility, but its good manners sometimes prevent it
from digging deeply enough into these sensitive and important
issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 1952EST &QL; 
