<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STAKE-0323-COX     03-22 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STAKE-0323-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEAR OF GREATER CRISIS DRIVES KOSOVO PEACE EFFORT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Once again, the United States and its allies stand at
the brink of a risky military mission to counter Serb atrocities in
the troubled Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape this time is Kosovo, a small province of 2.2
million people. There, Serb troops backed by tanks have rampaged
through rural villages, killing often execution style an estimated
2,000 ethnic Albanians over the past year and running a quarter of
a million more from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, some 40,000 Serb troops were in and around Kosovo,
with more reported en route.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke made a last-ditch effort Monday
in Belgrade to convince Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic to accept a
peace plan, President Clinton warned that NATO is prepared to
attack Serb military positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Milosevic continues to choose aggression over
peace, NATO's military plans must continue to move forward,''
Clinton said in Washington. ``Serbia's mounting aggression must be
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton summoned leaders from both parties in Congress for a
White House briefing on the matter this (Tuesday) morning.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the atrocities in Kosovo lies a larger strategic fear.
Continuing fighting in that pocket of Serbia the main state in
what's left of Yugoslavia might spill over into neighboring
Macedonia, where tensions already run high among minority ethnic
Albanians and majority Slavs, or even into Albania itself.
</P>
<P>
   Instability in either of those countries, in turn, might ignite
a broader Balkan war that could, U.S. diplomats have warned,
eventually pit NATO allies Greece and Turkey against one another.
</P>
<P>
   Regional experts say the chances of such a worst-case scenario
are remote, but the implications are frightening. Balkan discord
sparked World War I, and it's been Serb ferocity over much of this
decade that's been responsible for Europe's worst bloodshed since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Given the region's propensity as a tinderbox, Clinton contends
it's better to try to put out the fire in Kosovo than to risk
seeing it spread out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced we'll be dragged into this thing under worse
circumstances, at greater cost, if we don't act,'' Clinton said
Friday. (cq)
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially what you're seeing here is the beginning of a
worse problem,'' said former U.S. diplomat Daniel Serwer, a senior
fellow for Balkan studies at the U.S. Institute for Peace, a think
tank in Washington. ``What you're setting out to do is prevent that
from getting worse,'' said Serwer, who served as special U.S. envoy
to Bosnia from 1994-1996.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   NATO's plans for doing that revolve around some 400 warplanes
and support aircraft half of them American based in Italy, Germany
and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Initial attacks would begin with the launching of scores of
long-range cruise missiles fired from four U.S. ships and two
submarines in the Mediterranean and Adriatic and from B-52 bombers.
The mission would be to knock substantial holes in the formidable
Serb air defense network of Soviet-built surface-to-air missiles
and anti-aircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
   Phase two would involve attacks by stealthy F-117s and by F-16s
and F-15s accompanied by EA-6B electronic jamming aircraft. Again,
the initial targets would be anti-air defense systems and the
electronic and communications networks that support them.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, if all goes as planned, U.S. and other NATO pilots
should be able to fly over much of Serbia in far greater safety. At
that point, A-10 Thunderbolt tank killers might be expected to fly
in low and slow to target ground combat units and armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO hope is that, once the Serb military begins taking
heavy losses, Belgrade will throw in the towel and agree to a peace
accord signed last week in Paris by the Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement similar to the one that put a U.S.-led NATO
peacekeeping force in Bosnia calls for a NATO peacekeeping force to
enter Kosovo. The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) has
planned for a force of 28,000 ground troops, 4,000 of which would
be American.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to restore to Kosovo the autonomy it enjoyed until
Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia, began stripping it away in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement signed last week by the Kosovar Albanians,
control of most of Kosovo's political, judicial, legal and
educational institutions would be transferred from the Serbs who
make up only 10 percent of the population in the province to the
ethnic Albanians. The latter account for 90 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians see such an arrangement as the first step
toward creating an independent nation of Kosovo, to be dominated by
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs fear precisely that outcome, which explains why
Milosevic is opposed to the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Formally the United States is opposed to independence. Clinton
has suggested, however, that if Milosevic continues to reject the
U.S.-backed peace plan, and NATO air strikes are required to break
the Serb military stronghold on the region, all bets could well be
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is their (Serbs') best chance to keep Kosovo as a part of
Serbia and as a part of Yugoslavia,'' Clinton said of the peace
plan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   (story can end here)
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Kosovo has affronted the world with a
humanitarian crisis closely mirroring the terror Serbs inflicted
for 3.5 years across neighboring Bosnia. There, more than 200,000
people, most of them civilians, were killed and 15 times that
number were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   That crisis ended in the fall of 1995, only after a week and a
half of U.S.-led NATO air strikes targeting Serbs and three weeks
of strong-arm diplomacy led by Holbrooke ending in the Dayton
Accords. The result was a massive U.S.-led NATO peacekeeping force
that remains in Bosnia even now, with no prospect of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   There are other places in the world, where atrocities
perpetrated upon civilians have provoked outrage. Sierra Leone, the
Sudan and Rwanda come quickly to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Kosovo, however, strikes closer to home for
many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like to see people slaughtered, we don't like to see
people chased from their homes, especially in large numbers,
especially in Europe,'' said Serwer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
