<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHYSICS-BALLET-COX     03-22 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSICS-BALLET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Physics in '99: Dissecting movements of dance to their core
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Torque, mass, parabola, trajectory _ these aren't
terms that dance across your mind as you watch a rail-thin
ballerina floating effortlessly through a series of tour jetes or
executing 32 of the whipped turns called fouettes.
</P>
<P>
   But for Kenneth Laws, a physicist who teaches at Dickinson
College in Carlisle, Pa., the terms and the tours go hand in hand,
as he explained Monday in a session called ``The Physics of Dance''
for the American Physical Society. His talk was one of hundreds of
presentations that are going on at the American Physical Society's
conference in Atlanta this week, commemorating the association's
100th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Laws is a balletomane on several fronts. He has taken dance
classes, ferried his children to ballet lessons and served as board
chairman of the Central Pennsylvania Youth Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 20 years ago, when he began to wonder how dancers
accomplished all that gravity-defying stuff, he offered some
thoughts (and a set of line drawings that look like industrial
blueprints) to Scientific American's column called ``The Amateur
Scientist.'' The resulting article, published in June 1982, has
blossomed into two books and many lectures for physicists and dance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Using a model, dancer Amy Kohler of Chicago, Laws showed his
audience at the Georgia World Congress Center a 30-second sequence
from the ballet ``Serenade.'' Then he took apart the movements:
arabesque, pirouette, jete. Kohler, who has worked with Laws
before, broke down the steps into their smallest components and
demonstrated them in slow motion _ or as slow as a flying step can
be performed.
</P>
<P>
   Laws indicated _ on this elfin dancer, who carries possibly 105
pounds on her 5-foot, 7-inch frame _ the center of gravity in the
pelvic girdle. When Kohler launches herself into the air for a jete
and stretches her legs into a split, he explained, the body's
center of gravity rises _ in freeze-frame photography or with video
you can see it _ because there's so much less weight to support
beneath the pelvic girdle.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes it possible for a dancer to suspend herself
for a breathtaking second in midair _ or for Michael Jordan to
float halfway down the court as he sinks yet another basket.
</P>
<P>
   Later Laws partnered Kohler in a lift that carried her about 3
feet off the ground. ``They don't call me Arnold for nothing,''
said Laws, flexing an academic bicep.
</P>
<P>
   Then he dissected the lift. Without assistance, he explained,
Kohler is able to jump only about 8 inches off the floor; if she
just stands there, he can lift her dead weight only to the same
height. It takes both their energies to create the illusion of
weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Kohler, who has danced with Chicago Ballet and Ballet Iowa and
is working on a master's degree in dance therapy at Columbia
College, said not one of her ballet instructors has explained how a
pirouette or a jete works.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I did the session in Chicago,'' she said, ``I went back
into class _ and my turns were so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
