<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta deal to buy ASA near close
 &HT;    By staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines' buyout of regional affiliate Atlantic
Southeast Airlines is as good as done.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said Monday it now holds 91 percent of ASA Holdings Inc.
shares, following a tender offer that expired last week. It already
owned 28 percent and needed a majority to prevail in the buyout.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will close at a final ASA Holdings shareholder meeting
next month, and the the regional carrier will become a wholly owned
subsidiary of Delta, which made the move to gain complete control
of ASA's operations and routes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta paid $34 a share, or about $700 million, and took out a
$500 million line of credit to finance the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
