<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILBY-GREENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILBY'S FRIENSHIP LACED WITH DECEIT _ YET LOYAL TO THE END 
ROPE SPRUCES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kim Philby was the most devastating Soviet mole ever to
penetrate the British secret service. Graham Greene was one of the
century's great novelists and an iconoclast. Together, they forged
a complicated friendship that lasted half a century and flummoxed
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   When Philby was exposed as a double agent in 1963, Greene earned
the opprobrium of their native England by publicly defending
Philby's treason. Greene maintained that Philby merely followed a
higher morality than country _ his belief in communism.
</P>
<P>
   But theirs was a friendship woven of deceit as well as loyalty.
How much did Greene know of Philby's secret life as a spy? Did
Philby betray Greene as well as England? Did it continue into their
final years?
</P>
<P>
   There are tantalizing insights into these questions tucked away
in the John J. Burns Library at Boston College, where some of their
lambent correspondence is preserved in the 60,000-item archive of
Greene's manuscripts and letters. The college purchased the papers
in 1994, three years after Greene's death at age 86. Philby died in
1988 at age 76.
</P>
<P>
   The letters may be no more than the musings of two duplicitous
old men who chose to stay in touch as they aged, Philby from his
apartment in Moscow, and Greene from his villa in the south of
France. But they could also represent feints by each man to mislead
the other _ and the other's country.
</P>
<P>
   Is Philby, a full KGB colonel, speaking for that outfit in his
letters? Is Greene passing all that Philby writes to the British
SIS and American CIA, as his official biographer believes? Does it
matter?
</P>
<P>
   Both write elliptically, and glide past unspoken questions of
complicity as they exchange mordant judgments on the Ayatollah
Khomeini, John Paul II, Ronald Reagan, and other questions of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Betrayal is sticky stuff. John le Carre, an expert on the
subject, agonized over it to Timothy Garton Ash in a recent issue
of The New Yorker. Le Carre was a British spy for almost 16 years.
He betrayed relentlessly for country. The morality of the
tradecraft troubles him today. He calls the conundrum ``a question
that's haunted me these last 45 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Philby _ the model for le Carre's definitive spy story
``Tinker, Tailor, Soldier, Spy'' _ betrayal had been a way of life
since he was recruited by the Soviets as a student at Cambridge to
spy for them. Philby's deception over the years was brilliant, and
he rose to the highest ranks of British intelligence before he fled
to Moscow, one step ahead of British agents sent to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   It was Philby who recruited Greene, already an established
writer, into British espionage during World War II. The two became
drinking partners and fast friends.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's attraction to Philby was anchored in part by his
instinctive support of the maverick. ``Greene liked odd men out,''
says Norman Sherry, his biographer. ``He was against powerful
figures.'' Greene was also entranced by Philby's fluent ability to
deceive, a theme in Greene's fiction. ``Greene admired Philby's
ability to wear a mask so perfectly,'' says Sherry, who knew Greene
for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry says that the only argument he ever had with Greene was
over Philby. ``Somewhere in his early life, Greene said that you're
absolutely doomed if you are betrayed by your friend,'' he recalls.
Sherry reminded Greene of his early comment and Greene replied,
``Yes, yes, I still feel that way.'' But when Sherry raised the
subject of Philby the betrayer in this context, Greene became
furious. ``Greene got so damned angry that I'd caught him out,'' he
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Philby's letters are marbled with comments on global politics
and humor. Questions of deceit and betrayal aside, they reflect the
freshness of contemporary comment on what we today know as history.
And what Greene once described as Philby's ``chilling certainty in
the correctness of his judgment'' pervades his letters.
</P>
<P>
   In a missive early in 1980, for example, Philby dismissed
Khomeini with the snotty disdain of a member of London's venerable
Garrick Club while identifying with acuity the source of his
fundamentalist strength that remains relevant today, in and outside
Iran:
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to take the view that the Ayatullah is a hateful old
fraud and that his precious Islamic republic is meaningless. But
the point is that he stands for a very powerful negative _
revulsion against Great Power domination _ which is not confined to
Muslim peoples. And, for the time being, we have to live with him.
So what?''
</P>
<P>
   Philby viewed the two superpowers at the beginning of 1980 with
a gimlet eye: ``I am afraid we are in for a difficult year. I don't
believe in the Soviet threat to Europe, I don't believe in a NATO
threat to the Soviet Union (though I do believe that renewed
efforts will be made to detach our allies from the Warsaw Pact.)''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding ``this infernal Afghan business,'' he wrote, ``I need
hardly tell you that I an very unhappy about it; what may surprise
you is that I have met no one here who is happy about it. Was it
essential to take up the military option, as it is called
nowadays?''
</P>
<P>
   Is all of this misinformation? At one point, Philby sought to
assure Greene that he spoke for himself. ``When you next buy Pravda
at your local newsagent,'' he wrote, ``you will see that I am
expressing my own views, not those of the government.'' Yet in one
letter in 1980, Philby promises to pass on ``to the competent
authorities'' a Graham idea of joint action between the Soviet
Union and the United States in hot spots around the globe such as
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry, a Briton who has been working on his Greene opus for
over 20 years, is convinced that Greene gave his Philby
correspondence to Western intelligence. ``It is my belief that his
correspondence to Philby was under the instruction of SIS and the
CIA,'' Sherry says. ``He knew important people there. I'm convinced
he was hoping to make Philby a treble agent.''
</P>
<P>
   The treble agent theory is pure supposition on Sherry's part,
who concedes he has no love for Philby. He declined Philby's
invitation to Moscow for the Greene biography and stopped writing
to him after he got what he needed from him by letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, he was a traitor,'' says Sherry, noting that Philby
trained scores of agents to be sent into Albania, where they
perished. ``Philby loved to betray,'' he adds. ``He made friends
with those people he sent there, knowing he'd already betrayed
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sherry maintains that Greene's much-publicized
anti-Americanism was fabricated. ``All of it was balls, in my
view,'' he says. It was, said Sherry, a ruse _ an attempt to echo
Philby's views as a way to draw him back to the West. The two men
clearly missed each other's company; as Philby reportedly told
colleagues, ``I'd like to be with &UR;  &LR; Graham Greene with a bottle of
wine between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene and Philby both despised Pope John Paul II. In a letter
in 1982, after a papal visit to Central America, Philby wrote, ``I
have a feeling that the next few years there will see much
nastiness, and I doubt whether John Paul II's visit to Hispaniola
will do much for the desamparados. I don't like the showbiz,
kissing tarmac, etc., and his views on sexual matters seem to me to
be unimaginative and unkind. As for politics, he is involved
willy-nilly and he must know it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, Greene wrote to Philby three years later, ``My
Dear Kim, You know how much I share your views not only about a man
in Washington but about a man in Rome. He is the most political
pope we have suffered for many generations.'' Greene added in
reference to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and President Reagan,
``I wish I was a fly on the wall when there is a meeting between
your man and the B-film actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Booze was a constant for both men and a problem for Philby. In
one letter, he described himself as ``an aging gentleman belonging
to what Auden called the cigarette and alcohol culture.'' He sent
Greene a postcard from Havana in which he offered New Year's
greetings from the Bar Floridita, ``where the daiquiri
originated.'' He signed it ``Your fan in Havana, KP,'' adding
``Muchos daiquiris en la Floridita.''
</P>
<P>
   He later wrote Greene, ``The daiquiris didn't bother my sinus,
which, if I indeed have one, has so far been as quiescent as my
liver. But I found that those infernal ice chips interfered with
serious drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Philby loved women as much as alcohol. In 1965, he inscribed a
book to the wife of fellow spy Donald MacLean that read: ``To
Melinda with love from Kim Nov 1965 _ An orgasm a day keeps the
doctors away!''
</P>
<P>
   But the light banter does not disguise the depth of the
friendship. Before Philby died, Greene visited him in his Gorky
Street apartment in Moscow, where he lived with his young Russian
wife, Rufina.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's loyalty to his old friend was most obvious in his
introduction to Philby's 1968 autobiography, ``My Silent War.''
Greene wrote, ```He betrayed his country' _ yes, perhaps he did,
but who among us has not committed treason to something or someone
more important than a country?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
