A0128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-RDP-ART-1130(2     03-22 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-RDP-ART-1130(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVEY WEINSTEIN, MOGUL IN LOVE ... WITH WINNING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(jw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ The post-Oscar King of Hollywood lives in
New York, behaves like an old-time studio mogul and has plenty of
enemies. Especially Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the unexpected triumph of ``Shakespeare in
Love'' over ``Saving Private Ryan'' as best picture, Harvey
Weinstein, co-chairman of Miramax, which made ``Shakespeare,'' was
fielding phone calls in his Beverly Hills hotel suite and accepting
congratulations. His costly promotion campaigns for two films,
``Shakespeare'' and ``Life is Beautiful,'' had paid off even more
lavishly than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   Why the 5,500 member of the Motion Picture Academy of Arts and
Sciences split their vote between ``Shakespeare in Love'' and
``Saving Private Ryan'' was the source of discussion all over
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks, which produced ``Private Ryan'' with Paramount, was
nothing less than devastated, even though their World War II epic
picked up five Oscars, including one for Steven Spielberg as best
director. Executives at Dreamworks, including Jeffrey Katzenberg,
one of its founders, have said in recent weeks that Weinstein had
upped the ante by spending millions to promote ``Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenberg's partners, Spielberg and David Geffen, were also
known to be angry with Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mechanic, chairman of Fox Filmed Entertainment, whose movie
``A Thin Red Line'' fared poorly in the Academy Award and box
office sweepstakes, said that the Oscar process had started to
resemble an expensive political campaign, and that Weinstein shared
some of the blame for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire academy process is overbloated,'' Mechanic said.
``It's like the process of trying to win an election. It's no
longer about the material or the merit. It's about how much money
you spend. It's not what the academy founders set out to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic said that Weinstein, who runs Miramax with his brother,
Bob, was unusual among studio executives because he was consumed
above all with winning Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other company, Miramax was set up for
specialized movies and tend to be movies that the academy
recognizes,'' he said. ``They've focused on one thing: the Academy
Award process. The rest of us are in the business of making
different types of films, some of them meriting academy attention,
some not.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein was unavailable Monday morning. But more than anyone
else in today's Hollywood, this 46-year-old executive has been
compared with old-line studio moguls. Miramax employees said that
Weinstein was tough, irascible, opinionated, temperamental and
difficult but often had superb taste. His critical and commercial
successes include ``The Piano,'' ``Pulp Fiction,'' ``Il Postino,''
``Cinema Paradiso'' and ``The English Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein, a big, imposing and perennially rumpled figure who
usually has a cigarette dangling from his mouth, is both popular
and unpopular among filmmakers. He has collided with prominent
directors like James Ivory and has been nicknamed ``Harvey
Scissorhands'' by others because of his tendency to edit and take
over films. Other filmmakers, though, including Quentin Tarrantino,
Jane Campion and Billy Bob Thornton, enjoy good relations with him.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein is direct. In 1993, when he heard that Time magazine
was about to run an article revealing that Jaye Davidson, the
``female'' lead in ``The Crying Game,'' was a man (which was not a
surprise because Davidson had won an Oscar nomination as best
supporting actor), Weinstein called a top editor 18 times in one
day in an unsuccessful attempt to keep Davidson's sex a secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes him unusual is the results,'' Mark Urman,
co-president of Lion's Gate Films, which released ``Gods and
Monsters'' and ``Affliction,'' said Monday. ``Look at what happened
last night. The machinery Harvey puts in place is like a
juggernaut. All predictions, all sense of logic and in some
instances a sense of fairness is thrown out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual _ but not unprecedented _ for academy voters to
cast ballots for the director of one film while choosing another
movie as the year's best. It has happened 18 times, beginning with
the very first Oscar. In recent years, for example, Warren Beatty
won the best director Oscar for the 1981 film ``Reds,'' but the
year's best picture was ``Chariots of Fire.'' In 1989, ``Driving
Miss Daisy'' won the best picture award, but its director, Bruce
Beresford, was not even nominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love,'' an elegant comedy about a love affair
between Shakespeare and a restless woman who yearns to act, won
seven Oscars at the 71st annual Academy Awards on Sunday night,
including those for Gwyneth Paltrow as best actress and for Marc
Norman and Tom Stoppard for original screenplay. Miramax's ``Life
is Beautiful'' won the best actor award for Roberto Benigni and was
chosen as best foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise over the award for best picture extended even into
Walt Disney Studios, whose parent company owns Miramax. ``I was
stunned that `Shakespeare in Love' won after the Spielberg award,''
said Joe Roth, chairman of Disney Studios. ``It seemed like
`Private Ryan' had all the criteria to take best picture. Why
didn't it? Perhaps `Shakespeare' was able to convince a lot of
women voters to vote for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other studio executives and producers said that ``Private Ryan''
was simply not as fresh as ``Shakespeare'' in the minds of academy
voters. The Spielberg film opened in July, and although videos were
sent to academy members, many of them may not have watched again
because the material was harsh.
</P>
<P>
   One top producer, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said: ``
`Saving Private Ryan' suffers on cassettes. If you see it at home,
you are by no means as impressed with it as you were in a movie
theater. And `Shakespeare in Love' is a more intimate picture, it
plays well on cassette. It may actually be enhanced by watching it
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   But Terry Press, the marketing chief at Dreamworks, responded:
``That goes to a larger issue. You're a member of the Motion
Picture Academy, not the television video academy. These movies are
meant to be seen in movie theaters, all of them. They're not meant
to be stopped and started and paused when the phone rings or to
feed the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   One Dreamworks executive said that ``Shakespeare'' may have
triumphed because the biggest bloc of academy voters are actors and
the film is a tribute to acting and theater. On the other hand
``Private Ryan'' is the work of a virtuoso filmmaker, and as a
result he was given the Oscar for best direction. There was the
possibility, too, that the majority of academy voters simply
preferred the comedy to the tragic war drama.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shadowing the entire process, though, was the expensive
promotional campaign for ``Shakespeare,'' which may have reached
$10 million to $15 million, including Hollywood trade paper
advertisements as well as ads in newspapers promoting the film,
which is expanding to theaters around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed,'' said Damien Bona, co-author of ``Inside
Oscar,'' (Ballantine), who writes frequently about the Academy
Awards. ``Every day in the trade papers you were bombarded with
Miramax ads. It's nothing new. They've always done this. But the
degree to which they've done it this year is astonishing.'' In some
ways the advertising campaign for ``Shakespeare'' may have created
a sense of momentum in the minds of academy voters that helped
place the film at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gill, president of Miramax's Los Angeles office, and Marcy
Granata, its executive vice president for marketing, vigorously
denied that the company had overspent on the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people accuse us of spending more than Dreamworks,
but actually we spent less,'' said Gill. ``We counted. Basically
they bought 165 total pages in the Hollywood trade papers. We
bought 118 total pages for `Shakespeare.''' This omits, however,
Miramax's hefty promotion of the movie in general newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
