<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAROQUE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME BAROQUE DISCOVERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the New York Collegium instantly acclaimed as a
new force on the early-music scene in the city this season,
hard-working older ensembles have to be asking whether they, after
all, have been merely chopped liver.
</P>
<P>
   Artek, for one, has afforded many pleasures in its 14 seasons,
as it did on Wednesday evening in a mostly fascinating program of
French Baroque music at the Church of the Resurrection in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   What it has not achieved, and what, for that matter, the New
York Collegium has yet to show, is consistency over the long haul.
Performance levels can vary drastically from night to night and
even within a single concert.
</P>
<P>
   In this adventurous and well-stuffed program of small-scale
works, the level was reasonably high. The featured works, ending
each half of the program, were lovely solo cantatas by Michel
Pignolet de Monteclair: ``Le Mort de Didon,'' sung by Jessica
Tranzillo, a soprano, and ``Pan et Syrinx,'' sung by Barbara
Hollinshead, a mezzo-soprano.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in ``Pan et Syrinx,'' the little-celebrated
Monteclair came across as a fine and inventive composer, as he has
before in performances by another worthy New York Group, Concert
Royal.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the rest of the program, Enrico Gatti, a violinist,
and Colin St. Martin, a flutist, variously combined with Gwendolyn
Toth, a harpsichordist and the director of Artek, and a few other
players. Strong cases were made for works by Marin Marais, who has,
alas, slouched back into obscurity after a mild flurry of activity
surrounding the film ``Tous les Matins du Monde''; Michel Corrette,
a composer perhaps even more inventive and less celebrated than
Monteclair, and Francois Couperin.
</P>
<P>
   Spirited playing by St. Martin was not enough to elevate a flute
suite by Jacques-Martin Hotteterre above the level of Baroque
routine. Ms. Toth offered enjoyable tidbits by Jean-Henri
d'Anglebert and Louis Couperin, but Daniel Swenberg's uncompelling
account of a guitar suite by Robert de Visee served merely to make
the evening seem long.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it left a listener basically satisfied. It's just that
one of these days, that listener would like to be, and stay, wowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
