A0132 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-DEFIBRILATOR-CO     03-22 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-DEFIBRILATOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Science/Health: Training on defibrillator is easy
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new, easy-to-use device that jump-starts a stopped
heart could save up to 100,000 lives a year, if it goes into
widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   The device is an Automated External Defibrillator, a simplified
version of the defibrillators used by medical professionals on
people suffering cardiac arrest. The device delivers a powerful
electric shock to the heart, forcing it to resume beating.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross is recruiting companies across the nation
to buy defibrillators and train employees in their use. On Monday,
Steve Bullock, the organization's acting president, hosted a
training session at Cox Enterprises, which owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the workplace that many of these (cardiac arrest)
incidents happen,'' Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   The primary advantage of the device is that it requires little
training, and can be used during the crucial first few minutes of a
heart attack, while the ambulance is on its way. CPR may still be
required to ensure the victim's body is receiving oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The device literally talks users through the steps of restarting
a person's stopped heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apply pads,'' the device says. ``Plug in connector.''
</P>
<P>
   It checks for a heartbeat; if none is detected, the device tells
the user to shock the victim by pressing a flashing button.
</P>
<P>
   Thedefibrillator, which was developed by Heartstream, a division
of Hewlett Packard, costs about $3,500 per unit, said David Todd of
the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross eventually will expand its program to include
shopping malls and stadiums, where emergency response tends to be
slower because of difficult access, Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
