<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-RELEASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH HALT RELEASE OF FOUR IRA PRISONERS?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British government Monday halted the release of
four Irish Republican Army prisoners, a move that pleased neither
IRA sympathizers nor those who assert that the Northern Ireland
peace process has awarded too many concessions to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Home Secretary Jack Straw, who is responsible for prisons and
law enforcement, said he needed legal clarification on whether the
prisoners were entitled to early release under the Good Friday
Agreement of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the sensitivity of the issue and the timing, at a
point when the peace process is stalled over the fate of the IRA's
weaponry, that nearly every one saw hidden motives to Straw's move.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein, the party aligned with the IRA, accused Straw of
trying to assuage Protestant unionists in Northern Ireland who have
been calling for a halt to prisoner releases until the IRA begins
to turn in some of its arsenal. Sinn Fein officials warned that the
move would only inflame opinion among republican skeptics who say
the British government is supporting unionists attempting to
rewrite the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But if the move was meant to appease unionists, few of them saw
it as such. Ian Paisley Jr., son of the fundamentalist preacher who
leads the most recalcitrant of the unionist parties opposed to the
peace process, said it showed that the British government values
English lives more than those lost in Northern Ireland. Each of the
four prisoners whose releases were halted were convicted in English
courts, three for killing people in English cities.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four prisoners whose releases were indefinitely put on
hold was Patrick Magee, the IRA bomber who masterminded the 1984
explosion at the Grand Hotel in Brighton which killed five people
and nearly killed its primary target, then-prime minister Margaret
Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Magee, who is hated by Conservative Party members in Britain
because it was their annual conference he bombed, was supposed to
serve 35 years of a life sentence. But under the terms of the Good
Friday Agreement, which crafted a political settlement in Northern
Ireland, Magee and all other members of paramilitary groups
committed to the peace process are to be released before July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While Magee was not expected to be released for several more
months, Straw's action halted the scheduled release Tuesday of Paul
Kavanaugh and Thomas Quigley, convicted of 1985 bombings in London
that killed three people, and Gerard McDonnell, who was sentenced
to life in prison in 1986 for a bombing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Straw described the legal review sought by Straw
as a technical, not political, matter, saying Straw had legitimate
questions about how the agreement's prisoner release provisions
applied to inmates in England and Wales.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman denied that the government was sending a warning
that the release of its prisoners would be halted if the IRA
continues to refuse to turn in any of its weapons. Nor was the move
aimed at bolstering unionists, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said a court is likely to rule very soon, if not
Tuesday, whether the releases can go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is committed to meeting our obligations under
the Good Friday agreement,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But after emerging from a meeting with IRA prisoners in the Maze
prison outside Belfast, Gerry Kelly, a Sinn Fein assembly member
who served a lengthy prison sentence for IRA bombings, described
Straw's move as disgraceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's political,'' he said. ``The question is, is the British
home secretary bigger than the Good Friday Agreement?''
</P>
<P>
   Unionists and republicans face a new deadline of April 2 to
resolve their dispute over the IRA's weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists refuse to form a local government, or allow Sinn Fein
members to sit in the new Cabinet where both sides will share
power, until the IRA begins disarming. The IRA and its allies in
Sinn Fein say that nothing in the agreement links disarming to
forming a new Northern Ireland administration and triggering the
return of power from the British Parliament to a local assembly in
Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, during St. Patrick's Day festivities in Washington,
President Clinton urged the parties to put their disputes aside and
implement the terms of the Good Friday Agreement in full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
