<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saving lives made easier with new, easy-to-use Automated
External Defibrillator
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new, easy-to-use device that jump-starts a stopped
heart could save up to 100,000 lives a year, if it goes into
widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   The device is an Automated External Defibrillator (AED), a
simplified version of the defibrillators used by medical
professionals on people suffering cardiac arrest. The AED delivers
a powerful electric shock to the heart, forcing it to resume
beating.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross is recruiting companies across the nation
to buy AEDs and train employees in their use. On Monday, Steve
Bullock, the organization's acting president, hosted a training
session at Cox Enterprises, which owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is in the workplace that many of these (cardiac arrest)
incidents happen,'' Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   The primary advantages of the AED is that it requires little
training, and can be used during the crucial first few minutes of a
heart attack, while the ambulance is on its way. CPR may still be
required to ensure the victim's body is receiving oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   The AED literally talks users through the steps of restarting a
person's stopped heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apply pads,'' the device says. ``Plug in connector.''
</P>
<P>
   It checks for the victim's heartbeat; if none is detected, the
device tells the user to shock the victim by pressing a single
flashing button.
</P>
<P>
   The AED, which was developed by Heartstream, a division of
Hewlett Packard, costs about $3,500 per unit, said David Todd of
the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross will eventually expand its AED program to
include places such as shopping malls and stadiums, where emergency
response generally tends to be slower due to difficult access,
Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  `Look Good ... Feel Better': The American Cancer Society's
program that helps women recovering from cancer learn how to use
wigs, makeup and other techniques to lift their spirits is
celebrating its 10-year anniversary. The program's van, with a
customized classroom, is making a two-day visit to Atlanta today as
part of a 22-city tour. A cerebration and demonstration will be
held at 10:30 a.m. today at Northside Hospital's emergency room
area in Atlanta. While appointments for the van visit have been
filled, ``Look Good ... Feel Better'' programs are available
year-round. For information about the nearest program, call
toll-free, 1-800-395-5665.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
