<SLUG> BC-LASER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Physics in '99: New tool may detect earlier signs of cancer
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new laser system will give doctors another tool for
peering into the human body to detect very early signs of cancer
without having to remove tissue for diagnostic tests, researchers
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In tests on patients with a precancerous condition that can lead
to colon cancer, the laser-induced ``fluorescence spectroscopy''
system performed just as well as _ or better than _ biopsies and
other conventional detection methods, said physicist Mary-Ann Mycek
of Dartmouth College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the laser-based technique does not require the removal
of tissue, it represents a tremendous advance over the current
practice of tissue biopsy,'' said Mycek, who presented her findings
at the American Physical Society's 100th anniversary meeting in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In a biopsy, a doctor removes a portion of diseased tissue and
sends it to a laboratory to determine if it is malignant,
precancerous or benign.
</P>
<P>
   Very early detection and treatment of diseased tissue can
prevent the development of cancer. Mycek said that when the laser
system can detect subtle, microscopic chemical and structural
changes in the tissue that may be symptoms of early precancerous
conditions. The technique could be widely available within a few
years, Mycek added.
</P>
<P>
   In other reports Monday at the physicists' meeting:
</P>
<P>
   _ Philip Wyatt of Santa Barbara, Calif., said he has developed a
fist-size device similar to a smoke alarm that would give an early
warning of a biological warfare attack. The physicist said the
device uses a laser to quickly detect anthrax spores or other
dangerous microbes that may be released by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   _ A theory by University of Pittsburgh physicist Ernest
Sternglass says the universe will continue to expand until it
reaches a maximum size 200 times its present radius and will
neither fly apart into dead ashes, as predicted by some, nor
collapse into a fiery point. ``It will allow life to continue
forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The next generation of computers, electronic optical
instruments and photovoltaic cells may not be based on spinach _
not silicon _ say researchers at the Oak Ridge National Laboratory
in Tennessee. The scientists have developed a way to manipulate
spinach leaf proteins so that they absorb energy from the sun and
power electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
