<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-PITCHERS-H     03-22 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PITCHERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ It's the ninth inning. Astros closer Billy Wagner
is on the mound.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fastball, right?
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Wagner almost certainly would have gone with his
trademark 100-mph fastball in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner, fast becoming one of the game's top closers, wants
something to complement his blazing fastball. That has led him to
develop a second pitch, a slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just like to head out there with another pitch,'' said
Wagner, who has 53 saves over the past two seasons. ``I think it
makes me more of a pitcher than a thrower, because now when guys
get up there they can no longer say, `OK, I've got to get ready for
the fastball.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's not uncommon to see pitchers try to expand their repertoire
in an effort to remain a step ahead of the competition. That's one
of the primary reasons for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Astros lefthander Trever Miller is working on a ``drop-and-down
sidearm'' offering, pitching with a motion that allows him to come
at a hitter with his fastball and slider at a lower angle. The
angle, similar to how Los Angeles' Kevin Brown pitches _ ``but
without that kind of velocity,'' Miller jokes _ gives Miller's
pitches a different look, something that is particularly effective
against lefthanded hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, they can't pick up one arm angle,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Why do pitchers feel compelled to try different things?
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Vern Ruhle said, ``It's an addition to the basic
things they do. They are trying to give the hitter another look, or
another thought, to see if they can round themselves out a little
bit. There's a statement that says, `You're either getting better
or you're staying the same.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're staying the same, somebody else is getting better
and it looks like you've fallen back. It's a progressive mindset
of, What are you doing to improve your game?''
</P>
<P>
   Early last season, the Astros suggested Wagner work on a second
pitch. The idea was reaffirmed last fall when, on a trip to Japan
with other major-leaguers, he kept hearing the same thing from
closers Trevor Hoffman, Mike Jackson and Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Their advice: Don't throw the fastball so much.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, 27, spent the rest of the offseason working on the
slider, a pitch that starts out looking like a fastball but takes a
short, sharp break just before reaching the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The results this spring have been encouraging. Wagner is 2-0
with 14 strikeouts in nine innings while allowing one earned run.
On Saturday against Detroit, he struck out two of the four batters
he faced, going with the slider ``three or four times.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wagner will continue to rely heavily on his hard one, just
the presence of a second pitch gives him an advantage, manager
Larry Dierker said. A slider averages 6 to 7 mph less than most
fastballs and usually breaks about nine inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he throws it (the slider) enough so people know he
will throw it, that might be the tiny little difference that keeps
them from catching up to his fastball,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said the slider is the perfect pitch for Wagner, as
opposed to trying to learn a curve, which isn't as common among
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The key is to find which pitch, or what different style, best
suits a particular pitcher. And what he is trying to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you try and do is imagine what's the best combination of
pitches a guy can have to make it difficult on a hitter,'' said
Dierker, who won 139 games in 14 major-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy throws sidearm, you don't try and teach him to throw
a forkball,'' he said. ``You can't throw a forkball sidearm. You
have to look at the way a guy throws, and then say, `Well, here's
what he has that is good. What does he not have that would
complement that thing the most, that he may be able to learn?'''
</P>
<P>
   For many pitchers, change is a constant.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a career-high 16 wins last season, righthander Jose
Lima is trying to improve his slider and gain better command of his
sinking fastball and changeup.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Crow, challenging for a spot in the bullpen, is working on
a delivery that will give him better command of both corners of the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   When Crow joined the club, the Astros noticed he was successful
on the inside corner against righthanded hitters. It wasn't the
same when he threw outside. To help fix the problem, Crow has
shifted his position on the rubber in an effort to go straight at
hitters instead of throwing across his body.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to learn something new during the spring can help _ but
it also can hurt a player trying to make the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cabrera began last season with the Astros but missed most
of the year with a sore right shoulder. He didn't pitch winter ball
and entered camp last month lacking velocity on his fastball
because of the long layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had my fastball like it used to be,'' Cabrera said.
``They told me if my fastball didn't return like it used to be, I
needed to work on a two-seamer (sinker) to get hitters out.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I need to throw a lot of innings and try to pick up my
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   To help offset the loss in speed, the Astros encouraged Cabrera
to continue working on getting more movement on his sinker, which
he has thrown infrequently this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Righthander Jeff McCurry has been learning a sinker to go with
his fastball and slider. His greatest concentration, however, has
been in trying to hold runners on base better by using a speedier
delivery to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera and McCurry will continue their development in the minor
leagues when the season starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (spring training) is the perfect time for a veteran pitcher
to work on something but very difficult for a guy trying to make
the team,'' Dierker said. ``Sometimes you have to take a step
backward before you take two steps forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy trying to make the team can't afford to take a step
backward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
