<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo! Internet Life
 &HT;    Record companies: Be afraid, be very afraid.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an ongoing series of the 100 greatest minds of the 20th
Century, Time, ($3.95) profiles a new batch of braniacs. Some are
predictable (such as Albert Einstein and Sigmund Freud) and some
offbeat (like philosopher Ludwig Wittgenstein, and chemist Leo
Baekeland, the inventor of the first true plastic.) At 232 pages,
it is a huge issue, with other attractions as well, including a
detailed look at the balloon in which Swiss psychiatrist Bertrand
Piccard and British balloon instructor Brian Jones flew around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Punch line: How did Evander Holyfield rate a tie when he
fought Lennox Lewis? The headline ``Grand Larceny'' ought to give
you an idea. Sports Illustrated ($2.95) calls the Holyfield/Lewis
fight an ``unconscionable draw'' in a contest that clearly should
have gone to Lewis. ``Holyfield kept his belts? He looked lucky to
be alive,'' writes Richard Hoffer. ``Then seeing a jaunty Lewis,
largely unmarked, but without the belts he deserved, gave you that
old familiar feeling; shame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At the end of his rope: Dan Osman pioneered the edgiest of
extreme sports, a thrill-ride he called ``free-falling.'' Created
by a climber who kept slipping, it consists essentially of jumping
off very high places and falling a long way, to be jerked to a stop
by a climbing rope. But last year, when Osman leaped off the
1,100-foot Leaning Tower in the Yosemite National Park with a rope
that was supposed to bring him up 150-feet short of the bottom, he
miscalculated. Craig Vetter writes about the death of the daredevil
in the new Outside ($3.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keeping small fry safe: Speaking of safety, a new study
reveals that 85 percent of car seats are used incorrectly. Parents
($2.95) shows which seats work well, how to fit your child to the
proper seat, and how to install the one you've got.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wired for sound: What is .MP3? It is a compression format, a
way to digitally store high quality music and sounds, to be
delivered over the Internet. It is also giving nightmares to the
music industry, because the spread of .MP3 sites on the Web herald
a coming world of instant music distribution, a world in which
record stores will be irrelevant.  &QR;  Yahoo! Internet Life ($3.99, or
on the Web at www.yil.com) tells about the coming distribution
revolution, which, right now, is missing one thing, good music by
recognizable artists in the .MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lucky 13: Everything doesn't necessarily get better when you
hit it big. Friends fall away, your privacy is reduced and you have
to leave an old life behind. On the other hand, you can afford a
new house and throw yourself a heck of a party. Those are the major
indulgences for a machinist and his wife, when they win $6.5
million (after taxes) at Powerball. Money ($3.95) profiles the
Columbus, Ohio couple, John and Sandy, who are at least savvy
enough to avoid giving their last names to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hey, no sunburn! A new generation of college students are
forgoing the beer bongs and wet T-shirt contests of Spring Break to
rebuild churches and deliver food to sick shut-ins. U.S. News &AMP;
World Report ($2.95) writes up the new altruistic youngsters who,
instead of getting wasted, are getting to work.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
