<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-AFFIRMATIVEACTION23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A calm, thoughtful TV debate on race
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of blacks and whites of differing viewpoints sits around
a large table in front of television cameras and are pressed to
defend their positions on the role of race in America today.
</P>
<P>
   On some shows, the producers would be looking for passion,
explosive outbursts, maybe even some name-calling.
</P>
<P>
   In the restrained world of Charles Ogletree, however, there's
barely a raised voice or an interruption. Televised tranquility _
what a concept. Not that sparks don't fly; just that the intent is
not to start a conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree, a Harvard law professor, is the moderator of the Fred
Friendly Seminars, named for the late CBS News president who
exemplified some of the best impulses of TV journalism, and who
started these round tables. Ann Coulter, the jabber-jawed attorney
who was nearly ubiquitous during Monica-gate, and Ann Lewis, White
House director of communications, are the most recognizable;
they're joined by a roster of activists, academicians and people
with a tendency toward thoughtfulness even if they are members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The established format of the Friendly Seminars is for Ogletree
to pose a quasi-hypothetical situation _ a state university that
has weighted its admissions process and given preference to a black
candidate over a white _ and then challenge the panelists on the
morality of the problem. Between Ogletree's incisive questioning
and the panelists' willingness to listen rather than bark out
prepared killer sound bites, the hour is filled with more
intelligence and even genuine good will on a contentious subject
than a typical month's worth of TV debating.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: Beyond Black and White: A Web companion to the PBS
series on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.pbs.org/pov/tvraceinitiative/beyondblackandwhite/index.ht
ml
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond Black and White:
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative Action in America''
</P>
<P>
   11:30 tonight on WGTV.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A welcome how-to in moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
