<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CD23-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music back up prayers, chants
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you wonder when you see ``Abba Pater'' on sale at
stores, Pope John Paul II did not head over to the Vatican
recording studio for a day in the booth with earphones.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the pope's CD a tribute to a Swedish rock group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abba Pater'' (being released today in joint observance of Holy
Week and the 20th year of John Paul II's papacy) combines the
pope's voice with musical backdrops written _ collaged would be a
better word _ by Italian pop arranger Leonardo de Amicis. (Music
for two of the 11 tracks was provided by Stefano Mainetti.)
</P>
<P>
   The pope's voice is taken from recordings of the outdoor Masses
he has celebrated in Italy, France, Spain and the United States. In
addition to the languages of these countries, he prays and chants
the liturgy in Latin. Selections include ``Pater Noster'' (``Our
Father'') and the Beatitudes (from the Sermon on the Mount in the
Gospel of St. Matthew), as well as standard prayers from the Roman
Catholic liturgy that are given fancy new titles such as ``Christ
Is Freedom'' and ``Father of Light.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope's voice _ robust in some places, frail in others _
shows how much the man has aged in office. That vigorous Polish
cardinal, Karol Wojtyla, who greeted the world in its entire Babel
of tongues when he became pope in 1979, is now 82, an old man with
Parkinson's disease, who says he wants only to meet the new
millennium. No matter how one feels about the pope's conservative
theological positions, there is something very moving about his
all-too-discernible humanity. He is a man almost used up in the
service of God.
</P>
<P>
   What a shame the music behind him is so bland and gummy. It
ranges from phony Albinoni to pseudo-African chorus-and-drum stuff
_ ``Lambarena'' without any real Bach for backbone. It all
resembles the soundtrack to ``The Mission'' or ``Oscar and
Lucinda,'' up-river epics that are really symbolic spiritual
quests. With the voice of the pope offering a genuine ``interior
pilgrimage,'' as the CD proclaims, this musical pablum is doubly
insulting.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church has almost 2,000 years of great music
in its archives, from Gregorian chants to the mystical essays of
Olivier Messiaen. Yet the producers of this record _ Radio Vaticana
and the religious publisher San Paolo Audiovisivi, which will also
issue the title track as a music video _ ditched all of it in favor
of New Age schmaltz. How very Vatican II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abba Pater''
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Classical.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
