<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-UCONN-C     03-22 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-UCONN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UConn has 'The Bounce' that counts
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he ran through warmups before Connecticut's matchup with
Virginia in December 1998, Khalid El-Amin could not ignore the
screaming Cavaliers fan in the first row under one hoop at
University Hall. Every time the Huskies' pudgy point guard drove to
the basket during the layup drill, the fan held up a Domino's Pizza
box and yelled at El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   The reference to El-Amin's celebrated midsection and affection
for all things covered in cheese, sauce and pepperoni drew a
grudging chuckle from the player.
</P>
<P>
   Then El-Amin hit only two of 13 shots in the Huskies' 74-63
victory. But that was the first and last time, he insisted, that he
ever permitted a weighty jibe to hurt his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy kept yelling at me, 'Hey, are you hungry Khalid?
When's the last time you ate? If you're not hungry now, then you
will be by halftime.' `` said El-Amin, listed generously at
5-foot-10 and conservatively at 203 pounds. ``I didn't think it
would get to me like it did, because I've heard that kind of stuff
before. But I played a miserable game. And then I promised myself
that, any time it happened again, I'd make somebody eat his
words.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of his two seasons at Connecticut, the loquacious
El-Amin has been a man of his word. He has started 69 of 71 games
and his 1,060 points rank third in UConn history for a player in
his first two years. He led the club in assists and steals both
seasons and made five game-winning shots, including three in the
final 10 seconds of games.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Richard Hamilton, the pogo-stick forward and co-Big
East player of the year, is the Huskies' clutch player. In
application, however, it is El-Amin who typically has the ball in
his hands at the end of close games.
</P>
<P>
   UConn players call Hamilton ``The Bomb'' and El-Amin ``The
Bounce,'' for his ability to transfer his electric personality to
the court.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way for El-Amin almost from the moment he laced
up his first pair of sneakers at age 4 and his father, Charles
El-Amin, noticed the effortless way his son burst off the dribble
past older kids in their Minneapolis neighborhood. By the time he
was in third grade, El-Amin was playing on his brother's
seventh-grade team. Three times he led Minneapolis North High
School to the state championship, and El-Amin twice was state
player of the year. He committed to Clem Haskins' program at
Minnesota, then angered the locals by reneging on his promise and
heading to chilly Storrs, Conn., where he sensed the opportunity
for the national title was better and where ``they needed a vocal
guy like me to fire them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotion and competitiveness certainly mark El-Amin's game, but
it is his blinding quickness on the dribble that amazes opponents.
Connecticut is a team that looks to run at every opportunity, with
Hamilton and fellow forward Kevin Freeman among the best finishers
in the country, and El-Amin usually is at the middle of their
break. His jump shot frequently abandons El-Amin for stretches --
he was zero-for-12 Saturday afternoon in his foul-plagued
performance against Gonzaga -- but he is uncannily accurate at
crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   In profile, El-Amin, looks more like basketball writer than an
All-Big East player. On a playground, however, the Pillsbury point
guard would make plenty of dough, boy, hustling all the
disbelievers.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, he has used the ``Fat boy'' and ``Tubby''
barbs as motivation. In a game at Pittsburgh early this year, he
rallied the Huskies with five points in the final nine seconds,
then leaped onto the scorer's table after his game-winning
buzzer-beater to confront the fans who had taunted him. Against
Iowa last week, he twice responded to ugly chants from Hawkeyes
supporters by taking the ball the length of the court for layups.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like one of those Cabbage Patch dolls, you know?''
Freeman said. ``You look at him and think, 'No way can he be that
good.' But he really is a special player. And just as important,
he's a special person, too.''
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin's style and physique are different from any of the other
Final Four point guards -- Mateen Cleaves of Michigan State,
William Avery from Duke and Ohio State's Scooney Penn.A devout
Muslim who prays five times daily and rarely makes eye contact with
visitors to the locker room, El-Amin is a mouthy, whirling dervish
on the floor, constantly calling attention to himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that any of the other players in St. Petersburg
have been forced to learn responsibility at such a young age.
El-Amin was married at 16, fathered one son, Tezzaree, out of
wedlock at 17 and now has a two-month-old son, Ishmael, with his
wife, Jessica. He has deemed Jessica off-limits to the media, and
discussing his religion also is taboo, although he volunteered that
his father is a former imam and an older brother now holds that
title as a respected leader of his faith.
</P>
<P>
   Team manager Josh Nochimson, with whom El-Amin, Jessica and
Ishmael share a large, off-campus apartment, said last week that
Khalid plays for his sons and held up a pair of sneakers with their
names written on them. UConn coach Jim Calhoun, who had been
barraged by questions about his program's failure to make the Final
Four, it up when the subject turned to his point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's incredibly mature, about 15 going on 35, and very
bright,'' Calhoun said. ``People see the flash and the dash, but he
only lets you through a door to his life that he opens himself. The
place he is most comfortable is on the court, running the show, and
few people can run it like he does.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
</P>
<P>
   Info on Connecticut's Khalid El-Amin:
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) www.b-ball.com:8008/ uconn/players/amin.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
