<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES HEAR HOW CLINTON SEEKS DISMISSAL OF HIV-INFECTED OFFICER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: San Antonio, Texas) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president should be able to fire an
HIV-infected Air Force major who defied an order not to have
unprotected sex, the Clinton administration argued Monday before
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The administration urged the justices to overturn a military
court's decision blocking the firing of Maj. James T. Goldsmith of
Lackland Air Force Base in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith's attorney countered that President Clinton, although
commander-in-chief of the armed services, has no constitutional
authority to fire the airman.
</P>
<P>
   Although the issue of presidential authority was at stake, the
justices appeared more concerned with the nuances of the military
justice system than with Clinton's constitutional authority as they
pressed the administration's lawyer, U.S. Deputy Solicitor General
Michael Dreeben, and Goldsmith's attorney, John Economidy of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Why was a basic personnel decision before the military's highest
court in the first place? the justices asked. But Goldsmith's saga
is anything but basic, agreed attorneys for the government and the
major.
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith was court-martialed and found guilty of willfully
disobeying Col. John P. Tagnesi's order that he tell intimate
partners he is HIV-positive and to use protective methods to
prevent transfer of his infection. Goldsmith, who had unprotected
sex with a female officer and a civilian woman, was sentenced March
4, 1994, to six years' confinement at the U.S. Disciplinary
Barracks at Fort Leavenworth, Kan. He also forfeited $2,500 per
month for the six years because of his disobedience and related
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Although the court chose not to discharge him from the military,
the Air Force, acting at Clinton's behest, initiated Goldsmith's
discharge based on his conviction. Goldsmith challenged his
dismissal as unconstitutional, saying he already had been punished
for his actions and that the president's effort to fire him would
amount to a second punishment, in violation of the constitution's
prohibition on double jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton sought to fire Goldsmith under a 1996 law
allowing the president to terminate officers who had been sentenced
to at least six months in prison. The major argued that the
Constitution prohibits the president from relying on that 1996 law
because it was not enacted until after Goldsmith had committed his
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces agreed with the
major and issued an order Aug. 25, 1997, blocking the president.
Two months later, Goldsmith's sentence expired and he returned to
duty status.
</P>
<P>
   Dreeben, pressing the president's case, told the justices that
the Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces had no jurisdiction to
rule on what amounted to a personnel dispute between the president
and Goldsmith. The major should have taken his concerns not to a
military court but to the Air Force secretary, the Air Force's
Board for Correction of Military Records or a federal district
court, Dreeben said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist questioned whether the
Board for Correction is the proper venue for a personnel issue.
Rehnquist, a published historian, noted that the Army's Board for
Correction recently ruled not on a personnel issue but on a
longstanding appeal when it cleared Dr. Samuel Mudd of wrongdoing
for setting the broken leg of Abraham Lincoln's assassin, John
Wilkes Booth, in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer then asked Dreeben why the military's
highest court would lack jurisdiction to decide the merits of
Goldsmith's constitutional challenge to the president. ``We have an
expert military court saying he (Goldsmith) is right,'' Breyer
said, referring to the Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Dreeben said military courts are designed to
enforce the Uniform Code of Military Justice and to re-enforce
order and discipline in the ranks. Constitutional claims are more
appropriately handled in federal civilian courts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Countering Dreeben, Economidy said the Board for Correction is
ill-suited for hearing constitutional challenges to adverse
personnel actions. The board would regard Goldsmith's appeal as an
extension of the court-martial proceeding, over which the board has
no authority, Economidy said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rehnquist disagreed with the attorney's argument that the
board's jurisdiction is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Economidy responded that he had no time to test the open
question of whether the board could consider the constitutional
claims of his terminally ill client. Instead, the attorney said he
turned to the Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces because it
certainly has jurisdiction to hear constitutional challenges to
presidential personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client at the time was dying,'' Economidy said. ``I had to
move very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldsmith is still on duty at Lackland. The justices are
expected to render their decision in the case, Clinton vs.
Goldsmith, by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
