<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIAONE-COX     03-22 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIAONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comcast to purchase MediaOne; broadband on the way to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The $60 billion bid by Comcast Corp. to buy MediaOne
Group is aimed at building a global powerhouse for all manner of
digital telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the companies _ both large cable television
operators in metro Atlanta _ said they agreed to a stock swap that
will create the nation's 36th-largest corporation, putting the
combined company in position to compete for consumers and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, almost certainly bound to include job cuts after the
merger, is an endorsement of the notion that high-speed data
delivery _ broadband _ will soon be the means for transmitting
voice and information. It will be the way that consumers get their
television, video and Internet access, as well as their phone
service, all on one line. The much-ballyhooed convergence of
technologies will let either a phone or cable company be the
primary provider of service.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gantt, president of the Ansley Group, said the
Comcast-MediaOne deal is confirmation that the struggle for
dominance between cable companies and phone companies is under way.
``People are looking for a high-powered pipeline into the houses.
This is the globalization of convergence, where all the telecom
companies try to hook up the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast will pay for MediaOne in assumed debt and stock, giving
1.1 Class A shares for each MediaOne share.
</P>
<P>
   Industry consolidation has been the trend, as partners look for
more muscle in buying power and lower costs through greater scale.
Most prominent of recent months was the massive purchase of cable
company TCI by AT&AMP;T, a deal intended to give the long-distance
company a way to customer homes.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Roberts, president and chief executive of
Philadelphia-based Comcast, told reporters that the deal will let
the combined companies move up to a new league. ``In one fell
swoop, we can create the pre-eminent broadband distribution company
in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 million subscribers, the combined company would lag only
Time Warner with 12.6 million and AT&AMP;T's TCI unit with 12.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bruce Leichtman of the Yankee Group said that bigger
companies can negotiate better contracts with programmers and
suppliers and can cut redundant costs. ``That size gives you a lot
of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller carriers like Adelphia and Atlanta-based Cox
Communications can prosper, but they must at least consider
mergers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, spokeswoman Ellen East of Cox Communications, which has
about 3.8 million subscribers, said size is not all-important.
``Equally important is having the right markets, dominating those
markets and having quality operations in those markets. We may be
smaller than some, but we are far ahead in launching new
services.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cable companies are not directly competing with each
other. Their long-range rival is the entrenched local phone
company.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lillis, president and chief executive of MediaOne, said
the souped-up Comcast will be able go after customers it now
ignores. For example, the companies' networks already pass tens of
thousands of small businesses. ``We currently get just about zero
revenue from small business, but small business can buy and sell an
awful of things on the network. We see a stunning opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   A strategy of luring businesses would thrust Comcast into a
market traditionally controlled by local phone companies like
BellSouth. That dominance is already under attack by large
providers like MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T as well as smaller rivals like
Level 3, Intermedia, NextLink and ICG Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Creech, BellSouth spokesman, said the company believes it
can compete against cable companies offering packages of phone,
Internet and television service. For instance, BellSouth offers
wireless television and high-speed digital subscriber lines for
Internet access now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mosaic approach, but in the long term it will alow us
to respond to customers with video, and high-speed Internet
access.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is vulnerable because coverage areas of its wireless
television and DSL services are both spotty. Wireless television
depends on being in sight of a tranmitter, and DSL is available on
500,000 lines out of several million in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Reali, analyst for Dataquest, said there are now about
600,000 subscribers to high-speed cable modems in North America,
compared with only about 62,000 DSL lines in service. ``But it's
going to be a very aggressive year for DSL.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has been a supporter of the broadband service known as
At Home, while MediaOne uses a service called Roadrunner. While the
companies have not said which service will get the nod, Reali said
she expects a sharing of the two that could speed the roll-out of
service for both.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, like other cable companies, Comcast and MediaOne were
originally one-way systems built to transmit television signals to
viewers. But in the past several years, the cable industry has
spent upwards of $5 billion upgrading networks to handle two-way,
high-speed data. MediaOne has spent about $1 billion, much of it in
metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, both Comcast and MediaOne will have completed 70
percent of the planned upgrade, according to Roberts. ``That
broadband platform is what this merger is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The huge value of the Comcast deal is seen as pre-empting any
rival offers for MediaOne. But even assuming no bidding war, the
agreement is subject to approval of federal regulators and
completion is not expected until late this year. At least until
then, the companies will continue as separate entities and Atlanta
customers will see no effect on service, officials said. MediaOne
spokesman Dave Wood went a step farther, promising no rate
increases for the duration of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, the merger will give the combined company about
804,000 subscribers, according to Roberts. MediaOne has about
540,000 subscribers, including operations in Atlanta, as well as
other parts of metro Atlanta counties. MediaOne lines pass about
900,000 homes, and the construction of upgraded lines for video is
now about one-third complete, said spokesman Reg Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast, the state's second-largest cable company, has systems
in parts of DeKalb County, including Dunwoody, Doraville and
Chamblee, as well as Walton, Carroll, Gordon and Paulding counties,
and in some communities outside metro Atlanta. Comcast officials
were unavailable to provide information about the extent of the
company's upgrade effort in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
