<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR BROADCAST LOST AT LEAST 9 MILLION VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday night's Academy Awards broadcast on ABC suffered a
significant ratings drop from the 1998 version, drawing at least 10
percent fewer viewers, preliminary figures showed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen's early figures projected a 34.7 rating, which would be
6 points, or 17 percent, lower than that of the the 1998 broadcast.
But ABC's own estimate of the total number of viewers who watched
at least some part of the show was 78 million, down about 10
percent from 87 million viewers a year ago. Official ratings are to
be issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives quickly pointed out that last year's show was
wildly popular, largely because the wildly popular ``Titanic''
dominated the awards. This year was also the first time that the
Oscar ceremony was held on a Sunday night, although that decision
was made at least partly to maximize its ratings potential.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the numbers fell far enough that the Academy Awards will
probably not even be the second highest-rated television show of
the year, after the Super Bowl, as it usually is. It won't even be
the highest-rated broadcast on ABC this season, because it looks as
if Oscar will lose to Barbara Walters' interview with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky interview this month averaged a 33.4 rating, while
ABC's estimates of the Academy Awards show put it in the range of a
28 to 29 rating. (Each Nielsen rating point represents 994,000
homes.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC, which charged advertisers a record $1 million for each
30-second commercial during the Oscars show (dwarfing the $800,000
figure sought but paid only for a couple of commercials for the
Lewinsky interview), tried to play down the disappointment by
noting that this year's show did better than the 1997 Academy
Awards broadcast, a gain of about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But that show was the lowest-rated Oscar show in a decade. At
the time ABC said the low ratings resulted from a lack of
enthusiasm about that year's big movies, with ``The English
Patient,'' based on the novel by Michael Ondaatje, leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   This year, another English film with literary roots,
``Shakespeare in Love,'' was the big winner, taking seven awards
including best picture. Both films happen to have come from the
same studio, Miramax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
