<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPLANE-SAFETY-2TAKE     03-22 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPLANE-SAFETY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY BOARD SEEKS TO ANSWER SOME LONGSTANDING QUESTIONS ABOUT
BOEING 737 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Colo., Md., Fla., Conn.)  (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Transportation Safety Board will try
on Tuesday to end the longest investigation in its history, and
establish the reason for two crashes and several harrowing
incidents involving the world's most popular jetliner, the Boeing
737. But after four and a half years of intensive investigation,
there are no simple answers in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The board has already issued 27 recommendations, most concerning
the possibility of rudder malfunction since beginning its
investigation of a fatal crash of a USAir jet in Pittsburgh in
September 1994. When it meets Tuesday to consider the probable
cause of that crash, it could vote to issue new recommendations,
which would cost Boeing and the airlines billions of dollars to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   One recommendation drafted by the board's staff calls for the
Federal Aviation Administration to assure that the rudder control
mechanism is more ``reliably redundant,'' one board official said.
The board often does not specify what hardware should be changed or
added, but people involved in the investigation said that
recommendation could mean a second hydraulic mechanism to control
the rudder.
</P>
<P>
   Another recommendation under consideration is to broaden the
testing beyond the hydraulic valve, and to look for the possibility
that a pressure wave, like a bang in the pipes of an old house when
someone turns off a faucet, is intermittently causing malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Boeing and the FAA, which would decide if more
changes are needed, have been arguing that the stubby twin-jets
have always been safe and have been made yet safer by the many
lessons learned in the first stages of the investigation. It
centered on USAir 427, which went down in September 1994 on an
approach to Pittsburgh International Airport, killing all 132
passengers and crew. The findings, however, could also have a
bearing on the crash of United flight 585, another 737, which
crashed in Colorado Springs in March 1991, killing all 25 aboard.
That crash thus far has been attributed to a meteorological
phenomenon called wind rotor.
</P>
<P>
   Other 737s have experienced rudder problems. Most recently, a
737 operated by USAirways, as USAir is now known, made an emergency
landing in Baltimore while en route from Orlando, Fla., to
Hartford, Conn. The plane had already been equipped with a new
hydraulic valve meant to eliminate a possible problem identified
after the Pittsburgh crash _ a valve that controls a rudder has
been found to jam. When that happens, and the pilot steps on a
pedal calling for a small move in one direction, the rudder can
swing all the way in the opposite direction, and stick there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Boeing and the FAA say that a variety of changes already
made or now in progress will reduce risk to an infinitesimal level.
``We believe we have fixed any possible scenarios that may have
been associated with the accident,'' said Elizabeth Erickson,
deputy director of aircraft certification at the FAA, although she
added that it was possible no one would ever be certain of what
caused the Pittsburgh crash.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing executive, Michael Denton, a former chief project
engineer for three versions of the 737, said the investigation was
``really a very serious business for the Boeing company and it's a
very serious business for the flying public.'' He said, though,
that even without a definitive cause for the accident, ``Over the
last four and a half years, the aviation industry and the Boeing
company made the 737 a safer airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing insists that there is no sign of malfunction in the
rudder; one of its theories is that a crew member stomped on a
pedal that controls rudder movement, and held it there as the plane
then skidded through the sky, nose turned too far sideways until it
could no longer fly and then corkscrewed to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators have conceded that there are no signs or
marks on the rudder's hydraulic valve, recovered from the wreckage.
But the airplane's path could have been caused only by a hard swing
of the rudder to one side, engineers say, and Boeing agrees that
the reason might have been mechanical, even if there is no physical
evidence for that.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty for so long about so popular an airplane is what
airlines, plane manufacturers and safety officials fear most. But
the FAA and Boeing say they are in the midst of a major renovation
of the planes in service, of which there are about 1,300 registered
in this country and 3,000 worldwide. Those changes, combined with
changes in procedures and pilot training, have solved the problem,
they say, even if they cannot say what the problem was.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the point, Boeing produced a video to explain its
position that the plane was safe before the crash but has been made
even safer since then. At the end of the eight-minute program, the
narrator solemnly assures listeners that there have been 50 Boeing
737 landings or takeoffs during the video's running time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the investigations have turned up troubling factors about
the plane. One is a mechanism for jamming the valve that controls
the rudder without leaving any scars or marks that investigators
can find later.
</P>
<P>
   Four board members will vote to determine probable cause; a
fifth, John J. Goglia, recused himself because he worked for USAir
at the time of the accident. A key question before them is whether
the rudder design, driven by a single hydraulic valve, meets the
standards for redundancy. Before the accident, Boeing and the FAA
said that it did, because it had two different moveable portions,
one inside the other, to translate the pilots' commands into
channeling of hydraulic fluid and movement of the rudder, and that
if one failed, the other would continue working.
</P>
<P>
   But the safety board may have identified two mechanisms by which
a single failure could cause a rudder malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA and Boeing have taken several steps. One is to replace
part of the hydraulic valve, to preclude a jam in part of its
intricate mechanism from causing the rudder to move opposite from
the way the pilot wanted. Another is to reduce the maximum
hydraulic pressure _ and thus the maximum angle that the rudder can
swing _ when the plane is above a few hundred feet. (It must be
able to swing freely at low altitude, to handle an engine failure
on takeoff, when a big rudder is vital to handle the uneven thrust
from the remaining engine.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Any rudder malfunction is now more benign,'' said Ms.
Erickson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has also distributed training materials for pilots, to
teach them more about how to cope with a plane at an ``unusual
attitude,'' that is, with the wings banked at over 45 degrees, or
the nose pointing up more than 25 degrees or down more than 10
degrees. But in a position that is unusual on the eve of a board
vote to determine the cause, both the company and the FAA
steadfastly maintain that while the problem is solved, its precise
nature is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the hearing,'' said Denton, ``we don't have
conclusive evidence that would allow us to say it was flight crew
or a specific airplane system that caused the rudder to go hard
over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
