<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0165 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV28-NYT     03-22 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRANBERRY BOGS  
 GETTING MARRIED IN FRANCE  
 SEEING THE LATEST FASHIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL FREIREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)My family and I are interested in visiting the Ocean
Spray cranberry factory and its cranberry bogs. Are there tours and
what would be the best month to go? _ Jo Laflin, West Hartford,
Conn.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. There's not much of a chance that you'll see both the bogs
and the factory on the same trip. A bog that's on display is in
Plymouth, Mass., on Cape Cod, and the Ocean Spray factory that the
public can see is in a suburb of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The bog display is part of Cranberry World, which has a museum
that uses videos and interactive displays to tell the story of
cranberry cultivation from before Pilgrim times to today. Both
modern and early harvesting tools are on view.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is free, as are samples of cranberry drinks and
snacks, and there is a gift shop whose wares include
cranberry-scented candles and cranberry candy. If the demonstration
bog doesn't satisfy, a drive along Routes 3, 44 and 58 near
Plymouth and South Carver should.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-minute walk from Plymouth Rock, Cranberry World is open
this year from May 1 to Nov. 28. The hours are 9:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.
daily. Information: (508) 747-2350 or (800) 662-3263. The sponsor
of the museum is Ocean Spray, a cooperative of growers in five
states and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best time of year to visit Massachusetts cranberry
country is October. That is when the bogs are flooded in a process
called wet harvesting. Water reels _ huge devices resembling
eggbeaters _ churn the water to loosen the berries, which then
float to the surface and are gathered. Also in October, from the
10th to 12th this year, there's an annual harvest festival in South
Carver, Mass., at the Edaville Cranberry Bog, on Rochester Road,
off Route 58. (It's a 15-minute drive from Plymouth.) The program
lists harvesting tours, craft demonstrations, a cranberry museum
and entertainment. Admission is free, with a suggested $1 parking
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Ocean Spray plant, where drinks are bottled and canned, is
at 1301 American Pacific Drive in Henderson, Nev. It is part of
Cranberry World West, and in addition to exhibitions and free
drinks and snacks, visitors can pause at a viewing bay to watch
part of the production process. Often that means bottles being
labeled; there is no actual plant tour. Information: (800)
289-0917.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to go the state that has become the country's
leading cranberry producer, it's Wisconsin. There, in the town of
Warrens, six miles east of I-94, you'll find Cranberry Expo, a
museum (with a video and exhibitions that include harvesting
equipment from the 1870s to today) and craft and gift shops. Open
April 1 to Oct. 31 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $5. Cranberry Expo is at 28388 County EW, a 45-minute
drive, basically west, from Lacrosse. Information: (608) 378-4878,
fax (608) 378-4290. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)We would like to get married in Paris. What
arrangements would we have to take care of to get a marriage
license? _ David A. van der Steen, Brooklyn, N.Y.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It may be good news or a nuisance, but there is a residency
requirement of at least 40 days. That means that either the
prospective bride or bridegroom must have lived in the same
departement (district) or arrondissement for at least 30 days
before the civil ceremony plus the 10 days during which the
marriage banns are published where the ceremony is to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Under French law, the ceremony must be performed by a civil
authority. And if there is a religious ceremony, it must follow the
civil one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noting that residency and other rules may vary, French officials
urge a check with local authorities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for required documents, among them are these:
</P>
<P>
   _ A medical certificate from each party with results of blood
tests. The certificates must be submitted before the banns can be
published and be dated within two months before the banns are
published. Americans can be examined in the United States by a
doctor approved by the French Consulate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ A birth certificate translated into French and affidavits by
the couple stating, if applicable, how a previous marriage came to
be terminated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ An affidavit (certificat de coutume) in French by an approved
lawyer stating that each party is free to marry in France and that
the marriage will be recognized in the United States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a list of authorized translators and doctors, get in touch
with one of the French Consulates General in the United States.
Among them is one at 934 Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10021; (212)
606-3689, fax (212) 606-3620; www.franceconsulatny.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I am interested in the fashion industry and designer
collections and would like to attend runway shows given by
designers in New York. How could I arrange that? _ Nora Gorton, La
Mirada, Calif.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The showings of fashion collections in New York are for
buyers, the media and corporate sponsors, but not the general
public, according to the Council of Fashion Designers of America,
which organizes them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You won't be able to see the shows in person, but you can catch
some of the runway action on television or the Web. The men's
spring-summer collections for 2000 are scheduled for this July 26
to 29, and the women's spring-summer collections for 2000 for Sept.
12 to 17. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, www.7thonsixth.com, is the official fashion designer
council site. A generous dose of fashion is dispensed by E!
Entertainment Television and by Style, a cable channel that repeats
some E! programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the regularly scheduled fashion programs are these:
</P>
<P>
   E!'s ``Fashion File,'' on Saturday at 10 a.m.,
``Video-fashion,'' on Saturday at 10:30 a.m. and ``Model TV,'' on
Tuesday at 5:30 p.m. These times apply to both Eastern and Pacific
time zones; all three shows are also on Style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Style's ``Model,'' on Saturday at 10 p.m. Eastern, 7 p.m.
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's ``Style With Elsa Klensch,'' on Saturday at 10:30 a.m.
Eastern and 7:30 a.m. Pacific time.
</P>
<P>
   VH-1's ``Fashion Television,'' with Jeanne Beker, on Friday at
7:30 a.m. on both coasts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you visit New York, stop at the Costume Institute of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue and 82nd Street; (212)
535-7710. From April 6 to Aug. 22, the exhibition is ``Our New
Clothes: Acquisitions From the 1990's,'' which includes the work of
Geoffrey Beene, Calvin Klein and Giorgio di Sant'Angelo. Admission
to the museum is $10. Closed Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
