<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      03-22 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S POLICY ON KOSOVO FACES RISKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In six years, President Clinton has managed to
dispatch the US military to such far-flung corners of the world as
Haiti, Bosnia and Iraq without having to justify a single American
combat death.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kosovo situation threatens to snap that streak of good
fortune, diplomatic experts say. Regardless of whether Monday's
last-ditch effort by the United States to find a diplomatic
solution works or fails, US military personnel, as even Clinton
admits, are much less likely to emerge unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   If diplomacy fails, American and NATO pilots are poised to
launch air strikes in Kosovo, strikes that would require the pilots
to face sophisticated Yugoslav air defenses and maybe to fly low to
go after Serbian ground troops, which would significantly increase
the risk.
</P>
<P>
   If Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic calls off an offensive
against ethnic Albanian rebels and signs a peace agreement,
Americans and other NATO troops, acting as a peacekeeping force,
would be thrust into the middle of a bitter civil war. The shooting
could possibly continue up until the day they arrive _ and probably
after.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, this is a very dangerous climate in which
things can and probably will go wrong, in which Americans and
others are going to die, or at least we'll have to be prepared for
that,'' said Ivo H. Daalder, a former National Security Council
official who is now a visiting fellow in foreign policy studies at
the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Clinton administration's efforts so far to explain
the rationale for its military plans have been insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way to make the case, and it's not an easy
case to make. Most people don't know where Kosovo is. There have
been horrific things happening, but the scale is relatively small.
If 2,000 people had died in a year, that's a lot,'' Daalder said.
He compared Kosovo to the 10-month-old war in the Horn of Africa
between Ethopia and Eritrea, where many more have died without
triggering a US impulse to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has stepped up up his campaign to sway a divided
Congress and a skeptical public on why the country should become
engaged in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After devoting only a radio address to the issue last month,
Clinton last Friday began trying to lay out the case for military
action, saying of the Serbs, ``I think the threshold for their
conduct has already been crossed.'' He declared, ``If we don't act,
the war will spread.''
</P>
<P>
   He also summoned a bipartisan group of lawmakers to the White
House that day, and he has invited in 50 to 60 congressional
leaders, including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, to discuss Kosovo Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after returning from an overnight stay at Camp David,
Clinton said ending the tragedy in Kosovo is ``the right thing''
and the ``smart thing to do, very much in our national interests,
if we are to leave a stable, peaceful and democratic Europe to our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned a lot of lessons in the last 50 years,'' he
said. ``One of them surely is that we have a stake in European
freedom and security and stability. I hope that can be achieved by
peaceful means. If not, we have to be prepared to act.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that with so much at stake in Kosovo _ the lives of
American and other allied troops, Europe's role and future, the
credibility of NATO and the destabilization of American allies such
as Greece and Turkey, it is imperative that Clinton make a stronger
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the biggest immediate foreign policy
challenge of his presidency,'' said Janusz Bugajski, director of
Eastern European studies at the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, a foreign policy think tank. ``This is a
crisis in the middle of Europe, which threatens to spill throughout
the Balkans and threaten NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is even bigger than Bosnia,'' he continued. ``Bosnia was
a much-more self-contained conflict. If this is allowed to
continue, it could draw in several neighboring states.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that any military action carries risk, Mike Hammer,
a spokesman for the National Security Council, said having a peace
agreement in hand would significantly lower the risk of casualities
and was one reason Clinton sent US special envoy Richard Holbrooke
to Belgrade Monday to try to persuade Milosevic to stop Serb
aggression in the province, where ethnic Albanians are seeking
their independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deployment of the military is never without risk,'' Hammer
said. ``However, moving into a permissive environment, where the
parties have agreed to allow a NATO peacekeeping force, is
something where the risks are considerably less, as we have seen in
Bosnia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daalder said a diplomatic settlement may be difficult. ``We're
asking Serbs to withdraw some 38,000 troops out of Kosovo, and
asking the (Albanians) to de-militarize and put their trust in
NATO. Those are big demands that may not be easily heeded to, and
we may have to use force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we deploy troops in Kosovo and haven't made the case, the
reaction in the country may force us to take action that we
otherwise wouldn't want to take,'' Daalder said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bugajski said the consequence of not acting are even
grimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest failure would be if NATO and the US simply sit by
and allow these massacres and displacement of population to
continue,'' he said. However, he added, ``The question is if NATO
is to bomb, what would happen next?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
