<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-SHORTAGE-ART-     03-22 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-SHORTAGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURRENT NURSING SHORTAGE MORE SERIOUS THAN THOSE OF PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., N.J., Colo., Tenn., Kan., Fla., Mass., Wash.,
Ariz., N.M., Iowa, Canada) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Driven in part by an aging population and the
turmoil of managed care, the nation's hospitals are experiencing a
shortage of registered nurses, especially the specialized, highly
trained nurses who staff operating rooms, emergency rooms,
intensive care units and pediatric wards for high-risk babies.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage began a year ago in California and this year it has
touched nearly all acute care hospitals, where patients go with
strokes, heart attacks and major surgery, and which employ nearly
two-thirds of all registered nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're experiencing what almost every hospital is
experiencing,'' said Kathleen Smith, director of acute care patient
services at St. Mary's Hospital in Waterbury, Conn., which has
placed newspaper advertisements inviting operating-room candidates
to open houses and hospital tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a shortage of more experienced nurses, particularly in
specialty areas,'' Ms. Smith said. ``We're seeing nurses getting
older and older, and not enough new nurses are coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   In a striking response to the shortage, the St. John's Regional
Medical Center in Oxnard, Calif., the principal hospital serving
Ventura County north of Los Angeles, announced on Thursday that it
would close part of its acute care space.
</P>
<P>
   The California Nurses Association said that St. John's was
raising the pay of critical care nurses by $5 an hour, to more than
$20 an hour, angering many other nurses who have been denied
raises.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing shortages happen every decade or so and have always
corrected themselves as wages rise and lure more students into
nursing. But this time, nursing schools and hospital administrators
say the cycle seems to have stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals and nurses' organizations see many causes of the
decline. One is demographic. Nurses are growing older and retiring
just as the baby-boom generation approaches the age of failing
health. Women, who still make up 90 percent of all nurses, also
have far more and better-paying career choices than they once did,
including becoming doctors. And nurses often cite unintended
consequences of hospital belt-tightening, with laid-off nurses
rebuffing appeals to return to the bedside and shifting instead to
new administrative jobs with pharmaceutical and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   For several years at least, hospitals warn, the shortage will
worsen. For patients, that could mean waiting longer for a nurse's
intervention, or, in extreme cases, traveling to hospitals farther
from home for acute care. The American Association of Colleges of
Nursing says that its 500 or so member colleges, which produce
nurses with bachelor's and master's degrees, enrolled 5.5 percent
fewer nurses last year than in 1997, the fourth decline in as many
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shortage appears to be a new and different type,'' said a
report last month of a survey of 338 acute care hospitals sponsored
by the American Organization of Nurse Executives, a subsidiary of
the American Hospital Association, and conducted in collaboration
with the Department of Health and Human Services and the American
Nurses Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previous shortages,'' the report said, ``have been about
sufficient numbers of nurses, while this shortage appears to be
about an increased demand for nurses with competence, skills and
experience to meet patient demand for care in a changing health
care system.''
</P>
<P>
   Deloras Jones, director of nursing for the California Division
of Kaiser Permanente, the big health maintenance organization that
treats patients in its own hospitals, sees two shortages.
</P>
<P>
   There is a shortage now, Ms. Jones said, arising from a serious
lack of experienced, specialized registered nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are at the verge of a very serious shortage related to
the aging of the work force,'' she said. The average age of nurses
is 45, about a decade older than the average for the population.
They will be retiring with the baby-boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Of 190,000 working nurses in California, Ms. Jones said, the
state's licensing board found that 57,000, about 30 percent, were
over 50, and that half planned to retire within four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of nurses who are currently practicing are in the
46-to-58 age range,'' said Kathryn Hall, executive director of the
Maryland Nurses Association. ``Add five or ten years, and they'll
be retiring. Then you look back to the 18-to-27 age bracket, and
the numbers are just staggeringly low.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the flow of young people into nursing diminishing,
so is the quality of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have a shortage in terms of educational preparation,''
said Arlene Sargent, director of the undergraduate nursing program
at Samuel Merritt College in Oakland, Calif. Jeanne Jenkins, a
spokeswoman for Merritt, said the college has kept enrollments
steady only by dipping deeper into the waiting list for less
qualified applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are seeking women who have left nursing to raise
children, and full-time nurses, who can be lured into extra
part-time assignments with wages of $30 or more an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Rowe, 33, has bachelor's and master's degrees in nursing
from Rutgers University. She is a full-time nurse in the intensive
care unit at Cooper Hospital in Camden, N.J., and is paid $20.80 an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   It can be arduous work. Cooper has maintained its customary
staff of nine registered nurses each shift for the unit's 16 beds,
but to shave costs, Cooper has eliminated all but one of three to
four aides, so nurses take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Rowe and many nurses, full-time is a three-day week of
12-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So then I moonlight,'' Ms. Rowe said, through an agency called
Favorite Nurses. One day a week, the agency dispatches her to
another hospital. ``I get $30 an hour days, $36 nights,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing journals and newspapers are awash with advertisements
for nurses like Ms. Rowe. ``R.N.'s'' shouts an employment agency's
advertisement for a Washington, D.C., hospital. ``Big Bonus
Bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A hospital in Colorado Springs, Colo., promises $1,000 bonuses
to local nurses it hires, $2,000 to other Coloradans and $5,000 to
nurses from other states. Like many hospitals, St. Francis Hospital
in Memphis, Tenn., is advertising $1,000 bounties to employees who
lure friends to its nursing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Nursefinders, a temporary help agency with 119 offices in 36
states, has 8,000 nurses in hospitals, but the company cannot keep
up with the demand. ``We're filling half the orders we receive,''
said Neal Ostman, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are going to new lengths to keep nurses, especially
those with young children. Dawn Murphy, director of human resources
at St. Luke's Hospital in Kansas City, Mo., said that to retain
part-time nurses, the hospital has cut to 16 from 20 the hours they
must work to earn health and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's is also dispatching recruiters to Canada, so far with
little success. Lots of luck, said Deborah Moores, managing
director of Medhunters, a Toronto company that places nurses with
American and Canadian hospitals. ``The Province of Ontario wants to
hire 10,000 nurses,'' Ms. Moores said.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage has been a boon to a growing corps of nomad nurses,
called travelers. Mary Gibson, 59, of no fixed address, became a
registered nurse after raising three children. After a divorce, she
sold her home in Andover, Mass., and 11 years ago loaded a minivan
with her television, VCR, linens, dishes, pots and pans, family
photographs and stethoscope, and hit the road.
</P>
<P>
   This winter Ms. Gibson is parked at a hospital in Cape Coral,
Fla., where she works three 12-hour shifts a week on a
post-operative neurosurgery floor. She has also worked in Seattle;
Phoenix; Albuquerque, N.M.; Boston; Fontana, Calif.; Washington,
D.C., and Fall River, Mass. Where next? ``It's way too soon to
think about that,'' Ms. Gibson said. ``I'll be here to mid-June.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gibson's actual employer is TravCorps of Malden, Mass.,
which says it has 1,300 travelers, nearly all nurses, working three
to six-month stints at understaffed hospitals. The company provides
Ms. Gibson's benefits, apartments, utilities and travel expenses,
and her wage of $20 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals that hire travelers say they are constrained by the
exigencies of managed care _ the cuts in reimbursements they
receive from Medicare, insurance companies and health maintenance
organizations. So among other cost-cutting measures, they have
eliminated the cushion of nurses that let them respond to surges in
demand for care, like flu epidemics.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, the patient services executive at St. Mary's, which
has 347 beds, keeps a permanent staff to accommodate its average of
150 patients. That staff alone is hard to maintain, so she has
added some travelers. When the number of patients exceeds 150, she
plumbs her list of 30 or 40 ``per diems'' _ free-agent nurses,
usually with other regular jobs, who can come in for a shift.
</P>
<P>
   But all the bonuses and recruiting have done little to break the
shortage. During the last shortage, a decade ago, ``employers were
able to throw dollars at it, and the nurses appeared,'' said Ms.
Hall of the Maryland Nurses Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many had left the profession but were still out there,'' Ms.
Hall said. ``Now the majority are working, so bonuses are just
luring nurses from hospital to hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools of nursing detect a big change from the days, four or
five years ago, when hospitals were laying off nurses in response
to the cost-cutting pressures of managed care and urging the
schools to cut back enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   After a long hiatus, said Mary Blegen, associate dean for
academic affairs at the University of Iowa's nursing school,
``Recruiters are coming in from all over the country, and they're
talking about sign-on bonuses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
