<SLUG> BC-HOMEBUYER-PREFERENCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNTY HOME BUYERS RANK LONG BEACH AS TOP CHOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Beverly Hills has ZIP code cachet. Santa Clarita
offers tract after tract of new homes with vistas of rolling,
brush-covered hills. So where would new home buyers in Los Angeles
County prefer to put down roots?
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa by the Sea. Really, no joke.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive year, Long Beach is considered the
most desired locale in Los Angeles County for new home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita, fast become the in spot for maturing Generation
Xers, ranked second in the survey by The Meyers Group Consulting
Services LLC, an Irvine-based real estate consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is based on eight factors such as jobs, crime rate,
attractions and housing affordability, plus Meyers' own subjective
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach got great marks in just about every area except crime
and things to do, even thought the city has a new aquarium. Its
crime ranking, based on statistics from the FBI, was the highest in
the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita, on the other hand, got the best crime ranking.
But there isn't much to do there, either, except enjoy the safe
streets. That is, assuming you can afford to buy a house there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare (Long Beach) with the ability to buy a home
at a reasonable price, where else would you rather go?'' said John
Burns, Meyers' senior managing director.
</P>
<P>
   This is how cities cities in Los Angeles County stack up as the
preferred address for new home buyers. The numbers reflect total
rankings in eight categories, with lower numbers best:
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach 22
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita 26
</P>
<P>
   Glendale 27
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles 27
</P>
<P>
   Torrance 27
</P>
<P>
   Burbank 28
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena 32
</P>
<P>
   Downey 38
</P>
<P>
   West Covina 38
</P>
<P>
   El Monte 38
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2041EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-TDNA-COX     03-22 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TDNA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On big issues, Bush takes a seatBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As his audience widens, Gov. George W. Bush
remains a presidential contender with a penchant for dancing around
the soft edges of hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   On topics like affirmative action, hate crime legislation and
making abortion a litmus test for U.S. Supreme Court nominees, Bush
is less than perfectly clear.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these issues _ ones that can quickly define a candidate
for a nationwide electorate looking for signals _ came up at a
Monday news conference after a Bush speech to the Texas Daily
Newspaper Association.
</P>
<P>
   On affirmative action, Bush declined to serve up a clear stance
on whether race, ethnicity and gender should play a role in
decisions concerning college admissions and awarding of state
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am for is called affirmative access. For example, I
signed the law that said if you end up in the top 10 percent of
your class that you are automatically admitted to state
universities as part of affirmative access,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That program, approved by the 1997 Legislature, has yet to
produce the results envisioned by those who saw it as a way to
attract minority students after courts struck down affirmative
action policies that gave an edge to minority students.
</P>
<P>
   On state contracts, Bush said he is ``for policies that will
encourage small-business growth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm against is quotas. I'm against hard quotas, quotas
that basically delineate based upon whatever. However they
delineate, quotas, I think, vulcanize society,'' he said. ``So I
don't know how that fits into what everybody is saying, their
relative positions. But that's my position.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically if race, ethnicity or gender should be
factors in contract decisions, Bush replied: ``I support goals. I
think it is important to have goals. But the main goal is how do we
foster entrepreneurship. And how do we foster growth of small
business.''
</P>
<P>
   On current legislative efforts to increase penalties for hate
crimes: ``I've always said all crime is hate,'' he said,
discounting the possibility that some thief, somewhere, might be
driven by something else, perhaps hunger, greed or passion.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing hate crimes, Bush always notes that John William
King of Jasper, convicted in the dragging death of James Byrd Jr.,
was sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a more harsh penalty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But King was eligible for the death penalty only because
prosecutors were able to prove he was killed during a kidnapping.
Without that finding, the racial hatred motive would not have been
sufficient to bump the crime to capital level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll deal with the bills when they make it to my desk,'' he
said. ``This is what happens during every legislative session.
Halfway through I'm asked to make comments on hypotheticals. Let's
see what the bills look like when they make it to my desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if criminal penalties should be enhanced if hate toward a
specific group is the motive, Bush said, ``How do you determine
hate? That's what someone needs to explain to me, not in a press
conference.''
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Bush declined to say he would use the issue as a
litmus test in making appointments to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a president's philosophy should be a key factor in
making appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy was a driving variable when I made the decision
on the four (Texas) Supreme Court judges I named,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean he would appoint only anti-abortion rights
justices to the U.S. Supreme Court?
</P>
<P>
   ``My criterion is going to be as to whether or not people will
use the bench to interpret the Constitution or write the laws,'' he
said. ``I believe in strict constructionism when it comes to the
Constitution of the United States and for the federal bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he appoint a judge who, perhaps in a previous life as a
politician, had taken a position on abortion not totally consistent
with his?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't decided if I'm running for president of the United
States yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He may or may not have, but groups involved in the abortion
fight have declared him in the race and fair game. Though Bush
believes his position is perfectly clear, it has drawn criticism
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes abortion should be illegal except in cases
involving rape, incest or the life of the mother. But he sees
little chance of making that the law of the land anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The National Right to Life Committee, a leading anti-abortion
rights organization, has decided Bush's position entitles him to
the ``pro-life'' label he hangs on himself.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Life League, another anti-abortion rights group
based in Washington, said Bush ``abdicated his right to be
described as a pro-life'' because ``he apparently does not see the
child at fertilization as a member of the human family who deserves
total protection under the law and within the context of our social
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   From the other side, Bush is taking on-air shots this week from
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL Director Kate Michelman said her group will run TV ads in
Iowa and New Hampshire to show that Bush and Elizabeth Dole oppose
``a woman's right to choose . . . . but they both know they must
communicate more moderate views in order to be elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bush, ``I don't expect to get everybody's vote should I
decide to run for president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: kherman(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
