<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-LOBBYISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL EXECUTIVES WORK THE ROOM AT OPEC MEETING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ The Libyan oil minister's senior bodyguard
kept a stern vigil outside his boss' 12th-floor suite at the Hotel
Intercontinental on Monday, but not to protect him from terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, his mission was to ensure the privacy of meetings among
the minister, Abdallah Salim al-Badri, and American oil executives
who were discreetly slipping in and out. The Americans did not want
to attract attention that could be picked up in Washington, where
contacts with Libya are officially discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Such clandestine meetings are not uncommon surrounding important
meetings of the 11-member Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, such as the one that begins on Tuesday. Scores of oil
company executives and industry analysts are drawn to Vienna,
OPEC's headquarters, hoping for an audience with an oil minister.
</P>
<P>
   This is a city famed for its discretion, secret banking and
effective security, a place where American oil executives can see
Libyans, Iranians and Iraqis without stirring the ire of Washington
for skirting sanctions imposed on those countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else are you going to see all these people gathered in
one place where you can further your commercial goals, don't have
to worry about traveling to difficult places like Libya, Iraq or
Iran and do it discreetly?'' asked Nordine Ait-Laoussine, Algeria's
former oil minister, now a prominent consultant who brokers such
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the time and trouble may be worth the effort. There
is hope here that the protracted decline of oil prices is coming to
an end. OPEC is on the verge of cutting its production deeply to
push up prices. The worst of the Asian crisis appears to be over,
which could stimulate demand for oil.
</P>
<P>
   There are other, politically sensitive reasons for American oil
industry emissaries to take a particular interest in this gathering
_ changes among three renegade members that suggest doing business
with them may soon be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq already is selling oil again under U.N. guidelines. U.S.
relations with Iran have shown signs of a thaw. And there is even a
crack in the ice with Libya, which made overtures last week to ease
its isolation by agreeing to relinquish suspects wanted for trial
in the bombing of Pan Am flight 103 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has got to keep the contact with these huge oil
producers when these sanctions come off. The Americans don't know
why they are doing what they've done and how to undo it,'' said
Oscar Whyatt, former chairman of the Coastal Corp., a large U.S.
energy company. Whyatt is known for his contacts with some of the
world's most frowned-upon oil producers, including a famous visit
in 1990 with Iraq's Saddam Hussein to persuade him to release
hostages then held by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot come out of this world without any friends,'' Whyatt
said Monday as two assistants waited to accompany him to a
minister's rendezvous. He would not say whom he had met, but others
said he saw both the Libyan and Iraqi oil ministers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official from Chevron Corp., fresh out of talks with
Iraqi oil officials, confirmed the notion of talks now, business
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the United Nations and American sanctions, we can
talk. We don't sign on any deals, but we can talk,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are signing deals with Iraq, so are the French,''
he added. ``We are behind. We should be ready, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraqi oil already makes its way to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Although Iraqis have refrained from selling oil directly to U.S.
companies to make a political point, they sell their oil for food
to the French and Russians, who make a profit by reselling it to
U.S. companies. Robin D'Alessandro, an oil trader with Vitol, a
large international commodities firm, said she bought Iraqi oil
through Russian intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   American oil industry representatives are not the only outsiders
who come to the such OPEC meetings. It is also important for oil
industry analysts like Gary Ross to be here. He is president of a
New York-based consulting firm, Petroleum Industry Research
Associates, and he sells advice to oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   As he came over Monday afternoon to shake hands with Prince
Salman, the deputy oil minister of Saudi Arabia in the lobby of the
ANA hotel, Ross was mindful of the importance of such connections.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting usually follows such handshakes and the knowledge
acquired in that meeting translates into money and retainers. Asked
if it was worth traveling from New York for this, Ross himself
asked: ``What do you think?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
