u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIG-BAND-COX     03-22 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-BAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Band Hall of Fame swings open
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With the sun ablaze in the sky and
Sinatra resounding in the air, Sally Bennett's 32-year quest to
establish a home for the Big Band Hall of Fame came to a happy
conclusion Monday afternoon: South Florida's newest museum opened
its doors to the delight of hundreds of swing-loving well-wishers.
</P>
<P>
   The museum occupies the first floor of a historic downtown
building where Palm Beach Community College began offering classes
in 1933. Thanks to a $1.9 million renovation, paid for by the
college, it's now home to such priceless bits of memorabilia as
Harry James' trumpet, Buddy Rich's snare drum, and Count Basie's
cap. To say nothing of a mirrored ball that once hung in Chicago's
famed Aragon Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel vindicated,'' said Bennett, who started the
organization in Cleveland in 1967, then moved it to Palm Beach
County in 1981. ``A lot of people didn't believe I had all these
artifacts.''
</P>
<P>
   By Bennett's own admission, the museum is small in scope:
Through photos, sheet music and assorted mementos, panels outline
the skeletal history of the big-band era, from the music's early
connections to jazz to the emergence of ``sweet'' bands to the
final heyday with the arrival of television. Other displays honor
the dozens of hall inductees.
</P>
<P>
   There's also ample space given to Bennett's efforts to establish
the hall as well as a wall of fame featuring a portrait of Bennett
and photos of her with big-band legends.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett makes no apologies for what's there, save for noting the
fact that the exhibits still need to be better labeled and a
``listening station,'' featuring more than 500 recordings, is
awaiting installation. Instead, she sees the museum as something to
build on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I established the concept,'' Bennett said. ``The Country Music
Hall of Fame started out in a room no bigger than a chicken coop.''
</P>
<P>
   Those on hand seemed thrilled to have a chance to remember the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a terrific boot out of the thing,'' said Palm
Beach resident Philip Kamler, a tenor saxophonist turned bicycle
manufacturing executive. Now retired, he recalls the days when he
played ``with lots of bands'' in New York, making the union minimum
of $8 a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to these guys playing rock music today. All they are
is a bunch of Johnny One-Notes,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting the low-key nature of the museum, Monday's ceremony
was a study in simplicity. A few congratulatory telegrams _ from
Bob Hope, Steve Allen and Jupiter Island resident Perry Como _ were
read. A few brief speeches were given. And then Bennett cut a big
red ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was music as well. A trio dubbed the Swing
Sisters sang a couple of Andrew Sisters favorites. And baritone Bob
Hoose crooned some Sinatra classics _ and added a thought of his
own between songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's neat is Ohio has the Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame, and now West Palm Beach has the Big Band Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
