r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUGRATS-MOVIE-LADN     03-22 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUGRATS-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS OF `RUGRATS' COULD BE BEGINNING OF RICH FRANCHISE FOR
NICKELODEON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ ``Rugrats: The Movie'' has became the first
non-Disney animated movie to take in $100 million in domestic
ticket receipts, becoming the 13th member of an elite and extremely
profitable club.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount, which released the $25 million Klasky/Csupo
production in November, announced Monday that ``Rugrats'' had
grossed $328,545 at 403 theaters over the weekend to go past $100.1
million after 122 days in release. What it means is the 8-year-old
Nickelodeon cable show has established itself as an ongoing
money-maker for parent Viacom Inc. through sequels, toys, videos
and theatrical productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its tremendous performance at the box office has launched a
new movie franchise which thoroughly complements the highly
successful Nickelodeon TV series,'' said Paramount distribution
chief Wayne Lewellen.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the cable show draws 24 million viewers weekly, the
movie's prospects were uncertain because the style represented a
departure from classic Disney animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very gratified that there's acceptance for alternative
animation,'' said Albie Hecht, president of Nickelodeon Film and TV
Entertainment. ``We've taken a very contemporary approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugrats'' begins its foreign roll-out this week. ``I'm bullish
about overseas because it's a very universal movie,'' Hecht said.
``The Rugrats already speak 17 languages on the TV shows. Everyone
sees themselves in the Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rugrats'' is the most successful of challenges to Disney's
status as king of animation, where each domestic box office dollar
represents as much as $4 of profit once the ancillary products are
factored in. Just in the last half-year, DreamWorks' ``Antz'' and
``Prince of Egypt'' have generated combined grosses of close to
$190 million, but Warner Bros. stumbled with ``The King and I,''
taking only $4 million on its opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon is at work on a pair of animated projects _ a
``Rugrats'' sequel expected to be released November 2000 and the
fantasy-adventure ``Bone,'' due in 2001. It employs more than 300
animators working at its Nickelodeon animation studio in Burbank on
five TV series and movie projects.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom Chairman Sumner Redstone, in a speech to Wall Street
analysts last month, stressed the value of the Nickelodeon brand
and pledged the division would release one animated movie per year
starting in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge for us because we don't really have a house
style so we re-invent ourselves every time out,'' Hecht said.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom investor Marvin Roffman, principal of Roffman Miller
Associates of Philadelphia, endorsed the commitment to animation.
``There's tremendous potential to create a franchise that
translates all over the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Disney has high hopes for its animated ``Tarzan,''
due June 18. Its last project, ``A Bug's Life,'' performed in line
with expectations with U.S. grosses near $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
