<SLUG> BC-RODMAN-CONVERSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERSE TELLS RODMAN HE'S OUT OF THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Converse Inc. has told Dennis Rodman the buzzer has sounded.
Their game is over.
</P>
<P>
   After a continuing series of untoward events involving the
forward for the National Basketball Association's Los Angeles
Lakers, the North Reading, Mass., company has quietly ended his $15
million endorsement deal.
</P>
<P>
   Converse informed Rodman last week that it is exercising an exit
clause built into his contract about a year before it expires,
according to sources within the company and others close to Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said Rodman, who believes Converse still owes him
about $3 million, has vowed to fight the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was to use Rodman's obvious visibility to
increase the numbers in the basketball shoe area _ where sales are
flat industry-wide _ to try to solidify the core business while
expanding into fashion and performance sneakers,'' said Gregg
Hartly, executive director of the Sporting Goods Manufacturing
Association. ``It didn't work. Dennis was always in the spotlight
more for his personality problems than what he did on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Converse lagged behind its major competitors Adidas,
Nike, and Reebok in market share and in marketing punch, with no
marquee basketball player to endorse its shoes. When it began the
year by announcing it had lured Rodman away from Nike _ Technicolor
hair, tattoos, body piercing, unpredictable personality and all _
Converse engendered widespread criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Just before signing with Converse, Rodman had kicked a
photographer during a nationally broadcast game. The NBA suspended
him for the attack; Eastman Kodak and Carl Jr.'s, a West Coast
hamburger chain, pulled television ads featuring him.
</P>
<P>
   After the signing, senior vice president of marketing James E.
Solomon sought to deflect the cameraman-kicking incident by
describing Rodman as ``an inherently good individual who has a
strong competitive spirit and a good work ethic.'' But Monday
Solomon was said to be in a meeting, and he did not return
telephone calls. That left Kellie A. Buckley, senior public
relations manager, to face the questions. ``I'm not in a position
to shed any light on this,'' Buckley said.
</P>
<P>
   During a national broadcast Sunday, NBC's courtside reporter,
Jim Gray, said Converse ``terminated that contract due to breach of
contract involving terms of behavior, number of games played, and
not having a deal in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketing experts wondered from the beginning whether Rodman's
unpredictability would hurt Converse more than not having a major
NBA endorser. Then, on July 15, 1997, just seven months into the
deal, Converse's shares fell 5.9 percent in heavy trading.
Investors were said to be concerned that the demand for Rodman's
shoe, the All-Star '99, was more than 10 percent lower than the
company and industry observers had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The company's numbers have worsened. Converse _ the pioneer in
basketball sneakers with its trademark hightops, the Chuck Taylor
All Star _ dropped from fifth in market share in the United States
in 1997 to seventh last year. This month, Converse reported
revenues declined by 31.5 percent from $450.2 million in 1997 to
$308.4 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales of Rodman's shoes were never what they wanted, and
the fact is now that very few athletes are doing anything these
days to sell shoes _ let alone Dennis Rodman,'' said Bob Williams,
president of Burns Sports Celebrity Service in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Converse closed at 3 3/8, down 1/8. In the last year, it
has lost more than half its value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
