<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0190 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWYORK-POLICE-BOS &LR;      03-22 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWYORK-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON'S STATURE ENHANCED IN RESPONSE TO POLICE SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was ``Lawyers Day'' Monday, with about 70 lawyers
and an equal number of publishers, officials, and ordinary folks _
lined up outside New York Police Department headquarters to get
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Ossie Davis and Ruby Dee are slated to get cuffed
Tuesday. Wednesday is ``Labor Leaders Day,'' with Dennis Rivera and
a caravan of his hospital-union workers waiting to commit civil
disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   The daily procession is the handiwork of the Reverend Al
Sharpton, whose racial protests of the past have stirred much
controversy. But this time, his cause is so lauded, his tactics
have been so skillful, and his opponents have reacted so
gracelessly, that Sharpton stands on the verge of fulfilling his
longstanding dream _ to become the preeminent black leader of New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the protest is the Feb. 4 killing of Amadou Diallo,
an unarmed African immigrant who was shot 41 times by four police
officers while standing on the porch of his own apartment house in
the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The officers said afterward they thought Diallo had a gun, but
the excess of their action has touched off protests against police
abuse generally, especially in minority neighborhoods, where
officers _ many of them white and from the suburbs _ routinely
frisk anyone engaged in ``suspicious'' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a grand jury investigating the incident, three
separate probes have been launched _ by Attorney General Janet
Reno, US Attorney Mary Jo White, and New York State Attorney
General Elliot Spitzer _ into whether the department's practices
betray a pattern of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The probes seem to have broadened the appeal of Sharpton's
protests.
</P>
<P>
   At least two-thirds of the lawyers arrested here Monday were
white _ the first time in 10 days of protests when white people
have numbered more than a handful.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jewish groups _ long wary of Sharpton, suspecting him or
his followers of anti-Semitism _ are joining in. The conservative
American Jewish Committee last week echoed Sharpton's call for more
diversity in the police force and ``zero tolerance for police
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The more liberal Jews for Racial and Economic Justice is urging
its 900 members to join Sharpton's protest Wednesday. Its director,
Cindy Greenberg, expects 40 or 50 Jews to show up and get arrested,
including a dozen rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected we'd work with Al Sharpton,'' Greenberg said
Monday, ``but he's shown great leadership on this issue. We've been
exceedingly impressed. I suspect we might form coalitions on other
issues in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, asked Monday how much longer he can sustain these
demonstrations, replied, ``As long as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has accused the protest organizers of
having purely political motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about the police,'' one aide said Monday. ``It's
more about Rudy the Republican governing the city better than his
predecessors ever wished they could have _ and they're angry about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   City Hall is especially galled that Giuliani's predecessor,
David Dinkins, had himself arrested last week _ since there were
nearly twice as many police shootings under his regime (212 in 1993
compared with 111 last year), and far more incidents of violent
crime.
</P>
<P>
   However, even some of Giuliani's supporters say the mayor could
have done more to contain the political outrage over the Diallo
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Days passed before Giuliani expressed much more than ``regret''
over the shooting. Police commissioner Howard Safir even went off
to a conference in Los Angeles shortly after the shooting _ which
Giuliani said he approved, since there was ``no crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir worsened perceptions this past weekend by going back to
Los Angeles, on the eve of City Council hearings on police
brutality, to attend the Academy Awards _ though he did show up at
the 9 a.m. hearing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Giuliani has denounced the protests as ``silly'' and
a ``publicity stunt'' _ which has only strengthened the protesters'
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have done so many little things to look better on
this,'' one business leader, who generally supports Giuliani, said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides insist the mayor did plenty. He postponed a
political trip to Texas. He worked with the State Department to
bring Diallo's parents from overseas, tried to meet with them when
they finally arrived, waited an hour for them in their hotel lobby,
but was turned away _ probably, City Hall suspects, at Sharpton's
urging.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton denies having anything to do with their spurning.
However, it is clear that, unlike last year's police horror _ when
the mayor promptly condemned the police torture of Haitian
immigrant Abner Louima _ Giuliani's initial inaction on Diallo
allowed Sharpton to step in and control the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, Sharpton tapped into his network of activists and
loyalists. A few thousand people attended rallies outside Diallo's
apartment, on Wall Street, at the US courthouse plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the brilliant, sustainable stroke, inspired by
civil-rights movements going back to Martin Luther King and beyond
_ the sit-in. Anyone who had ever been harassed by police or who
simply held a grudge against Giuliani _ and the numbers of both
groups are legion _ could play an active role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hardly had to call anybody to come out here,'' Sharpton
said. ``Everybody's been calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike the '60s sit-ins in the South, late-'90s protesters
in New York don't have to worry about getting their heads bashed
in.
</P>
<P>
   Civil disobedience here is professionalized, on both sides of
the stand-off. Every day, at 11:30 a.m., those who want to be
arrested line up at One Police Plaza and walk through a corridor
that officers have created with barricades. They sit down at the
building's entrance, chanting slogans (``No justice, no peace'')
and singing songs (``We shall overcome''). An officer tells them
they are violating the law and orders them to move. A few other
officers lock their hands in plastic cuffs, and lead them into the
building. They are transported to a precinct a few blocks away,
booked, given a summons to appear in court, and released.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's aides even collect the protesters' names and give
them to the police ahead of time, to expedite the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, so many people wanted to be arrested, they had to be
divided into two waves. Meanwhile, 200 others marched in a circle
toward the rear of the plaza. At 12:45, Sharpton made a speech,
announced which prominent people will be marching the next few
days, told everybody to disband peacefully, and the demonstration
broke up.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said the protests will continue until the four officers
who shot Diallo are arrested. The grand jury is expected to hand
down indictments in a week or so. The officers have not yet
testified, and their lawyers are encouraging them not to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
