<HEADER>
A0191 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-2TAKES-     03-22 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: AMERICAN ENVOY HAS LITTLE MANEUVERING ROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (See KOSOVO, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-RDP)  
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of all the times that Richard Holbrooke, the
Clinton administration's envoy, has negotiated with the Yugoslav
leader, Slobodan Milosevic, the room for maneuvering has probably
never been so restricted and the options so unpalatable.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after President Clinton announced that Milosevic had
gone over ``the threshold,'' Holbrooke was negotiating to avert
NATO air strikes that Washington finds itself on the point of
ordering, but which administration officials acknowledge is not
their favored option.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Serbian forces march across Kosovo, torching
villages, sending refugees fleeing and bringing retaliation from
the guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, Holbrooke has made it
plain that he cannot remain in Belgrade very long.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said on Monday that they had set a
rough deadline of 24 hours for Holbrooke to get a cease-fire or
stop negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   It was too embarrassing, they suggested, for Holbrooke to be
talking to Milosevic while his forces were battering ethnic
Albanian civilians, actions that the threatened air strikes are
supposed to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if Holbrooke got an immediate cease-fire from Milosevic,
he then had to pretty much restrict his talks to the terms of a
settlement calling for the deployment of 28,000 NATO peacekeepers
in Kosovo. The settlement has already been signed by the ethnic
Albanians in Paris. Holbrooke said he try to persuade Milosevic
again that the agreement would benefit the Serbs because it called
for the disarmament of the ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has surprised Washington with his
tougher-than-expected resistance to NATO troops on Serbian soil. At
talks on Monday morning at NATO headquarters, Holbrooke suggested
there might be a chance to give Milosevic a face-saving device by
calling the troops something else but still retaining NATO control,
said a NATO diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000 American troops the administration pledged for
peacekeeping could only participate if they were in a NATO force
with NATO commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Third, if Holbrooke failed to get a cease-fire, the Clinton
administration would be faced with going ahead with NATO air
strikes against Serbia, perhaps as soon as 24 hours after the
envoy's departure from Belgrade, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the event that Holbrooke leaves Belgrade without an
agreement, he would go first to NATO headquarters in Brussels,
where the secretary general of NATO, Javier Solana, has the
authority to tell NATO commanders to go ahead with air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement on Monday, Clinton said NATO's plans would
continue to move forward. On the eve of a visit to Washington by
Yevgeny Primakov, the Russian prime minister, Clinton also said he
had sent a letter to President Boris Yeltsin ``about the urgency of
the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have indicated that they would not mind
if Primakov postponed his visit because of the threatened NATO
strikes, which Russia opposes.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, because of the dramatic surge in Serbian military
action, the administration finds itself confronted with the choice
of air strikes sooner than it anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton said that the Serbs had reached a threshold
of violence that was unacceptable, but he left vague the timing, or
even if, air strikes would be used. It was reasonable,
administration officials argued, after Clinton's statement to send
an emissary to Belgrade to present the peace settlement personally
to Milosevic and urge him one last time to sign on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Saturday, 1,400 international monitors, put in place
by an agreement Holbrooke reached with Milosevic last October that
has long since fallen apart, were withdrawn from Kosovo, giving
what turned out to be the opportunity for Milosevic's forces to
strike more forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were aware that Milosevic
might take advantage of the vacuum left by the unarmed monitors,
but asserted that the safe departure of the monitors was the
uppermost consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors' usefulness had been reduced by threats from
Serbian forces, the officials said. Because the monitors were
unarmed the danger to them had increased dramatically, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the monitoring mission, American Ambassador William
Walker, reluctantly recommended their withdrawal to Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on Thursday, for safety reasons. The
secretary agreed with him, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright then called the Norwegian foreign minister, Knut
Vollebaek, who as chairman of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, had the authority to make the decision. The
organization, a 54-nation group based in Vienna, served as
overseers of the monitors.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Serb soldiers virtually applauded as the monitors left Kosovo
Saturday morning, easing their exit so much that it took only six
hours instead of eight hours for the convoy of cars to make their
way over the Kosovo border and into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   This was the signal, some officials said, that Milosevic was
going to carry out his often voiced threat to start an offensive
that he bragged could finish the Kosovo Liberation Army in five to
seven days.
</P>
<P>
   As the administration finds itself getting closer to air
strikes, it also finds itself having to explain more clearly the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has invited the top congressional Republicans and
Democrats to the White House on Tuesday morning to overcome
mounting skepticism about the wisdom of an air campaign against a
sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, the administration has said that the purpose of the
air strikes would be to ``degrade'' the capability of the Serb
forces. The primary targets of the air campaign would be Serbian
fixed military installations in Serbia and Kosovo, a province of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   By concentrating on such military targets, the likelihood of
hitting ethnic Albanian civilians, who make up more than 90 percent
of the population in Kosovo, or Serbian civilians, would be
minimized, military experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, administration policy makers acknowledge that bombing
is ``not a good option,'' as one expressed it on Monday. ``It
creates all kinds of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Air strikes against Serbian forces would embolden the Kosovo
Liberation Army, a guerrilla group that has been fighting for the
past year for the independence of the province.
</P>
<P>
   By strengthening the guerrillas, the bombing would also
strengthen the clamor within Kosovo for independence. Thus, very
quickly, Kosovo could change from being the autonomous region
envisioned in the Paris peace agreement to a quasi-independent
statelet, on the border of Albania and Macedonia where restive
Albanian populations would be eager to redraw their borders.
</P>
<P>
   A central tenet of the administration's Kosovo policy has been
that independence of Kosovo is unacceptable. Kosovo should remain,
at least, for the next three years, an autonomous part of Serbia
and not set a precedent for breakaway ethnic groups in Europe, the
administration has argued.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2120EST &QL; 
