<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-BOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA FRENZY ALIVE AND WELL IN LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The face, the hair, the way she thanked him for
his interest, every facet of Monica Lewinsky made Mark Carpowich's
hands tremble Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Just seeing her up close was worth the wait, he said. And the
Ph.D. candidate in political science had waited more than eight
hours, since 5:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Carpowich, 25, was first in line at Lewinsky's book signing in
the Century City shopping maze, an event touted as the only US stop
on a book tour that has otherwise kept her overseas. Behind him the
line snaked past Brentano's bookstore, into the parking lot, onto
the sidewalk and around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Academy Awards, it seemed that all of L.A.
wanted a brush with celebrity of a different sort, although more
than a few book buyers had plans to give their copies as gag gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' Carpowich gushed
before meeting his crush. ``This isn't a regular celebrity type of
thing. I mean I wouldn't show up for Cindy Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, his voice shaky, he added, ``She was really nice. She
shook my hand. She is so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, Lewinsky was expected to scrawl her name in blue
marker almost 1,500 times, the number of copies of ``Monica's
Story'' that Brentano's bookstore reported selling before she
arrived, fashionably late. That extra 45 minutes in line had the
crowd grumbling that she had probably stayed out too late at
``Vanity Fair'' magazine's post-Oscar party.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, wearing a dark blazer over a pale blue top and with
her hair returned to its natural pouf, described the experience of
mixing with so many movie stars as ``bizarre. It was really
surreal.'' Asked whether it was a relief to have the nation's eyes
turned to other newsmakers for a change, she said ``It was
different,'' then smiled, signed the book in front of her and said,
``Thank you for coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, her fans _ some of them sitting in lawn chairs,
others sprawled on the grass, all of them jealously guarding their
spots in line _ described Lewinsky as gracious. Homemaker after
filmmaker, sales clerk after insurance executive also called her
``a part of history'' whose story they could afford for a
discounted $21.25, including tax. Lin Smith, 32, who works in movie
transportation, described the signing as ``just like the one for
Cher or Fergie, you know Sarah Ferguson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all these people who are curing all these diseases and
Monica Lewinsky is the one who is going to be remembered,'' said
Kristen Wilcox, a 29-year-old student who left her home in Irvine
at 6:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Added Liberty Leigh, 39, who manages another bookstore, ``I
wanted to meet her and thank her and give her some support, to say,
`Hang in there.' She has shown strength and courage and she still
walks among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone in line liked Lewinsky. Sir James Brown,
a 22-year-old sales clerk who was second in line, summed up the
attitude of many when he said, ``It was just too weird. How could
you not be here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole story's a joke, so I'm giving them as jokes,'' said
Linda Charlan, 40, a Beverly Hills homemaker who had made friends
with the people around her after six hours in line. ``I'm getting
cigars to go along with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hahn, a 28 year old from Hollywood who wants to make
movies, got in line at 10:45 a.m. for Lewinsky's scheduled 12:30
p.m. appearance. The reason: ``I forgot my mom's birthday and want
to make it up to her with something unique.'' To kill time, Hahn
perused ``Terror in 1012,'' the chapter describing how
representatives of independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr questioned
Lewinsky when they first approached her about her relationship with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wehrman, who deals in autographs and other memorabilia,
said he is counting on continued interest in Monica Lewinsky and,
by extension, the story she told to British author Andrew Morton.
Every time he moved forward, he had to nudge along the five boxes
of books he came from New York to buy and have signed. As a crowd
formed to watch the crowd, he said he intends to hawk them on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say this is the only book signing in the US so they're
going to be worth something,'' said Wehrman, 32, who paid $900 for
50 copies. ``She's going to be really scarce. I think $800 apiece
is a reasonable figure. I've already had an offer for $1,200.''
</P>
<P>
   With huge initial buildup, and a star turn with ABC's Barbara
Walters, ``Monica's Story'' has sold about 600,000 copies,
according to the publisher, St. Martin's Press, although it has
slipped from the top spot to No.3 on the New York Times best-seller
list. But her publisher insisted that Lewinsky will not attempt to
boost sales by signing books again in her hometown or anywhere else
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a piece of history, just like Marilyn Monroe and John
Kennedy,'' said Manuel Ybarra, 52, who works on an oil rig off Long
Beach when he isn't in line getting books signed by Cher, Dolly
Parton or Monica Lewinsky. ``I had to be here and, from the looks
of it, so did a lot of other people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
