<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      03-22 0270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Tuesday, March
23, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet on the Post-Intelligencer's National/Foreign Desk at (206)
448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SHALIKAShVILI (Undated) _ NATO has the ability to destroy
much of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's military
infrastructure, but had better be prepared to suffer some
casualities in the process, says Gen. John Shalikashvili, retired
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. Shalikashvili, President
Clinton's principal military adviser for four years until his
retirement in 1997, also warned in an interview that Yugoslavia has
had the opportunity to study U.S. and allied military tactics
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Redmond. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSIONARY-SLAIN (Undated) _ Deena Umbarger trained to be a
lawyer, but the Washington state native stumbled into social work
while trying to decide what she wanted to do with her life. She
fell in love with the new line of work and it was a love affair
that cost her her life. Umbarger was gunned down on the
Somali-Kenya border last weekend in what authorities say was a
random shooting.
</P>
<P>
   By Jack Hopkins. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
