<SLUG> BC-COMCAST-MEDIAONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE GIANT COMCAST TO ACQUIRE MEDIAONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comcast Corp. Monday said it will acquire New England's largest
cable television operator, MediaOne Group Inc., combining the
nation's third- and fourth-largest cable companies into a media
giant that can compete against the likes of AT&AMP;T Corp. and Time
Warner Inc. in offering television and telephone service and
high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The $55.5 billion deal is the industry's second-biggest merger
ever, slightly smaller than AT&AMP;T's recently completed acquisition
of Tele-Communications Inc. for $59.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The new Comcast will have 11 million subscribers in 33 states,
trailing only Time Warner's 12.6 million customers and AT&AMP;T's 12.5
million. In taking over Englewood, Colo.-based MediaOne's
Massachusetts operations, Comcast will become the largest cable
company in the state, with 1.1 million customers. Massachusetts
will become the company's single biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scale is critical, as we are at a point in this industry where
very important public policies are going to be settled as important
technology choices are being made,'' said Charles M. Lillis,
MediaOne's chief executive. ``The new Comcast can be the global
broadband leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast officials said they expect to save as much as $575
million annually by consolidating headquarters and reducing the
combined operation's 34,000-person work force by less than 5
percent. But because Comcast has no operations in Massachusetts, a
spokesman at MediaOne's local operations, based in Chelmsford, said
no layoffs were planned locally and that there are no immediate
plans to alter cable operations or rates.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been a flurry of deals in the
telecommunications industry as companies have sought to build clout
and customers to offer an expanding number of communications
services, the deal came as something of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was speculation in recent months that MediaOne was in
play to be acquired, but I don't think anyone thought it was
imminent,'' said Douglas S. Shapiro, cable analyst at Deutsche Bank
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Shapiro said, the merger is a good one for both
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comcast with MediaOne are clearly now one of the premier cable
players with a very strong balance sheet to do other cable
investments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies generated $8 billion in sales last year,
earning $2.4 billion before interest, taxes, depreciation, and
amortization.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have been growing incrementally. MediaOne has
added 200,000 Massachusetts customers from Time Warner while
Comcast recently added Greater Philadelphia Cablevisions's 79,000
customers and is acquiring controlling interest in several other
cable operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the trading and dealing has changed the whole cable
industry,'' said Bruce Leichtman, director of the Yankee Group's
media and entertainment strategies. ``There are no middle players.
The consolidation is creating three very large companies in
AT&AMP;T-TCI, Time Warner, and now Comcast with MediaOne.''
</P>
<P>
   The big three are also part owners of each other's businesses,
along with a hodgepodge of other assets. Comcast, for example, is
the primary owner of the QVC home shopping network and the E!
Entertainment Television network. It also is a major partner of a
joint venture that owns the Philadelphia 76ers basketball team and
the Philadelphia Flyers hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne Group, which was created with the acquisition of
Boston-based Continental Cablevision in 1996 by US West Inc., was
spun out from the regional telephone company last June. It owns a
25 percent stake in Time Warner's cable business, 30 percent of
Telewest Communications PLC, the United Kingdom's number two cable
company, and a 50 percent stake in New England Cable News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this combination is very positive,'' said Philip
Balboni, president and founder of New England Cable News. Balboni
said Comcast has about 200,000 cable subscribers in southern
Connecticut who do not have access to NECN now.
</P>
<P>
   Under the merger agreement, MediaOne shareholders will receive
1.1 shares of Comcast stock for each share they hold. The swap is
valued at $80.16 a share, a 17 percent premium over Monday's
MediaOne closing price of 68 1/2. The stock rose 7 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast shares fell 5 3/8 Monday to close at 64 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   When the merger is completed, MediaOne stockholders will have a
controlling interest in the combined companies, owning 64 percent
of the equity.
</P>
<P>
   However, Comcast's top management will retain voting control of
the combined companies through separate Class B voting shares.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia-based Comcast is headed by Ralph J. Roberts, who
will remain chairman of the combined company with his son Brian as
president. Lillis, MediaOne's chairman, will become vice chairman
of the combined companies and serve on the Comcast board.
</P>
<P>
   To further ensure the acquisition gets completed, MediaOne is
barred from seeking other offers. However, if it receives and
accepts a higher offer, MediaOne must pay Comcast a $1.5 billion
termination fee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
