<SLUG> BC-MISSIONARY-SLAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE AFFAIR WITH HER JOB COST RELIEF WORKER HER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUMNER, Wash. _ Deena Umbarger never planned on a career in
social work that would take her to far-off and sometimes dangerous
places.
</P>
<P>
   But the 35-year-old relief worker was shot to death Saturday as
she sat at a tea house near the spot where the border between Kenya
and Somalia meets the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Sumner High School and the University of
Washington, Umbarger had a legal career in mind. She obtained a law
degree from Yale, which pretty much assured her of success in that
profession.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger quickly became disenchanted with the law while
traveling from one end of the country to the other, helping set up
health maintenance organizations and other medical groups. She
decided to try something else.
</P>
<P>
   While still making up her mind on what she wanted to do, a
friend from Seattle suggested she find temporary employment with
the United Methodist Committee on Relief, the disaster relief arm
of the United Methodist Board of Global Ministries. That's where
the friend worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A job is a job,'' Maryann Workman, the slain relief worker's
mother, said Monday at the family home in Sumner. ``She took that
job until she had time to decide what she wanted to do. And she
fell in love with the work.''
</P>
<P>
   That was back in 1997. The love affair with her job was to cost
Umbarger her life.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger was shot to death while having tea with town elders
from the tiny community of Kiumigio on the border of Kenya and
Somalia. A lone gunman broke into the meeting and opened fire on
the participants.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the shooting is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger had worked for the United Methodist Committee on Relief
only about three months when she asked for an overseas assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The agency initially sent her to Kenya, but later transferred
her to the Republic of Georgia, a part of the former Soviet Union.
She had been a project manager in Kenya and was finance officer for
the agency in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger asked her agency, which feeds refugees and has peace
and reconciliation programs in Kenya, to send her back to that
African nation. ``She loved Africa,'' her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger knew she was going back to a politically unsettled area
and had some concerns about her safety, Workman said. But Umbarger
thought she would be safe in Kenya, where she had an apartment in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kenya there is not too much fear for safety,'' her mother
said. ``But when you get to Somalia, everyone is packing guns and
it is scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Somalia has been a site of armed conflict for more than a decade
and arms pass back and forth over the border area frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger was helping develop agricultural projects for the area
when she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Methodist relief officials said they are still awaiting more
details of Umbarger's death from the U.S. State Department in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports of the killing were sketchy and contradictory.
There was even a dispute over the location.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan police told the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi that Umbarger was
shot on the Somali side of the border and taken to a medical clinic
in Kiunga, just south of the border, where she was pronounced dead,
embassy spokesman Chris Scharf said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan police spokesman Dola Indidis, however, said police are
still investigating on which side of the border she was shot. There
have been no arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, she went into the area for meetings ... and
was attacked by a gunman who invaded the meeting. Someone unknown
just started shooting wildly,'' said Lesley Crosson, spokeswoman
for the Global Ministries board.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, workers at the Methodist relief agency, like
Umbarger's mother, are grieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deena's death is a tragedy,'' Dr. Randolph Nugent, chief
executive of the Global Ministries board, said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did she possess a brilliant mind, she also possessed
a deep passion for justice and a love for those who so desperately
need the kind of support provided through the outreach programs.
... We regret, very much, Deena's death.''
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger was a 1981 graduate of Sumner High School. She attended
the University of Texas initially, but transferred to the
University of Washington where she graduated magna cum laude with a
degree in psychology in 1990. She put herself through college by
working in the accounting department of Group Health Cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Umbarger graduated from Yale Law School in 1994 and accepted
employment with a Washington, D.C., law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Workman said she was surprised to see her daughter leave the
legal profession and go into relief work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to stop and think that the law degree opened
doors for her. Getting a law degree at Yale gives you more options
in life. And how lucky can you get when you love your work?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Workman will have to make arrangements to have Umbarger's pet
dog, Halley, brought back from Nairobi. The dog, a gift when she
graduated from law school, has traveled everywhere with Umbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her mother, survivors include her father, Dean Umbarger
of Cypress, Texas, and two sisters, Samantha Miller of Tacoma and
Leeann Handy of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from wire services.
</P>
</TEXT>
