<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON &LR;      03-22 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Rolling Over 401(k) Cash Into an IRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I contribute at work to a 401(k) plan that is invested
in fixed-income securities. I am thinking about leaving to join
another company, and I would like to take the money with me. I
don't plan to touch the money. I only want to roll it over into an
individual retirement account and invest it in stocks in hopes of
getting a better return. Am I allowed to do this, or must I leave
the money in the old plan until I retire?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says
there's no reason why you can't roll your 401(k) money over into an
IRA. In fact, you can put the money in your pocket if you prefer.
However, if you don't roll the money over, you must pay taxes on
the amount withdrawn. And if you are not yet 59-1/2 years old, you
also would have to pay a 10 percent penalty tax.
</P>
<P>
   You should tell your plan administrator what you intend to do.
If the administrator raises an objection, ask to see a copy of the
rules governing your plan. If the rules forbid you to take away
your 401(k) money after you leave, then the rules may be in
conflict with the law. Your next step would be to complain to the
U.S. Labor Department's office of pension and welfare benefits at
(202) 219-8776.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, however, you will be permitted to walk away with
your money when you quit, or soon after. It may be that the plan
administrator distributes pension money to departing employees only
on certain dates. If that is the case, and you have to wait a month
or two, just grin and bear it. No need to bring the Labor
Department into the act.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Dividend Mystery
</P>
<P>
   Q: I receive a substantial amount of my income from dividends
paid out by the various companies whose stock I hold. Why is it
that the stock price is reduced by the amount of the dividend
payout on the day the stock goes ``ex-dividend''? I asked this
question of a couple of stockbrokers, and they don't have a clue. I
would think that dividends are a form of profit-sharing _ meaning
that the dollars come from operating profits, not shareholder
equity. Having the stock price reduced on ex-dividend dates tells
me that I'm not really getting anything additional for my money,
just a reallocation of funds.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I can understand why you are confused, but the last
sentence of your question hits the nail on the head. The payment of
a dividend is indeed just a reallocation of funds _ from the
company treasury to you.
</P>
<P>
   You seem to imply that there is some authority figure out there
decreeing that the price must go down after a dividend is paid. In
fact, there is no official markdown. It is simply a case of the
market doing the logical thing. Prospective buyers automatically
will offer less for the stock the day after a dividend is
distributed because they won't get the dividend.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way:
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you agree to buy a dozen rubies from a jeweler at $500
apiece, or $6,000 for the lot. The jeweler gives you one ruby
today, and you pay him $500. Tomorrow, he will deliver the
remaining 11 rubies and ask for the balance. In effect, that lot of
rubies went ex-dividend by $500 today. Do you think you still
should pay the jeweler $6,000 tomorrow after paying $500 today?
</P>
<P>
   Getting Paid in Stock
</P>
<P>
   Q: The officials of a private startup company have asked me to
accept some of the company's stock as compensation for services
rendered. What are the tax implications if I accept? Do I have to
determine a theoretical value for the stock and report it as
taxable income? Or can I wait until there is an initial public
offering so that the value will be indisputable?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I'm afraid you can't wait. The moment you receive the
stock, it becomes taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   However, you shouldn't be forced to figure the value of the
stock yourself. The company must obtain an appraisal of the stock
it gave you so that it can report the amount to the IRS on Form
1099.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the appraisal will become your cost basis in case
you ever sell the stock. Keep your fingers crossed and pray that it
goes public soon, because IPO stocks these days have a delightful
tendency to climb very far, very fast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
