<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0199 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SFCHRON &LR;      03-22 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Airline Web Sites Take Off
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Confounding the experts, the nation's airlines have turned into the
800-pound gorillas of the Internet travel industry.
</P>
<P>
   Their share of online travel bookings soared from 20 percent in
1996 to 50 percent last year and is expected to exceed 60 percent
of the rapidly growing market three years from now.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, travel consultants were saying the
airlines could never dominate the online market. That's because
unlike online travel agencies, they have an obvious bias: They
limit their Web sites to their own flights.
</P>
<P>
   But one leading airline _ American _ has been making a big
splash with its own online travel agency, called Travelocity, which
offers complete schedules and bookings for all the airlines, not
just its own.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity _ at  &LR; www.travelocity.com  &LR; _ is running neck and
neck in volume with the biggest independent online agent,
Microsoft's MSN Expedia  &LR; (www.expedia.com).  &LR; They each are booking
$11 million worth of travel per week.
</P>
<P>
   American and other airlines also are luring hordes of customers
to their own Web sites by offering a selection of ultra-bargain
fares that aren't available anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   And they are providing other attractive inducements as well _
most notably, generous amounts of frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   The frequent-flier deals on the United Airlines Web site
 &LR; (www.ual.com)  &LR; won the allegiance of Jacqueline John, a photo
editor with Sunset magazine in Menlo Park, and her boyfriend, John
Cleary, who works for the California Institute of Technology in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They fly United whenever they visit each other on weekends _
``just because of the frequent-flier miles,'' Cleary says. In a
year and a half, they each have earned enough miles for &LR;   &LR; free
round-trip flights to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines would prefer that you book directly with them because
they don't want to pay commissions to travel agents, online or
offline.
</P>
<P>
   And they would rather have you book on their Web sites rather
than going through their telephone reservation clerks because that,
too, saves them money.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are in a penny-pinching mood because many of them
spent the early part of this decade losing money and flirting with
bankruptcy. Now that the industry is looking reasonably healthy
again, it is doing everything in its power to stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring this, Delta recently caused a storm of protests
from consumer groups by slapping a $1 surcharge on all flights not
booked online. However, none of the other airlines was willing to
go that far, and Delta quickly withdrew the surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have put the screws to the traditional, offline
travel agents in recent years, slashing the commissions for
agent-booked business from a flat 10 percent of the total fare to
either 8 percent or $50 per round-trip, whichever is less.
</P>
<P>
   They compensate the online travel agents even more stingily _ a
maximum commission of $10 per flight _ on the premise that those
agents don't need big commissions because their costs are low.
</P>
<P>
   Most conventional agents have responded to the squeeze by
charging their customers a $10 or $15 fee for each booking.
Customer fees used to be unheard of, but the agents feel they have
no choice if they want to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence of any meaningful customer resistance to
the service fees,'' said Paul Rudin, senior vice president for
legal and industry affairs with the American Society of Travel
Agents in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   That may be correct _ for now. Vasts hordes of travelers still
lean heavily on travel agents, if only out of habit.
</P>
<P>
   But as more households go online and as the savings from
Internet bookings attract more attention, there is bound to be
erosion in the market share held by traditional agents.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are being squeezed even harder than the
conventional agents, the online agencies haven't imposed fees on
their customers _ yet. They can't risk alienating customers while
they are still in a formative stage.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they remain mired in red ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not profitable yet,'' acknowledges Suzi LeVine, product
manager for MSN Expedia.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than charge fees, Expedia hopes to enhance its bottom
line by rustling up more advertising for its Web site, which
already is generously festooned. Its home page yesterday featured
ads from the Hyatt hotel chain, American Express and the Barnes &AMP;
Noble bookstore chain.
</P>
<P>
   Expedia also hopes to expand its bookings of hotel rooms and
rental cars and to diversify into vacation packages and cruises,
all of which command larger commissions than airline bookings.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of airline travelers still book their flights
through conventional travel agencies. It is a century-old tradition
that won't die easily.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, about $3.9 billion worth of travel business will
be booked via the Internet, according to Jupiter Communications, a
New York consulting firm that tracks online services.
</P>
<P>
   While that is only a 1.3 percent sliver of the $300 billion
worldwide travel industry, it amounts to nearly twice the Internet
total for 1998, notes Fiona Swerdlow, a Jupiter analyst.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, online travel bookings should be closing in on $12
billion annually, Swerdlow says, and the potential seems
practically unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has become the ATM of the travel industry,'' says
Mary Papenfuss, managing editor of Consumer Reports Travel Letter
in San Francisco. ``It's definitely a problem for travel agents.
It's definitely in the airlines' best interests to cut out the
middleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Dackman, director of public information at the
Exploratorium in San Francisco, recently discovered the advantages
of online flight booking when she tried to make reservations for a
vacation trip to Italy by phoning a couple of airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time on the phone, but I couldn't get days
and cities I wanted at a reasonable price,'' she complains.
</P>
<P>
   A friend tipped her off to Travelocity, and she logged onto the
Web site and followed the prompts, filling in her preferred dates
of departure and return.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds, she recalls, ``it came up with a fabulous
price'' _ a $668 round-trip Lufthansa fare. That was less than half
the lowest price she had been quoted over the phone by the airline
reservation clerks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0200 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-22 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Investor Relations Consultant Gets Booted From
National  Organization 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Lisa Herbst, the Silicon Valley investor relations consultant who
recently settled an insider trading case with the federal
government, has been ousted by the national organization that
oversees her profession.
</P>
<P>
   The board of directors of the National Investor Relations
Institute voted late last week to terminate Herbst's membership for
violating the organization's code of ethics, says NIRI chief
executive Louis Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were several parts of the code that we felt she was in
violation of, but one was enough,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   The NIRI board decided to terminate her membership after holding
a hearing for Herbst, where she testified via telephone. The
Pleasanton investor relations consultant presented her case and
attempted to defend her membership, which was jeopardized by the
insider trading allegations made by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1995 and 1998, Herbst allegedly used nonpublic
information to trade on clients Adobe Systems of San Jose, Asyst
Technologies of Fremont and Splash Technology Holdings of
Sunnyvale. As part of her settlement, Herbst agreed to return all
profits from her stock trades, with interest, and pay a penalty.
Her total fine was $32,799.
</P>
<P>
   During her NIRI hearing, Herbst refused to answer questions from
the board on the advice of her lawyers. As part of her February
settlement with the SEC, Herbst neither denied nor admitted any
guilt but is prohibited from discussing the details of her
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with Herbst's situation say the SEC contacted
the investor relations consultant after being quoted in Street
Smarts on &UR;  &LR; March 2. SEC officials reminded Herbst that talking
about her case violated her deal with the government and that it
could sue her for breach of settlement, the source says. Herbst
would not comment for this column.
</P>
<P>
   The national NIRI decision was the third shoe to drop on Herbst.
The first was her SEC settlement, and the second was her dismissal
from the office of the local NIRI chapter in Silicon Valley. Street
Smarts spotlighted Herbst's settlement with the SEC, noting that it
was rare for the government to go after investor relations
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Herbst's case was noteworthy because she was a
two-time president of the Silicon Valley chapter of NIRI, which
voted to oust her from office while her status with the national
organization was under review.
</P>
<P>
   One would think that an officer of a professional organization
responsible for setting the standards for an industry would have a
fullunderstanding of the laws and would avoid compromising
situations. But two distinct juries of Herbst's peers have ruled to
the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   It was critical for NIRI to take Herbst's miscues seriously. If
the group failed to take action, NIRI's credibility and authority
would have been undermined. For the most part, the organization has
earned the respect of corporate America, and its members have kept
their noses clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time that NIRI has terminated a person's
membership for cause since we were formed in 1970,'' Thompson
notes.
</P>
<P>
   But the importance and sway of investor relations, which is a
relatively young field, has grown immensely during this bull
market. Public companies with active stocks have learned that
sophisticated investor relations departments can play a huge role
in shaping the perception of their companies' performance on Wall
Street, especially when it comes to the art of managing earnings
expectations of financial analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the IR directors' relatively newfound clout is rather
tangible. It is not uncommon for in-house IR officers to report
directly to chief financial officers _ even at huge corporations.
Outside consultants often gain similar access to executive suites.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, as the power of the IR community has increased, so has the
temptation to abuse the power of the office. All of this might
partially explain the SEC's heightened interest in investor
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, the SEC made it illegal for investor relations
consultants (usually those who are not employees of the
corporation) to receive stock or stock options from public
companies as a form of payment.
</P>
<P>
   Because of abuses related to rules that allow companies to
distribute stock to their own employees, the SEC will not allow
consultants who provide investor relations counsel or shareholder
communications services to receive stock from their clients. The
new rule will become effective April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtably, this is a hot-button issue for the Bay Area, where
outside investor relations consultants tend to accept stock more
than any other region accept for New England, Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that this is going to cause some heartburn,'' says
Thompson, who will address the Silicon Valley chapter of NIRI on
this topic next week.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's new rules are in line with NIRI's own guidelines,
which state that IR consultants should not own stock in their
clients. Period.
</P>
<P>
   As a personal matter, Thompson takes it one step further and
doesn't own individual stocks at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern has always been regarding conflict of interest,''
Thompson says. ``You might be less interested in getting (certain)
news out there if it's going to pound your stock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
