   (NYT14) RANALAI, India -- March 22, 1999 -- INDIA-CHRISTIANS,
3-22 -- Chito Kara, a Christian, shows her burned house to
relatives. A dispute between Hindus and Christians over a cross
erected on a nearby hill erupted in violence earlier this month
leaving 150 homes, all belonging to Christians in the village,
gutted by fire. (Celia Dugger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 22, 1999 -- NY-SAFIR, 3-22 -- New York
City Police Commissioner Howard Safir and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
right, during a news conference earlier this month. Some of Safir's
critics argue that the commissioner, as well as the Giuliani
Adminstration itself, refuse to come to grips with the extent to
which the recent killing of Amadou Diallo has begun to overshadow
the achievements of the Giuliani's police department. (Nancy
Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- March 22, 1999 -- NY-POLICE, 3-22 -- State
Comptroller Carl McCall, center, flanked by Rep. Jose Serrano,
D-N.Y., and Bronx Borough President Jose Ferrer, right, are led to
police vehicle following their arrest on Monday outside police
headquarters. As the city's top cop found himself engulfed by
growing criticism of his leadership, more than 141 demonstrators
were charged in the largest number of arrests to date in protests
against police tactics and the shooting of Amadou Diallo. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 22, 1999 -- CABLE-MERGER-IMPACT, 3-22
-- Ralph Roberts, left, chairman and founder of Comcast Corp.,
Chuck Lillis, chairman and CEO of MediaOne Group, center, and Brian
Roberts, Comcast's president, during a news conference about their
merger on Monday. Comcast Corp. will buy MediaOne Group Inc. for
$48.65 billion in stock, combining the nation's third- and
fourth-largest cable television providers in the industry's richest
merger ever. (Fred. R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 22, 1999 -- NURSES-SHORTAGE, 3-22 --
Dr. Joli Yuknek and nurse Diane Heater tend to a young patient in
the emergency room at the Westchester Medical Center in October,
1998. The nation's hospitals are experiencing a shortage of
registered nurses, the specialized, highly trained nurses who
manage and staff operating rooms, emergency rooms, intensive care
units and pediatric wards for high-risk babies. (Chris Maynard/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- March 22, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP, 3-22 --
President Clinton approaches the podium to deliver a statement
about the situation in Kosovo on Monday outside the White House.
Clinton said the situation in Kosovo was dire and renewed his
threat of air strikes against the Serb forces.(Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LOS ANGELES -- March 22, 1999 -- OSCAR-BENIGNI, 3-22 --
Roberto Benigni with his two Oscars Sunday night. Benigni won the
awards for best actor for his performance in ``Life Is Beautiful,''
and also collected the foreign-film Oscar. The comedy-drama from
Italy is about a man who seeks to protect his son from the
Holocaust. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- March 22, 1999 -- SCI-COOLIDGE-DOCUMENATRY-2,
3-22 -- Naturalists like Harold Jefferson Coolidge used these tools
on expeditions to Africa and Asia in the 1920's and 30's in
studying the animals they killed to observe. Ancient footage of
African expeditions by early conservationists like Coolidge
represent a sort of gorilla skeleton in the closet of the global
conservation movement. But eventually Coolidge became evolved a
major force behind preserving the kind of rare species he had once
shot. (Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- March 22, 1999 -- SCI-ZERO-GRAVITY-EXERCISES,
3-22 -- Students from Colorado State University test an exercise
machine during a weightless experiment aboard a NASA test aircraft
last week. As a January 2000 launching date for the first resident
mission to the new International Space Station approaches, NASA now
is making its most serious effort ever to break the muscle barrier
to extended stays in zero gravity. (NASA/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- March 22, 1999 -- SCI-COOLIDGE-DOCUMENATRY,
3-22 -- Jonathan Schwartz, of Interlock Media Inc., holds a caliper
used by Harold Jefferson Coolidge while working on editing a
documentary of the conservationist. Ancient footage of African
expeditions by early conservationists like Coolidge represent a
sort of gorilla skeleton in the closet of the global conservation
movement. But eventually Coolidge became evolved a major force
behind preserving the kind of rare species he had once shot. Now,
his expedition films are being crafted into a documentary. (Rick
Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- March 22, 1999 -- OSCAR-RDP-4 3-22 --
James Coburn holds his Oscar for best supporting actor while
standing next to actress Kim Bassinger who presented the award to
Coburn, Sunday night following the award ceremony. The award to
Coburn, who played an alcoholic and abusive patriarch in
``Affliction,'' symbolized a comeback for the 70-year-old actor,
who overcame a 15-year battle with arthritis that nearly ended his
career. The award was, in some ways, a homage to the 40-year career
of the rangy, gravel-voiced actor, a star of westerns the 1960s who
developed into one of the most versatile character actors in films.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- March 22, 1999 -- OSCAR-RDP-3, 3-22 -- The
producers of the film ``Shakespeare in Love'' celebrate their Oscar
victory along with the film's star and best actress winner Gwyneth
Paltrow, Sunday night following the 71st annual Academy Awards
ceremony. From left are Donna Gigliotti, Harvey Weinstein, Paltrow,
Edward Zwick and Marc Norman. In an upset, the movie about the
personal life of William Shakespeare, was selected as best picture.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- March 22, 1999 -- OSCAR-RDP-2, 3-22 --
Dame Judi Dench with her Oscar for best supporting actress in
``Shakespeare in Love,'' Sunday night. In an upset, ``Shakespeare
in Love'' was also selected as best picture at the 71st annual
Academy Awards. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES -- March 22, 1999 -- OSCAR-RDP-1, 3-22 --
Sophia Loren, who presented the Oscar for best foreign film to
fellow Italian Roberto Benigni, backstage Sunday night during the
71st annual Academy Awards. Benigni was the first actor to win an
Oscar for a foreign language film since Miss Loren won for ``Two
Women'' in 1961. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
