<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ENVOY HEADS LAST-DITCH EFFORT ON KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Under orders not to let Serbia delay NATO
action while Kosovo burns, an American diplomat struggled early
Tuesday to negotiate at least a cease-fire. American officials said
that talks were expected to continue into the day.
</P>
<P>
   The American negotiator, Richard Holbrooke, met with President
Slobodan Milosevic for more than three hours in a last-ditch effort
to resolve the crisis and forestall NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke then returned to the American Embassy for nearly three
hours of consultations with Washington and NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is engaged in a large offensive against the Kosovo
Liberation Army in Kosovo, and Washington and the West said that if
he does not agree to a NATO-led force to monitor a peace settlement
in the province, NATO will bomb Serb military targets.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces have already destroyed three of the KLA's seven
regional headquarters, a senior NATO official said Tuesday, adding
urgency to the Holbrooke mission. Milosevic has been told by his
generals, the official said, that Yugoslav troops could complete
their sweep by Friday, destroying the KLA's command and control.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's mission here ``is a last-ditch effort and it's got
to be quick,'' the official said. ``We want a quick determination
from Holbrooke about whether we're at the end of the process or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington and NATO have presented the talks as a final chance
for Milosevic to avoid severe military punishment; Milosevic, while
sounding tough, typically waits until the last moment to make
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, as Holbrooke was meeting with Milosevic,
President Clinton warned that military action could be imminent.
``If President Milosevic continues to choose aggression over peace,
then NATO's military plans must go forward,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that 30,000 more ethnic Albanians have been displaced
from their homes over the last few days, and said: ``We cannot
allow President Milosevic to continue the aggression with
impunity,'' adding that America's security interests must include
``Europe's freedom and security.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior NATO official said that without at least a verifiable
ceasefire, there was little point in talking further.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we want is to have Milosevic tie up Holbrooke
with fake negotiations while the Serbs clear up in Kosovo, and we
end up with both a diplomatic failure and a military fait
accompli,'' the senior NATO official said. ``Milosevic has already
had a three-day head start.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark's comment that
air strikes could occur ``within hours,'' and said: ``Some allies
feel strongly that every day is a lost day.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO air strikes would be designed to destroy Yugoslavia's
integrated air defense system and then to send fighters and bombers
to hit Serb military targets involved in prosecuting the war
against the KLA in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether NATO would thus be acting as the KLA's air force,
which Western officials had said was not their goal, the official
said: ``The KLA, whatever else they've done, have signed the peace
agreement. So we have a bit of a moral obligation to the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serb offensive followed immediately upon the sudden
withdrawal on Saturday of the some 1,400 unarmed verifiers of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe. Asked if their
rapid removal from the province was not an invitation to Milosevic
to attack, the official said that many NATO members had been
pressing for air strikes to begin immediately, with no final
Holbrooke mission.
</P>
<P>
   But some concerns with NATO, especially from the Italians, who
are a part of the contact group, combined with criticism from
within the American Congress, argued for longer consultations and a
last chance for Milosevic to change his position.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb military campaign of the last few days has also served
to harden solidarity within NATO about the need for air strikes,
and has allowed the Americans to push for a more intensive set of
strikes. Washington argued that initial cruise missile strikes
intended to destroy Yugoslavia's sophisticated air defense should
be followed _ without pause for Belgrade's reflection _ by
intensive fighter and bomber attacks on Serb military positions in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Americans said, Milosevic would succeed in his
aims to damage the KLA while NATO appeared to be standing by. That
new discussion within NATO required further time, the officials
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO will be blamed,'' the official said, ``it will be
blamed for delay, not for impetuosity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only Tuesday that NATO countries gave Secretary-General
Javier Solana the authority to order expanded air strikes on ``a
much more diverse target list, a much more intensive pace of
operations and an expanded geographical zone,'' a NATO official
told reporters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The official also said NATO was urging Kosovo Liberation Army
guerrillas to refrain from ``murder and bombing'' _ like the ambush
of four Serb policemen in downtown Pristina Sunday night _ that
would justify further Serb attacks. There were two more bomb
attacks on bars in Pristina, with at least one dead and eight
wounded, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Holbrooke's meeting with Milosevic, the Serb president
met with the three chairmen of the suspended peace talks on Kosovo,
American Christopher Hill, EU representative Wolfgang Petritsch and
Russian Boris Mayorsky. The meeting, which the three diplomats and
Holbrooke had agreed would be limited to a discussion of the
political side of the Kosovo agreement, did not go well, said
officials at the meeting, which lasted 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was emotional and lively,'' Petritsch said. They wanted to
give Milosevic an accurate account of the political arrangements,
fearing that he had misinformation. When Milosevic called the
Albanians ``terrorists and separatists,'' Petritsch said: ``Well,
after they signed the agreement, you can only call them Albanian
autonomists.'' The agreement calls for effective self-rule in
Kosovo, but the province will remain a sovereign part of Serbia and
Yugoslavia for at least the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Holbrooke's turn, and he concentrated on the damage
NATO was about to do to Milosevic's army and regime if Belgrade's
position did not change and the offensive stop.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Brussels, after talks with NATO leaders and the
British, French and German foreign ministers, Holbrooke said: ``We
are not _ and I cannot stress this too highly _ going to get into a
talk-while-fighting-intensifies situation in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that NATO is ``on the brink'' of military action. ``It
is not too late to avoid it, but the window is narrowing.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's Solana said: ``We think that this is the moment of
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO is being careful not to claim that the goal of any
bombing is to force Milosevic back to the bargaining table.
Instead, NATO officials are insisting that the only goal of air
strikes is to ``degrade'' Serbia's military ability to inflict harm
on the KLA and innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   It is the human tragedy that provides NATO its legal
justification to bomb a sovereign country, especially in the
absence of any United Nations Security Council resolution
authorizing military action.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials kept up a defensive, wounded tone, and called in
Western ambassadors to the Foreign Ministry to protest the
possibility of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Milan Milutinovic, the Serbian president, said Serbs were ready
to defend themselves if the West tried to impose a solution in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want war,'' he told the Greek newspaper Ethnos. ``We
are seeking a peaceful resolution. But if someone attacks us, or if
someone imposes, then of course we will fight for our homeland.''
</P>
