<SLUG> BC-CABLE-MERGER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE COMPANIES TO MERGE, IN A RACE TO THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: listed on some skeds as CABLE-TELEVISION)) 
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(wg) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Comcast Corp. said Monday that it would acquire
MediaOne in a $53 billion merger that will create the third largest
cable television company in the nation but has little to do with
television.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is driven by the cable industry's race with telephone
companies to offer superfast access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As the only two industries that have communication cables
passing almost every house and business in the country, cable and
telephone companies are positioning themselves to grab a share of
the other's business. Indeed, AT&AMP;T earlier this year paid $55
billion for the cable provider TeleCommunications Inc. just to get
access to wires that can carry phone and Internet services in homes
along with television.
</P>
<P>
   The local Bell phone companies will begin offering high-speed
Internet access over standard telephone lines this year throughout
much of the country. This leaves cable operators facing a kind of
competitive threat unknown in their local television monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday whether or how much the merger would
affect rates for cable customers, though it is certain they will
not go down.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons MediaOne was willing to be acquired is that it
will reduce the cost the combined company pays for cable
programming. But those savings _ as well as any increases in cable
rates as industry regulation ends this year _ will almost certainly
be invested in technology to provide data services, and eventually
phone services, to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a race to be first to offer Internet access and
ultimately telephone service to the upscale neighborhoods that will
buy it first,'' said Howard Anderson, president of the Yankee
Group, a media consulting firm. ``It's called the `first move
advantage.' If customers go with the phone companies, it will be
hard, if not impossible to lure them back to cable. So cable
companies want to get big so they have as much cash flow as they
need to build their Internet business. Size is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast's president, Brian Roberts, said that both Comcast and
MediaOne had raised their rates 5 percent last year, which he
called a conservative increase. And he made a point of warning that
any attempt by the Federal Communications Commission to institute
price controls on cable rates would harm cash flow that the
companies have been investing in upgrading their systems to handle
Internet and phone services.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Ambrust, an analyst at Paul Kagan &AMP; Associates, a media
consulting firm, said the 5 percent increase imposed last year by
both companies was ``middle of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Comcast has six million cable subscribers, primarily along the
Northeast corridor from Baltimore through Washington, Delaware,
Philadelphia, New Jersey and Connecticut. MediaOne has about five
million customers, most of them in the Boston area, though it also
has cable systems in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia-based Comcast, with a market value of $24.4
billion, is controlled and managed by the Roberts family through
9.4 million shares that carry 15 votes each. That gives the family
80 percent of all votes. Individual investors own 30 million shares
of single-vote stock, and 328.6 million shares of nonvoting stock
are owned by institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Since MediaOne is valued at $41.7 billion, its president, Chuck
Lillis, was asked at a news conference why it was not his company
that was doing the acquiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Roberts didn't want to sell,'' Lillis said.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, MediaOne was the more obvious takeover target. A
spinoff of U.S. West, it is the only large _ and still independent
_ cable company that is not controlled by a single shareholder or
family. And it is viewed as having significant room for improved
management. Compared with Comcast, whose profit margins on cable
operations are about 48 percent, MediaOne has margins of about 38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast is offering 1.1 of its shares for each of MediaOne's 664
million shares. The Roberts family will keep control because all
the shares being offered are nonvoting stock. Based on the closing
stock prices on Friday, before the deal was announced, Comcast was
paying $80.16 a share,
</P>
<P>
   The one glitch in the deal could be MediaOne's relationship with
Time Warner. MediaOne owns 25 percent of Time Warner Entertainment,
the spinoff that includes Warner Bros., Home Box Office and 10
million of Time Warner's 12 million cable subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and his father, Ralph, the company's 79-year-old founder
and chairman, both said Time Warner's chairman, Gerald Levin, has
been extremely supportive of the deal. But some bankers and others
suggested that Time Warner, with a market capitalization of $80
billion, could play spoiler by making its own bid for MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have blocking rights on the sale of MediaOne,'' a Time
Warner spokesman said, emphasizing that it had no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast's Brian Roberts insisted that Time Warner had no such
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides agreed that once the merger was complete, the
combined company will not get MediaOne's seat on the management
committee of Time Warner cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Still deals are like courtships, and an unexpected rival can
inspire possessive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As one investment banker put it: ``On the one hand, MediaOne has
been sitting there for two years, no one made a bid, and Time
Warner is the most logical guy given that they already have an
interest.'' He added, ``When somebody says speak now or forever
hold your peace,'' that can prompt a move.
</P>
<P>
   Stock in Comcast fell $5.375 on Monday to close at $64.75 while
stock in MediaOne rose $7.75 to close at 68.50.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast said cash flow for the merged companies in 2000 would be
about about $1.9 billion after all cost savings had been factored
in. Brian Roberts said he planned a 5 percent cut to the combined
34,000-person work force. Assuming those improvements, Comcast
would be paying about 15 times MediaOne's cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is the upper end of recent transactions,'' said
Salvatore Muio, who heads his own investment management firm.
``However in a stock deal, that is rather meaningless, since the
stock price fluctuates.''
</P>
<P>
   When the merger is complete, MediaOne shareholders will own
about 64 percent of the equity of the combined companies. Using
Friday's closing prices, Comcast paid $80.16 per share, based on
its closing price of $72.875. That represented a 32 percent premium
to Friday's close of $60.75.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, Salomon Smith Barney and Davis Polk Wardell
represented Comcast as bankers and legal advisers respectively.
MediaOne's investment bankers were Lehman Bros and Allen &AMP; Co. Weil
Gotshal and Manges were legal advisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
