<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0255 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      03-22 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO POISED FOR AIRSTRIKES ON SERB FORCES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S.-led NATO forces made final preparations for
airstrikes against Serbian military positions amid last-minute
pressure Monday on President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to
sign a Kosovo peace agreement and allow international troops to
police the deal.
</P>
<P>
   An aerial bombardment by NATO and a spirited response from
sophisticated Yugoslav air-defense installations could lead to the
most high-powered military conflict in Europe since World War II.
Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic said Yugoslavia would respond to
airstrikes ``with all the resources we have.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
warned Milosevic in statements from Washington as U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke held yet another face-to-face talk with the
Yugoslav leader in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the brink of military action,'' Holbrooke said
before he met with Milosevic. After four hours of talks with
Milosevic, Holbrooke advised Clinton administration leaders in
Washington that there had been no significant progress, U.S.
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke reported by a secured telephone line to Albright and
Defense Secretary William Cohen, who then briefed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Additional Milosevic-Holbrooke talks were expected Tuesday in
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, the U.S. sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on state television in Belgrade, Holbrooke
blamed Milosevic and his top aides for the prospects of military
strikes by NATO. ``They have the power to stop this tragedy,''
Holbrooke said. ``They have the power to reverse it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Milosevic is known for his brinksmanship, Yugoslav
leaders had signaled there was little chance for a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pressure can change our principled stand,'' Jovanovic said
in a CNN interview before the Milosevic-Holbrook meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a statement at the White House, repeated his
preference for a resolution ``by peaceful means,'' but added: ``If
not, we have to be prepared to act. ... Serbia's mounting
aggression must be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders said they were ready to strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very substantial and detailed plan for such an air
campaign, which can be rather long and protracted,'' Gen. Klaus
Naumann, NATO's military chief of staff, said in a CNN interview
from alliance headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the diplomatic push, Russia voiced anew its opposition to
NATO military moves against Serbia, and the U.S. Senate debated
whether use of American forces should require specific
congressional authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, pressed toward a procedural
vote Tuesday on her call for barring U.S. participation in NATO
airstrikes until the House and Senate concur and Clinton lays out a
detailed plan for U.S. involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison apparently lacked the votes to cut off debate on her
proposal. Clinton planned to call a bipartisan group of House and
Senate members to the White House on Tuesday in a bid to dampen
congressional criticism of the policy as the prospect of airstrikes
increased.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison conceded ``timing is bad'' for the debate, ``but I
don't know when it gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we go bombing sovereign nations, we ought to have a
plan,'' she said. ``Before we put one American in harm's way, I
want to know what is the intention here. What is the reality?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., responded that the measure could lead
to ``a policy of paralysis.'' Biden, senior Democrat on the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, said the only question for NATO is:
``What will happen if we don't act?''
</P>
<P>
   Describing Milosevic as a cold-blooded murderer, Biden recited
graphic details of the killing reportedly being carried out now by
Serb forces against the ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   If there are NATO airstrikes, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
said, the ``immediate goal is to degrade the ability to repress the
Kosovar people.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright denied reports the United States was also considering
use of ground troops unless Milosevic agrees to a peace deal and
allows NATO forces to help police the deal. Albanian Kosovars have
signed off on such a plan, but Milosevic has rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no plans for a ground part of this,'' Albright said.
``We obviously have an intention for Americans to be part of a NATO
implementation force. But there are no plans to use ground forces
as a part of this initial strike activity or follow-on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Serbia, the principal republic in
Yugoslavia and is populated primarily with ethnic Albanians. When
many of the Albanians intensified their separatist drive last year,
Milosevic responded with a military crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting raged in portions of Kosovo on Monday between
government forces and the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, news
services reported. Several villages were ablaze, and there were
unconfirmed reports of new mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that Serb forces are now engaged in further
attacks on Kosovar civilians,'' Clinton said. ``Already more than
40,000 Serb security forces are poised in and around Kosovo with
additional units on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart reported ``tens of thousands of new refugees heading
back to the mountains, all of this bringing us closer to the
humanitarian crisis we've been working very hard to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   And the spokesman was clear on Clinton's view of Milosevic. Does
the U.S. president trust Milosevic, the White House spokesman was
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people have been killed in the year of conflict,
and hundreds of thousands have fled their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic criticized NATO's move toward airstrikes in a letter
to the British and French foreign ministers read on Yugoslavian
state television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your people should be ashamed, because you are getting ready
to use force against a small European nation because it protects
its territory against separatism and its people against
terrorism,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there was ``strong unity'' among NATO allies for
air raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that we cannot allow President Milosevic to
continue the aggression with impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton had written President Boris Yeltsin of
Russia to again detail the rationale for NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are categorically against the use of force against
Yugoslavia,'' Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov told
reporters in Moscow as he prepared for a trip to Washington on
Tuesday. ``We believe that political levers to influence the
situation are far from being exhausted yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, however, said that the United States and its allies
``have gone the last mile here. ... Time has run out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said a NATO decision to launch airstrikes ``is not
constrained by the timing of Prime Minister Primakov's visit'' to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
