u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRUISE-SHIP-DUMPING-N     03-22 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-SHIP-DUMPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE LINE PLEADS GUILTY TO UNTRUTHS ON DUMPING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Alaska, Fla., N.Y., Puerto Rico, Mexico)   (jw) 
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a surprise move, Royal Caribbean Cruises pleaded guilty
Monday to criminal charges of making false statements to Coast
Guard inspectors in an effort to conceal discharges of oily waste
water from one of its ships on three separate occasions in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The company pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles
to all three counts of an indictment brought last month. The plea
was entered without any agreement with prosecutors on sentencing
and came as a surprise to government prosecutors. The company faces
fines of at least $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief hearing before Judge Consuelo Marshall, an attorney
for Royal Caribbean, Jan Handzlik, admitted that crew members
aboard the Nordic Prince presented records concealing illegal
discharges of contaminated waste water into the Pacific Ocean three
times in 1994 during routine Coast Guard inspections. The ship
regularly sailed from Mexico to Los Angeles and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   William Carter, the assistant U.S. attorney handling the case,
said outside the courtroom that the ship's record books were
replete with false entries intended to hide the fact that the
ship's pollution-control equipment was not functioning. Carter said
investigations into similar false bookkeeping were continuing in
New York and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Royal Caribbean pleaded guilty in Miami and in San
Juan, Puerto Rico, to similar charges covering the same period of
time involving five ships, including the Nordic Prince. Those pleas
were the result of a plea bargain, but Justice Department officials
said the agreement did not limit the government's authority to
bring additional charges in other jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   The charges to which Royal Caribbean pleaded guilty last June
represented the largest criminal case of ocean pollution ever and
focused attention on difficulties in regulating the fast-growing
cruise industry, in which every major ship sailing out of American
ports is registered with a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Schiffer, assistant attorney general for environment at the
Justice Department, said the Los Angeles charges were based on
conduct that was distinct and independent from the actions covered
by the Miami and San Juan plea bargains.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its earlier agreements, the company instituted new
environmental regulations aboard its ships and began installing new
pollution-control equipment to reduce its discharges to well below
international and U.S. requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean, the world's second-largest cruise company, had
fought the original charges by claiming that its ships operated
outside U.S. jurisdiction because the company was incorporated in
Liberia and its ships flew Liberian and Norwegian flags. But
federal judges in San Juan and Miami rejected the argument.
</P>
<P>
   Government attorneys had speculated that the company might raise
the same jurisdictional question in Los Angeles in the hope of
winning more sympathetic treatment, but Monday's plea seemed to
indicate that Royal Caribbean has abandoned that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Martenstein, a vice president for the cruise company at its
Miami headquarters, declined to discuss the company's legal
strategy or the status of the other criminal inquiries. But she
indicated that Royal Caribbean wants to end the string of
embarrassing cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that what was done was wrong,'' she said.
``We have acknowledged these incidents. We've already apologized.
We've already paid a fine.''
</P>
<P>
   While each of the three counts in the Los Angeles case carries a
potential $500,000 fine, the ultimate fine could be much higher.
The law allows the judge to assess penalties equal to twice the
revenue gained from each of the cruises involved in the guilty
plea. Carter said the government was still trying to calculate the
revenue from the cruises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
