<SLUG> BC-U.S.-U.N.-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. WARNS U.S. TO PAY DUES OR LOSE ASSEMBLY VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States will need to pay at least
$250 million to the United Nations this year if it is to avoid
losing its vote in the General Assembly, the U.N.'s senior
financial officer has warned.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Connor, undersecretary general for finance and
management, pointed out that the figure was appreciably more than
the $197 million that the United States paid toward the end of last
year to avoid losing its vote in the Assembly this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Article 19 of the U.N. Charter, a country cannot vote in
the General Assembly if its total unpaid dues exceed the sum of its
total assessments for the last two years. The U.S. vote in the
Security Council, which is far more powerful than the General
Assembly, would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Connor said it was becoming increasingly difficult for the
United States to avoid losing its vote for two reasons. The first
is the cost of peacekeeping operations is falling rapidly. That
reduces the assessment, increasing the risk that total U.S. debts
to the United Nations of $1.6 billion would exceed its last two
annual membership bills.
</P>
<P>
   A second difficulty is the tendency for Congress to place
conditions on U.N. payments like freezing the budget and seeking
assurances that the organization will not create an international
army.
</P>
<P>
   That slows the rate at which the administration can hand over
the money, after congressional approval, Connor said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking change in the U.N. finances he discussed was
the decline in peacekeeping costs. After bumping along for most of
the U.N.'s history at about $400 million a year, the peacekeeping
budget took off in 1992, climbing rapidly to more than $3 billion
in 1994 and 1995. But 1996 brought a sharp decline, to just under
$1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The budget has fallen further, to an expected $900 million this
year, and it is projected at $650 million in 1999, after decisions
to phase out operations in Angola and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Connor said the U.N. financial position, usually precarious, was
better in a number of ways at the end of 1998 than it has been for
years. At $736 million, its cash reserves were higher than at the
end of 1997 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Unpaid dues are also lower than in those two years, at $2
billion. And unpaid debts to member states to cover peacekeeping
troops and military equipment are also slightly lower, $872
million.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last year, 117 member countries had paid their
dues in full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
