<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     03-22 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER IS BIG BONUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Angels signed pitcher Tim Belcher last Dec.
18 to a two-year contract worth $10.2 million to provide innings
and veteran leadership. The Angels expect him to pitch deep into
games and give them a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   The club also got a little bonus in Belcher _ an opening-day
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Because Chuck Finley's sore neck has put him behind in his
preparation for the season, Belcher will make his third career
opening-day start. He started the opener for the Dodgers in 1989
and for the Royals last season.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins has not told Belcher that he's got
the assignment yet. He's a little superstitious. ``I've told guys
early and the next thing you know. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Collins conceded that Belcher, 37, is smart enough to figure it
out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher will pitch in one more Cactus League game on March 27.
On April 1, he'll pitch in a minor-league camp game in Mesa to
remain on his normal rotation while the rest of the team takes the
day off. On opening day April 6, he will start against the
Cleveland Indians at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher made 88 pitches in 52/3 innings Monday against the San
Diego Padres, giving up three runs (none earned) and five hits in
the Angels' 8-5 win. He did not allow a hit until the fifth, when
the Padres scored three times, aided by two Angels errors.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a guy thing: Catcher Phil Nevin had four hits Monday,
but it shouldn't have come as a surprise. He had a new coat of
toenail polish applied Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin said his daughter painted his toenails one night last year
after he fell asleep and the next day, he hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin had a big day despite getting whacked on top of the head
and knocked woozy when hit by Gary Matthews Jr.'s bat on Matthews'
follow-through.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mo knows: First baseman Mo Vaughn had a double, single, two
walks and one RBI, both of his hits going to the opposite (left)
field and both with two strikes and with men on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to situational-hit as much as I can,'' Vaughn said. ``I
really try to concentrate on that, that's what you work on. You get
up with guys in scoring position, you've got to get them in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
