<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA WILL FIGHT ANTI-SEMITIC TIDE, PRIMAKOV TELLS U.S. JEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov promised a group of
American Jews Monday that the Russian government will combat a
rising tide of anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov provided the assurance in a meeting with
representatives of the Anti-Defamation League. The Kremlin has
condemned anti-Semitism, but Primakov has previously said little
about the problem, although he has Jewish family roots.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to fly to Washington on Tuesday to seek Western
financial credits, however, he spoke out in an apparent effort to
set a positive tone for his mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say unambiguously that the government takes a very strong
position against any manifestation of nationalism, including
anti-Semitism,'' Primakov told the Jewish group, its
representatives said.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that Primakov promised to support new legislation
to clamp down on fascist and extremist groups. He was reported to
have said that he wants Jews to feel at home in Russia and to have
condemned the anti-Semitic tirades of Albert Makashov, a former
general and a Communist lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Makashov has to be condemned fair and square
and unambiguously for his pronouncements in an open and undisguised
way,'' Primakov was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of Russia's currency in August, there have
been growing incidents of anti-Semitism. Many Jews in Moscow say
they do not feel in danger, but the problem is more serious in the
provinces. Earlier this month, for example, the lone synagogue in
the Siberian city of Novosibirsk was vandalized.
</P>
<P>
   Makashov has been one of the most vitriolic leaders of the
anti-Semitic crusade. He has blamed Jews for the nation's economic
ills. In a recent speech in southern Russian city of Rostov, he
virtually invited Cossacks to sack Jewish homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist-led parliament, however, has declined to condemn
him. On Friday, 104 members voted to censure Makashov while 133
rejected the measure. Instead, the parliament charged that the
press is exaggerating the danger of Russian fascism.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Primakov plans to meet on Thursday in the United States with a
group of American Jews. Abraham Foxman, the national director of
the Anti-Defamation league, said Primakov's remarks Monday were
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is his first significant public statement condemning not
only anti-Semitism in Russia but the specific utterances of
Makashov,'' Foxman said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel also met here with
Primakov Monday and expressed concern over anti-Semitism and the
sale of Russian missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu indicated in an interview on Russian television that
he was prepared to discuss cooperation on high-technology projects
and the possible purchase of air defense systems from Russia. That
could be an incentive to Russia to cut off the sale of missile
technology to Iran, a top Israeli and American priority.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at a Moscow Synagogue on Sunday, Netanyahu condemned
anti-Semitism and invited Russian Jews to immigrate to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible epidemic, which is above all dangerous for
the society in which it is developing,'' he said. ``I want you to
come to Israel, but the choice is in your hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
