<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TIG     03-22 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE CALL COULD MEND A FRACTURED FRIENDSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ He is, as always, standing tall and strong in
the morning sunshine at Joker Marchant Stadium, but there is no
mistaking the pain in Larry Parrish's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It is deep and it is real and he doesn't know exactly how to
make it go away.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when we would both rather be talking about baseball and
starting pitchers and what Parrish, who manages the Tigers now, is
going to do about the nice problem of having too many good, young
outfielders, we're talking about hurt feelings instead.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about friendship and integrity and all those
things that, in the end, are more important than baseball.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about Buddy Bell, who, until Sept. 1, was probably
the closest friend Parrish has had in the game.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't spoken since that day.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours earlier, in Sarasota where Bell is now the
Reds' minor-league director and manager in waiting, I had seen the
same pain on his face, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I want to talk about,'' Bell said quietly.
``It's not an issue with me.''
</P>
<P>
   His eyes said something different. It is very much an issue with
Bell, just as it is an issue with Parrish. And it's an issue with
baseball people, who care so much about both men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tito told me the other day I needed to call Buddy,'' Parrish
said yesterday before the Rangers and Tigers played an exhibition.
``I've definitely been thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tito is Phillies manager Terry ``Tito'' Francona. He and many
others in baseball are as distressed as I am about the falling out
between Bell and Parrish over what amounts to little more than ugly
rumors and misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   They are good men, so much alike, so strong in values and
conviction. They connected instantly when Parrish came to Texas in
1982. They each combined a passion for life and the game they loved
with an essential decency that became the foundation for the
respect and affection they had for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Bell and Larry Parrish: On any list of all-time Rangers,
they're together, right at the top.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it seemed so fitting when they came together again in
Detroit two years ago, Bell as manager and Parrish as his bench
coach. This, you figured, was like reuniting a knife with a fork or
peanut butter with jelly; like Staubach with Pearson, Pippen with
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy and L.P.: This was, again, a perfect pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Together they would resuscitate the moribund Tigers, bringing a
spark back to one of the American League's charter franchises.
</P>
<P>
   And then real life came along and spoiled it.
</P>
<P>
   First came Bell's firing Sept. 1. Suddenly he was gone and
Parrish was interim manager. He got the job full time in
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Happens in baseball every year. A manager gets canned, a coach
the manager had brought in as his right-hand man is asked to step
into the job. It's not particularly pleasant for anyone involved,
but it's the way the game too often works.
</P>
<P>
   Except this time the greatest casualty is a 17-year friendship.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the situation is what part, if any, Parrish
played in Bell's firing. Did he privately second-guess his friend's
baseball decisions? Was that confidence betrayed?
</P>
<P>
   It has become almost a ``he-said, no-he-said'' situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first I heard anything about this was a few days after
Buddy was fired and Al Kaline came back from a card show in New
York,'' Parrish said. ``He told me Buddy was up there ripping me,
saying I'd back-stabbed him. I said, `Whaaaaat?' ''
</P>
<P>
   If either of them had picked up a phone and talked then, you
probably wouldn't be reading this now. They could have talked it
out. But pride and stubbornness got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't call me either,'' Parrish said defensively. ``It
hurt me and I didn't think I'd done anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record _ and Bell privately acknowledges this even now _
nothing Parrish did had anything to do with Bell's mutual parting
with the Tigers. Mark that down to irreconcilable differences with
general manager Randy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Friends _ insiders who are close to both men _ say they have no
reason to believe that Parrish said anything derogatory about
Buddy. It would have been totally out of character, based on their
history together.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's loyalty to his friends is unquestioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as loyal a person as you'll ever meet,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Was Parrish, excited about getting his chance to manage in the
big leagues, as sensitive to Bell's feelings about being fired as
he might have been? Perhaps not. Has he changed some things from
the way Buddy did them to put in his own tweaks? Sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about baseball,'' Parrish said. ``It's
not right or wrong. It's just different ways of doing things. If
anybody said Buddy messed the club up last year, that would be
wrong, because we just weren't that good a club.''
</P>
<P>
   Parrish, sometimes honest to a fault and wanting to be loyal to
his employers, admits he hasn't always handled questions from the
media as well as he might have.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to answer questions without stepping on
anybody's toes,'' he said, ``and sometimes you step all over them
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   So Parrish puts off the phone call, waiting, trying to figure
out where to start and what to say.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tigers visit Sarasota, Bell makes sure he's somewhere
else. He puts up a disinterested front, trying to act like all this
doesn't matter anyway, but he's not fooling anyone.
</P>
<P>
   One of them _ Parrish probably, because Buddy feels like he's
the offended party _ needs to pick up the phone and make the call.
</P>
<P>
   It should have happened a long time ago. This is a friendship
worth saving.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
