<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A FREEWAY LAND WITHOUT A CAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARTHA STEVENSON OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southern California has for so long been the land of the freeway
that the idea of negotiating it carless seems daunting, even
revolutionary. But as traffic has thickened so that many highways
become eight-lane parking lots during increasingly extended rush
hours, residents and visitors are turning to public transportation
to get around, and municipalities are extending mass transit
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers to far-flung or rural destinations in the region may
still need a car, but for those willing to do a little homework,
getting around Southern California by bus, rail, trolley, subway or
even air can be inexpensive and convenient alternatives to the
frustration and anxiety of the highways.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered this firsthand on a recent bus trip into downtown
San Diego from my home near Mission Bay, about seven miles away. At
the Old Town transit hub, two couples of retirement age got on. In
the four days they had been in town from Sioux City, Iowa, they
said, they had seen a lot of San Diego without a car _ the Zoo, Sea
World, Coronado, Old Town, the harbor (by boat). They recommended
the Old Town Trolley, a narrated tour of much of San Diego that
allows passengers to get on and off wherever they choose.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were delighted with how easy it had been to
travel by bus, trolley, taxi and boat, and with the advice they'd
got from local residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is an excellent resource for information about
traveling around the area. A recent search of ``Southern California
mass transit'' turned up timetables, fares and phone numbers for
train, subway, trolley and bus service and plenty of maps.
</P>
<P>
   James Mohler operates www.transit-rider.com, a site devoted to
mass transit in California with many helpful hints. Another
independent but quirkier site for insider information is Nik
Trendowski's www-scf.usc.edu/maburke/transit/. His
spur-of-the-moment trip by public buses from Los Angeles to San
Diego and back by Amtrak in one day sounded like fun, and he
offered other tales of the bus system and a listing of interesting
routes.
</P>
<P>
   Around Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles area sprawls across several counties and is
served by a motley assortment of private and municipal transit
systems. But the new light-rail Blue and Green Lines, and the
nearly finished Red Line subway, in combination with buses and the
new Metrolink commuter train line, can make getting around
manageable, even enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   The metropolitan bus lines have a mixed reputation, with reports
of rude drivers who stop where and when they deem best, but as mass
transit becomes more popular, this may improve.
</P>
<P>
   There are some areas of maximum convenience for those without
cars, besides downtown Los Angeles, which is well served by all
transportation, including Amtrak. Most lines converge there at
Union Station, where the Los Angeles Metropolitan Transportation
Authority operates one of its customer service centers, which
provide maps, timetables, transit passes, tickets and free bike
permits; it is open Monday to Friday 6 a.m. to 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Transportation Authority bus fares are $1.35, and
transfers are 25 cents. Weekly passes cost $11; children under 5
ride free.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sgt. Jake Bushey of the Los Angeles Police
Department, security for the MTA system has been handled for the
last two years by the city police. Security within the stations,
and on the trains and buses, includes plainclothes and uniformed
officers patrolling stations and trains along with security
personnel hired by the MTA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is panhandlers at the station exits,'' he
said, with the Hollywood, Wilshire, and downtown stops being the
prime panhandling sites.
</P>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, besides having a lovely pedestrian promenade with
restaurants and theaters, and its famous pier and beach, has the
Big Blue Bus line, with routes connecting to Los Angeles
International Airport (the No. 3 bus) and the Getty Museum (the No.
14), among other destinations.
</P>
<P>
   It also has the Tide Shuttle, a subsidiary service that cruises
up, down and around Santa Monica itself for 50 cents, and the No.
10 express bus ($1.25), which shoots along (or so one hopes) the
Santa Monica Freeway to downtown.
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, at the south end of the Blue Line trolley, has a
free downtown bus service, the Passport, that goes to attractions
like the Queen Mary and the Aquarium of the Pacific, a new
water-taxi service between attractions that costs only $1, and a
visionary Bike Station, a municipally financed center with rentals,
repairs, information and bike parking. Nearby are 33 miles of
bicycle paths around the port.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach Transit also operates $2 round-trip buses to the
Getty Museum on Thursday, Friday and Saturday. There is also
regular bus service (90 cents) to the Long Beach Airport, which is
served by the regional carrier Win Air, as well as American West
and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES AIRPORT has frequent shuttles that connect to the
Metro Green Line. From there, a transfer to the Blue Line at the
Rosa Parks station will take travelers north to downtown (at the
Seventh Street Transfer Station, a switch to the Red Line will take
one to Union Station, three stops to the east, or north up to
Wilshire Center).
</P>
<P>
   From the Rosa Parks station, the Blue Line also goes south to
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ROUTES TO ATTRACTIONS, according to Mohler, include the MTA No.
460 bus, which goes from downtown (it stops at Sixth and Hill
Streets) to the Norwalk Green Line, Knott's Berry Farm and
Disneyland (one can catch this bus from the Norwalk Green Line
station, as well). There is also a bus line, the No. 420-424, from
downtown to Universal Studios and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Line subway is completed in 2000, North Hollywood
will be more accessible from downtown by mass transit. In fact,
five more stations, including Hollywood and Vine, are scheduled to
open June 12.
</P>
<P>
   The popular (and free) Getty Museum is served by the No. 434
bus, in addition to the Big Blue Bus from Santa Monica. The No. 434
also serves Malibu, and is worth a ride, Mohler says, just for a
glimpse of that community.
</P>
<P>
   FROM LOS ANGELES TO SAN DIEGO, the most convenient trip is by
Amtrak, although many airlines offer the 120-mile flight between
Los Angeles International and San Diego International.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak has frequent trains in each direction; the trip takes
about 2 hours, 40 minutes, and the standard adult fare is $22. (At
the Fullerton Amtrak stop, passengers can connect across the street
to an Orange County Transportation Authority bus, the No. 43 south,
to Disneyland.)
</P>
<P>
   Greyhound buses also connect the two cities, with a stop in Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Coaster, a commuter line with fewer trains at midday and on
weekends, runs between the Santa Fe depot in downtown San Diego and
Oceanside in north San Diego County. It stops at many interesting
beach towns along the way, like Carlsbad, where Legoland opened on
March 20.
</P>
<P>
   Around San Diego  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Diego itself is served by an efficient bus line, as well as
a trolley system that covers much of downtown and extends all the
way to Santee in the east and south to the San Ysidro border
crossing, a short walk from Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 992 municipal bus links San Diego International Airport
to the downtown San Diego transit hub in less than 15 minutes, and
stops at all three terminals. At the Transit Store downtown,
visitors can find bus or trolley maps for specific routes.
</P>
<P>
   A new transfer policy allows two hours of travel in any
direction, with bus transfers valid for the trolley and vice versa
(though fare surcharges could apply); a trolley day pass and a
discount ticket package are available. On weekends, up to two
riders 18 and under with a paying adult travel free; monthly passes
allowing unlimited travel on buses and trolleys are $50.
</P>
<P>
   The bus fare is $1.75 (dollar bills are accepted) for most
lines, but the elderly and students pay less. As in Los Angeles,
trolley tickets, $1 and up depending on distance, are sold through
vending machines at all stations, but it is pretty much an honor
system, with tickets checked occasionally by fare inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The north part of San Diego County, in addition to the Coaster
train, also has the new PAL Shuttle bus, which stops at the
Carlsbad Coaster station, Palomar Airport (where you can catch
United Express and American Eagle flights) and Legoland, among
other destinations. Prepaid tickets are $3, half the regular $6
fare.
</P>
<P>
   North County Transit District buses connect most towns in that
part of the county _ from Oceanside to La Jolla to Ramona _ but the
distances involved and the infrequency of the buses (usually about
half an hour) can make getting around a chore.
</P>
<P>
   On Two Wheels
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, bicyclists can transport bikes free on all MTA
buses, almost half of which are equipped with racks in the front,
with most of the remainder to be fitted by June. Some regional bus
lines, like Long Beach Transit, do not handle bikes; in Orange
County, most municipal buses have bike racks.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of advice from Mohler: before getting off the bus,
bicyclists should alert the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Bikes are allowed on MTA railways with a free permit, but not
during rush hours. Metrolink trains, which operate primarily for
commuters and have the most frequent service during rush periods
into and out of downtown Los Angeles (but have very limited weekend
service), also have free space, two bikes per car.
</P>
<P>
   Bicycles can also be taken free onto San Diego municipal and
North County buses; there is space for two bicycles on a rack at
the front of each bus. A permit to take a bike on the trolley costs
$4 at the Transit Store, and is valid for three years (photo
identification necessary).
</P>
<P>
   On the Coaster, bicycles ride free, and are stored on the lower
level of the train, through the doors marked with a bicycle emblem
(this being San Diego, surfboards less than six feet are also
allowed).
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, and for the most part in San Diego, there are
bike paths along the major rivers. The San Gabriel and Los Angeles
River paths are popular with recreational cyclists and, to a lesser
extent, commuters (reconstruction of the Los Angeles River path
should be completed by summer). Esthetics and safety on the paths
should improve as use increases, with call boxes planned for the
future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In place of a car &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
