<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Wine Lovers, A Palace in Portugal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a new addition to the network of government-run inns,
called pousadas, in Portugal: the 31-room Pousada Solar da Rede in
a 17th-century Baroque palace built by the Italian architect
Niccolo Nazzoni. The decor is also 17th century, with reproductions
of furniture of the period.
</P>
<P>
   The palace is set in a 100-acre vineyard and olive and orange
grove near Mesao Frio in northern Portugal. Among the amenities is
a wharf for cruises along the Douro River between Porto and Spain.
The location in the Douro Valley, where grapes for port are grown,
offers visitors a chance to investigate the region's wine
production. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   November through March, rates range from about $90 for a single
to about $135 for a suite for two, with tax and Continental
breakfast, based on 177 escudos to $1. From April through October,
a single will start at about $155 and a suite at about $200. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information, call Marketing Ahead at (800) 223-1356. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All About France On a Telephone Line &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning a trip to France and have a question about a
historic site, an art exhibition, a music festival, transportation,
or a place to eat or stay, there will be a new number to call
starting Thursday: (410) 286-8310. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Agents for the information service, provided by the French
government Tourist Office and known as France-on-Call, will take
questions Monday through Friday from 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. Eastern time.
The new number replaces (202) 659-7779, which can be used through
Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information and brochures will be available through the
France-on-Call program as well as from the French government
Tourist Office's Web site, www.francetourism.com, and from the
tourist offices in New York, Los Angeles and Chicago. The New York
office is on the 16th floor of 444 Madison Avenue (between 49th and
50th Streets). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tourist office is continuing a program with Mastercard
International that offers discounts on air fares and
department-store purchases. For a copy of the guide and an Air
France vacation brochure, call (800) 237-2623. Late next month,
France-on-Call plans to issue the Insider's Good Value Guide to
France, which will include tips on shopping, culture and
transportation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Freireich &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long Island Beachhead For Southwest Airlines &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines began flying to Long Island this month,
providing service to MacArthur Airport in Islip, N.Y., from
Baltimore-Washington, Chicago, Nashville and Tampa. And US Airways
began a new service, hourly flights between La Guardia and Dulles
International Airport outside Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southwest is offering 12 flights a day from Long Island: 8 to
Baltimore-Washington, 2 to Midway in Chicago and 1 each to
Nashville and Tampa. The walk-up fare between Islip and Washington
is $65 one way; the seven-day advance-purchase fare to Washington
is $78 round trip with an overnight stay required. Information:
(800) 435-9792. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first US Airways flight from La Guardia to Dulles is at 6:30
a.m. daily and the last is at 8:30 p.m.; the schedule from Dulles
is the same. Until Wednesday, a three-day advance-purchase fare,
requiring a Saturday night stay, is $98 round trip. Starting
Thursday, this fare will require purchase 21 days in advance, also
with a Saturday stay. The walk-up fare is $149 each way.
Information: (800) 428-4322. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ancient Thracian Art On View in Boston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They had no alphabet and left no documents about their culture.
Most of what is known about the Thracians, who, from the earliest
historical times, occupied land that is now part of Bulgaria,
northern Greece, western Turkey and Romania, came from the writings
of their neighbors, especially the Greeks and the Romans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancient Gold: The Wealth of the Thracians, Treasures from the
Republic of Bulgaria,'' which will open Wednesday at the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston, offers some more clues. The exhibition
includes more than 200 gold and silver objects, dating from before
4000 B.C. through 400 A.D., many of them unearthed since the 1970s
from royal tombs and burial mounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Archeologists have turned up highly sophisticated artifacts that
depict the Thracians as warriors, masters of horse-drawn chariots,
and skilled goldsmiths and potters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One jug in the exhibition, from the fourth century B.C.,
features two intricately gilded horsemen in trousers and chitons
aiming their spears at a boar, a detailed female bust and a female
head that attaches the handle to the body of the jug. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another vessel from the same era is shaped like a helmeted
female head, engraved with a Tree of Life and adorned with a sphinx
atop the handle. A third gold piece, from 1500 B.C., consists of
three ovoid vessels soldered together in an arrangement that
allowed liquids to be mixed and poured together through one spout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancient Gold'' also includes royal necklaces, rings and other
jewelry, armor, fancy horse bridles and adornments, chariot
decorations, and bowls and ceremonial objects. They come from 19
Bulgarian museums, and many have never before been out of the
country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ancient Gold'' will remain at the Museum of Fine Arts until
June 6, then move to the Detroit Institute of Arts, June 27 to Aug.
29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, 465 Huntington Avenue, Boston, is open
every day: admission is $10. Information: (617) 267-9300 or www
.mfa.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get Thee to a Nunnery With a New Italy Guide &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bed and Blessings, Italy,'' a new paperback ($16.95, Paulist
Press) describes 131 convents and monasteries that take overnight
guests for around $50 a person in Rome, $30 elsewhere. The authors,
June and Anne Walsh, say that most places are welcoming, but that
they are basic and generally do not take credit cards. The book can
be ordered from (800) 218-1903. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Easter Chase: Bring Your Own Basket &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the Easter season, children visiting New England have a
choice of historical sites for egg hunting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Newport, R.I., the Preservation Society of Newport County is
sponsoring its 10th Annual Easter Egg Hunt and Brunch on the lawn
at Rosecliff, the 1902 white-glazed terra cotta mansion built by
Stanford White and modeled after the Grand Trianon at Versailles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 10 a.m. next Saturday, two concurrent egg hunts will
be held: one for toddlers through age 5, the other for children 6
to 12. Prizes will be awarded to the lucky ones who find the 12
eggs, out of a total of 1,000, that bear the names of the society's
other properties. After the event, an informal brunch of eggs, ham,
fruit and muffins will be served to the children and their
parents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the event for nonmembers is $27.50, $12 for
children 6 to 12 and $3 for the 3 to 5 set. The event, with the
Easter Bunny on hand, will run rain or shine. Reservations are
required. For information, call (401) 847-1000, extension 140 or
150. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In North Bennington, Vt., egg hunting will take place on the
grounds of the Park-McCullough House. This 35-room Victorian
mansion, built in 1865, is operated by the Park-McCullough House
Association and serves as the community center. Sponsored by the
local Lions Club, the hunt for several hundred eggs will begin at
noon on Easter Sunday or, in case of rain, at the same time the
next Sunday, April 11. All ages are welcome, but the event is
intended primarily for younger children. Admission is free.
Information: (802) 447-7459. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Megan Fulweiler
</P>
