<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 PROPOSED ITALIAN BANK COMBINATIONS WIN FAVOR OF MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Share prices of two big Italian banks sought by domestic
rivals increased in value Monday, reflecting investors' delight
with the premiums that buyers will pay to gain greater size in
Italy's fragmented banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deals _ a stock offer upward of $16 billion by
Unicredito Italiano for Banca Commerciale Italiana, and San
Paolo-IMI's $9.7 billion bid for Banca di Roma, also in stock _
were both disclosed over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Banca Commerciale stock rose nearly 5 percent in Milan trading,
to 7.547 euros, or $8.23, after reaching an intraday high of 7.95
euros. Banca di Roma's shares gained 7 percent, closing at 1.512
euros.
</P>
<P>
   The offers mark the latest in a series of large-scale
combinations among European banks intended to strengthen their
positions for the rapid growth expected as the Continent's
financial markets effectively merge into one. Earlier this month,
Banque Nationale de Paris, one of France's largest, sought to
become the world's largest bank by assets by bidding for two
domestic rivals, Societe Generale and Paribas, and offering more
than $37 billion in stock. Other huge mergers within national
boundaries have taken place over the last year in Spain, Germany
and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's banking system has been particularly sclerotic, the
victim in the past of political intrusion, poor management and weak
or nonexistent financial services. But a decision by the Italian
government in the early 1990s to take the country's state-owned
banks public, new legislation on their independence and the
pressures of European financial unification have started a
transformation of the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the current deals, Unicredito will exchange eight of its
shares for every five of Banca Commerciale, at a 17.5 percent
premium based on Friday's closing stock prices; San Paolo will
exchange two shares for every 19 of Banca di Roma, at an 18 percent
premium.
</P>
<P>
   Banca Commerciale has yet to respond to the offer; Banca di Roma
told San Paolo it is studying the offer.
</P>
<P>
   If the Italian combinations succeed, they will create two big
banking groups _ one led by San Paolo as the nation's largest, with
$308 billion in assets, and the Unicredito-led group second, with
assets of $280 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What is notable about these banking combinations, as well as the
proposed deals in France, is that they are indeed confined to
national boundaries. Some analysts say that in banking, the
obstacles to large mergers and acquisitions across European borders
largely remain blocked by political interests, labor union
resistance and rigid bank ownership structures.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, while analysts agreed that the deals could help loosen the
Italian banking industry, they said further reorganization would
probably come within national boundaries before significant mergers
or acquisitions across borders.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hoge, European banking analyst at Credit Suisse First
Boston in London, said foreign bidders were discouraged by
political pressure that they go easy on in cutting jobs. And given
the low return on equity of banks in Italy _ an average of 5
percent _ the motivation for entering the market diminishes. Thus,
he said, with few exceptions, ``instead of outright cross-border
takeovers, what you'll see will be banks taking equity shares in
foreign banks'' without making full acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   That Unicredito and San Paolo should find themselves at the
vanguard of the action is not surprising. Unicredito, which wants
to call the new combined company Eurobanca, is run by Alessandro
Profumo, 42, a former McKinsey banking consultant who is among the
most aggressive modernizers in Italian banking. San Paolo, which
merged last year with the investment bank IMI, has long been a
force in the heavily industrial north of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Major institutional investors in the Italian banks welcomed the
combinations. Deutsche Bank, which owns shares in both Unicredito
and Banca Commerciale, called the proposed combination a ``positive
step, in view of the reorganization of the Italian banking
market.'' ABN Amro, the Dutch bank that earlier this month acquired
an 8.75 percent share in Banca di Roma, likewise welcomed the San
Paolo bid.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government also expressed approval. Prime Minister
Massimo D'Alema, speaking at a news conference, said, ``We have
followed these developments, having at heart the possible
invigoration and modernization of our banking system, which was
undoubtedly very fragmented.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
