<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ UNDETERRED BY CONTRACT TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez vowed this
winter that his contract status would not become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time American League most valuable player appears to be
correct in that assessment, and his white-hot spring serves as
proof.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was 2-for-3 with a two-run single and a walk in four
plate appearances in the Rangers' 3-2 loss to the Detroit Tigers
yesterday at Joker Marchant Stadium. That improved Gonzalez's
batting average this spring to .444 (16-for-36) with two home runs
and 11 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have a preoccupation with their contract,''
Gonzalez said. ``I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's representatives, Jim Bronner and Fernando Cuza, met
10 days ago with Rangers president Tom Schieffer and general
manager Doug Melvin in Port Charlotte, Fla., for what both parties
described as exploratory discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer and Melvin learned that Gonzalez wants to remain with
the Rangers beyond the 2000 season. Gonzalez learned that the
Rangers share that desire.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the parties did not discuss specifics on the length and/or
value of a contract extension, Schieffer said. Gonzalez will earn
$8.5 million this season, and the Rangers will likely exercise
their option for the 2000 season that will pay the outfielder $7.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez avoids conversations about his contract, but he said no
further discussions between his representatives and the Rangers are
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of my mind,'' Gonzalez said. ``It's too early to
worry about my contract. Baseball is the only thing on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said he concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan is committed to this game,'' Oates said. ``Guys, we don't
know half of what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez can be found most nights at the Rangers' Charlotte
County Stadium complex working with personal trainer Angel
Precinal. That commitment is seldom publicized.
</P>
<P>
   ``His prime years may be ahead of him,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make Gonzalez worthy of a contract worth more than the
one the Anaheim Angels gave first baseman Mo Vaughn, who signed a
six-year contract worth $80 million this winter?
</P>
<P>
   Could Gonzalez command more than the seven-year, $105 million
contract pitcher Kevin Brown received from the Los Angeles Dodgers
this winter?
</P>
<P>
   ``The best time to talk about a contract is the winter,''
Gonzalez said. ``Right now, it's time for me to play baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
