r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TRADES-TEX     03-22 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TRADES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL WILL WATCH WINGS FOR TRADES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barring a major surprise, the eyes of the NHL will be on Detroit
today to see if the Red Wings shore up their defense before the 2
p.m. CST trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche acquired Theo Fleury last month. The
Stars bolstered their lineup with the acquisition Sunday of winger
Benoit Hogue. The Flyers already had traded for winger Mark Recchi.
And the Phoenix Coyotes made a slick pickup in taking versatile
center Robert Reichel last week to answer a glowing need on the
second line.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel had a goal and an assist in his first game with the
Coyotes onSunday, a 4-1 victory against the Los Angeles Kings and
is expected to be in the lineup tonight when the Stars unveil a
lineup featuring Hogue on the second line at left wing.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it's time for the Red Wings to answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit News yesterday reported that defenseman Uwe Krupp
(who signed a four-year, $16.4 million, free-agent contract in the
summer) will not return this season and that his career could be in
jeopardy because of a back injury. That means, the Red Wings likely
will make a deal for a defenseman today. The problem is, the
high-quality defensemen available are themselves fighting injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Former Stars captain Mark Tinordi of the Washington Capitals has
been out a month and likely will miss the first round of the
playoffs with a broken foot. Ulf Samuelsson of the New York Rangers
is out two to three weeks with a broken bone in his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Both players were expected to be in heavy demand on the trade
market. But now, what do teams like the Red Wings do when they're
eyeing damaged goods?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very interesting place right now,'' Stars general
manager Bob Gainey said of the trade market. ``It seems like
there's still plenty of activity out there.''
</P>
<P>
   While no major deals were announced yesterday, there was plenty
of chatting among general managers. Gainey said the Stars have a
few calls out, but wouldn't specify more than that. With Hogue in,
the Stars still could try to swing a major deal for a second- or
third-line center _ going after the likes of the New York
Islanders' Trevor Linden or Claude LaPointe. Or they could simply
pick up a spare-part defenseman to bolster their depth in the event
rookie Brad Lukowich isn't ready for the competition level of the
NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could do nothing. After all, the Stars have the best
record in the NHL and already have addressed the one weak spot in
the lineup by acquiring Hogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we'll know \Rtoday\S,'' Gainey said coyly.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also will know what the rest of the league has.
Phoenix still is seeking defensive help. The Avalanche also could
use an extra defenseman. The Edmonton Oilers have been changing
their lineup every day after adding goalie Tommy Salo, defenseman
Christian Laflamme and forwards Daniel Cleary, Chad Kilger and
Ethan Moreau. The Calgary Flames have lost Fleury, but have added
veteran Tom Chorske, and the San Jose Sharks are said to be
flirting with Linden, Shayne Corson of the Montreal Canadiens or
Joe Juneau of the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks, Flames and Oilers are all potential first-round
playoff opponents for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, a hundred deals are rumored. Most notable are the
Flyers searching for another defenseman and the Ottawa Senators'
interest in Canadiens center Vincent Damphousse.
</P>
<P>
   In a minor deal yesterday, the Stars signed free-agent
defenseman Alan Letang from the Canadian National Team and assigned
him to the Michigan K-Wings. Letang, 23, likely comes with the
recommendation of Stars defenseman Doug Lidster, who was helping
coach the Canadian National Team before being signed by the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Letang was placed on waivers and sent to the Michigan K-Wings,
along with winger Jamie Wright.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
