<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTS-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND AMERICAN MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., N.Y.)  
 CHANGES COME TO CAMPBELL SOUP, TOYS `R' Us, PROGRESSIVE INSURANCE (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring has sprung and the change in seasons has brought a change
in the status of several accounts and assignments, with billings
estimated at $375 million.
</P>
<P>
   The largest shift involved the Campbell Soup Co., which is
reassigning media planning and buying for United States brands _
with billings estimated at more than $200 million _ to the Media
Edge in New York, the media services arm of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Those duties, for products like soups, juices and pasta sauces,
had been handled since 1995 by the Campbell Media Alliance in New
York, a media services unit set up by the TN Media unit of True
North Communications specifically to work for Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assigning our media activities to the Media Edge is a logical
extension of our partnership with Y&AMP;R,'' Tim Callahan, vice
president for global business development at Campbell in Camden,
N.J., said Monday. His reference was to Young &AMP; Rubicam
Advertising, a sibling of the Media Edge, which is one of two
agencies handling worldwide creative assignments for Campbell
brands along with the BBDO Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Campbell eliminated the advertising sibling of
the Campbell Media Alliance _ Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding Worldwide _
from its agency roster in November.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said the Media Edge offered ``some technologies and
modeling'' that ``will give us efficiencies and effectiveness in
our media.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Drexler, chairman at TN Media in New York, attributed
the departure of the assignment to a disagreement over
compensation. Of the approximately 35 employees of the Campbell
Media Alliance, he added, ``some have chosen to leave for other
positions and some who have expressed an interest in staying will
be retained and we will try to redeploy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Gordon, president and chief executive at the Media Edge,
said she expected to hire about 25 additional employees to handle
the Campbell media services. Rather than forming a stand-alone unit
for Campbell, she added, the duties will be handled within the
Media Edge the way the agency works for clients like the Clorox Co.
and the Colgate-Palmolive Co.
</P>
<P>
   Another change involved Toys ``R'' Us Inc., which dismissed its
incumbent creative agency, Kaplan Thaler Group in New York, by
eliminating the shop from a review on its account, with billings
estimated at $50 million. The dismissal came as the review, which
began early last month, was narrowed to finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Thaler, which had handled creative assignments since
March 1998, was eliminated by mutual agreement, said Warren
Kornblum, chief marketing officer at Toys ``R'' Us in Paramus, N.J.
Discussions were continuing about the status of the incumbent media
agency, he added, which is Quantum Media International in New York,
owned by Bohbot Entertainment and the Media Inc. unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Kaplan Thaler, president and chief executive at Kaplan
Thaler, has worked for Toys ``R'' Us for almost two decades there
and at J. Walter Thompson New York and Wells BDDP; she also wrote
the Toys ``R'' Us jingle that begins ``I don't want to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they feel they need a global agency,'' Ms. Kaplan
Thaler said, ``and that's fine. I wish them luck.'' This will
enable the agency to ``pitch some competitive accounts,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Three agencies seeking the creative account were also
eliminated: Bozell Worldwide in New York, a unit of True North;
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi in New York, part of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, and
the Playa del Rey, Calif., office of TBWA/Chiat/Day, part of the
TBWA Worldwide unit of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists are a team of two Leo Burnett Co. units in
Chicago, Leo Burnett USA, creative, and Starcom Media Services,
media; Deutsch Inc. in New York; Doner in Southfield, Mich.; the
Media Edge, and a team of two Interpublic agencies, Ammirati Puris
Lintas in New York, creative, and Western Initiative Media, Los
Angeles, media.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision is expected by the end of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In another change, Progressive Insurance is ending a brief
relationship with Arnell Group Brand Consulting in New York and
embarking on a review of its creative and media planning
assignments, with billings estimated at $70 million. Media buying
will remain in house.
</P>
<P>
   Moira Lardakis, a spokeswoman in Cleveland for Progressive, part
of the Progressive Corp., said Arnell, which had worked for the
company since August, was not among the agencies being invited to
take part in the review. Progressive will invite about 20 shops to
participate and expects to make a decision in the next two months,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   The review stems from ``an evolution in Progressive's overall
brand-building effort,'' Ms. Lardakis said, to focus on
``direct-response advertising and cooperative capabilities.''
Arnell, which has no direct-response operations, specializes in
brand- and image-building campaigns; its work for Progressive
involved introducing an elaborate campaign centered on driving
safety that licensed the movie character E.T. and included
sponsorship of the halftime show at Super Bowl XXXIII last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial mission was clearly image and awareness,'' said
Peter Arnell, the chairman at Arnell. ``The notion of going to
direct is a huge surprise, out of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have neither the expertise nor the interest'' in
direct-marketing assignments, Arnell said, adding that he suggested
to Progressive hiring Draft Worldwide in Chicago, a unit of
Interpublic that specializes in direct marketing, or Deutsch, which
has a direct-marketing unit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, David Pecker, who will soon become chairman and chief
executive at American Media Inc. in New York, is undertaking a
review for an assignment with billings estimated at $50 million to
promote the company's two weekly tabloids, The National Enquirer
and Star.
</P>
<P>
   The assignment, covering consumer and trade advertising, is
intended to help ``delineate the two brands,'' said Pecker, who is
finishing up as president and chief executive at Hachette
Filipacchi Magazines in New York, part of Lagardere Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Enquirer positioning is news you want to read about
tomorrow,'' he added, ``while Star is more celebrity-driven.''
American Media is being acquired by Evercore Capital Partners LLC.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker confirmed a report this week in the trade publication
Advertising Age that he had asked six agencies for proposals for
campaigns. The agencies, all in New York, are Arnell; Deutsch;
DeVito/Verdi; DiNoto/Lee; Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners, part of Saatchi
&AMP; Saatchi PLC, and Mezzina/Brown. A decision is expected in early
May.
</P>
<P>
   Pecker and Arnell have worked together on several projects for
Hachette Filipacchi magazines like Elle, George, Mirabella and Sony
Style. While ``Peter and I have been friends for a long time,''
Pecker said, ``we want to give everybody a fair chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
