<SLUG> BC-DOW-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY SECTOR AS DOW'S PARTY POOPER
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Put away the party hats, the bunting and the punch bowl. For the
moment, Dow 10,000 seems to be receding into the mists of what
might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after again brushing the magic number, the broad market
averages drifted downward. The Dow Jones industrial average lost
13.04 points to close at 9,890.51. In addition, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 2.28 points, to 1,297.01. The Nasdaq
composite index, which has been the top performing index this year,
lost 25.33 points, a decline of slightly more than 1 percent, to
finish at 2,395.94.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a momentous day, by any means. That the stock market
is struggling after touching the tantalizing 10,000 mark several
times in the last several sessions, however, makes some investors
wonder whether there will be more down than up for share prices in
the weeks ahead. Are the market's gains of the first few months of
1999 all there is?
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Dow closes above 10,000 soon, several strategists
believe investors would be wise to limit their stock market
expectations for the rest of the year. One reason is that bond
yields keep inching up, making those investments increasingly
attractive to investors. Monday, the 30-year government bond traded
at a yield of 5.57 percent, up from 5.52 percent a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps a more troubling reason to fret about the market's
immediate future is the recent weakness in technology stocks, a
previously dominant force in the bull's run. With the group
faltering, the continued strength of the overall market comes into
question.
</P>
<P>
   Technology's impact on the market looms large for several
reasons. Of the 10 industry sectors in the S&AMP;P 500 index,
technology is the largest. Technology stocks make up 19 percent of
the value of the S&AMP;P, up from just 8.4 percent 10 years ago. Of the
35 new companies added to the S&AMP;P index last year, 10 were
technology concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is a much bigger factor in the market than it is in
the economy. Though technology accounts for only 6 percent of the
nation's gross domestic product, companies in the sector produce 12
percent of the S&AMP;P index's total earnings.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise, then, that technology shares have been the
crucial fuel inside the stock market rocket of the last three
years. In that time, returns in technology stocks were not just
better than any other sector, they were roughly double those
produced by the next highest-performing group _ in last year's
case, health care.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this hot streak is on ice. The bellwether technology stocks
that led the market up _ IBM, Dell Computer, Cisco Systems, Intel
and Compaq Computer, among others _ are now well off their highs.
Intel is down more than 18 percent from its peak of two months ago,
and IBM is about 15 percent below its January high. Cisco has
fallen 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, concerns that Dell Computer may be shipping fewer
personal computers in the current quarter drove its shares down 5.9
percent, or $2.375, to $37.875. Kevin McCarthy, an analyst at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities Corp., cut his earnings
forecast for Dell in the April quarter by almost 12 percent. The
stock is down 30 percent from a high of $54.3125 on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   And worries that weak computer demand will keep Compaq Computer
from meeting analysts' earnings expectations has pressured that
stock. Compaq has fallen more than 38 percent in less than two
months. It closed Monday at $30.125.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, analysts are cautious about many technology
companies. Christine Callies, U.S. equity strategist at Credit
Suisse First Boston, points out that except for the largest
technology stocks, analysts' revised earnings projections in the
overall group are either flat or negative.
</P>
<P>
   Some investment strategists have argued that weakness in
technology shares will not hurt the overall market because other
industry groups, such as financials and capital goods companies,
will take over the market's leadership. The current fluctuations
represent a healthy sector rotation and nothing more, according to
these people.
</P>
<P>
   But Byron Wien, U.S. investment strategist at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, is not so sure. ``One thing that tech has going for it
is it's open ended,'' he said. ``The products and concepts are so
exciting, these stocks can keep going up multiple points a day,
weeks in a row. I don't think the potential of the financials and
capital goods companies is that great.'' Now that tech is no longer
driving the market, Wien believes its upside is limited.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime trader recalls another era when technology stocks
led the market up: the go-go years of the early 1970's. IBM, Xerox,
Polaroid and a technology conglomerate called University Computing
were among the darlings that helped propel the Dow Jones average
over 1,000 in 1973. One by one, they crumbled. And they took the
overall market down with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
