<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMCAST BUYING MEDIAONE IN A DEAL WORTH $53 BILLION
</P>
<P>
   Comcast plans to acquire Mediaone for $53 billion, creating the
nation's third-largest cable television company.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, has almost nothing to do with television. The
reason for the combination is the cable industry's race with
telephone companies to offer superfast access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE PRICES INCREASE SHARPLY
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have risen more than 8 cents a gallon in the
last two weeks, and experts expect further increases in the weeks
ahead. But although the increase represents one of the steepest
short-term surges since the Persian Gulf war, gas prices remain
extremely low by historical standards.
</P>
<P>
   Oil executives and ministers held clandestine talks ahead of an
important meeting of the 11-member Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries in Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET FAVORS 2 ITALIAN BANK DEALS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Banca Commerciale Italiana and of Banca di Roma, two
Italian banks whose proposed purchase by domestic rivals was
disclosed over the weekend, both jumped Monday. Alessandro Profumo,
chief executive of Unicredito Italiano, explained plans to buy
Banca Commerciale Italiana. The offers are the latest efforts at
combinations among European banks.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECTING PRIVACY ON THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   A nonprofit group that monitors online privacy policies scolded
but declined to pursue an audit of one of its biggest donors,
Microsoft. The decision comes at a critical point in the
negotiations between the United States and the European Union over
whether companies can police themselves in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   CLEARING COMPANIES PLAN TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Depository Trust Co, and National Securities Clearing Corp., two
critical pieces of Wall Street's behind-the-scenes machinery,
announced that their boards had approved a plan to combine.
</P>
<P>
   STRONGER FUND OVERSIGHT PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman, proposed strengthening
oversight of mutual funds by independent directors but stopped
short of offering more sweeping changes.
</P>
<P>
   ALL MAJOR STOCK GAUGES DECREASE
</P>
<P>
   Although cable television and Internet stocks gained, stock
prices fell over all, with the Dow Jones industrial average sliding
13.04 points, to 9,890.51. The Nasdaq composite index lost 25.33
points, to 2,395.94, as personal computer makers shares sold off.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 2.28 points, to
1,297.01.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices fell amid expectations that investors would
snap up a record $7 billion bond sale by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH CONCERN TO BUY U.S. FILTER
</P>
<P>
   Shares of U.S. Filter slipped 12.5 cents, to $30.375, after
Vivendi SA of France said it would buy the company for $6.2 billion
in cash. The two companies are a jigsaw-puzzle fit: U.S. Filter is
the largest global supplier of industrial water-treatment equipment
and services, while Vivendi dominates global municipal markets.
</P>
<P>
   COLGATE LOSES TAX SHELTER CASE
</P>
<P>
   Colgate-Palmolive lost a bid to gain tens of millions of dollars
in tax benefits through an offshore shelter devised by Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. The Supreme Court rejected its appeal without comment.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL SOUP REASSIGNS WORK
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup is reassigning media planning and buying for U.S.
brands _ with billings estimated at more than $200 million _ to the
Media Edge in New York, the media services arm of Young &AMP; Rubicam.
Stuart Elliott: Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN PHONE COMPANIES MERGE
</P>
<P>
   Four of Canada's smallest phone companies have agreed to a $1.86
billion merger to create a single competitor to Bell Canada for
eastern Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
