A0308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PATAKI-NYT &LR;      03-22 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GOVERNOR'S MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, March 23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his motivation, Gov. George Pataki made sensible
suggestions on Sunday about how New York City's mayor, Rudolph
Giuliani, should respond to the civic turmoil over the shooting of
Amadou Diallo by police officers. Part of political leadership,
Pataki said, is ``listening to criticism and responding
appropriately to criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Giuliani's responses have been in the right direction.
He has expressed his dismay at the shooting and reached out to the
dead West African immigrant's family. The problem is that the scale
of those responses has not been large enough. Moreover, there is a
public perception that Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir are defensive rather than open in their attitude. Safir
fumbled badly over the weekend by turning up at the Academy Awards
in Los Angeles at a time when the city council was in doubt whether
he would appear at a public hearing Monday on police tactics. He
did attend the hearing, and spoke of the need for ``dialogue'' and
``healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing is needed because the city's minority communities have
been wounded by fear of the police. A cross-section of elected
officials and civic leaders are joining the continuing protests at
Police Headquarters because they regard Giuliani's and Safir's
responses as inadequate to the depth of that wound. These two
leaders must move beyond their statistic-filled and rhetorical
responses.
</P>
<P>
   So far it has been the protesters, led by the Rev. Al Sharpton,
who have done a good job of reaching out and broadening their
message. The volunteers for arrest have come to include elected
officials, Jewish leaders, former Mayor Edward Koch and the Rev.
Floyd Flake, who has been one of Giuliani's most prominent black
allies. Monday 141 people were arrested, and although many are
political rivals of the mayor, their unity carries a message beyond
politics-as-usual.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani says Sharpton's motives are political and
self-aggrandizing, and he may have the same opinion of Pataki's.
But to say that politicians behave politically is to state the
obvious. What matters is whether they are right. In this case,
those calling for a broader, deeper show of mayoral leadership are
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
