<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-LEAGUE-GUN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man threatens Little League coach with pistol, is held for
evaluation
 &HT;    By Joe Brogan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A man who reportedly pointed a pistol
at the head of a Little League coach for five minutes Sunday during
an argument over a batting cage was ordered held Monday without
bail.
</P>
<P>
   John Skrandel, 28, was charged with aggravated assault after the
incident. A judge Monday ordered him to undergo a psychiatric
examination. Skrandel is scheduled to return to court at 9 a.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 players, ages 11 and 12, ran to safety after they saw
the gun, police said. No one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Skrandel, a recently-divorced attorney, was at the Osborne Park
batting cages with his 6-year-old son. Michael Adams, a Little
League coach, asked Skrandel to move to another cage because the
one he was using was the only one that could accommodate the Little
League pitching machine, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Skrandel refused and when Adams insisted, Skrandel attacked him
with an aluminum baseball bat, a police report said. Adams, a golf
professional at the PGA National community, blocked the bat and
threw it away.
</P>
<P>
   Then Skrandel went to a gym bag and pulled out a .40-caliber
Glock pistol with laser sights, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, 44, of Palm Beach Gardens, told police Skrandel went into
a combat shooting stance and pointed the weapon at his head while
screaming obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   A recreation league worker called 911 on her cell phone after
seeing the altercation. Skrandel unloaded the pistol before police
arrived and did not resist arrest, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams wasn't available for comment Monday, but his wife, Margie,
said her husband told her, ``I wasn't afraid. I knew there was
nothing I could do. It was out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Margie Adams: ``I think the ones who were terrified were
the kids. They ran everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' children, Amanda, 9, and Matthew, 11, also were there.
``They were so scared they were shaking all through practice,''
Margie Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Brogan writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
