<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-LVMH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING MAY INTENSIFY FIGHT TO CONTROL GUCCI
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The takeover struggle for the Gucci Group seemed to
intensify on Monday night when a Dutch arbitration court handed
down a mixed ruling that was described as a victory both by the
famous fashion house and its unwanted suitor.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing in the Netherlands, where Gucci is incorporated, was
requested on Friday by LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the
world's largest maker of luxury goods, after Gucci announced that
it had struck a deal to sell a 40 percent share to Francois
Pinault, owner of Au Printemps, France's biggest department-store
chain, to thwart LVMH's advances.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Arnault, the LVMH chairman, asked the court to
invalidate the Gucci-Pinault deal, and replace Gucci's board with
an independent overseer. At the same time, LVMH began an
$81-a-share offer for all the Gucci shares it did not already own.
LVMH has been pursuing Gucci since January, when it announced that
it had assembled a 34.4 percent stake in the company and demanded
representation on its board.
</P>
<P>
   The Gucci-LVMH battle has come to symbolize the kind of
unfettered takeover wrangling, intrigue and cross-border alliances
that are expected to increase in a more and more cohesive Europe.
Already, the phasing in of the single currency, begun in January,
is being regarded as a catalyst for recent big banking deals.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle for Gucci has pitted two willful French
billionaires, Pinault and Arnault, against each other for control
of a legendary fashion designer, which almost everyone regards as
Italian despite its corporate base in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Dutch court had ordered Gucci and LVMH
to negotiate a settlement, but on Friday, the day those talks were
to begin, Gucci sprang the surprise deal with Pinault, infuriating
LVMH.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a full day's hearings, the Dutch court rejected
the LVMH request to invalidate the Gucci-Pinault deal and rejected
the naming of an independent overseer for Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   But the court reinstated LVMH's voting rights as a Gucci
shareholder, which it had frozen in the earlier order. It also
ordered Gucci and LVMH to discuss LVMH's bid for all of Gucci's
shares, a ruling that set the stage for the takeover fight to
intensify.
</P>
<P>
   Domenico De Sole, Gucci's chief executive, called the rulings a
``total victory,'' since the court effectively rejected LVMH's two
central demands. He said Gucci would ``go through the procedure''
of discussing the LVMH bid, though he made clear that the Gucci
board was not prepared to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   James Lieber, an American lawyer who is senior vice president of
LVMH, said LVMH viewed the court's ruling ``with great
satisfaction.'' Reached by phone in Amsterdam, he said, ``Once
again, we have observed that the rabbits De Sole pulls out of his
hat are the source of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He welcomed the court order for a resumption of talks, and
argued that Gucci's ``board has the duty to get the highest
price,'' and that was clearly LVMH's. His company is bidding $81 a
share, compared with $75 from the Pinault group.
</P>
<P>
   But De Sole said the Gucci board was not required to accept the
highest price. Justifying acceptance of a lesser bid, he said, was
the management independence that the Pinault group had assured
Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't give up control,'' he added. ``They invested in the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   The next stage in the struggle, it appeared, would be for the
allegiance of Gucci's big institutional investors in the United
States. While these investors ``have been loyal to De Sole in the
past,'' Lieber said, ``they have indicated they wanted to review
the agreement'' between Gucci and Pinault.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, De Sole accused LVMH of attempting to sway the
views of investors, and said he had received firm assurances of
support from three major mutual fund groups _ Scudder, Templeton
and Harris.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH was dealt a further blow when Standard &AMP; Poor's said it was
placing LVMH under observation for a possible reduction of its
credit ratings because of the financial strain the bid for Gucci
would put on its finances.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci shares rose 10 percent to 73.7 euros. LVMH fell slightly,
while Pinault-Printemps-Redoute, Pinault's company, fell 6 euros or
4 percent to 144 euros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
