<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FINAL FOUR TEAMS, PATHS WERE DIFFERENT, GOAL THE SAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Some of the coaches have cried. Their players
have slapped high-fives, fashioned necklaces from the nets snipped
after winning regional championships and, as Connecticut coach Jim
Calhoun joked Monday, are nursing sore shoulders from
congratulatory backslapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no trouble getting our kids to class on time,'' Calhoun
said. ``They got there early to hear how well they did. I was just
as bad. I showed up for coffee early, too, to get my back patted.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State. Duke. Ohio State. UConn. Each team's story line
is as different as the four regions they traveled through to reach
the Final Four of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans bring Magic to Florida _ as in Magic Johnson. He
drove the bus to Michigan State's last championship appearance in
1979 and won the collision with Indiana State and a guy named Larry
Bird.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils (36-1) offer destiny. They have won four
tournament games by an average of 30 points and, in many corners,
have become locks to win their third national championship in the
eighth Final Four appearance for coach Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes are a fast-breaking advertisement for the second
chance. Their coach, Jim O'Brien, left Boston College two years ago
after a bitter dispute with administrators. Their guard, Scoonie
Penn, followed his coach, sat out a season and now shines as the
brightest Buckeye of all. His teammates were 8-22 last season and
have pulled off the most dramatic turnaround in NCAA history.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies are making history, crashing their first Final Four
after three regional final losses that had confined Calhoun to that
sports limbo called Unable to Win the Big One.
</P>
<P>
   Now forget all that because it has nothing to do with which team
will win it all next Monday in St. Petersburg, Fla. Human interest
doesn't win championships _ defense, dominant players and desire
do.
</P>
<P>
   And Duke leads in all three categories. The Temple Owls had
fewer turnovers and more second-chance points but shot just 42
percent _ a tournament high for Blue Devils opponents _ and lost by
21 points in the East Regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Elton Brand is the best big man in the country. Temple
coach John Chaney proclaimed Trajan Langdon the ``best pure
shooter'' he has seen in years. And National Basketball Association
scouts and executives said the freshman Corey Maggette would be the
top player selected if he decided to enter the draft. He's a Duke
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Scarier is that back in October, Krzyzewski told his players
that nothing short of a national title was acceptable. They not
only embraced it, but also believed their press clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be cocky or anything, but we're definitely a
championship-caliber team,'' Blue Devils forward Chris Carrawell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Closer than many care to believe is UConn. The Huskies (32-2)
beat bigger and underrated Gonzaga, 67-62, in the West final by
holding the Zags to 35 percent shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga outrebounded the Huskies by 47-33. These feats were
especially impressive because UConn's one true big man,
6-foot-11-inch Jake Voskuhl, spent important minutes on the bench
with foul trouble, as did its floor general, Khalid El-Amin, who
was 0 for 12 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies are deeper and more athletic than Duke. They go nine
deep; the Blue Devils spell their top five with scaled-down minutes
from Chris Burgess, Nate James and Maggette. ``Whoever says we
bring waves and waves of players didn't do well in math,'' said
Krzyzewski, who has been both amused and irritated by the
perception that his team is loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies also have blue-chip talent. The all-America forward
Richard Hamilton does more than score, though he had 21 points in
the regional final. He shut down Richie Frahm and handled the ball
while El-Amin was on the bench. When he is focused, El-Amin is a
better floor leader than the Blue Devils' William Avery _ though he
lacks the Duke guard's 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   In Voskuhl and Kevin Freeman, the Huskies boast a tough, smart
interior that has yet to be intimidated by some of the best inside
men in the country. They play in a league with talents like Ron
Artest and Tim James and will not shrink from Brand.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that the Big Ten representatives, Ohio State
(27-8) and Michigan State (33-4), earned their way to Florida. The
Buckeyes, especially, were impressive, upsetting top-seeded Auburn
and St. John's in the South. Penn and Michael Redd have been the
most impressive backcourt duo in the tournament. But getting there
may be enough of a reward for a young team.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Spartans are hard to get excited about. They
turned the ball over 19 times against Mount St. Mary's, let
Oklahoma and Mississippi stay in the game with them and withstood a
Kentucky charge.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State coach Tom Izzo and O'Brien have echoed Calhoun's
remarks that the Blue Devils are the best team in the country. But
all are hoping for what they call in boxing a puncher's chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are far and away the best team in the nation,'' Calhoun
said again Monday. ``But I haven't always seen the best team win.''
</P>
<P>
   And his Huskies have the best chance of connecting on that
roundhouse blow next Monday in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
