<HEADLINE>
NAVY ADMIRAL REMOVED FROM POST OVER AN AFFAIR
</HEADLINE>
   (wg) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two-star admiral in charge of the Navy's air
forces in the Mediterranean was formally relieved of his duties
Monday after an investigation found that he had had an adulterous
affair with a civilian and then lied about it to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Rear Adm. Paul (Scott) Semko, a graduate of the
U.S. Naval Academy who rose through the ranks over nearly three
decades, received a punitive letter of reprimand for violating
Article 133 of the Uniform Code of Military Justice, which
prohibits ``conduct unbecoming an officer.''
</P>
<P>
   The punishment stopped short of criminal charges, but within the
Navy's hierarchical system of promotion, a punitive letter of
reprimand almost always becomes an indelible mark on an officer's
resume that effectively ends his or her career in the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Though prosecutions of adultery in the military are relatively
rare, the case against Semko follows a highly publicized series of
cases involving sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a two-star Army general, David Hale, agreed to plead
guilty to eight counts of misconduct stemming from affairs he had
with the wives of four subordinate officers. In December, a
one-star admiral, John Scudi, agreed to early retirement at a lower
rank, with a reduced pension, and penalties including 30 days of
house arrest, after investigators accused him of steering $150,000
in government contracts to a woman with whom he was having an
adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials noted that the charges against Semko, though
serious enough to warrant punishment, did not involve other
accusations of wrongdoing, as with Scudi. The officials, who spoke
on the condition of anonymity, said Semko's relationship involved a
woman not connected with the Navy and, evidently, did not directly
affect the ``good order and discipline'' of his commands.
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by the Navy in Naples, Italy, said its
inspector general opened an investigation into Semko's behavior
``based on an anonymous letter'' received in January.
</P>
<P>
   Semko, who is married and has two grown children, took over his
command in May 1998. A pilot, he previously held several command
posts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said the affair had lasted some time during Semko's assignments in
the United States but had ended by the time he took command in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to adultery, he was accused of making false official
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Semko, 50, appeared on Monday before Adm. James Ellis Jr., the
commander of naval forces in Europe, in what is known as an
admiral's mast. Earlier this month, he was temporarily relieved of
his duties as the investigation continued; that was made permanent
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he will serve in Ellis' office, awaiting reassignment.
While he could theoretically receive another command, the officials
said that was unlikely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
