<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WATERED-DOWN RACISM RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, March 23: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By killing a resolution condemning ``the racism and bigotry
espoused by'' a white supremacist group called the Council of
Conservative Citizens, Republican congressional leaders have set
back their party's effort to be viewed as inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was proposed a month ago by Rep. Robert Wexler, a
Florida Democrat, but garnered only a small number of Republican
co-sponsors, including such New York lawmakers as Michael Forbes
and Peter King. They, at least, saw the need to distance the House
from the extreme group, which has cultivated connections to the
Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, and Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of embracing the resolution, Republican leaders
decided to kill it. To cover their tracks, the Republicans plan to
pass a substitute resolution Tuesday that contains a strong general
denunciation of ``all those who promote racism, anti-Semitism,
ethnic prejudice, or religious intolerance'' but omits any mention
of the council.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, pressed to explain his refusal to back a version of
Wexler's resolution in the Senate, gave dancing answers that
recalled his shifting explanations after news accounts exposed his
links to the council. To his credit, the majority leader has
condemned the racist views of the council, but he has resisted
repudiating the group itself.
</P>
<P>
   The original resolution gave Lott a new chance to sever his
connection with the council and ease doubts about his commitment to
fairness as the leader of the Senate. Sadly, he declined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
