<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAMINA WORRIES PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Right-hander Chan Ho Park came off a career
high in innings pitched _ then went to Bangkok, Thailand, and
pitched for his native Korea in the Asian Games. Korea won the gold
medal, Park's stature grew and now Park is concerned about the
adverse affects of all that pitching late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Park was loosey-goosey after his best outing of the spring, a
six-inning masterpiece in which he struck out six and allowed three
hits in a 4-1 win against the Kansas City Royals on Monday. But he
also knows something is odd this spring, and it's not just his
solid place in the Dodgers' starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good, but I'm worried for later in the season,'' Park
said. ``I'm ready so quick in spring training because I pitched in
the winter. It makes me worry that later in the season, maybe I'll
get tired too quick. That's why I'm trying to be more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Park is being touted as the No. 2 starter behind staff ace Kevin
Brown and is coming off a 15-9 season in which he pitched 2202/3
innings. But he's also a very different pitcher in the first and
second halves of the season. Park was 16-12 with a 4.09 ERA in
April, May and June. He was 18-10 with a 3.21 ERA from July to
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's going to have any trouble late in the
season,'' pitching coach Charlie Hough said. ``The guy is in great
shape and we, as coaches, can make sure he stays that way. We'll
watch his pitch counts and make sure he stays strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The year-round pitching isn't the only thing that could weigh on
Park as the season moves along. A contract talk is expected, though
it's clear Park doesn't want to talk much about it. He is two
arbitration hearings away from free agency, but already Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone and Park's agent, Steve Kim, have had
preliminary discussions about a long-term contract. Park is trying
to stay clear of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pressure,'' Park said. ``I don't want to think about
the contract during the season. I don't want to lose a game and
then think, `Oh, I have to sign a contract soon.' ''
</P>
<P>
   __ Keeping the rhythm: Right-hander Ismael Valdes has been the
best Dodgers pitcher this spring in every aspect, which is why he
wants to stay with his current routine. While many of the Dodgers
bolted from Dodgertown after Monday's game for a day of R&AMP;R, Valdes
asked to stay around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to pitch, so he's going to pitch in the Triple-A
game,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing in the minor-league game will enable Valdes to work
every fifth day, which has worked well so far. Valdes is 2-0 with a
0.71 ERA in four spring starts.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hundley watch: Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he's
thinking about using catcher Todd Hundley when the team travels to
Kissimmee on Thursday to face the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the latter part of the week,'' Johnson said.
``He's going to need to catch a few times. It takes time to work up
to nine innings.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Johnson said shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek, bothered by shin splints the last few days, should be
ready to play Wednesday against the Cleveland Indians. . . .
Right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna on Sunday came out of his
workout without pain, Johnson said, which is a big step in getting
him ready for the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
