<HEADER>
A0322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UGAWOMEN-COX     03-22 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGAWOMEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Dogs on way to San Jose
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ For the first 13 minutes against Iowa State Monday
night, Georgia played some of its best basketball of the season
with a trip to the Final Four on the line. And for most of the
remaining 27 minutes, the Lady Bulldogs battled their own sloppy
play and some feisty resistance by the Cyclones in the last stop on
the way to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lady Dogs held on despite a late Iowa State rally for an
89-71 victory in the Mideast Regional final to earn them their
fifth trip to the Final Four later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller won Mideast Regional MVP honors and scored a
career-high 33 points for Georgia (27-6), which plays either
Tennessee or Duke Saturday in a national semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   Coco Miller had 16 points, Pam Irwin-Osbolt had 15 and Angie
Ball had 11 for Georgia. Iowa State was led by 19 points from
Desiree Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (25-8), making its first trip ever to the Elite 8
after upsetting Connecticut on Saturday, doggedly fought back in
the final five minutes, applying a rare full-court press to force
Georgia into turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-point basket by Frese with 3:28 to play cut Georgia's lead
to 74-63, but Kelly Miller sank two free throws on the ensuing play
and the Cyclones threw an inbounds pass away. But Angie Welle
banked home a trey for a 76-66 score, the closest Iowa State would
get.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia had trouble making free throws, missing five of its next
seven, but Coco Miller canned two from the line, then pulled down a
big rebound on an Iowa State miss as the clock wound down under two
minutes. Georgia's Deana Nolan typified the chaotic nature of play
early in the second half, when Iowa State crept back to within 12
points, rousing nearly 3,000 Cyclones fans who made the trip across
the Midwest. Nolan picked up three fouls in 56 seconds, as Iowa
State went into the bonus within the first five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A jumper by Desiree Francis helped Iowa State close to 40-28 at
the 16:52 mark. The Lady Dogs also played sloppily, turning the
ball over in the open floor and failing to box out. But Iowa State
never found the range from the perimeter, and Georgia warmed up
enough to made a comeback nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Miller broke the Georgia record for 3-pointers in an NCAA
game, and buried her sixth trey with 12:59 to play for a 53-35
lead. Iowa State got only four free throws and a bucket in the
following sequence, and back-to-back baseline jumpers by Nolan and
Tawana McDonald made the score 59-37 with 11:03 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   It was very apparent near the end of the first half that
Georgia's biggest battle was going to be keeping the sharp edge
maintained over the first 13 minutes, when the Lady Dogs bolted out
to a 31-10 lead. Georgia made 13 of its first 20 shots, with Kelly
Miller hitting her first eight attempts from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Iowa State was a miserly 3-for-15, with Georgia's
ball pressure taking out the Cyclones' lethal 3-point shooters.
Iowa State made only two of nine treys, and went without a field
goal for 7:50 as Georgia kept the heat on.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa State began mixing up zone defenses toward the end of
the first half, and that confused Georgia, which missed six
straight shots as the Cyclones cut it to 16 at 31-15 on a drive by
Tracy Gahan with 4:26 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia also encountered foul trouble in the middle, with
McDonald and Angie Ball each picking up two personals, and its
inside game was ineffective against the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin-Osbolt hit two straight jumpers and Ball sunk one as
Georgia finished the half strongly, leading 37-22. Kelly Miller had
18 points and Irwin-Osbolt had nine at the break.
</P>
<P>
   Frese, who leads Iowa State with 17 points a game, was limited
to six, but her teammates shot only 25 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
