<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FASHION DESIGNERS' ANNUAL GALA SETS THE DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Council of Fashion Designers of America's annual
awards gala, until this year a highlight of New York's winter
social season, is now a late-spring event. The black-tie affair
will take place on June 2 at the 69th Regiment Armory, in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Fern Mallis, the council's executive director, had said earlier
that the new American show dates in February for the fall
collections would mean that her organization would have to move its
awards show, normally held in February.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the council expects finally to complete negotiations
to televise the show, sometimes called the Oscars of fashion. The
move has been in the works at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still in its final stages of negotiation, but it's going
to be on television this year,'' Ms. Mallis said. She would not
reveal details of the pending agreement. In the past, both network
and cable television representatives have come to the table. The
program will not be shown live, Ms. Mallis added.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to this year's dinner, for which 1,000 guests are
expected, will have the same price as last year's _ $1,500 each.
Tables, which will seat 10, will range from $15,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The honorees for the gala are to be announced at a news
conference on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Among the categories honored will be designer of the year for
women's wear, designer of the year for men's wear and accessory
designer of the year. Nominees for the Perry Ellis Awards for new
design talent in men's and women's wear will also be revealed on
Wednesday, but the winners will not be named until the night of the
gala.
</P>
<P>
   Starting last year, the design council began to allow its
members to vote on some awards, along with the usual panel of
retailers and journalists. These included the Perry Ellis Awards,
the Lifetime Achievement Award and the International Designer of
the Year Award. ``Designers said they wanted to have more
participation,'' Ms. Mallis said.
</P>
<P>
   Because it has been more than a year since the last awards, the
industry has voted on winners in most categories based on three
collections _ two from last year along with those shown in
February.
</P>
<P>
   It is now seeping into fashion that women who crave comfort in
clothes should not have to give up style, trends or designer
touches to get it.
</P>
<P>
   The moment seems to have given birth to Skye, a new collection
by Gale Parker, a former designer at Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker, who has a full head of vibrant gray-flecked hair and
crinkly laugh lines, is an interesting story.
</P>
<P>
   As a young girl of 19, she modeled for Valentino, and then
worked in design for Halston and Diane Von Furstenburg, and edited
at Vogue. She later fell in love and moved to California. There,
raising children and getting a little bored, she bumped into an old
friend, Joel Schumacher, whom she knew from his days as a window
designer at Henri Bendel. Schumacher, now a top producer, was then
still young to the film industry, but he secured several styling
and costume design jobs for Ms. Parker on his films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the movies to go to Ralph,'' Ms. Parker said. She
stayed with Lauren from 1989 through 1995, and has since worked for
the Limited and in her own consulting business until starting Skye
with Karen and Phil Sadick.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker is the designer, and the Sadicks help with financing
and running the company. The also own Chelsea Textiles, a home
accessories company.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker likes an easy, bohemian classic look for her
collection. There's a floor-length burgundy mohair and cashmere
cardigan over a matching dress, a velvet peasant top in rich
russet, a gray viscose quilted jacket with ornate frog closures,
and long skirts with the most elegant elastic waists you have ever
seen, beaded and embroidered with folkloric touches.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $120 to $800 retail, and Ms. Parker hopes to
have the collection available in stores soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
