<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SHALIKASHVILI-     03-22 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SHALIKASHVILI-SPI </SLUG>
  
 FORMER JOINT CHIEFS CHAIRMAN WARNS OF NATO CASUALTIES
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO has the ability to destroy much of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's military infrastructure, but had better be
prepared to suffer some casualities in the process, Gen. John
Shalikashvili, the retired chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Shalikashvili, President Clinton's principal military adviser
for four years until his retirement in 1997, said he will be
surprised if Milosevic holds firm and subjects his country to NATO
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But if he does refuse to back down and NATO is forced to act,
allied planes may find the skies over Yugoslavia much more deadly
than those over Iraq, he said in a telephone interview yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia's air defenses are well-integrated and very
formidable and could pose some problems for NATO pilots,'' said
Shalikashvili, who also served as supreme allied commander in
Europe before becoming chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   He said Yugoslavia has been able to study U.S. and allied
military tactics against Iraq and to prepare its defenses
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to compare this to Iraq, but Yugoslavia's defenses
are every bit as good, if not better, and we won't have the
capability to take out their command and control systems quite so
easily,'' the retired four-star Army general said. ``The Serbs have
had time to learn from Iraq and have had the time to take advantage
of what they've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalikashvili said Operation Desert Storm against Iraq marked
the first time that such a lethal combination of advanced weapons
and technology was used, including cruise missiles, stealth
bombers, electronic warfare techniques and precision bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that came as a great surprise to the Iraqis,'' said
Shalikashvili, who now lives near Tacoma. ``It allowed us to
operate with a great deal of latitude. If it becomes necessary in
Yugoslavia, the result will be the same in the end, but it will not
be as easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first few days, I think you need to go on the
assumption that you will suffer casualties. That's the only prudent
way to approach this.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalikashvili said one of his main concerns is that the Clinton
administration may have delivered ultimatums before it garnered the
necessary domestic support for its Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult when you're not involved day-to-day... but
what I always worried about is before you issue ultimatums or
threaten force, you make sure that you have done all your homework
and have the concurrence and support you need to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Monday took up legislation aimed at blocking funds
for any military intervention in the Kosovo crisis unless President
Clinton first obtained congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we go bombing sovereign nations, we ought to have a
plan,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, a sponsor of the
restricting legislation. ``There is no clear policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalikashvili said the task in Yugoslavia in some ways will be
tougher than Iraq because NATO is not going in to wage all-out war,
but to conduct air strikes and to coerce Milosevic to sign a peace
agreement. And it will not have gathered the massive assets
available for the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Serbian troops are currently sweeping through
Kosovo Albanian villages in what Shalikashvili said is probably an
attempt to destroy the Kosovo Liberation Army's command and control
system. He said it would be nearly impossible for NATO air strikes
to immediately stop the ground operation and ethnic cleansing in
Kosovo's scattered villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what you can do is make ethnic cleansing very costly,'' he
said. ``It has never been a question of going after tanks and
individual police and army units on the ground. I don't think
Milosevic would be terribly persuaded if you just shot up some of
his tanks. You've got to hit his high-value targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Those targets include the Yugoslav command and control network,
its air traffic control system and communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to use the same approach we used with Saddam
(Hussein, in Iraq),'' Shalikasvili said. ``If he comes out of his
box, you have to hit him hard enough to get him back inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalikashvili said the United States has ``painted NATO into a
corner.'' If Milosevic refuses to back down, the organization must
act if it is to maintain its credibility. Otherwise, he said, NATO
will end up like UNPROFOR _ the toothless U.N. Protection Force in
wartime Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of NATO will certainly not be enhanced if NATO
chooses not to take any action,'' he said. `I think it would set a
bad precedent if NATO without good reason backs away.''
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, Milosevic dragged out negotiations as
long as possible and usually was able to take the process to the
brink before backing down. Shalikashvili said he's probably using
the same strategy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic sees this as a good opportunity to wipe out the
opposition,'' he said. ``But it would surprise me if he chose to
proceed and for us to start bombing and, in the end, to allow the
destruction of all these high-value Serb targets. I don't think
he's that kind of man. He's gambling that we will give him enough
time to do what he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke would decide Tuesday
whether to continue talks with Milosevic, Shalikashvili said:
``That's one more day in which Milosevic can continue to do what he
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the retired general said, ``if anybody can bring
Milosevic to the negotiating table, it's Dick Holbrooke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
