<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-FASHION-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNERS HAD OSCAR JITTERS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Sunday, about 1:30 p.m. in Los Angeles, and Randolph Duke,
the designer, relaxed and triumphant, is having a pedicure.
</P>
<P>
   There are those designers who send armies of assistants to Los
Angeles to entice Oscar celebrities into their clothes, but for
those like Duke, Pamela Dennis, Mark Badgley of Badgley Mischka and
Kevan Hall of Halston, there is no surer way of getting their
designs on Hollywood's elite on its biggest night of the year than
by planting themselves in town days before the event.
</P>
<P>
   For these designers, Oscar night is a fashion Olympiad filled
with grief, 24-hour work days and, when things go right, gleeful
triumph. On Sunday all four of these designers walked off with a
prize. Most notably, Badgley Mischka dressed a newly romantic
Jennifer Lopez in a black strapless full-skirted silk gown. Duke's
catches included Kim Basinger, Minnie Driver and Geena Davis in the
silver-sequined dress she wore as a presenter. Ms. Dennis' big win
was Liv Tyler in her lavender strapless gown, and Hall dressed
Sarah Michelle Gellar, queen of the teen-age market.
</P>
<P>
   But getting to that point meant harrowing nights that ended at 1
a.m., followed by days that began at 3 a.m. Duke was trying to buy
some well-earned relaxation on Sunday, a few hours before the
arrivals at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion. ``Thank you,'' he said
as he bade goodbye to his pedicurist. ``It didn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that the same could be said of the previous four days he and
other on-site designers had spent luring stars into their clothes.
Despite creating temporary studios in glamorous hotels like
L'Ermitage and the Avalon in Beverly Hills, drudgery was never far
from hand. Hall flew directly into town from a fabric show in
Paris, and although he has a home in Los Angeles, he set up shop on
Tuesday in the L'Ermitage. It was crucial that potential clients
and stylists, who are conduits to the stars, could get to him
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's first order of business was to set up racks for the
clothes shipped from New York and to ready a VCR for a tape of his
collection. He also had to deal with the lighting. ``In a hotel
room everything is mood lighting,'' he said by phone. ``If you're
here to do business, you need halogens to really see the detail of
the gown better.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Mark Badgley touched down ``at the crack of
dawn'' and headed straight for the Four Seasons for a fitting with
Andie MacDowell, who was vacillating between two of his dresses.
``We talked about shoes and the jewelry,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Following his meeting with Ms. MacDowell, Badgley sped to the
Chateau Marmont hotel to meet with Ms. Lopez. She was not there,
but he left the dress he had brought from New York for her with his
assistant, Karen Handley. The next day, Friday, he was on a plane
back to New York, not knowing which dress, if any, Ms. MacDowell
would choose.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Miss Handley called him to say the dress fit Miss
Lopez, she liked it and so did Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, who
accompanied the actress to her fitting.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock edged toward lunchtime at L'Ermitage, Hall
observed, ``We didn't have breakfast.'' He and his publicity
assistant, Rebecca Lewis, had begun the day at 9 a.m. by readying
two dresses for the local tailor. They returned numerous telephone
messages from journalists, stylists and celebrities' press
representatives. ``These are calls I did not anticipate,'' said an
elated and exhausted Hall, who was joining the Oscar race for the
first time. He took over the design reins at Halston from Randolph
Duke last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to be here,'' Hall added. ``You have all the
gowns and suits here for the clients to really see, and you can fit
them and give them a lot of personal attention. Celebrities and
women generally love to work with the designer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Duke, now on his own, was on his second trip to the Oscars, and
he worked intensely with Kim Basinger on her white strapless gown,
even heeding her suggestion to change the fabric. Having parted
ways with his longtime publicist, Sandra Graham, who helped him
engineer an Oscar triumph last year by putting Minnie Driver in one
of his designs, Duke had his hands full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wound up working with everyone personally,'' he said later.
``The minute I picked up the phone I got a call-back.'' Duke, did
not, however, know what he was getting into in the case of Ms.
Basinger. At 8:30 a.m. Saturday, he comandeered a car to the Los
Angeles airport to pick up Ms. Basinger's altered dress sent from
New York by Federal Express. ``We had a little problem with fitting
Kim,'' Duke said. ``I asked for my seamstresses to come out to Los
Angeles, but they just couldn't. They're 60 years old. They have
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Duke met Rita Wilson, Tom Hanks' wife, for a fitting at
her house. ``It's amazing what you have to go through to dress
someone today,'' Duke said. ``It's like a fashion show: work, work,
work, try, try, try, look, look, look.'' But the publicity gained
by having a nominee or presenter wear one of his dresses was worth
every effort, he continued, adding, ``This can put fashion
designers on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   As evening came to Los Angeles on Saturday, the unexpected break
came for Hall: Whitney Houston wanted to try on his dresses, and
Hall took off in a flurry.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Houston took nothing from Hall. ``It was still
good,'' Hall said Monday. ``I got to meet Whitney and set up future
appointments with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's nightmares gave way to Sunday morning's insanity. At
1 a.m. Sunday, Ms. Dennis was on her way to the Beverly Hills Hotel
to see if she could offer something Ms. Houston might like.
``Someone was rehearsing, she didn't have a dress, we haven't eaten
all day,'' Ms. Dennis said later Sunday in a kind of
discombobulated frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dennis had a limited selection for Ms. Houston. The designer
had sent out several dresses for stars to look at, and some seemed
to be hoarding them. ``Do these people keep things to keep them
away from other people?'' Ms. Dennis asked.
</P>
<P>
   Foodless and sleepless, Ms. Dennis had answered approximately 70
messages over the weekend, at least half from accessory designers
urging her to push their wares with the stars. But they picked the
wrong designer. Ms. Dennis had a trove of accessories from her own
personal wardrobe for any star who needed them.
</P>
<P>
   In the wee hours of Sunday morning, Ms. Houston, a friend of Ms.
Dennis', had still not made up her mind about what to wear. Ms.
Dennis was on her way to the rescue with a full skirt with rose
trim and a tube top. ``I hope to God it fits,'' the designer said.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:45 p.m. Sunday, she made a second visit to Ms. Houston,
after picking up shoes for her at Barneys.
</P>
<P>
   It was just about this time that Duke was pampering his feet.
``I pulled my personal credit card out a lot of times,'' Duke said.
``I haven't seen anyone pull out a checkbook. Is it appropriate to
send them a bill? I don't know what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's pedicure was almost over. ``I just got a call an hour ago
saying Kim was wearing the white,'' he said happily.
</P>
<P>
   A weary Duke had chosen to skip the final Sunday fitting for Ms.
Basinger. He left things in the hands of Steve Chester, his
creative director, who called from the actress' house with the good
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like when an actress gives me something about what they like
and what's best for them,'' Duke said. ``Although some know better
than others, Kim is very involved, which I respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
