<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PROSPECT-LADN     03-22 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PROSPECT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROPS FAILING IN DODGERS FARM SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ There was a time when you could count on a
couple of things from the Dodgers: The team would be in the thick
of the division race and have one of the top rookies in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   From Jackie Robinson to Todd Hollandsworth, the Dodgers have
prided themselves on their farm system and its ability to produce
Rookies of the Year. The organization boasts 16 award winners since
1947.
</P>
<P>
   But after having the top NL rookie for five consecutive years
from 1992-96, the Dodgers have been shut out of the award the last
two seasons. On the surface this doesn't seem to be a big problem,
but it's a sign the farm system is beginning to show some cracks.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for the present and near future isn't good. Trades
have cost the Dodgers much of their young talent. Top prospects
such as Paul Konerko, Dennis Reyes, Peter Bergeron, Ted Lilly and
Wilton Guerrero were traded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The team's lack of depth in the system is illustrated by
Baseball America's rankings of the top 100 prospects. The rankings
are subjective but have the input of general managers and scouts.
The Dodgers' top prospect in those rankings is catcher Angel Pena,
listed at No. 41. He's the only Dodger on the list.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers must dip into the minors to replace an injured
player, there's little from which to choose. That's why the team
brought so many journeymen _ catcher Rick Wilkins, infielder Scott
Livingstone, reliever Greg Cadaret _ to spring training this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's where it needs to be,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said of the farm system. ``I think we have some help,
but we don't have the insurance you'd like in all areas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Kevin Malone is now the general manager, in large
part, because of his very, very strong background in scouting and
player development,'' club president and CEO Bob Graziano said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Malone's first actions was to reorganize player
development. Charlie Blaney, with the Dodgers 32 years including
three as vice president of minor-league operations, was forced into
retirement. Bill Geivett was brought in from the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays to take charge of the minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work harder than any other professional sports
organization,'' Geivett said. ``The people that we have must have a
passion for this. It must be their job, their hobby, what they want
to do. I won't be comfortable with our minor-league system until we
can reach down and grab whatever players we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the Dodgers' 24 minor-league coaches weren't asked to
return. On the scouting side, director Terry Reynolds was
reassigned. Ed Creech was brought in from the St. Louis Cardinals
to head the amateur scouting department. Also, Acey Kohrogi was
named director of Asian operations and Jack Zduriencik was named
director of international operations.
</P>
<P>
   There's also been a change in how the Dodgers scouting
department evaluates players. Instead of labeling a player as a
major-league talent, the Dodgers now rate their players in seven
categories, including all-star or superstar potential, utility
players and pinch-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Creech) is a quality evaluator,'' St. Louis general manager
Walt Jocketty said. ``There hasn't been a lot of change in the
organization and sometimes that's good. Sometimes you have to bring
change to bring in fresh ideas and fresh people. I think they're
taking a step in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   A strong minor-league system is paramount to consistent winning.
Look no further than the New York Yankees and Atlanta Braves. Those
organizations are built on the farm system, dipping into the
free-agent market to fill holes.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees needed extra outfield help down the stretch a
year ago, they turned to the minor leagues and Shance Spencer, who
hit .373 during the final 27 games, including 10 home runs.
Meanwhile, the Braves called up Bruce Chen to fill a hole in their
starting rotation. In four starts, Chen was 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the 1999 Dodgers have been built through the
marketplace. Of the 28 players expected to battle for a spot on the
25-man roster, 16 became Dodgers through trades or free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said the free-agent signings of pitchers Kevin Brown and
Alan Mills and center fielder Devon White were needed for the short
term _ and the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be successful you need that foundation in player
development, and right now we're just building that foundation,''
Malone said. ``We're not looking for the short fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think we're making these major-league,
free-agent acquisitions for the short term. They don't understand
that the truth of the matter is those signings were made as much
for the present as it is for the future. It buys us time to
replenish the farm system.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's come with a hefty price tag: Those free agents have
pushed the Dodgers' payroll past $80 million. It was an investment
in the future the team had to make if the farm system is to bear
fruit again. &QL; 
MAJOR PROBLEMS IN THE MINORS
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at top minor-league prospects who are no longer
with the Dodgers: &QL; 
__ Paul Konerko: Two-time L.A. minor-league Player of the Year . .
. traded to Cincinnati, which sent him to Chicago (AL), where he
will play every day. &QL; 
__ Dennis Reyes: Was 2-3 (3.83 ERA) in '97 and 0-4 (4.71 ERA) in
'98 . . . traded to Cincinnati, where he was 3-1 (4.42 ERA) and
will start in '99. &QL; 
__ Ted Lilly: California League (A) Pitcher of the Year . . .
traded to Montreal . . . will start '99 in AAA . . . should be with
Expos by All-Star break. &QL; 
__ Wilton Guerrero: Hit in high .280s for L.A. . . . traded to
Montreal . . . Hit .284 in '98 for Expos and will start in '99. &QL; 
__ Peter Bergeron!tab!OF!tab!21!dlim!Hit .317 with 33 stolen bases
for San Antonio (AA) . . . traded to Montreal . . . Set for AAA in
'99 and majors in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
