<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-EGYPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EGYPT, MRS. CLINTON PARRIES QUESTIONS ABOUT SENATE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Hillary Rodham Clinton deflected questions Monday
about whether she plans to run for the Senate from New York, but
said she was looking for a way to advance the issues involving
children and women ``I've spent more than 25 years working on.''
</P>
<P>
   With even shopkeepers here speculating that Mrs. Clinton might
run, she paused during a 12-day tour of North Africa Monday to
address questions about her plans. She repeatedly emphasized that
she was here to promote goodwill and good works, not her political
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with a lot of people in the last month,'' Mrs.
Clinton said of her consideration of a campaign, ``and I will
continue that when I return home. But right now I want to focus on
the issues that are really at the base of this very important
partnership and friendship between the United States and Egypt,
which I think is in the best interests, long-term, of the people of
both countries.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first full day of her trip, Mrs. Clinton hopscotched
across Cairo Monday at a pace that would exhaust many candidates,
let alone diplomats. She paid an hourlong call on President Mohamed
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt then stopped at a bazaar, an educational
center, a health clinic, a synagogue, and a church, squeezing in a
lunch and a reception along the way.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving on Sunday, Mrs. Clinton toured two mosques. She
is trying on this trip in part to encourage religious tolerance and
allay any suspicions of American regard for Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Of six questions from reporters, four dealt with the Senate
race, although Mrs. Clinton did not always choose to interpret them
that way. Asked about her ``future plans'' by an Egyptian reporter,
she responded: ``Well, tomorrow I'm going to Luxor.'' The audience
laughed and clapped.
</P>
<P>
   Trying another gambit, an American then noted that some people
who spoke with the first lady Monday told reporters that they hoped
Mrs. Clinton would run. What was her reaction? ``I have enjoyed
meeting all of the people that I've met so far,'' Mrs. Clinton
said, ``and we've talked about important issues that are really
critical to the lives of the people in Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a reporter asked the question head-on: Was the first
lady considering a campaign? Mrs. Clinton replied that she would
keep consulting people about it, but that for the time being she
was thinking about Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   But after a more roundabout question about the best way to
promote her ``global mission'' on behalf of women, Mrs. Clinton
became more expansive. ``I don't know the answer to that,'' she
said. ``But I do know that I want to continue speaking out on
behalf of the issues that I've spent more than 25 years working on,
having to do with improving the lives of children and giving more
opportunities of all kinds to people, particularly women, and
improving relations around the world, among democracies, and making
it clear that we have a lot to learn and give to one another in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Any way that I can continue to do that I intend to.
But the form that will take I really, I can't predict at this
time.'' Mrs. Clinton, who had previously issued only a written
statement and made an oblique public joke about the Senate race, is
considering a campaign for the seat to be vacated by Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, who is retiring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   During this Middle East tour, Mrs. Clinton is not visiting
Israel _ a stop important to many New Yorkers _ because, her aides
had said, it would be improper for her to go so close to the
elections there. She intends to visit Israel and Jordan later this
year, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
