A0481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPTON-NYT &LR;      03-22 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYA FALLS FROM NO. 1 SPOT AFTER LOSS AT LIPTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Carlos Moya, the world's No. 1 player, wore
an invisible bounty on his head along with his signature white
headband as he shuffled out to the grandstand court Monday for his
fourth-round assignation with the scruffy Sebastien Grosjean of
France at the Lipton Championships.
</P>
<P>
   But when Moya stalked away from the broiling court 2 hours 39
minutes later, he was no longer a marked man, no longer No. 1 and
no longer a contender at this bustling $4.6 million event.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Moya was the victim of a 3-6, 6-4, 7-6 (11-9) upset
crafted by a 20-year-old player in baggy shorts and a wrong-way
baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I win, but I win,'' said Grosjean, who
escaped three match points belonging to Moya during their madcap
tie breaker, then converted his own second match point with a
laser-like forehand down-the-line pass.
</P>
<P>
   Moya intercepted the pass, but his feeble backhand volley found
its way to the net and died without crossing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he was a little bit nervous,'' Grosjean said of the
loser, who was also a little bit contentious and exited the court
without shaking the hand of the chair umpire.
</P>
<P>
   Moya's premature demise guaranteed that second-seeded Pete
Sampras, who manhandled Albert Costa of Spain, 6-4, 6-4, at sunset,
will regain his No. 1 spot on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, a two-time Lipton champion who has not won this title
for five years, had thrown a minor tantrum when he learned that his
fourth-round match with Costa was scheduled for the grandstand.
Thanks to the interminable outing of Moya there, Sampras was
switched to the stage he prefers, the stadium, and took care of
business in 81 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras seemed more apprehensive about his coming quarterfinal
against seventh-seeded Richard Krajicek than excited about
regaining his ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said it once and I'll say it a thousand times, it doesn't
matter what you're ranked this time of year,'' Sampras said.
``Don't get me wrong; I'm pleased, but I'm more concerned about my
match tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is 2-5 against Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   When Moya, 22, the French Open's reigning champion, usurped
Sampras at the top by reaching the final last week at Indian Wells,
Calif., he responded to his first outing as a No. 1-ranked target
by faltering in that final against unseeded Mark Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   Here on this windswept tropical island, Moya faltered again,
this time battered less by his opponent _ whose hit-or-miss
flailing produced 81 unforced errors _ than by his own inadvertent
blend of tentative ball-striking and anxious mistakes. Moya
double-faulted eight times and had 72 unforced errors, an
unconscionable display for a topspin artisan like himself.
</P>
<P>
   The red and yellow Spanish flags that had waved so boldly in the
jam-packed bleachers during the first set were flying at
half-staff, and the spectators were marveling at the audacity of
this fleet-footed French scrapper in the same breath that they
mispronounced his name as ``Gross-jeans.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Frenchman did not seem to mind that nobody knew who he
was. Grosjean, who loves Florida so much that he intends to
relocate to Boca Raton with his wife, Marie, and 5-month-old baby,
Lola, just stuck his racquet in the air and applauded the crowd
with his free hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' he said. ``Here, I have pleasure to play.
This is my best win. It's great here.''
</P>
<P>
   In other matches, 16th-seeded Serena Williams, on a tour-leading
13-match unbeaten streak after capturing her first career titles
back-to-back at Paris and Indian Wells, pounded Magui Serna of
Spain into a speedy surrender, 6-1, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was serious, I stayed focused, I was motivated,'' said the
17-year-old Williams, who faces third-seeded Monica Seles in the
Round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Corretja, seeded fourth, was yet another Spaniard who had a
bad day at the Lipton despite his 12-4 record here.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja had a chance to claim the No. 1 ranking by winning this
title, but instead of advancing to the quarterfinals, he fell, 7-5,
6-3, to fourth-seeded Thomas Enqvist of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In another upset on the men's side, 30th-ranked Nicolas Kiefer
of Germany followed his ouster of fifth-seeded Patrick Rafter by
ambushing 12th-seeded Greg Rusedski of Britain, 4-6, 7-5, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   The captain of the United States Davis Cup team, Tom Gullikson,
has selected Jim Courier, Jan-Michael Gambill and the doubles
specialist Alex O'Brien to join Todd Martin on the squad that
tackles Britain, led by the top 10-caliber duo of Tim Henman and
Greg Rusedski, in the first round next month in Birmingham,
England. Gullikson's options were narrowed when Pete Sampras, Andre
Agassi, and Michael Chang deemed themselves unavailable for the
April 2-4 encounter, but he consoled himself with a positive
statistic. ``I will say that between Jan-Michael, Jim Courier and
Todd Martin, we have a 13-2 record over the two English players,
but there's a lot that goes on when putting together a team,'' said
Gullikson, who was informed by Agassi that he will never play Davis
Cup again because he is outraged by the USTA's dismissal of Dr.
George Fareed, the longtime team physician.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
