</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD DEED REPAID WITH APPARENT LOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (EDITORS: Dennis McCarthy is a Daily News columnist) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What's the old saying, no good deed goes
unpunished? You don't have to remind Mike Motazedi.
</P>
<P>
   His good deed was taking pity on a local homeless man a couple
of months ago and giving him a job.
</P>
<P>
   In January, I wrote about the kindhearted Motazedi, owner of a
suburban Woodland Hills 7-Eleven convenience store, and how he set
60-year-old James Cooper up in an apartment and bought him some
clothes while he was in training to take over the graveyard shift
at the store.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, around 11 p.m., police say, Cooper paid him
back.
</P>
<P>
   The store surveillance video camera caught Cooper making two or
three trips in and out of the store with his arms full of
merchandise, police said. Police arrived and called Motazedi, who
took stock: The safe was empty, the cash register was empty, and
cartons of cigarettes and other merchandise _ altogether valued at
around $3,500 _ were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Burglary detectivesfrom the Los Angeles Police Department's West
Valley Division took the videotape from the store as part of their
grand-theft investigation, said Detective Supervisor Roland
L'Heureux.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until around 3 a.m. Thursday that some of Motazedi's
night owl customers figured something was wrong when they walked
into the Ventura Boulevard store and no one was in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called the police, and the police called me,'' Motazedi
said Monday, still in a bit of shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurts, but it doesn't change my mind,'' Motazedi said.
``People need a second chance, and I'll continue to give them one.
Life sometimes isn't fair. Sometimes you win, sometimes you lose.
This time, I lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that hurts most, say Motazedi and store manager Daljit
Singh, is that Cooper didn't bother to lock up the place when he
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought we were doing a very good thing helping him,
but he obviously didn't think so,'' Singh said. ``We had no idea he
would do something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   When I talked to Cooper in January, he was extremely grateful
for the job opportunity while being very candid about his past,
including a stretch in prison 30 years ago for robbery, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him (Motazedi) about it, and how I lost everything to a
bad gambling habit in the '60s and early '70s _ my marriage, my
home, everything,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   He figured once Motazedi heard all the shady details of his
background, the store owner would say, sorry, but he couldn't be
trusted behind a cash register.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Motazedi hired him.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman was impressed that the homeless man never
hassled any of his customers, and was always courteous to everyone
as he pushed his shopping cart filled with bottles and aluminum
cans down the boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew was the man I had seen outside on the street, not
the man from 30 years ago,'' Motazedi said at the time. ``This man,
I felt I could trust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He promised not to gamble again if I hired him,'' Motazedi
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night he didn't show up for work. He asked for a second
chance, and I gave it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday night, police said Cooper paid him back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-22-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990322.0499 </DOCNO>
