<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIO-STATE-PENN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCKEYES RISE TO MEET PENN'S EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Scoonie Penn's October utterance is rehashed in coming months
and years, no doubt it will take its place somewhere a notch below
Babe Ruth's called home run or Joe Namath's Super Bowl prediction.
</P>
<P>
   No, Penn did not actually predict before the season that Ohio
State would be in the Final Four and contemplating a semifinal
matchup against Connecticut. He merely suggested that this team's
goal should be higher than the stated mark set by coach Jim O'Brien
_ which was just to have a winning season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had five consecutive losing seasons,'' O'Brien told the
media the day before practice began. ``I think realistically before
you start talking about postseason play and the NCAA Tournament,
you have to establish that you're going to win more than you
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Not good enough, said Penn, who sat out an 8-22 season in
O'Brien's first year in Columbus, Ohio, after, in effect, following
him from Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make the NCAA Tournament,'' Penn boldly stated.
``That's realistic to me and the rest of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates took more the line of their coach. But as March
has revealed, O'Brien has been forced to admit that James
``Scoonie'' Penn's foresight was 20/20.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he made that comment,'' O'Brien said, ``I was one who
thought he was crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, my whole feeling was that I just wanted us to be
better than we were a year ago. Scoonie's mentality was that he had
played in two NCAA Tournaments at Boston College, and he felt that
when March comes around, you play in the tournament. He obviously
knew more about what was going on than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State not only landed a tournament berth for the first time
since the Jim Jackson era (1990-92), but finds itself in the Final
Four for the first time since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes finished second in the Big Ten to Michigan State,
forging a 12-4 record after winning only one conference game the
previous season. Their turnabout was the program's best ever. Penn
became the Big Ten player of the year. O'Brien was the popular
choice as coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes have surprised even their 5-foot-9 junior point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't put us in the Sweet 16,'' Penn said. ``I was just
hoping we would make the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn said his belief that his team was better than modest
preseason hopes was validated in December by victories against
Alabama-Birmingham, North Carolina State and Mississippi to win the
Puerto Rico Holiday Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a turning point for us,'' he said. ``We won
three tough games in a row, and the guys became confident we could
do some things. We came together and started the season off
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes have two big-time tournament players in their guard
combination of Penn and Michael Redd, who many believed was
deserving of more than second-team Big Ten honors. But they also
have a freshman guard, Brian Brown, who plays like a winner, and
two very good role players _ forward Jason Singleton and center Ken
Johnson, who was MVP of the South Regional championship victory
against St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   They are all very athletic and appear capable of matching
semifinal opponent Connecticut in that department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their strength is the way they play together,'' St. John's
coach Mike Jarvis said. ``All five of their players are really good
at defensive help. They cover very well, use their athletic
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a very deceptive team. We may have underestimated
their physical ability. They get to loose balls very quickly, they
have good hands, they all jump well. They're strong. And I don't
know if we've played a better backcourt all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn is the catalyst, the newcomer. Redd is the established
go-to player, and there has nothing but compatibility between the
two, a key to this team's chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoonie brought a different attitude to this program,'' Redd
said. ``He's been a winner all his life. He brought us another
scoring weapon and a lot of leadership. This has been a dream
season for us, a total turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn is not making any Final Four predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often you get opportunities like this,'' he said.
``We've got to take full advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens Saturday in St. Petersburg, Fla.,
O'Brien says this will remain a season he'll not forget. And that
some might say the fourth-seeded Buckeyes don't belong in a Final
Four with three No. 1 seeds doesn't phase him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I am thankful for is for the opportunity to get to
Ohio State, but more importantly, to coach this group of kids,'' he
said. ``They're respectful and they've done everything we've asked
them all year long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're party crashers at the Final Four or not.
We'll just have to see what happens. Nothing that happens now can
change the way I feel about this season. But the thing I've talked
to the team about is, let's don't settle for what we've
accomplished. Maybe we can get a little more.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
