<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING, DEPLETED NETS ROLL TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Jayson Williams smiled as he watched
Stephon Marbury skidding around the court, hitting an assortment of
shots from inconceivable angles in the fourth quarter, putting the
finishing touches on one of the New Jersey Nets' few happy nights
this season.
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to get excited about the team's future as Marbury
had 31 points and 12 assists to lead the Nets over the Toronto
Raptors, 106-87, at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But for Williams, who is trying to live up to his $100 million
contract, every rebound he grabbed (15) and every shot he blocked
(four) meant a clenched jaw and a wince of pain.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams left the floor in the third quarter with his
fourth foul, he was greeted by teammates who celebrated his fourth
blocked shot. But he carefully extended only his right hand, trying
to salvage the ligament damage in his left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game Williams sat at his locker with his left hand
encased in protective padding. He said he would not give up on a
lost season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it can be turned around,'' Williams said. ``Just
as easy as we lost so many, we can win with the homestretch going
on. I've got to say glass is half full because I think we're going
to turn this thing around.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Don Casey, with little else to turn to, is hoping that
Williams is able to play through the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will get to that point,'' Casey said. ``If
the team is involved and competing, it's important for the
franchise to finish strong, to still compete to set the tone for
the future. Unless it's threatening to his future, to pump some
life into this, I expect him to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams wasn't the only Nets player hurting. Scott Burrell
chipped a bone in his right foot in Sunday's loss at Cleveland and
will be out about 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Rony Seikaly, after playing Sunday with inflammation of the
plantar fascia of his right foot, was on the sideline again Monday
night. And Jim McIlvaine was placed on the injured list Monday with
torn cartilage in his left shoulder, and will undergo arthroscopic
surgery on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Chris Carr scored 24 points and Jamie Feick, a
free agent signed earlier in the day, played a solid inside game.
</P>
<P>
   Like Carr _ who played just eight minutes in his first four
games with the team but who has become a regular part of the
rotation in the last two games as well as the team's most dangerous
scorer _ Feick stepped into a Nets uniform and found himself on the
floor for 27 minutes and he grabbed eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   With the 6-foot-8-inch, 255-pound Feick the team's lone big man
off the bench with only eight players dressed tonight, Williams
knows that he is being counted on. But he said that he would meet
with a hand specialist, Dr. Charles Melone, this week to assure
himself that he is not risking further damage by playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's come to a point where I can't even get a good night's
sleep anymore,'' Williams said. ``I've been here since about 1:30
this afternoon. This is the most pain I've ever played in. I don't
want to ever do this again. I'm going to meet with Charlie one day
again this week, make sure I'm not doing any further damage because
now it even hurts when I run, the vibration. It's not getting any
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there is pressure on me, you know, not to lie. When you
are the highest-paid player, you get all the blame. But that's part
of the job, so I've got to keep playing. People don't understand.
You get out here and it's, whew.''
</P>
</TEXT>
