<HEADER>
A0490 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1STLD-     03-22 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ENVOY HEADS LAST-DITCH EFFORT ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for general rewrite. Incorporates statements from Holbrooke.
Changes ``Tuesday'' to ``Monday'' in 6th graf.) (mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Under orders not to let Serbia delay NATO
action while Kosovo burns, an American diplomat struggled early
Tuesday to negotiate at least a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The American negotiator, Richard Holbrooke, met with President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia for more than three hours in a
last-ditch effort to resolve the Kosovo crisis and forestall NATO
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke then returned to the American Embassy for nearly three
hours of consultations with Washington and NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke met reporters at a Belgrade hotel in the middle of the
night, and said, ``I would be misleading you if I suggested that
today's talks resulted in any substantial significant change in the
situation.'' He added that the heightened military activities in
Kosovo ``make it extremely difficult to pursue peace.'' He said he
would assess the situation later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is engaged in a large offensive against the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army, and Washington and the West say NATO will
bomb Serbian military targets if Milosevic does not agree to a
NATO-led force to monitor a peace settlement in the province. The
NATO plan calls in effect for self-rule in Kosovo, but the province
would remain a sovereign part of Serbia, which is part of
Yugoslavia, for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces have already destroyed three of the Kosovo
Liberation Army's seven regional headquarters, a senior NATO
official said on Monday, adding urgency to the Holbrooke mission.
Milosevic has been told by his generals, the official said, that
Yugoslav troops could complete their sweep by Friday, destroying
the rebels' command and control. The Serbs also burned villages and
drove civilians from their homes in the province, whose population
is predominantly ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's mission ``is a last-ditch effort, and it's got to be
quick,'' the NATO official said. ``We want a quick determination
from Holbrooke about whether we're at the end of the process or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   If the talks break down, Washington and NATO have promised
severe military punishment for Milosevic. The Yugoslav leader,
while sounding tough, typically waits until the last moment to make
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton warned that military
action could be imminent. ``If President Milosevic continues to
choose aggression over peace, then NATO's military plans must go
forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said 30,000 more ethnic Albanians have been displaced
from their homes in the last few days. ``We cannot allow President
Milosevic to continue the aggression with impunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO official said that without at least a verifiable
cease-fire in Kosovo, there was little point in further talking.
``The last thing we want is to have Milosevic tie up Holbrooke with
fake negotiations while the Serbs clear up in Kosovo,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized the comment by NATO's supreme commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark, that air strikes could occur ``within hours,'' and
said, ``Some allies feel strongly that every day is a lost day.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO air strikes would be intended to destroy Yugoslavia's
integrated air defense system and then to send fighters and bombers
to hit Serbian military targets.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether NATO would thus be acting as the Kosovo Liberation
Army's air force, which Western officials had said was not their
goal, the official said: ``The KLA, whatever else they've done,
have signed the peace agreement. So we have a bit of a moral
obligation to the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian offensive followed the sudden withdrawal on Saturday
of the 1,400 unarmed verifiers of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe. Asked if their rapid removal from the
province was not an invitation to Milosevic to attack, the official
said many NATO members had been pressing for air strikes to begin
immediately, with no final Holbrooke mission.
</P>
<P>
   But some concerns within NATO, especially from the Italians,
combined with criticism from the American Congress, argued for
longer consultations and a last chance for Milosevic to change his
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian military campaign of the last few days has served to
harden solidarity in NATO about the need for air strikes, and has
allowed the Americans to push for a more intensive set of strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Washington argued that initial cruise missile strikes intended
to destroy Yugoslavia's sophisticated air defense should be
followed _ without pause _ by intensive fighter and bomber attacks
on Serbian military positions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, if there was a pause, the Americans said, Milosevic
would succeed in his aims to damage the rebels seriously while NATO
could appear to be standing by. That new discussion in NATO
required further time, the officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was only on Monday that NATO nations gave the alliance's
secretary- general, Javier Solana, the authority to order expanded
air strikes on ``a much more diverse target list, a much more
intensive pace of operations and an expanded geographical zone,'' a
NATO official told reporters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The official also said NATO was urging the Kosovo guerrillas to
refrain from ``murder and bombing'' _ like the ambush of four
Serbian policemen in downtown Pristina on Sunday night _ that would
justify further Serbian attacks. There were two more bomb attacks
on Monday night on bars in Pristina, with at least one dead and
eight wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Before Holbrooke's meeting with Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president met with the three chairmen of the suspended peace talks:
Christopher Hill of the United States, Wolfgang Petritsch of the
European Union and Boris Mayorsky of Russia. The meeting, which was
limited to a discussion of the political side of the Kosovo
agreement, did not go well, said officials at the meeting, which
lasted 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was emotional and lively,'' said Petritsch. They wanted to
give Milosevic an accurate account of the political arrangements,
fearing that he had misinformation. When Milosevic called the
ethnic Albanians ``terrorists and separatists,'' Petritsch said,
``Well, after they signed the agreement, you can only call them
Albanian autonomists.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke concentrated on the damage NATO was about to do to
Milosevic's army and government if Belgrade's position did not
change and the offensive stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting Milosevic, Holbrooke made a direct appeal to
Yugoslavia's people to accept foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers ``would protect both the Albanian and Serb
communities from the kinds of violence, indiscriminate and
unnecessary violence, which has been taking place,'' Holbrooke told
an independent television production company, Anem. ``This force
would be for the benefit of all people in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Monday in Brussels, after talks with NATO leaders and
the British, French and German foreign ministers, Holbrooke said,
``We are not _ and I cannot stress this too highly _ going to get
into a talk-while-fighting-intensifies situation in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   He said NATO was ``on the brink'' of military action. ``It is
not too late to avoid it, but the window is narrowing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said, ``We think that this is the moment of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO is being careful not to claim that the goal of any
bombing is to force Milosevic back to the bargaining table.
Instead, NATO officials are insisting that the only goal of air
strikes is to ``degrade'' Serbia's military ability to inflict harm
on the Kosovo Liberation Army and innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   It is the human tragedy that provides NATO its legal
justification to bomb a sovereign country, especially in the
absence of any U.S. Security Council resolution authorizing
military action.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian officials kept up a defensive, wounded tone, and called
in Western ambassadors to the Foreign Ministry to protest the
possibility of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Milan Milutinovic, the Serbian president, said Serbs were ready
to defend themselves if the West tried to impose a solution in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want war,'' he told the Greek newspaper Ethnos. ``We
are seeking a peaceful resolution. But if someone attacks us, or if
someone imposes, then of course we will fight for our homeland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
