<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGAN-STATE-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG BLUE STOP SIGN ON SPARTANS' TITLE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news conference featuring Michigan State's Tom Izzo had
frittered down to its final question on Sunday night. Izzo was
almost out of his chair, eager to return to the Spartans' delirious
locker room at the Trans World Dome in St. Louis. But then that
daunting four-letter word was uttered. Duke. Coach, what about
playing Duke?
</P>
<P>
   Izzo laughed, claiming that he had hoped to escape without
discussing Duke and instead revel in the draining 73-66 victory
over Kentucky for at least one day. Even one hour. Realistically,
Izzo was only teasing about avoiding the most obvious of questions.
He knew the Duke question was going to come one minute after
Michigan State prevailed, and he knows the queries will hound the
underdog Spartans until the teams tangle on Saturday at the Final
Four in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   After snatching the Midwest Regional championship, the Spartans
got to cut the nets and go to bed dreaming about Duke. Were
blindfolds included? Now that the Spartans fulfilled a Final Four
dream that had not happened in East Lansing, Mich., since Magic
Johnson's team won the national title 20 years ago, they must
figure out how to choreograph what would be a monumental upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that Duke is as good a team as there's
probably been in the NCAA tournament in a lot of years,'' Izzo
said. ``But I'm not going to throw in the towel. We're going to try
to do the things we do and show up next Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Spartans talked about the impromptu midnight workouts
that bonded them this season, about the rugged style that they have
utilized and about the faraway hopes of a championship that they
all harbored, their party was interrupted with mentions of Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils stifled Michigan State, 73-67, on Dec. 2 in
Chicago, in a game Duke led by as many as 21 points. Mateen Cleaves
was asked if he had been itching for a rematch. The muscular point
guard shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a shot at them,'' Cleaves stressed. ``You don't
want to play Duke, but we'll play them. They're a tough team.
They're hard to scout because they got a team filled with
all-Americans. They all do something. They play together, and they
have good chemistry. It's hard to beat teams like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, echoing his coach almost verbatim, Cleaves said, ``We're
going to show up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It will be blue collar against Blue Devils. It will be sturdy
versus smooth. It will be the No. 1-seeded team from the Midwest
against the No. 1-seeded team from the East. It will be the
Spartans (33-4), who have won 22 straight, trying to shock the Blue
Devils (36-1), who have won 31 in a row and taken games by an
average of more than 25 points. Do the Spartans have to be perfect
to advance to Monday's title game?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to play a real good game to beat them,''
Andre Hutson said. ``You can't make too many mistakes. Duke
capitalizes on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutson realizes that Duke's prowess makes magical Michigan State
a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why a lot of people don't expect us to win,'' he
said. ``We're not filled with all-Americans and players you've
heard of, and we don't have a great history of winning every year.
It's expected for the doubters to be doubting us.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Blue Devils throttled Michigan State more than three
months ago, they made 24 of 41 shots from the field (58.5 percent),
while the Spartans made just 27 of 70 (38.6 percent). Cleaves was
the main culprit in the brick session with a 3-for-17 effort, which
cannot happen again if the Big Ten school is to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, a round-faced junior with a hop in his step and Johnson
as a mentor, is the undisputed leader of the Spartans. Befitting
the Spartans, he has the sort of ugly jump shot that belongs in a
YMCA, but Cleaves is tough on defense, unselfish and clever on
offense and a player whose decent statistics do not tell the tale
of his value.
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing 7-of-11 shots against Kentucky, Cleaves was
involved in three of the game's most crucial plays. He nailed a
3-pointer two seconds before halftime to give the Spartans
momentum, he hoisted a football pass to Hutson put them ahead to
stay with 7 minutes 30 seconds remaining and he boosted the lead
with another 3. If the Spartans somehow stun the Blue Devils,
Cleaves will surely guide them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got confidence in my team,'' said Cleaves, embracing the
notion of playing Duke. ``It's great for people not to believe in
us because we believe in ourselves. That's what we have to keep
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
