<SLUG> BC-BKW-PURDUE-RUTGERS-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE PULLS RANK AGAINST RUTGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ZACH BURGESS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAL, Ill. _ It was one of those times when all the right
things had been done. Great defense, clutch shooting. Rutgers Coach
C. Vivian Stringer could not have asked for more from her team.
</P>
<P>
   But the rumblings of a great team in the making would have to
wait another year. For the second consecutive year in the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament, Rutgers ran into the
No. 1 team in the nation. For the second consecutive year Rutgers
came home short of its goal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite long stretches of flawless basketball, Rutgers managed
to self-destruct while Purdue found its game. The result was a
75-62 victory for the Boilermakers before a rousing crowd of 8,844.
The victory advanced Purdue to the Final Four, where it will play
the winner of the West Regional final between UCLA and Louisiana
Tech, which was being played later Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers was leading by 53-49 with 6 minutes 26 seconds to play
in the game, but Purdue put on a late surge behind Ukari Figgs and
Stephanie White-McCarty. They scored all of Purdue's points in an
11-0 run to put the Boilermakers in command, 60-53. White-McCarty
finished with 22 points and was named the regional's outstanding
player. Figgs scored 18 points, 13 in the final 6:33 in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers was led by Shawnetta Stewart, who kept the Knights in
the game with 9-for-22 shooting and finished with 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to win,'' Stringer said. ``We had
balance inside and outside. But we said before the game if Cooper
scores a lot, it's going to put more pressure on us. We felt Cooper
could not show up. They, Purdue, did what they had to do. They went
to the basket and got to the foul line, but we shot ourselves in
the foot. That's basically it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to Purdue's Camille Cooper, the inside threat
who made 8-of-9 attempts and finished with 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had momentum for the whole game, but let it get away in the
last three minutes,'' Stewart said. ``We turned the ball over. We
let it slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Stringer can take pride in taking her team to the final
eight in four short years. And she can boast that she is building a
solid program.
</P>
<P>
   From the time Stringer took over the Rutgers basketball team,
she made her goals for the program known. Rutgers was not going to
be another Big East school laboring in the shadows of Connecticut.
And even though she will have to wait another year before she can
possibly get Rutgers here again, she can start to see her vision
coming true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not claiming that we're altogether there now,'' Stringer
said. ``But what I am saying is that we certainly have grown. We're
not the same freshman team that we were. I think that Purdue ...
being No. 1 ... we live in shock. The babies have grown up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Early on, Rutgers did what had got it here in the first place
and it looked as if Purdue's 29-game winning streak would come to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights played a defense so suffocating, so stingy
and so frustrating that the best team in the nation looked as if it
would self destruct under the relentless pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Rutgers match-up zone was too much to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue was held below its season average in the first half,
shooting 34.8 percent from the field, while Rutgers was a
remarkable 53.6 from the field in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers began the game by pounding the ball inside. But Purdue
made a run to go up 14-8 with 10:26 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers came back to tie the score at 14-14, went on a run to
take a lead of 34-26.
</P>
<P>
   But Purdue opened the second half with a 7-0 run to close within
33-34 on Cooper's 3-point play at 17:21.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cooper added another layup at the 15:18 mark, which closed
Purdue's deficit to 35-37. At that point, Cooper had scored the
last seven Purdue points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
