<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-BROADBAND-NY     03-22 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BROADBAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING TO FORCE A GIANT TO SHARE ITS VITAL LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also CABLE-MERGER, CABLE-MERGER-IMPACT) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ As two giant cable television companies were
justifying their merger as key to competing in the high-speed
Internet access business, executives of Internet companies
attending a computer conference here were sparring over how open to
competition cable modem services and other so-called broadband
products should be.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the debate was the insistence by a coalition of
Internet service providers that AT&AMP;T open up the broadband cable
network the long-distance giant acquired with its recent purchase
of Tele-Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   With telephone and cable companies eager to grab a portion of
each other's business and establish a solid foothold in the
high-speed data, or broadband, business, companies like America
Online and Mindspring Inc., which were built on offering consumers
dial-up access to the Internet, have expressed concern that their
businesses could be damaged if they are cut off from the chance to
offer their own high-speed services over other companies' cables.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the coalition members has been calling on both the Federal
Communications Commission and Congress to force AT&AMP;T to give them
equal access to customers of these services.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's cable network is standardizing on the At Home cable modem
service, of which AT&AMP;T is the largest stockholder. At Home provides
not only the technology for very high-speed access but an Internet
portal, the World Wide Web page that the vast majority of At Home's
customers see first when they fire up their browsers. Thus
customers who might now log on through America Online or Mindspring
or might have their home pages set to Yahoo or MSN or some other
portal service will automatically see At Home's pages when they
have a cable modem installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a choice,'' said Charles Brewer, the chief executive
of Mindspring. ``We can choose whether we want to have a
competitive telecommunications market or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger of Comcast and Mediaone announced Monday was in large
part prompted by the need to compete for Internet customers with
telephone companies that have begun offering advanced high-speed
services known as digital subscriber lines, or DSL. America Online
has already announced several deals with phone companies to offer
its own high-speed access in some regions.
</P>
<P>
   But Brewer insisted that competition between cable companies and
phone companies was not sufficient to guarantee genuine consumer
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the FCC, William Kennard, told conference
attendees Monday that his agency was going to act cautiously in
assessing the need to regulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nascent business,'' Kennard said. `We have to have a
healthy dose of humility before we waltz into the marketplace and
start imposing regulatory solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said Monday that cable and phone companies
would soon face competition from broadband technologies now on the
drawing board, including two-way satellite access, fixed-point
wireless networks and mobile wireless access in the form of
third-generation digital cellular devices.
</P>
<P>
   David Nagel, chief technology officer for AT&AMP;T, said high-speed
digital cellular would be ``one of those things that may come
faster than people currently think.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest sparks flew Monday when Nagel suggested that the
Internet service providers' demands for access were an attempt by
narrowband companies to get a ``free ride'' on AT&AMP;T's multibillion
dollar investment in a high-speed digital cable network. In
addition to the $55 billion that AT&AMP;T paid for Tele-Communications
Inc., it has said that it will have to invest billions more in the
cable network to ready it for cable modems and local phone
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's such a load of smelly stuff,'' responded Brewer. ``No
one is proposing that we get a free ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanette Symons, the chief technology officer of Ascend
Communications, a maker of networking gear that in January merged
into Lucent Technologies, said that nationwide broadband service
was still more than five years away.
</P>
<P>
   And she added that insufficient attention had until now been
given to issues like privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
