<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS NOTEBOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darrick Martin sounded like the slacker edition of the village
watchmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consistent minutes are important,'' the Clipper point guard
said one day after being on the clock for 47 minutes (and change)
in his team's semi-startling 100-85 victory at Minnesota. ``When
any player can play and relax, he's going to have a better chance
to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin produced 22 points and seven assists against the
Timberwolves, but his longevity had more to do with necessity than
performance. Sherman Douglas, who has shared the point-guard role
with Martin, was scratched from Sunday's game after straining his
left quadriceps in Friday's loss at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' injury - which may be linked to overcompensating for a
lingering groin pull - could keep him on the pine for a few more
days. Whither Pooh Richardson? Well, that third point-guard option
remains on the injured list. ep For reinforcements, Elgin Baylor,
the team's vice president of basketball operations, is using the
promise of a 10-day contract to beat the bushes for a playmaker.
His best bet figures to be the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers hope to have someone signed and in uniform for
Wednesday's Sports Arena date with Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   __ `Kandi Man' can ... rebound: Rookie center Michael Olowokandi
pulled down a career-high 16 rebounds against the Timberwolves, and
he credits a healthy memory with this backboard tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi had a vivid recollection of how the T'wolves
dominated the inside during last month's visit to the Sports Arena,
and vowed to preempt an encore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't match their intensity the first time,'' he said,
``but I tried to make sure it didn't happen again. I just hope this
will be something we can keep building on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sense of purpose has to be there; it has to become a
habit.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Horror show: Clippers coach Chris Ford thinks his team may
have been frightened into Sunday's lively performance during a
screening of footage taken from the loss in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed them the Toronto film,'' Ford said, ``and I think it
stressed the importance of being physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with increased aggression in rebounding and on defense,
the Clipper offense had enough flow to make it go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were practically flawless as far as moving the ball goes,''
said Ford, who had three subs - Lamond Murray (19), Rodney Rogers
(14) and Lorenzen Wright (14) - combine for 46 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
