A0502 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-SIGNING-LADN     03-22 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-SIGNING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS BRAVE LINE, RISK SHAME OF BEING SEEN WAITING FOR LEWINSKY
</HEADLINE>
 (EDITORS: note language in 12th graf) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After partying with Madonna and other glitterati
at a post-Oscars party, Monica Lewinsky ended her homecoming tour
by signing books for hundreds who wanted a autographed piece of
history _ for $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   More that 400 people clutching copies of ``Monica's Story''
waited up to eight hours Monday outside Brentano's bookstore in the
tony Century City district west of downtown, where Ronald Reagan
keeps an office just a block away &UR; . &LR;  The curious and the mercenary,
the supportive and the cynical all hoped to get an autograph and
exchange a few words with the former Beverly Hills High School
student who carried on an 18-month affair with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a circus, but I'm proud to be a member of this
circus,'' said Adolfo Ramirez, 22, skipping classes for the day
from Santa Monica City College _ another Lewinsky alma mater.
``It's not every day you get to meet someone who almost brings down
a president. I'm just curious to see what she looks like in
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Lewinsky was the toast of the Vanity Fair
post-Oscar party, chatting with star after star _ the famous lining
up to meet the infamous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her if she met Matt Damon,'' said Lynn Harrington, 19,
a California State University, Chico, student who came to the book
signing after visiting a friend in town. ``She said she met Ben
Affleck. She said he's very cute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tell if she was hung over from the weekend,'' said
Chuck Noyes, 44, of Malibu, who had five copies signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was vibrant and wonderful,'' added Harrington's friend,
Angela Davies, 19, a student at California State University,
Northridge. ``She actually seemed like she was willing to converse
more than the security was letting. And she was made up to a T.''
</P>
<P>
   The first person in line arrived at 5:20 a.m. Mark Carpowich, a
political science graduate student at the University of Southern
California, said he thought he should get a head start for the
12:30 p.m. signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a big crush on her for about a year, so I wanted to
meet her in person,'' he said. ``I wish I would've shaved.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky arrived late, however, and didn't start signing until
about 1:20 p.m. Then, after patrons had been told she would sign
every book for every person in line, that was cut to 400 copies
total.
</P>
<P>
   That was good news for those early in the line, like a pair of
autograph dealers who flew in from New York to have Lewinsky sign
50 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got very mad,'' said Elaine Brophy, 29. ``She was bitching
about it: Oh, my hand hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Her partner, Mike Wehrmann, 32, said they paid $900 total for
the five boxes of books, but hope to get up to $600 apiece for
them.
</P>
<P>
   The first customers got Lewinsky's full name in curvy, looping
letters that flattened out as the afternoon wore on. Pretty soon
she was signing only ``Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like she's Madonna or something,'' Brophy said.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Kelly, 29, of Santa Monica applauded Lewinsky for
admitting she made a mistake and for baring her soul in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell her I admire her and I wish her every
success,'' she said. ``I think she single-handedly changed the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders will now have to be more circumspect, since
Lewinsky showed people what goes on behind the scenes, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody was thrilled to see the circus had come to town,
though.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Berardis of West Hollywood was trying to fight through
the crowd to get to the theater next door, to see the film ``Baby
Geniuses'' with her 7-year-old grandson and his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see a movie, not her,'' said Berardis, 57. ``She's
a public nuisance, as far as I'm concerned. She's cost a lot of
taxpayer money _ I don't see the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Bookstore officials said Monday they didn't know how many copies
they sold. But the line of patrons snaked outside the store, along
the Yin Yang cafe next door, downstairs through the parking garage,
back outside around Houston's restaurant, along Santa Monica
Boulevard and around the corner to Century Park West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the biggest loser in the world,'' said Travis
Ruff, anchoring the end of the line. ``It's Monica Lewinsky and I'm
standing here for hours. I just feel like an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Loyola Marymount student said he feared someone
he knew would drive by and see him. He never got inside, but bought
an autographed copy from a woman who had an extra, for only $5 over
the retail price.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's more interested in the souvenir than in its
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care. I don't like her. I don't like any of it,'' Ruff
said. ``But there's nothing more fun than a sex scandal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
