<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCHESNE COULD BE TRADED TO PHILADELPHIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With the NHL trading deadline rapidly
approaching, the Philadelphia Flyers emerged Monday night as the
primary suitor for the services of Los Angeles Kings defenseman
Steve Duchesne.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kings waived the disappointing Duchesne last week,
Flyers general manager Bob Clarke indicated he probably would not
be interested in picking him up. But Sunday, Flyers defenseman Eric
Desjardins suffered a knee injury that is expected to sideline him
for several weeks. This might have opened the door for a deal in
which the Kings would unload Duchesne while agreeing to pay a large
portion of his salary. The NHL trading deadline is noon today.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings signed Duchesne last summer to a three-year,
$11.25-million contract, with a player's option for a fourth year
at $3.75 million. In a deal sending Duchesne to Philadelphia, the
Kings would get little if anything in return. But they would rid
themselves of a player whose addition they came to regard as a
mistake over the course of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Duchesne has a no-trade clause in his contract, but it is
believed Philadelphia is a team he'd be willing to join. The
33-year-old Duchesne played for the Flyers in 1991-92, scoring 18
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Duchesne deal might not be the only one the Kings make
today. General manager Dave Taylor, who did not comment on the
Duchesne matter, spent much of Monday on the telephone looking to
make one or more deals to improve the team for the long haul. With
playoff hopes declining, any trades the Kings make will be with an
eye to the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
