<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-22 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BRIERE/DE     03-22 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BRIERE/DEALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIERE BACK IN MINORS, STILL IN COYOTES' FU TURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes were piling on the team bus after their
game in St. Louis on Thursday when the word spread that rookie
center Daniel Briere was getting sent back to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the players noticed the 5-foot-9 Briere digging for
his baggage and they stepped off, one by one, to console and
comfort him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a touching moment at a trying time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got there a little late and saw him standing there and,
yeah, it was pretty emotional,'' left wing Greg Adams said. ``We
all feel for him. We all like Danny, he's a great kid. He's going
to be a good hockey player, no question, but he needs some time and
something like this can build character.''
</P>
<P>
   Briere can only hope. Especially after the Coyotes' further
clouded his future on Saturday by acquiring an elite center in
Robert Reichel from the New York Islanders for Brad Isbister and a
swap of draft picks. It was a move made for immediate help, a trade
that could put Phoenix back into contention to challenge for the
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Briere, who made a surprise visit Monday to the Coyotes'
Scottsdale practice facility before returning to Springfield today,
wishes a trade wouldn't have become necessary. When the team traded
Cliff Ronning to Nashville, it was to give Briere the opportunity
to center the second line. But the 21-year-old eventually failed to
produce as hoped, mostly due to inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Briere initially didn't want to discuss his demotion, but after
a moment, he relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to win here like everybody else,'' he said. ``They
made a move to win right away and in a sense, I'm happy for the
guys. I was here all year, I still feel like I'm a part of the
team. But now I'm going to Springfield for I don't know how long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I have to worry about is to play well. You
never know what might happen. If somebody gets hurt, I might be
able to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still the matter of today's NHL trading deadline, too.
Rumors have been rampant that Briere might be involved in a
last-minute trade, possibly with the Montreal Canadiens, but
General Manager Bobby Smith quashed those reports on Monday. He
said Briere, the organization's most skilled prospect, isn't going
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens, however, apparently have interest in fourth-year
pro Jason Doig, a 6-foot-3, 220-pound defenseman, who has agreed to
remain in the minors on a ``conditioning assignment.'' Montreal
recently had as many as five scouts in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, which hosts Dallas tonight at 7, can afford to move
Doig, in part because Smith has stockpiled blueliners in the past
two years. The Coyotes, in fact, will be overstocked when Jyrki
Lumme, J.J. Daigneault and Gerald Diduck return from injuries.
Lumme and Daigneault could be back this week. Diduck should be
ready for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Throw them back into the mix with Teppo Numminen, Keith Carney
and Oleg Tverdovsky and the Coyotes will have some interesting
decisions to make regarding the likes of Deron Quint, newly
acquired Jamie Huscroft and minor-league call-up Brad Tiley, all of
whom have been playing well.
</P>
<P>
   Quint's name has been mentioned in trade rumors a few times this
season, but Coach Jim Schoenfeld said he was the team's best
defensemen in Sunday's 4-1 victory over Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the way I've been playing,'' Quint said. ``I
think I've proved a lot of things to a lot of people, and a lot of
people doubted whether I could play.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is doubting whether Briere can play. He averaged 57 goals
and 139 points in three seasons at juniors before turning pro last
season, then was named the AHL's rookie of the year after scoring
32 goals and 96 points at Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   But with Jeremy Roenick and now Reichel entrenched as the
Coyotes' top two centers, what's to become of Briere? He clearly
isn't a third- or fourth-line player, yet Smith said he envisions
Briere playing all season in Phoenix next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Bobby didn't say that to me,'' Briere said. ``I just
know I have to work hard to earn my place again next year. I
learned a lot being around here all year, and I understand what's
going on. I'm not bitter or disappointed, but I definitely want to
get my confidence back and play a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
